<SLUG> BC-NY-IMPEACH-RALLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ACROSS U.S. RALLY AGAINST IMPEACHMENT TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Calif., Ariz., Mich., .C.)  (See related stories: IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEAC-STEELE) 
(fb) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Union leaders, Democratic Party officials and hundreds of other
people came together Tuesday night in cities across the country to
watch President Clinton's State of the Union address and to show
their opposition to the impeachment process, warning Republicans
that they would pay for it at the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   People for the American Way, a liberal advocacy group that has
been trying to rally support for the president, organized the
anti-impeachment forums in 17 cities, among them San Diego,
Detroit, Tucson, Ariz., and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, where more than 400 people gathered at the
headquarters of one of the city's most politically active unions,
speaker after speaker condemned the Senate trial and promised that
those who voted for impeachment would find themselves out of office
after the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of the campaign to oust those who voted
the wrong way,'' said Dennis Rivera, president of the union, 1199,
the National Health and Human Service Employees Union, which has
dedicated its 80-person telemarketing office to the
anti-impeachment effort. ``We don't condone the president's
behavior, but the people have indicated that they don't want him
removed from office. They want us to get back to the issues that
are important to America.''
</P>
<P>
   The event's organizers distributed buttons that read ``Nov. 7,
2000'' the date of the next national elections, and Barbara
Handman, director of the union's New York chapter, promised that
her group would focus on the seats of those who voted for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those who addressed the crowd were law professors and
historians who described the impeachment process as dangerously
flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that Clinton is suffering from self-inflicted
wounds,'' said historian Arthur Schlesinger, ``but the Republicans
are lowering the bar of impeachment and extending high crimes and
misdemeanors to private conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlesinger, who said he could not recall a more bizarre period
in American history, drew cheers when he described Rep. Henry J.
Hyde, R-Ill., who led the prosecution of the president, as ``a
demagogue straight out of central casting.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Jay Williams, a professor of law at Columbia
University, said that she found the prosecution devoid of legal
rationale. ``What I'm hearing are words like `sacred,' `honor,'
`faith' and `belief.' It's more of a religious trial, a witch hunt
by a hypothetical moral majority trying to impose a standard of
behavior that very few people can live up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Mayor David N. Dinkins compared the Senate
proceedings to some of the darkest episodes in American history,
among them the internment of Japanese-Americans in World War II and
the many years that the American government failed to oppose
apartheid in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, he said, the country's constitutional foundation
is being threatened by political partisanship. ``There have been
too many instances when good people were silent, or not vocal
enough, in the face of what they knew was wrong,'' Dinkins said.
``This, I believe, is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many at the event said they were drawn by fear, not
partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Brady Wyman, 54, a Manhattan businesswoman, said she
worried that if the Republicans succeeded in ousting the president,
the country's democratic system could be threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid of the Republicans, afraid that they're leading us
down a very dangerous road,'' said Ms. Brady Wyman, who said she
was an independent. ``To me this prosecution is being run by
vindictive people who are motivated by hate. I came here because I
feel like I have to do something, otherwise it will be too late.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
