<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO INDUSTRY SHOCKED BY CLINTON'S PLAN TO SUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: STATEOFUNION-RDP, STATEOFUNION-ASSESS,
STATEOFUNION-SCENE, STATEOFUNION-SOCSEC, STATEOFUNION-REPUBS,
STATEOFUNION-FOREIGN, STATEOFUNION-MEDIA, STATEOFUNION-WALLSTREET,
STATEOFUNION-ABSENCES) 
(nk) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's announcement that the Justice Department was
preparing to sue cigarette makers came as a shock to the industry,
which thought it had put most of its legal problems behind by
defeating congressional efforts to regulate nicotine and by
settling a series of lawsuits brought by states.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the four major cigarette makers agreed to pay 46
states and five territories $206 billion over the next 25 years to
settle the state suits, which sought to recover their Medicaid
costs for treating smoking-related illnesses. They had previously
reached separate settlements with four states for a total of $40
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton surprised the industry and Congress by announcing
that the government would file its own action seeking the recovery
of federal money, from Medicare and other programs, spent on
smoking-related illnesses. He said the money would be used to
strengthen Medicare, the federal program that provides health care
to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the cigarette industry, Scott Williams, said the
president's comments were ``blatantly political,'' demonizing the
tobacco companies because they were an easy target.
</P>
<P>
   ``This political and economic terrorism against the industry has
got to stop,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Under an earlier settlement proposed in 1997, the tobacco
companies would have paid $516 billion but would have ended the
threat of lawsuits from both states and the federal government. The
industry, however, mounted an intense campaign against the bill and
defeated it.
</P>
<P>
   After that defeat, Richard Scruggs, one of the plaintiffs'
lawyers who helped draw up the first state lawsuits against tobacco
makers, continued lobbying Clinton administration officials to file
a Medicare lawsuit against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' lawyers in the first suits have already been awarded
billions of dollars in legal fees for work on behalf of states.
Scruggs is the brother-in-law of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Scruggs did not return a telephone call Tuesday night seeking
comment. But in earlier interviews, he said that the Justice
Department did not appear eager to file such a suit.
</P>
<P>
   Any federal lawsuit brought to recover Medicare money would face
the same hurdles as the state lawsuits, which were based on novel
legal theories. Because all of the state cases were settled before
they were resolved by a judge or jury, the legal underpinnings of
the lawsuits were never tested in court.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, federal officials may seek to use the threat of a
lawsuit to force concessions from the industry not won in the state
round of settlements, like federal regulation of nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of smoking were enthusiastic about the announcement.
Matthew Myers, a lawyer with the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids, a
group in Washington, D.C., said he believed that a federal lawsuit
would open up a new front in the tobacco war. A federal lawsuit
could prove a far greater financial threat to cigarette makers than
all state actions combined, Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette producers participating in the plan are the Philip
Morris Companies; R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, a subsidiary of the RJR
Nabisco Holdings Corp.; Lorillard Tobacco, a subsidiary of the
Loews Corp., and Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco, a subsidiary of BAT
Industries PLC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
