<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-TICKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS' TICKETS PRICES REMAIN UNCHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the fourth consecutive year, the Cardinals have decided not
to raise ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes four months before a multipurpose stadium
project will be on the ballot in Mesa, Gilbert and Queen Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials also hope to build on their first non-strike
playoff appearance in 23 years and the franchise's first playoff
victory in 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision not to raise prices comes three weeks after
the popular move of giving starting quarterback Jake Plummer a
four-year, $29.7 million contract extension, making him the
second-highest-paid player in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way we're saying thank you to our fans,''
Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill said Tuesday. ``We had very loyal fans
this year and think we're developing a strong fan base.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be an exciting off-season, and we have a lot
of momentum going. We have good feelings here in our office, in the
locker room and around town.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' average ticket price remains at $33.28, which
ranked 17th in the 30-team NFL last year. Several teams already
have announced ticket increases.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, the Diamondbacks caused a stir by raising
ticket prices 12.1 percent for next season. The number of season
ticket holders dropped 28 percent from March 1998 to January 1999,
from 36,000 fans to 26,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns raised ticket prices an average of 13 percent for this
season. The Coyotes didn't raise ticket prices for their 1998-99
season.
</P>
<P>
   According to Team Marketing Report, the four professional
leagues increased tickets an average of 7 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials think the team's first winning season in
Arizona, coupled with keeping ticket prices the same, could bring a
significant increase in season ticket sales for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The team sold 31,019 season tickets last year, the most since
having 48,122 in 1994, Coach Buddy Ryan's first season. The
Cardinals drew an average of 53,819 fans, their third-best since
moving from St. Louis in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to make a concerted effort (to sell) more season
tickets,'' Bidwill said. ``We can get more ticket revenue by
selling more tickets than by (raising prices).''
</P>
<P>
   Season tickets will cost from $180 (south end-zone bleachers) to
$1,800 (loge 50-yard line) in 1999. More than 54 percent (39,182
seats) of 72,994-seat Sun Devil Stadium will be available for $25
per game or less if purchased on a season ticket basis.
</P>
<P>
   Season ticket holders will get 10 to 20 percent discounts on the
single-game price if purchased by June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals play one of the toughest schedules in the league
next season, including four home games against playoff teams _ the
San Francisco 49ers, Dallas Cowboys, Buffalo Bills and New England
Patriots. They also will play two home preseason games against
undetermined opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is expected to announce dates and kickoff times for the
regular season in late April or early May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to help us as far as season tickets to have some
games against tough teams,'' Bidwill said. ``It is a tough
schedule, but they have to play us, too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
