</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-UNION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FOCUSES ON ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Standing in the very chamber where he was impeached
last month, facing the very senators who are now considering
ousting him from office, an embattled President Clinton Tuesday
night delivered a determined defense of the State of the Union
while avoiding any mention of the state of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, delivering his sixth annual address to a joint session
of Congress, laid out a bold proposal to allow the government to
invest a portion of the Social Security trust fund in stocks,
called for a substantial increase in military spending and urged
Congress to pay for 50,000 more police officers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to demonstrate that he is focused on issues, even if
Congress is focused on impeachment, Clinton took his case directly
to those who have stood behind him throughout the past year _ the
American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fellow Americans,'' he said. ``I stand before you to report
that the state of our union is strong. ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps in the daily press of events, in the clash of
controversy, we do not see our own time for what it truly is _ a
new dawn for America,'' he said. ``A hundred years from tonight, an
American president will stand in this place to report on the state
of the union. He or she will look back on a 21st century shaped in
so many ways by the decisions we make here and now.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, echoing congressional calls for a new era of
bipartisanship, he said: ``Let it be said of us ... that we were
thinking not only of our time, but of their time; that we reached
as high as our ideals; that we put aside our divisions and found a
new hour of healing and hopefulness; that we joined together to
serve and strengthen the country we love.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton for the second year in a row gave top billing in his
speech to the importance of ``saving'' Social Security. The Social
Security Trust Fund is expected to run out of money by 2032, and
politicians of both parties have expressed a commitment to
rejiggering the system in a way that will generate enough money to
pay retirement benefits for current workers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans, whose formal response was delivered by
Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., and former Seattle Seahawk Steve
Largent, R-Okla., continued to complain that the president was not
offering specifics, Clinton was more precise than he was a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the number of elderly Americans set to double by 2030,
the Baby Boom will become a Senior Boom,'' Clinton said. ``Last
year, we wisely reserved all of the surplus until we knew what it
would take to save Social Security. Again, I say, we should not
spend any of it until after Social Security is truly saved. First
things first.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed setting aside 60 percent of the federal budget
surplus for the next 15 years for Social Security, and investing a
small portion of that in the stock market. He also suggested
setting aside 16 percent of the surplus for Medicare, and 11
percent of the surplus in Universal Savings Accounts that Americans
could invest individually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Social Security and Medicare is the right way to use
the surplus,'' he said. ``If we do so, we will still have the
resources to meet urgent national needs in education and defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's 77-minute speech drew a mix of reactions. Some
Republicans, including House Managers Henry Hyde and Bob Barr,
boycotted the speech. Supreme Court Chief Justice William
Rehnquist, who is presiding over the impeachment trial, and Sen.
Slade Gorton, a Washington Republican who has skipped the last
several State of the Union speeches, also stayed away.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were restrained in their applause, and two leaders,
House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, and House Majority Whip
Tom Delay, R-Texas, glowered throughout the speech, rising only to
applaud home run slugger Sammy Sosa, seated with Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were a smattering of empty seats on the
Republican side of the chamber, the Democratic side of the chamber
was packed, with some members standing in the aisle or sitting on
armrests. An observer shouted ``Viva Clinton'' as the president
entered, and Democrats on occasion whooped to demonstrate their
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to hear him speak _ he's a great communicator,'' said
Rep. Jack Metcalf, R-Wash. ``But he wasn't talking about
reinventing government, but about renewing the expansion of
government we had been holding in check. It was not a State of the
Union but list of ideas of things we wish we could accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Democrats were skeptical of the laundry list of
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an extraordinary speech, with almost something for
every American,'' said Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore. ``I counted three
dozen new initiatives and new programs. But he avoided the
difficult choices _ a parsing of this budget would show that it is
based on unrealistic revenue and budget assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., although generally supportive,
expressed some concern about Clinton's proposal to close failing
schools and crack down on substandard teachers. A former
schoolteacher, she argued that the emphasis should instead be on
helping teachers and schools improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shutting down schools that continually fail _ that's good
rhetoric, but let's make sure there's a place for them (the
children) to go,'' she said. ``Let's go in there and help them
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats were generally enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy Sosa never hit one that far,'' said Rep. Jim McDermott,
D-Wash. ``It was a wonderful speech, and will force Congress to
deal with two major issues _ Social Security and Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., expressed hope that Clinton's speech
would change some views in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw a lot of uncomfortable folks realizing the policies
he's advanced are in touch with the American people,'' he said.
``He was honest about tackling our most difficult problems, and
America will respond to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress behaved courteously, applauded frequently,
disagreed on substance and demurred on scandal. Like the president,
Republicans wanted to show the country they can conduct the
nation's business even as the impeachment proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   The major policy difference came in the area of tax cuts. Dunn
proposed an across-the-board 10 percent cut in tax rates; Clinton
called only for a handful of smaller tax measures.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did propose a $1,000 tax credit for the aged, ailing or
disabled or their families.
</P>
<P>
   In a section of the speech that could have important
ramifications for the Northwest, Clinton urged ``a freer and fairer
trading system for the 21st century.'' He seemed to threaten trade
sanctions against Japan if that country doesn't reverse a surge of
steel exports, and he called for a new round of global trade
negotiations ``to expand exports of services, of manufactures, and
most of all, farm products.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must tear down barriers, open markets, and expand trade,''
he said. ``At the same time, we must ensure that ordinary citizens
in all countries benefit from trade _ pressing for trade that
promotes the dignity of work, the rights of workers, the protection
of the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called for reversing a decline in the level of
military spending. He said his budget proposal would call for ``a
substantial increase in the next year for readiness and
modernization, and pay and benefits for our troops, and sustained
increases over the next six years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the heirs of a legacy of bravery represented by
millions of veterans,'' he said. ``America's defenders today stand
ready at a moment's notice to go where comforts are few and dangers
are many, doing what needs to be done as no one else can. They
always come through for America. We must come through for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Crime rates have been declining nationally, but Clinton
continued to push for new crime-fighting measures. In his 1994
State of the Union address Clinton called for hiring 100,000 new
police officers around the country, and Tuesday night he called for
hiring half again as many.
</P>
<P>
   On education, always a top priority for voters, Clinton said SAT
and math scores have been rising, but that the federal government
needs to hold states and school districts more accountable for the
way they are spending federal dollars. He called for closing the
nation's worst schools and requiring teachers to pass performance
exams.
</P>
<P>
   The speech included a laundry list of proposals, many of which
are unlikely ever to be enacted by a Republican-controlled
Congress. He called for a $1 per hour increase in the federal
minimum wage, for extending the federal Family Medial Leave Act to
small companies, and for tax credits for stay-at-home parents. He
proposed more empowerment zones in struggling cities and for more
crop insurance for struggling farms.
</P>
<P>
   He praised immigrants, saying ``they are revitalizing our
cities, energizing our culture, building our new economy.'' But he
also urged them to learn English and about democracy, and said he
would propose increased spending to help them do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
