<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS' LAMENT: A GOOD BIG MAN IS HARD TO FIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If the NBA insists upon force-feeding the public a
slapdash season full of Fat Alberts and Homer Simpsons, the least I
can do is highlight the local cartoon _ the Sonic center position.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quiz to see if you've been following this unanimated
feature:
</P>
<P>
   Can you name the starting center when the Sonics ended the
playoffs each of the past three seasons?
</P>
<P>
   If you said Sam Perkins (1998), Terry Cummings (1997) and Frank
Brickowski (1996), you should be ashamed of yourself for not having
a more varied life in spring.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you can take some pride in landing upon the central
failing of the local franchise this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it is a profound scoop. With the notable exception of
All-Star Jack Sikma (1977-86), center has been the franchise's
curse.
</P>
<P>
   Much as with the Mariners in left field and the Seahawks on the
offensive line, the Sonics' weakness apparently defies resolution.
The latest confirmation comes with news that Jim McIlvaine is on
the verge of being traded.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, traded. Unbelievably, to another NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if the Sonics are getting much in return. In
soon-to-be-37-year-old Michael Cage and perpetually injured Don
MacLean, the Sonics are receiving from New Jersey the equivalent of
gym socks.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Nets seem willing to take on McIlvaine's
remaining five years and $20 million-plus on his contract. Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Next, tell me that the Dodgers think Bobby Ayala is Cy
Young-bound.
</P>
<P>
   Not that McIlvaine isn't a swell guy; so, too, are Cage and
MacLean. But as NBA fans learned during the last few months, the
league is about little more than money. These are not money
players, except that they cost a lot of money. The imminent deal is
merely a swap of problems.
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine might be the poster child for the toxicity of the
NBA's economic system. Through no fault of his own and every fault
of the system and team president Wally Walker, the Sonics foolishly
gave him a $33.7 million, seven-year contract that put him in a
brutal pressure cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, then-Sonic coach George Karl had no place for a
slow big man in his defensive system, nor did he have the patience
to work with a project. Besides, Karl considered McIlvaine Walker's
guy, and Karl is just self-destructive enough to allow his contempt
for Walker to influence his handling of McIlvaine.
</P>
<P>
   The poor guy was doomed in Seattle the moment he signed the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   A recent conversation with Pete Newell, guru to many of the
NBA's big men, confirmed the shortcomings. Lamenting McIlvaine's
slowness and his loss of offensive ability due to the need to bulk
up, Newell, who has tutored him over several summers, simply shook
his head when asked whether McIlvaine is capable of breaking
through to become a significant contributor.
</P>
<P>
   His physical limitations, combined with the contract pressure
and Karl's mismanagement, led to the destruction of whatever
confidence and presence McIlvaine might have possessed.
Consequently, on the eve of the past two playoffs, Karl switched to
his backup centers, Perkins and Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, Cummings and Brickowski, power forwards breaking down
at or near the end of their careers, were forced into the post by
default. Karl felt he couldn't count on McIlvaine, and in 1996,
felt the same way about Ervin Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   To make his defensive system work, Karl wanted super-athletic
players between 6-4 and 6-10 who could defend more than one
position.
</P>
<P>
   Which worked fine, until the playoffs. Not only did the Sonics
lack a banger for the more physical postseason, the demands of
Karl's defense wore out the regulars.
</P>
<P>
   Karl's six-year neglect means the Sonic pivot carousel spins
faster. With limited room under the salary cap, the Sonics will
seek another temporary retread, perhaps 7-foot free-agent Olden
Polynice.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't good enough for the Sonics a decade ago, when he was
their first-round draft choice. Now 34, he isn't likely to have a
late bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice already is part of the tepid legacy that includes Bob
Rule, Jim Fox, Tom Burleson, Jim McDaniels, James Donaldson, Alton
Lister and Benoit Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sonics media guide, the list of top single-game
rebounders goes 12 deep. Only one comes after 1983 _ Cage, in 1991.
Among the club's career rebound leaders, 6-5 guard Nate McMillan is
fifth, trailing Sikma and forwards Shawn Kemp, Cage and Spencer
Haywood.
</P>
<P>
   A good big man always has been an elusive quantity in the NBA.
Bloating due to expansion has created an even higher premium. It
seems the only way the Sonics will get a quality galoot is to pull
a Clipper to get in position to draft one from college.
</P>
<P>
   Short of such a dive, coach Paul Westphal might as well cajole
his old Phoenix Suns teammate, 6-9 Alvan Adams, out of retirement.
Adams can't be much older than Cage and Polynice, and for 50 games
he can stand at 25 feet and shoot.
</P>
<P>
   In a carnival sideshow season just short of featuring bearded
ladies and two-headed calves, Adams would hardly be considered a
freak.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
