<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0194 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEOFUNION-RDP-2NDL     01-20 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNBOWED, CLINTON PRESSES SOCIAL SECURITY PLAN
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: CORRECTS second-to-last graf, The administration hopes ...,
to change `private' to `public' in phrase `the law, which governs
aid to PUBLIC schools'; SUBS 3rd graf to add color from speech;
ADDS reference to Sammy Sosa and Rosa Parks, recasts description of
president's comments on first lady; ADDS Dunn on GOP response,
RAISES graf on foreign policy.)  (See related stories:
STATEOFUNION-ASSESS, STATEOFUNION-SCENE, STATEOFUNION-SOCSEC,
STATEOFUNION-REPUBS, STATEOFUNION-FOREIGN, STATEOFUNION-MEDIA,
STATEOFUNION-WALLSTREET, STATEOFUNION-ABSENCES) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton proposed Tuesday night that the
federal government invest for the first time in the stock market to
strengthen Social Security, as he delivered a confident report on
the State of the Union to a Congress considering cutting short his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in the grand chamber of the House of Representative a
month to the day after he was impeached there, Clinton also urged
Congress to begin contributing $33 billion a year to a new system
of retirement accounts for American workers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The President smiled and even joked with his audience of
antagonists and allies as he ignored the trial steps away in the
Senate _ where lawyers began defending him just a few hours earlier
_ and envisioned using the rest of his term to strengthen the
nation's schools, military forces and programs for the elderly. In
a sure-footed, 77-minute address, Clinton coupled a rosy appraisal
of the nation's state with an urgent appeal for action, flaunting
his laurels but insisting he would not rest on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is working again,'' Clinton said. ``The promise of our
future is limitless. But we cannot realize that promise if we allow
the hum of our prosperity to lull us into complacency.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced Tuesday night that the Justice Department was
preparing to sue tobacco companies, opening a new front in a war
that has repeatedly gained him political ground. He argued that
federal programs like Medicare were due hundreds of billions of
dollars for the costs of treating lung cancer and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The president left it to his lawyers to attack the charges he
broke the law to cover up his affair with Monica Lewinsky, the
former intern. But he seized on his State of the Union message as
his most potent defense, just as for the last turbulent year he has
counted on his dogged advocacy of popular programs to sustain him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton exuded ease and a sense of political control, reacting
with unmistakeable delight when both sides of the chamber erupted
in applause for his call for equal pay for equal work by women or
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was more encouraging, you know,'' he said, grinning and
spreading his arms wide as he bent slightly from side to side.
``There was more balance on the seesaw. I like that!''
</P>
<P>
   After the traditional bipartisan ovation welcoming the
president, Democrats applauded far longer and louder, and some of
Clinton's accusers sat with lips compressed and hands folded.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton tried to draw his opponents in. Early, he recalled
the acceptance speech of the new Speaker of the House, Dennis
Hastert, who called for members to work together in a spirit of
civility and bipartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Speaker, let's do exactly that,'' the president said,
turning and extending his hand to the Republican. A surprised
Hastert accepted the handshake.
</P>
<P>
   The president presented his legislative shopping list _ from an
initiative to ease traffic congestion to a $1 billion program to
help people switch from welfare to work _ to a Republican Congress
with far different plans for spending the surpluses accumulating
after decades of deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if some of his plans stand little chance of passage,
Clinton was able to command a television audience for a recitation
of the economic benefits of his leadership _ and an implicit
argument that the trial is an unwarranted distraction from
important business.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our budget surplus growing, our economy expanding, our
confidence rising, now is the moment for this generation to meet
our historic responsibility to the 21st century,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Calling this time ``a new dawn for America,'' he urged his
listeners to ``put aside our divisions'' and find ``a new hour of
healing and hopefulness.''
</P>
<P>
   The president recognized several people in the galleries to
underscore his points. Among them, Sammy Sosa, the home run hitter,
and Rosa Parks, the civil rights demonstrator, brought thunderous
applause that created an image of bipartisan bonhomie, at least on
television. The president also singled out his wife, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, whose loyalty and advice have been key to his political
stamina. ``I'd like to take just a minute to honor her,'' he said.
Mrs. Clinton beamed as the president gazed up at her through
squinting eyes. She rose, sat, then rose again to wave and
acknowledge applause.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Clinton was interrupted about 98 times by the usually
partisan applause.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating the peculiar political dynamic unfolding here,
Republican Senate leaders also seemed eager on Tuesday to play down
the trial. They laid out their own legislative agenda in the
morning, insisting that mulling the first removal ever of a sitting
president would not divert them from what the Majority Leader,
Trent Lott, called ``the people's business.''
</P>
<P>
   In giving the Republican response, Rep. Jennifer Dunn of
Washington assured her viewers that ``our country is not in
crisis,'' and that ``no matter what the outcome of the president's
situation, life in America will go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton devoted only a fraction of his speech to foreign policy,
joining in one paragraph a statement of pride in Northern Ireland's
peace with a condemnation of the violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Though the president called for sure-fire political initiatives
like putting 50,000 more police officers on the street, he also
used his speech to push beyond his short-term predicament. He urged
a long-term fix to the Social Security system his associates said
he hopes will shine through the historic blot of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating a political free fall over the coming budget
surplus, Clinton urged Congress in his State of the Union Message
last year to ``Save Social Security first.'' That proved a deft
political move, stifling Republican appeals for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But with the surpluses growing and a new politics of prosperity
firing legislators' imaginations, Senate Republicans declared that
they would seek a 10 percent cut this year in personal income tax
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Clinton again moved to box them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reach out my hand to all of you in both house of both
parties and ask you to join me in saying: We will save Social
Security now,'' he said. ``Last year, we wisely reserved all of the
surplus until we knew what it would take to save Social Security.
Again, I say, we should not spend any of it until after Social
Security is truly saved. First things first.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For a month, the White House has deliberately leaked out
proposals from Clinton's State of the Union speech to capture
headlines showing the president at work. But it held back its plans
for Social Security as well as for tobacco, to insure that
Clinton's substantative proposals, rather than the spectacle of his
appearance before Congress, would drive Tuesday night's news
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton argued that 62 percent of forthcoming federal surpluses
should be earmarked to preserve Social Security, a program that was
at the heart of the Democratic New Deal but that has since
developed overwhelming popular support.
</P>
<P>
   Another 15 percent of the surpluses, Clinton said, should go to
protect the Medicare program, which assists the elderly with health
care. The president would spend about 11 percent of the surpluses
to create new retirement savings accounts, called ``universal
savings accounts.'' Under his plan, money put into the accounts by
workers would be matched by the federal government, which would
spend some $33 billion a year on the program.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the surpluses _ roughly another 11 percent,
according to the administration _ would go to defense and domestic
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Clinton proposed that $2.7 trillion of a projected $4.4
trillion in surpluses in the next 15 years be reserved for Social
Security. The changes Clinton seeks in the system, the
administration contends, will keep it solvent until 2055. It is now
projected to run out of money to pay the claims of retirees _ who
are expected not only to grow in number but also to live longer _
by 2032.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration's goal is to secure Social Security until
2075, which means Tuesday's plan even by Clinton's standards is
only a partial solution. Clinton made clear that he had no interest
in pursuing politically unattractive options, like tax increases or
what he called ``drastic cuts in benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton argued that Social Security would be stronger if it
could invest some of its trust fund in the stock market, where it
could earn higher returns than from the Treasury bonds it invests
in now. Although state governments invest their pension plans in
stocks, this would be the first venture by the federal government
into the market.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the administration proposed investing up to 25 percent
of the new money for Social Security, or $700 billion, in stocks
over the next 15 years. Gene Sperling, the director of the National
Economic Council, said that under this plan, Social Security would
never have more than 15 percent of its assets in the market, a
level he called ``far, far more conservative than any pension plan
in the country does.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration proposes to work with Congress to create a
privately managed system to invest the money without political
interference.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans signaled they had no interest in the president's
suggestion. ``Government-controlled investment in markets is
contrary to free enterprise,'' said Bill Archer, the Texas
Republican who is chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
He said such investment ``will open the doors to all kinds of
mischief involving government dictates, favoritism and cronyism.''
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the surplus money Clinton hopes to reserve for
Social Security _ about $2 trillion _ would, like the money he
would set aside for Medicare, go to pay off the federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   That would simultaneously reduce the amount of government debt
and increase Social Security's financial reserves. It would help
bring down interest rates, stimulate new investment and create
conditions for faster economic growth to guard against the strains
caused by the retirement of the baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling said that under this plan, the federal debt would fall
as a percent of the domestic product from 44 percent today to less
than 10 percent by 2014. When Clinton took office, he said, that
number was 50.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In proposing his fix for Social Security, Clinton heeded the
demands of his core Democratic constituencies, rejecting a
Republican call that individuals be permitted to make some of their
investment decisions about the money the government deducts from
their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he called for maintaining Social Security as a
``defined benefit'' plan, that is, one with a guaranteed payout.
But Tuesday night he also proposed the system of personal savings
accounts, which are similar to what Republicans are seeking as at
least a partial replacement for Social Security. For the president,
the new accounts would supplement Social Security, not replace it.
</P>
<P>
   Each worker would receive some flat payment, say $100, to open
an account. If he or she then chose to deposit more money,
administration officials said, the government would match a portion
of it, perhaps in the form of a tax credit. Sperling said that the
administration favored weighting the matching system so that it
provided greater benefit to lower-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides repeatedly referred to the agenda he presented
Tuesday night as the most aggressive he has offered since 1993 and
far different than the kind of agenda one might expect from a
president contemplating his seventh year.
</P>
<P>
   They were emphasizing that Clinton intended to stick around, and
they were trying to draw a sharp contrast with the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed a raft of domestic initiatives, including
several to bolster education. This year, Congress must reauthorize
the Elementary and Secondary Education Act, as it does every five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The administration hopes to amend the law, which governs aid to
public schools, to demand that states and school systems begin
testing new teachers for competence, identify failing schools and
shut them down if necessary, and end practices like ``social
promotion,'' or moving children into the next grade even if they
have not gained the necessary skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year the government invests more than $15 billion in our
public schools,'' Clinton said. ``I believe we must change the way
we invest that money, to support what works and to stop supporting
what does not work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
