<HEADER>
A0202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEMS-NYT &LR;      01-20 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS, SWIFT AND STRONG, SUPPORT THE PRESIDENT, THOUGH SOME
SLIP FOLD
</HEADLINE>
   (See related stories: IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-STEELE,
IMPEACH-RALLY, EDIT-IMPEACH-RUFF) 
( nk ) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ In an almost, but not quite, unanimous display of
support, Democratic members of Congress rallied around President
Clinton on Tuesday night, invoking nearly identical phrases as they
applauded his proposals and urged an end to the partisan warfare
that has threatened his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of Clinton's history of delivering State of the Union
speeches that stretched past newspaper deadlines, Democratic
leaders were faxing out their reactions even before he finished
speaking and were reaching through history for superlatives to
praise his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not since the president's first State of the Union address
have we heard as vigorous an agenda as he set forth tonight,'' said
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri. ``He has put
forward an historic and aggressive set of initiatives, taking a
giant leap toward addressing American's concerns as we approach a
new century.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts described the speech as
``an impressive vision for America, an excellent agenda for working
families for the next two years and beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Charles E. Schumer of New York said the speech was
``the best argument for ending the impeachment trial with dispatch
because it showed all important things we should and could be
doing, such as helping Social Security and making the schools
better.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic reviews were not all raves.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding the considerable pressure on party members to
support Clinton, some Democrats, particularly liberal ones, were
unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota said, ``His incrementalist
policies as outlined again tonight will not do nearly enough to
bridge the broad and growing chasm that divides the wealthy and the
prosperous from the majority of Americans who continue to struggle
to make ends meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone complained that instead, the president had included
what Wellstone described as meager efforts to deal with health
insurance and child care, among other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than boldly addressing one of the biggest concerns of
many working families, paying for child care, the president has
warmed over last year's plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ernest F. Hollings of South Carolina attacked Clinton's
plan to use part of the nation's surplus to bolster the Social
Security system, a plan he described as ``nothing more than a
modern-day Ponzi scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   But they were the minority. Most Democrats, emerging from the
chamber after the president's speech, offered strong support for
his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John B. Breaux of Louisiana applauded Clinton's plan to use
part of the surplus to encourage Americans to set up private
savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man's a wonder, he really is,'' Rep. Carolyn McCarthy of
Long Island, N.Y., said of the president. ``I think he was actually
better this year than last year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 0042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
