<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS IMPRESSED WITH SKINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the first round of last summer's NBA draft, the
Clippers selected a post player equipped with the luxury features
of strength, wisdom and an allegiance to hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Well, he's here.
</P>
<P>
   No, Michael Olowokandi is next month's news. The guy we're
referring to is ex-Baylor center Brian Skinner, the Clippers'
selection with the 22nd pick. Skinner was one of five lonely
Clippers to participate in Tuesday's optional workout at Carson's
Veterans Park Sports Complex, and the reviews were favorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good big man,'' new teammate Lamond Murraysaid. ``He's
quick and strong, and he has a nice shot.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite the team's abundance of large laborers, the
6-foot-10, 257-pounder newlywed (he and Rebecca Williams were
married Jan. 9) could have a nice shot at playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to do the things, the sure-fire things, that
I know I can do well, and that's defense and rebounding,'' said
Skinner, who took advantage of the NBA lockout by going to low-post
school in Houston. The faculty included such established NBA
postmasters as Hakeem Olajuwon, Antonio McDyessand Shaquille
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to focus on those two things. You do the dirty
things, you can't go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy should please Clippers coach Chris Ford, who
just happened to be a presiding judge during Skinner's first
pre-draft tour last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was head coach of the Milwaukee Bucks when Skinner checked
in for an audition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did good,'' Skinner said. ``Basically, it's how you
perform in a one-hour period.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically seems to be one of Skinner's favorite words, and a
basic, fundamental approach defines his style of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the NBA would be a lot like college,'' he said,
``but it's not. You may only have to be really good at one or two
things, but that may be enough. Basically, you go with what
works.''
</P>
<P>
   Fab Five: Skinner and Murray were joined at Tuesday's workout by
guards Eric Piatkowski, James ``Hollywood'' Robinsonand Charles
``Spider'' Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of this session was a series of sprints _ known in
hoop lingo as ``suicides'' _ conducted by show-no-mercy strength
and conditioning coach Johnny Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first time I did one of these in about four
years,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' absentee list includes forwards Rodney Rogersand
Maurice Taylor (who have yet to attend one of the voluntary
workouts), forward Lorenzen Wright, centers Keith Clossand Stojko
Vrankovic, and point guard Pooh Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Points in contention: While the basketball world waits for the
start of the NBA's free-agent shopping riot, the Clippers remain
mum about their point-guard quest. New Jersey free agent Sherman
Douglas is believed to be a top candidate, but a league source said
the nine-year veteran may be leaning toward remaining with the
Nets. Miami free agent Eric Murdock _ who's expected to remain with
the Heat or replace Douglas as the Nets' backup _ remains in
contention, as does Darrick Martin, the free-agent Clipper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
