<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0207 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METCALFE-WOMENSPORTS-     01-20 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METCALFE-WOMENSPORTS-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN GAIN COACHING CONTROL ON WNBA BENCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the final coaching pieces fall into place for the WNBA's
third season, half of the now 12-team league will be directed by
men.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Allen, an assistant to Nancy Lieberman-Cline for the
Detroit Shock last season, soon will be named coach of the
Sacramento Monarchs. Deposed New York Liberty Coach Nancy Darsch is
expected to take over the Washington Mystics.
</P>
<P>
   Allen joins Frank Layden (Utah), Orlando Woolridge (Los Angeles)
and Richie Adubato (New York) as former NBA head/assistant coaches
or players at the helm of a WNBA team. The other WNBA male coaches
are two-time Coach of the Year Van Chancellor (Houston) and Brian
Agler (Minnesota), who took the Columbus Quest to back-to-back
American Basketball League titles.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor and Agler also are general managers, as are the
Mercury's Cheryl Miller, Lieberman-Cline, Marynell Meadors
(Charlotte) and Carolyn Peck (Orlando). The other women's head
coaches are Darsch and Linda Hill-MacDonald (Cleveland).
</P>
<P>
   When the WNBA debuted in 1997, seven of eight head coaches were
women. Both midseason coaching changes saw women replacing women.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of 10 teams had women coaches to begin the 1998 season,
but two of the three firings saw women replaced by men (Layden and
Woolridge).
</P>
<P>
   The trend disturbs Lieberman-Cline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's free enterprise, you can hire whoever you want to hire,''
she said, ``but my point is the men have twice as many
opportunities,'' because women are not considered for NBA jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, Milwaukee's George Karl considered hiring Miller
for his staff before deciding the move was too radical for his
first season with the Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discussed the possibility (of hiring Miller) with our
management,'' Karl said on his radio talk show in Seattle. ``We
felt in a new situation it was better to go out and make the sure
call than maybe take a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Cheryl Miller is a lady who could end up on an NBA
bench some day. She's a pretty tough-minded person. She wouldn't
back down.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman-Cline said she has no problems with teams hiring the
likes of Chancellor and Agler, whose collegiate careers were in
women's basketball. And she said until the WNBA has more coaching
stability, the top women's college coaches, male or female, are not
going to venture from their secure and high-paying positions.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who is returning to Turner Sports with the end of the
NBA lockout, is beginning the final season of her initial Mercury
contract.
</P>
<P>
   She missed some of early training camp last season because of
her Turner playoff obligations, turning to the Mercury full time in
late May before a June 11 opener. The impact of her absence was
miniscule compared to the week-of-the-opener arrival of half her
roster from the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   The post-lockout NBA season will conclude about a week later
than the normal regular season, so Miller's assistants, Carrie Graf
and someone yet to be named, will handle much of camp until early
June.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-game WNBA schedule will be announced late this month or
in early February, with play to begin the second week of June.
</P>
<P>
   Miller recently returned from a trip to Australia, where she
watched the Jan. 8 Women's National Basketball League game between
Mercury teammates on the Melbourne teams. The Tigers, with Kristi
Harrower's 14 points and four assists, beat the Bulleen Boomers,
with Michelle Timms' 13 points and five assists, 63-49.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, Adelaide Lightning, Boomers and Sydney Flames are
battling for the final two of four playoff berths.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury center Jennifer Gillom cut short her second season in
Turkey and will appear with teammate Toni Foster to sign autographs
from 6-7 p.m. Saturday before the ASU-Oregon women's game at Wells
Fargo Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Foster is running a basketball clinic at the Mesa Senior Center
from 8:30-9:30 a.m. Friday, while Gillom is to be the keynote
speaker at ASU's Martin Luther King rally at noon Jan. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Gillom joined Teresa Weatherspoon, Kim Perrot, Tammi Reiss and
other WNBA players in New York this week to film a Budweiser
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury's Bridget Pettis is second in Italian A1 League
scoring with an 18.6-point average; Brandy Reed is third (20.6) in
the Spanish First Division; Marlies Askamp is first in rebounding
(12.3) and eighth in scoring (17.3) in the EuroLeague; and Michelle
Griffiths has helped her Italian League team in third place. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
