<HEADLINE>
CROWD AT RESTAURANT FILLS IN THE BLANKS IN CLINTON'S SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ President Clinton didn't say a word about ``it''.
</P>
<P>
   He boasted about the balanced budget. But he wouldn't talk about
``that''.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called for 50,000 more police officers on the street and
touted the fact that the crime rate has dropped for six years
running. He saluted the Desert Fox troops and praised his wife. But
he never mentioned ``her''.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to. The crowd at Nixon's restaurant and bar said
it all.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Seivert slammed him for his affair with Monica
Lewinsky, while she nursed a Corona beer at this bar, which prides
itself for its political conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is comedy,'' added Chad Howlett, who came to watch the
show after work. ``He's such a joke. No one takes him seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   For 77 minutes, Clinton talked about everything under the sun,
including global warming, Y2K and social security. He trotted out
every feel-good symbol from the civil-rights icon Rosa Parks, to
baseball hero, Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Still few paid total attention. Not many lent their respect.
</P>
<P>
   As Shane Cretacci saw it: ``It's a little too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Clinton took the podium, the crowd at Nixon's already was
betting that he wouldn't be man enough to discuss his impeachment
trial, which threatens to undermine his presidency. That he
wouldn't be repentant.
</P>
<P>
   And when he took time to honor his wife, a woman passing by the
restaurant in Phoenix's ritzy Esplanade couldn't help but yell:
``Give me a break. This is so disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the crowd here came to see if they would have
a change of heart about the president _ and about their elected
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Clancy, who voted for Clinton in 1992, couldn't restore his
faith in them.
</P>
<P>
   Cretacci, a Republican, bashed his party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel good about the way the Republicans have handled
this matter at all,'' he said. ``They've spent too much on this.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead of listening, the gang here talked about work. Basic
watercooler chatter. Every now and then, someone would make a
remark about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one table laughs about his social security spiel.
``He's trying really hard to keep the baby boomers happy,'' said a
man at a table.
</P>
<P>
   Stefanie and Michael Lipson managed to make it through dinner
without hearing much of the president's words. ``I'll catch up with
it later,'' promised Michael. ``It's too noisy over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Too add to the festivities, bartender Murray Blake came to work
dressed in a judge's robe and pounds on the bar with his gavel when
the crowd gets too boisterous.
</P>
<P>
   However, he confesses, the robe isn't all in honor of Clinton.
Starting next week, he's going to make Monday night at the bar
``Murray-Ally McBeal'' night, where women can present their case
against their boyfriends and let him issue a ruling on them.
</P>
<P>
   He's off to make another drink. But a woman at the bar leans
over and tells me she doesn't think the president would win a
favorable decision.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton, finally ends his speech, two men at a table get up
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   One turns to me, winks and says: ``It's only fitting that we
came to Nixon's to see the president give his speech. Everything
has a happy ending.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton's impeachment trial progresses, Julie
Amparano will be taking the pulse of people in the Valley. Do they
care about President Clinton's trial? Do they want him removed from
office? What does captivate Americans? She looks for the answers.
Amparano can be reached at 444-8394, or at
julie.amparano(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
