<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARIZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS FOCUS ON RELAY EVENTS  
 HOPE TO CRACK NATION'S TOP 20 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-SWIM-SIDE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even given a lack of athlete consensus as to if or when a
coaching change was needed in Arizona State women's swimming,
opinion is unanimous that the season need not be wasted.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 Championships, Feb. 25-27 in suburban Seattle, begin
five weeks from Thursday. The NCAA Championships, March 18-20 at
the University of Georgia, are an additional three weeks out.
That's not much time to adapt to a new coaching style and pull
together the relays that are so critical to a respectable finish at
nationals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoring individually just doesn't do the trick,'' said junior
Casey Murphy, a co-captain. ``So many teams that just bring relays
have scored higher than us. That's what is going to get us into
that top 20 or 15.''
</P>
<P>
   The ASU medley relays and 800-yard free relay are ranked among
the top eight nationally, and the 400 free is 12th. The 200 free is
not among the top 15.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Chasson, now coaching the ASU men and women, thinks both
teams can improve upon their 1998 national finish (men 10th, women
29th) and that the women are capable of cracking the top 20 for the
first time since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Camilla Johansson (backstroke), junior Carolyn Adel
(middle-distance freestyle and individual medley) and freshmen
Riley Mants (breaststroke) and Sarah Baham (butterfly) all have at
least B qualifying times for nationals, with five chances still to
make the automatic cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, co-captain Tiffany Houser, Lauren Morelli, Stephanie
Elwonger and Anna Ericson are others who can qualify, depending how
they adapt to Chasson's workouts and training with the men.
</P>
<P>
   The teams are practicing together from 6-8 a.m. Their afternoon
workouts overlap for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a lot more satisfaction if you beat one of the
guys than to beat a girl,'' said Adel, who agrees that rapport
between the two teams is improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know each other better because you spend so much time
together, and there is definitely a lot more respect because you
know what everybody else does. In separate programs, you kind of
know what they do, but you've never been there and actually done
the same sets, so there is not that same level of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Adel and the freshmen standouts are among those who question why
Coach Tim Hill was removed at midseason.
</P>
<P>
   After a university committee studied attrition within the
program, Hill was placed on administrative leave for the rest of
the school year, with his contract not to be renewed. Hill has been
at the pool almost daily since the change four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a very good relationship with Tim, but the first
time I saw him was kind of awkward because you really don't know
what to say,'' Adel said. ``He actually called me at home (during
semester break) and told me what happened. I think he's handling it
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Chasson made the time to take his new team to a trust-building
ropes course in Scottsdale and hiking on South Mountain and met
individually with each swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the decision was made, the team was kind of coming
apart,'' Chasson said. ``There were people that were pro-Tim,
anti-Tim and ambivalent. So the main thing was to bring everybody
back together.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the team should benefit from having the cloud
of doubt removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, I've really gained so much,'' Houser said. ``I'm
very happy to be here, and I think that's what is making me swim as
well as I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Casey (Murphy) and me, it was difficult because as
captains we have to think for the team. We were seeing a lot of
hurt. We see now the team is kind of turning around, people are
happier, the attitude overall is much better. You can sense that,
and of course that's going to make me swim better because they're
happy, I'm going to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Baham, from Arcadia, Calif., already has set a school record
(54.76 seconds) in the 100 butterfly, breaking a mark that stood
for 17 years, and is third all-time in the 200 fly. Mants, a 1996
Canadian Olympian, is ranked second nationally in the 200 breast
off her time (2:12.70) at the Texas Invitational in early December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks I'm doing really well and is confident that
I'm going to go to NCAAs and I believe it, but I don't expect just
to go,'' Baham said. ``I want to go and be a name up in front. I
got the school record so I guess that's good, but I expect a lot
more out of myself than most people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mants said she is swimming better than she has since the Atlanta
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real happy here and I like the team, I like the coaches,
the environment,'' she said. ``I never found anything wrong with
Tim. . . . I guess they wanted what was best for the team, and I
guess this is it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
