<SLUG> BC-STATE-REAX-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STATE VIEWERS APPLAUD CLINTON'S SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As Washington state voters watched President Clinton's
State of the Union speech Tuesday night, they seemed to be hearing
his message and marveling at the embattled president's fabled
performance under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared to have succeeded in going over the talking
heads in the nation's capital and connecting with the ``other''
Washington that has twice backed him for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man's ability to pull this off, with the pressure this
bird is under, is really phenomenal,'' said Patricia Fleeson, a
longtime Bellingham civic activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can put the strains on the back burner, put his energy into
a speech like this, and address people with hope and aspiration,''
she added. ``He's somethin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Austin, owner of the Merchants Deli in Walla Walla, added:
``This guy gives a speech, doesn't he? Whether you are a Clinton
enthusiast or opposed to Clinton, you have to agree on his ability
to communicate his message.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has sometimes been faulted by critics for ``bite-sized
proposals'' and the lack of an overarching vision. But the
specifics in Tuesday night's speech appeared to be one of its major
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Tilly, a Chelan County Public Utility District
commissioner, watched Clinton from her home in Wenatchee. He struck
a chord with the former high school music teacher on the issue of
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked what he said about more money for summer school,
after-school programs, children needing special help, and money to
modernize schools. I liked that emphasis,'' Tilly said.
</P>
<P>
   A Snohomish County businessman, Chuck Shigley, chuckled over the
multiplicity of programs that Clinton was able to shoehorn into a
speech that lasted about 77 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm exhausted,'' Shigley added. ``He stuffed at least six
pounds into a five-pound bag. But I liked it for its brightness and
upbeatness.''
</P>
<P>
   Shigley has been a substantial contributor to such Republican
politicians as Sen. Slade Gorton and Rep. Jack Metcalf of
Washington. But he was disappointed at Washington GOP Rep. Jennifer
Dunn's televised response to Clinton, particularly her
no-tanks-in-the-streets reference.
</P>
<P>
   And Shigley noted that Clinton has not been shy about
appropriating ideas from Republicans. Several proposals popped up
last night _ retirement security savings accounts, performance
exams for teachers _ originally suggested by GOP officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded awfully Republican to me, he seems to be taking a
page out of the Republican playbook,'' said Berandine Rogstad,
until recently Republican chairman in Whatcom County. She pointed
to Clinton's talk about local control of education and tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last night's performance, Rogstad still believes Clinton
is ``an embarrassment to our nation. ... No, I don't think he is
credible or effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Natt, publisher of the Daily News in Longview, said,
however, that Clinton's agenda is ``very clever politics''
especially in the context of the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cast such a wide net and couched it in terms that you would
think, `Geez, what laudable goals, and we should work together to
get these things done.' Implicit in this feeling is that he gets to
keep his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Democrats and Republicans, so bitterly divided over Clinton
and different even in their body language Tuesday night, succeed in
working together in the 106th Congress?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty to do and we ought to get at it. As soon as
possible,'' Natt argued. ``If we can get the impeachment matter
behind us, yes, they can work together. We've got to get the
impeachment matter behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not been known for spontaneous humor in his
speeches, one factor that has caused pundits and the public to
wince at how long the president can keep talking.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, however, the president seemed unusually light on
his feet, with quips about the lone congressman who stood and
applauded his proposals to combat the Y2K problem, and his joke
about the inequality in applause from Democratic and Republican
sides of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept a wonderful sense of humor. I was not expecting him to
play the crowd with such wit,'' said Valerie Bystrom, a teacher at
Seattle Central Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Perry, a longtime labor union activist from Bellingham, said
one strength of the speech was that ``Clinton enjoyed himself,
while the Republicans did not enjoy themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But Austin applauded Republicans for their courtesy toward a
president that a majority, at least in the House, have voted to
impeach and are campaigning to remove from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican side of the aisle were very courteous in their
approach,'' he said. ``They set the trial aside.''
</P>
<P>
   But Drew Pettus, a Bellingham attorney, criticized the ``glum,
spoiled-sport'' look on the faces of Republican lawmakers. ``He
(Clinton) created a contrast, of a president dealing with problems
important to the average person, and the other side taking a johnny
one-note approach. They seem to have one thing on their minds:
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Haman, a Republican activist on Whidbey Island, saw part of
the president's speech before going off to a meeting of the Langley
cemetery board. Haman voiced worry that Clinton has appropriated
his party's ideas while the GOP has buried itself with the
impeachment effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having watched Clinton tonight, I was impressed how he once
again picked up on Republicans' issues,'' said Haman. ``Most of his
initiatives have their origins in things we were saying and doing.
But nobody remembers that these belong to the Republican Party.
Perhaps the reason is that we have been so busy trying to destroy
him that we have forgotten how to promote ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were jubilant over the president's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pushed the right buttons for me,'' said Peggy Johnson, an
administrator of a care facility in southwest Washington. She
praised Clinton's proposal of tax credits for families caring for
an aging or disabled relative, and his promise of affordable
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, Clinton still seems to have the ability to
make the country feel bullish and buoyant, despite the never-ending
drumbeat of scandal from Washington, D.C., commentators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is such a contrast,'' said Seattle architect Arne Bystron.
``It is so hard to believe that those people are so wound up
looking at their navels that they can't see what is happening out
in the rest of the country. He can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 0050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
