<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARIZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIMMING PROGRAM PER FORMING A FLIP TURN AT ASU  
 COACHING CHANGE SEEN AS KEY 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-SWIMMING-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you hear the buzz?
</P>
<P>
   It's soft, still imperceptible to those outside of swimming, and
perhaps nothing more than the reverberation of a midseason coaching
change and the shift of four-time Olympic medalist Gary Hall Jr. to
Arizona State for training, but it's a sound nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need more good buzz about ASU, and if there's a
combined program and people are happy and they're swimming well,
then that's going to help spread the word to coaches all over the
place and swimmers,'' said Mike Chasson, who in his first season as
ASU men's coach recently inherited the women's team upon the firing
of 14th-year Coach Tim Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more swimmers, male or female, who are swimming fast and
have good things to say,'' the better, Chasson said. ``Let's say
the guys' team is doing really well, but another coach is coaching
the women and they're all unhappy and they're complaining. That's
negative PR for our program.''
</P>
<P>
   That, more or less, was the problem at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   Due to attrition and injuries, the women's senior class that
began with eight swimmers was reduced to one, co-captain Tiffany
Houser. There are seven juniors remaining from an original class of
15. Assistant coaches came and left with regularity.
</P>
<P>
   A committee formed by the athletic department in November to
study the women's team, which fell to its lowest national finish
(29th) under Hill last season, concluded immediate action was
required. So on Dec. 28, rather than continuing a 10-day vacation,
Chasson began integrating the women into a combined program under
his direction.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the timing, the change didn't surprise others in the
club swimming community, which was a surprise to Chasson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how they knew it was going to happen when I
didn't know,'' said Chasson, who was hired away from Harvard to
replace the retiring Ernie Maglischo as men's coach. ``I did not
expect to be doing this in the middle of the season, there's no
doubt about it. I didn't expect to be doing it at any point. My
first wish would really have been that Tim had done a great job and
was still going to be coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only comment to (the committee) was if you're really going
to make a change, then I think the best thing for Arizona State
swimming is to have a combined program.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, Southern California, Georgia and Auburn are among the
schools with combined programs, and all have men's and women's
teams in the national top 10. The ASU men (3-2) are ranked 10th,
while the women (5-2-1) are 20th.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean it happens overnight,'' Chasson said. ``It's
taken Frank (Busch, UA coach) about five years to really get it
rolling, then the last couple of years they've been really kicking
butt. When people think about Arizona, they're thinking fast
swimming, not that they have a fast men's team or women's team.
They're thinking swimming is fast. That's the biggest plus about a
combined program.''
</P>
<P>
   Busch, the 1998 USA Swimming Coach of the Year, is in his 10th
year in charge of Arizona's combined program. The women were
runner-up and the men sixth at the 1998 NCAA Championships. Busch's
club program, Hillenbrand Aquatics, was women's and combined winner
at the U.S. Championships.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old Chasson also directs Sun Devil Aquatics, the
club team based at ASU's Mona Plummer Aquatic Center.
</P>
<P>
   Chasson points to UA's Rick DeMont and Eric Hansen, former coach
of the Phoenix Swim Club, as head-coach caliber assistants that
Busch is able to retain because of a combined program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can afford to pay quality assistant coaches more money,
which means we're going to get better coaches, and they're going to
stay longer,'' said Chasson, who plans to retain Victor Wales next
season and open the other two assistant jobs to a national search.
``I think the jobs are going to have an incredible amount of
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   A third benefit of a combined program, Chasson said, is that the
budget can be used more efficiently with less duplication of
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting, of course, is more demanding for two teams,
especially since Hill did not sign anyone in the fall. Chasson said
Wales has done a good job catching up with the best unsigned
high-school women, and club coaches are contacting him about their
prep juniors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
