<HEADER>
A0214 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-LONGLEY-AZR &LR;      01-20 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-LONGLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGLEY TOUTS HIS DEFENSE, SHOOTING  
 COLANGELO CONFIRMS DEAL TO ACQUIRE CENTER FROM BULLS, CLEAR SPACE
ON
 SALARY CAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unofficially, it's official.
</P>
<P>
   Suns President Jerry Colangelo confirmed Tuesday the Suns have a
pending sign-and-trade deal with Chicago for Luc Longley, and the
7-foot-2 center from Australia made his first appearance at
informal workouts at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be specific except to say we expect Longley to be in
a Phoenix uniform, and it's going to be one of those sign-and-trade
deals with Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns will send three players _ Mark Bryant, Martin Muursepp
and Bubba Wells _ and a conditional first-round draft pick to
Chicago for Longley.
</P>
<P>
   Longley didn't come cheap, but the Suns took only $4 million
onto their salary cap and cleared $3 million, thus obtaining a
30-year-old starting center while losing only $1 million of cap
space.
</P>
<P>
   That could be an important aspect of the deal if the Suns have
to replace Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   Longley was cautious about assuming that the deal with Chicago
is done, but he said he hopes that it will be when a new collective
bargaining agreement is signed and players can begin signing deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first choice,'' Longley said. ``I'd like to be
here. I don't think any deals are done. Nobody knows what the
salary cap rules are going to be yet. And most of the major players
will fall into place first.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds good. Except Longley drove from Chicago to Phoenix. He's
planning to stay awhile.
</P>
<P>
   And when the deal is done, the Suns will have a center who said
his strengths are his passing ability, defense, midrange jump shot
and savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Phoenix signs me, it's because of my defensive abilities,''
Longley said. ``If I were going to take out an ad in the paper, it
would say, `Defensive post player who loves a warm climate.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Longley was a key component of the Bulls' triangle offense
because of his ability to read a defense and make the correct pass.
But he's also a dependable shooter who can pull defensive shot
blockers away from the basket. He believes Phoenix fans will
appreciate his total game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last four or five years, I've been a very specific role
player,'' he said. ``I'm capable of doing different things.
Basketball has got a lot of different aspects.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Longley couldn't contain his dry humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed the triangle,'' he added, smiling. ``But I can
really let my ballhandling skills flourish in the West.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls apparently made little effort to keep Longley once
Michael Jordan made his decision to retire, and Longley said he was
disappointed and surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other team in the hunt contacted me before the Bulls
did,'' he said. ``But you don't want to be in the carcass of a
once-great team waiting for the (vultures) to come pick us apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've got two young kids. It would be nice to be able to
let them go outside and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Longley played collegiately at New Mexico, and his wife is from
Albuquerque. He also has a new restaurant opening in Scottsdale in
the spring. He said his American roots are planted in the
Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   But he's still an Aussie first.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he'll bring to the Suns if the deal is struck,
Longley thought for only a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australian jokes and Foster's,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
