A0215 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE-AZR &LR;      01-20 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSER TO RUNNING FOR WHITE HOUSE, DAN QUAYLE RIPS `LIBERAL
REPUBLICANS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Saying he is ``on the verge of announcing his
candidacy'' for the White House, former Vice President Dan Quayle
has issued a strongly worded attack on ``liberal Republicans,''
with veiled references to other GOP contenders John McCain and
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had it up to here with Republican leaders who are more
interested in pleasing the ``New York Times'' and appearing on
``Meet the Press'' than standing up for what is right and the
people they represent,'' Quayle said in a fund-raising letter
issued Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have ordered my staff to never _ EVER _ utter the words
`compassionate conservative'! This silly and insulting term was
created by liberal Republicans and is nothing more than code for
surrendering our values and principles,'' Quayle wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Among the possible candidates for president, it is Arizona Sen.
John McCain who has received the most favorable coverage from East
Coast media such as the ``Times'' in recent years. The
``compassionate conservative'' slogan is generally attributed to
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's letter signals the start of the first real contest
between him and other GOP White House contenders in the race to
raise the huge amount of funds needed to be seen as a viable
candidate in 2000. It is estimated that a successful candidate will
have to raise as much as $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The staggering cost of running for president has both Arizona
candidates already scrambling for dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle has scheduled a fund-raising event Jan. 25 during the
Phoenix Open, while McCain is planning a major event at the Arizona
Biltmore in March.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, McCain and Quayle, along with publisher Steve
Forbes, the winner of Arizona's 1996 GOP presidential primary, are
scheduled to appeal to California Republicans at California's GOP
state conference next month.
</P>
<P>
   With its early 2000 primary, scheduled March 7, and its rich
cache of delegates, more than any other state in the nominating
process, California is viewed as crucial to any Western candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Quayle has said he is leaning toward a run for the
White House, but his fund-raising appeal, on ``Quayle 2000
Exploratory Committee'' letterhead, makes clear he is ready to jump
into the contest.
</P>
<P>
   McCain filed his exploratory committee papers Dec. 30. He could
not be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have reached this critical point only after spending many
long hours with my wife and children over the holidays, considering
the pros and cons of such a massive undertaking,'' Quayle wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Quayle added, ``my family agreed that America
desperately needs a strong new leader who can restore faith, trust
and integrity to the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said his deadline for developing a draft presidential
platform is Jan. 29.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Quayle appears to position himself on the right
side of the GOP field with his attack on ``liberal Republicans''
and the ``compassionate conservative'' slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sick and tired of watching the Republican Party and our
conservative values take it on the chin from Bill Clinton, Al Gore
and the liberal Democrats,'' Quayle wrote.
</P>
<P>
   An aide said Quayle plans to reiterate the message Friday in a
speech before conservatives in Washington, D.C., at the
Conservative Political Action Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new poll shows that McCain is leading the GOP
presidential field in Arizona, while Quayle, who plans to announce
his presidential campaign in Indiana, trails far behind.
</P>
<P>
   The Behavior Research Center poll showed that McCain would lead
with 26 percent of Arizona Republican voters if the primary were
held today.
</P>
<P>
   It also showed Arizona GOP voters support Texas' Bush, giving
him 21 percent, and two-time former Cabinet member Elizabeth Dole,
giving her 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only 9 percent of voters said they would vote for Forbes, who
has become a regular at Arizona GOP functions, and 5 percent said
they would vote for Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 535 voters, taken Jan. 9-14, had a margin of error
of plus or minus 4.3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Earl de Berge said the numbers suggest Quayle's
strongest appeal in Arizona is among older, more conservative
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's backers, he said, ``seem to be more to the right than
McCain or Dole or even Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the South Carolina Republican Party announced Tuesday
that McCain will be the featured speaker at the party's main
fund-raiser this year.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will speak at the state's annual Silver Elephant Banquet
March 12, state GOP Chairman Henry McMaster said. &QL; 
Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
