<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOCCHET ENDS SCORING SLUMP  
 MOVES WITHIN 1 GOAL OF 400 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he was in a bit of a slump, having scored only three goals
during a recent 15-game stretch, Coyotes forward Rick Tocchet said
he'd take a goal anyway he could get one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could go off somebody's butt or even go off my own, I don't
care,'' Tocchet said.
</P>
<P>
   He got his wish Tuesday night during a 4-2 victory over the St.
Louis Blues, scoring his 14th goal _ and the 399th of his career _
when he put one in off St. Louis defenseman Rudy Poeschek in the
second period, leaving him just one shy of reaching the 400-goal
milestone he seems to have been chasing for months now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple more chances after that (to get No. 400), but
you try not to think about that,'' Tocchet said. ``The way things
were going there for a while, I was starting to say to myself, `I
want to get it this year, not next year.' But you've just got to
keep shooting the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Number 399 was ugly, though.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Plate breaking &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes center Jeremy Roenick said he is only half looking
forward to the skills competition that preludes the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like doing the rapid-fire contest,'' he said, ``but other
than that . . .''
</P>
<P>
   What about the accuracy event, where players stand high between
the circles and try to break round plates fitted in four spots in
front of the net?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I used to like that one,'' Roenick said. ``Two years in
a row, I broke all four of them in six shots. (Boston's) Ray
Bourque beat me both years, though. He went four for four.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Slap shots &QL;  &QL; 
Versatile center Mike Stapleton, one of the Coyotes' top penalty
killers, did not play Tuesday because of a charley horse he
suffered during Sunday's 1-1 tie in Chicago. He is listed as day to
day.
</P>
<P>
   Two Coyotes farmhands, defenseman Brad Tiley and goalie Robert
Esche, have been selected to play in the American Hockey League
All-Star Game on Jan. 25 in Philadelphia. Tiley leads the
Springfield Falcons in scoring among blueliners, and Esche is the
team's starting goalie.
</P>
<P>
   This is Tiley's second straight All-Star selection. He missed
last year's game, however, because of a broken jaw. Tiley recently
returned to the Springfield lineup after missing four games because
of a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are expected to unveil their third jersey on
Saturday, Feb. 6 when they host the Chicago Blackhawks in a special
1 p.m. start. The jerseys are green and feature the head of the
Coyotes logo.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis defenseman Al MacInnis took over the NHL lead in goal
scoring by a defenseman this season when he collected his 12th on
the power play at the 19:59 mark of the first period. MacInnis
ranks fifth all-time among blueliners with 282 goals _ 11 shy of
Phil Housley and 22 behind No. 3 Denis Potvin. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
