A0217 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CASSTEVE-NS-COLAN     01-20 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CASSTEVE-NS-COLANGELO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NUGGET OF ADVICE FOR MCDYESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He gazed down at the America West Arena practice court and
listened to a familiar sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thump, thump, thump ''.`` .''`` .''
</P>
<P>
   The source wasn't a dribbling basketball but the rapid beat of
his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver''.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, Jerry Colangelo jammed his hands into the deep
pockets of his gray slacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the kid thinking''?``''
</P>
<P>
   Exasperated, he felt his anger and blood pressure rise.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo is accustomed to having things his way. He usually
gets what he wants, whether it's a Charles Barkley or a Randy
Johnson or a baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Before last season, the Suns wanted Antonio McDyess and got him,
and paid a high price. Phoenix gave up Wesley Person, Tony Dumas,
plus two first-round and two second-round draft picks for the young
Denver Nuggets star. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trade brought lots of smiles
</P>
<P>
   The day the trade was announced, the boss looked almost as happy
as McDyess, who couldn't stop smiling, and his smile is one of
those smiles that lights up and warms a room.
</P>
<P>
   He was out of dead-end Denver. A Sun now, McDyess proudly held
up his new jersey. No. 34. Barkley's old number.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess had joined a playoff team and an organization with a
winning tradition. He and Jason Kidd represented the new Suns: the
cornerstones of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo stared in silence at the hardwood court Tuesday
morning. There was Luc Longley, the Suns center-to-be. There was
Kidd. But no McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   A free agent, McDyess is home in Houston, or maybe on his way to
Denver. Colangelo and McDyess haven't spoken. The team owner can't
pick up the phone and call the player and ask what he is thinking.
Until the NBA lockout settlement is put into writing, contact
between management and players is prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   So Colangelo walks the halls of the empty arena, wondering,
waiting, sensing perhaps the worst is about to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns may lose McDyess, who was the best player on the team
down the stretch last season. Remember the night he scored 37
points against the Lakers in the Forum? During the one-man show,
Bryan Colangelo, seated in the stands, turned and looked at Arn
Tellem, the agent McDyess recently fired. Tellem smiled at
Colangelo, and the smile said, ``He's going to cost you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns never would have traded for McDyess if they hadn't
expected to re-sign him. They were prepared to pay (fill in the
blank). Under the old rules, they could have offered the moon. Now
the most the Suns can pay McDyess in the first year of a new
contract is $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Will McDyess take it? Who knows. The Suns are lucky if the
player's new agent, who also represents Nick Van Exel, returns
their phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of our control,'' Colangelo said. Those five words
sounded foreign to him.
</P>
<P>
   Pros, cons of Denver &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver. Is he nuts''? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McDyess should tune out his friends for a moment and do what
many people do when they are contemplating an important decision,
like whether to accept a new job. Take a sheet of paper. Draw a
line down the center. On the left write ``Pros.'' On the right
``Cons.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Pros'' for going to Denver:
</P>
<P>
   1. Familiar with city.
</P>
<P>
   2. Will play 45 minutes per game.
</P>
<P>
   3. Get to wear those mittens I bought two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   4. New team has four draft picks, thanks to me.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Cons'':
</P>
<P>
   1. Nuggets won 11 games last year.
</P>
<P>
   2. Team is up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   3. New coach has never coached in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   4. Get to play with Van Exel, who takes shots (lots and lots of
them) instead of Jason Kidd, who gets me shots.
</P>
<P>
   5. Less money.
</P>
<P>
   The decision facing McDyess is what neurosurgeons refer to as a
``no-brainer.'' My simple rule of thumb in advising an athlete
where to play professional basketball is this. Never ever go to a
city where the NFL team wins more games than the NBA team. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 0053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
