<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0218 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BOYCOTT-AZR &LR;      01-20 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BOYCOTT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 ARIZONA CONGRESSMEN SKIP CLINTON'S SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGON _ Rep. John Shadegg was not alone in boycotting
President Clinton's State of the Union address Tuesday. A second
Arizona Congressman, Rep. Matt Salmon, joined in _ although he
cited a lack of business in Washington this as a key reason for
skipping the event _ and so did about 10 other members of the
House.
</P>
<P>
   In the Arizona delegation, Sen. Jon Kyl and Rep. Bob Stump
passed on the speech, but for unrelated reasons. Kyl went home sick
Tuesday afternoon, while Stump watched the speech from his
Washington office, as he has done often in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Arizona delegation attended the address.
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg explained his boycott in a letter to his colleagues
co-written by Rep. Bob Schaffer, R-Colo. ``The president is
demonstrating his lack of respect for the Congress,'' the
Republicans wrote. ``We will not play a role in facilitating his
disrespect.''
</P>
<P>
   Schaffer, in an interview before the speech, said he was staying
away out of respect for the presidency, which he said Clinton had
``defiled'' by his affair with Monica Lewinsky. Permitting the
speech to go forward, he said, was ``conveying a sense of normalcy
to the country and to the world that I think is inaccurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other members of the House who were reported as
boycotting the president's appearance were Rep. Bob Barr., R-Ga.,
one of the 13 House prosecutors in the Senate impeachment trial,
and House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, in a statement, said he would watch the speech on
television but believed it was ``inappropriate and awkward for the
president to make this speech directly to those sitting in judgment
of him and those presenting the case against him in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde has led the case seeking Clinton's removal from office. He
also decided not to attend, but it is not an unusual practice for
him, according to a spokesman, because Hyde is not comfortable in
large crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior Republican, Rep. John Boehner of Ohio, decided to
skip the speech, but his spokesman said it had nothing to do with
the impeachment trial. Boehner was in Hawaii with his wife
celebrating their 25th wedding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Also conspicuously absent when the justices of the Supreme Court
entered the House chamber was Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who
is presiding over the Senate trial deciding whether to remove
Clinton from office. Rehnquist's aides reportedly had questioned
whether it was appropriate for him to attend the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg gained national attention by announcing he would boycott
the speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republic'' readers reacted negatively to the move. Calls and
e-mail were running 2-1 against his decision, with some saying it
showed disrespect for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   One man said he'd never vote for another Republican. Another
condemned both Shadegg and ``The Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares about Shadegg? The Republican Party is dead.
Finished. So is your paper,'' the man said.
</P>
<P>
   But others expressed outrage that Clinton would go before
Congress in the middle of the trial and praised Shadegg for
skipping the speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the only one who's not a hypocrite. They'll all be
sitting there and applauding the president,'' another woman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Noble, the district director for Shadegg's local office,
said the office received 224 calls in support of skipping the
speech and 162 against.
</P>
<P>
   ``People rarely call to express support,'' Noble said. ``For us
to have those kinds of numbers _ it's significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Paranzino, Salmon's chief of staff, said Salmon stayed in
Arizona to be with his family. He had no meetings in Washington
this week, so he didn't feel the need to attend the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon believes Clinton should have postponed the address.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not making a big issue of it,'' Paranzino said. ``He felt
the timing was inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Stump's chief of staff, Lisa Jackson, said Stump had long
planned to watch the speech from his office. He was not protesting
the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans decided to follow the lead of new House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who wrote in a letter Friday that despite
the ``discomfort,'' Congress had a duty to hear the views of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of respect for the office of the presidency, and for the
state of our union, we will listen to the president's remarks
soberly and with the dignity that befits the United States
Congress,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of Democrats who planned to skip the
speech, and most of the members of the minority party seemed
unfazed by the boycott. Said Barney Frank, D.-Mass., a member of
the Judiciary Committee: ``No one cares about that. Any member of
Congress who thinks there's significant interest in where he parks
his ass for the evening is delusional.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press and the Boston Herald contributed to this
article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
