r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-MCDYESS-AZR &LR;      01-20 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-MCDYESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLANGELO CONFOUNDED  
 MCDYESS' MIND-SET BAFFLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suns President Jerry Colangelo, frustrated and perplexed, said
Tuesday that he's at his wits' end trying to figure out free agent
forward Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess still had not indicated Tuesday evening whether he will
return to the Suns or sign a deal with the Denver Nuggets, but most
signs were pointing toward his defection to the Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the most telling: Colangelo confirmed that the Suns have
not been able to get McDyess' agents to return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 32 years, this is a new one on me,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   A McDyess friend, who is screening his telephone calls, at first
said Tuesday that a decision would come today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to get up in the morning, make his decision and
pack his bags,'' the friend said.
</P>
<P>
   But by Tuesday afternoon, the same friend said McDyess had
decided to take his time and might not make a decision until Friday
or Saturday. McDyess never has met Denver's new coach, Mike
D'Antoni, and could be planning a meeting when contact between
players and teams is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Another delay in finalizing the collective bargaining agreement
between the NBA and its union has pushed the start of training
camps back to at least Thursday and may mean shortening the season
from 50 games to 48 or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   While there were reports Tuesday that McDyess has ruled out the
Suns, sources said the team has not been informed of any decision.
But Colangelo said the Suns will be ready to move to other options
if McDyess chooses to play in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to be prepared if we don't (get him back),''
Colangelo said. ``For every logical reason in the world, he belongs
in Phoenix. He may or may not be influenced by people around him.
We don't have any access to him, so we don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never in a position where it's totally out of our control
like this. We find ourselves in an unusual position, and we just
have to play it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns gave up a lot to obtain McDyess in October 1997: Wesley
Person, Tony Dumas, two first-round draft picks and a pair of
second-round picks in a three-team trade.
</P>
<P>
   The club made that deal expecting to re-sign McDyess. But in the
summer, he fired his original agent, Arn Tellem, and hired Tony
Dutt and James Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, when we made the deal for Antonio, we felt very
confident, based on his representation and his desire to be here,
that we would be able to re-sign him,'' Colangelo said. ``We were
building around Antonio and Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed feelings. I'm very disappointed we gave up what
we did to get Antonio McDyess, but I'd do it again because it was
the right thing to do at the right time. This has nothing to do
with the decision to go after him in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Suns lose the McDyess sweepstakes, Colangelo said the
team will ``go to option B, option C. Life will go on.''
</P>
<P>
   There were reports Tuesday that the next option will be signing
Charlotte free agent center Vlade Divac. But league sources told
``The Arizona Republic'' that the Suns still hope to sign Minnesota
free agent forward Tom Gugliotta if McDyess leaves.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of Luc Longley, the Suns could play Divac at
power forward. But Gugliotta seems to be a better fit at that
position. If Gugliotta either turns down the Suns or decides not to
wait on McDyess' decision, Divac is a possibility. The Suns also
could look at other options, such as re-signing Clifford Robinson
and adding another free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The club is known to have considerable interest in Miami free
agent guard Brent Barry, who also is being pursued by the Chicago
Bulls. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
