<P>
   &UR; ADULTERERS AND LIARS _ BUT AMERICA STILL LOVES POLITICIANS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Marshall &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Egregious and criminal conduct; repeated lying;
adultery, obstruction of justice and perjury. In great detail,
these are the charges that have been lobbed against the President
of the United States in the past few days. Is it any wonder that
Americans have such a low opinion of their politicians?
</P>
<P>
   Except, it seems, they don't. Most of the evidence shows that
Americans have, over the last few years, recovered some of their
trust in politics and government, and calling someone a politician
is no longer the worst insult you can level. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Article stands in 875 words; total uncut version is 975.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-US-LOVES-RASCALS-875&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH THE PRESIDENT! (BORIS, NOT BILL) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Phil Reeves &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The president is threatened with impeachment. His
enemies believe he is guilty of high crimes (not to mention
misdemeanors), and want him thrown out of office. They regard him
with a venom that at times defies explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, he is not Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   These days all eyes are on Washington and the president's
impeachment trial. But, for the past six months, a 15-member
Russian parliamentary commission has been busy investigating
whether there are grounds to impeach Boris Yeltsin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Article stands in 575 words; total uncut version is 800.) &QL;
