<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0222 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     01-20 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CAN it be merely a coincidence that the hero of Charles Dickens'
classic novel Great Expectations, a young lad who enjoys a life of
quality and growth through the help of an unknown benefactor, is
named Pip?
</P>
<P>
   You decide.
</P>
<P>
   In the modern version, Pip, also known as Scottie Pippen, is
heading for Houston and fresh glories after his unknown benefactor
(Michael Jordan) disappeared into the mists of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you judge this week's development, for content,
drama and hairpin turns, this is one terrific story, part Dickens,
part Alfred Hitchcock. The Rockets have almost lost the capacity to
surprise us, pulling a superstar out of their hats year after year.
First, there was the Clyde Drexler trick, then the Charles Barkley
sleight of hand, and now comes Pippen, who has won six rings,
meaning enough for his shooting hand and one for his toes or nose,
if he were that kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   The expectations for the Rockets are now as high as the highest
mountain. In Houston, of course, this would be Mount Olajuwon. It
would appear that by capturing the most desirable free agent on the
market, Les Alexander has made a payment on the new
state-of-the-art arena his heart craves. Give Les credit: He isn't
afraid to pull the trigger. He is a hyperactive deal-maker who has
tried to sneak a hockey team out of Canada, flirted with the NFL,
bought an indoor football club and a women's basketball team and,
for all we know, bid on the exclusive rights to the Y2K virus.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, of course, Rockets management is as talkative as
Marcel Marceau. Until the new labor agreement with the players'
union has been signed and sealed, any discussion about another
team's talent can be construed as tampering. If the Rockets so much
as said Scottie Pippen is ``a good American,'' wham, there goes a
$100,000 fine or more.
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen issued his own news release out of Chicago, which
means this is one deal the Rockets can take to the bank. One way or
another, they already have. Scottie will average more than $13
million a year over the next five seasons. At 33, three years
younger than Hakeem Olajuwon, Pippen becomes the candidate most
likely to lead the Rockets into their new sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   How big is this acquisition? Let's go to the record books.
</P>
<P>
   He restores the Houston franchise to its full quota of NBA
legends _ three out of the 50 greatest. He has been selected seven
times to the NBA All-Star and All-Defensive teams. And he was the
second-leading tourist attraction in Chicago, clearly behind Jordan
but well ahead of the stockyards.
</P>
<P>
   He will be a superb addition to the Rockets' roster, if just to
hear him talk about Michael, whose departure from the game was
treated not like a retirement but as an abdication. Because he is
human, you expect Pippen to be motivated by a desire to prove he
can win a title without Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he has grown weary of being asked about His Airness, but
then you recall Don Larsen's reply to a reporter who wondered if he
ever got tired of answering questions about his perfect game in the
World Series. ``No,'' said Larsen. ``Why should I?''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen can't shake the connection and probably wouldn't if he
could. So he hears the references, how he played Ginger Rogers to
Jordan's Fred Astaire, Robin to Batman, Keith Richards to Mick
Jagger, Lou Gehrig to Michael's Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   But if Scottie was not Jordan's equal, neither was anyone else,
and he never fit the bill as a true sidekick. Both could play
anywhere and do everything, the difference being that Michael
sometimes did it with a smile on his face or his tongue sticking
out. They were teammates for 9{ years, and neither won a title
without the other.
</P>
<P>
   You can't recall a city ever suffering a double hit the size of
this one, although the Florida Marlins' casting off most of a
world-championship team might put Miami close. But the Fish lacked
the history of the Bulls, Michael and Scottie.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie in 1987, Pippen came out of rural Arkansas as a
small-college All-American, distant and unpolished, unsure how to
react to Jordan's constant needling. But Michael had a mission. He
needed to disprove the opinion that he was a super one-on-one
player who could not lead a team. He needed another weapon in his
quest to win a title.
</P>
<P>
   He tested Scottie and found out soon enough that he had the
right stuff. ``There are only a handful of guys,'' Jordan said,
``who understand how to be predators on defense. Scottie committed
to it from day one. That told me he was special. Very few young
guys come in with the idea of doing all the thankless stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the game the Bulls played when they were winning three
titles in a row twice. This is the game favored by Rudy
Tomjanovich. And if Pippen can help the Rockets return to the
trophy room, he won't go unthanked.
</P>
<P>
   Great expectations, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
