<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLING RISK WORTH REWARD FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure, there is more than a trace of a risk in signing a pitcher
with a 4.41 earned-run average to a three-year, $10.5 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're scoring along with the Rangers at home, get used
to it.
</P>
<P>
   The signing of Rick Helling is exactly the kind of risk _
general manager Doug Melvin might call it ``speculative investing''
_ that the Rangers appear ready to take, as they plot their course
for 1999 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, the idea is to tie up young, arbitration-eligible
players to multiyear contracts. There are risks and rewards on both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   The player gets a guaranteed payday for two, three or four
seasons. The club, on the other hand, gets to avoid a costly round
or two of unpredictable arbitration. A general manager can give his
owner at least a ballpark idea of what the upcoming seasons' base
payroll will be. ``Cost certainty,'' Melvin calls it.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians have been trying to do the same thing with
their core of young stars. The Pittsburgh Pirates, who can't afford
to be anything but small-market frugal, have followed the same
system in tying up Francisco Cordova and Jason Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signing Rick Helling is part of that way of thinking,'' Melvin
said. ``You're trying to put some of the most valuable parts of
your club together, and then hope that they can interact with your
minor-league system to give you the kind of solid ballclub you
want.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Rangers' case, catcher Ivan Rodriguez is under contract
through the 2002 season, after signing a five-year, $42 million
extension in July 1997. First baseman Rafael Palmeiro is spoken for
through 2003, thanks to the five-year free-agent contract he signed
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton is signed through 2002. Left fielder
Rusty Greer has two more years left on his deal, plus a club option
for 2001. Right fielder Juan Gonzalez is obligated through the 2000
season, though the Rangers will try to sign him to a contract
extension this spring. Closer John Wetteland is also signed through
the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many seasons ago, the Rangers just didn't do business
that way. Young players seemed to progress through annual bouts of
arbitration, where tension and sometimes animosity would take root
between management and the player's agent. As soon as the player
would reach free agency, he'd bolt.
</P>
<P>
   (See Brown, Kevin).
</P>
<P>
   The current cluster of long-term deals, however, gives Melvin a
solid nucleus to build upon. Only Palmeiro is over 30. Ideally, as
Melvin said, the rest of the puzzle would be filled in by the
club's minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   Just put the numbers in place. Second baseman Mark McLemore has
been a loyal and valuable contributor. But he has one year left on
his contract at $2.4 million, and then is a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Tom Goodwin will make $3.2 million this season
and then, he, too, is a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The two brightest, closest-to-ready prospects in the Rangers'
farm system are a center fielder (Ruben Mateo) and a soon-to-be
second baseman (Kelly Dransfeldt).
</P>
<P>
   More puzzle parts: Subtract the salaries of McLemore, Goodwin,
Roberto Kelly and Luis Alicea (both signed only through 1999), and
you have approximately $8.5 million to spend in the year 2000
toward _ what? Pitching?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some risks involved,'' Melvin concedes. ``The
players you sign long-term have to stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you really have to make sure you pick the right players.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling is Exhibit A of why the Rangers are right to take the
risk. Signing young players to contracts like his gives the team
the luxury of a wider timetable to evaluate its investment.
</P>
<P>
   With more time, again, it's easier to make the puzzle pieces
fit. Trading Dean Palmer, for instance, gave the Rangers Goodwin _
but it also bought more time for Mateo to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin is convinced that pulling the plug relatively early in
the 1997 season _ trading Palmer, Ken Hill and Ed Vosberg _ when
the club was 6 1/2 games out of first place, was a key factor in
winning the AL West title in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be another player or two on this club that we want
to do on a multi-year deal,'' Melvin said. ``If players are willing
to do it and willing to come forward, the Helling signing is
evidence that we're willing to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are risks. But there's also a new owner, and he
doesn't seem to like second place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
