<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACROIX FACES OLD FRIENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Nearly three months after being traded to
the Kings by his father, left wing Eric Lacroix played Tuesday
night for the first time against his former team, the Colorado
Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   In October, with Colorado off to a poor start, there were
murmurs from a portion of the Denver media that Eric Lacroix was on
the Avalanche roster only because his father, Pierre, is the team's
general manager. Notably, a column in the Denver Post ran under the
headline, ``It's time for total eclipse of this son.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Lacroix was traded soon thereafter, and when the Kings next
faced the Avalanche, earlier this month, he was unable to play
because of an injury. He was understandably on edge before
Tuesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you play against your old team for the first time,
it's a weird feeling,'' said Lacroix, who began play Tuesday with
no points in 29 games this season but recorded an assist on Garry
Galley's first-period goal. ``I'm very nervous. It helps that it's
been awhile. It would have been tougher if I had to play them right
away (after the trade).''
</P>
<P>
   As for his feelings toward his former teammates, he said: ``I
didn't leave behind 25 enemies. I left behind 25 friends.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Pierre Lacroix said he has put the difficult
situation behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much happened other than it became a distraction,'' he
said. ``Everyone on the team was clear that Eric Lacroix had done
nothing wrong. It was just the fact that he was the son of the
general manager that made it difficult for some not on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he regretted trading for his son in the first place _
the Kings originally had dealt Lacroix to Colorado in 1996 for
goalie Stephane Fiset _ Pierre Lacroix said: ``I never go back on a
decision. I'm a guy who goes very deep in reflection when I make a
decision. When we traded for him, we did it for the right hockey
reasons. When we acquired him, I voted against him as a dad. And
the others said to me, `You can't vote as a dad. You have to do it
for the good of the team.'''
</P>
<P>
   Courtnall returns: After missing two months with a broken ankle,
winger Russ Courtnall returned to the lineup, in a different role
from the one he had when he was injured during a loss at San Jose
on Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   When he was injured, he was on a checking line. Tuesday night,
he began the game on a line with Olli Jokinen and Luc Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different role than I've had since I was here,'' said
Courtnall, who signed with the Kings as a free agent early last
season. ``I'm looking at it as a great opportunity. There's an
offensive opportunity there that hasn't been there since I've been
here. When I came here, (coach) Larry (Robinson) put me in a
checking role, and I tried to take that opportunity and do the best
I could at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Colorado defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh played in just
his fourth game this season and his first against the Kings. He
spent the first three months of the season in a contract dispute
with Colorado before signing a two-year deal worth $6.7 million....
Winger Craig Johnson skated Tuesday morning, but his upper-body
movement clearly was restricted by the pain from the separated rib
cartilage that has sidelined him on a week-to-week basis....
Defenseman Steve Duchesne played after missing one game because of
back spasms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
