r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-CEBALLO     01-20 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-CEBALLOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENT SAYS MAVERICKS' OFFER TO CEBALLOS IS INSULTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The agent for free-agent forward Cedric Ceballos
accused the Mavericks of low-balling his client and not negotiating
in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Slaughter said the Mavericks offered Ceballos a
take-it-or-leave-it three-year deal for about $6 million. He said
that none of the years equalled the $2.5 million Ceballos made last
season and that he felt the 6-foot-7, eight-year veteran deserved
better treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have thought Cedric is a dog as a player,''
Slaughter said. ``They figured the man would come running to
anything they offered. It just doesn't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cedric was a great performer for Dallas, and they're asking
him to take a pay cut? You expect them to at least offer him what
he made last year. But ... they decided to be stingy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson said he made a fair
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more than fair,'' Nelson said. ``But I really don't
think a guy should ever sign a contract that he's not happy with.
So if Ced's not happy with what we offered, I'm glad he didn't
agree to it, and he shouldn't agree to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson and Slaughter left the door open for Ceballos to change
his mind and accept the offer.
THOMAS ON BOARD
</P>
<P>
   Former TCU standout Kurt Thomas agreed to a one-year, $1 million
deal to play for the Mavericks this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said from the beginning that I wanted to be here in
Dallas,'' Thomas said. ``I've got a one-year deal on the table, and
then when this season is over hopefully they'll offer me a
long-term deal, and then I won't ever have to leave Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries limited Thomas to 23 games the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to show that I'm healthy,'' Thomas said. ``I know I'm
healthy.'' Bradley trade? Nelson first laughed out loud, then
denied a rumor that the Mavericks were about to trade center Shawn
Bradley to the Charlotte Hornets for all-star guard Glen Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I love Shawn, I'd probably have to do that one,''
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked again if there was anything to the rumor, Nelson laughed
out loud again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you tell by my response?'' he said. ``If that's true,
consider it done from this side. I haven't heard of that one.''
WALKER SWITCHES AGAIN
After switching agents over the weekend, Mavericks forward Samaki
Walker apparently has had a change of heart and switched back.
Walker returned to former Los Angeles Lakers guard Norm Nixon
instead of switching to Dallas-based agent Randy Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame myself for making the change before, and I'm man
enough to admit it,'' Walker said. ``You can't have pressures in
this league get to you and allow you to make immature mistakes. I
thought I did that, and I'm back with Norm. I think I need to give
him a fair chance to get the job done.''
BRIEFLY
Mavericks guard Khalid Reeves has changed agents from Slaughter to
Dwight Manley, who represents Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie guard Greg Buckner (6-4, 210) has been added to the
Mavericks' training camp roster. Dallas drafted Buckner in the
second round (53rd overall). He averaged 16.3 points per game for
Clemson last season.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he's trying to work out a deal for second-round
draft pick Ansu Sesay to play in Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
