r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     01-20 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE MUST WIN STADIUM FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The neighbors who oppose construction of a new Cal State
Northridge football stadium near the site of the old one _
precisely 75 yards to the south of the old one _ want to tell you
it's not Northridge football they oppose.
</P>
<P>
   They also want to tell you they have no ax to grind against the
university.
</P>
<P>
   They also want to tell you they are not weirdos or political
activists but everyday homeowners _ as Linda Tripp might put it _
just like you.
</P>
<P>
   One of their leaders, Pat LoPresti, is a soccer mom ``and a
softball mom and a baseball mom'' who's also a homegrown Green Bay
Packers fan. That's how much she likes sports.
</P>
<P>
   If Northridge played its football games on the Pierce College
field in Woodland Hills as she'd prefer, LoPresti said from her
house in Northridge, ``I'd coordinate the bus trips.''
</P>
<P>
   LoPresti also has a husband, a son and a daughter, a dog and
three turtles, and one of the turtles is missing but certain to
turn up. That's how normal she is.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is great except for the stuff in the first
paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   Because no matter how it's dressed up, a vote against a new
stadium, in the area between Zelzah and Lindley avenues known as
North Campus, is a vote against Northridge football.
</P>
<P>
   If Matadors football is ever going to be more than it is, it's
not going to do it in the little box of splinters known as North
Campus Stadium, which is below Big Sky Conference standards and
scheduled to be razed after next season anyway to make way for a
biotech facility. It's going to do it in a stadium that will
impress recruits, sponsors and fans.
</P>
<P>
   Even a spruced-up Pierce College stadium, a hundred stoplights
away, is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, it is not expected to come to that when the
committee assigned to choose the best possible place for the
Matadors' new field holds its ninth _ and final scheduled _ public
hearing Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is expected to brush aside the Pierce proposal and
vote to recommend a stadium be built on North Campus just north of
Lassen Street, a modest little 8,000- to 9,000-seat number with the
flexibility to grow to 15,000 or so.
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote, though, half an hour of public discussion is
scheduled, giving the leaders of local homeowners' organizations
one last chance to vent their anger and fears about this addition
to the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In those 30 minutes, starting at 6:30 p.m. in the Grand Salon of
the university's student union, we're likely to hear more passion
than the Northridge football program has stirred up in the past 37
years. Hey, any excitement should be considered progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to give up,'' said Bob Buckles, who has lived
in the neighborhood for 40 years and whose children are Northridge
graduates. ``I love football. I watch it constantly. I go to games
when I can. (But) I am also a resident and I don't want my peace
and quiet disturbed _ mightily.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckles and others in the anti-stadium movement _ which claims
membership in the low thousands _ charge that university
administrators really have their eyes on the revenue a stadium
could generate with non-athletic events.
</P>
<P>
   They say the Fourth of July celebrations in North Campus Stadium
are bad enough, what with the noise and the clogged driveways and
the littered front lawns. Imagine the carnage when the rock
concerts let out!
</P>
<P>
   ``The university (used to be) a plus because there was some open
space with corn fields,'' said LoPresti, who moved into the
neighborhood 12 years ago with her husband Bob, a former Northridge
baseball player who is one of two confirmed stadium opponents on
the site committee. ``We ran with the dog, we flew kites. Now there
are dorms there.''
</P>
<P>
   The ever-changing face of the campus, and the ever-changing
plans for further construction, have led the neighbors to distrust
the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen an absolute litany of promises the university has
made and broken,'' Buckles said. ``I've seen, I think, 14 master
plans. I've lost count.''
</P>
<P>
   And the opponents are dubious of future promises, like the site
committee's recommendation that a panel including neighbors be set
up to approve or disapprove non-athletic events for the new
stadium. They claim this committee is stacked and that one would be
too.
</P>
<P>
   All of which David Honda, chairman of the site committee, refers
to as ``paranoia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of it has been stirred up by the homeowner
groups (that) really haven't explained to their constituents that
this isn't a stadium, it's a football field,'' Honda said. ``I've
had homeowners call me up and say, `I don't want the Rose Bowl in
my backyard.' This isn't going to be the Rose Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling them paranoid might not be the way to win over the
stadium opponents. If trust is an issue, the administration would
be better off taking steps to restore it. Why not surprise the
homeowners, and actually give them a meaningful say in the
stadium's use?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the stadium will be built whether or not the
neighbors like it, unless they pull a rabbit out of a lawyer's hat.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the site committee will have done its narrowly-defined
job by picking the best possible place for the football team to
play. It's an all-too-rare case of mission accomplished for an arm
of the Northridge athletic program.
</P>
<P>
   After this, the next excitement Northridge football creates
could have a little more to do with football. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 0123EST &QL; 
