u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PROFILE-MICONE-SUP     01-20 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PROFILE-MICONE-SUPERBOWL-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS FULL-TIME MISSION IS THE SUPER BOWL HALFTIME
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.J., Fla., Texas, Pa., Ill.)  (Editors: Word in boldface should be set in italics.) 
(fb) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ed Micone, the fellow at Radio City Entertainment who oversees
the Super Bowl halftime show and brings in the big-name talent
(harder than you might think, because what the halftime talent is
paid for the Super Bowl is nothing), is a charming, fun-loving guy.
</P>
<P>
   He's got breakfast waiting when you arrive (he normally doesn't
eat breakfast, Micone says, but maybe the visitors do), and a gag
picture of himself _ and we are talking the top executive at Radio
City Entertainment, here _ dressed up as a Rockette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be comfortable,'' Micone, 49, says at his offices upstairs at
Radio City Music Hall. ``Make believe this is your house'' _ though
who has a house with autographed pictures of Whitney Houston and
Robin Williams and Liza Minnelli on the walls?
</P>
<P>
   Thus it is somewhat painful, after the requisite discussion of
the halftime stars at this year's Super Bowl game Jan. 31 in Miami
(Stevie Wonder, Gloria Estefan and Big Bad Voodoo Daddy), the cost
of producing said halftime show ($3 million) and Micone's track
record (Radio City Entertainment has been involved with six Super
Bowl games) to bring up the sorry matter of the reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Super Bowl, the more money that's spent, the worse it
gets,'' read a 1997 report in The Dallas Morning News. (``We didn't
produce that one,'' Micone says. ``We brought in the talent.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``If they put all of these moments on one video collection,
you'd have one awful video,'' The Chicago Sun-Times said the same
year. (``Who writes these?'' Micone says, equal parts wounded and
amused.)
</P>
<P>
   And, from The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, regarding the '96 show
starring Diana Ross, who was airlifted off the stage at act's end
in a helicopter: ``Why do stars agree to step into the Super Bowl,
anyway, when it's as hopeless a setup as the entertainment world
offers?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they like it,'' Micone says. ``Diana Ross, she loved
it. It's a huge event _ we have maybe 800 million viewers. It's a
charitable event _ the sponsor gives $100,000 to the artist's
favorite charity. It's fun. Did you see the show with Diana Ross
going up in that helicopter? She wasn't sitting way in the back.
She was right at the edge. Where did you say this was from?
Pittsburgh. I'm not so worried.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who consider the halftime shows at the Super
Bowl intermission as the time to go to the bathroom or get a beer.
</P>
<P>
   It is the mission of Ed Micone to keep them in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   A former International Creative Management agent who was brought
into what was then Radio City Productions 10 years ago to beef up
concert events, Micone first snagged the National Football League
as a client in 1994, when he recruited Michael Jackson for the
halftime show. Today Micone is executive vice president and
executive producer of Radio City Entertainment, which oversees all
concerts and events at Madison Square Garden, Radio City Music Hall
and a number of big-site sports productions. Credited with bringing
big-name entertainers to the Music Hall, he has doubled the concert
revenue in the last 10 years. When Micone attended a Rangers game
recently, his name was flashed in lights.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   `` 'Cause I'm  &UR; big &LR; ,'' Micone says, laughing at himself. `` Man,
that's what my wife calls me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The son of a dentist in Summit, N.J., Micone was hooked on music
from the time he saw the Beatles on Ed Sullivan when he was 13. He
was a drummer in his own band by the eighth grade. He also
negotiated beautifully for his band: got each member $5 an hour, he
says proudly, with a 10-minute break. At C.W. Post College, Micone
did even better. He booked the band that played the Fillmore East,
in Manhattan, before or after their weekend concerts, at a
much-reduced rate. The Beach Boys played C.W. Post five times.
Micone made money for the college and left school with a career.
</P>
<P>
   At age 26, he married Cheryl Graham, from the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very independent,'' Micone says. ``Before I asked her
to marry me I said, `Imagine this: It's a Friday night, we have
eight people coming over for dinner and I call up and say: ``Hi,
honey. It's Ed. I'm going up to Montreal to see Gordon Lightfoot''
_ he was a client then _ ``I'll be home Sunday.'' I'd love the
response to be: ``Fine, have a good weekend, see you Monday. No
problem.'' '
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `No problem.' I said, `Then we should get married.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Micone negotiated his marriage proposal? ``Probably.''
</P>
<P>
   The Micones have now been married 22 years and have a daughter,
Devon, 15, and a son, Graham, 19. They live in Annandale, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   His salary, Micone does not wish to reveal. What he wants to
share, very much, is the oversize Radio City Entertainment Guest
Book he has started. Down on the floor, excited as a kid with his
autograph collection, sits Micone, flipping through pages signed by
Rosie O'Donnell and Elton John and Adam Sandler and President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this awesome?'' Micone asks. ``Pretty cool, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   He stops at a note from John McColgan, the director of the
Riverdance troupe, whom Micone brought to Radio City.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The best eight days of my life,'' ' Micone reads. ``That's
what I do for a living. That's how I want people to leave. Saying,
`That was the best time of my life.'' '
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
