u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-SENATORS-     01-20 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-SENATORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LOSE AGAIN, BUT SHOW SIGNS OF LIFE
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In losing their third consecutive game Tuesday night,
the Rangers probably played better than they have in some of their
17 victories. Although the Ottawa Senators took a 2-1 decision at
Madison Square Garden, the Rangers had a dozen good scoring chances
and competed well against a young, strong team that has chewed up
most of its opponents in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the night, it was a match of tactics and strategy,
and the patient Senators got the big break, midway through the
third period, when they scored the winning goal. The home customers
booed the Rangers in the final minutes, proof that a sophisticated
city is not necessarily full of sophisticated fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the passion tonight was very good,'' Rangers Coach
John Muckler said. ``I thought we worked hard. We got some very
good chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat dropped the Rangers three games below the .500 mark.
Their longest losing streak is four games, at the beginning of the
schedule. The Rangers play Florida at home Thursday night in their
final appearance before the All-Star Game break.
</P>
<P>
   Not participating for a change in the midseason classic is Brian
Leetch, the Ranger captain and attacking defenseman. Leetch has no
goals in his last 18 games. He has six for the season. But Leetch
had many effective shifts Tuesday night and put several shots
toward the net. He played like a man about to break out of a
scoring drought. Typical of his frustration was a play in the final
minute. Trying to pass the puck up ice for a final rush, Leetch
lost control when his stick snapped in half.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch said the stick may have been cracked on the face-off,
just before he got the puck. ``It just broke in my hands,'' said
Leetch, who had four shots on goal. Muckler had said minutes before
that many Rangers are ``squeezing their sticks right now,'' a
hockey expression indicating tension during a scoring slump.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch added, ``We've got to score more than that to win hockey
games.'' The Rangers (17-20-7) have two goals in their last three
games.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky of the Rangers played despite what appeared to be
a stiff and sore neck. Between shifts, while sitting on the bench,
Gretzky took his helmet off and applied a heating pad. In the third
period, Janne Laukkanen of Ottawa poked the puck from Gretzky's
stick at the Senators' blue line and then flattened the Great One
with an unpenalized cross-check to the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spasms in my neck,'' Gretzky said. ``I'm trying to find
out from the doctor what is wrong. Nobody seems to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senators took a 2-1 lead at 9 minutes 43 seconds of the
third period on a goal by Radek Bonk, who stood in front of Mike
Richter's net and directed upward a pass from Andreas Dackell.
Turning over the puck as he tried to skate out of the zone was
Rangers defenseman Peter Popovic, who was bothered by the
unpenalized hook of Magnus Arvedson.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers took a 1-0 lead on a first-period power-play goal,
their first with the manpower advantage in four games. The Senators
tied it at even strength later in the period, and the second period
was scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring for the Rangers, at 7:56, was John MacLean, his 16th
goal of the season. He put a rebound past Ottawa goalie Ron
Tugnutt, who had stopped a back-handed shot by Adam Graves. Setting
it up with a pass from behind the Ottawa net was Gretzky, who got
the other assist.
</P>
<P>
   After another Rangers power play, Ottawa countered and scored at
15:10. Bruce Gardiner got credit after his pass across the slot was
accidentally deflected by Leetch. The Rangers on the ice may have
been tired from setting up plays at the other end of the ice. A
young team of strong skaters, the Senators play a disciplined style
under the coaching of Jacques Martin. They often wait back in the
neutral-zone trap and take advantage of turnovers with
counter-rushes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators' captain and best player is Aleksei Yashin, who set
up the tying score by carrying the puck up ice and fighting off a
check before passing to Gardiner. Yashin came into the game with 20
goals and 31 assists for a team-best 51 points. In the plus/minus
ratio, he led the Senators with a plus-19.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Yashin and Pavel Bure led the Russian Olympic team
to a silver medal in Nagano, Japan. A large player at 6 feet 3
inches and 228 pounds, Yashin plays with an unusual combination of
size, grace and power, which might remind fans of a certain age of
Jean Beliveau, the Montreal Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   Yashin had five shots on goal Tuesday night, most of any player.
``We've worked hard at our skill level and our work level,'' Yashin
said of the Senators (24-14-6), who are 9-1-3 in their last 13
games. ``A lot of teams respect us very much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senators, an expansion team in 1992-93, struggled in their
first few seasons. With patience and high draft choices, they have
now built a contender. Even their uniforms have improved. On
Tuesday night, they wore their alternate ``third'' jerseys, mostly
red with a diagonal black sash across the middle with a gold
centurion head on the front. Except for the classic logos and
uniforms of the Old Six teams, this is one of the best-looking
National Hockey League outfits. The team has asked the league to
wear these uniforms regularly next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
