<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIAN-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEWITT, TEEN-AGE WILD CARD, UPSETS PIOLINE
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tennis is on the rise in Australia, as the record crowds
coursing through the turnstiles confirm. And the way Lleyton
Hewitt, a 17-year-old wild card, played Tuesday night in upsetting
13th-seeded Cedric Pioline, 6-3, 6-1, 6-1, in the first round of
the Australian Open, will do nothing but increase the enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   With his baggy clothes, slight frame and clearing complexion,
Hewitt looks more like a young man who belongs on a skateboard than
on Center Court at a Grand Slam event. But anyone who watched his
perfectly disguised lobs and bold passing shots and returns against
Pioline could see that the teen-ager was in his element and
flirting with that state of grace tennis players call ``the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt defeated Patrick Rafter, a countryman, last week in
Sydney, and last year he became the youngest player in 10 years to
win an ATP event, defeating Andre Agassi along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Though he struggled for much of last season, he reached the
final again in Adelaide two weeks ago and the quarterfinals in
Sydney. Now, in Melbourne, he has his first victory in a Grand Slam
event, and it came against a player who has already reached two
Grand Slam finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously a guy who feeds off the home crowd,'' Pioline
said. ``I think he did just about everything he wanted to do out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other seeded men's players were also beaten Tuesday. The
first to fall was No. 12 Albert Costa, beaten by Martin Damm of the
Czech Republic in five sets. The second to fall made more noise in
Melbourne: It was No. 4 Carlos Moya, who was beaten by Nicolas
Kiefer of Germany in four sets.
</P>
<P>
   Moya was still recovering from a virus he caught in the first
week of January in Perth that kept him in bed for several days. He
made numerous errors, failed to capitalize on Kiefer's short shots
and generally bore little resemblance to the player who won last
year's French Open and reached the semifinals of the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, seeded fifth, sent a message to the field, overwhelming
the potentially dangerous Hernan Gumy of Argentina, 6-0, 6-3, 6-0.
No. 2 Martina Hingis, No. 5 Monica Seles and No. 10 Steffi Graf
advanced with ease in the women's event.
</P>
<P>
   No. 12 Anna Kournikova also won, but it was anything but easy.
She served 17 double faults in the opening set of her match with an
American, Jill Craybas, and finished with 23 double faults, losing
her serve eight times in 13 attempts. The remarkable thing was that
she still won, 7-6 (7-1), 7-5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 0137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
