</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CLAM-BOAT-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAM BOAT AND CREW OF 4 DISAPPEAR OFF NEW JERSEY
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POINT PLEASANT BEACH, N.J. _ For the second time in less than
two weeks, a commercial clamming boat has vanished in the surging
Atlantic Ocean off New Jersey, this time leaving only a large oil
slick, a few pieces of debris and no sign of her four crew members.
</P>
<P>
   The 74-foot vessel, the Adriatic, apparently went down on Monday
afternoon amid high winds and heavy seas shortly after the crew was
able to send a garbled Mayday call that gave no indication of her
location. And after nearly 24 hours of searching, the Coast Guard
on Tuesday evening reported finding only a life ring, an empty
survival suit, some buckets, pots, cups and a first-aid kit.
</P>
<P>
   In midafternoon Tuesday, the Coast Guard sent divers into 60
feet of water about eight miles southeast of Barnegat Light, but
the divers found no sunken debris, said Lt. John Brenner, a
spokesman at the Coast Guard's station in Atlantic City. He said
two cutters and a helicopter would continue searching overnight
from the shoreline to 14 miles out into the Atlantic. But he held
out little hope of finding the crew.
</P>
<P>
   The sinking of the Adriatic was yet another sobering blow to the
men along the commercial fishing docks on Channel Drive in this
small town that is at once a fishing village and oceanfront
playground. In the last two weeks, two other commercial clammers
have been lost in the Atlantic, and another was wrecked on a jetty.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 6, the Beth Dee Bob sank off the coast of Manasquan,
with the loss of her four crew members. On Jan. 8, the Cape Fear,
which left Point Pleasant Beach several months ago to clam off New
England, sank off New Bedford, Mass. Two crew members were lost.
</P>
<P>
   And on Sunday, a day before the Adriatic vanished, the Ellie B,
a 65-foot Rhode Island boat using Point Pleasant Beach's wharves
temporarily, struck one of the rock jetties at the mouth of the
Manasquan Inlet, just north of here, and broke up. Her three crew
members jumped overboard and were saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's devastating to think they're just gone, just gone,'' said
Jim Parascandolo, who regularly fished the Atlantic for whiting and
squid until he started raising his family 19 years ago. ``Everyone
has a shiver today.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Adriatic apparently vanished about 3 p.m. on Monday after
sending an unintelligible distress call, the Coast Guard said. The
only words that Coast Guard radio operators could make out were
``Mayday, Mayday,'' Brenner said. Operators could not understand
the ship's name in the distress call, he said, and since no
location was given, no search could be started.
</P>
<P>
   Radio operators, he said, called for a repeat of the distress
call and asked ships off New Jersey if they had heard it. Neither
request brought any new information.
</P>
<P>
   At about 8 p.m., he said, the Coast Guard got a call from
officials at Barney's Dock in Atlantic City saying that the
Adriatic had been scheduled to dock there at 7 p.m. and was an hour
late.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard started to search immediately and found the
slick and the bits of debris two hours later, Brenner said.
</P>
<P>
   At about the time the Adriatic called in the Mayday, the
Atlantic was stormy. The National Weather Service said Tuesday that
its forecast for the Atlantic for midafternoon Monday was for
southerly winds of 25 to 30 knots, with seas of 5 to 7 feet. At
about 5 p.m., two hours after the distress call, the Weather
Service said it issued a special marine warning, advising ships of
winds above 34 knots and increasing waves.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Cohen, owner of Point Pleasant Packing, a wholesale
company here that used to buy the Adriatic's clams, said
speculating about the Adriatic's problems was futile. Commercial
fishing, he said, is one of the nation's riskiest occupations. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The fact we've had four accidents in 13 days doesn't mean
it's getting riskier,'' Cohen said. ``The risk doesn't get more or
less.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
