<HEADLINE>
SLAYING OF WITNESS WAS COINCIDENCE, PROSECUTOR SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETH, N.J. _ Calling the occurrence ``purely
coincidental,'' the Union County prosecutor said Tuesday that a man
who was shot to death over the weekend, just two days before the
opening of a murder trial in which he was to testify as an
eyewitness, had not been killed to prevent his testimony but had
instead fallen victim to his own involvement with drugs and guns.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the prosecutor, Thomas V. Manahan, came just
moments after an assistant prosecutor asked a judge in Union County
Superior Court to postpone the case, saying the ``execution'' of a
key state witness had left other witnesses terrified. He pleaded
with the judge to give investigators two weeks to solve the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Edwin R. Alley, denied the request for an
adjournment, siding instead with lawyers for the three defendants
in the case who argued for their clients' right to a speedy trial.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, investigators did not need two weeks. Minutes
after the judge's ruling, at a news conference across the street in
which Manahan was expected to comment on the ruling, he announced
that the death of the witness was not related to the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are saying that it was purely coincidental,'' Manahan said.
``An unfortunate tragedy that sometimes occurs when people who are
involved in the illicit drug trade and guns get caught up with
matters that sometimes result in the termination of their life.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Manahan said that the witness, Dylan George, had a criminal
record involving drug and weapons charges, but he would not discuss
the evidence that led investigators to conclude that the shooting
and the trial were unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   George, 29, was found fatally shot on Sunday in a parked car in
Plainfield, officials said. An acquaintance of George, Michelle
Milligan, 14, who had been sitting in the passenger seat of the
car, was also shot. She remained unconscious and in critical
condition Monday at Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital in New
Brunswick and has been unable to speak to investigators. Officials
expressed the belief that George, not Ms. Milligan, was the target
of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   George had been scheduled to testify against Tanny Miller and
Bobby Clayton, who are charged with murder in connection with the
fatal shooting of a Plainfield man in 1996 during a robbery. A
third defendant, Leroy Golden, faces armed robbery and weapons
charges in the same case. All three men have been in prison
awaiting trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
