r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT     01-20 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FADING FAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ It was only a few days ago that the Kings seemed in
prime position to make a strong run for a playoff berth in the
second half of the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   But as they awaken today, with one game remaining before the
All-Star break and 38 to go in the season, the Kings' hopes once
again are fading.
</P>
<P>
   The latest setback was a 5-4 loss to the Colorado Avalanche on
Tuesday night before an announced crowd of 9,692 at the Forum, a
defeat in which Kings goalie Stephane Fiset struggled against his
former teammates. A Donald Audette goal with 12 seconds to play
made the final score deceptively close.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Kings (16-24-4) to 1-3-1 in their last five
games and left them five points behind San Jose and St. Louis in
the race for the final two Western Conference playoff berths. Joe
Sakic scored twice for Colorado (21-19-4), which had been 1-5-1 in
its last seven visits to the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The only good news for the Kings was that Eric Lacroix recorded
his first point this season and Russ Courtnall had a goal and an
assist in his first game in two months after recovering from a
broken ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix, playing against Colorado for the first time since he
was traded to the Kings early in the season, assisted on a Garry
Galley goal 5:58 into the game that gave the Kings a 1-0 lead. It
was the first point for Lacroix in 30 games this season and his
first in 41 games dating to last season. Lacroix hasn't scored a
goal in 42 games dating to last season.
</P>
<P>
   The lead lasted less than seven minutes, erased by Sakic's first
goal, a rising shot from the right circle that went between the
legs of defenseman Doug Bodger and over Fiset's glove at 12:16.
</P>
<P>
   Ten seconds later, Shean Donovan redirected a shot from the left
point by Chris Drury past Fiset, giving the Avalanche the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second period, Courtnall partially fanned on a shot
from the slot. The shot fooled Colorado goalie Patrick Roy, the
puck skittering over his right shoulder and into the net at 3:16,
tying the score, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   But 4:30 later, Sakic blasted an unscreened slap shot from the
left circle between Fiset's pads, and Stephane Yelle scored in
similar fashion three minutes after that when the Kings got caught
deep in the offensive zone and allowed a 3-on-1 rush.
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes into the third period, the Kings had a chance to
cut the deficit to 4-3, but Roy stopped Courtnall on a breakaway,
and about a minute after that, Valeri Kamensky scored on a
breakaway of his own, making it 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille scored his 25th goal this season and the 503rd of
his career with 13 minutes to play, bringing the Kings to within
5-3. Audette scored on a power play and with Fiset off for an extra
skater with 12.8 seconds left, accounting for the Kings' final
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, the ominous upcoming schedule doesn't hold
a great deal of promise as far as getting back in the playoff race
is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Next up for the Kings are the New Jersey Devils, who are nine
games above .500 and visit the Forum on Thursday. Then, after
Sunday's All-Star Game in Tampa, the Kings hit the road for games
against Dallas, Washington, Buffalo and Philadelphia, four teams
that are a collective 36 games above .500.
</P>
<P>
   After those games, the Kings will have just 33 to play, and will
have to consider themselves fortunate if they aren't any further
behind in the standings than they are today.
</P>
<P>
   They will have to find some scoring, too.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Kings are mired in notable goal-scoring droughts.
Among the forwards, Pavel Rosa has one in 14, Yanic Perreault has
none in six and four in 37, Jozef Stumpel has one in seven, Olli
Jokinen has none in eight and one in 21, and Vladimir Tsyplakov has
none in 10.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Kings' defensemen, they've scored a combined 10 goals
this season _ one fewer than St. Louis' Al MacInnis and Vancouver's
Adrian Aucoin have all by themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
