<HEADLINE>
N.Y. MAYOR DISTANCES HIMSELF FROM LOBBYIST MARRIED TO HIS AIDE 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS for story slugged NY-PARKING on master sked.) 
 (fb) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani said Tuesday that his
administration would stop doing business with a lobbyist who is
married to one of his top aides, though he said the lobbyist had
not persuaded the city to grant special parking privileges to a
major Wall Street firm.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after the Daily News reported on Tuesday
that the city had granted the privileges to Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
after the firm hired Suri Kasirer as a lobbyist. Kasirer is married
to Bruce Teitelbaum, who spent more than two years as the mayor's
chief of staff and now runs Solutions America, a political action
committee formed by the mayor last spring to raise money for
travel, political seminars and potential campaigns for higher
office.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Tuesday that he alone had negotiated the parking
arrangement, which allows limousines picking up employees of
Goldman, Sachs to idle in zones where parking is otherwise
prohibited. The mayor said that Jon Corzine, the former chief
executive of Goldman, Sachs, had proposed the arrangement during a
breakfast meeting they had last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need a lobbyist to deal with this administration,''
Giuliani said. ``Goldman, Sachs alone, I think, pays 20 to 25
percent of the remaining unincorporated business tax in this city.
So we want to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasirer refused to comment on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
