<SLUG> BC-CONN-OFFICER-CHARGED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT OFFICER IS CHARGED WITH MURDER
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A police officer in New Milford, Conn., turned himself in to
State Police on Tuesday after being charged with murder in the
shooting death of an unarmed suspect last month.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Scott B. Smith, 27, is charged with killing
Franklyn Reid, also 27 and from New Milford, about 11 a.m. on Dec.
29.
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators with the state Attorney's Office in
Waterbury, Smith used excessive force and shot Reid in the back,
just below the neck, while he was on his knees after a foot chase.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators' report, which was released on Monday, said
that Reid suffered a contact wound, indicating that the gun was
pressed against his back, ``or close to it,'' State Attorney John
A. Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, a felon with a record that included convictions for
assault and sexual assault, was wanted on charges including
violating probation, six counts of telephone harassment and three
charges of failure to appear in court.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and his partner, David Shortt, were backing up another
officer who had been pursuing Reid when they spotted the suspect at
a New Milford gas station. Reid ran away and Smith chased him on
foot.
</P>
<P>
   Smith told investigators that after he caught Reid and forced
him to his knees, he did not see the suspect's hands, and that Reid
made a quick move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed at the time he was either going to shoot me or stab
me,'' he said. ``Out of fear for my life at that instant, I
discharged my weapon one time, striking Mr. Reid.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who has been on the police force in New Milford for about
two years, was released on $250,000 bond after being arraigned in
Superior Court in Bantam, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly said he believed that Smith was the first Connecticut
police officer charged with murder for a killing that occurred
while on duty. If convicted, he would receive a mandatory sentence
of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's lawyer, Thomas J. Allingham, said his client would hold
a news conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is also the target of a civil rights wrongful death
lawsuit filed last week in U.S. District Court in Bridgeport by
Reid's family. The lawyer for the family, Richard Bieder, did not
return a telephone call Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting has raised questions of racial bias, since Reid was
black and Smith is white. New Milford has a population of about
27,000, and less than 1 percent, about 200 people, are black.
Neither Mayor Art Pietler nor James D. Sweeney, chief of the
42-member Police Department, returned calls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Allingham said, ``Race didn't have anything to do with this
event.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
