<SLUG> BC-GOTTI-TRIAL-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS SEEK TO PUT GOTTI ON TRIAL TWICE
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Almost a year to the day that John A. Gotti
was indicted on racketeering charges and accused of being the
acting head of the Gambino crime family, federal prosecutors asked
a judge on Tuesday to allow them to try Gotti twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want as much blood as they can get,'' said Gotti, 34,
shaking his head as he left a hearing at the U.S. Court for the
Southern District here on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have asked Judge Barrington D. Parker Jr. to allow
them to try Gotti along with two other men, Salvatore Locascio and
Vincent Zollo. All three are accused of extortion, loan sharking
and fraud. That case is expected to last about two months.
</P>
<P>
   Then the government would like to put Gotti, the son of John J.
Gotti, the imprisoned Gambino crime family boss, on trial again _
this time along with three other defendants on more limited charges
of selling phony prepaid telephone calling cards. That case could
also last two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Gotti links the various crimes together, this
commonality _ now limited to one defendant _ does not negate the
fact that the other five defendants will ultimately sit through
substantial portions of the trial unnecessarily,'' Carol L.
Sipperly, the assistant U.S. attorney in charge of the case, wrote
in a letter to the judge last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti's lawyers objected to the strategy, noting that the case
was now far simpler than it was when it started last Jan. 21, when
23 people were indicted en masse and lawyers and defendants had to
be spread out over several courtrooms just to find enough seats.
</P>
<P>
   Now, most other defendants have pleaded guilty and there are
only six men left, with far less evidence required. And so, said
Sarita Kedia, one of the defense lawyers, they can easily be
prosecuted together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gotti shouldn't have to endure two trials,'' Ms. Kedia
said. ``We want one trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The government should either try the six men together, Ms. Kedia
said, or allow the evidence regarding Gotti's alleged involvement
in the calling card scam to be presented during his racketeering
trial. The three other defendants in the telephone card case,
including Denny McLain, a former pitcher for the Detroit Tigers,
could be tried separately, she said. Parker said he would rule on
the issue next week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Prosecutors were unsuccessful in two attempts Tuesday to
restrict Gotti's actions. They sought to have Gotti's bail revoked
because of an incident in November when he strayed farther on his
property than is allowed _ later saying he was playing soccer _ and
was out of range of electronic monitoring for 20 minutes. The judge
refused the request.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also unsuccessfully objected Tuesday to allowing
Gotti to meet with any of his former co-defendants, saying he had
too much influence over them. Ms. Sipperly said that on Jan. 12,
just before Gregory DePalma, 66, and his son Craig, 32, pleaded
guilty to racketeering charges, they met with Gotti and his lawyer
for a jail house interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gotti was directing the DePalmas' plea,'' Ms. Sipperly
said. ``He had a 15-minute visit on Jan. 12 with the DePalmas to
tell them not to implicate him. It was exactly what Mr. Gotti was
taking care of that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kedia called the government's scenario ridiculous. She said
that Gotti did not know the DePalmas were preparing to plead guilty
that day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
