<SLUG> BC-NY-SPECIAL-ED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFERRALS TO SPECIAL EDUCATION FALL IN NYC
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first time since 1990, New York City schools
have cut down on the number of children they are referring for
evaluations to determine whether they should be placed in special
education, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew
announced Tuesday. They attributed the decline to improvements in
educational programs.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing one of the thorniest problems the schools face _ one
with racial as well as educational dimensions _ the mayor and the
chancellor said that referrals since September were down 25
percent, or about 3,800 children, from the same period a year ago.
At a joint news conference at City Hall, they said the decline
resulted from new procedures to identify students with learning
problems and give them the help they need outside the context of
special education.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said that Crew, supported by the mayor, was simply
trying to crack down on referrals to special education. The city
has been under pressure from the Office of Civil Rights in the
federal Education Department to stem what federal officials say are
disproportionate referrals of black and Hispanic students into
special education; in June, a mayoral task force called for
policies leading to fewer referrals.
</P>
<P>
   Special education classes are supposed to help children with
learning or behavior problems, but usually end up as pathways to
academic failure, with few children ever returning to regular
classes or receiving a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Randi Weingarten, president of the United Federation of
Teachers, said Tuesday that some school districts had responded to
the mayor's task force by trying to impose an outright ban on
referrals, regardless of whether children were receiving the help
they needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There clearly has been a re-evaluation of how to do
referrals,'' Ms. Weingarten said. ``And that's clearly come down
from both the mayor as well as the chancellor, to the point where
we've had to stop the abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weingarten did not cite specific districts, but she said
that when the union complained that children might not be getting
the services they needed, Crew had ordered districts to evaluate
any children who needed it.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Crew said he had not set any quotas for reducing the
number of referrals. ``This is not about setting a target
numerically,'' he said. Rather, he said, teachers had found other
programs to help children with learning problems. In particular, he
cited Project Read, a $150 million program started last year to
provide remedial reading instruction to about 104,000 children
during and after school.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Coltoff, executive director of the Children's Aid
Society, said he feared that the reduction in referrals would not
be accompanied by an increase in the number of teachers, aides and
guidance counselors whom children with learning and behavioral
problems need.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 0158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TRASH-TUSSLE-NYT     01-20 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRASH-TUSSLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAYS HIS TRASH REMARKS GOT TWISTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-TRASH-TALKS) 
(bl) 
By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Making it clear that he was tired of talking trash,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani tried Tuesday to contain the furor over his
comments last week that a ``reciprocal relationship'' exists
between the cultural mecca that is New York City and out-of-state
communities whose residents generate garbage in their pursuit of
enlightenment here.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor used the word ``spin'' and its grammatical cousins
nine times in arguing that the news media had misrepresented his
discussion of a private company's contract to ship the city's
garbage to Virginia. The news reports prompted Virginia Gov. James
Gilmore to dash off a letter to Giuliani last week in which he took
umbrage at any suggestion that New York City's cultural
achievements ``obligate Virginia and other states to take your
garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written reply, which was sent Tuesday and released publicly
by City Hall, Giuliani said: ``There is no reason for you to be
offended. No one is obligated to accept New York City's garbage. It
is a relationship of mutual benefit entered into freely and
voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a news conference Tuesday, the mayor was less restrained
in defending his earlier comments. ``I didn't say that they were
obligated to take the garbage,'' he said. ``Somebody put that spin
on it, so now they're spinning based on the spin, and then
everything is spun around.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose after Waste Management Inc., a national disposal
company that transfers 2,400 tons of city garbage a day to Virginia
and other destinations, signed a contract with a barge company to
ship up to 4,000 tons a day to a new port in Charles City, Va.
Giuliani has contended that federal laws protecting interstate
commerce allow such contracts, which are often with poorer
communities that need revenue. City officials also say that the
arrangement creates thousands of jobs and is environmentally sound.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that while presenting this argument last week, the
mayor never said that other states were ``obligated'' to take the
city's trash. But the context of his comments suggested that the
city was owed some consideration because of its stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Virginia like to utilize New York because we're a
cultural center, a business center,'' he said at the time. ``What
goes along with being a cultural and business center is you're very
crowded. We don't have the room here to handle the garbage that's
produced not just by New Yorkers but by the three million more
people that come here that utilize the place every day. So this is
a reciprocal relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor had also said that the city contributes billions of
dollars more to the federal government than it receives, so ``one
of the things we need from the rest of the country is to assist
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the mayor said that he felt no need to apologize ``for
an unfair spin, or an erroneous spin, that somebody else puts on
the comments that I actually make.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Mark Miner, the press secretary for Gilmore, said
that the mayor's letter suggested he was backpedaling. ``The
wording that he's using today as opposed to last week is much
different,'' Miner said. ``I think he realized what he said last
week was inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on issues beyond this thing called ``spin,'' Giuliani
said the garbage debate was purely a matter of business. ``If you
want the money that goes with it, you take the garbage,'' he said.
``If you don't want the money that goes with it, we can move on and
find lots of other opportunities and places.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
