<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0313 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEOFUNION-SCENE-SF     01-20 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-SCENE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOW CLINTON TURNED THE BIZARRE DAY TO HIS ADVANTAGE  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Whatever the euphemism used to describe President
Clinton _ the split-screen president, the great compartmentalizer,
the political Houdini _ it fell short Tuesday as he pulled off a
feat that will go down in Washington legend.
<P>
   In the afternoon on one of the most bizarre days ever witnessed
in the Capitol, the U.S. Senate sat at Clinton's impeachment trial
for felony perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   By evening, the Senate joined the House, which passed the
articles of impeachment exactly one month ago, to hear him deliver
his State of the Union message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awkward timing, yes, but that's OK,'' said Sen. Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif., as she left the impeachment trial and headed back
to her office before the speech. She said she fully expects the
speech to boost Clinton's public approval rating, adding,
``although I don't know how much more popular he can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Clinton speak, one would never know that anything
else was going on in Washington besides health-care tax credits or
teacher standards or changes to Social Security. It was an eerie
demonstration of Clinton's fierce determination against wounds _
however self-inflicted _ that would have leveled other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But the impeachment cloud was clear enough inside the House
Chamber, where Clinton's unspoken predicament hung nearly palpable
in the air. Democrats gave a rousing cheer at first lady Hillary
Clinton's entrance, as if lending every ounce of moral support they
had. They embraced him, and pumped his hand and clapped his back as
he walked toward the podium.
</P>
<P>
   And throughout his address, Democrats rose every few seconds in
extended boisterous ovations for Clinton throughout his long
address, while Republicans mostly sat, sometimes applauding
politely, but generally looking deeply cynical.
</P>
<P>
   Some seemed to be gritting their teeth, others sometimes
chuckled, as Clinton claimed credit for welfare reform and budget
surpluses that they pushed through against veto threats.
</P>
<P>
   Newport Beach Republican Chris Cox, a member of the GOP House
leadership, acknowledged the cynical smiles. ``It was because the
president was announcing for the first time support for programs he
had opposed prior to this evening,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan to remove the Social Security earnings limit for
seniors who work ``was none other than (House Speaker) Denny
Hastert's bill, which the White House has opposed,'' Cox said,
``and the president didn't credit anyone for years of work on that,
even though they were all seated in the chamber. I've sponsored it
since 1989. And he called on Congress to pass it when his
opposition has stopped it all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who helped escort Clinton into the chamber, said Clinton
``was noticeably awkward and uncomfortable beforehand, compared
even to last year, when his State of the Union followed by six days
the first announcements of his affair with a White House intern.''
</P>
<P>
   The usually sociable Clinton ``had trouble making small talk,''
Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton seemed fully at ease once he reached the embraces
and smiles of Democrats, who greeted him with rousing enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Democrat Maxine Waters, one of Clinton's fiercest
defenders on the House Judiciary Committee, was riveted to his
every word, calling out ``Yes, Yes'' with ebullient applause when
Clinton mentioned rebuilding schools or drug coverage in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has a president delivered a State of the Union
speech while under trial for impeachment. Of course, only one other
president has been impeached, and that was 130 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Postponing the speech, as some had once suggested, was never
even contemplated at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally his call,'' said Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif.,
who had dropped in to watch part of the impeachment trial in the
morning, even as he praised Clinton's education initiatives and
private accounts for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we wanted him to know he's welcome, and we are going
to welcome him as the president of the United States,'' Dreier said
just before the speech. ``It's very apparent to me that he
obviously wanted to do it, so we're going to recognize the
importance and reverence of the institution, and we will treat him
appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox put it more bluntly. ``We were all there out of respect for
the office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yuba City Republican Wally Herger said Clinton offered some
``very positive goals'' but said early cost estimates of Clinton's
proposals had tallied $57 billion, ``just when we're beginning to
balance the budget and pay down the $5.5 trillion national debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Herger said he was initially skeptical about Clinton's
appearance, but agreed with Speaker Hastert's decision to extend
the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans hardly felt warm. ``Just looking at the
applause,'' Herger said, ``the fact that it was respectful and not
much more than that speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Many conservatives were irked, although they held their tongues
in public. ``It's even worse than it was last year,'' said a Senate
GOP leadership aide. Referring to GOP Senators, he said, ``Any of
their peers they know, Democrat or Republican, would not be so
graceless or tactless as to show up at this time. But the lowest
level of behavior is what they've come to expect from Bill
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats, by contrast, were thrilled that Clinton was
plowing forward. ``This whole impeachment trial is bogus,'' said
Oakland Democrat Barbara Lee. ``It should have never been voted out
of our House. The president is doing the absolute right thing to
present his State of the Union because the people of this country
deserve a president and a congress who are doing the business of
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always relished his State of the Union address, an
opportunity to outline his policy agenda in a setting of high
presidential pomp and political leadership, walking down the aisle
pumping the hands of the nation's lawmakers, before a crowd
including his cabinet, the justices of the Supreme Court and the
military's Joint Chiefs of Staff, all carried live on national
television.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton again listed a raft of his favorite policy proposals,
describing dozens of of programs with energy and enthusiasm, as if
in a final campaign, but this time, it was a campaign to
resuscitate his presidency and his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   It was no easy task. House Republicans and a handful of
Democrats had a month ago voted to impeach him. The House
prosecutors who had just spent three days before the Senate
denouncing him for felony crimes and urging his removal from
office, sat sternly facing him.
</P>
<P>
   Senators, Democrat and Republican, had days before taken an oath
to ``do impartial justice'' and were hours before sitting at his
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Walnut Creek Democrat Ellen Tauscher said she was ``just happy
to see that this evening, at least for as long as the president was
speaking, is to some extent about the working families of Alameda
and Contra Costa counties ... that we're talking about things
tonight that are finally about the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   How many of Clinton's proposals will pass is another question.
Rep. Randy Cunningham, R-Calif., characterizing the icy reception
of the Republicans, said Clinton ``always gives a good speech but
he ran out of money after the first 10 minutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
