<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIPANSIDE-BACKGROUND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAIPAN AND THE NORTHERN MARIANAS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT COLLIER  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Saipan, the largest of the Northern Marianas, is home to the
Chamorro indigenous people, who remain a privileged class today.
The island was claimed for Spain by Ferdinand Magellan in 1521 but
was virtually depopulated during 350 years of Spanish rule. It was
governed by Germany from 1899 to 1914, then conquered by Japan in
World War I. During the subsequent years, the Japanese heavily
developed fishing and sugarcane industries.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1944, nearly 40,000 Japanese troops and several thousand
Japanese civilians died defending Saipan and neighboring Tinian
against invading U.S. Marines. In the final days, the Japanese
troops ran out of ammunition yet nearly overran U.S. lines with
suicidal bayonet charges. Thousands more jumped off cliffs to their
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 U.S. soldiers were killed in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   In 1945, the Tinian airstrip was the world's busiest airport,
serving as the launching pad for the intensive American bombing of
Japanese cities. The planes that dropped the atomic bombs on
Hiroshima and Nagasaki took off from Tinian.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the Northern Marianas were administered by the
United States under U.N. authority as a trust territory. The
islands slumped into somnolence and obscurity, and fishing and
farming were abandoned. From 1953 to 1962, Saipan was closed to the
U.S. public and was used by the CIA as a training center for
Chinese anti-Communist guerrillas. In 1978, the islands became a
self-governing U.S. commonwealth, and in 1986, residents were
granted U.S. citizenship, although they cannot vote in federal
elections. Tourism and clothes manufacturing started in the
mid-1980s, and grew rapidly with heavy Asian investment.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Marianas' economy is rigidly balkanized, and local
attitudes rely on stereotypes that would be considered shockingly
racist on the U.S. mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign workers make up 91 percent of the private workforce, in
which occupation is largely determined by national origin. Most
hotel workers are Filipino, while most garment workers are Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese are given garment production work because they are
viewed as hard-working, obedient and unlikely to protest. (In
China, unions are part of the oppressive government structure, and
independent, American-style unions are unheard of.)
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say the Northern Marianas system promotes a
parasitic relationship in which the indigenous islanders live off
the fruit of sweatshop labor by an indentured foreign workforce
while ceding overall control to Asian tycoons.
</P>
<P>
   Another unsavory aspect of Saipan is the growth of prostitution.
Internet ads tout the island as a sex destination, and it ranks
with Bangkok and Manila as a regional sex-industry haven. Federal
law-enforcement officials say Japanese and Chinese organized-crime
syndicates have taken control of Saipan's sex trade and are now
using it as a beachhead to expand into drug trafficking and other
businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 0220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0324 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STATEOFUNION-     01-20 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STATEOFUNION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES A `NEW DAWN' 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
Washington _ President Clinton, appearing undaunted by his own
impeachment, introduced a sweeping agenda for his remaining time in
office last night, proposing scores of new policies including huge
infusions of cash to bolster Social Security and Medicare.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Addressing the nation from the very chamber where two articles
of impeachment were passed against him last month, an upbeat
Clinton spoke forcibly for nearly 11/2 hours, without a single
reference to the scandal that has plagued his administration for
the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps in the daily press of events, in the clash of
controversy, we do not see our own time for what it truly is _ a
new dawn for America,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   The nationally televised speech provided Clinton a chance to
present a remarkable smorgasbord of policy initiatives, from
testing teachers and fixing Y2K computer problems to protecting
against international terrorism and ending job discrimination
against gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   It also capped an extraordinary day that began with the
president's legal team defending him against charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice, providing the nation an odd juxtaposition
of their chief executive's strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand before you to report that the state of our union is
strong,'' said Clinton, who by one count was interrupted by
applause 95 times.
</P>
<P>
   Returning repeatedly to the populist programs that have been a
hallmark of his presidency, Clinton announced a new initiative
against the tobacco industry. He said the Justice Department will
take the industry to court over reimbursement for health care
costs. White House aides said the president's upcoming budget will
include a new 55-cents-a-pack tax on cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As everyone knows, our children are targets of a massive media
campaign to hook them on cigarettes,'' Clinton said. ``I ask this
Congress to resist the tobacco lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   The president insisted repeatedly that the nation's good
fortunes, and its newly found budget surplus, should be preserved
to prepare for economic challenges as the ``Baby Boom'' becomes the
``senior boom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With our budget surplus growing, our economy expanding, our
confidence rising, now is the time for this generation to meet our
historic responsibility to the 21st century,'' Clinton said.
``Let's get to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton strode into the House chamber accompanied by Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Senate Pro Tem Strom
Thurmond, R-S.C., just eight hours after the president's attorneys
opened their defense in the Senate trial over his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the chamber, there were only occasional signs of
awkwardness. All but a handful of lawmakers attended the speech.
Even the House ``managers'' who are bringing the case against him
stood to applaud at numerous intervals, such as when Clinton paid
tribute to Chicago Cubs right fielder Sammy Sosa, who was seated in
the gallery between first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore's wife, Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were more subdued than usual, and according to one
report, photographers overheard Lott as he left the chamber asking
a companion whether Clinton had ``no shame.''
</P>
<P>
   In the official GOP response, RepS. Jennifer Dunn of Washington
state and Steve Largent of Oklahoma outlined their disagreement
with the president over his failure to call for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Largent concluded by saying that ``reconciliation requires the
humility and courage to say, `I'm sorry. I was wrong. Will you
forgive me?,''' apparently in reference to Clinton's difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   The president set a bipartisan tone at the top of his speech
when he turned to greet the newly elected speaker of the House,
Dennis Hastert of Illinois, and declared:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Speaker, at your swearing in, you asked us all to work
together in a spirit of civility and bipartisanship. Mr. Speaker,
let's do exactly that.''
</P>
<P>
   However beyond the flowing rhetoric, the policy initiatives
outlined in the speech immediately set up a major confrontation
between Clinton and House Republicans, who have called for an
across-the-board 10 percent tax decrease.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the budget surplus to be spent on three broad
areas: Social Security, Medicare and a new program to allow
individuals to supplement their Social Security savings with a
government program similar to a 401(k) account.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed that 62 percent of what the White House
estimates will be a $4 trillion budget surplus over the next 15
years be set aside for Social Security to ensure that the system
remains solvent through the year 2055.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we must aim higher,'' the president said, calling on
Republicans to join him in the politically difficult decisions that
must be made to keep the retirement system solvent for the
remainder of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic departure from past practice, Clinton proposed
that up to a quarter of new Social Security money be invested in
private markets, in the hopes that it will earn higher returns.
Many economists, including Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan, have warned that public investments in private companies
runs the risk of politicizing the market.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also proposed a new program for Universal Savings
Accounts, which would allow individuals to spend pretax dollars on
retirement accounts, and up to $600 billion over the next 15 years
to improve Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generation is determined not to let our growing old place
an intolerable burden on our children and their ability to raise
our grandchildren,'' he said. ``Our economic success and fiscal
discipline now give us the opportunity to lift that burden.''
</P>
<P>
   In remarks hailed by gay and lesbian groups, Clinton spoke in
defense of the Employment Non-discrimination Act and the Hate
Crimes Prevention Act, which would bolster efforts against
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discrimination or violence because of race or religion,
ancestry or gender, disability or sexual orientation, is wrong,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He made a strong appeal to expand international trade, calling
for a new round of negotiations under the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Reiterating initiatives that have been announced almost on a
daily basis over the past couple of weeks, the president also urged
spending billions of dollars for new programs on child care,
education, crime-fighting, the environment and the Pentagon. And he
called for raising the minimum wage by $1 an hour over two years,
to $6.15.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, as has been typical of his previous six State of the
Union addresses, spent relatively little time on foreign policy. He
said the United States must step up its efforts to prepare against
possible chemical or biological warfare, and proposed $4.2 billion
_ a 70 percent increase _ to dismantle and destroy Russia's nuclear
arsenal and redirect the work of Russian scientists from weapons to
civilian research.
</P>
<P>
   The president also said the United States will continue to
contain Iraqi President Saddam Hussein. ``And we will work for the
day when Iraq has a government worthy of its people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the killing of more than 40 ethnic Albanians
in Kosovo, Clinton said the United States and NATO allies ``are
pressing the Serbian government to stop its brutal repression in
Kosovo, to bring those responsible to justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
