<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Washington) _ Two NATO generals who flew to Belgrade on
Tuesday to face down the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic,
made little headway in persuading him to halt the attacks of his
troops in Kosovo, the Clinton administration says. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Berlin) _ NATO warned the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, on Tuesday to stop an offensive in Kosovo or
face possible air strikes, but the alliance faces enormous
obstacles to ever carrying out such a threat. A news analysis. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-MOOD (Sao Paulo) _ Brazil's empty stores are perhaps the
clearest sign that the country may be able to avoid a return to the
inflation that many predict is inevitable. With customers already
scarce, any sudden price increases would only make matters worse.
By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-ULSTERSPEAK (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ The quality
of debate in the Northern Ireland Assembly is reaching new
metaphoric heights, or depths, in the language of Ulsterspeak, the
tongue used here by politicians in which traditional euphemism is
now increasingly enhanced by fulmination. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-RDP (Washington) _ President Clinton proposed
Tuesday night that the federal government invest for the first time
in the stock market to strengthen Social Security, as he delivered
a confident report on the State of the Union to a Congress
considering cutting short his presidency. By James Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ Insisting that President Clinton
``must not be removed from office,'' White House counsel Charles
Ruff opened the president's defense against impeachment charges on
Tuesday with sweeping denials of the accusations against Clinton
and stinging attacks on the House prosecutors. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-REPUBS (Washington) _ Republicans seek to dispel
the image of a Congress consumed by impeachment, putting forward a
policy agenda that calls for a sweeping across-the-board tax cut
and pledging to join President Clinton in the struggle to put the
Social Security system on a firm financial footing. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-ASSESS (Washington) _ Without once uttering the
word ``impeachment'' or making any obvious reference to the deeds
that have put him on trial, President Clinton made a forceful
argument against conviction in a lengthy State of the Union message
that detailed an ambitious and activist agenda for what he prays
will be his remaining 730 days in office. A news analysis, by John
M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ A Supreme Court roundup, leading with the
case of a shoplifter with two prior felonies who appealed
California three-strikes law; the high court rejects case, but in
an unusual move inviting judicial scrutiny of such laws. Other
court action. By Linda Greenhoue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOTHEBY-INTERNET (New York) _ Sotheby's plans to begin
auctioning art, antiques, jewelry and other collectibles over the
Internet. By Terry Pristin.
</P>
<P>
   DICTIONARY-HOMOSEXUAL (Undated) _ Merriam-Webster Inc., the
nation's oldest and largest dictionary publisher, on Tuesday took
steps to remove references to homosexuals in its classic collegiate
thesaurus amid complaints about a word list of offensive slurs and
synonyms. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Chase Manhattan Corp. on Tuesday
posted operating earnings of $4.02 billion for 1998, up 4.4 percent
from $3.85 billion a year earlier. Chase's performance is all the
more remarkable for having occurred in a year that tripped up other
financial goliaths. It also has proved to be a bank adept at
ghostbusting _ at least for the time being _ the bogyman haunting
all of Wall Street: risk. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Microsoft Corp. on Tuesday
reported that quarterly earnings rose 75 percent, or 73 cents a
share, over the same period last year, exceeding analyst
predictions of an increase of 59 cents a share. By Lawrence M.
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   DERIVATIVES-BORN (Undated) _ Brooksley E. Born, head of the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission, said Tuesday that she would
step down after a year of sharp public disagreements with other
regulators and Clinton administration officials over regulation of
the financial derivatives markets. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   ATHOME-EXCITE (Undated) _ Raising the stakes in the race to
capture Internet users and the dollars they are increasingly
spending online, At Home Network confirmed Tuesday that it plans to
acquire Excite Inc. for $6.7 billion, the largest in the recent
spate of consolidations among Internet companies. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-AD-COLUMN _ And the major independent agencies continue
to dwindle down to a precious few, to quote a snippet of
``September Song'': Jordan McGrath Case &AMP; Partners in New York
agreed Tuesday to be bought by Havas Advertising in Paris. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   OFFICEMAX-COMPUTERS (Undated) _ Officemax will shift its
computer sales from low-price personal computers to higher-end
computers in an effort to halt its losses in the cutthroat market.
The news follows by a day Officemax's announcement that it will
begin a test program of selling only International Business
Machines computers in six cities.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Much has been written about the
president's dual _ and dueling _ personalities. But the dichotomy
reached an absurd level with Impeachment Bill and State of the
Union Clinton. The president and his doppelgaenger were side by
side in Congress Tuesday, but did not acknowledge each other's
existence. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Once those witnesses arrive in the
president's impeachment trial _ we know now that what the
Republican majority wants, it gets _ the Senate's door will be open
to the truly unpredictable. We might even find ourselves with a
contender for ``trial of the century'' at last. By Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-COLUMN-SPARKS (Purchase, N.Y.) _ John Starks Jr. heard the
rumors Tuesday morning and decided to confront his father. ``My son
asked me today, `Dad, I got to leave school?' I said: `Yeah, maybe.
I'm not sure.' He said, `But Dad, we've already been out to Golden
State.' '' By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN (New York) _ The young player was a member of
a team in the West and, angry at his manager, the player attacked
him. The 28-year-old player slugged the 48-year-old manager,
causing a triple fracture to the manager's right cheekbone as well
as back injuries related to the assault. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE (Moved in ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR; SCI-OBESITY-DRUG (Undated) _ A new study, reported in the
Journal of the American Medical Association, finds that the
anti-obesity drug orlistat significantly promotes weight loss,
slows weight gain and moderates obesity-related risk factors.
However, some scientists see troublesome side effects. By Gina
Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Undated) _ Federally financed researchers will
soon be able to work on human embryonic stem cells, the source
cells from which the embryo develops, as a result of a ruling
Tuesday by the Department of Health and Human Services that a
congressional ban on human embryo research does not apply to the
cells. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-LINCOLN-PAINTING (New York) _ Lincoln Center constituents
argue over the Jasper Johns painting and plans to sell it. By Carol
Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-WRITERS (St. Petersberg) _ Arts Abroad: In St.
Petersburg, honors for Pushkin and Nabokov. By Herbert Mitgang.
</P>
<P>
   MILKY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Milky Way'': Ali Nassar,
director. In Arabic, with English subtitles. Revewed by Lawrence
Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICIAN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Winners'': Paul Cohen,
director. Competition for violinists and pianists. In French,
Russian, Flemish, English, with English subtitles. Reviewed by
Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Age of Terror,'' by David
Plante (St. Martin's). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (moved in ``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR; FRANCE-THREE-STARS (Paris) _ Starting up and running a
three-star restaurant is an astonishingly expensive proposition. A
typical three-star restaurant has two employees for every guest.
And with France's heavy taxes and formidable social charges, even
lunch and dinner bills of up to $500 per person fail to cover
costs. A debate is simmering in France over just how much trouble
the 21 three-star restaurants are in. How creative _ not just in
their cooking, but in their financing _ do chefs have to be, merely
to survive? Many now have backers; one is even going public. Will
the wildly escalating costs of running these establishments drive
the best and the brightest elsewhere? By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN-STOCK (Undated) _ Let's face the truth once and for all.
Most people _ and that includes many chefs _ don't bother making
their own chicken stock, despite the constant urgings that it's the
only legitimate way to go. If you're among the abashed, buck up.
Confident cooks have known for years how to take a can of chicken
broth, a bouillon cube or even a cup of water and make the most of
it. And no apologies are necessary; it's still real cooking. Even
the best chefs will tell you so. By Mark Bittman. With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   APERITIFS (Undated) _ On most fronts, American diners have
become more sophisticated and demanding, but when faced with the
aperitif moment, they flinch. ``Something to drink before the
meal?'' is a question brimming with promise. But the truth is, most
people are confused about what an aperitif is and what it is
supposed to do, and that includes professional bartenders. Is it
the same as a cocktail? If not, then where is the dividing line?
Questions like these have challenged the finest minds in drinkdom.
By Bill Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
