 ENTERTAINMENT No 417 - January 20, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 417 -- Jan. 20, 1999 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. MELANIE GRIFFITH'S WALK ON THE WILD SIDE It's been 11 years
since Melanie Griffith charmed the world as the baby-voiced heroine
of ``Working Girl'' (1988.) Since then, she's made lots of films
and lots of headlines as well, remarrying Don Johnson, divorcing
him and then marrying Spanish star Antonio Banderas. Now she's
reinventing herself as a character actress in the controversial
``Lolita,'' and as a heroin addict in ``Another Day in Paradise.''
In this interview Griffith talks about how she brought her own past
drug problems to bear on her role as an addict, why at 41 she is
venturing into the world of independent films and how she and
Banderas handle a family whose four children have a total of three
different fathers and two different mothers. By Jeanne Wolf. 1,400
words + photo. 2. FROM CUBE TO TUBE : SCOTT ADAMS TAKES 'DILBERT'
OUT OF HIS CUBICLE He's already visible in 1,900 newspapers, 16
books, a popular website and more than 100 licensed products, but
now Dilbert (about a profoundly over-burdened engineer trapped in
his microscopic cubicle,) is about to reach his biggest audience
yet, with a new animated series. It's only the latest triumph from
cartoonist Scott Adams, who also serves as the series' co-executive
producer and co-writer. Adams talks about the new series, how he's
learning to write for television and how his comic strip cured him
of his lifelong shyness. By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
KENNETH BRANAGH ON HELENA, HAPPINESS AND THE ART OF ACTING Kenneth
Branagh has wielded the sword of Henry V and shaped the monster of
Frankenstein, but his latest film is one of the most unique in his
career. Not only is it a rare venture into a contemporary story and
a particularly difficult role as a troubled artist involved with a
victim of Lou Gehrig's Disase, but ``The Theory of Flight''
co-stars Helena Bonham Carter in the first film they have made
together since becoming a couple. Branagh talks about the new film,
the pluses and minuses of co-starring with his girlfriend, his
divorce from frequent co-star Emma Thompson and why the man many
consider to be his generation's greatest actor has, nevertheless,
struggled with self-doubt. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   4. GETTING OFF THE NANNY TRACK : FRAN DRESCHER ON LIFE AFTER
'THE NANNY' Behind her nasal voice and calculated ditziness, Fran
Drescher is nobody's fool. As star, executive producer and
occasional director of her long-running hit ``The Nanny,'' she has
capitalized on her comic persona to create a hit movie, a
best-selling book and one of the funniest shows on television.
Drescher talks about her recent decision to end the series after
this season, her efforts to expand her interests and capabilities
behind and in front of the camera, why she chose to rock the
``Nanny'' boat by having her character get married and have a baby
and how she is continuing to deal with life after her 17-year
marriage to high-school sweetheart Peter Jacobsen, from whom she is
now separated. By Christopher Loudon. From TV Guide Canada. 1,400
words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
A MATTER OF PRIDE : CHARLEY PRIDE'S ENDURING LOVE AFFAIR WITH MUSIC
Virtually none of today's country singers has had to contend with
the social and cultural barriers that confronted country music's
greatest black entertainer, Charley Pride. Now secure in his place
in music history, Pride, 60, talks about his early struggles, the
white musicians who opposed and supported him, why he doesn't have
a recording contract at present and why there are still so few
black artists in the world of country music. By Jerry Armor. 1,300
words + photo. 6. EMILY WATSON FAITHFUL TO GENIUS OF 'JACKIE' Emily
Watson received an Oscar nomination for her remarkable screen debut
in ``Breaking the Waves'' (1996,) as a troubled young woman who
spoke to God. Now, for only her third film role, there's Oscar talk
again. In ``Hilary and Jackie,'' Watson plays the celebrated
cellist Jacqueline du Pri, whose life was as dark and turbulent as
her music was sublime. But the Scottish actress is quick to point
out that she is really far more normal - and content - than the
characters she plays. By Joshua Mooney. 1,200 words + photo. 7.
JAMES COBURN WELCOMES MEAN ROLE IN 'AFFLICTION' Hollywood veteran
James Coburn was writer-director Paul Schrader's first and only
choice to play the abusive, alcoholic and altogether frightening
father of the Nick Nolte character in the dark, uncompromising
movie ``Affliction.'' Coburn, 70, naturally, was flattered.
Schrader said he wanted an actor whom you associated with a
Hollywood male hero. So Coburn certainly fit the bill. By Kenneth
M. Chanko. From The Boston Globe. 1,400 words + photo.
</P>
