<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0595 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1998-BOOM-TIME-NYTSF &LR;      01-20 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1998-BOOM-TIME-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY AMERICANS WANT TO PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of the daily New York Times
op-eds. To publish as a ``separate buy'' article, please contact
your New York Times Syndicate sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. Or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City
at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By LESTER C. THUROW  
 c.1999 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The last two years have been fabulous years
economically. Inflation has disappeared; unemployment, like murder,
is down to levels not seen since the 1960s, and growth is a
vigorous 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market has made millionaires irrelevant. To be rich
today, one has to be a billionaire. Nothing in the memories of
those now alive compares with what has happened in 1997 and 1998.
Even in the high-living 1980s, the misery index _ inflation plus
unemployment _ was always far higher.
</P>
<P>
   True, we are in the midst of the longest peacetime expansion in
American history. Yet, as in all economic stories, there is another
side.
</P>
<P>
   A slightly longer view shows median family incomes that haven't
risen since the early 1970s, yet the average wife is working 15
more weeks a year than she did back then. Real wages for 80 percent
of the male labor force are below where they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 90 percent of the stock market gains have gone to the top
10 percent of the households, and the bottom 60 percent of
Americans cannot benefit from the market boom because they don't
own any stock. There have been better years in the past: Growth was
6.5 percent in 1964 and 1965, inflation was much lower in 1961 and
1962, and unemployment was at 3.5 percent in 1968 and 1969.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans don't want to hear that other story, any more than
they want to hear about President Clinton's impeachment trial.
Americans want to party.
</P>
<P>
   The right defining statistic for the last two years is the
negative savings rate first recorded in September 1998. Negative
savings rates hadn't been seen since 1933. The Great Depression was
under way, unemployment was approaching 30 percent, earnings had
collapsed, unemployment insurance benefits had yet to be invented,
no one had heard of welfare, and assets had to be sold if someone
wanted to eat. Consumption was above income because for too many
people there was no income.
</P>
<P>
   A very different story has to be told to explain 1998's negative
savings rates. Americans felt rich because of the booming stock
market and, not surprisingly, wanted to spend some of their new
wealth. Consumption exceeded income not because incomes were down
but because wealth was up.
</P>
<P>
   Americans were tired of watching their wealth grow on paper and
wanted to feel and touch some of their money with
bigger-than-that-of-my-neighbor sport utility vehicles,
10,000-square-foot homes or other conspicuous consumption.
</P>
<P>
   This story sounds reasonable until you think about it for more
than a microsecond. Negative savings rates first occurred in
September when the market was plunging. At that time there were
real fears of an American meltdown of 1998 that would rival the
collapse of Japan's bubble economy in 1990. Russia was going down
the tubes and carrying some very big banks with it. Bankers Trust
and Bank of America announced billion-dollar losses.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil was shaking, as it is now, and it seemed likely that it
would carry the rest of Latin America down with it, as it does now.
A government-organized rescue was being shaped for a
trillion-dollar hedge fund, Long-Term Capital Management, to
prevent it from pulling down the financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan at the Federal Reserve Board lowered interest
rates three times in four weeks _ once on an emergency basis. In
September no one was predicting that soaring stock prices would
return in November. Those who had been market optimists in August
were scorned.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this bad news dampened Americans' desire to spend.
They consumed like the stock market was going up when in fact it
was going down. Americans simply wanted to party, party. And in
part because they did so, the market went back up.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems that the interesting questions about 1997 and 1998
are probably sociological and not economic. These two years were
good economically, but we seem to feel far better about them
sociologically than their performance warrants. Why?
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of reasons to party.
</P>
<P>
   One can have a party to celebrate a victory. However one
calibrates America's performance in the last two years, it is far
better than that of the rest of the world. In 1990 only one of the
10 most valuable companies in the world was American. In 1998 nine
of the 10 most valuable companies in the world were American.
</P>
<P>
   One can also have a party to push out of one's mind, at least
for a short period, things that one would rather not think about.
There is a lot to push out of one's mind: the impeachment trial,
dying children in Kosovo, a failing peace agreement in the Middle
East and chaos in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that the political analysts have it wrong on Clinton's
impeachment. They explain the opinion polls supporting the
president with the argument that the public gives him credit for
the economy's performance and doesn't want to take a chance on
disrupting those good results. But do that many Americans truly
believe that the good economy would disappear if Clinton
disappeared?
</P>
<P>
   Or one can have a party simply to announce that ``I am rich.''
In this case, the bigger the party, the better. The whole purpose
of the party is to make my neighbors envious of my success.
</P>
<P>
   Americans can of course want to party for any one of these
reasons. They must remember that like all parties, the good times
have to end. But who wants to think of the prospects for 1999 _ our
ballooning trade deficit, Brazil's incipient meltdown, slower
economic growth _ when 1998's party is still under way?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Lester C. Thurow, a professor of economics at Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, is the author of the forthcoming ``The
Wealth Pyramid: New Rules for a Knowledge-Based Economy.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------ &QC;
</P>
