<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-ABUSE-TRAINING21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Training to identify child abuse surveyed
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Only about half of Texas professionals who
regularly come in contact with children say they are required by
their employers to learn the signs of child abuse or neglect. But
83 percent of the teachers, police officers, social workers,
doctors and other professionals surveyed say they have been trained
to recognize signs of trouble, a new report released Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by University of North Texas researchers
for the Children's Trust Fund of Texas, follows a recent state
study that found that the number of Texas children known to have
died from abuse or neglect rose more than 70 percent between 1997
and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent contradictions between the two studies could not be
immediately explained.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Trust Fund of Texas, established by the Texas
Legislature in 1985, helps set state child abuse policy and
provides money for local child abuse prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the first of its kind in Texas, and researchers
didn't know whether other states have produced similar reports. As
a result, they were unable to say whether training has improved or
declined in Texas or how the state rates nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-two percent of the 601 police officers, court officials,
social service workers, child care providers, teachers, principals,
school counselors and health care providers who were surveyed by
telephone said they had to undergo training on child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-four percent of law enforcement officers said training
was required, while only 52 percent of health care providers, 36
percent of school teachers and 21 percent of court officials said
they had to undergo training.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin Police Department and the Austin Independent School
District both require child abuse training.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of respondents said they were
``definitely'' trained adequately to recognize abuse, but more than
33 percent said they were only ``somewhat'' prepared and a little
over 4 percent said they were ``not at all'' equipped to recognize
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Scott McCown, who oversees the placement of
Travis County abused and neglected children into safe homes, noted
that among state caseworkers, training is closely linked to
employee turnover. Because workers often leave for less-stressful
jobs, it is difficult to maintain a corps of experienced and
well-trained caseworkers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's two kinds of training: There's your initial training
and there's continuing training,'' McCown said. ``We need both of
those, and to take advantage of it, you've got to have people stay
on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, McCown warned Gov. George W. Bush and the
Legislature that Child Protective Services was increasingly
strained. Using a citizens' grievance procedure outlined in the
Texas Constitution, McCown delivered a data-packed petition to Bush
and lawmakers. He recommended that 2 cents of every dollar from the
state's anticipated multibillion-dollar budget surplus be set aside
to help abused and neglected children.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Miguel Wise, whose 1997 bill mandated the study, said he
plans to propose legislation that would expand training on child
abuse. But he acknowledged that money could be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Additional training obviously will be a larger drain on local
police departments and state agencies,'' said Wise, D-Weslaco. ``We
may not be be able to get all the hours we'd like to see without a
city or county going broke.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
