<HEADER>
A0606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN21-COX     01-20 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Annoying phone-based pitches have made us fear taking calls
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I punched the speaker-phone button on a kitchen
wall phone and then hit the the speed-dial number of a friend whose
wife was in the hospital recovering from an operation.
</P>
<P>
   If he answered, I intended to pick up the handset to talk to
him. I've never liked to be put on a speaker phone. Your voice
reverberates like you're talking into a washtub. I also don't like
the feeling that I could be talking to a roomful of people.
</P>
<P>
   My friend answered. But before I could raise the handset, he
hung up.
</P>
<P>
   I hit the redial button.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, why did you hang up so quick?''
</P>
<P>
   ``After I say 'hello,' and no one answers immediately, I hang
up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it didn't take me that long,'' I said. ``I was just
reaching for the handset when you hung up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Telemarketers have that little pause in there after you answer
the phone before they say anything,'' he explained. ``They drive my
crazy. That's why I hang up if there's a pause after I answer the
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard of such a thing,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot you've never heard about. I pay attention. You
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a point. I've never analyzed nuisance calls from
telemarketers with a stopwatch. My method to prevent telephone
salesmen from invading my privacy with their relentless sales
pitches is to allow my answering machine to pick up telephone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Very few telemarketers will leave a message on an answering
machine. They just dial some another poor sap's telephone. They
play the odds. Eventually, someone will answer and present the
opportunity for money to flow into the caller's bank account.
</P>
<P>
   My answering machine method is far from satisfactory, however.
Although attitudes have changed a lot since answering machines
first came out, there still are a lot of people besides
telemarketers who don't like to talk to a machine.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem with my answering-machine solution to
telemarketers is that I have to be within earshot of the machine to
tell if someone I want to talk to is leaving a message. That's a
pain.
</P>
<P>
   And if I do pick up the phone quickly enough when I'm expecting
a call, we both have to wait until my own irritating answering
machine message is finished playing.
</P>
<P>
   All of this trouble is caused by telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to avoid unwanted sales pitches is Caller ID. A
number of my friends say they don't answer the phone without first
checking their Caller ID to see who is calling. Telemarketers
generally block their names and telephone numbers from showing up
on caller ID.
</P>
<P>
   Texas must have more telemarketing than any other state. Or
perhaps Texans have less tolerance for telemarketing than other
Americans. Or maybe we're simply nosier than other people because
Texans believe in Caller ID nearly as much as the death penalty,
which means nearly everyone has Caller ID.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with screening out telemarketers with Caller ID is
that people are missing phone calls they might want to take because
some calls come from areas in which Caller ID is not offered.
</P>
<P>
   People who block Caller ID out of a sense of personal privacy
often don't get their calls answered because many people will not
answer a phone call unless they can tell who is calling.
</P>
<P>
   Telemarketers, bless their souls, are people, too. They're out
there earning a living by churning up $550 billion in annual sales
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But telemarketers also are people who are driving many otherwise
sane Americans crazy. Telemarketers are ruining the convenience and
pleasure of owning and using a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   I want to be able to answer my telephone again without being
hassled by strangers trying to take my money.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
