<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0607 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKWOMEN-WANT21-COX     01-20 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKWOMEN-WANT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What black women want: A spiritual man
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Looks didn't even make the list.
</P>
<P>
   (Not that anybody would mind a date with Denzel Washington...)
</P>
<P>
   Spirituality, sensitivity and strength of character are the most
vital traits in a mate, according to a new book called All the Man
I Need: Black Women's Loving Expressions on the Men They Desire.
</P>
<P>
   White women, on the other hand, tend to go for guys who display
affection and treat them as equals. But more on that later.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many women's magazines talk about what men want in women,''
says Anaezi Modu, who co-wrote the book with fellow Princeton grad
Andrea Walker. ``I wanted to know what women valued. In their own
words.''
</P>
<P>
   Modu, inspired by a GQ ad that asked, ``What makes a man a
gentleman?'', decided to pose a similar question in contest form:
Describe your ideal partner in 75 words or less. Although she and
Walker offered a $1,000 prize and approached numerous women's
magazines, only Essence and American Woman were interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't set out to do a survey of just black women,'' Modu
says. ``And then we were overwhelmed by nearly 2,000 responses from
Essence readers.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Woman survey, meanwhile, generated fewer than 200
letters from its predominantly white readership _ too small of a
sampling _ so Modu and Walker narrowed the focus of their book to
black women. They chose 350 submissions from the Essence mailbag
for All the Man I Need, which also includes passages from black
writers, former slaves and religious texts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that surprised me was that an overwhelming
majority of submissions were written in the form of poetry,'' says
Walker, 41, who is black. ``There was a rhythm to what these people
were writing. Many didn't care that they disqualified themselves
from the contest because they went over 75 words. They just felt
certain things needed to be said.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those things:
</P>
<P>
   ``He will possess intellect and integrity, constantly striving
for self-improvement while empowering others. A preservationist for
family, Christian and moral values.'' _ Deidre Wilson,
Robersonville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideal man is an intellectual with common sense. He is
strong even when no one is looking. His beauty lies in his generous
spirit and belief in God. He is nobody's victim and feels no need
to carry his legacy like a cross.'' _ Adrienne Maynard-Melchor,
Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to toss out the complex description of Mr. Right and be
thankful for a level-headed brother with a job!'' _ Shetina Dawn
Wallace, Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   While some responses were humorous, most revealed a sincere
desire for an honest, respectful, God-fearing man.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you read the entries, you can feel the African-American
cultural influences in the way the women express themselves,'' says
Modu, 38, who lives with her daughter in Providence, R.I., and runs
her own design, marketing and architectural management firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strong emphasis on spirituality is a reflection of the
black experience in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Religious conviction, however, appeared much less frequently in
white respondents' essays. The most sought-after mate, according to
American Woman readers, is one who shows affection (i.e., sends
flowers, remembers birthdays, calls during the day).
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we had so few American Woman responses, we couldn't
make a direct comparison,'' says Walker. But she added that many
traits _ sensitivity, loyalty and integrity among them _ were
common denominators.
</P>
<P>
   ``But spirituality by far and away was the most glaring
difference. In hindsight, this is to be expected. Part of growing
up in the black community is learning to turn to a higher power to
guide the way. It's ingrained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing that struck me was the heavy emphasis on
romantic gestures in the American Woman readership,'' says Walker,
a married attorney in Newark, N.J., with two kids. ``Not to say
that Essence women don't want this, but they seemed to be saying,
`Sure, that stuff is nice, but here are my basic requirements.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another difference in the essays was that white women stated
more often the need for equality.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Essence women, equality is important, too, but it wasn't
mentioned in an equal-rights context. The thought is, `I've been
independent for so long, and I've borne the burden of raising a
family for so long that I've had ``equality.'' I'm ready for some
sharing of responsibilities.'''
</P>
<P>
   For Debra Johnson of West Palm Beach, who answered the ad,
responsibility and spirituality make up her ideal man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independent enough to make responsible decisions and strong
enough to progress despite the obstacles,'' she writes, on Page
142. ``Spiritually secure and aware, he must be faithful to himself
before he can be faithful to anyone else.... A giver _ mentally,
spiritually, emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been into looks,'' says Johnson, 28, an
administrative assistant who is divorced and has a 6-year-old
daughter. ``I go for a sense of humor because that usually leads to
a good personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
