<HEADER>
A0609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAST-WEIGHTPLAN21-COX     01-20 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAST-WEIGHTPLAN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author hopes to lift weight of world from fat folk
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Cynthia Last was disgusted with her
obesity.
</P>
<P>
   A teenager struggling with self-worth, she vowed not to let her
looks define her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured my best chance of finding success was by developing
my intellect,'' she writes in her new book, The 5 Reasons Why We
Overeat: How to Develop a Long-Term Weight Control Plan That's
Right for You ($19.95, Birch Lane Press.)
</P>
<P>
   Last studied psychology in college, particularly behavioral
sciences, and developed a weight-loss plan for herself. She focused
on the psychological reasons she was eating, not the diets that
never worked.
</P>
<P>
   She dissolved from a size 11 to a size 5, a weight loss she's
maintained for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to eat due to anxiety and impulsivity,'' says Last, now
a psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   That meant she had to focus on reducing the tension and stress
that led to self-medicating with food, and to become more aware of
what and where she was eating.
</P>
<P>
   Once she did that, the weight loss kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food is similar to smoking cigarettes, or using alcohol. It's
a substance you use to try to cope with life. The better able you
are to develop coping skills, the less you will rely on these kinds
of substances to get through day to day life,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   The book divides overeaters into five types: The Impulse Eater,
The Hedonist, The Stress Reducer, The Avoider, and The Energizer.
</P>
<P>
   The Hedonist, for example, is an outgoing person who uses food
as a pleasure trip, savoring and devouring slowly. They tend to
gain weight by consuming too many calories. Weight-loss treatment
focuses on substituting lower-calorie, yet tasty foods, and working
other enjoyable activities into their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Last's plan includes a self-test to identify which eating type a
reader is. The purpose is for readers to start making changes
immediately _ no sessions with a therapist required.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things that are new in the book,'' says Last,
also a professor at Nova Southeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It poses psychological solutions. You use an anxiety treatment
plan, for example, to learn how to face and solve problems. Other
weight-loss programs offer dietary solutions to an emotional
problem. This book conceptualizes overeating as primarily
psychological and offers entirely psychological answers. It also
offers an entirely different treatment program, based on the reason
you overeat.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's one big no-no, no matter what type of overeater you
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask you not to weigh yourself while you're learning the
skills. The weight is the wrong focus,'' she warns. ``If you
eliminate why you overeat, the weight will drop off.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Susman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
