u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENOIR21-COX     01-20 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENOIR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boca Brings On The Old Masters
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Pierre-Auguste Renoir is one of the
world's great painters. Al Hirschfeld is one of the century's great
caricaturists. Masters in different fields, their work celebrates
life.
</P>
<P>
   Renoir died in 1916 at 78, after creating about 6,000 paintings.
He never stopped working despite crippling arthritis. At 95,
Hirschfeld continues to produce his lively drawings of show-biz
personalities for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   There's another connection between these two different artists _
both have shows in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   Renoir and The Cote d'Azur: Homage and Celebrations opened
earlier this week at the Boca Raton Museum of Art. In Line With Al
Hirschfeld opens Saturday at the International Museum of Cartoon
Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to do a retrospective _ the greatest
masterpieces of Renoir,'' said Boca Raton Museum director George
Bolge. ``What we're doing is re-creating a sense of the working
environment of a great artist at the peak of his popularity.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which has already sold about 10,000 tickets, comes
from The Renoir Museum in Cagnes-sur-Mer in the south of France.
The museum is in the artist's former home on the Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition runs through March 14 and has about 95 paintings,
drawings, sculpture and ceramics by Renoir and others, as well as
such artifacts as the great man's chair, coat and easel.
</P>
<P>
   Renoir's late work from Cagnes-sur-Mer is controversial, or at
least unusual in the way it was created. He settled there with his
family around 1905. The son of a poor tailor, he was a cheerful,
common-sensical man who had achieved financial success. He was
``perhaps the first great artist who never painted a sad picture,''
noted writer Octave Mirbeau.
</P>
<P>
   But, by around 1912, he was confined to a wheelchair with
rheumatoid arthritis and painted with the brush strapped between
his twisted fingers. He continued to push himself, even deciding to
try sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   His noted dealer, Ambroise Vollard, arranged to find him a pair
of hands. Vollard asked the sculptor Aristide Maillol to work with
the older man, but Maillol was too far along in his own style to
make a collaboration work. So Vollard found a young Spaniard named
Richard Guino.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sat down and worked on drawings together,'' said Bolge.
``They worked on sculptures together. The old man would be there,
say something and touch the clay,'' and Guino would then add or
subtract the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward the end, Renoir wasn't doing a great deal of
painting,'' Bolge added. ``But sculpture opened up a new vista for
him.'' The ideas kept coming. ``You couldn't kill that creative
zeal. You can see the artist continuing to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition contains only six small paintings by Renoir but
34 sculptures by Guino/Renoir, as well as some of Guino's own work.
There are also portraits of the master done by artists visiting
Cagnes-sur-Mer. ``Artists liked to paint the master painting,''
Bolge noted.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition will cost about $150,000, making it the museum's
most expensive ever, he said. And there's talk of the local museum
shipping a contemporary art exhibition to The Renoir Museum. Bolge
would like to push the idea of forming a sister-city relationship
with Cagnes-sur-Mer.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that tucked away in the south of France are a
number of other unusual museums devoted to French masters. ``We
wouldn't mind doing more of this kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   While Renoir gained fame as an Impressionist, and spent a
lifetime painting beautiful women, Hirschfeld has spent his long
life caricaturing women _ and men _ with wit and empathy.
</P>
<P>
   The Hirschfeld show, which runs through May 9, features
approximately 70 drawings and prints, including caricatures of such
luminaries as Greta Garbo, Charlie Chaplin, Zero Mostel, Laurel and
Hardy and Vanessa Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   Born in St. Louis in 1903, Hirschfeld published his first New
York Times caricature in 1928. It depicted the Scottish vaudeville
star Harry Lauder. But Hirschfeld had already established a
reputation in show business by that time.
</P>
<P>
   He began as an office boy at Goldwyn Pictures in 1920. Two years
later, he was art director at Selznick Pictures. He was noted for
his movie-poster work before his first theater caricature, which
appeared in The New York Herald Tribune in 1926. He agreed to work
exclusively for The Times in 1943. The deal was sealed with a
handshake.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his famous caricatures, the show has drawings and
sculpture by the teenage Hirschfeld, movie posters and political
caricatures of the likes of Ross Perot and famed union leader John
L. Lewis. Hirschfeld will be honored at a museum reception on Jan.
30.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the chance to play everybody's favorite Hirschfeld
game _ locating his daughter Nina's name, which he has been hiding
within his drawings since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schwan writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
