A0611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRACE-ADKINS21-COX     01-20 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACE-ADKINS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adkins' diet: True grit and a big plate of hits
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In John Wayne-speak, country singer
Trace Adkins is one tough hombre.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the 6-foot-6, 37-year-old Louisiana native has
weathered a hurricane while working on an offshore oil rig. He's
survived two near-fatal car accidents _ his nose had to be sewed
back on after one of those. He lopped off his left pinkie once
while opening an oil barrel and told doctors to sew it back on at
an angle so he could still play guitar. A bulldozer nearly cut off
his legs. And an ex-wife once shot him through the heart.
</P>
<P>
   All of which adds gravity when he says that his next album, due
out later this year, is ``do or die'' for his career.
</P>
<P>
   Do or die for a guy who's almost bought the farm so many times?
Sounds serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really needs to be successful,'' says Adkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really do anything about that fact or dwell on it. I
can only do what I can to make the best record I can make. If radio
embraces that, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   His first effort, Dreamin' Out Loud, sold more than a million
copies in 1996 and produced two monster hits, the lonesome
tearjerker Every Light in the House and (This Ain't) No Thinkin'
Thing.
</P>
<P>
   His second album, Big Time in 1998, sold more than 500,000
copies and scored well with the song Lonely Won't Leave Me Alone,
but it didn't pass muster for Adkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was a disappointment,'' he said. ``It's sold just
under a million copies, but it should have been a better album.''
</P>
<P>
   He and veteran Nashville producer Emory Gordy have polished off
17 tracks for Adkins' third release, tentatively titled Get Real.
They're in the process of honing the songs and culling them to
about a dozen tunes for the final disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best adjective I can use to describe it is that it's a
little more mature,'' he said. ``Lyrically, vocally,
instrumentally, it's just more ... mature. I think that just comes
with growth, with being in the business and getting more
comfortable with yourself and more at ease with how you want to
project yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was a dip in quality, Nashville didn't notice. The
Country Music Association nominated him for a Horizon Award in
1998, essentially anointing him as a star in the making. The
TNN/Music City News Awards also named him the Male Star of
Tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   And he's garnering the respect of idols such as Buck Owens and
Merle Haggard. ``Waylon Jennings called the other day and said he
wrote a song he thought I might like,'' Adkins said. ``That blew me
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Adkins first started performing with a gospel quartet when he
was a high school student in Sarepta, La. He continued to sing
gospel throughout his years at Louisiana Tech University, where he
studied petroleum technology. A vocal teacher suggested he consider
studying opera, but he decided to use his rich baritone to pursue a
career in country music.
</P>
<P>
   He worked on an oil rig for a few years after graduation and
played honky-tonks on weekends before being discovered by a Capitol
Records executive at a roadway beer joint in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   His live performances, in fact, may be his best kept secret.
When he opened for Clint Black in June, he stoked the crowd to the
point that women were screaming by the time he left the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our shows have always done well,'' he said. ``The rumor has
gotten around that we do a pretty decent show.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean he'll be doing the usual amount of
hip-swiveling when he performs at the fair. Adkins said he tailors
his road show for the family crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little cleaner,'' he said. ``I like to say my show is
same for every audience, but it's not. In a club or in a venue,
it's a more mature show. I cut my teeth in beer joints and when I
go back and do a show there, it's a beer joint show. At the fair,
it's just a good, family show, but that's cool too. I love every
kind of venue.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
