<SLUG> BC-BEAUTIFUL-CHICKS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What makes a good-looking chick? Think all chickens are created
equal?
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bleach jobs and blow-drys, clipped nails
and preening. Yes, it's chicken-judging time at the South Florida
Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Birdly beauty is all in the breeding, owners say. You have to
have a pretty face and nice legs. And you have to make a good first
impression, because judging can take just seconds, says Dale
Porcher, local poultry judge and a West Palm Beach veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   Any of this sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Like human beauties, good-looking chickens have a lot in common.
They must have faces smooth and fine in texture, and beaks in
proportion to their well-rounded heads.
</P>
<P>
   And the beauty must be natural. Chickens with mascara dabbed on
imperfections, for instance, are disqualified, Porcher says.
</P>
<P>
   When he makes the rounds of cages, Porcher carries a copy of the
American Poultry Association's The Standards of Perfection, which
contains pictures of the ideal breeds. Judging is easy _ whichever
chicken looks the most like its picture wins.
</P>
<P>
   Could a similar ``standard of perfection'' for humans exist?
``That's garbage,'' Porcher says quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Not that people aren't trying. New Mexico State University
psychologist Victor Johnston has even created a computer-enhanced
face of the ``perfect'' woman, complete with full lips and dainty
bone structure.
</P>
<P>
   Such beauty ideals have been tied to a woman's fertility,
Johnston says. Full lips and delicate bones are considered ``high
estrogen markers,'' and fertility is desirable in a mate. With
today's fertility clinics and drugs, though, and women in their 50s
having babies, those ``markers'' are irrelevant, Johnston says. But
the beauty ideal lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Good looks mean even less with chickens. A winner doesn't mate
better, owners say. It doesn't taste better. It doesn't even
produce more eggs.
</P>
<P>
   A blue-ribbon bird is just the result of good food, a thorough
shampoo and a little pluck. Would those outside the poultry
community see beauty in Taylor's prize-winner? We asked West Palm
Beach plastic surgeon Frederic Barr to take a gander at the Buff
Brahma hen and give us feedback. Barr did more than that; he
composed this couplet: ``Her beak is petite with a slight
coquettish flair/her neck is quite youthful, not a hint of a wattle
there.'' (Later, he admitted, ``I'm a fish person. I've never even
owned a parakeet.'') THE PERFECT CHICKEN? When a group of farmers
compiled The Standards of Perfection for chickens a century ago,
they created a different one for each breed. No judging Brahmas
against Rhode Island Reds. Give different looks a chance, they may
have mused. That doesn't mean they weren't picky. Here's what your
aspiring Buff Brahma cochin bantam hen has to measure up to: Comb:
Five points, no wrinkles Beak: Stout at the base Face: Smooth, fine
in texture Eyes: Medium in size Wattles: Small, nicely rounded
Earlobes: Oblong Head: Neat, fairly full in skull Neck: Short,
nicely arched, plumage very full Back: Very broad, shoulders broad
Tail: Short, broad at base, carried rather low Wings: Small,
well-folded and carried with no drooping Breast: Low in front, of
great breadth and depth Body-fluff: Full and well-rounded Legs: Set
well apart, straight when viewed from the front Lower thighs:
Moderately large, with great profusion of soft fluff plumage Hocks:
Well-covered with a profusion of soft, flexible feathers Shanks:
Short, stout in bone Toes: Four on each foot, straight,
well-spaced, middle and outer toes heavily feathered to ends
Weight: 34 ounces THE PERFECT CHICK? Defining a female ``standard
of perfection'' is much more murky. But researcher Victor Johnston
at New Mexico State University tried. In a project conducted over
the Internet, he asked thousands of people to rate several faces on
a scale of 1 to 9. From that, he ``bred'' the perfect face. Eyes:
Large, well-spaced Cheekbones: High Nose: Small Chin: Delicate
Forehead: High Lips: Full This is just a computer image, of course.
The real perfect woman, he says, would have to be Ingrid Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-01-19-99 1657E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
