<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0621 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUMMEL-MUSEUM21-COX     01-20 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMMEL-MUSEUM21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hummel Museum struggles against financial woes
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Inside a vault that guards a trove of loaned
artwork sits a portrait of the artist as a young nun. The black and
white photograph of a smiling Sister Maria Innocentia _ her hands
neatly tucked in the sleeves of her habit _ stands out against the
vault's white walls and the stacks of cardboard boxes that hold her
drawings.
</P>
<P>
   The German nun, born Berta Hummel, is internationally recognized
as the artist whose drawings captured tender moments of children at
play. She also is the namesake of the Hummel Museum _ a source of
civic pride in this city whose heritage is distinctly German.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a little more than six years after it opened, the Hummel
Museum has hit hard times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've fallen behind in our payments,'' said Doreen Schaeffer,
the executive director. ``The bank has been more than patient with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit museum, a refurbished savings and loan building
that houses the world's largest collection of Hummel's charcoal and
pastel drawings and oil paintings, is behind $60,000 on mortgage
payments, utilities and salaries and has $350,000 in long-term
debt, Schaeffer said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, which draws about 20,000 visitors a year, has
counted on admissions, memberships, gift shop sales and local
benefactors to defray expenses. But the October floods that ravaged
Central Texas hit New Braunfels hard, destroying businesses and
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big donors have been hurt, and you don't have the guts to
ask them for more,'' said local resident Sieglinde Schoen Smith,
who helped found the museum and who, as a child in Germany, was a
model for some of Hummel's drawings.
</P>
<P>
   The museum was facing closure this month, but new donations _
most of them from the M.I. Hummel Collectors Club, which has more
than 300,000 members, and Goebel, the German company that produces
figurines based on Hummel's drawings _ will keep it open for now.
Museum President John Lovett said the facility must retire its
long-term debt and raise money for an endowment fund to secure its
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an international treasure,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Immortalizing childhood
</P>
<P>
   Both Smith and Hummel grew up in southern Germany, though they
were born 32 years apart.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's father was a garment manufacturer who employed nuns from
a Franciscan order in the Convent Siessen to sew clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Hummel was already a well-known artist whose work
supported the convent, which she had joined in April 1931. She had
sold the licensing rights for the figurines to Goebel, whose sales
saved the company's factory from closure in 1935. Before that, her
images graced postcards and greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's father, who she says ``was more Catholic than the
pope,'' commissioned the nunin 1942 to do a portrait of his
16-month-old daughter. She wore a dress adorned with bluebells and
a garland of the flowers on her head that she had worn in a spring
children's festival.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, Smith accompanied her father to pick up the
portrait _ a Christmas present for her mother. As they waited,
Smith, dragging a puppet of a joker behind her, stood in front of
the convent's Christmas tree, her mouth agape as she stared at one
of the lighted candles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sister Hummel came down the steps to the hallway and spotted
me right away, and with great joy said, `Don't move. I'll be right
back,' '' Smith said. The nun returned with a pad and charcoal; she
quickly sketched the image and handed it to Smith's father.
</P>
<P>
   Both pieces, ``Child with Bluebells'' and ``Sieglinde's First
Tree,'' became Hummel figurines.
</P>
<P>
   Wartime art defied Nazis
</P>
<P>
   Berta Hummel was born in 1909 and died at age 37 from
tuberculosis. She was, by all accounts, a spirited nun who
sometimes defied convention.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, the Nazis took half the profits from her
artwork. The government shut down the convent and its school, but
Hummel continued to draw.
</P>
<P>
   Though her work is most often associated with the happy,
chubby-cheeked children of the figurines, she also produced
numerous religious works. As the war raged, Hummel drew pictures of
angels underneath a six-pointed star and wearing robes adorned with
the star that represents Judaism. She drew a postcard-size
Christian cross with a Jewish menorah laid over the image and a
single candle blazing in the middle, her way of expressing the
validity of both faiths under God. ``If she would have been caught
with that little picture in her pocket it would have been bye-bye
Sister Hummel,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The war cut the Smith family off from the convent. Smith
wouldn't return until 1987 _ 24 years after she had moved to Fort
Worth. The nuns, who were chronicling Hummel's work, were excited
to find out that Smith was the little girl in the copies of two
pieces they had been unable to trace.
</P>
<P>
   Preserving Prints
</P>
<P>
   After returning to Texas, Smith and her husband, Bill, decided
to make prints of Sieglinde's originals. They drove to New
Braunfels to meet Ken Armke, a Hummel dealer, who agreed to
distribute a limited edition of the prints.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had they begun marketing the prints when attorneys for
the licensing house Ars A.G. of Switzerland notified them that
reproductions of original Hummels was the company's exclusive
right. Hummel herself had sold the company all publishing rights to
her art.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths flew to Switzerland to work out a deal. The couple
also learned that the company had more than 300 Hummel originals
stored in crates. Sieglinde Smith said the president, Jacques
Nauer, told her Hummel's work was so popular in the United States
that he was negotiating to open a museum in New York or at Disney
World's Epcot Center in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had a better idea. ``Maybe a small town, a town where
Sister Hummel would have liked to live during her life time, maybe
a town with a German heritage would be more suited,'' she told
Nauer.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths moved to New Braunfels in 1991, and with the help of
Armke and the Chamber of Commerce, Nauer agreed to put the museum
there. It opened in October 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the original artwork, the museum features an exhibit of
Hummel's life, including her easel, her private kneeler from the
convent and other artifacts. It also displays more than 1,500
Hummel figurines, many of them on loan from private collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 57, restored many original drawings herself after
learning the process from a University of Texas museum curator.
With eraser shavings, a Q-Tip and magnifying glass, she
painstakingly cleaned each piece of artwork, removing decades of
accumulated dirt.
</P>
<P>
   She keeps the shavings and Q-Tips handy inside the vault where
she works at a table underneath the photo of Sister Hummel.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of the museum's closing weighs heavy on Sieglinde's
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's past sad,'' she said. ``The artwork's in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum's board of directors plans to sit down with its
creditors this month, Schaeffer said. ``The board will have to sit
down and talk, make some decisions and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. E-mail: kslperkes(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
