<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0622 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIM-ALEXIS21-COX     01-20 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIM-ALEXIS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The squeaky-clean Kim Alexis talks about God, kids and local tv
project
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ At first, former supermodel Kim Alexis is
so perfect, so distressingly polished, that you want to shake her
until her teeth (never a cavity!) rattle like a handful of dice.
</P>
<P>
   It's not her fault, really. She just keeps saying these things
in that calm, pleasant, TV-ready voice.
</P>
<P>
   Things like, ``I was a great kid. I can't imagine that I did
much wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``My morning routine takes about two minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``I never had to wear braces or glasses when I was a kid.''
Acne? ``No acne.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a relief, then, to sit in on the taping of her television
show, Parenting in the '90s and Beyond, in Delray Beach and watch
her say ``de-shi-sions'' instead of ``decisions'' and roll her eyes
like anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Alexis? That someone would even have to ask shows how
quickly the world of modeling sheds its skin.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis was one of a handful of women _ Kelly Emberg and Christie
Brinkley were others _ so tall and blond and dominant in the early
1980s that someone came up with the term ``supermodels.'' Alexis
remembers hearing it after she signed a contract with Revlon in
1983 and someone told her she was one.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the era of successors Linda-Naomi-Claudia-Cindy-Kate.
And these days, Alexis, 38, is two decades older than even the
average model.
</P>
<P>
   But she's not crying about it.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis holds the record for Glamour covers (29) and once made
headlines for being Vogue's cover girl in back-to-back months, but
now she can't remember the last time she was on the cover of
anything.
</P>
<P>
   And she hardly keeps in touch with anyone from her modeling
days. When another '80s supermodel, Carol Alt, was in Africa
recently, the two exchanged e-mails. And Alexis stays in touch with
Emberg, Rod Stewart's girlfriend before he married model Rachel
Hunter. ``But I don't really hang out with anybody,'' Alexis says,
and these days that means anybody outside her family.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, former NHL player Ron Duguay (they married
in Tampa), live in Southern California with five kids among them _
two sons from Alexis' first marriage, Duguay's two daughters and
the couple's 4-year-old son, Noah.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular day it's been more than a week since Alexis
has seen them. While Duguay keeps house _ he even buys Alexis'
clothes and packs them _ she travels to work on various projects,
such as commercials for Monistat, infomercials for a teeth whitener
and even a bit part in Eddie Murphy's Holy Man. She calls home
every day.
</P>
<P>
   Three times a year, she visits the Five Star Productions studio
in Delray Beach to tape bits for the show on parenting. (The next
one will air at noon Feb. 6 on WFOR-Channel 4 in Miami.)
</P>
<P>
   The show's set is your basic American living room, with flowers
and photos and fake sunlight that does not move an inch across the
carpet. The photos are not of Alexis' family and probably came with
the frames, says a show employee.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis, says director Bill Horneck, ``comes with nothing but her
clothes and her smile.''
</P>
<P>
   The walls are not thick enough. A truck rumbles by, and taping
stops, and everyone plays the game of ``What's that sound?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a garbage truck to me,'' Alexis says. A few
minutes later a train passes, then something else. ``A plane!''
someone guesses. ``A Piper Cub!'' Alexis says, looking around
playfully, a challenge. ``But where is it going, though?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vero Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a car horn breaks up a take on breast-feeding.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for the noise, taping could be done already.
Alexis usually nails her lines in a couple of tries.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, she answers Horneck's questions about his
4-day-old daughter, Julia. (How long for the eyes to focus? he
asks. Two weeks, she says.)
</P>
<P>
   Then they start on the whole stork concept. ``It's dumb,''
Alexis says. ``Who ever thought of a dumb stork? What does a stork
have to do with newborns?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hel-lo,'' Horneck replies, ``how else do the babies get
there?''
</P>
<P>
   Alexis' black dress pants are now a size 10. That came with
having a third son, she says. The weight came off easily enough the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   She had her first boy when she was 25, modeling like crazy and
using an IUD. It was a surprise, both to her and her first husband,
a Jacksonville businessman. ``God determined when I would have
kids,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   With Alexis, ``God'' is not just a toss-off comment, like
``knock on wood.'' She walks into her dressing room and returns
with her Bible, in its quilted blue carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bad marriage,'' she says, talking about her first
husband. ``I reestablished myself with this.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past seven years, she has answered fan mail with her
photo and a verse of Scripture. When asked about her most unusual
fan, this is her answer:
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four months ago, a man wrote me back. He said he was
planning to murder his cellmate. But he got my picture with the
Scripture in a swap. He said he pulled it out and read it, and it
changed him. He really had had the whole thing planned out.''
</P>
<P>
   (The quote was from Romans, Chapter 12: ``Recompense no man evil
for evil. Provide things honest in the sight of all men. If it be
possible, as much lieth in you, live peaceably with all men.'')
</P>
<P>
   She put that story in her new book, A Model for a Better Future,
which she describes as a Christian book on morals and a self-help
book for mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Her philosophy now, she says, is ``What's the use of something
if it doesn't benefit people?''
</P>
<P>
   So she picks projects such as her other television show, Healthy
Kids, for the Family Channel, or her appearances on the 700 Club,
where she is the fashion and nutrition correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   If she hadn't moved from modeling to speaking roles, she says,
she either would be retired from the business or doing catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   No nips or tucks or lifts for her, no surgical anti-aging magic.
She doesn't even diet. `` `Diet' is a stupid word _ no one knows
what it means anymore,'' she says. Because she is allergic to
anything made with wheat, though, she eats carefully. Veggies, eggs
and meat, lots of salad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sparkle in my eyes is from the inside,'' Alexis says, and
she doesn't mean that to be sappy.
</P>
<P>
   Modeling, it turns out, was a fine way to make a living. Alexis
would love to land the cover of Vogue again, but if she asked, she
says, ``they'd laugh at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall, ``All-American'' blondes have given way to models with
what she calls a ``peculiar'' look. Quirky is in.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she's 38 and a size 10. As always, incredibly young and
incredibly thin is in, too.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis says the young models today are not as . . . she pauses,
then comes up with three words: trained, responsible, and
conscientious. ``They expect to be paid and don't expect to work as
much,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Example _ if I were modeling today, I would be standing
instead of sitting now, so I wouldn't be wrinkling the pants. These
girls are all over the place, goofing up their hairdos. They're not
as self-conscious.''
</P>
<P>
   She was raised to be responsible, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't there anything she's done that she wouldn't want her kids
doing? Hmmm, she can't think. In high school in upstate New York,
when she wasn't swimming or marching in the band, she even asked
for extra homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' she says, finally, ``maybe I would say, `Don't go to New
York City at age 18.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Too late, perhaps. Her oldest son, Jamie, 12, recently was
``discovered'' by a talent scout. He has not yet started modeling,
Alexis says.
</P>
<P>
   But Mom is looking for agencies now. As usual, she'll carry her
Bible with her.
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
