<HEADER>
A0624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS21-TAKE     01-20 1768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS21-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ Take One.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or E-mail
him at q&AMP;(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that England's Royal Mint had
introduced a coin in memory of Princess Diana, with her portrait on
one side and the image of Queen Elizabeth II on the other. How can
I obtain one?
</P>
<P>
   A: The memorial coin, introduced in London Jan. 5, is available
now in cupro-nickel, with gold and silver proof coins to follow
later in the spring. The commemorative, with a portrait of Diana in
profile on one side and the standard image of Queen Elizabeth II on
the other, is about the size of a silver dollar. The initial
version costs $14.95, plus $4.95 for postage and handing. The price
of the silver and golf proof coins will be announced later. In the
United States, orders and inquiries should be addressed to the
British Royal Mint, Cheyenne, WY 82008-0031. For information, call
1-800-221-1215.
</P>
<P>
   Each coin is packaged with a selection of photographs of the
princess and printed quotes from Queen Elizabeth and Earl Spencer,
Diana's brother. Beginning July 1, the cupro-nickel BU (Brilliant
Uncirculated) memorial coin will be available from banks and post
offices in the United Kingdom at its face value of five pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can a man who says he speaks no English and is not a U.S.
citizen receive a summons to become a juror?
</P>
<P>
   A: Names of potential jurors are obtained from several sources,
and they don't deal with the person's language ability. But jurors
must be U.S. citizens, so non-citizens who receive a summons need
to respond to the court, indicating their non-citizen status, which
makes them not qualified to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can we bid on the O.J. Simpson items that will be
auctioned in Los Angeles?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absentee bidders will be able to purchase a catalog for $10
describing items contained in the 75 lots of sports memorabilia,
furniture and decorative arts, rugs and paintings seized by court
order from Simpson's residence. The catalog just went to the
printer, Butterfield spokesman Levi Morgan told Q&AMP;A, and is
expected to be ready Jan. 25-26. It will have the complete
inventory, so potential bidders will be able to select items of
interest and submit absentee bids by fax or phone. Catalogs can be
ordered by calling 1-800-223-2854 (extension 525) or via the
auction house's Web site (http://www.butterfields.com). Morgan said
more than 60 percent of Butterfield's buyers make absentee bids
instead of attending auctions in person at the firm's galleries in
Los Angeles, San Francisco and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The property will be available for public preview 9 a.m.-5 p.m.
Feb. 12 at the Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield gallery, 7601 Sunset
Blvd., Los Angeles, with items offered to highest bidders starting
at 6 p.m. (local time) Feb. 16. The property, consigned for sale by
attorney Michael Myers, the State Court receiver, is to be sold on
behalf of the families of Simpson's ex-wife, Nicole Brown Simpson,
and Ronald Goldman, both murdered in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Included among the auction items are about 90 of Simpson's
sports trophies, including his 1968 Heisman Trophy, as well as
several Tiffany style lamps, Asian furniture, and a painting,
``Picasso Girl,'' by former disco diva Donna Summer.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield, 323-850-5843.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article reported that U.S. planes returned to the
aircraft carrier Carl Vinson after carrying out a raid against
Iraq. Who is or was Carl Vinson, and why is an aircraft carrier
named after him?
</P>
<P>
   A: The USS Carl Vinson (CVN 70, nicknamed ``The Gold Eagle,''),
the third Nimitz-class aircraft carrier to be commissioned, is part
of the Navy's Pacific fleet. Vinson (Nov. 18, 1883-June 1, 1981), a
Democrat, served two terms in the Georgia House of Representatives
and in 1914 won a race for a vacant seat in the U.S. House of
Representatives. He served in Congress from Nov. 3, 1914, to Jan.
3, 1965. In the House, he was chairman of the Armed Services
Committee 1949-53 and again 1955-65. During the 1930s, Vinson,
grand-uncle of former Sen. Sam Nunn, advocated a substantial
strengthening of the Navy. Believing that peace depended upon a
strong military posture, in 1950 Vinson criticized defense
reductions proposed by Defense Secretary Louis Johnson. During the
Eisenhower administration, Vinson opposed the doctrine of massive
retaliation relying on nuclear weapons, and emphasized instead the
importance of maintaining a strong conventional force capable of
dealing with less than total war.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can we determine how long food products will be safe to
consume? With the year 2000 coming up and Y2K problems expected,
many people will be stocking up on supplies.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not a food-safety issue, said nutritionist Chris
Rosenbloom, professor at Georgia State University and spokeswoman
for the American Dietetic Association. To assure optimal quality,
look for canned goods with a ``best if used by'' date on the label
or can. Most canned foods are safe for one year, she added, and
their shelf life can be assured by storing in a cool, clean and
dark pantry or cupboard.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen foods stay good for four months to 12 months, depending
on the type of food. A whole cut of meat, for example, lasts longer
than something that has been cut up. The foods should be frozen in
their original packaging, because commercial packaging usually is
air-tight, Rosenbloom added. Items such as non-fat dry milk also
can be stored, because all you do is add water when you need it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw a billboard saying the rock group Hole is up for a
Grammy award. Can you print some background information about them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's the scoop, excerpted from The New Rolling Stone
Encyclopedia of Rock &AMP; Roll. Hole was formed in Los Angeles in 1990
by Courney Love. By the time she formed the group with Eric
Erlandson, Love already had appeared as a vocalist in San Francisco
in an early incarnation of Faith No More and the all-female band
Sugar Baby Doll.
</P>
<P>
   Hole began garnering attention with live performances and two
early singles, ``Dicknail'' and ``Retard Girl,'' and English tours
and the two recordings made Hole the darling of the United Kingdom
music press. Things slowed down during Love's courtship and
eventual marriage, in 1992, to Nirvana's Kurt Cobain. In 1994,
Cobain was found dead of a self-inflicted gunshot wound, at the
same time Love's album ``Live Through This'' (with Erlandson, Patty
Schemel and Kristen Pfaff) was winning rave reviews. After bassist
Pfaff overdosed on heroin in 1994, Love enlisted Canadian bassist
Melissa Auf Der Maur.
</P>
<P>
   Love's ``Celebrity Skin'' is up for three Grammies, including
rock album.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend told me that Atlanta is second only to Denver in
elevation among major U.S. cities. Is that true?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Several cities with sizable populations are higher. Here
are some examples, with populations based on July 1996 Census
Bureau estimates, and elevations: Denver, 497,840 (5,260 feet);
Albuquerque, N.M., 419,681 (4,955 feet); El Paso, Texas, 599,865
(3,695 feet); Tucson, Ariz., 449,002 (2,390 feet); Las Vegas,
376,906 (2,000 feet); Oklahoma City, 469,852 (1,195 feet); Phoenix,
1,159,014 (1,090 feet); and Atlanta, 401,907 (1,050 feet).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the FBI still have people in North Carolina searching
for Eric Robert Rudolph?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Most certainly we do,'' said FBI spokeswoman Celestine
Armstead. ``There likely will be a presence there until Rudolph is
captured.'' The Southeast Bomb Task Force is made up of agents from
the FBI; Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms; and Georgia
Bureau of Investigation, she added. Rudolph has been charged with
the fatal bombing at Atlanta's Centennial Olympic Park July 27,
1996; the double bombings at the Sandy Springs, Ga., Professional
Building Jan. 16, 1997; the double bombings at Atlanta's Otherside
Lounge Feb. 21, 1997; and the bombing of the New Woman All Women
Health Care Clinic in Birmingham, Ala., Jan. 29, 1998, killing
Birmingham police officer Robert Sanderson and severely injuring
Emily Lyons, the clinic's head nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the ``super collider'' that was in the
news several years ago? Were any significant developments
attributed to it, or was the project scrapped?
</P>
<P>
   A: The super-costly project collided with budget realities and
was stopped in its tracks, but only after $2 billion had been spent
on it. The Superconducting Supercollider (SCC), designed to allow
physicists to create and study high-speed collisions of atomic
particles, was approved by Congress in 1989 after the selection of
a site near Waxahachie, Texas. Its development was dogged by
construction delays and cost overruns, and many scientists had
questioned its practical value.
</P>
<P>
   Although the project survived several congressional attempts to
kill it, it finally bit the dust for good in 1993 when the House
voted to order House-Senate conferees to revise a bill attempting
to keep it alive and kill it for good. Under a conference-committee
agreement, the $640 million originally allocated to the SSC for
1994 was left in the energy bill to pay to shut down the project,
whose costs to complete by then had escalated to a predicted $4.4
billion. More than 14 miles of particle-collision tunnel and dozens
of other facilities had been built, but had to be dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was reading your recent answer about the people in the
Taster's Choice commercials, it occurred to me that Michael, the
man across the hall, is none other than Giles on ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer.'' Can you confirm? Who are the other actors in the
now-canceled Taster's Choice romantic triangle?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're right about the actor portraying Michael in the coffee
commercials. He is Anthony Stewart Head, who later would become
Rupert Giles, the mentor of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'' Sharon
Maughan played the woman in the commercials and Trevor Eve was her
ex-husband. Maughan and Head are British stage performers who
played similar romantic parts in TV commercials for Gold Blend
coffee, a Nestle's brand sold in Britain. Eve, also British, played
a much heftier role in a two-part drama, ``The Politician's Wife,''
aired in 1996 by Masterpiece Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
