<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS21-TAKE     01-20 1774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS21-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that political public opinion polls are conducted
by organizations that call people's homes on weekdays between 8
a.m. and 5 p.m.? Most working-class Americans wouldn't be home, so
it wouldn't be a fair cross-section.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Gallup Organization, which calls itself ``the world's
leading source for public opinion data since 1935,'' says its
polling hours are restricted to 5 p.m.- 9:50 p.m. weekdays, 10
a.m.-6 p.m. Saturdays, and 3 p.m.-9 p.m. Sundays. ``People who say
we call during daytime hours on weekdays are misinformed,'' said
Maura Strausberg, research librarian at Gallup's headquarters in
Princeton, N.J. She also said telephone numbers are computer-picked
at random, and people are not asked their political affiliation,
``so if people are upset with what the polls show, that means
they're upset with the American public.'' Gallup's procedures and
findings on political and other polls are consistent with those of
other polling organizations, Strausberg added.
</P>
<P>
   Information can be found online at www.gallup.com and click on
How Polls Are Conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently reported on donations to the American Red Cross
while Elizabeth Dole was its president. Is Hillary Rodham Clinton
still the spokeswoman for the Salvation Army? What were the total
contributions from the time she was appointed until now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Clinton's role with the Salvation Army was not comparable to
that of Dole, president of the American Red Cross for eight years.
Clinton was spokeswoman only for the Salvation Army's 1994
Christmas campaign. It was a one-time fund-raising effort. In 1994,
the organization's Christmas kettle campaign raised about $65
million, about $1 million more than the previous season, said Army
spokesman Lt. Col. Tom Jones. Several previous first ladies,
including Eleanor Roosevelt and Barbara Bush, had been national
campaign chairpersons, as have nonpolitical figures such as Johnny
Carson. There was no national spokesperson this past holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm sure I read somewhere that there would be no leap year in
2000. I can't recall the reason. Can you advise me?
</P>
<P>
   A: Next yearwill be a leap year and will have a Feb. 29. As
explained in World Almanac 1999, a leap year occurs in every year
that can be evenly divided by four, except the years that mark the
even hundreds, such as 1500. The only century years that are leap
years are those that can be divided by 400, such as 1600 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can you tell me about Italian tenor Andrea Bocelli? I
haven't been able to find out much about his developing career or
his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   A: Bocelli grew up among the vineyards and olive groves of his
family estate in Lajatico, a community in rural Tuscany near Pisa.
Visually impaired by glaucoma from birth, he was struck in the head
by a soccer ball at 12 and lost the remainder of his sight due to a
brain hemorrhage. He studied piano as a child, and learned to play
both flute and saxophone, at the same time developing a passion for
opera. He studied law at the University of Pisa, earning a law
degree in 1986. While in law school, he earned money by performing
in piano bars.
</P>
<P>
   After a year as a court-appointed defense attorney, Bocelli quit
and began studying voice with tenor Franco Corelli, continuing to
appear at piano bars to pay for lessons. In 1987, a student, Enrica
Cenzatti, walked in and fell in love ``first with his voice, then
with him,'' as she once told an interviewer. Married in 1992, they
have two sons.
</P>
<P>
   After winning an audition, Bocelli toured Europe in 1992 with
Italian rock star Zucchero Fornaciari. The next year Bocelli made
his first recording, and in 1994 he recorded his first album, which
went platinum in a matter of weeks. His 1996 single of ``Con te
Partiro'' (``Time to Say Goodbye'') broke sales records across
Europe, and was followed by ``Romanza'' (``Romance''), a collection
of ballads that topped charts worldwide. Earlier this month he was
nominated for a Grammy in the ``new artist'' category.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of insurance policy would President Clinton have
that would give him $475,000 to apply to the Paula Jones $850,000
settlement? Do we know the name of the insurance company?
</P>
<P>
   A: The company is Chubb Group Insurance, which had funded part
of Clinton's legal defense. Administration officials said $475,000
came from a Chubb policy against civil liability that Clinton
purchased years ago, before he was president. The policy is known
as a personal liability umbrella, an option often available on
standard homeowners' policies.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $375,000 of the Jones settlement came from a blind
trust containing investments for the president and Hillary Rodham
Clinton. That was personal money, most of it made by the first
lady, who has been the family's major breadwinner during the
president's 25-year political career.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw where Barbra Streisand will perform at the MGM Grand in
Las Vegas on New Year's Eve 1999. Do you have any information about
tickets?
</P>
<P>
   A: No information is available yet, according to the casino
hotel. Those interested are welcome to call 702-891-7488 later to
check, but at this time no reservations are being taken, and no
confirmation of anything is available, a spokeswoman for MGM Grand
VIP Casino Services told Q&AMP;A. She couldn't even provide a suggested
date when information might become available, but said people ``can
call as often as they wish.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard a quote that ``the sword of Damocles may hang over
Clinton's head.'' Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both Cicero and Horace tell the story of the flatterer
Damocles, a 5th century court follower of Dionysius I (405-367
B.C.), the Elder of Syracuse. Damocles annoyed Dionysius with his
constant references to the ruler's great power and consequent
happiness. Deciding to teach the sycophant the real perils of
power, he invited Damocles to a magnificent banquet, surrounding
him with luxuries that only a king could afford. Damocles enjoyed
the feast until he glanced up and saw a sword, suspended by a
single hair, pointing directly at his head, after he which he lay
there cowering, afraid to eat, speak or move.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson was that there always are threats of danger, fears
and worries that prevent the powerful from fully enjoying their
power. The ``sword of Damocles'' has become a symbol of those
fears.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When a vehicle is entering an Interstate highway from an
on-ramp, who has the right of way? I always understood that it was
the entering vehicle, unless signs state otherwise, but I don't
think a lot of drivers out there know this.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's the responsibility of the driver coming down the ramp to
merge safely into traffic, said Pam Short of the Georgia Department
of Public Safety. To put it the other way, it is not the
responsibility of drivers already on the Interstate to let the
entering vehicles in. So, the traffic already on the highway has
the right of way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the U.N. resolution authorizing the United States to
establish the no-fly zone over northern and southern Iraq?
</P>
<P>
   A: After Iraq's 1991 loss in the Gulf War, Iraqi troops launched
a campaign of repression against Kurds, mostly in northern Iraq,
and other people opposed to Iraqi President Saddam Hussein. Those
actions were condemned by the United Nations Security Council in
U.N. Resolution 688, which ordered Iraq to end the repression. To
enforce the U.N. resolution, and to check the Iraqi military, the
United States and its Gulf War coalition partners told Iraq its
military aircraft would be shot down if they flew north of the 36th
parallel or south of the 32nd parallel. The southern boundary later
was raised to the 33rd parallel.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the telecasts of pro football games, viewers could see an
imaginary line showing where the offense needed to go for the first
down. How is that done?
</P>
<P>
   A: L-VIS (Live Video Insertion System), developed by Princeton
(N.J.) Video Images, is described by the company as ``a system of
proprietary hardware and software designed to insert electronic
images into live televised broadcasts.'' The inserted images may be
two- or three-dimensional, static or animated, opaque or
semitransparent, and may be placed so they appear to exist on the
playing field. If a player or other object moves in front of an
inserted image, the L-VIS system is programmed so that the passing
object obscures that portion of the inserted image.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Epstein of Princeton Video Image told Q&AMP;A that
applications can be tailored to the market of specific TV
audiences. For example, an advertising image can be made to appear
on the wall of a stadium behind a pitcher, let's say in a game
between the San Francisco Giants and the San Diego Padres. People
at the ballpark may see a blank wall; TV viewers in San Diego will
see an advertisement from a company targeting them; and TV viewers
in San Francisco may see yet another image tailored specifically
for them. Before the broadcast, the images to be inserted _ such as
the first-down line _ are prepared and the operator identifies the
location in the broadcast scene where they will be inserted. The
L-VIS system recognizes the scene in ``real time'' during the
broadcast and inserts the image as instructed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is NBC's Tom Brokaw's professional and educational
background?
</P>
<P>
   A: He started at KMTV in Omaha, Neb., where he was morning news
editor in 1962-65. In 1965-66, he was a news editor and anchor of
the 11 p.m. nightly news broadcast at WSB-TV in Atlanta. As
explained in Current Biography, since NBC didn't have a
network-staffed bureau in the South at that time, Brokaw also
contributed occasional reports on the burgeoning civil rights
movement to the network's ``Huntley-Brinkley Report.'' In 1966
Brokaw moved to the West Coast to become a reporter, and
subsequently anchor, of the late-night newscasts at KNBC-TV, the
network's owned-and-operated station in Los Angeles. In April 1971
he was chosen by NBC to anchor an edition of ``First Tuesday,''
NBC's monthly prime-time news magazine. In 1973 he became NBC's
White House correspondent, and in 1976 he took over as host of
``Today.'' In 1982 he became anchor and editor at ``NBC Nightly
News.''
</P>
<P>
   Born Thomas John Brokaw on Feb. 6, 1940, in Webster, S.D., he
graduated in 1962 with a degree in political science from the
University of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
