A0630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN21-CO     01-20 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Headline here
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas Lawyer jokes ... You like 'em, I like 'em, grandma
likes 'em, everybody likes lawyer jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one I bet you haven't heard, though it's been around for
some 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Lee Thompson, having gone to school on the GI-Bill after
serving in World War II, had finally gotten his law degree,
returned home to Lufkin and hung out his shingle, eager for
business.
</P>
<P>
   Business, at it turned out, wasn't so eager for him. Days passed
into weeks, weeks into months while Billy Lee lived day to day,
hand to mouth, trying to support his young family.
</P>
<P>
   His friend and colleague, Clark Anderson, sought to reassure him
that the business would come, just give it time. This very day,
Clark would say, might be the day when the kind of lawsuit a lawyer
dreams of comes your way.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Billy Lee put much stock in what his friend said. Clark
was a good lawyer, but more than the law, Clark enjoyed a good
time. The secret to a happy life, he'd tell you, was to be happy.
</P>
<P>
   But, 'lo and behold, there came a day when a letter arrived in
Billy Lee's mail that promised exactly what Clark had predicted the
kind of lawsuit a lawyer dreams of.
</P>
<P>
   Scratched out in pencil on notebook paper, it read something
like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Lee Billy,
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard from our cousin that you have made a lawyer. I want
you know how proud I am. I always knew you would do good. You come
from fine folks, your mother especially.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you are busy being an important lawyer at the county
seat, but I hope you can find it in your heart to help me with this
terrible thing that has happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few months back, one of the company trucks ran over me while
I was walking past the mill on my way to Wednesday night prayer
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driver was drunk, like he always is half the time.
Everybody had been telling the company they ought to fire him
before something like this happened, but they wouldn't listen. I
don't know why, but some people say it's because he is a nephew of
the owner's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upshot is, I am hurt bad in my back so that I can't hardly
get around. The company wants me to take some cash they've offered
but it doesn't seem like very much for how bad hurt I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much left, except those the medals I brought back
from the war. I am hoping you can advise me on what to do. I am
afraid they are trying to take advantage of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still live in the same place, behind the school. You can
find it easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truly yours,
</P>
<P>
   ``Cousin John.
</P>
<P>
   ``P.S. Remember me to your dear mother.''
</P>
<P>
   No return address, no telephone number. The postmark indicated a
rural area that covered much of the south end of the county.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Lee searched his memory for a clue as to Cousin John's
identity. He asked friends and family, and though some had a vague
recollection, nobody could recall for sure a Cousin John.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Lee took it on himself to find Cousin John, leaving the
office for days at time, when he should have been working on deeds
and wills, driving the farm roads of the county, searching for that
house behind that school, wherever it was.
</P>
<P>
   It was several weeks later that the second letter arrived:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Lee Billy,
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought by now I would have heard something from you. I know
you must be busy but I need help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company lawyer is nagging me to sign a paper and take
their deal. I don't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``My back is getting worse, and the medicine the doctor
prescribed is awfully expensive. I am here almost all the time.
Please contact me soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truly yours,
</P>
<P>
   ``Cousin John.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Lee searched the south part of the county, the north part
of the county, the river roads and pig trails, but no Cousin John.
He was losing sleep over it and, worse, knew that he was about to
lose the chance of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   He could think of little else, night and day, even at parties
when members of the county bar association got together for no
other reason than to celebrate being lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   There Billy Lee stood, a cold drink in his hand, wondering if
he'd ever hear from Cousin John again, when Clark eased up behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   Slapping him on the back, Clark inquired, ``How you doing, Lee
Billy?''
</P>
<P>
   So it was, all those years ago, when lawyer jokes were the jokes
lawyers played on each other.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Billy Lee and Clark are now lawyers in heaven where, I
imagine, Clark is having a good time and Billy Lee is still trying
to get even.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
