<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, January 21, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-CLINTON _ Clinton's State of the Union speech reveals
his incessant focus on himself. (Matthews, Atlanta Journal).
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ I've never analyzed nuisance calls from
telemarketers with a stopwatch. My method to prevent telephone
salesmen from invading my privacy with their relentless sales
pitches is to allow my answering machine to pick up telephone
calls. Very few telemarketers will leave a message on an answering
machine. They just dial some another poor sap's telephone. They
play the odds. Eventually, someone will answer and present the
opportunity for money to flow into the caller's bank account.
(Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ It was the editors' idea that I
attend the George W. Bush Inaugural Ball for people 35 and under.
My bosses think it's funny to send an old, limping, sore,
gray-headed columnist such as myself to the young people's affair
to see if they'll actually let me in. Of course, they let me into
the Young Texans Ball. The Republicans sold me a ticket for $40 to
get in, just like they did to everybody else. What do they care how
old I am? All they wanted was my money. (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN- Billy Lee Thompson, having gone to school on
the GI-Bill after serving in World War II, had finally gotten his
law degree, returned home to Lufkin and hung out his shingle, eager
for business. (Murray, Lufkin Daily News)
</P>
