<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Thursday, January
21, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   THE LAYOUT'S DONE FOR YOU: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are
available for purchase in paginated form:
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-JEWS _ She saw Halley's Comet, crawling out of bed at 3
a.m. on May 16, 1910, worried about ``what will happen to us when
we pass through its tail.'' She was horrified when Leo Frank, a
friend and her husband's first cousin, was lynched in 1915 within
20 miles of her Atlanta home on Washington Street by an
anti-Semitic mob. She was ``shocked'' when the Titanic went down,
but ``thrilled'' by the countless ``acts of self-sacrifice'' of
doomed men ``standing bravely, calmly, even gaily'' as they helped
women and children fill the lifeboats. She gave refuge to refuge to
a family of African-Americans during bloody race riots here in 1906
in which 10 blacks and two whites were killed. She sent her three
Jewish brothers - one with the unlikely nickname of Bubba - off to
fight in World War I, tried to ignore the latent and blatent
anti-Semitism of early 20th century Atlanta. Helen Jacobus Apte,
born in Hawkinsville in 1886, was an ``ordinary'' Atlanta
housewife, fiercely proud of being Jewish and a southerner, who
faithfully recorded the history of the city, and the world, in a
diary she kept from her marriage in 1909 until her death in 1946.
Found by chance in 1995, her elegantly-written words have just been
published in a new book, ``Heart of a Wife: The Diary of a Southern
Jewish Woman,'' that records in detail most important events that
occurred over some four decades. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 45. WITH ILLUSTRATION and PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FEMINISTS _ The feminist movement sold women the wrong bill of
goods, making women believe they could postpone marriage and
children to concentrate on their careers. But now the daughters of
women who followed those rules are realizing they can't have it
all, says Diane Crittenden. She urges women to get married young,
have children early and put family over career. Crittenden, 35, is
editor of Women's Quarterly, a conservative newsletter, and her new
book is ``What Our Mothers Didn't Tell Us.'' (Hill, Atlanta
Journal-Cnstitution). 20-25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   RENOIR _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Pierre-Auguste Renoir is one of
the world's great painters. Al Hirschfeld is one of the century's
great caricaturists. Masters in different fields, their work
celebrates life. Renoir died in 1916 at 78, after creating about
6,000 paintings. He never stopped working despite crippling
arthritis. At 95, Hirschfeld continues to produce his lively
drawings of show-biz personalities for The New York Times. There's
another connection between these two different artists _ both have
shows in Boca Raton. (Schwan, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRACE-ADKINS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In John Wayne-speak,
country singer Trace Adkins is one tough hombre. Consider that the
6-foot-6, 37-year-old Louisiana native has weathered a hurricane
while working on an offshore oil rig. He's survived two near-fatal
car accidents _ his nose had to be sewed back on after one of
those. He lopped off his left pinkie once while opening an oil
barrel and told doctors to sew it back on at an angle so he could
still play guitar. A bulldozer nearly cut off his legs. And an
ex-wife once shot him through the heart. All of which adds gravity
when he says that his next album, due out later this year, is ``do
or die'' for his career. Do or die for a guy who's almost bought
the farm so many times? Sounds serious. (Houck, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LAST-WEIGHTPLAN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Cynthia Last was
disgusted with her obesity. A teenager struggling with self-worth,
she vowed not to let her looks define her. ``I figured my best
chance of finding success was by developing my intellect,'' she
writes in her new book, The 5 Reasons Why We Overeat: How to
Develop a Long-Term Weight Control Plan That's Right for You
($19.95, Birch Lane Press.) She dissolved from a size 11 to a size
5, a weight loss she's maintained for 20 years. (Susman, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKWOMEN-WANT _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Looks didn't even make
the list. (Not that anybody would mind a date with Denzel
Washington...) Spirituality, sensitivity and strength of character
are the most vital traits in a mate, according to a new book called
All the Man I Need: Black Women's Loving Expressions on the Men
They Desire. (Grantham, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTIFUL-CHICKS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bleach jobs and
blow-drys, clipped nails and preening. Yes, it's chicken-judging
time at the South Florida Fair. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KIM-ALEXIS _ DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ At first, former supermodel
Kim Alexis is so perfect, so distressingly polished, that you want
to shake her until her teeth (never a cavity!) rattle like a
handful of dice. It's not her fault, really. She just keeps saying
these things in that calm, pleasant, TV-ready voice. Things like,
``I was a great kid. I can't imagine that I did much wrong.'' And
``My morning routine takes about two minutes.'' (Anna, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HUMMEL-MUSEUM _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Inside a vault that guards a
trove of loaned artwork sits a portrait of the artist as a young
nun. The black and white photograph of a smiling Sister Maria
Innocentia _ her hands neatly tucked in the sleeves of her habit _
stands out against the vault's white walls and the stacks of
cardboard boxes that hold her drawings. The German nun, born Berta
Hummel, is internationally recognized as the artist whose drawings
captured tender moments of children at play. She also is the
namesake of the Hummel Museum _ a source of civic pride in this
city whose heritage is distinctly German. Now, a little more than
six years after it opened, the Hummel Museum has hit hard times.
(Perkes, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   ARTEXHIBIT-NELLIE _ NEW YORK _ Scene piece from the opening of
the Nellie Mae Rowe exhibit at the American Museum of Folk Art in
New York. This show puts the metro Atlanta artist, who died in
1982, on the map. Story will explain why this is important and talk
to all the players who made it happen: collector Judith Alexander,
curator Lee Kogan, etc. (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
40ish. WITH PHOTOS. (Rowe, her art).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NELLIE-BIO _ Quick look at Nellie Mae Rowe. (Brock, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).10.
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOOD _ FOOD 0115 _ If your New Year's resolution included
eating healthy and losing weight, you probably put Tex-Mex food on
the ``red light'' list. No more nachos nuked in the microwave. No
more Friday lunches at the cantina with the gang from work. But
everyone knows today's deprivation is likely to be tomorrow's
binge. So we have a better plan. Go ahead and dine on some
favorites, such as guacamole and enchiladas, but use lighter
recipes that are loaded with flavor, not fat. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet FOOD page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BURNSCLUB _ Throughout the country and in parts of Atlanta,
those of Scottish decent celebrate the birth of their country's
favorite poet with Burns' night suppers. Though the centerpiece is
always haggis _ an aquired taste for sure _ the rest of the meal
will likely have more universal appeal. (Lee, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BURNSCLUB-RECIPES _ Recipe page to go with BURNSCLUB story
centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Lee, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
Rocky Road Candy. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. This week: The Super Bowl party table.
(Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN _ Not available this week.
</P>
<P>
   SALMON _ Salmon has replaced tuna as the most popular fish among
Americans. (Heller, Dayton Daily News). WITH ILLUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-RECIPES _ Dayton area chefs reveal their favorite salmon
preparations. (Heller, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
