   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS (San Francisco) _ 1998 was the most brutal year of the
decade for job cuts nationwide, according to the outplacement firm
of Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas. Nobody can say employers don't
give 110 percent; last year's 677,795 cuts surpassed the worst
previous carnage (1993) by 10 percent and were 56 percent worse
than in 1997. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   PORTALS (San Francisco) _ The recent multibillion dollar Web
mergers are about who's going to rule the next generation of
couch/computer potatoes _ and their credit cards. The enormous sums
being paid for portals, some analysts and industry insiders say,
are based on the possibility of accessing personal data on the
flood of home Internet users expected to come on-line as affordable
high-speed Internet access breaks out in the consumer market. By
MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   HOT-REAL-ESTATE (San Francisco) _ The real estate agents who
sold a two-bedroom penthouse for $15 million cut threw the ceiling
on high-priced property in San Francisco. The price made it the
most expensive home ever sold in San Francisco and was double the
previous high of $7.5 million fetched in 1997 for a Pacific Heights
showcase mansion. By CORRIE M. ANDERS.
</P>
