<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-BIZ-ONLINE-SHOP-A     01-20 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-BIZ-ONLINE-SHOP-ART-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLICK FOR CUSTOMER SERVICE. THEN WISH YOU HADN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. 
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If online retailers steamrolled their way into the spotlight
during the past holiday season, one thing is clear: They crushed a
few toes along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have long lamented the state of customer service on
line, but perhaps never as vociferously as in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   Stories abound of vendors that shipped late, sent the wrong
product and then ignored complaints, or that required customers to
pay the cost of returning goods and then tacked on restocking
charges. And then there's the loathsome ``auto response''
electronic mail reply, with advice on everything but what the
customer asked about.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to sum up online customer service in a word, David
Cooperstein, senior analyst with Forrester Research, an Internet
consulting firm, responded: ``Pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Web sites have the powerful advantage of making companies seem
accessible and easy to interact with. it's an appearance that all
kinds of companies, not just retailing, can have troubl living up
to.
</P>
<P>
   Brightware, an e-mail software company, reported Thursday that
it had tried contacting the 100 largest American public companies
by e-mail. Twenty-six either did not accept e-mail or made it so
difficult to find the e-mail forms on their Web sites that the
surveyors gave up trying. Of the remainder, only 15 responded
within three hours; 10 didn't reply at all.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Garelick of Somerville, Mass., knows the frustration of
unrequited e-mail. In early December he ordered the movie ``Out of
Sight'' on DVD from Bigstar Entertainment, an online movie
retailer. Between Dec. 28 and Dec. 30, Garelick sent e-mail to
Bigstar three times, asking why the movie hadn't arrived. ``I
would've been fine with an auto response,'' said Garelick, who
eventually received the disk in January. ``I just wanted an
assurance that they were at least working on it. From now on, I'm
not doing business on line with anyone who doesn't have a phone
number.''
</P>
<P>
   Having a number to call was small comfort to Duke Nguyen of
Cincinnati. Nguyen said he ordered three items from the Internet
site of Intuit in early December and then tried to change his order
by phone. ``Every time, after 20 or so minutes of waiting, I gave
up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He tried faxing in his order change. but the original items were
delivered to him. ``Finally, I called and just put on my speaker
phone while I waited,'' he said. After an hour someone answered and
he was able to arrange a return. But then Intuit credited him for
less than the full value of the goods, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He tried using a new e-mail button on Intuit's Web site but got
an automated response suggesting, among other things, that he call
customer service. ``I'm computer-literate,'' Nguyen said. ``But
when it comes to service, these things scare the heck out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and industry leaders say problems often occur because
companies rush to get products and prices onto their Web sites
while underestimating the time and resources needed for customer
service.
</P>
<P>
   But David Levipsky, executive vice president of Bigstar, said
that wasn't the case with his site. The company had anticipated a
holiday rush by installing a ``very cutting-edge'' e-mail system,
he said, adding, ``So it's surprising to me that this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Intuit, Larry Wolfe, senior vice president for the
company's tax-software division, said the company does the best it
can. ``Often in December and January, there are times when people
wait longer than we'd like them to wait,'' he said. ``But we take
it very seriously, and we work very hard to keep call times down.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say poorly designed Web sites draw complaints. ``If a
site is designed well, most of the complaints don't happen,'' said
Cooperstein of Forrester, noting that many sites fail to offer
enough information so that customers can help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for consumers, analysts said, is that Internet
merchants are starting to learn two lessons: that ignoring e-mail
is the best way to turn customers into enemies, and that improving
Web sites is more cost-effective than dedicating battalions of
employees to answer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The e-mail deluge everybody was worried about we looked at as
a total gift,'' said Matt Hyde, director for online sales at REI, a
retailer of outdoor goods. ``We've made hundreds of changes to our
site based on customer service data.''
</P>
<P>
   A result: The ratio of e-mails to orders at REI dropped sharply,
he said, and so did payroll costs for customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer uses a combination of software and employees to
respond to its 10,000 weekly e-mails, answering three-quarters of
them within a day, said Manish Mehta, a senior online support
manager for the company. Dell's Web site features a wide range of
self-service information, including detailed technical support
tips.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers are becoming less tolerant of poor service from online
retailers. ``Consumer expectations have definitely grown, because
certain sites have set a high standard,'' said Jakob Nielsen, a
site design expert and publisher. ``Fair or unfair, other sites
have to live up to that standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps so. But Kent Krueger, co-founder of the Sitstay GoOut
Store, said sites that are honest with consumers can weather
service problems. Sitstay, which sells specialty products to dog
owners, was the only Web site to get a five-star rating for
customer support among 500 rated in December by Bizrate, a market
research company that surveys online shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started selling doormats with little Yorkies on them and
got a huge number of orders that we weren't prepared for,'' Krueger
said. ``So we got in touch with everyone and told them who we were,
what had happened, and we were working on it.'' As a result, he
said, no customers canceled orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, if you're honest and have a little fun, people
will have a good attitude,'' he added. ``But it could also be that
dog owners are just a different breed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-15-99 1845EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
