u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-NETFILES-SFCHRON &LR;      01-20 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETFILES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Support for Net Pioneer's UFO Theory  
 By Jon Swartz   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's all alien to me.
</P>
<P>
   The phone calls and e-mail poured in last week after The
Chronicle's front-page story on Joe Firmage, the Internet pioneer
who was forced to resign as chief strategist at USWeb/CKS because
of his belief in aliens and UFOs.
</P>
<P>
   Firmage's otherworldly theory, detailed in his 600-page online
treatise, ``The Truth'' (www.thewordistruth.org), is a doozy: He
links many of history's major religious and technological events to
``visits'' from extraterrestrials. He even recounts a close
encounter of the third kind in his Los Gatos home in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The readers' overwhelming verdict? Firmage, 28, is an earnest,
brilliant individual who has put the truth, as he sees it, before
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on to something big that bears further investigation,''
said Suleiman Edmondson, a writer-TV producer based in Richmond.
``What Joe is saying is very accurate. Elements of the secret
government know about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Harold Puthoff, a respected physicist at the Institute for
Advanced Studies in Austin, Texas: ``These are certainly
speculative and provocative theories, but on the other hand, he's
not a crackpot. As far as whetherwe'll meet up with E.T., the jury
is still out. The proof is yet to be found. The fact that (Firmage)
opened up the issue required a lot of courage. He stuck his neck
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Marrs, a journalist in Dallas who has written extensively
about UFOs and the Kennedy assassination, said: ``Firmage is a
brilliant guy. He picked the brains of top researchers to come up
with his ideas. There have been dozens of works on the
Roswell-technology connection.''
</P>
<P>
   An authoritative read is the 1997 book ``The Day After Roswell''
by the late Colonel Phillip J. Corso and Bill Birnes, publisher of
UFO Magazine in Los Angeles. Like Firmage, they contend that the
origins of high-tech inventions such as lasers and the microchip
can be traced to a purported alien spacecraft crash in 1947 in
Roswell, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Truman absolutely wanted technology companies like
Bell Labs and IBM to take a look at material from the wreckage,''
Birnes said. ``Joe is right on.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, a Daly City woman who supports Firmage, claims that
she has been visited by aliens 33 times and has been implanted with
alien materials. And another man swore that extraterrestrials are
in cold storage at the White House. Uh-huh.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing fan club and wall-to-wall media coverage
(CNN, ``Hard Copy,'' WCBS-AM), Firmage's unique views are
tantamount to career suicide. Be careful what you wish for.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, he tendered his resignation, and he has spent
the past few days fielding a blizzard of media requests. Fearing a
market and public relations backlash, executives of USWeb/CKS, an
Internet services company worth about $2 billion, are trying to
keep a low profile. Nonetheless, he has his defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the same skepticism about the JFK assassination when I
came out with my book (`Crossfire: The Plot to Kill Kennedy') in
1989,'' Marrs said. ``Now, my conclusions of a government
conspiracy are in the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   So does this whole high-tech episode merit a future segment on
``The X-Files''?
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the popular TV program declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   OVERSEAS INTERNET: The World Wide Web is an American fad but
hardly a hit in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While an estimated 60 million Americans _ almost a quarter of
the population _ are surfing the Web, less than 10 percent of
Europe's 350 million citizens regularly venture into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   A major culprit: Slow acceptance of telecom deregulation
overseas has limited online penetration in Europe. In Italy, for
example, only 5 percent of the population is connected to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That should change dramatically during the next few years,
however, as telecommunications rules loosen and foreign governments
encourage more Net connections to businesses and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Net will grow at an explosive rate, especially in
countries such as France, Sweden, Holland, Germany and England,
where Social Democratic governments are encouraging sales of
tax-free, low-cost computers,'' said Johan Stuel von Holstein,
founder of IconMedia Lab, the largest Internet service company in
Europe. ``Those countries want everyone to have access to PCs at
home and at work.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sweden, about 65 percent of the population is logged on.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, major European corporations, led by Volkswagen and
BMW, have vast Net access. Indeed, online-related revenues abroad
will skyrocket to $64.4 billion in 2001 but still lag far behind
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   SITE OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Animal lovers, check out www.friskypet.com, a Dear Abby site for
man's best friend and other pets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
