<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-REPORT19-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Browse without leaving a cookie trail 
By Mark Clothier  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Surfing the Web is getting to be a little like living
in a glass house _ much of what you do goes noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Those who run Web sites use things called ``cookies'' and
``referrers'' to see what we search for, where we go and what we
buy. The cookies and referrers give the information to Web sites,
market researchers and ad agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Most browsers let you control whether you want to accept
cookies. With Netscape's browser, you can find it under the
``edit'' part of the toolbar, then look in the ``advanced''
category.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, shutting off the cookie accepter shuts off your
access to some sites, or at least limits what you can do there.
</P>
<P>
   A software product from a Cambridge, Mass., company blocks
cookies for you, without limiting your access to different Web
sites. interMute which can be downloaded from
http://www.intermute.com, sells for $19.95. A 14-day trial copy is
free.
</P>
<P>
   The software also lets you restrict other things, including Java
applets (the bit-heavy applications that make Web site ingredients
flash, scroll and move), banner ads and background music.
</P>
<P>
   The program acts as a filter between your browser and the Web.
It works on most common browsers, including recent versions of
Microsoft's Internet Explorer and Netscape's browser. Once
installed, the program runs when the computer starts.
</P>
<P>
   interMute works on Windows 95, 98 and NT platforms, as well as
on UNIX and any Java-compatible system.
</P>
<P>
   Companies willing to pay to lure online shoppers
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, Forrester Research predicts advertisers will spend $605
million to get you to do your car shopping online, $187 million to
convince you to house-hunt online and $460 million so you will
check the Web classifieds for job openings. That's up from 1997
totals of $16 million, $5 million and $48 million for car, house
and job shopping online ad spending.
</P>
<P>
   So far, those doing the shopping are mostly just browsing. A
Millward Brown Interactive study asked 527 Internet users about
online auto-shopping habits. The 1998 study found that while 42
percent of those surveyed used the Internet to research their car
purchase, only 0.6 percent bought their car online.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly attractive features are likely to increase
those numbers. Some auto-shopping sites let you place a free
classified ad, find trade-in and market prices for cars, check loan
and insurance rates, and check through a database of recalls.
http://www.autoweb.com, http://www.carpoint.msn.com and
http://www.autos.yahoo.com offer several of those features.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a home loan on the Web is also becoming more popular.
Myers Internet Services predicts 12 percent of all mortgage
applications will take place on the Internet by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Portal sites such as http://www
</P>
<P>
   .excite.com and http://www.yahoo
</P>
<P>
   .com offer features that let you calculate mortgage rates and
get credit reports as well as information about schools and home
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Time to get a printer as good as your photos
</P>
<P>
   So, you got your new scanner or your digital camera for the
holidays, and now you want to start printing the pictures. But your
poor printer quality makes them look like pulp comic drawings.
</P>
<P>
   It might be time to upgrade your color printer to match your
scanner and digital camera. Hewlett-Packard released the HP DeskJet
882C for the home market. The photo-quality printer has a suggested
retail of $299.
</P>
<P>
   The new HP DeskJet prints up to eight pages per minute. It uses
Hewlett-Packard photo resolution enhancement color-layering
technology to print photo-quality images. The feature creates the
photo-quality image by blending tiny drops of ink.
</P>
<P>
   The printer comes with a CD-ROM that lets you edit your photos
and create greeting cards, banners and calendars.
</P>
<P>
   The printers are available at most major electronics retailers
and online at http://www.shopping.hp.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
