<HEADLINE>
I GOT THAT OL' MS. PAC-MAN FEVER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID HOYE   
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - One of my first jobs out of college was editing a
weekly newspaper in California's ``Silicon Valley.'' It was fun
putting out the ``Cupertino Courier,'' but I was a little too
efficient and found myself with lots of free time.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I never told the boss! Instead, I'd join a couple
other guys who edited other weekly newspapers owned by the same
newspaper chain and we'd all sneak across the parking lot to a
nearby convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   Our goal: The Ms. Pac-Man machine!
</P>
<P>
   I hate to admit this _ especially in print _ but we used to
spend about an hour a day pumping quarters into that stupid
machine, which stood in the store's front window and exposed us to
numerous odd looks from productive members of society.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't care. We were Ms. Pac-Man addicts. We lived for the
chance to guide Ms. Pac-Man through her maze, gobbling dots and the
four monsters. My friend, Steve, actually developed a sore wrist
from using the joystick too much.
</P>
<P>
   I know. It all sounds very pathetic. But it was fun. And we were
young and crazy.
</P>
<P>
   So what's my excuse now?
</P>
<P>
   Yep. Twenty years later, I find myself playing Ms. Pac-Man
again. This time it's on my home computer using Microsoft's Revenge
of Arcade. The $25 CD-ROM package comes with Ms. Pac-Man and other
ancient arcade games such as Rally-X and Mappy.
</P>
<P>
   I've had it for a few weeks now, and signs of my old addiction
are reappearing. Sometimes I sneak in to our spare room to play a
quick game. And I've even created a desktop shortcut so I can
launch Ms. Pac-Man without delay!
</P>
<P>
   There's something about those old arcade games that I can't
explain. Some of them never interested me. But some of them, not
just Ms. Pac-Man, are fun enough that I'd rather play one of them
instead of a new 3D adventure game.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, well. I consider myself lucky _ not because I can now play
Ms. Pac-Man without needing quarters, but because my wife has yet
to voice an observation I know she's made: Playing Ms. Pac-Man is
one heck of a sorry way to use a Pentium II computer! &QL; 
Macintosh news to use
</P>
<P>
   After the recent Macworld Expo/San Francisco '99 trade show,
Apple unveiled a number of new computer models, including Power Mac
G3s and iMacs that come in assorted colors, not just the original
translucent blue.
</P>
<P>
   PC-makers have taken notice of the iMac's popularity, which has
been credited with turning Apple back to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   (For a more detailed look at the new iMacs, check out Gene
Steinberg's column on Arizona Central at
www.azcentral.com/computing/news/mac/steinberg.shtml.)
</P>
<P>
   A prediction for 1999: By year's end, look for PC-makers to
offer PC versions of the iMac _ colorful and sculpted
IBM-compatible machines that will make the old beige boxes look,
well, like old beige boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of iMacs, Apple Computer has finally eased up on its
pricing. For several months, no matter where you looked to buy, an
iMac was going to cost you $1,299. Period. Now, retailers are free
to price according to demand. Initially, the cost of the all-in-one
machine dropped to about $999. But the last time I checked, some
online retailers were offering iMacs for $979.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MP3 to the rescue!
</P>
<P>
   In a recent column, I discussed the popular MP3 format for music
files. The technology has taken over music sites all over the Web,
offering computer users the ability to download near CD-quality
music in just minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, I've heard from several readers who have had trouble
downloading the necessary software to play MP3 files. Apparently,
many download sites have been too busy to handle all the download
requests.
</P>
<P>
   The download problem seems to have affected Macintosh users a
bit more severely, perhaps because Mac users tend to be more active
online than PC users. So, if you're a Mac user looking for a copy
of the MP3 player MacAmp, check out www.macamp.com. If that site is
busy, check a mirror site at
ftp://mirror.doit.wisc.edu/mirrors/apple/macamp/.
</P>
<P>
   If you love MP3 but want to play the files with something other
than WinAmp or Mac-Amp, a reader named Ron suggests you try
Sonique, an MP3 player for your PC made by Night55 Inc. You can try
Sonique at www.sonique.com.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sources tell me that the Diamond Rio, a Walkman-like
player that can hold up to 60 minutes of MP3 music files, will in
the future be able to play music files in other formats as well.
Some readers were wondering about that, as they've discovered that
MP3 isn't the only data-compression format being used on music
files.
</P>
<P>
   And did I say MP3 would be big? That prediction is holding true,
at least for now. An IDG.net reporter covering the recent Consumer
Electronics Show in Las Vegas reported that MP3 was on everybody's
mind. Samsung Electronics, for example, announced it will roll out
its own MP3 devices under the name Yepp. The devices don't have the
memory of Diamond's Rio, but are smaller, about the size of a
credit card. It seems as though the MP3 cat is out of the bag,
regardless of how strongly the recording industry opposes it. &QL; 
Don't worry. Be happy!
</P>
<P>
   Well, here we are in the final year before the dreaded Y2K bug
attacks. As you know, it's supposed to hit at midnight Jan. 1. What
say we all spend the night sitting in a cornfield somewhere?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, OK. Dumb idea. While we're thinking of what else to do, here
is some of the latest Y2K news:
</P>
<P>
   - From the I-Guess-This-Was-Bound-To-Happen Department:
``Wired'' magazine recently reported that Y2K blacklists are
starting to crop up. Yep. Companies that have solved their Y2K
problems don't want to mess with businesses that haven't solved
their Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wired'' reported that banks have started assigning customers
with low-, medium- or high-risk ratings. Even Federal Express has
gotten into the act, branding primary business partners with the
colors green, yellow or red depending on how much work they've done
toward solving their Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wired'' pointed out that some federal guidelines actually
require such ``leper lists'' be created as part of ``appropriate
risk control.''
</P>
<P>
   - Don't let the federal government's involvement in the ``leper
lists'' fool you. Uncle Sam is as far behind in solving its Y2K
problems as anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a reassuring quote from Joel Willemssen of the General
Accounting Office:
</P>
<P>
   ``All the government agencies will not be done on time,'' he
recently told CNN. ``There will be some failures. Right now as a
country we do not know where we stand on water, power and
telecommunications.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot dog! That cornfield is starting to sound better and better!
</P>
<P>
   - And if Y2K isn't enough for you to worry about, the ``New York
Times'' reports that there's a time-related glitch that will rear
its ugly head in certain Windows applications April 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The bug, which Microsoft has owned up to, will cause programs to
behave as if it was an hour earlier than the correct time shown by
internal Windows 95, 98 and NT clocks.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the bug is supposed to correct itself a
week later on April 8, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   So, start planning now. You'll be able to wander in to work an
hour late for an entire week in 2001. If the boss complains, you
can blame your home PC! &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-18-99 1309EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
