<HEADLINE>
FED OFFICIAL DISPUTES Y2K ECONOMIC CRISIS THEORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ROSS KERBER AND KIMBERLY BLANTON   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Casting aside gloomy predictions about the impact of
Year 2000 computer glitches on the economy, a top Federal Reserve
official said Tuesday she does not expect the US economy to go into
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Minehan, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston
and one of the co-chairs of the Fed's Y2K committee, disputed a
widely cited forecast that there is a 70 percent chance software
problems caused by the date change to Jan. 1, 2000 would lead to a
recession.
</P>
<P>
   The bleak forecast comes from the prominent Wall Street
economist, Ed Yardeni, who is chief economist of Deutsche Bank
Securities in New York. He predicts that software disruptions could
slow transportation, knock out telephone services, and generally
throw business operations off stride.
</P>
<P>
   By Yardeni's thinking, the impact of turning the calendar over
to Year 2000 would be comparable to the oil-price shocks of 1973,
which threw the United States into recession.
</P>
<P>
   Although Minehan has ``a lot of respect for Yardeni,'' she said
in an interview Tuesday, ``It just doesn't seem realistic to say
that it would produce, all by itself, a recession.''
</P>
<P>
   Minehan said she believes that a more moderate forecast by
DRI/McGraw Hill, the economic forecasting firm Lexington, Mass., is
more realistic. Released last March, DRI described a scenario in
which businesses are required to spend more and stock up on
computer hardware, adding about 0.1 percent to the economy's total
product in 1999. Then, in 2000, limited disruptions caused by
computer malfunctions as well as a loss of productivity by workers
could reduce GDP by just 0.2 percent. There is ``a 20 percent
probability that reality will be this bad or worse,'' DRI/McGraw's
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Minehan suggested it is also conceivable that businesses would
build inventories later this year. ``Just as some people might
themselves prudent if they took out a little extra cash, some
businesses might attempt to stock supplies and other things'' in
expectation of problems with their electricity or other services,
Minehan acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, the impact would be minimal, she said. The inventory
buildup would be adjusted in 2000 in what is known as an
``inventory cycle''; the two would cancel each other out.
</P>
<P>
   Minehan's comments were part of a broader push by the Fed to
bolster public confidence in the ability of large financial
institutions and the central bank system _ the lifeblood of the
economy _ to cope with the looming date change.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming specific economists, Fed Governor Edward W. Kelly
told a Senate committee last April that forecasts of a Y2K-induced
recession were ``probably a stretch.'' Kelly and Minehan are among
four co-chairs of a Fed committee preparing the US central bank for
2000 and assessing the potential impact on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Minehan's critique of Y2K economics appears to be the first
direct comment by a Fed official specifically about Yardeni's
forecast. Her comments take on added significance because she is
also chairwoman of separate Fed committee that has been working for
more than two years with the 12 regional banks and their member
financial institutions to prepare for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   On that point, Minehan sought to reassure: ``Everything at the
Fed that is mission critical is Y2K ready,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not realistic to think there will be no glitches either.
There will be glitches,'' she said. ``But, as far as we can see, at
this point, a reasonable scenario is that most important things
will work, at least from the perspective of the financial services
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Yardeni in an interview Tuesday, reiterated his
recession forecast, which was based in part on his reviews of
company filings to the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be right about this,'' Yardeni said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-19-99 1918EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
