<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE BLIND TO PLUSES OF HAVING 3-BUTTON MOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.1998 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I'm a computer novice, but I just got a new one, and I really
like it. I have seen several references to three-button mice. I
went to look at them and even saw four-button mice! Can you tell me
why I might want more than two buttons? And why would I even
consider four?
</P>
<P>
   A: You certainly don't need more than two buttons, but having
three and maybe even four means more convenience.
</P>
<P>
   In Windows 95, 98 and NT 4.0, the left mouse button is used to
select and launch files and programs, while the right mouse button
is used to do all kinds of nifty things that are largely
conveniences. The most important is to generate pop-up menus. What
these menus include depends on what's being clicked upon, a feature
known as ``context sensitivity.''
</P>
<P>
   If you right-click on the open Windows 98 desktop, you'll get a
different set of menu choices than if you were to right-click on,
say, an icon on the desktop. Novices often don't play with this
feature, but it is very, very handy, and is a quick way to learn
about the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   For example, most people who use Microsoft Word, Microsoft Works
or Corel's WordPerfect probably cut or copy a word by highlighting
the word, then moving the mouse cursor to the button bar at the top
and hitting the Cut or Copy buttons. But you also can right-click
on the highlighted word and Cut and Copy will appear there as menu
choices. This is faster than dragging your mouse cursor across the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   What happens, though, when you add a third mouse button? Windows
doesn't have a natural use for a third button, though the software
that comes with these mice lets you program the middle button to do
things.
</P>
<P>
   On my system, for example, I have the middle button programmed
to act as a double-click. When I want to launch something that
doesn't respond naturally to the single-click feature of Windows
98, I use that middle button. When I was using Windows 95, which
didn't have the single-click option, I just about wore that middle
button out!
</P>
<P>
   Many mice now come with a wheel that doubles as a middle button.
The wheel is used to scroll up and down through long documents, and
it's great for reading Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   I use one of those four-button mice you talked about, a Logitech
MouseMan Wheel. The fourth button is where the thumb rests, and I
have it programmed to perform an auto-scroll _ click the button,
and all I have to do is move the mouse downwards and the page
scrolls automatically.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's now a beta-test version of Internet Explorer 5 I can
get from Microsoft. I really like version 4, and I want to try 5,
but I have Windows 98. Since IE4 is integrated into the Windows
desktop, will installing 5 give me problems?
</P>
<P>
   A: It shouldn't give you any more problems than any other
beta-test software. Internet Explorer 5 is designed to work with
the Windows desktop, as is version 4, so you should not normally
anticipate any conflicts. I have it installed on a couple of
machines _ but not my everyday system _ and it seems to work just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   However, beta software is unfinished software. There is plenty
of work left to be done on IE5, and there are plenty of bugs in it.
If you have access to a secondary machine, I'd put it there first
before moving to the system that you use every day.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if you buy the Office 2000 beta for Microsoft, it
will try real hard to convince you to install IE5, though it will
take no for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-15-99 1326EST &QL;
