<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Score a touchdown at Super Bowl party table
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Super Bowl Sunday is a uniquely American celebration of a
uniquely American game. In the 32 years since the first Super Bowl
was played in 1967, the day has turned into a grand nationwide
party. Not only for die-hard football fans but for just about
everyone else, it is almost impossible not to get caught up in the
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   While the TV is the center of this party, food plays an
essential role in Super Bowl Sunday tradition. This is not a day
for delicate souffles, fussy pastries or cucumber sandwiches. Super
Bowl food should be easy to eat, hand-held if possible, it should
be tasty, there should be lots of it and it should go well with
beer.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl Sunday fare most likely will be eaten from the
La-Z-Boy or the sofa. It should be assumed that the eater can, at
any moment during the game, jump up, stomp, yell and maybe even
lose control of the eating mechanism altogether. The food could
easily end up thrown onto the carpet, or on the ceiling or hurled
at the dog. Got the picture?
</P>
<P>
   In spite of this, it is indeed possible to put on a lovely,
civilized and refined (well, maybe not refined) Super Bowl party
for your nearest and dearest fans.
</P>
<P>
   A must-visit is Kraft Foods Super Bowl site at
http://www.kraftfoods.com/html/features/superbowl/index.html, which
goes a long way toward helping you organize the shindig. It begins
with great suggestions on decorating your ``playing field'' (i.e.,
table) by covering it with green paper or plastic, using white tape
to create yard lines and the liberal use of toy footballs, pompoms,
pennants and megaphones. Then there is the food. Chicken wings,
chili and chips and dip are served by the metric ton on Super Bowl
Sunday. All fine fare, of course, but why not make this the year to
diversify?
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has divided the day into three sections, with recipes to
fit. First there is ``Warm Up,'' with recipes for hot and cold
appetizers, dips and punches. At ``Break and Huddle'' you will find
sandwiches and salads; and at ``Cool Down'' there are recipes for
post-game desserts and tempting coffees.
</P>
<P>
   Another site, though dated, at http://
cocktails.miningco.com/library/weekly/aa011998.htm, also offers
excellent advice, tips, activities, games, trivia and recipes.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to go light on the advice but are looking for tons
of Super Bowl recipes, Epicurious fills the bill. In attempting to
``elevate the tone'' of the event, Epicurious, at
http://food.epicurious.com/eeating/e04superbowl/superbowl.html,
comes up with a multitude of wonderfully creative menus and recipes
for pizzas, salsas, spreads, dips, sandwiches and noshes.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to any of these sites will help you score a touchdown on
the big day.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Black Bean Pinwheels
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Chilling time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded Monterey Jack cheese, with or without jalapeno
peppers
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon onion salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canned black beans, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   3 10-inch flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Thick and chunky salsa
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, mix cream cheese, Monterey Jack cheese, sour
cream and onion salt with an electric mixer on medium speed until
well-blended. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place beans in food processor and process until smooth. Spread
thin layer on each tortilla. Spread one-third of cheese mixture
over beans on each tortilla. Roll tortillas tightly. Refrigerate 30
minutes. Cut into 1/2-inch slices. Serve with salsa.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 130 calories, 5 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 53), 11 grams carbohydrates, 20 milligrams
cholesterol, 152 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Six Points Football
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 40 minutes Freezing time: 6
hours
</P>
<P>
   1 4 1/8-ounce package instant chocolate pudding and pie filling
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cold milk, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups heavy cream, whipped, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 3 3/8-ounce package instant vanilla pudding and pie filling
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup creamy or chunky peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   4 1-ounce squares semi-sweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup shredded coconut, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 drop green food coloring, optional
</P>
<P>
   Line a 6-cup football-shaped mold with plastic wrap. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, prepare chocolate pudding according to package
directions, using 1 1/2 cups milk. Fold in 1 cup whipped cream.
Spoon half the chocolate pudding into prepared mold and spread it
up the sides of the mold. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In another medium bowl, prepare vanilla pudding according to
package directions, using remainder of milk. Stir in peanut butter.
Fold in 1/2 cup whipped cream. Spoon vanilla mixture into center of
chocolate pudding in mold. Top evenly with remaining chocolate
pudding, spreading a spoonful at a time to prevent sinking, and
encasing the vanilla mixture. Cover. Freeze at least 6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Just before removing dessert from the freezer, melt
chocolate and margarine over low heat in a double boiler, mixing
until smooth. Set aside. If desired, tint coconut with food
coloring. Arrange on serving plate. Unmold football onto serving
plate. Remove plastic wrap. Working quickly, spread chocolate onto
football. Pipe remaining whipped cream to add football details.
Serve immediately or freeze until serving time. Let stand at room
temperature 20 minutes for easier slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Football-shaped 6-cup molds are at many specialty shops.
We found them at Michaels Arts &AMP; Crafts for $9.99.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without coconut): 500 calories, 9 grams protein, 36
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 65), 41 grams carbohydrates,
75 milligrams cholesterol, 390 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Detail from
http://www.kraftfoods.com/html/features/superbowl/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
