<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocky Road makes for sweet and easy candy
 &HT;    By MarciA Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kathy Seamen's (e-mail) request for the Rocky Road Candy recipe
from the back of a 1982 package of Borden's chocolate chips was
answered by Irene Osborne of Morrow, who says she's used it for
years. You can spread the candy in a rectangular pan, and then cut
it into squares, or drop it from a teaspoon into irregular shapes.
Either way is very easy, and very sweet.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Borden's Rocky Road Candy
</P>
<P>
   Makes 40 squares
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 7-8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   112-ounce package semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   114-ounce can sweetened condensed milk (not evaporated milk)
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   2cups dry roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   110 1/2-ounce package miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   Line a 9-by-13-inch pan with wax paper and set aside. In heavy
saucepan over low heat, melt chocolate chips with sweetened
condensed milk and margarine; remove from heat. In large bowl,
combine nuts and marshmallows; fold in melted chocolate mixture.
Spread in prepared pan. Chill 2 hours or until firm. Remove from
pan, peel off wax paper and cut candy into squares. Cover and store
at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you prefer, drop mixture from a teaspoon onto wax
paper-lined baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Per piece: 146 calories, 3 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 49), 18 grams carbohydrates, 3 milligrams
cholesterol, 55 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  S.L. Harrod (e-mail) is looking for a Vidalia onion casserole
that includes onions, butter and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tiffany Kramer (e-mail) would like a recipe for German
Chocolate Pie similar to one she had 25 years ago. Closer to a
brownie than a pie, it is chewy and not cakelike. It includes two
pie shells, cocoa, coconut, cornstarch and sweetened condensed
milk.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Teresa Martin of Stone Mountain asks for the recipe for
Italian Cake, a light brown cake with nuts and a cream cheese
icing. She also is looking for a butter pecan cake. Both are cakes
that a friend's mother made when Martin was growing up in Saginaw,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for recipes for this column should be sent
to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone
number. E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry write for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
