<HEADER>
A0787 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SATELLITE-FLARES1     01-20 1579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SATELLITE-FLARES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FLARING' SATELLITES IGNITE ASTRONOMICAL DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By Michael Browning   
 c. 1999 Cox News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Piercing the night with sudden shards of
light, a new globe-girdling array of 79 communications satellites
called Iridium, lofted by Motorola Inc., is already arcing across
the heavens, emitting brilliant ``flares'' from their
super-reflective antenna-panels, bedazzling and bedeviling
astronomers by turns.
</P>
<P>
   For earthlings able to afford the $3,000 cellphones capable of
using the satellites, the Iridium satellites are a modern miracle,
enabling instant wireless voice and data communication between any
two points, anywhere on the planet. The $500 pager units for the
network are manufactured locally, at Motorola's Boynton Beach
plant. The $5 billion system has already been successfully tested,
and Motorola hopes to have 5 million subscribers by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Six necklaces of 11 satellites each now surround the earth,
arrayed longitudinally, creating a bead-like electronic cage within
which the world slowly spins. Because some of the satellites have
malfunctioned and others are being used as backups, there are 13
more aloft than are actually needed.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere on Earth is unreachable anymore, thanks to this new
network.
</P>
<P>
   But an unanticipated side effect of the satellites _ brilliant
solar reflections of light as they pass overhead _ has caused
concern among astronomers, some of whom see the satellites as yet
another source of light pollution in a world where the magic and
majesty of the star-sown night sky are already under assault from
myriad streetlights and neon signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think it's a shame that yet another natural resource
has to be ruined by an unregulated commercial venture,'' said Mike
Stebbins, a computer analyst who is past president of the New
Hampshire Astronomical Society. ``Why should those of us who do not
wish to call the North Pole have to endure the clutter of those who
do?''
</P>
<P>
   Too new to gauge effect
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Fredrickson, president of the Astronomical Society of
the Palm Beaches, said the flares were too new a phenomenon to have
impacted club members yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that eventually the Iridium flares will become a
nuisance to people taking shots of different parts of the sky,
looking for comets, asteroids and novae in distant galaxies,''
Fredrickson said. ``We will have a ROBOscope project doing exactly
that, and I feel like it's just a matter of time before someone
takes a picture of one of these flares.''
</P>
<P>
   But, added Fredrickson, for people who are interested in
satellites, rockets and space flight, rather than ``pure
astronomy,'' the flares may prove exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer intensity of the Iridium flares has to be seen to be
believed. For up to 20 seconds, the evening or early morning sky
will suddenly emit an eye-needling flash, 100 times brighter than
the planet Venus, equal to all the light of a crescent moon. Then,
as swiftly and unexpectedly as it appeared, the spark of light
vanishes.
</P>
<P>
   So bright are the flares that they can sometimes be seen in
broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
   Computer programs available over the Internet can help predict
to the second exactly when the flares will be visible and precisely
where in the sky they will appear.
</P>
<P>
   Renowned satellite observer Paul Maley, of the NASA/Johnson
Space Center Astronomical Society, was the first to correctly
identify the cause of the flares in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I learned that a bright glint had been observed by one
amateur astronomer in Canada (Dr. Brian K. Hunter of Ontario), then
another, it occurred to me that these might not be accidents,'' he
recalled. ``Many satellites can occasionally flare up to look like
very bright stars for short periods. But the super high brightness
of the Iridiums was the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the days went on, I began to do some reading on the
constellation design. Through professional contacts I was able to
get in touch with someone at Motorola. After that, things began to
fall into place.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the designers at Motorola were as surprised as
anyone to find that the satellites were flaring. It turned out that
the triple-vaned door-size Main Mission Antennas (MMAs), made of
aluminum and coated with silverized Teflon, were almost perfect
mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-degree tilt of the antennas away from the axis of the
satellite would catch the sunlight and flash it down to Earth at
certain times and in certain places.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite watchers began to speak of the ``Golden Hour'' and the
``box,'' the time and place in the sky where Iridium flares were
most likely to appear.
</P>
<P>
   The satellites do not always live up to predictions. Some are
tumbling in orbit, useless. Others, for reasons as yet unexplained,
flare twice. The brightness of the flares varies, depending on how
far away from the center of the satellite's exact north-south path
the observer is standing; they are brightest in a narrow swath
about three miles wide.
</P>
<P>
   Two computer programmers, Rob Matson and Randy John, wrote a
program that is available on the Internet
(http://members.aol.com/skysatrj/) and Maley still recalls the
thrill of awaiting the launching of multiple Iridium satellites
aboard American, Russian and Chinese rockets. As the satellites
slipped into north-south orbit, all five flared gloriously, in
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In August 1997, I was able to videotape the flaring of all
five recently launched objects within a two-minute period as they
passed west of Houston,'' Maley said. ``It was quite unbelievable
to see one after the other brightening up to surpass the brilliance
of every star in the sky that morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iridium satellites contain no iridium. The name comes from a
miscalculated number. It was originally believed that 77 satellites
would be needed to cover the Earth completely, and 77 was the
atomic number for iridium on the periodic table of elements. Later
it was found that only 66 were needed, but since 66 was the atomic
number for the element dysprosium, and ``dysprosium'' doesn't sound
as catchy as ``iridium,'' Motorola decided to keep the original
name.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike high-orbit communication satellites, which relay a
terrestrial signal straight back to Earth, the Iridium array move
in low Earth orbit, handing off the signal from one satellite to
the next, like the baton in a relay race, until it reaches the
proper destination and is beamed down to a ground relay station.
Because the satellites travel north to south and south to north in
six orbital planes, the farther north or south you are, the more
flares you will see.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the North Pole, theoretically you could see as many as
1,000 flares a month,'' Maley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Blessing or a Curse?'' asked Florida-based astronomer Philip
Chien in one of the first articles to discuss the Iridium flares,
in the May 1998 issue of Sky &AMP; Telescope. Chien concluded that,
because the flares are so brief, and relatively predictable,
astronomers ought to be able to plan around them.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of other light pollution
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more than 8,000 artificial objects in space, and
every one of them has the potential for leaving a streak on a
long-duration photographic exposure. So in percentage terms,
(these) additional objects and a handful of upper rocket stages do
not add up to a very large addition,'' Chien wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider the Iridium satellites as `light pollution,'
'' said Lee Dolan, responding to a question posted in connection
with this article on CompuServe's Astronomy Forum. ``Around where I
live (in a garden condominium complex) there are bright sodium
vapor lamps under the eaves, and I have enough trouble finding a
place around here where I don't have any lights shining in my eyes.
Tell me about light pollution!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit to being an Iridium addict,'' e-mailed Malcolm
Ellis of Cambridgeshire, England, replying to the same question.
``I find the predictability a great boon and conversation piece,
when I can say to friends, `Come outside and see this.' And there
spot, on time, a glorious flare. Even my 3-year-old grandson and
6-year-old granddaughter are impressed with my apparent
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Maley believes the satellites are an exciting new celestial
phenomenon, one that should literally spark people's interest in
the heavens. ``They are so highly visible, they are bound to draw
the public's attention to the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Iridium Web sites
</P>
<P>
   Here are some useful Web sites connected with the Iridium
satellite flare phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   A central clearinghouse page, with multiple links to other
sites, is http://www2.satellite.eu.org/sat/vsohp/iridium.html
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of the flares are at:
http://www2.satellite.eu.org/sat/vsohp/iridpix.html
</P>
<P>
   A program to predict the flares can be downloaded at
http://members.aol.com/skysatrj/
</P>
<P>
   Another is at http://www.fc.net/: http://www.gsoc.dlr.de/satvis
</P>
<P>
   The SeeSat-L mailing list has frequent reports of Iridium
flares. You don't have to be a member to read the messages. The
site is at:
http://www2.satellite.eu.org/sat/Seesat/Dec-1998/date.html
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a very interesting, visual site where you can watch
mini-movies of Iridium flares is at
http://members.aol.com/uwereimann/ir45.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
