<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Great performance by Hurt makes story of obsessive love
worthwhile
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Love and Death on Long Island'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see one of the best performances that probably
won't be nominated for an Oscar, you need to see John Hurt in this
melancholy but very funny spin on obsessive love.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt plays Giles De'Ath, a middle-aged writer who personifies
everything fusty, British and Old World. So it's more to his
surprise than anyone else's when he becomes enamored of a young
American teen idol named Ronnie Bostock (Jason Priestley), star of
a series of shlocky, ``Porky's''-like comedies. He tracks the young
star down in Long Island and insinuates himself into his life. But
the attraction is less a sexual one than a leverage for Giles to
awaken to the neon-bright possibilities of pop culture and to find
a brand new facet of his long-smoldering personality.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt is brilliant in the part (though Academy members may forget
his work since the film barely was distributed last year), and
Priestley is equally fine as the puppyish young stud. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
