</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of movies recently released on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' (R) _ A vivid, funny look at coming
of age on the fringes. Vivian Abramowitz (Natasha Lyonne) is the
odd girl out in a post-divorce family led by a father (Alan Ar-
</P>
<P>
   kin) who, every three months or so, skips out on rent and moves
his brood to another fleabag on the edge of Beverly Hills. Director
Tamara Jenkins re-creates the humiliations of adolescence with
wince-inducing accuracy. Lyonne is terrific at navigating the
waters of teen angst. Grade: A -
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Smoke Signals'' (PG-13) _ A bittersweet coming-of-age comedy
about two Native Americans who leave their dilapidated reservation
to go to Arizona to fetch their father's (one biological, the other
spiritual) ashes. Rambling and rough around the edges, with a honed
casualness that suggests the early '70s, Chris Eyre's debut film is
still definitely worth a look. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Buffalo 66'' (unrated) _ Don't shuffle off to this
``Buffalo.'' Former Calvin Klein underwear model Vincent Gallo
wrote, directed and stars in this uneven fable about an ex-con who
kidnaps a voluptuous teen (Christina Ricci) to pose as his wife
while he visits his parents (Ben Gazzara and Anjelica Huston). The
first half is amusingly bonkers, thanks to the cast, but overall,
the film is all over the place _ self-pitying and sardonic, arty
and maudlin. Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Return to Paradise'' (R) _ Hardly paradise. Three guys party
hard together in Malaysia. Two (Vince Vaughn and David Conrad)
return home and find out, two years later from a lawyer (Anne
Heche), that the third (Joaquin Phoenix) has been jailed on drug
charges since they left and will be hanged in eight days unless
they return to share the responsibility. But that also means
sharing the jail time. It's a terrific moral dilema that's
squandered by an inept script. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
