</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You name it _ title can make, break a flick
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's in a name? Plenty, according to the movie marketing
mavens. That's why ``Playing by Heart,'' ``Stepmom'' and ``At First
Sight'' are on theater marquees instead of ``Dancing About
Architecture,'' ``Goodnight Moon'' and ``Sight Unseen.'' That's why
``Lost Moon'' became ``Apollo 13'' and ``Everybody Comes to
Rick's'' became ``Casablanca.'' And why just about every movie
Woody Allen has ever made wasn't released under its original title:
``Untitled Woody Allen Project.'' Here are some pictures you might
want to rent at your local video store. Just don't look for them
under their original title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Thousand''
</P>
<P>
   You know it as: ``Pretty Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The original title was ``Three Thousand'' because that's how
much money Richard Gere first promises Julia Roberts in the film.
But according to director Garry Marshall, when test audiences were
given the premise and that title, they thought it was something
about hookers from the moon (maybe their memories of ``2001: A
Space Odyssey'' got them confused).
</P>
<P>
   ``My Posse Don't Do Homework''
</P>
<P>
   You know it as: ``Dangerous Minds''
</P>
<P>
   The original title was ``My Posse Don't Do Homework'' because,
as is so often true with name changes in Hollywood, that was the
title of the book by LouAnne Johnson, the inner-city teacher whose
experiences provided the movie's framework. But words such as
``Posse'' and ``Homework'' didn't exactly scream ``new Michelle
Pfeiffer movie.'' To her credit, Pfeiffer fought with the producers
(Don Simpson and Jerry Bruckheimer) over the title change, but she
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cop Tips Waitress $2 Million''
</P>
<P>
   You know it as: ``It Could Happen to You''
</P>
<P>
   The original title came from a tabloid newspaper headline that
topped the real-life story of a New York cop (Nicolas Cage) who
gave a waitress (Bridget Fonda) half a lottery ticket in lieu of a
tip. The marketing department should've worried less about the
title and more about how to sell audiences on this low-key charmer
(it tanked in theaters). But the dominant artistic force in
Hollywood _ the test audience _ decreed the title was too
descriptive. According to writer-director Andrew Bergman, the focus
groups felt, ``You sit there waiting for (Cage) to give her the
money.'' As opposed, I guess, to waiting for Godzilla to show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stray Dogs''
</P>
<P>
   You know it as: ``U-Turn''
</P>
<P>
   Director Oliver Stone preferred the original title for his cult
film starring Sean Penn as a drifter who runs into trouble in the
form of Nick Nolte and Jennifer Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   But the powerful Stone had to bow out when an even more powerful
(well, more venerable) director objected. Japanese master Akira
Kurosawa threatened to sue, claiming it was too close to ``Stray
Dog,'' the English-language title given one of his films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anhedonia''
</P>
<P>
   You know it as: ``Annie Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he got past the ``Untitled Woody Allen Project'' phase, the
filmmaker wanted to call his 1977 Oscar winner ``Anhedonia,'' which
means an inability to experience pleasure. But then he found out
that no one knew what ``anhedonia'' meant. However, the new title
wasn't just a way of giving in to everyone else's more limited
vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   It also suggested a shift in emphasis in the movie, from Allen's
own misery to his relationship with Diane Keaton.
</P>
<P>
   Other titles you won't find: ``Suck the Bullet'' (``Dead Men
Don't Wear Plaid''), ``Dangerous Days'' (``Blade Runner''), ``Billy
the Third'' (``Tommy Boy''), ``I Was a Teenage Teenager''
(``Clueless'') and ``E.T. and Me'' (guess what?).
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
