<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-POP12-COX     01-20 0273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DiFranco shifts into jazzier gear
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody's cooler than Ani DiFranco, the scrappy, self-invented
singer-songwriter and roving cult figure who, if you follow the
business pages of The New York Times, has put her hometown,
Buffalo, N.Y., back on the road to financial prosperity _ seemingly
single-handedly. The success of her record label, Righteous Babe,
and the steady growth of her audience, puts DiFranco in an enviable
spot: She can flirt with celebrity but still cruise just under
pop's often-compromising radar.
</P>
<P>
   Though the new-school folkie's last album, ``Little Plastic
Castle,'' threatened to blow her cover, ``Up Up Up Up Up Up'' is
low-key and much less conceptual. It's a loose-hanging collection
of songs that shifts between socially conscious observations (``
'Tis of Thee,'' the title track) and emotional conversations with
lovers and family. The thoughtful protest stuff is heartfelt but
disposable, while the confessionals often boast a raw, engaging
integrity. Slippery grooves, funky organ vibes and the singer's
sometimes risky forays into jazz-style vocalizing give the album an
improvisatory flow that's quietly refreshing, even though there's
nothing here with the visceral punch of 1995's artistic
breakthrough, ``Dilate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Up Up Up
</P>
<P>
   Up Up Up''
</P>
<P>
   Ani DiFranco. Righteous Babe. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   A funkier, friskier DiFranco.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
