 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
It's easy to stay on time, anywhere in the world 
By Jack Warner  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My computer runs at 400 MhZ (Macho 6, or 0.24 ounces
per thousand of blood testosterone). Nonetheless, it was 10 minutes
slow this morning.
</P>
<P>
   I discovered this lamentable condition while examining a neat
little program called Time and Measures, from QM Labs.
</P>
<P>
   In its default configuration, T&AMP;M presents the user with a
two-frame window, the larger showing a pretty globe. You can rotate
it side to side, up and down. To do anything with it, you find the
country in which you are interested, zoom in until you find a city,
and click on the city.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller frame will then provide you with the correct date
and time in that city, as well as its longitude and latitude in
case you are navigating. If you don't want to go through all this
show and tell, you can just select a city from a long list.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the program's only trick. As the title indicates, it
will also convert measurements: Fahrenheit to Celsius or Kelvin in
temperatures, and English/metric in weights, volume, area and
distance. Type the number you wish to convert into the appropriate
box, click convert, and the conversions are shown instantly.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if you type ``3'' into the ounce box, you get not
only what that amounts to at every level of metric weight, but its
portion of a pound and even a ton.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few disappointments in T&AMP;M. It doesn't have as many
cities as it should _ nothing is shown, for instance, between Accra
and Monrovia on the west coast of Africa. One assumes the
intervening countries and capitals are all on the same time zone,
but it seems as though they ought to be there nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   In the weight conversion feature, grains are not addressed.
</P>
<P>
   T&AMP;M costs $35, and you can download a free demo from
http://www.qmlabs.com. However, if you are connected to the
Internet, you really don't need to buy a program for these
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Date and Time Gateway at http://www.bsdi.com/date/ will give you
the time _ OK, it's military time, but I know you can figure it out
_ for just about any city in the world. Local Times Around the
World at http://www.hilink.com
</P>
<P>
   .au/times/ does the same. Global Metric Time Service (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .globalmetric.com/time/) is a nice site intended to let you set
up a list of five cities and get the local time there every time
you log in.
</P>
<P>
   For measurement conversions, all you need _ more than you need,
probably _ is Megaconverter (http://www.megaconverter.com/). Here,
you can find that 1 U.S. gallon is equal to 15.68628 Danish paegl,
as well as 3.78541 liters. It will also tell you that 4.5 grains
equals 0.01029 ounces, or 0.00072 Polish funts.
</P>
<P>
   In checking on the time sites, I discovered my computer's clock
was running 10 minutes slow. At the National Institute of Standards
time page (http://www.bldrdoc.gov/timefreq/javaclck.htm), I found a
neat little program you can download, then run every time you log
onto the Internet. It will check with the NIS page, reset your
clock to conform with the atomic clock, and go away in the blink of
an eyeball _ 0.815 of a second, or 1.51 Moldavian grunts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
