</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIEVAL-ARCADE-ANTIQUES-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 12TH CENTURY ABBEY YIELDS ITS SECRETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of front view of 12th century `abbey door' is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 Paula Deitz is the editor of the Hudson Review  
 By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few months ago, Ward and Co., New York dealers of
ancient and medieval art, sent out a lavish, fold-out booklet of
photographs to display some of the rare objects from its
collection. Most of the objects were from prehistoric or classical
times, but an arresting one was from the medieval world: an arcade,
or arch, from a 12th-century Romanesque choir screen from the
church of the Abbey of Cluny in Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   This architectural fragment was enticing because it conjured up
an entire structure yet stood on its own as a piece of sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom in New York holds that when something
noteworthy comes on the market, you had better go see it
immediately before it disappears. The arcade was no exception: it
was soon back in private hands. Fortunately, its new owners,
Charles and Alexandra van Horne, allowed a visitor to examine the
arcade, which now resides in the dining room of their Manhattan
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The 40{-inch-high arcade is in good company: it is flanked by a
pair of stone capitals, originally owned by William Randolph
Hearst, and an assortment of medieval heads, from church gargoyles
to manor-house sculptural reliefs, on pedestals. The van Hornes
call the collection their ``ghosts and orphans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I began buying architectural fragments 20 years ago, when I
lived in England,'' said van Horne, an investment manager. He was
soon joined in this endeavor by his French-born wife-to-be. ``We
were attracted by carvings with a pagan influence, and each
purchase drew us into a new time period from around the eighth to
the 15th centuries,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In acquiring the arcade, the van Hornes have become caught up in
a kind of archeological jigsaw puzzle: scholars are working from
the scattered ruins of the abbey to determine its original
appearance. The church, completed in 1130, was the largest
ecclesiastical building in Europe until St. Peter's Basilica in
Rome was finished five centuries later. Under the dominion of the
powerful Benedictine order, the construction and decoration of the
church influenced the spread of Romanesque architecture throughout
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Singing was at the core of monastic life at Cluny. A choir of
200 chanted plainsong in the church behind the decorated choir
screen, which separated the monks from the congregation. The screen
was a free-standing architectural element that reflected the
exuberant carvings of the nearby capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Unsurprisingly, the architect had probably been trained as a
musician, and music, like mathematics, was the controlling idea
behind the elegant proportions of the church's interior.
</P>
<P>
   The church remained in use until the 18th century. ``At an early
stage of the French Revolution, the whole abbey site was divided
into four parts and auctioned off for its valuable building
stone,'' said Neil Stratford, the chief curator emeritus of
Medieval and Later Antiquities at the British Museum, who is the
general editor of the ``Corpus of the Sculpture of Cluny, Vol. 1,''
to be published in France in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The church itself was demolished over a period of 30 years, he
said, with only two sections remaining, including the great
transept and its tower. Stratford asserted that the nearly 100
fragments of the choir screen that have been accounted for made it
the largest ensemble of church furniture in Europe to survive from
the Romanesque period.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the fragments were used as building material in local
houses, which had similar Romanesque arcades decorating their
facades. The van Horne arcade was found in the courtyard garden of
an antiques shop in Burgundy. With its pilaster, capital and
cornice intact, it is one of the better preserved pieces from the
screen. Some pieces of the choir screen have been reassembled and
are on view at the Ochier Museum in Cluny.
</P>
<P>
   The Cluny sculptors were inspired by classical motifs like those
found on the Roman gates of nearby towns. Among the arches there
was a great variety of patterns. The rosette on the van Horne
arcade has five petals, while one on another fragment from the
screen on display at the Cloisters, the medieval branch of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in Fort Tryon Park in Manhattan, has
seven.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, David A. Walsh, an archaeological historian at the
University of Rochester who is collaborating with Stratford, has
solved the longstanding mystery of the appearance and location of
the choir screen in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the system of holes and the rudimentary markings on
the backs, we realized that the roughly 100 bays of arcades were
connected to architectural piers and attached to an elevated wall
in a U-shaped configuration that opened to the high altar at the
apse end,'' Walsh explained. The monks sat in rows facing each
other surrounded by the choir screen, which rose 10 to 12 feet
behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then, in the 15th century, sumptuous tapestries depicting
the coat of arms of the abbot's family or a series of religious
scenes were hung in tiers from iron hooks _ the van Hornes's has
one _ on the decorated side seen by the monks,'' he said. Suddenly,
the scene comes alive with the echo of plainsong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
