<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0910 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-BURNSCLUB21-COX     01-20 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BURNSCLUB21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A feast fit for a poet
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Toted in to the sound of bagpipes, praised in the
immortal words of Scottish poet Robert Burns, and then slashed with
knives slipped out of socks on kilted legs, the haggis offers up
its mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared in the traditional way, they include chopped sheep's
heart, liver and lungs, mixed with oatmeal, suet and onion, stuffed
into a sheep's stomach and boiled. Modernized versions may
substitute lamb or calf liver, perhaps with sausage, for much of
the organ meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recipe's disgusting,'' says Ginger McMillan Kozlosky, a
native of Dundee, Scotland, who lives in Dunwoody (Ga.). ``I can
take about one teaspoon a year.''
</P>
<P>
   A man's a man for a' that, but it takes a man revered like
Rabbie Burns to launch thousands of teaspoons of the ``Great
Chieftain o' the Puddin-Race.'' The well-loved bard, a plowman,
satirist, sentimentalist and lover of lassies and whiskey, is the
author of ``Auld Lang Syne,'' ``A Red Red Rose'' and considerable
national pride.
</P>
<P>
   So on Monday, Scots and their descendants will gather for a
Burns Night Supper and an evening of remembrance, revelry and
feasting.
</P>
<P>
   Almost since Burns' death, in 1796 at age 37, Scots have set
aside his birthday, Jan. 25, to celebrate the ``immortal memory.''
There's a ritual to the remembrance, observed from Burns' native
land to wherever Scots have settled. In Atlanta, groups like the
Burns Club, a literary and social club, and the St. Andrew's
Society, a heritage organization, will put on their finest _ Prince
Charlies and kilts for men, dresses for women _ and celebrate in
the time-honored way. The Burns Club holds its feast in a granite
cottage on Alloway Place in East Atlanta, a replica of Burns'
birthplace in Alloway, Scotland, that the group built in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   First comes Burns' ``Selkirk Grace'':
</P>
<P>
   Some hae meat and canna eat,
</P>
<P>
   And some wad eat that want it;
</P>
<P>
   But we hae meat, and we can eat,
</P>
<P>
   And sae the Lord be thanket.
</P>
<P>
   Then bagpipes herald the arrival of the haggis, borne in with
great ceremony on a big tray, guarded with swords and greeted with
Burns' ``Address to a Haggis.'' The Scotch comes out, the toasts
begin and the real feasting starts. There are toasts to the
lassies, to queen, country and president, and to the immortal
memory of Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists dine on cock-a-leekie soup, bashed neeps and
tatties (mashed turnips and potatoes), haggis, beef or lamb and
trifle or clootie dumpling, a raisin-studded pudding. Many who
celebrate modernize the menu. The Burns Club, which celebrates
Saturday, will have roast beef, spinach, kale, potatoes and trifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a haggis, of course,'' says Grant Crate, a member
from Lawrenceville (Ga.). ``We don't really have a traditional
Scottish dinner much anymore. People are getting a little too fancy
for just a little basic bashed neeps, that kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``hamely fare'' of Scotland won praise from Burns, who
ragged those preferring French ragouts and fricassees to haggis.
But it's still looking for respect.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlosky works at Taste of Britain, a food and gift store in
Norcross (Ga.) that sells haggis, bridies (meat pastries) and other
English and Scottish fare. She sticks up for the food of her native
land, especially the salmon, strawberries and raspberries.
</P>
<P>
   But even she admits that ``most people turn up their noses at
Scottish cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the kind of backbreaking farm work that weakened
Burns' heart and led to his early death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people that emigrated to this country truly
are from Scottish peasant stock, where the food had to be very
substantial and very heavy,'' says Jacqueline Stewart of Pinehurst,
N.C., managing director of Scottish Heritage USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food was more a utilitarian thing than a culinary aesthetic
thing. The upper crust of Scotland were very much influenced in
their daily lives by France, so there is this dichotomy between the
very plain and the very elegant food.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the rest of Britain, there's a cooking renaissance going
on in Scotland, with chefs like George Mckay of Balbirnie House
turning out smoked salmon salad with brown butter vinaigrette and
Tony Pierce of Knockinaan Lodge crafting hot sticky toffee pudding
souffle with honey and single-malt ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of preparing a Burns Night Supper, there's no
need to choose between plain or fancy. We've put together a menu
with the best of both.
</P>
<P>
   Let other poets raise a fracas
</P>
<P>
   Bout vines, and wines, an drucken Bacchus,
</P>
<P>
   An crabbit names an stories wrack us,
</P>
<P>
   An grate our lug:
</P>
<P>
   I sing the juice Scotch bear can mak us,
</P>
<P>
   In glass or Jug.
</P>
<P>
   O thou, my Muse! guid auld Scotch drink!
</P>
<P>
   Whether thro' wimplin worms thou jink,
</P>
<P>
   Or, richly brown, ream owre the brink,
</P>
<P>
   In glorious faem
</P>
<P>
   Inspire me, till I lisp an wink,
</P>
<P>
   To sing thy name!
</P>
<P>
   _ from ``Scotch Drink'' by Robert Burns
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
