<HEADER>
A0912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-BURNSCLUB-RECIPE     01-20 2293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BURNSCLUB-RECIPES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scottish heritage groups stage many of the Burns Night suppers
in the United States. Yet there's no reason you can't put together
a home celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Pick up a book of Robert Burns' poetry, some Scotch and, if
you're going all the way with the ritual, some bagpipe music.
Prepare a few toasts, too, and brush up on the lyrics of ``Auld
Lang Syne,'' which traditionally concludes a Burns supper.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Web sites give ideas for toasts and contain
selections of Burns' poetry; try starting out at the Bard, at
http://www.rabbie-burns.com, or Burns Country,
http://www.robertburns.org.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find a haggis recipe here _ we tried an Americanized
version, and still couldn't, er, stomach it. But if you're set on
upholding tradition, you can buy haggis at specialty food stores
like Taste of Britain in Norcross. It's a good idea to call ahead
to make sure it's in stock.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the most important ingredient for a successful
Burns celebration: good companions. Or, as Burns wrote, ``But a
club of good fellows, like those that are here, And a bottle like
this, are my glory and care.''
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Balbirnie Smoked Salmon Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 serving Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here's an elegant way to start an evening of Scottish food, from
George Mckay, executive chef of Balbirnie House, near Glenrothes.
</P>
<P>
   For each serving:
</P>
<P>
   2 toasted brioche (or other toast) triangles
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon creme fraiche or sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Handful mixed baby salad greens
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces thinly sliced smoked salmon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely diced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon capers
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Brown Butter Vinaigrette (recipe at right)
</P>
<P>
   Spread the brioche with creme fraiche; sprinkle with black
pepper. Arrange a few salad leaves over the top with smoked salmon
slices rolled into curls. Sprinkle the plate with diced onion,
capers and parsley, then spoon three pools of the vinaigrette
around the salmon. _ From ``Piping Hot: The Scottish Heritage USA
Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with vinaigrette): 388 calories, 11 grams protein,
29 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 68), 18 grams
carbohydrates, 78 milligrams cholesterol, 838 milligrams sodium, 2
grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Brown Butter Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) butter
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon (about 2 tablespoons)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 shots (3 ounces) Scotch single-malt whisky
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs thyme, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy saucepan, cook the butter over medium-low heat until
it turns pale brown. Add the shallots and garlic and stir well to
prevent any scorching.
</P>
<P>
   Add the lemon juice, Dijon mustard and whisky. Slowly whip in
the vegetable oil until incorporated. Add the thyme, salt and white
pepper. Hold at room temperature. (Don't worry if the mixture
separates.)
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 73 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 8 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 97), less than 1 gram
carbohydrates, 21 milligrams cholesterol, 81 milligrams sodium,
less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Cock-a-Leekie Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 1/2-2 hours
</P>
<P>
   This nourishing soup is a Scottish favorite, either as part of a
celebratory meal or a simple family supper.
</P>
<P>
   1 small chicken with giblets (2 1/2-3 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 cups water
</P>
<P>
   6 leeks, cut in long pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup long-grain rice
</P>
<P>
   1 small carrot, grated
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Place chicken, giblets and onion in a large saucepan or Dutch
oven. Add water and bring to boil over high heat. Reduce heat to
low, cover and simmer for 1-1 1/2 hours until chicken is tender.
Remove from heat and skim off any white scum. Remove giblets and
discard. Remove chicken and strip meat from bones, discarding
bones. Return meat to the stock. Add leeks, rice and carrot. Bring
back to boil, cover and simmer for 30 minutes. Season with up to 1
teaspoon salt and pepper to taste. Add parsley just before serving.
_ ``Favorite Scottish Recipes,'' compiled by Johanna Mathie (J.
Salmon Ltd., $4.99)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 159 calories, 17 grams protein, 4 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 23), 13 grams carbohydrates, 47
milligrams cholesterol, 446 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Bashed Neeps &AMP; Tatties
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This side dish, better know to most of us as mashed turnips and
potatoes, is a hearty standard accompaniment on the Scottish table
and makes a nice presentation when served with their respective
garnishes. If you plan to serve the lamb recipe with roasted
potatoes, you may want to go with just turnips _ but for a buffet
few would object to potatoes in two guises.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound small turnips, quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 pound small boiling potatoes, quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 to 4 tablespoons warm milk, divided
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons warm heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Parsley
</P>
<P>
   Nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Boil the turnips in a saucepan of water for 2 minutes. Drain and
refresh under cold running water.
</P>
<P>
   In separate saucepans, boil the turnips and potatoes in water
just to cover until tender, 25 to 30 minutes. Mash each in separate
bowls with a little warm milk and butter. Season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heap the turnips and potatoes separately on plates. With the
back of a serving spoon, make a small indentation in each heap.
Into each, pour a little warm heavy cream and a pat of butter.
Garnish with chopped parsley on the tatties (potatoes) and a
sprinkle of nutmeg on the neeps (turnips). _ ``Piping Hot: The
Scottish Heritage USA Cookbook,'' edited by Jacqueline Stewart
(Cookbooks by Morris, $21.50). To order: 910-295-4448.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 182 calories, 3 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 54), 20 grams carbohydrates, 32
milligrams cholesterol, 117 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Nana Bruce's Leg of Lamb With Potatoes and Carrots
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 1/2-3 hours
</P>
<P>
   For color, we added carrots to the original recipe, which also
called for a bone-in leg of lamb, which we had difficulty locating.
</P>
<P>
   Mint sauce:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   Lamb:
</P>
<P>
   1 boneless leg of lamb, 5 to 6 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   5 pounds potatoes, peeled
</P>
<P>
   6 large carrots
</P>
<P>
   Gravy:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For the mint sauce: In a small saucepan, heat sugar, water and
vinegar. Place mint leaves in a small bowl; pour liquid over the
leaves and let stand 2 hours while lamb is roasting.
</P>
<P>
   For the lamb: Trim excess fat and membrane off the lamb. Wash
under running water, pat dry and place in a large roaster. Rub salt
on lamb; pour water in the bottom of the roaster. Roast with lid on
for about 45 minutes. Remove lid and continue roasting, basting
frequently, for another 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Put potatoes and carrots around lamb and roast until they are
done and the pan is sticky brown. Baste meat, potatoes and carrots
frequently. Increase the oven temperature to 400 degrees for last
15 to 20 minutes. Allow 2 1/2 to 3 hours total roasting time.
</P>
<P>
   For the gravy: Place lamb on a cutting board and put the
well-done, crispy brown potatoes and carrots into a large bowl.
Pour off any excess grease from the pan. Add the water mixed with a
little flour to the pan and stir to make the gravy. Accompany the
lamb with gravy and mint sauce. _ From ``Piping Hot: The Scottish
Heritage USA Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 436 calories, 36 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 22), 48 grams carbohydrates, 104
milligrams cholesterol, 210 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Oatcakes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In Scotland, oatcakes are traditionally buttered and served with
herring or cheese; alternately, they may be served with honey or
jam.
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups regular oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   5 to 9 teaspoons hot water
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Pulverize 1 cup of the oatmeal in a food processor. With the
motor running, add baking powder and salt and pulse, then add
melted butter. When all the butter has been absorbed, add the hot
water, a teaspoonful at a time, stirring constantly, to make a
smooth, firm paste.
</P>
<P>
   Gather the mixture into a ball and place it on a board or table
lightly sprinkled with 1/4 cup of the remaining oatmeal. Roll the
ball into the oatmeal until it is completely covered with flakes.
Spread another 1/4 cup oatmeal evenly over the board and, with a
rolling pin, roll the ball out into an 8-inch circle about 1/8 inch
thick. With pastry wheel or sharp knife, cut the circle into 8
pie-shaped wedges. Scatter the remaining oatmeal on a baking sheet
and, with a large metal spatula, carefully transfer the wedges to
the sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the cakes in the middle of the oven for about 15 minutes.
When the wedges are light brown, turn off the heat and open the
door of the oven. Leave the oatcakes in the oven for 4 or 5
minutes, or until they become firm and crisp. Serve at once. _ From
``Food of the World Series, Cooking of the British Isles''
(Time-Life Books, 1975, out of print)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 161 calories, 6 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 28), 24 grams carbohydrates, 8 milligrams
cholesterol, 368 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Shortbread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40-45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   There's one must for shortbread, says Ginger McMillan Kozlosky
of Dunwoody (Ga.): ``It should melt in your mouth when you eat
it.'' Kozlosky, a native of Dundee, Scotland, has been preparing
the Scottish favorite for more than 45 years. This is her aunt's
recipe. Rice flour gives a lighter texture to the shortbread, but
all-purpose flour can be substituted if you can't find rice flour.
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup rice flour (available in Asian grocery stores, some
larger
</P>
<P>
   supermarkets and health food stores)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 2 teaspoons caster sugar or superfine sugar (found
in the sugar section of larger supermarkets; or make your own by
pulsing granulated sugar a few times in the food processor)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar, for dusting pan
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. In a medium bowl, mix flour, rice
flour and 1/2 cup caster sugar. Cut butter into small pieces and
drop into flour. Rub into flour with fingertips or use a pastry
cutter. Knead mixture together until it forms a soft dough. Dust a
9-by-9-inch pan with confectioners' sugar. Press the dough into the
pan, about 1/2 inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Score lightly into 12 pieces. Prick dough all over with a fork.
Sprinkle 1 to 2 teaspoons caster sugar over top. Bake about 45
minutes until a creamy color, not brown, although there might be
some touches of brown on the edges or raised parts. It should feel
soft. Cut through the scored pieces and let cool and harden in the
pan. _ From Ginger McMillan Kozlosky of Dunwoody
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 228 calories, 2 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 61), 21 grams carbohydrates, 41
milligrams cholesterol, 157 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Scots Trifle
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: one hour or more
</P>
<P>
   For a festive dessert, you could do as some Scots in this area
will be doing and make a trifle, such as this easy one.
</P>
<P>
   1 10 1/2-ounce angel food cake (7-by-4-inch loaf shape)
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup jam (strawberry or raspberry)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange juice or fruit syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sherry or marsala
</P>
<P>
   1 5.1-ounce box instant vanilla pudding, prepared according to
package directions, using 3 cups 2 percent milk (or 2 cups homemade
custard)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Split the cake horizontally into four layers, each about 1/2
inch thick. Spread two of the layers with jam; top each with one of
the remaining layers. Cut ``cake sandwiches'' crosswise into
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-quart glass or souffle dish, arrange half the cake
fingers. Set aside remaining cake.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine orange juice or syrup and sherry or
marsala. Drizzle half the juice mixture over cake in dish. Reserve
remaining half of juice.
</P>
<P>
   Pour half the pudding over the cake fingers in dish.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat, adding cake fingers, juice mixture and pudding. Cover
and chill one hour or until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, whip cream with sugar and vanilla extract,
about 4 minutes, and spread on top.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: Use sponge cake layers or ladyfingers in place of
angel food cake; add crumbled macaroons to the cake layers; top
with chopped nuts. _ Adapted from ``Piping Hot: The Scottish
Heritage USA Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 397 calories, 6 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 30), 63 grams carbohydrates, 48
milligrams cholesterol, 392 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
