<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0919 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-20 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IMPEACHMENT CLAUSE FOR THE NEW MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Count me among the 30 percent of Americans who,
according to the polls, are closely following the Senate's
impeachment trial of President Clinton. It has been suggested to me
that I should get a life and just ignore the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I should, too. Following the democratic process seems
painfully unfashionable these days _ like smoking cigarettes or
actually opening a book now and then. Interest in politics, even an
interest that pays the bills, seems clear and convincing evidence
that you're just not with it.
</P>
<P>
   But I've learned something by watching all this. I've learned
that we once again need to amend the Constitution of the United
States. We need, specifically, to alter the impeachment clause.
</P>
<P>
   It now reads, ``The president, vice president and all civil
officers of the United States shall be removed from office on
impeachment for and conviction of treason, bribery, or other high
crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that perjury or obstruction of justice is a
serious crime _ a ``high crime,'' if you will. There's also no
question that most people, for a variety of reasons, don't want
this president removed for committing this particular high crime.
The problem is that the Constitution, the supreme law of the land,
was written by a bunch of dead, slaveholding white males, and it
seems to mandate removing a president who commits a serious crime,
even though many people pretend that it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's my suggestion as to how to fix this outdated
document. The impeachment clause should be rewritten to read as
follows:
</P>
<P>
   ``The president, vice president and all civil officers of the
United States shall be removed from office on impeachment for and
conviction of treason, bribery, or other high crimes and
misdemeanors _ except in the following cases:
</P>
<P>
   ``1. If the high crime in question is in any way, shape or form
connected, however remotely, with private, consensual sexual
activity with any mammal or other life form;
</P>
<P>
   ``2. If those pushing the removal of the president, vice
president or civil officer strike most Americans as geeky,
judgmental, overly moralistic, mean, weird and have bad haircuts;
</P>
<P>
   ``3. If any other member of either house of Congress has ever,
at any time or place or in any form, engaged in any sexual contact
with any other life form to whom that member of Congress was not
legally married at that precise moment;
</P>
<P>
   ``4. If such high crime was investigated by any independent
counsel who is not of the same political party as the president,
vice president or civil officer;
</P>
<P>
   ``5. If the high crime in question, such as bank robbery or
murder, has no direct, immediate bearing on the nation's security
or policy;
</P>
<P>
   ``6. If it can be alleged, however tangentially, that any member
of Congress has ever engaged in any activity that in any way, shape
or form could be construed as remotely similar to the high crime
committed by the president, vice president or civil officer;
</P>
<P>
   ``7. If a majority of Americans, as measured by the polls,
figure that whatever high crime committed by the president, vice
president or civil officer is one that they might also have
committed in a similar circumstance;
</P>
<P>
   ``8. If such high crime was committed by any president, vice
president or civil officer who, when taking his sacred oath of
office, had his fingers crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   I understand that amending the Constitution is a cumbersome,
time-consuming process. But with such towering public sentiment
that the current impeachment clause is no longer in the country's
interest, it should be relatively easy to ram this change through.
And, when we're finished there, we ought to do something about that
dopey First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Most people would go for that, too.
</P>
<P>
   And in a heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0922 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANINI-HNS &LR;      01-20 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANINI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM ITALY WITH LOVE: PANINI BECOME AN AMERICAN CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If a hero is but a sandwich, panini are but a
snack.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? Don't be. Panini have simply been Americanized.
</P>
<P>
   Translated literally from Italian, panini means ``rolls'' or
``little breads.'' In Italy, the word is synonymous with appetizer
sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   There, they are designed to be eaten between meals, on-the-run
or standing at a chest-high counter, to be chased down with a quick
shot of intoxicating espresso. Sometimes they are served with
drinks before dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Panini (singular is panino) became popular in the United States
a decade or so ago. It is believed they first appeared in
California, notably at the Angeli Caffe in Los Angeles. By the time
they started showing up in New York, panini were being made with a
special grill that resembles a waffle iron.
</P>
<P>
   The key to first-rate panini, however, is not the grill but the
quality of bread used to prepare the sandwich. Panini can be served
hot or cold. However, artisanal breads, freshly baked and
preferably on a stone hearth, are a must for proper panini.
</P>
<P>
   As for the filling, there is no limit to what goes in the
panini. Simplicity and freshness are paramount, but there is no
right or wrong way to combine ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PANINI CAPRESE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 2 panini)
</P>
<P>
   1 large ball fresh mozzarella, about 1/2 pound
</P>
<P>
   2 large rolls, round or baguette-shaped
</P>
<P>
   Extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes, ripe but firm, cored and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Dried Mediterranean oregano, such as Greek oregano
</P>
<P>
   8 basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Cut the mozzarella in slices and place on folded clean tea
towels. Meanwhile, slice the rolls in half horizontally. Place
bread cut-side-down on a grill or cut-side-up under a hot broiler,
until lightly toasted. Drizzle both sides of the bread with olive
oil.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange tomatoes on bottom halves of rolls. Season with salt and
pepper, a sprinkling of oregano, and a drizzle of olive oil.
Arrange the mozzarella on top of the tomatoes. Season again with
salt, pepper, oregano and olive oil. Top with the whole basil
leaves. Cover the top halves of the rolls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GOAT CHEESE AND ROASTED PEPPER PANINI
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 panini)
</P>
<P>
   5 1/2 ounces goat cheese, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   3 green onions, trimmed of half of the green tops, finely
chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped basil
</P>
<P>
   1 small garlic clove, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons capers
</P>
<P>
   Small pinch hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   4 michette, or round rolls, about 5 inches in diameter
</P>
<P>
   Place the goat cheese in a bowl and combine with the green
onions, herbs and garlic. Season with salt and pepper. Set aside.
You can prepare cheese mixture several hours in advance.
Refrigerate, then bring to room temperature before using.
</P>
<P>
   Roast the peppers. Remove the blackened skin, core, seeds and
membranes. Cut into thick strips. Place on a plate and toss in
olive oil, lemon juice, capers and hot red pepper flakes. Season
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Split the rolls in half. Spread the goat cheese on the bottom
half of the rolls. Top with strips of roasted peppers and capers.
Drizzle the remaining juices over the inside of the top half of the
rolls. Cover panini with the top halves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Both recipes from Viani La Place's ``Panini, Bruschetta,
Crostini'' (Hearst Books, 1994)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PANINO RUSTICO
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 panini)
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless chicken breasts, skin on
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon raisins, plumped in hot water for 10 minutes, then
drained, optional
</P>
<P>
   Rolls of your choice
</P>
<P>
   Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Small bunch or arugula, stems trimmed, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400.
</P>
<P>
   Place the chicken on a baking sheet, skin-side-up. Bake for
about 15 minutes, or until cooked through. Remove from the oven and
let cool.
</P>
<P>
   When the chicken has cooled, remove and discard the skin. Shred
the meat and place in a medium stainless or glass bowl. Add salt
and pepper to taste. Use a citrus zester to zest the lemon directly
over the shredded chicken. Cut the zested lemon in half and squeeze
the juice from one half over the chicken. Add the olive oil,
balsamic vinegar, pine nuts and the raisins if desired. Stir gently
to mix.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble the panini, slather the bottom of a roll with Dijon
mustard. Spoon the chicken salad and some of the juices onto the
rolls and top with the arugula and the tops of the rolls. Cut in
half and serve.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipes From Evan Kleiman's ``Angeli Caffe: Pizza Pasta
Panini'' (William Morrow, 1997)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
