<P>
   &UR; WELCOMES AND WORRIES: KING HUSSEIN RETURNS TO JORDAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Tuesday, 19 January) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Cockburn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMMAN _ Piloting his own plane, King Hussein returned to Jordan
today following six months of chemotherapy treatment for cancer in
the U.S. While Jordanians publicly celebrated his reported cure
from lymphoma, they privately speculated about who will succeed to
the throne the king has held for 45 years _ and about the future of
their country after his reign.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of succession from King Hussein's point of view is
that Jordan cannot afford a weak ruler because it is less poweful
than all of its neighbors. He knows his dynasty cannot afford to
make too many mistakes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-KING'S-QUANDARY-JORDAN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADULTERERS AND LIARS _ BUT AMERICA STILL LOVES POLITICIANS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Marshall &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Egregious and criminal conduct; repeated lying;
adultery, obstruction of justice and perjury. In great detail,
these are the charges that have been lobbed against the President
of the United States in the past few days. Is it any wonder that
Americans have such a low opinion of their politicians?
</P>
<P>
   Except, it seems, they don't. Most of the evidence shows that
Americans have, over the last few years, recovered some of their
trust in politics and government, and calling someone a politician
is no longer the worst insult you can level. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Article stands in 875 words; total uncut version is 975.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-US-LOVES-RASCALS-875&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH THE PRESIDENT! (BORIS, NOT BILL) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Phil Reeves &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The president is threatened with impeachment. His
enemies believe he is guilty of high crimes (not to mention
misdemeanors), and want him thrown out of office. They regard him
with a venom that at times defies explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, he is not Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   These days all eyes are on Washington and the president's
impeachment trial. But, for the past six months, a 15-member
Russian parliamentary commission has been busy investigating
whether there are grounds to impeach Boris Yeltsin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Article stands in 575 words; total uncut version is 800.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-IMPEACH-YELTSIN-575&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE MUST INTERVENE IN KOSOVO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By The Editorial Board of The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Serbian forces may have cleared the bodies from the mosque. They
may have succeeded in hiding some of the evidence from
international observers. But the implications of the massacre in
the Kosovo town of Racak cannot be cleaned up so easily, for the
anger felt around the world has been both heartfelt and genuine.
</P>
<P>
   If we do not wish to see more innocent people die in vain, the
only solution is to intervene in force to secure the separation of
the combatants in Kosovo and to hope that negotiation is forced by
the stalemate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-ACT!-KOSOVO-EDITORIAL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSTANT HOLLYWOOD STARDOM _ FOR THE PRICE OF A STEAK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Special Attn: Travel Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Gumbel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, CALIF. _ What's the price of fame? At Tinseltown
Studios, it's an easy question to answer: $44.50.
</P>
<P>
   That's the cost of admission to a novel Southern California
theme park that promises to turn anyone who visits into a movie
star, at least for a couple of hours. Are you ready for your
close-up?... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550-words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-`VIRTUAL'-TINSELTOWN-RESORT-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTRITE `WHITE' DENNY'S DISHES UP DIVERSITY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Dejevsky &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The familiar yellow, red and green logo of Denny's
restaurants has added a new color: black.
</P>
<P>
   Since paying out a stinging $54 million settlement a few years
ago to two groups of aggrieved customers who claimed they had been
refused tables or service for no reason other than their skin
color, Denny's has embarked on an ambitious image makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of its employees are now black or Hispanic, and
one-third of its supervisory staff are minorities. It has minority
representatives on its board and puts all staff through
``diversity'' training.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Denny's franchises held by black Americans has
gone from one to 123 in six years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-MINORITY-MEALS-DENNYS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KREMLIN OWNS $650 BILLION WORTH OF PROPERTY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Phil Reeves &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ No matter that 40 million Russians are below the
poverty line. No matter that Moscow is looking for another
multibillion dollar bail-out from the International Monetary Fund
to plug a gaping hole in the budget, or that it defaulted on
foreign debts to the horror of the world's financiers only months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny part of the country, at least, is extremely wealthy, with
enough funds to pay off its international debts four times over.
The Kremlin owns $650 billion _ yes, billion _ worth of property,
making it one of the world's largest commercial entities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-KREMLIN-BILLIONAIRES-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
