<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MILITARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM MAKES MEXICAN SOLDIER A WANTED MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For most of the 24 years that he served as an Army
surgeon, Hildegardo Bacilio Gomez performed as most other soldiers
do: respectfully, obediently, and quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is Mexico's most wanted military fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Bacilio Gomez, a 43-year-old lieutenant colonel, has
been accused of desertion for failing to show up for work three
days last month.
</P>
<P>
   But he is more widely known for doing something rarely seen in
modern Mexican history: leading an internal rebellion in the armed
forces and openly criticizing his superiors and the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bacilio Gomez led about 50 fellow officers on an unprecedented
march late last month down Paseo de la Reforma, the capital city's
main boulevard, to protest what they say are deteriorating
conditions for Mexico's armed forces. Last week, in another
protest, he and five others attempted to deliver a letter outlining
their demands to President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Although the insurgency consists of only a fraction of Mexico's
175,000 soldiers and officers, it is unusual. In the 80 years that
the governing party, known as the PRI, has been in charge, the
country's military has been a mostly silent and loyal ally. In
exchange, presidents for decades have given military brass plenty
of autonomy to manage their own internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The group's protests have also brought new attention here to the
role of the military in a society that is discovering more openness
in its civil and political affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is highly unusual but not unprecedented,'' said Donald
Schulz, a professor at the US Army War College who has written
extensively on the Mexican military. ``A number of officers have
voiced similar complaints to me.''
</P>
<P>
   To show their unwillingness to tolerate such open rebellion,
military authorities arrested five of the protesters Jan. 11 and
charged them with sedition and insubordination. Top officials have
also warned that others who join the protests will be severely
punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must put before our own interests those of the sovereignty
of the nation, loyalty to institutions and the honor of the Army,''
Rafael Macedo de la Concha, the military's top prosecutor, wrote in
a statement issued after the march.
</P>
<P>
   Bacilio Gomez remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that military police will kill him, he has left Mexico
for Venezuela, his colleagues said last week, adding that he would
seek asylum there from that country's president-elect, Hugo Chavez
_ a former lieutenant colonel who was once jailed for leading a
bloody coup attempt in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities, however, believe that Bacilio Gomez is
still in the country and they are searching for him.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the dissident movement, which calls itself the
``Patriotic Command to Raise the Consciousness of the People,'' is
a demand that armed forces personnel receive the same rights as
ordinary citizens and that the military court system be reformed
along the lines of civilian courts to stop corruption and the
imprisonment of innocent soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Bacilio Gomez was sent to medical school by the military. His
career as a prenatal specialist proceeded normally until he was
jailed in September 1996 for abandoning his post at an Army
hospital, an accusation he denies. He temporarily left his
assignment, he said, to treat a pregnant woman in a private clinic
he and his wife, a physician, have been allowed to operate for 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon, the father of six children, was sent to jail for
three days and his monthly pay was slashed from $1,500 to less than
$200.
</P>
<P>
   After that incident, according to interviews he has given to
Mexican reporters, he started meeting other officers who said they
had been through similar experiences. The group of officers started
regularly holding secret gatherings early last year.
</P>
<P>
   At first, they tried direct appeals to General Enrique
Cervantes, the Mexican defense secretary. They sent him letters
arguing that most of the soldiers in military prisons had been
falsely or unfairly convicted and requested a meeting with him.
Cervantes never responded, so the officers chose their march down
Mexico City's main boulevard in protest.
</P>
<P>
   In statements released to the press and on the Internet during
the last few weeks, Bacilio Gomez also has criticized the country's
move toward a free-market society and expresses admiration for
Subcommander Marcos, the masked leader of a rebellion by indigenous
people in the southern state of Chiapas, and for Northern Ireland
political leader Gerry Adams, head of the Sinn Fein party. Bacilio
Gomez also admires Venezuela's Chavez, who decried massive
corruption in the military and in political parties as he moved
from coup leader to vote-getter.
</P>
<P>
   In writings, Bacilio Gomez has borrowed from that theme.
``Mexico is in flames, living in a Dantesque inferno,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Many within the military have ridiculed Bacilio Gomez and his
fellow protesters, calling them ``arrogant,'' ``clowns,'' and
``traitors.''
</P>
<P>
   One Army brigadier general, Alvaro Vallarta Cecena, wrote last
week in the Mexico City newspaper Reforma that ``when some soldiers
publicly and collectively raise their complaints against a superior
or make demands of any nature, they are flagrantly violating
military laws and the corresponding authorities should act.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican military's job has changed significantly over the
last 20 years. In addition to traditional tasks of protecting
borders and maintaining order when a natural disaster hits, more
units are being assigned to battle heavily armed drug cartels and,
more recently, to fight indigenous _ and often popular _ guerrilla
movements in the southern states of Chiapas, Oaxaca, and Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   Though the missions may be more dangerous, the soldiers' pay
remains among the lowest among government workers _ about $200 a
month _ less than half the salary of a judicial police officer in
Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many who don't like these new roles because they
feel they can be either corrupted or killed,'' said Jorge Chabat, a
professor specializing in security issues at the Center for
Research and Economic Science in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a military officer spoke up against his superiors
was in 1993. General Jose Francisco Gallardo Rodriguez openly
criticized the military for committing human rights abuses. The
general, who had also called for the appointment of a human rights
ombudsman, was charged with embezzling funds and sent to prison,
where he remains, despite protests from rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Military experts say the marches may foreshadow broader, deeper
discontent within the armed forces and an end to its tight-lipped
acceptance of a corrupt society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military has always been a hermetically sealed
institution, especially when it comes to internal problems,'' said
Schulz, the US Army War College professor. ``But now there's more
criticism coming out. It's quite an extraordinary change we've seen
in the last few years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
