<SLUG> BC-SPEECH-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL LAWSUIT TO SEEK COSTS OF SMOKING-RELATED ILLNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking the government's antitobacco fight to new
ground, President Clinton announced that the Justice Department is
drafting a lawsuit against tobacco companies to recover the
``hundreds of billions of dollars'' that federal agencies have
spent on smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Similar lawsuits led to a series of settlements last year
between state governments and the nation's largest tobacco
companies. In the biggest deal, the industry agreed to pay roughly
$206 billion to 46 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoking has cost taxpayers hundreds of billions of dollars
under Medicare and other programs,'' Clinton said in a surprise
announcement during his State of the Union address. ``The states
have been right about this: Taxpayers shouldn't pay for the costs
of lung cancer, emphysema, and other smoking-related illnesses. The
tobacco companies should.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Justice Department lawyers are ``preparing a
litigation plan to take the tobacco companies to court, and with
the funds we recover, to strengthen Medicare.'' He did not say when
the suit would be filed.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Tobacco Institute, which represents the
industry, did not return calls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has been considering a lawsuit against
tobacco companies ever since the first state case was filed about
four years ago, said Kathryn Kahler Vose, spokeswoman for the
Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We frankly have wondered why the Justice Department has not
moved more quickly against the tobacco companies, and we are
encouraged to hear that they are moving now,'' she said. ``The
tobacco companies are adding kids every day'' as customers, ``and
for the federal government not to hold them responsible is a real
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Antitobacco activists failed last year to push legislation
through Congress that would have forced the industry to pay $516
billion to the federal government and states over 25 years. The
bill also would have imposed advertising restrictions on tobacco
companies, forced them to reveal research documents, and levied
fines if the number of new teen-age smokers did not decline.
</P>
<P>
   Though contents of the Justice Department lawsuit were not
disclosed, the suit could seek some of those remedies. In its
settlement with the states, the tobacco industry agreed to new
restrictions on marketing to minors, though they were less
restrictive than envisioned in the federal legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, White House aides have said Clinton will push to
raise the cigarette tax this year by 55 cents pack. Antitobacco
activists say raising the cost of cigarettes is an effective way to
discourage teens from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also pushed to expand the Food and Drug
Administration's ability to regulate tobacco. In his address,
Clinton called on Congress ``to reaffirm the FDA's authority to
protect children from tobacco'' and said that ``our children are
targets of a massive media campaign to hook them on cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government spends money to treat tobacco-related
disease through several programs, including Medicare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
