<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0942 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CDROM-AFRICANA-BOS &LR;      01-20 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDROM-AFRICANA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES &AMP; GATES BRING DREAM OF DU BOIS TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On Monday, Martin Luther King Day, Microsoft released
Encarta Africana, its highly publicized CD-ROM encyclopedia devoted
to African culture throughout the world. This fall, Perseus Books
will publish a print version.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time anyone has been able to put the African
world in a jewel case _ or between two covers,'' Harvard University
professor Henry Louis Gates Jr. said Tuesday at a meeting with
Globe editors and reporters. ``To chart the contours of the African
world, that's what we were able to do,'' added Gates's fellow
Harvard professor Kwame Anthony Appiah.
</P>
<P>
   Gates and Appiah, who supervised the project, a joint
undertaking by Microsoft and Afropaedia LLC, were at the Globe to
demonstrate the CD-ROM. It contains 3,361 articles, totaling 2.5
million words, and includes hundreds of audio and video clips. The
cost is $49.95. The project drew on some 400 contributors,
including UN Secretary General Kofi Annan, musician Quincy Jones,
and actress Whoopi Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   Encarta Africana is an idea 90 years in the making. It was in
1909 that W. E. B. Du Bois, America's leading black intellectual
during the first two-thirds of this century, conceived the idea of
an Encyclopedia Africana to foster understanding, and thus
tolerance, of African people throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   He solicited 100 leading academic figures to serve on his
editorial board, among them the philosopher Henry James and
anthropologist Franz Boas. The only one to turn him down was
Harvard's president, Charles Eliot (Du Bois was the first black
Harvard PhD). Eliot offered what would prove to be an
all-too-pertinent piece of advice: ``Be sure to secure the funding
before you begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Du Bois intermittently worked at the project for the next
half-century. By the time of his death, in 1963, he had moved to
Ghana and revamped the encyclopedia as a purely African venture.
</P>
<P>
   It was as a Yale undergraduate that Gates first heard of Du
Bois's cultural grail. ``Like every other black intellectual then,
I was a Du Bois junkie,'' he recalled. A few years later, on a
fellowship at Cambridge University, he met Appiah, also a graduate
student there, and the Nigerian novelist Wole Soyinka, a future
Nobel laureate in literature. The three of them made ``a pact,'' as
Gates described it, to see Du Bois's encyclopedia into print.
Twenty-five years later, Gates noted with satisfaction, the dream
has become reality.
</P>
<P>
   Such prominent black Americans as Jesse Jackson, Julian Bond,
and Michael Jordan have already endorsed Encarta Africana, and The
Wall Street Journal's computer columnist, Walter S. Mossberg, has
called it ``a piece of software that demonstrates convincingly the
power of the computer to change society for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Du Bois's son, David, was shown the CD-ROM last month and gave
his blessing. ``Of all the reviews we would get,'' Gates said,
``none would be better than that.'' But the response to Encarta
Africana has not been universally favorable. Critics see Encarta
Africana drawing attention _ and financial backing _ away from Du
Bois's original Encyclopedia Africana project, which remains
headquartered in Ghana and has so far published three volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Others see the CD-ROM as the latest venture in what one might
call Skip Gates Inc. Gates, 48, has few peers, white or black, as
an intellectual entrepreneur. He's edited or written 16 books. His
articles regularly appear in such influential publications as The
New York Times and The New Yorker. He has climbed the academic
ladder with speed and dexterity: going in 12 years from Yale to
Cornell to Duke to Harvard. He has almost single-handedly turned
Harvard into a powerhouse in African-American studies, bringing to
the faculty such luminaries in the field as University of Chicago
sociologist William Julius Wilson, the late University of
Pennsylvania jurist A. Leon Higginbotham, and Princeton philosopher
Cornel West.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints have been heard about Gates creating a ``Cambridge
Mafia'' in Afro-American studies, and some critics see it as only
fitting that on Encarta Africana he has joined forces with his
namesake, Bill Gates, the founder of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it Gates &AMP; Gates _ or Gates squared,'' says Ray
Winbush, director of the Race Relations Institute at Fisk
University, in Nashville. ``Microsoft has good marketing. It's the
same thing with Gates &AMP; Gates. The Encarta Africana has the richest
man in the world working together with one of the most prominent
black academics in the world, and that's a seductive combination.
But I am convinced that it's not, by any means, a fulfillment of
the vision Du Bois had for his Encyclopedia Africana.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates, who amusingly recounted the disappointment of people
who'd take his telephone calls thinking he was the other Gates,
shrugged off such criticism. ``We went everywhere, hat in hand,''
he said. ``What we liked about Microsoft was they were willing to
do it.'' Among firms who turned down the project were Encyclopedia
Britannica, Prodigy, Voyager, Random House, Macmillan, and Simon &AMP;
Schuster. ``I threw a Hail Mary pass to Redmond, Wash.,'' Gates
noted, ``and they said, `Fly out here and talk to us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Added Appiah, ``There's a funny logic to that criticism. If the
argument is about quality, then the fact is Encarta (Microsoft's
flagship CD-ROM) is a terrific encyclopedia. You want to do the
best you can, and both in terms of quality and marketing Microsoft
allows us to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has announced it will donate 8,000 copies of the
CD-ROM to schools and libraries, and Perseus intends to donate a
comparable number of books. In addition, Gates and Appiah hope to
initiate a series of trial programs whereby Sunday schools in
predominantly black churches will receive the appropriate computer
technology and copies of Encarta Africana _ ``wiring the Sunday
schools,'' as Gates put it, ``and use this as bait to get history
in the congregation.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what was the single most important thing about Encarta
Africana, Gates said, ``That it exists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
