<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABE GETS A REFUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I feel much better knowing that smart people like famed
dealmaker Abe Gosman and his family do dumb things, too. The
difference between Gosman and the rest of us: He can call his pal,
the chief executive of Smith Barney Inc., and get his millions
back.
</P>
<P>
   Even after recovering his losses, the episode won't do anything
to help Gosman's image as a savvy investor _ a reputation recently
tarnished by an ill-fated ``Wheel of Fortune'' acquisition strategy
that cost him his job running Meditrust Cos., a Needham real estate
investment company, and cost shareholders a bundle.
</P>
<P>
   At this point Gosman and almost everyone involved in this sorry
mess would like it to just go away. But don't bet on it. The Gosman
affair has raised too many questions Downtown about a handful of
small-capitalization stocks, and who might have been doing what
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in short, is the story:
</P>
<P>
   The Gosmans charged they were victimized by a broker who sold
them stock in two small technology companies, Palomar Medical
Technologies Inc. of Lexington and NUKO Information Systems Inc. of
San Jose, Calif. Gosman's son, Andrew made the first investments,
and over a two-year period ending in March 1997 the family poured
$4 million into the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   What a disaster. The stocks tanked, and the Gosman's say they
eventually lost more than $2 million on Palomar; Andrew Gosman lost
another $360,000 on NUKO. Both stocks now sell for less than a buck
a share.
</P>
<P>
   The Gosmans cried foul.
</P>
<P>
   They say the Smith Barney broker who recommended the stocks,
David Smith of Santa Fe, had significant conflicts of interest he
never disclosed. Among them: Smith's wife, Carol,received low-cost
warrants in Palomar potentially worth $1 million or more, which
were in fact no more than disguised commissions paid to Smith for
bringing investors to Palomar. In addition, they also cite
documents that show Smith got NUKO stock on extremely favorable
terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Gosmans say they would have never invested had they known
Smith was being paid to bring investors to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Gosman, whose companies have paid Smith Barney millions
as a securities underwriter in many deals over the years,
complained directly to Jamie Dimon, then chief executive of the big
investment house. Smith and his firm denied wrongdoing, but after
months of negotiations Smith Barney last year coughed up $2 million
to the Gosmans, according to a filing with the National Association
of Securities Dealers. Smith, 45, was discharged in November for
not disclosing to Smith Barney that his wife received the warrants,
the documents show.
</P>
<P>
   None of the players would comment.
</P>
<P>
   Is this just another rich guy burned by a broker?
</P>
<P>
   Careful readers of the Globe's business pages will remember the
name Palomar. The company played a starring role in the long
investigation of H.J. Meyers, the high-pressure brokerage house
that was run out of town by the Massachusetts Securities Division
in 1997. In a civil complaint, the division charged that Meyers
sold vast quantities of Palomar stock to investors without
disclosing the risks or Meyers' financial ties to the company.
Investors lost more than $1 million on Palomar, the division said
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Gosmans dug just deep enough and pushed just hard enough to
get their dough back. That's what they cared about. But the affair
may well provide a roadmap not only on Palomar but other stocks
that could go beyond what regulators dug out on Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Gosmans and several other investors who got burned believe
what happened at Palomar and NUKO were not isolated incidents, but
instead a pattern of illegal ``finder-fee'' payments in the form of
advantageously priced securities for delivering investors to
companies.
</P>
<P>
   This raises all kinds of questions. If, for instance, Gosman is
right and Smith was being paid a fee to push the stock, who was
paying it? And was he the only broker being paid?
</P>
<P>
   Were other stocks manipulated? The Gosmans and others think so,
and they have named names of companies to Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The state securities division is investigating, but won't
comment. No, this is not going away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey is a Globe columnist. His e-mail address is
s-bailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
