<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER HOLDS THE HIGHER GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the afterglow of Sunday's stunning performance in stopping
the New York Jets' running game, Denver Broncos defensive
coordinator Greg Robinson had history to back him up when he made
this observation:
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time of the year, the teams that win run the ball and
stop the run. It is very difficult for a quarterback to try to win
a game all by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been 32 Super Bowls, and in 28 of them, the team that
prevailed in the ground game was victorious on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Only three times has the team that gained more yardage on the
ground lost. (I'm calling Super Bowl II even, as the victorious
Jets had just 1 more yard rushing than the Baltimore Colts.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in 13 of the first 14 Super Bowls (excluding Jets-Colts
in III), the winning team had more yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   In 16 of the last 17, the team with more rushing yards won the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh has been an exception. In Super Bowls XIII and XIV,
the Steelers were outrushed by Dallas and Los Angeles but still
won, as quarterback Terry Bradshaw had big passing games.
</P>
<P>
   In Super Bowl XXX, the Cowboys ran for just 56 yards against the
Steelers but got a gift-wrapped victory when Neil O'Donnell threw
three interceptions that crippled his team. Pittsburgh outplayed
Dallas that day but lost because of its own errors.
</P>
<P>
   This Super Bowl pattern is what makes the the Denver-Atlanta
matchup so interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Denver was second in the league running the ball, and third in
stopping the run.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was sixth in in rushing, second against the run.
</P>
<P>
   But lately Denver has been sensational on rushing defense.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four games, Denver is giving up approximately 1 yard
per rush. Atlanta is giving up 3 yards per rush.
</P>
<P>
   On the offensive side of the ball, Denver has the best football
player on the planet, Terrell Davis, and the better line. Jamal
Anderson of the Falcons is a terrific running back, one of the best
in the game, but he is not Davis. No one is.
</P>
<P>
   Davis gives Denver their edge. He is the best rusher in recent
playoff history.
</P>
<P>
   In seven games, Davis has carried 179 times for 1,038 yards,
setting NFL playoff records with 148 yards per game and 5.8 yards
per carry. Those are numers that no one can touch.
</P>
<P>
   Davis dominated last year's Super Bowl, a game in which his team
was a 14-point underdog and won. Despite having a migraine headache
that forced him to the bench in the second quarter (he forgot to
take his medicine before the game), Davis collected himself at
halftime and carried his team to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has been in only two playoff games in his career (the
last two weeks). Against San Francisco, he picked up 133 yards on
29 carries, but in Minnesota, he had only 67 yards on 23 carries.
The Vikings were focused on him, though.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, Davis rolled for 199 yards on 21 carries
against Miami, and 167 yards on 32 carries against the Jets. That's
an average of 7 yards per carry, which means he is on top of his
game.
</P>
<P>
   What will make this Super Bowl different from the 32 that came
before it is that, for the first time, the running backs _ not the
quarterbacks _ go into the game as the most important players on
their teams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
