<SLUG> BC-SPECIALK-ADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLOGG'S EATS ITS SPECIAL K AD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ooops!
</P>
<P>
   That's Kellogg's response to its new TV ad featuring a Diet
Debbie doll who ``crash diets'' and ``works out after every meal''
and proclaims, ``Only celery for me.'' Then the camera fades to the
written message ``Why do we do this to ourselves every January?
Let's just eat sensibly all year'' and an image of Special K
cereal.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was too many consumers didn't catch the spoof. They
wondered if a yearning-to-be-thin Debbie really was parking her
treadmill beside Barbie's little pink coupe on toy store shelves.
They wondered who was pushing dieting to young girls.
</P>
<P>
   So on Jan. 8, just 11 days after the first Diet Debbie ad aired,
Kellogg's yanked the 30-second spot and expects it to be completely
off the air by the end of the month. The folks at the
Illinois-based National Association of Anorexia Nervosa and
Associated Disorders, who once influenced milk producers to change
a ``milk mustache'' ad that had Ivana Trump saying, ``You can never
be too rich or too thin,'' didn't even have a chance to whimper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will admit we still don't always get it right,'' says
Kellogg's spokeswoman Karen Kafer. ``The execution was confusing to
consumers. We listened to consumers and we pulled it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled,'' says Beth Jacobsen of the anorexia
associationa, which had fielded a number of complaints about the
ad. ``I'm glad to hear they've pulled it.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie may have met a speedy demise, but still alive is
Kellogg's year-old effort to reshape its attitude about Special K
with a ``Reshape your attitude'' campaign that aims to sell cereal
by stressing positive body image and self-worth and sensible
eating. It's all part of a broader trend toward more realistic
portrayals of women in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the Special K commercials with the gorgeous, young,
impossibly thin model slipping into a pair of skintight jeans or a
little black dress only she can wear. Gone are the TV ads with the
camera surveying the long, svelte body of a model in a white
swimsuit before fading into an image of the ``K'' of Special K.
</P>
<P>
   Back again, in place of Diet Debbie, is Kellogg's ``bar guys''
ad, first aired during last year's Super Bowl. One man in a bar
promises to ``not freak out if I gain two pounds'' and another
glances at his pants and asks, ``Do these make my butt look big?''
This time the written message on screen is ``Men don't obsess about
these things. Why do we?''
</P>
<P>
   Another TV spot features blurred images and questions about role
models that allow for the possibility of a role model with hips.
New print ads include one with a photo of a baby girl who asks,
``Do I look fat?'' and another with a picture of a little black
dress (ah, the little black dress) that extols a perfect size 10
``and 12 and 14 and 16.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the aging of the baby boomers, consumers want images that
are more realistic,'' says Kafer. ``Women are speaking up and
saying we want images we can relate to at this point of our lives.
This is what our consumers told us. Beauty is not built around a
number on a scale or a dress size. That's why we reshaped our
campaign around looking good on your own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg's is not alone in trying to change its image by changing
its images of women. There are more ads these days featuring older
women or women with more than skin and bones. Anne Klein's recent
campaign featured such prominent women as former Texas governor Ann
Richards and basketball phenom Lisa Leslie wearing the company's
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can pick out a few people who are trying to do a better
job of this,'' says Deborah Warner, executive director of the
Harvard Eating Disorders Center, which has invited representatives
of Kellogg's and Anne Klein to a forum in Cambridge next month.
``It may seem subtle, but it's important. There is still a long way
to go, but this is improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Babson College marketing professor Kathleen Seiders sees
it, ``there are so many more women with power and education in the
forefront of consumerism saying that's not real'' to standards of
beauty that accept only the young and the thin. ``We're the most
sophisticated generation of consumers ever.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Diet Debbie, speculates Seiders, ``it sounds like it was
too ironic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
