<HEADLINE>
STRONG MILITARY, ANTITERROR GOALS LISTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While lauding US efforts to forge peace around the
world, President Clinton emphasized his top foreign-policy goals of
rebuilding the military and reducing terrorist and nuclear threats
at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``No nation in history has had the opportunity and the
responsibility we now have: to shape a world that is more peaceful,
more secure, more free,'' Clinton said in his State of the Union
address, noting US leadership roles in Northern Ireland, Bosnia,
and Middle East peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we work for peace, we must also meet threats to our
nation's security, including increased dangers from outlaw nations
and terrorism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amid growing concern over Russia's crumbling nuclear weapons
infrastructure at a time of heightened political and economic
uncertainty, Clinton called for a major boost in spending to reduce
the threat of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is proposing $4.2 billion for the effort over the next
five years, an increase of almost 70 percent over current spending.
He also, for the first time since 1985, proposed an increase in
defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   Calling his strategy ``cooperative threat reduction,'' the
president said it is in the nation's interest to work with Russia
and other members of the former Soviet Union to halt the export of
technology, nuclear material, and expertise to ``rogue nations''
such as Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The new funds will be used to expand efforts to reduce
stockpiles of nuclear materials and disarm existing nuclear
weapons. These initiatives include programs to tighten export
controls, destroy chemical and biological weapons facilities,
dismantle stored nuclear warheads, and find civilian jobs for
thousands of weapons scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The president also called on the Senate to ``end nuclear testing
forever'' by ratifying the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, and on
both houses of Congress to pay the nation's United Nations dues.
</P>
<P>
   Responding agressively to new threats against American security
does not just mean confronting Iraq's Saddam Hussein, he said. It
also means reversing the decline in military spending for the first
time in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Investing in ``troop readiness'' will be part of the proposed
$110 billion increase in spending to modernize the military over
six years, according to National Security Adviser Samuel R.
``Sandy'' Berger.
</P>
<P>
   That includes a 4.4 percent pay raise and enhanced benefits for
military personnel, as well as money to rebuild US embassies around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget also calls for a doubling of money for
antiterrorism efforts so the United States can defend itself
against biological and chemical weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0953 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-20 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATING, NOT CURBING POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trivialization of welfare hit a new apogee last week.
Wisconsin, one of the most aggressive states in driving the poor
off the rolls, released data that found that 62 percent of
recipients who left welfare in early 1998 still had jobs by last
fall. This prompted welfare guru Larry Mead of New York University
to say: ``These work levels represent the greatest achievement in
antipoverty policy since the Great Society.''
</P>
<P>
   That must be easy for him to say, since Mead is obviously not
one of the 38 percent of former welfare recipients who is
unemployed. It is amazing in an America that is supposedly in the
midst of a boom, that 4 out of 10 people in a given group are
unemployed and this is hailed as a major social victory.
</P>
<P>
   Even in 1933, at the height of the Great Depression, the
unemployment level was 24.9 percent. When a quarter of the entire
nation was unemployed, no one, not even the president of the United
States could trivialize the meanness. Life was mean.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune magazine called President Herbert Hoover a liar for
soft-pedaling the Depression by proclaiming, ``Nobody is actually
starving. The hoboes, for example, are better fed than they have
ever been.'' When thousands of poverty-stricken war veterans came
to Washington to seek relief. Hoover ordered General Douglas
MacArthur to disperse them with tear gas, torches and bayonets.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover kept smoking 20 cigars a day and kept to his
seven-course, black-tie dinners, even as Fortune wrote: ``Men who
lost their jobs dropped out of sight. They were quiet and you had
to know just when and where to find them: at night, for instance,
on the edge of town huddling for warmth around a bonfire, or even
the municipal incinerator; at dawn, picking over the garbage dump
for scraps of food or salvageable clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990s, the wealthy are once again lighting up cigars.
Fortunate Americans fill grocery carts in supermarkets so big that
we now call them super-supermarkets. We have convinced ourselves
that any claims of hunger are hollow and joblessness is a
self-inflicted wound. There is no doubt that forcing some former
welfare recipients into jobs has transformed their lives. But the
total picture reveals that welfare reform has a very hollow side
and is inflicting very real wounds.
</P>
<P>
   In a 75-page report issued last month, the Children's Defense
Fund and the National Coalition for the Homeless said that based on
federal and state data and local surveys, welfare reform has made
life significantly more difficult for former recipients. Life is so
much more difficult that it is hard to see how they are being put
on the road to self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   It is undeniably positive that 32.4 percent of welfare
recipients who were on welfare in 1997 had a job by March of 1998.
Ten years earlier, only 20.7 percent of welfare recipients in 1989
found work by March of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But the jobs that the former recpients are finding are extremely
uneven. The CDF and the NCFTH found that only 28.8 percent had
wages above the poverty level, while 51 percent had wages that did
not even reach 75 percent of the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   In metropolitan Cleveland, only about 25 percent of former
welfare recipients earned poverty-level wages in the final four
months of 1996, while about 50 percent earned nothing at all. In
Maryland, the average salary of a former welfare recipient was only
76 percent of the poverty level for a family of three.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, only 27 percent had incomes above the poverty line
and in Milwaukee, only 16 percent had jobs that paid above the
poverty line for a family of four. Statewide, 62 percent of people
might have jobs. But in Milwaukee, according to the CDF and the
NCFTH, three out of four former welfare recipients were no longer
with the same employer nine months later.
</P>
<P>
   While welfare reform was fueled by Hooveresque stereotypes of
well-fed recipients using food stamps for sirloin steaks,
recipients who have been forced into work say they now have less
money than ever before. According to the data of the CDF and the
NCFTH, only 35 percent of former recipients in Wisconsin say they
had more money.
</P>
<P>
   According to the state's own data published last week, only 47
percent said they had more money off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, 49 percent of families reported a loss of income
compared to 40 percent who reported an increase. Welfare recipients
in several states report more families doubling up in apartments,
and significantly more families finding it difficult to pay for
rent or child care.
</P>
<P>
   No one would have a problem with welfare reform if we really
were undergoing the greatest achievement in antipoverty policy
since the Great Society. But without a movement to generate
sustaining jobs, particularly in tattered urban cores, no one can
even come close to calling this antipoverty policy.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, one could argue that thus far, welfare reform
is doing as much, if not more, to cement poverty than to crack it.
</P>
<P>
   Without evidence of a mass escape from poverty, welfare reform
is as mean as calling in MacArthur to drive the penniless out of
sight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
