<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0955 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONOTONY-LAW-BOS &LR;      01-20 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONOTONY-LAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THIS CITY, THAT BORING HOUSE WILL BE ILLEGAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLIET, Ill. _ Marilyn Treasure loves her new house. She smiles
up at the soaring ceilings, revels in its open floor plan, adds
grandmotherly touches to its cozy rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But city officials call it an eyesore, a crime against good
taste they intend to outlaw. Its chief offense: It's too boring.
</P>
<P>
   After months of debate and over protests from developers and
some homeowners who call it Big Brother at work and a hidden tax on
lower-income housebuyers, the Joliet City Council is joining a wave
of communities striking a blow for originality.
</P>
<P>
   Joliet next week intends to enact an antimonotony ordinance, a
local law that will require builders to vary the look of houses
built near to each other by alternating colors, roof heights,
windows, and other aesthetic features.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in short, Levittown backlash. After a half-century of
explosive growth of suburban subdivisions _ many built quickly and
cheaply with an emphasis on easy-to-replicate plans _ a growing
number of cities and towns have enacted laws to prevent any more of
what they call cookie-cutter atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   As Exhibit A in support of the Joliet ordinance, the law's chief
backer cites the three-year-old development on River Glen Drive
that Treasure and her husband, Francis, call home. Forty houses
along the curving street are identical: the same beige brick, beige
vinyl siding, white garage doors, chocolate roofs. They even have
the same view: a barren corn field with foot-high stalks peeking
through the snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you a drinking man? Well, you go home drunk, and you'd
never know which house was yours,'' said City Councilor Joseph
Shetina, chairman of the council's land-use committee and the prime
mover behind the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think developments like that are just a slap in the face to
the public,'' said Shetina, who runs a house appraisal company. ``I
understand that in the postwar era we needed to house people, and
these kinds of developments got built. I'm no moralist, I just
don't think we need that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   No one keeps track of how many antimonotony ordinances are in
place nationwide, but at least a dozen Chicago-area suburbs have
enacted them, as well as communities in Texas, Arizona, and
California. Planners say they are far less common in the Northeast,
and municipal and development groups say they know of no such laws
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But such laws have sprouted with increasing frequency in the
past decade around the nation's fastest-growing regions,
particularly those appealing to budget-conscious, middle-income,
and lower-income housebuyers. Joliet, for instance, has seen its
population grow from 77,000 to 90,000 in the past five years, owing
to its healthy stock of houses costing under $150,000 and its
proximity to Chicago, an hour's drive to the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, the idea was to make affordable housing available
to the middle classes in the suburbs,'' said Jim Schwab, researcher
with the American Planning Association in Chicago. ``The fact that
a lot of what was built was ticky-tacky or repetitive was
irrelevant. But after seeing those kinds of subdivisions over and
over, some communities have gotten a bad taste in their mouths
about it and want it stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   The Joliet ordinance, approved unanimously by the city's Plan
Commission and expected to be enacted by the City Council
Wednesday, would require that no dwellings next to each other have
a ``substantially similar front elevation or facade'' and that no
more than 25 percent of the houses on a street look the same.
</P>
<P>
   Judgments about what makes houses similar would be based on
factors including the basic building style, the color and type of
siding, roof heights, the location and size of front windows, and
the location and size of garage doors.
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance would not force changes to houses already built,
so it would have no practical effect on the Treasures and their
neighbors, a broad mix of young families, middle-aged couples, and
senior citizens. Still, the Treasures are offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see why it bothers anybody. If you don't know which
house is yours, you're pretty far gone,'' said Francis Treasure, a
retired chemist.
</P>
<P>
   Before buying their house, the Treasures lived for more than two
decades in a huge five-bedroom house they had designed themselves.
But after retiring, they were looking for a low-maintenance,
affordable house _ theirs cost about $100,000 _ in a nice
neighborhood. They saw plans for the three-bedroom house, and were
sold on it immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy here. If somebody doesn't like it, don't buy
it. But to pass a law against it?'' said Marilyn Treasure.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is bigger for local developers, who fiercely opposed
the ordinance until they realized its passage was inevitable. Then
they fought to ease some of its provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're infringing on my freedom as a builder,'' said Larry
Capista, president of Phoenix Developers, which he said has built
1,400 houses in Joliet in the past decade. Signs for his next
developments, with names like Sunset East and Sunset Ridge, have
sprung up in the cornfields near the Treasures' house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the council members say they don't like driving down
the streets seeing the same house over and over. I drive a white
Lexus, and I don't like seeing other white Lexuses, but I can't
tell other people what cars to buy or not to buy,'' said Capista,
who owns a custom $750,000 house in Joliet's toniest neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Capista intends to build more than 200 new houses in Joliet this
year, and he said the ordinance might add several thousand dollars
to the roughly $150,000 price of each house. ``When you get to
$220,000 to $260,000, you can make them all different. In our price
range, we have to work on volume, because the margins just aren't
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most residents of River Glen Drive seem to agree with Capista,
but at least some wish there was more variety in their
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right price at the right place, but I do not think
that a builder should build like this,'' said Clara Petruska, who
lives down the street from the Treasures. ``I think a home should
look like the individual, and these don't.''
</P>
<P>
   While Joliet is just launching its fight against monotony, other
Chicago-area communities have been living with such laws for more
than a decade. One of the first was the village of Carol Stream, a
suburb with 38,000 residents about 20 miles west of Chicago that
enacted one of the strictest codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a real success,'' said the village planner, Tony
Budzikowski. ``We still have trouble with developers, because
they'll have a hot seller, and they want to put it straight down
the block. But that's not what the village wants.''
</P>
<P>
   As proof that every action has an equal and opposite reaction,
the rise of antimonotony ordinances comes at the same time private
homeowner associations are going in the opposite direction by
requiring conformity in things such as landscaping, additions, and
paint color.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably more with architectural controls than
anticodes,'' said Schwab, the planning researcher. But whether that
shows ``that suppressing wackiness is more important to Americans
than suppressing monotony, I just don't know,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
