<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US'S ENEMIES ARE ENJOYING THE SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The three men outside of Washington who may have the most to
gain from the dragged-out impeachment soap opera are foreign
leaders who individually chose this opportunity to escalate their
beefs with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Our old friend Saddam Hussein, our new enemy Osama Bin Laden,
and the infamous Slobodan Milosevic, have, coincidentally or not,
picked this time to raise the stakes. Clinton's hands are more or
less tied, they figure.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he ordered the four-day air campaign against Iraq as the
House of Representatives voted impeachment. But that retaliation
for the ousting of the UN weapons inspectors was too short to do
much but punctuate the disagreement between the Iraqi dictator and
the US, which with Britain provides the teeth in the now-bankrupt
weapons inspection scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, the rich Muslim who finances a string of terrorist
training depots, is the man who supposedly masterminded the US
embassy bombings in Africa. NBC News says he's supposedly planning
a fresh outrage to underscore his hatred of the American
government's foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
   And Milosevic, the closest thing to Hitler Europe has confronted
in the last half-century, has taken the audacious steps of
countenancing the massacre of Albanian civilians in Kosovo,
refusing access to the UN's war crimes prosecutor, and expelled an
American diplomat who blamed the massacre on Serb authorities.
</P>
<P>
   If they spend any time at all watching CNN, America's top three
enemies of the moment _ on any given day the trio may shuffle in
the rankings, but all three are consistently up there in the Bad
Guy Department _ have to be happy at the way Clinton is writhing to
get off the impeachment hook.
</P>
<P>
   The point has been made in this space previously that the world
does not go on hold while we sort out this Republican coup attempt
in D.C. The Japanese bankers, the Brazilian government, the
midwives of the already successful and potentially awesome Euro
experiment, the Asian currency speculators, the Chinese economic
planners, none of these people are backing off while the American
Congress sorts out its feelings about the president's dalliance
with a female intern.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do the world's Bad Guys, the men who most hate America,
take the week off just because Henry Hyde and Bob Barr and Trent
Lott are having a hissy fit. It does not work that way. So Boris
Yeltsin is in a hospital with a bleeding ulcer, and shadowy
ex-Soviet weapons makers are hiring out to anyone who'll write the
check? Sorry, we're doing impeachment in this country.
</P>
<P>
   So Clinton's personal architect of the Dayton peace accords is
awaiting Senate confirmation to be UN ambassador? Hey, too bad that
Clinton can't employ Richard Holbrooke's skills at the UN; the
Senate is holding up his confirmation over some financial
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is shaky? Canada is peeved about trade issues? The
Europeans are leaping into the future with their Euro currency
consolidation? Millions of Central American poor people are
scheming how to penetrate our borders for desperately needed work?
The Hurricane Mitch victims whose livelihoods were obliterated are
now headed this way? And we have no humane way of either preventing
them, or receiving them, or dealing with them once they sneak in?
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but the Congress is tied up with Monica. Like the cable
networks and the evening news, Congress has gone All Monica, All
The Time.
</P>
<P>
   It is small consolation to the people and the governments that
desperately need stability, strength, and leadership from the US.
</P>
<P>
   Let the word go forth, as JFK put it in his inaugural, that
Uncle Sam is having a midlife crisis. The most powerful government
on earth is dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is going to happen in D.C. until the Republicans have
wrung every last pathetic ounce of bathos from this dumb show. Now,
we're told, there will be witnesses deposed by the Senate. Drag it
out more, senators; go right ahead. That's your right as the
majority party. You can't dig up the 67 votes to oust him, but you
can easily round up the 51 votes to call witnesses, depose
different people, create more opportunities to screw up the
process, and hopefully smear Clinton some more.
</P>
<P>
   As a strategy, it's a classic short-term gain, long-term loss
for the GOP. The country is a rock-solid 2-1 in favor of letting
Clinton serve out his term as long as he's censured for what he got
up to with Lady Monica.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans get to conduct impeachment the way they want
because they have six more seats than the Democrats in the
435-member House, and 10 more seat-holders than the Dems in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Because the GOP holds a margin of a total of 16 seats out of 535
(one is an independent) _ a margin of control of less than three
percent _ the Congress is tied up in knots. And no one is happier
over this state of affairs than the three desperados who are
emboldened by our self-inflicted paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
