<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-20 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'LL MISS YOU JOE, HONEST . . . 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We can forgive the photo op in Carol Carreer's ice-encrusted
backyard, but who's idea was 1-800-JOE-4-OIL?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't the nuns ever teach you, Congressman, that an act of
charity only counts in Heaven if you don't attach your name to it?
</P>
<P>
   It has been hard to miss the fact that Joseph P. Kennedy II is
back in Massachusetts. If you haven't seen him in the blitz of
television commercials for Citizens Energy Corp., surely you caught
a glimpse of him on the local news Monday, in his polished black
wingtips, pumping heating oil into Ms. Carreer's empty fuel tank in
Jamaica Plain.
</P>
<P>
   No one is disputing that Kennedy is sincere in his efforts to
bring low-cost heating fuel to the poor and the elderly. He founded
Citizens Energy 18 years ago for just that purpose. And he used the
occasion of his final speech on the floor of the US House in
December to make an impassioned appeal to his colleagues to
remember the dispossessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think that the only moral standard in America ought
to be about sex. . .'' he said in what may rank as the most
heartfelt speech of his 12-year tenure in the House. ``The truth is
that there are too many people in poverty; there are too many kids
that do not have access to health care; there are too many families
that do not have enough food in their stomachs. These issues do not
receive even close to the amount of time and effort and energy that
we are now putting into trying to impeach the president.''
</P>
<P>
   No, insincerity is not Joe Kennedy's problem; overexposure is.
</P>
<P>
   After long and thoughtful consideration, the congressman chose
to surrender a secure House seat in the wake of the accidental
death of his brother Michael last winter. Both his large extended
family and Citizens Energy, which Michael had been running, needed
him back at the helm, a grieving and reflective Kennedy concluded
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Good reasons, then and now, to have exited the public stage, to
have set aside personal political ambition to focus instead on
life's larger questions. How refreshing it was to see such a public
man re-embrace private life.
</P>
<P>
   But old habits die hard. Since casting his final House vote
against the impeachment of President Bill Clinton last month, the
telegenic former congressman has not been out of our sight.
</P>
<P>
   There he is presiding at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   There he is delivering fuel oil to the needy.
</P>
<P>
   There he is distributing blankets to the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   We so admired Congressman Kennedy's plea for privacy. Why, oh
why, won't he claim it?
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Joe Kennedy is not the only Massachusetts politician
manifesting painful symptoms of withdrawal from the permanent
campaign. Former Boston mayor and US ambassador to the Vatican
Raymond L. Flynn and Congressman Martin T. Meehan come immediately
to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The man who, as mayor, routinely commandeered snowplows and fire
trucks to ensure a 30-second spot on the evening news opted to
undertake a doomed run to replace Kennedy in the 8th District last
fall rather than retire quietly to private life. Failing that,
Flynn has fashioned a public persona as host of a radio call-in
show on Saturday mornings, when most of his would-be
constituents/audience are at the supermarket or the dry cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Meehan, for his part, is so gripped by Potomac fever
that he is ready to forsake his pledge to serve no more than four
terms in the US House in order to remain in Washington. Never mind
that ``Eight is Enough'' was his campaign mantra when he defeated
Congressman Chester Atkins in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   That was then, when voters in the 5th District were calling for
term limits; this is now, when producers for the Sunday morning TV
talk shows are calling for Marty Meehan.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing new in all of this, of course. The political
limelight has always been blinding. The relentless attention has
always been as seductive as it is intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Kennedy never claimed that he was retiring permanently from
politics in Massachusetts. It was understood that his return to
Brighton and Citizens Energy Corp. represented a much-needed
timeout. We knew that this was a political hiatus, that he would be
back in public life, presumably as a candidate for governor or the
US Senate. There would be time, with the private man out of the
public spotlight, for both him and us to think about the future.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, Joe, we can't miss you until you go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
