<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYCOS-EYEBALL-BOS &LR;      01-20 1704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-EYEBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS LOOKS TO BOOST PROFILE, NOT PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Things happen fast on the Internet. At Lycos Inc., they happen
even faster.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Lycos was one of the Internet's coulda-beens. The
firm had been one of the first to offer an in-depth index of Web
sites. Yet as millions of new users came on line, relatively few of
them paid a visit to Lycos. According to the market research firm
MediaMetrix, only about 20 percent of Web users passed through
Lycos each month, while half of them were visiting the top spots
like Yahoo and the America Online site. The company's stock price
was hovering at around 17 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward 12 months, and the change is dramatic. MediaMetrix
now figures that 45 percent of Web users visited Lycos in November,
just a few percentage points behind Yahoo. According to Lycos chief
executive Bob Davis, about 50,000 people sign up for various Lycos
Internet services every day, compared with a few hundred a day last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a remarkably short period of time, the audience shifts have
been significant,'' said Davis.
</P>
<P>
   So has the industry's view of Lycos. ``I think the perception in
the marketplace is that they're now a close number two to Yahoo,''
said analyst Sherri Wolf of Adams Harkness &AMP; Hill in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The positive vibes have also helped run up the stock price of
the Waltham, Mass. company. Even after last week's slump in
Internet stocks, Lycos shares closed Friday at 87 7/8, giving it a
total stock market value of $3.8 billion. Not bad for a company
whose fiscal 1998 sales were just $56 million.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, many people believe that Lycos shares _ and other
Internet stocks _ are still wildly overvalued. It faces the tough
job of staying ahead in a fast-changing business where differences
among rivals can often be hard to discern. And some of those
rivals, notably America Online Inc., Microsoft Corp., and Netscape
Communications Corp., have deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Lycos has something that many other pure Net
stocks don't: a history of making profits. The firm was in the
black in the first two quarters of its 1998 fiscal year, which
ended July 31. Lycos has run up $112 million in losses since then,
but then, eyeballs are expensive, and Davis has been buying them by
the millions.
</P>
<P>
   Since last February, Lycos has expanded its audience by buying
up an attractive stable of Internet properties. The shopping spree
began with a deal that nearly didn't get made.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Bo Peabody, a political philosophy student at Williams
College in Williamstown, Mass. launched an Internet site called
Tripod. Peabody and Williams economics professor Richard Sabot
wanted to create an Internet community for people his age:
twentysomethings in college, or those recently embarked upon their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of traffic because we were one of the only good
sites out there,'' Peabody recalls. Traffic built even faster when
Tripod added a feature that for its time was quite radical. Anybody
who joined Tripod could set up a personal Web site at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   By the summer of 1997, Tripod had a million users and was being
courted by a variety of Internet companies, including Lycos. On the
verge of an acquisition deal with Lycos, Tripod announced it was
backing out and selling itself to AOL instead. But the deal fell
through, and Lycos was still interested. In marathon talks that
began on New Year's Eve of 1997 and ended late the next day, Lycos
and Tripod cut a deal worth $61 million. Sabot joined the Lycos
board and Peabody became a vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The Tripod deal set the tone for 1998, and the transformation of
Lycos. As the year wore on, Lycos acquired two more major Web
properties. The company paid $133 million for WhoWhere, a Internet
``white pages'' service for looking up the addresses and phone
numbers of people throughout the country. WhoWhere also gave Lycos
another free Web site service, Angelfire _ which targets
middle-of-the-road users rather than Tripod's Generation-X emphasis
_ and MailCity, a site that offers free e-mail services to anybody
with a Web browser. Between them, these sites brought at least 11
million more users into Lycos' orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible coup came in October, when Lycos plunked down
$83 million for one of the Internet's best-known brand names: the
on-line assets of Wired magazine. Included were the popular HotBot
search engine, the Wired magazine Web site, a technology news site,
and the satirical Web magazine Suck.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Lycos had thrown off its reputation as an on-line
weakling, a search service that people visited just long enough to
look up the location of a really interesting Internet site. Davis
had turned Lycos into a diversified network of Web communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole essence of Tripod is about belonging and
participating,'' says Davis. ``That is why we have been so
successful in growth this year. We've given people a reason to
stay, not a reason to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Sites like Yahoo and Netscape's Netcenter offer most of the same
features as Lycos, but in the form of a single large site. Davis
wasn't interested in that model. Instead, he's taken his cues from
the television industry. Consider the Walt Disney Co. It operates
the ESPN cable sports network, the cable Disney Channel for kids,
and ABC for viewers of traditional broadcast television. Each
channel aims at a different market segment, but Disney owns them
all.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, Lycos is now positioning itself as the Lycos
Network _ a system of distinct yet interrelated Internet services,
each with its own style and content. Some visitors will enjoy the
corrosive humor of Suck, while others will prefer the high-tech
savvy of Wired. The HotBot search engine specializes in brute-force
Internet searching for experienced surfers, while the original
Lycos site has a more Yahoo-like, user-friendly feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided the best way to catch Yahoo was to pursue a network
of branded sites, rather than one megasite,'' says Peabody.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the Lycos properties has links to the others woven into
its fabric. Visit any Lycos site and at the top of the page,
there's a window that lets the visitor search the Lycos index. At
the bottom of the search page, there's a ``second opinion'' link
that'll run the same search in HotBot. Pages are lined with
enticements to look up phone numbers, sign up for free e-mail, or
do a bit of on-line shopping. Each of these offerings will whisk
you off to some other Lycos-owned site.
</P>
<P>
   Davis credits the cross-linking between Lycos sites for most of
his network's booming growth rate. People come for the Internet
searching and stay for the free Web pages. ``This is the whole
point about multiple brands,'' says Peabody. ``We don't care if we
lose the user if they come to someplace we own.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Rappaport, an Internet analyst at Zona Research Inc. in
Redwood City, Calif., says the Lycos model is a clever way to keep
users on the reservation, by constantly giving them reasons to go
to a Lycos destination, instead of wandering off elsewhere.
``They're capturing what could be customer attrition within their
network.''
</P>
<P>
   This approach is also capturing the attention of businesses who
want to sell their wares on line. The on-line bookseller
BarnesandNoble.com, for instance, has a strategic relationship with
Lycos that links its on-line bookstore to the company's sites. Run
a search on any topic, and BarnesandNoble will offer to sell you a
book on that subject. The bookseller also plasters its ads across
the other Lycos sites.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Rosendorf, a vice president of marketing at
BarnesandNoble.com, has nothing but praise for the Lycos strategy.
``Lycos is more than an Internet play,'' said Rosendorf. ``Lycos is
a savvy media company...I think they're some of the smartest people
on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart enough to challenge dominant sites like Yahoo and AOL?
Peabody certainly believes so. ``I think that we will likely
surpass Yahoo in reach, probably in three months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL is a bigger challenge. Not only does AOL make a big
profit, but its core on-line service charges its customers, and 15
million people are happy to pay up. That gives AOL a cash flow that
other Internet companies only dream about. No surprise that Barry
Schuler, president of AOL Interactive Services, is losing no sleep
over the Lycos challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our growth is stronger than ever,'' Schuler says. In addition,
Schuler argues, visitors to portal sites like Lycos don't stick
around for long, but soon wander off to other locations on the
Internet. ``They haven't demonstrated any particular loyalty yet to
any brand,'' he said. On the other hand, Schuler estimated that
typical average AOL user stays on line for 50 minutes a day. That
gives AOL plenty of time to bombard visitors with ads and sell them
merchandise. Until Lycos and other portals can match this level of
brand loyalty, Schuler thinks he has little to fear from them.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis sees plenty of growth ahead for Lycos. In fact, he
worries that the Bay State may not be big enough for him.
``Massachusetts doesn't have the base that Silicon Valley does in
Web companies,'' Davis frets. ``As a result, we have a smaller
talent pool.'' His biggest worry is finding enough talented workers
for the next growth spurt.
</P>
<P>
   And where will the growth come from? Advertising revenue, of
course, and exclusive deals with partners like BarnesandNoble.com.
Lycos is also planning a much stronger focus on generating revenue
from selling goods through its own on-line store. Peabody says the
ultimate goal is to have on-line retailing generate half of Lycos'
revenue, up from the present 15 percent. Then there's the highly
visible Lycos Chevrolet racing on the NASCAR circuit, and a
nationwide ad campaign keyed to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, says Davis, there are so many deals still to be made.
``Any day of the week, there are scores of companies presenting
partnership offers to us,'' he says. Davis spends much of his time
weeding through them, looking for deals that will give Lycos one
more burst of speed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
