<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINES-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIGA'S GIDEON GARTNER EXPLAINS HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As exits go, this wasn't the kind any chief executive would
relish.
</P>
<P>
   Gideon Gartner, a legend in his industry and certifiable Big
Thinker, stepped down as CEO of Giga Information Group Inc. earlier
this month. It was just seven months since he stumped for the
Cambridge, Mass. company on an investment road show, pushing its
initial public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Giga, which had lost a breathtaking $54 million building its
technology information and consulting business before the IPO,
announced financial results that came up short in its first quarter
as a public company. The stock, which sold for 12 1/2 in the July
IPO, crashed to 2 3/4 in October and has since only recovered to 6
5/8. Giga will announce its fourth-quarter results Feb. 18., when
more red ink is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gartner is stepping back to serve only as chairman of the
young company, and a money man, chief financial officer Dan Clarke,
is running day-to-day operations until a new CEO is found.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of e-mail messages and a subsequent phone
conversation, Gartner, 62, insisted his departure was part of a
plan, that he jumped and wasn't pushed from the top job at the
company he named after himself (Giga represents the first two
letters of his first and last name).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll acknowledge the timing looks suspect given our third
quarter, and that the pressures of public ownership were
significant,'' he wrote. ``But the fact is that I cut back for
other reasons, following my original plan to do so, and I cannot be
a part-time CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   Gartner, a talented classical pianist as a young man, started
his business career at International Business Machines Corp. and
later became a star analyst on Wall Street with E.F. Hutton and
Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   Giga is Gartner's second venture in the technology information
business _ part think tank and part consulting operation _ that has
generated public competitors with billions of dollars in stock
market value. The granddaddy of them all is the Gartner Group,
which he himself started and left years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner is widely seen as a gifted conceptual thinker and many
people call him a visionary. But chances are they will also tell
you he has a hard time getting day-to-day operations to run
smoothly and the people he hires for that have a habit of leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Giga has had at least four CEO heir apparents in its brief
corporate life. Other top jobs have been filled several times as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``His strengths are his vision, ability to think through new
business models, and raise money,'' said Ken Marshall, one of
Giga's former chief operating officers. ``His ability to attract
very smart people is really up there. It's in the operational area
where he's had some challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Gartner says he's heard it before.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you think we built a $50 million (company) in less than
three years?'' he said. ``It's never happened before and I was the
executor. I'm constantly cited as a visionary but at Gartner Group,
I was the CEO, the chief operating officer, the president, and the
chairman for 12 years. I ran the company and I built the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Operations are an issue at Giga because it has lost so much
money. The mistake, some believe, was a failure to trim expenses
when overly optimistic sales projections did not come true. Giga
increased the bet.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner said there was no mistake, that the expenses were
necessary to build the business he envisioned and will turn out to
be money well spent.
</P>
<P>
   Giga attempted to offer corporate clients access to all types of
technology information at once, not pidgeon-holing them into
categories of expertise that could be built slowly. That meant Giga
needed to have lots of analysts on board from Day One and a big,
expensive sales force to sell them everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our model required the (spending) ramp. It was not a matter of
prudence, it was a matter of necessity,'' he said. ``In fact, I
believe we should grow even faster than we did. . . . Growing more
slowly would have led nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the attack was against his old firm, the Gartner
Group. He believed the Giga way of doing business could attract
customers away from Gartner, but speed was of the essence.
</P>
<P>
   What the results at Giga prove is a matter of interpretation.
Losses continue but revenues and the number of clients continue to
grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has proven the model is right,'' said Clarke, the
company's interim chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Anderson, president of the competing Yankee Group and a
Gideon Gartner critic, doesn't see how.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gideon's model is fatally flawed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gartner, he says he stepped aside as chief executive to
pursue personal interests and will continue to split his time
between homes in Aspen and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not wish to be CEO from Day One,'' he said in one
message. In another: ``My business card has always said, simply,
`Chairman.' I had plenty of good reasons to disclose my plans to
the board at year-end.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
