<HEADLINE>
WHERE WILL BUSH WATCH THE SUN RISE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The national media keep saying that it's a done deal: The
governor of Texas is a candidate for president of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Far be it from me to argue with the national media. After all,
they're only wrong about 100 percent of the time, aren't they? Who
could forget those predictions a year ago that President Clinton's
tenure in the Oval Office could be measured in days, not weeks?
</P>
<P>
   Or was it hours, not days?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. The big-time pundits always claim to know what will
happen before it happens. And the current wisdom is that George W.
Bush will go after his dad's old job in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Bush has plenty to do at the moment, having just
taken the oath of office to begin his second four-year term as
governor. Never mind that he insists he hasn't made a decision
about a presidential campaign. Never mind that he has serious
concerns about the effect on his family of a run for the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind all that, because the media say Bush is running _ and
that's all there is to it.
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds of media representatives who flooded into Austin
for Bush's swearing-in on Tuesday clearly weren't on hand to tell
the world what the governor said in his inaugural address _ unless,
of course, he'd decided to use the speech to officially declare his
candidacy for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting that all this attention is being focused on a
noncandidate when there are other Republicans who have announced or
all but announced their candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   Is it because Bush has been the runaway front-runner in the
early presidential preference polls? Is it because he's the son of
a former president? Is it because the media are always more
intrigued by a candidate who seems reluctant than by one who's
beating down their doors in search of support?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is all of the above, and more. The media also have
targeted Bush because he's been a remarkably successful governor in
an enormous, complex state and because his landslide re-election as
governor confirmed his appeal to a vast cross section of voters.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there's one other thing. As any fool can see _ which is
to say that even the oblivious-to-reality experts in the media can
see it _ Bush is the sort of person whom voters could count on to
restore integrity and decency to a White House where such qualities
have been sorely lacking in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Having said all that, you wonder: How can I possibly doubt that
Bush intends to seek the presidency?
</P>
<P>
   Well, one reason is that I asked him one day last fall if I was
making a fool out of myself by suggesting that his universally
expected presidential candidacy might be something less than a
foregone conclusion. He told me that I was not _ that he truly
hadn't made up his mind and wouldn't make up his mind until the
spring of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   I believed him. I still believe him.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand, folks. I'm not saying that Bush won't run
for president. I'm just saying that he hasn't made a final decision
and that all these media geniuses who say that he has don't know
any more about it than you and I do.
</P>
<P>
   Here's something to keep in mind about all this. The governor
spoke from the heart when he delivered that inaugural address
focusing on his hopes and dreams for the future of Texas and its
people.
</P>
<P>
   As he often did during the campaign, Bush closed his speech
Tuesday by quoting a friend who lives on ``the sunrise side'' of a
mountain _ ``the side to see the day that is coming, not the side
to see the day that is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As we head into a new century,'' Bush said, ``Texas lives on
the sunrise side of the mountain, and I see a very good day
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   No one should be surprised if the governor runs for president;
the pressure on him to make the race will only increase in the
coming weeks and months.
</P>
<P>
   But count me among those who won't be shocked in the least if
Bush decides to stay home and watch that very good day arrive in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
