<HEADLINE>
STRONG MILITARY, ANTITERROR GOALS LISTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While lauding US efforts to forge peace around the
world, President Clinton emphasized his top foreign-policy goals of
rebuilding the military and reducing terrorist and nuclear threats
at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``No nation in history has had the opportunity and the
responsibility we now have: to shape a world that is more peaceful,
more secure, more free,'' Clinton said in his State of the Union
address, noting US leadership roles in Northern Ireland, Bosnia,
and Middle East peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we work for peace, we must also meet threats to our
nation's security, including increased dangers from outlaw nations
and terrorism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amid growing concern over Russia's crumbling nuclear weapons
infrastructure at a time of heightened political and economic
uncertainty, Clinton called for a major boost in spending to reduce
the threat of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is proposing $4.2 billion for the effort over the next
five years, an increase of almost 70 percent over current spending.
He also, for the first time since 1985, proposed an increase in
defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   Calling his strategy ``cooperative threat reduction,'' the
president said it is in the nation's interest to work with Russia
and other members of the former Soviet Union to halt the export of
technology, nuclear material, and expertise to ``rogue nations''
such as Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The new funds will be used to expand efforts to reduce
stockpiles of nuclear materials and disarm existing nuclear
weapons. These initiatives include programs to tighten export
controls, destroy chemical and biological weapons facilities,
dismantle stored nuclear warheads, and find civilian jobs for
thousands of weapons scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The president also called on the Senate to ``end nuclear testing
forever'' by ratifying the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, and on
both houses of Congress to pay the nation's United Nations dues.
</P>
<P>
   Responding agressively to new threats against American security
does not just mean confronting Iraq's Saddam Hussein, he said. It
also means reversing the decline in military spending for the first
time in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Investing in ``troop readiness'' will be part of the proposed
$110 billion increase in spending to modernize the military over
six years, according to National Security Adviser Samuel R.
``Sandy'' Berger.
</P>
<P>
   That includes a 4.4 percent pay raise and enhanced benefits for
military personnel, as well as money to rebuild US embassies around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget also calls for a doubling of money for
antiterrorism efforts so the United States can defend itself
against biological and chemical weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
