<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0975 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-JEWS20-COX     01-20 1874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-JEWS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lost words of Atlanta Jewish housewife create stunning portrait
of a modern woman
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ She saw Halley's Comet, crawling out of bed at 3 a.m.
May 16, 1910, worried about ``what will happen to us when we pass
through its tail.''
</P>
<P>
   She was living in Atlanta when Leo Frank, her cousin's husband,
was lynched in 1915 by an anti-Semitic mob.
</P>
<P>
   She was shocked when the Titanic went down in 1912, but
heartened by doomed men ``standing bravely, calmly, even gaily'' as
they helped women and children into lifeboats.
</P>
<P>
   She was Helen Jacobus Apte, who was born in Hawkinsville (Ga.),
south of Warner Robins, in 1886 and moved to Atlanta at age 12. She
was an ``ordinary'' housewife with an extraordinary gift for
writing who faithfully recorded the history of the city, the South
and the world _ and documented the stiff-collared moral codes of
her times _ in a diary she kept from her marriage here in 1909
until her death in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Found by relatives in a closet in 1995, written longhand in
cracked leather volumes, it's just been published under the name
she gave it _ ``Heart of a Wife.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to giving the history of the era, the diary paints a
vivid picture of a well-off, post-Victorian woman who felt
frustrated and bored at the role society dictated for her as wife
and mother and sexually repressed in an era when the topic was
taboo.
</P>
<P>
   But she wasn't shy in her diary, even hinting at playful
dalliances with former beaus while her husband, Day Apte, a grocery
broker, was away on business.
</P>
<P>
   Sex, she wrote with a tinge of disgust eight months after her
nuptials, is the ``chief thought in life'' of men. They become
``wild with passion, which seems to spoil it all for me _ gives me
a little shock. It is hard for a woman to become accustomed to it
and look upon it as something right and natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet she adds: ``A still stranger thing is that a woman is
ashamed to show passion. She is afraid she will fall in her
husband's estimation, or in her own, that it makes her less pure.
Of course, that's absurd, but I guess it's because of long years of
training and the ideas that are instilled into girls' minds _ a
maidenly austerity, which is hard to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heart of a Wife: The Diary of a Southern Jewish Woman''
(Scholarly Resources, $55 cloth or $17.95 paperback) was edited by
one of her grandsons, Marcus Rosenbaum, 50, special projects editor
for National Public Radio in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum left Apte's words largely untouched, adding some
punctuation and some of his own essays to flesh out the diary's
prevailing themes _ morality, religion, history and the role of
women in those days.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum says Apte mentions the Frank lynching only once, in
passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother and other Atlantans didn't talk about it,
because they wanted to consider it as an anomaly,'' says Rosenbaum,
recalling recollections of his deceased parents and others who knew
Apte. ``And it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank, a young manager at the National Pencil Co., was convicted
of murdering Mary Phagan, a 14-year-old employee, mostly on the
testimony of a janitor, and sentenced to death. But after Gov. John
M. Slaton commuted the sentence to life, 25 men abducted Frank and
lynched him from an oak tree in Marietta (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   After that incident, Rosenbaum says, Atlanta's Jews ``did not
protest or shout their concerns. Instead, they tried even harder to
assimilate, to be just like their neighbors. And they tried even
harder to be inconspicuous. The entire incident was too disturbing,
because it went against their unending desire to be like their
neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Apte wrote with passion over the years about anti-Semitism,
bemoaning the fact that once she and her husband were called
``stinking Jews,'' fretting that ``it is still considered a term of
opprobrium to be called a Jew'' and suggesting that too many Jews
tried to hide their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am glad, proud to be called `Jew,' '' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Helen was also proud to be a Southerner.
</P>
<P>
   In a passage written in St. Louis, she declares: ``How different
the people are here than in the South. There is no class in them.
I'll never get used to their manners and customs, and how much more
refined we are than they.''
</P>
<P>
   After passing the wreckage of the battleship Maine during a
cruise to Havana in 1910, she writes: ``How my heart thrilled and
every man's hat came off as we sang `America' and `Dixie.' '' But
later she wonders whether ``the Spanish-American War was brought on
by politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there are time gaps in the diary, it records dozens of
historical events. In one case, Rosenbaum reaches back several
years before Apte's diary begins, quoting from a letter to her
husband about the Atlanta race riots of 1906.
</P>
<P>
   Angry mobs of whites had been stirred up by newspapers, which
insinuated blacks had been raping white women. Apte's family gave
refuge to a half-dozen or so ``pitiful'' African-Americans. ``I
really feel sorry for them,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in 1918, she worried that her three brothers _ one
nicknamed Bubba _ were heading off to fight in World War I.
``Yesterday our soldier boys went away,'' she says, ``brave and
gallant and gay and all with smiles on their lips.''
</P>
<P>
   Apte was something of a philosopher, writing about politics and
scientific wonders, such as ``a great dirigible balloon'' she saw
one day. ``My, my, what will be invented next,'' she wonders.
</P>
<P>
   In 1913, she wrote that ``everyone expects great things'' of
Woodrow Wilson, who had taken office the week before. On Nov. 29,
1917, she commented on the state of the world: ``The (Atlanta)
Journal had a cartoon of another planet, and the inhabitants looked
down on this one and said, `I'm thankful because I don't have to
live down there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She recorded conventional wisdom too, though in apparent whimsy.
She noted that many people wondered whether Halley's Comet was
causing strange weather. ``One thing sure, it is most unusual to
have such a cool May, and snow is falling in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that Apte, though she had to quit Girl's High at 16
due to illness, was intelligent, well-read, socially and
politically liberal, sensitive to racial discrimination and
injustice _ and in love with Atlanta, though she also lived in
Tampa, Tallahassee, Miami, Richmond and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My beautiful spring is here,'' she wrote in 1924. ``Atlanta is
really beautiful in the spring with the peach trees in bloom and
the dogwood trees a mass of white blossoms. The surrounding country
is rolling and lovely. The good old red clay hills of Georgia
always give me a thrill when I return from a trip _ they mean
'home.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She also fell into funks, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did we accomplish?'' she wrote after World War I. ``Is
the world now safe for democracy? Alas, we seem further than ever
from universal peace.''
</P>
<P>
   And occasionally she wrote with a forlorn hopelessness.
</P>
<P>
   In 1925, she quotes H.L. Mencken, then adds her own words, on
the human condition: `` `God, if he exists at all, is neither good
nor bad but simply indifferent _ an infinite force carrying on the
operation of unintelligible processes without the slightest regard
either one way or the other for the comfort, safety and happiness
of man.' . . . I still believe in some great, irresistible force,
some mysterious universal plan, some Power above, but what are we
in it all _ grains of sand, struggling ants, less than the dust.
Here today, gone tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum, who will be in Atlanta to discuss his book Feb. 28 at
the Bremen Jewish Heritage Museum, says his grandmother still has
``probably hundreds'' of relatives in Atlanta, including members of
the prominent Selig family, associated with Selig Enterprises, a
real estate development firm.
</P>
<P>
   The diary came to light in 1995 when Rosenbaum; his brother
David, a reporter for The New York Times; and their families were
cleaning out ``decades of stuff'' from their father's Tampa house
after his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately, we all realized that this was something special.
For one thing, it was so well-written. But it also seemed . . . my
grandmother had something to say.''
</P>
<P>
   He edited out ``a few boring passages,'' but he says his
grandmother left out more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't she write about the fact that my grandfather and
his brother Bill sponsored literally hundreds of Jews trying to
escape the Nazis in the 1930s, allowing them to immigrate to
America? Or why didn't she write more about her husband's business
_ the failures and the successes? I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   What he found most interesting was that ``everything was so
natural to her. It was natural to be from Atlanta. It was natural
to be a Jew. It was natural to be a Southerner and an American.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she sometimes felt the sting of anti-Semitism, ``she
apparently didn't feel she faced it personally,'' even though there
were organizations in Atlanta, such as the Piedmont Driving Club,
that excluded Jews, he says. Atlanta's Jews simply started their
own version, the Standard Club, and went to hotels where they
weren't excluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess she felt sort of like my father, who always said, 'If
they don't want me, I don't want to belong.' ``
</P>
<P>
   By her own account, Helen Jacobus Apte felt she did belong, not
in every club, but in the city, region and country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I live in Dixie, I am, I am,'' she wrote at one
point. ``In Dixie Land I take my stand to live and die in Dixie _ I
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The diary ends soon before her death in 1946. In Miami _ Dixie.
</P>
<P>
   EXCERPT
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, Saturday, Oct. 4, 1924. It is Yom Kippur, and Apte
still grieves for her mother, Alice Selig Jacobus, who died in May:
</P>
<P>
   Today is said to be the holiest Sabbath of the year and the Day
of Atonement. I didn't go to temple because I wanted to stay home
and relax. Besides, it tears me to pieces to say the Kaddish prayer
(of mourning) with all eyes upon me. I can't control my grief, and
I'm one of those who, when they grieve, want to crawl into a dark
place alone. These holidays have been very sad, of course, for all
of us, with our dear one gone. I'll be glad when they are over, and
yet these solemn days are beautiful. Though we modern reformed Jews
have drifted away from the rites and ceremonies of our faith,
``There is a mystic tie that binds the children of the martyr
race.'' The sound of the shofar thrills me more than any aria from
grand opera. It touches something way down deep in me, something
fundamental. It reaches the soul _ our own heritage. How some Jews
can be ashamed of being Jews has always seemed to me inexplicable.
In me burns the ancient pride of race. I am glad, proud to be
called ``Jew.'' It holds no opprobrium for me even though it is
meant that way. It is a terrible thing that anti-Semitism is
growing in this country. It will hurt worst those Jews who are
ashamed of their religion. Me, it cannot touch.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Heart of a Wife: The Diary of a Southern Jewish Woman''
by Helen Jacobus Apte
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
