<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNION-LEADER-ART-BOS &LR;      01-20 1623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION-LEADER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON UNION LEADER A MAN IN THE MIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some might say Michael Zagami holds an unenviable position.
</P>
<P>
   As head of Raytheon Co.'s 3,500-member technical union, he is
both man in the hot seat and man of the hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk around the plants all the time,'' said the 43-year-old
business manager for the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers Local 1505. ``I go out and see people, and the majority of
them know I've stood up for them.''
</P>
<P>
   But nearly three years after his election, Zagami and other
elected union officials are being challenged by a handful of vocal
workers who have watched the union's membership plummet from almost
6,000 in 1994. As the leader of one of the most visible unions in
the state, his travails illustrate the difficulties of running a
union in an era of mergers, reorganizations, and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders like Zagami must live up to labor's mission of
challenging company management and keeping union members happy
while also being realistic about job protections in an era of
manufacturing cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   At Raytheon, the first wave of layoffs under Zagami stemmed from
concessions the union agreed to before his election in 1996, but in
an election year, that doesn't matter much to Zagami's detractors.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon, the $20 billion Lexington, Mass. military contractor,
last year announced plans to eliminate 14,000 jobs, or 16 percent
of its defense work force, by the end of 1999. The cuts will come
through layoffs and attrition, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest reductions, as well as the recall of some workers at
a lower pay scale, were bitter pills for union members to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see that 50 people have been laid off, I see 50 faces
of people I know and I know they're suffering,'' said Bill Guthrie,
an electrical technician who joined the company 24 years ago.
``That bothers me. It makes me feel like Mike is not pursuing the
company as vigorously as he should.''
</P>
<P>
   In some unions, the business manager emerges as the union's
leader, more so than the president. At Local 1505, for example,
Zagami is the chief negotiating officer, spokesman, and union
representative.
</P>
<P>
   But for every man or woman who questions Zagami's leadership,
others point to a 1995 contract negotiated by a prior union team
and the concessions it accepted in order to keep one of the state's
biggest private employers from moving jobs out of state. It was
those concessions, Zagami's supporters say, that stripped some
workers of jobs and recalled others at lower pay, resulting in a
two-tiered pay scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Zagami got slammed,'' said Jacqueline Taylor, a 37-year
Raytheon veteran. ``He got brought into something he really didn't
expect. He's not responsible for what happened in '95. He's done
well by us.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Nancy Cruickshanks, a 45-year-old microelectronics
assembler at the company's Quincy, Mass. plant: ``The layoffs and
bringing people back at a lower rate of pay was a done deal. It was
part of the old, 1995 contract and it has nothing to do with
Michael Zagami. But the new contract is under Zagami, and it got us
a raise. Plus, the benefits are great.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, 41-year-old George Noel, a former union steward who
works as a radar tester, is one of Zagami's most strident critics.
Noel plans to challenge Zagami for the business manager's post this
summer. Noel's supporters say Zagami shuns those who were part of
the old union regime, seems disinterested in new ideas, and is
rarely available at the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his job to enforce the contract on a daily basis, but
there's no enforcement of the contract, and they (Zagami's regime)
have people who don't understand the language of the contract,''
Noel said. ``That's my main problem, there's no fight with the
company on anything that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Zagami's supporters, by contrast, describe him as a hardworking
union leader who has been wrongly blamed for the cutbacks and
changes that have ravaged the technical union in recent years. The
past decade has seen a string of Raytheon buyouts, layoffs, and
plant closings around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprising, the criticism comes several months before what
will likely be a hotly contested June election.
</P>
<P>
   Noel argued that he had reason to be angry. In August 1997, he
was ordered to appear before the union's trial board to answer to a
charge that he violated union rules when he spoke to the Lawrence
(Mass.) Eagle Tribune about the union's financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbled by debt, the union was facing an $86,000 bill for back
taxes and interest owed to the city of Waltham, Mass. for a
building it owned that had served as union headquarters. In a push
to increase the union's depleted treasury and pay off debts
inherited from the past regime, Zagami had announced a plan to cut
union leaders' salaries to save money.
</P>
<P>
   In the May 1997 article, Noel claimed the average Raytheon
employee was against the plan. He added that such a cut would send
the wrong message to the company. Days later, Noel was slapped with
an internal complaint for speaking out. The complaint was brought
by a union member.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in a strident letter to members, Zagami warned: ``The
place to discuss our business is in the halls of labor, our halls
of labor.''
</P>
<P>
   A reserved man who is reluctant to talk to the press, Zagami
said he declined to give interviews during contract negotiations
last year because of what he described as a longstanding policy not
to debate contract issues in the media. ``There is a history of
this local not talking to the press about union affairs,'' Zagami
said. ``It is a pledge to the union membership, but George Noel
broke the pledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Zagami had never held a union title before 1996, when he was
swept into office by a wave of discontent. He said he decided to
run for business manager because he wanted to help workers get
their due.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Watertown, just outside Boston, Zagami attended
Northeastern University, where he studied criminal justice. He was
a plumber at Raytheon for 14 years before he became a union
official. And he was raised by a union family: His father, who also
worked as a Raytheon plumber, belonged to the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the business manager who had no experience,'' Zagami
said, ``but all the experience that the 1995 negotiating team had
brought us a pay freeze for four years. . . I've done more for this
union than the previous officials ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, he has. Last year, he was instrumental in
developing a provision that prohibits union members from retaining
union protected status after switching from a union post to
management. The change came several months before Arthur Osborn,
president of the union, moved to a managerial job earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Once overburdened by debt, the union is now operating in the
black for the first time in years. In August, Zagami and his
officers paid off the union's real estate tax debt and sold the
former headquarters. Now, located in an industrial park in Bedford,
Mass., the union is looking for property to buy that will provide
adequate space for office staff and membership meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Also in August, about 2,700 Raytheon workers overwhelmingly
ratified a new two-year contract negotiated on Zagami's watch. The
pact increases wages by 9 percent over the two years and guarantees
that all work on four major contracts will be done by union
members. The agreement covers 3,500 Massachusetts workers at
Raytheon facilities in Andover, Quincy, Burlington, Bedford,
Sudbury, Tewksbury, Marlborough, and Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   But that victory was overshadowed last fall when the company
announced plans to pare its work force even further by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Recent news that new pay grades would be implemented at the
Advanced Device Center, which manufactures computer wafers for
commercial clients, led to some bad feelings among some workers
employed at the Andover site. Even though many will receive
upgrades and increases in pay, workers have said they were more
concerned about seniority than a raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new plan gives away our seniority,'' said a worker at the
Andover site who asked that his name not be used. ``It's upsetting
to people. They feel like they were sold out.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Zagami, company officials gave the union an
ultimatum: accept the plan or Raytheon would either close the unit
or move it to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, which was negotiated last year, a minimum of
131 people classified as level ``C'' have been moved to a higher B
classification. As Bs, they now have the chance to move from a B-1
grade to the highest category, B-3. Additionally, people in the
highest grade, including those with less seniority, or fewer years
of service, would be allowed to bump those in a lower category in
the event of layoffs, even if those being bumped had seniority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone starts at B-1, with an automatic $2 raise,'' said
Zagami. ``But a person at a lower scale can progress to B-3. . . If
we did not give Raytheon this flexibility, the company would have
sold the center or moved it to Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing, Zagami noted that heavy politicking by union members
during an election year has placed him in the spotlight _ and the
hot seat. ``No matter what I do right now, there will always be
someone who will say it's wrong,'' he said. ``In fact, prior to
this last contract, a lot of people would come up to me and say, `I
wouldn't want to be in your shoes.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
