<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-STEPHERSON-ART-BO     01-20 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-STEPHERSON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS EAGLE FLEW FROM UCONN'S CALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was 10, maybe 11, when her folks started driving her down to
Storrs. Brianne Stepherson was agog, stunned by the throngs of
deafeningly devoted fans with Husky paws painted on their cheeks
and the glint of success lighting their eyes. The University of
Connecticut women's basketball team was just hitting a national
stride that culminated with a glittering 35-0 season in 1994-95 and
continues to this day, and young Breezy Stepherson, the hardcourt
phenom from Middleton, Mass., was there to see it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Brianne was caught up when we first took her down
there,'' recalled her mother, Kathie, of that first frenzied game.
``The tears ran down her face, she was so excited. This is the
place she wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   So in the fall of 1996, while still a junior at Masconomet
Regional High School in Topsfield, Mass., Stepherson announced her
commitment to play for her beloved Huskies _ immediately before
UConn trounced Boston College, 76-38, in the annual Reebok Classic
at the FleetCenter in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The timing would prove ironic, because when UConn (15-2) meets
Boston College (13-3) Saturday afternoon in a key Big East matchup
at Conte Forum, the Huskies will find Stepherson starting at point
guard for those same Eagles. Averaging 9.3 points a game and still
growing into her role as a team leader, Stepherson also averages
plenty of sleep at night over her ultimate choice, the precise
circumstances of which are likely to remain a private matter among
the parties involved.
</P>
<P>
   One thing does seem apparent: Stepherson's change of heart
appears to hinge on a young girl's growing realization that things
aren't always what they seem at first glance; that a girl's first
love isn't necessarily the right one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all water under the bridge now,'' said Kathie Stepherson
of the months in which her daughter slowly discovered that UConn
coach Geno Auriemma was recruiting Keirsten Walters at point guard
despite her early commitment; in which she struggled through a Nike
camp while nursing a hip flexor injury and bladder infection and
was dismayed that Auriemma didn't ask if there was anything wrong;
in which she began to wonder if a powerhouse like UConn was the
best place for her after all. ``She's happy where she is. I think
what happened is the best thing that could have happened. I think
it's safe to say there are some things in her life more important
than playing basketball, and I don't think that necessarily takes
away from her talent.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the player herself: ``I don't even think about it, except
when people ask me,'' she said last week of the decision in August
1997 to rescind her verbal commitment to UConn. ``I know I made the
best decision for me. I'm just so happy here; I don't think it
could be any better.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a representative of the UConn sports information
office, Auriemma had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite back-to-back defeats last week, BC is having its best
year ever. Cracking the Top 25 for the first time in their history,
the Eagles were at No. 21 last week before dipping out of this
week's poll after the losses. Much of the credit goes to coach
Cathy Inglese, a respected and popular coach who took the
University of Vermont to two NCAA tournament appearances on records
of 29-1 and 28-1 in the early '90s before taking over a BC team
that was 10-17 in 1992-93, the season before she arrived. Last year
the Eagles were 17-11; if they right themselves after their recent
setbacks to Syracuse and Miami, they will be back in the hunt for
their first NCAA berth.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of program, it turns out, that appeals to
Stepherson: growing, rising, still focused on the journey rather
than the destination, still negotiating a gradual and hopeful
course toward the top echelons of women's college basketball
instead of plotting its strategy on how to stay there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had offered that to her way back,'' said Mark Trent, who
coached Stepherson for two years on the Massachusetts Magic AAU
team. ``I told her, `You can go to a program that is Top 10 every
year, Final Four, or you can go to a program you can help to the
next step and take some pride in that.' I think it was a great
choice for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, so did she. ``It was almost like a change of heart
in what I wanted,'' Stepherson explained last week regarding what
steered her away from UConn, a perennial contender for the national
title. ``I wanted to be part of that `first.' The first Top 25, to
be part of that is a big thing. I know we have a lot more to
achieve and that we haven't even tapped into what we're capable of
doing yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she thinks she has yet tapped into what she is capable
of doing, Stepherson _ an All-American who was rated one of the
nation's top 50 players coming out of high school, the starting
point guard for Masconomet since seventh grade who averaged 22
points, 8 assists, and 7.5 rebounds a game in her senior year
despite warming the bench every time the score got out of hand,
which it usually did _ is quick with a no.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult being a freshman,'' she said. ``You have to
find what your role is, what you can do, what you can't do, and
what they want you to do and not to do. At the point, I'm a little
bit tentative right now; in high school, I wasn't because I was the
leader of my team and I'd take the ball to the hole if I thought I
was open or I'd take a shot if I wanted to take that shot. When I
come in here, it's like, should I drive? Or I'm afraid to do this,
or afraid to do that. I have to develop my game so I have a lot
more weapons than just a driver and a passer.''
</P>
<P>
   Inglese doesn't mind being patient while Stepherson gets
comfortable with running the team and playing more aggressively,
although she also acknowledges it's a case of the sooner, the
better with backcourt mate Cal Bouchard out with a torn anterior
cruciate ligament. For one thing, less heralded fellow freshmen
Becky Gottstein and Nicole Conway have taken off some of the
pressure, with Gottstein (averaging 8.3 points, 7.1 rebounds, three
times named Big East Player of the Week) in the midst of an
outstanding season. For another, Stepherson missed three games with
a virus so nasty that a battery of tests, including two MRIs, were
performed at Massachusetts General Hospital to rule out anything
more serious; getting her back for 40 minutes in Saturday's loss to
Miami was an unexpected bonus. For a third, ``She is extremely easy
to coach,'' said Inglese. ``A lot of times, stars of their high
school teams aren't used to being told what to do, that they've
made a mistake. She is like a sponge; she's very eager to get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   And just as eager to put the UConn controversy behind her,
especially any notion that she was reluctant to compete with the
likes of Walters _ who signed with UConn just days after Stepherson
withdrew _ and Sue Bird, two guards ahead of her in the respected
Blue Star rankings. ``It was kind of confusing to me,'' she
acknowledged of learning that other point guards were still on
UConn's drawing board. ``Then I started thinking, you know, `He
probably is doing that because it's a business and he's going to do
whatever it takes to keep his team the top in the country.' A lot
of people said, `You took back your verbal commitment because you
were afraid or wouldn't get enough playing time.' That had nothing
to do with it. If they were my teammates, I wouldn't resent them or
anything. I'd just work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent agrees. ``My feeling is she would have earned her spot on
that team and they would have seen, day in and day out, that she is
a player to be reckoned with. Would she be the starting point
guard? I don't know that. Would she have had an impact on the team?
Absolutely. She would have an impact on any team in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Stepherson, she insists there are no hard feelings. None
whatsoever. Saturday's game will be special to her ``not for
anything that happened,'' but only because her Eagles will be
playing one of the best teams in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't try to play above what I can do,'' she vowed.
``Nothing held against them. I just think it would be great if we
could give them a good game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
