<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-STOCKS (Washington) _ The Fed's chairman, Alan
Greenspan, suggests stock prices may be too high even as he
acknowledges that the economy is rolling along with few signs of
the slowdown that the Fed had expected. Testifying before the House
Ways and Means Committee, he says those good economic times could
be lulling investors into a trap, as the rebound in share prices
over the last three months has left stocks at levels that ``would
appear to envision substantially greater growth of profits than has
been experienced of late.'' By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   (See also STATEOFUNION-GREENSPAN and SOCSEC-ECONSCENE listed
with other State of the Union stories under NATIONAL-GENERAL.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (new York) _ Greenspan's comments do not worry the stock
market, which focuses on happier things, like Tuesday's Microsoft
earnings report. At midday, the industrial average was up 44
points, or 0.5 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 52 points, or
2.2 percent. Elsewhere, prices rose 1.9 percent in Tokyo and 0.2
percent in Hong Kong. They rose 3.1 percent in Frankfurt and 0.9
percent in London. On the American debt market, the long bond was
down 29/32 point, with the yield at 5.21 percent. By Robert D.
Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SBC-COMCAST (Undated) _ SBC Communications buys Comcast's
cellular operations, paying $400 million in cash and assuming $1.27
billion in debt. SBC expands its presence in the northeastern
United States, gaining 800,000 customers. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ At the antitrust trial,
cross-examination continues of the leadoff witness for Microsoft,
Richard Schmalensee of MIT. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   GM-EARNINGS (Detroit) _ General Motors' profit before special
items rose 5.5 percent in the fourth quarter, more than expected,
as the company boosted production of high-profit pickup trucks. Net
income grew 7.7 percent. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ AMR, parent of American Airlines,
says profit before a special credit fell 14 percent in the fourth
quarter because of weak international sales. US Airways also posts
a decline, while America West records earnings that are better than
expected. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   TI-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Texas Instruments' profit before charges
rose 8.2 percent in the fourth quarter, exceeding forecasts, fueled
by strong demand for digital-signal processors. The company sold
its computer memory-chip business to Micron Technology in October
so it could concentrate on production of the processors, which are
used in everything from microwave ovens to cellular phones.
Including the charges, net income declined in the latest quarter.
Revenue also fell, reflecting the sale of the memory-chip business.
By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
