<HEADLINE>
26.2-MILE COMEBACK FOR STRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tidbits gathered from here and there:
</P>
<P>
   --There it is, right there in the results of Sunday's Houston
Marathon: Kerri Strug, No. 1107, age 19, 4 hours, 12 minutes, 6
seconds. And yes, it is the Kerri Strug, of Olympic gold medal
gymnastics, vault-on-a-bad-ankle fame. Now a student at Stanford,
Strug told the Houston Chronicle last week that she still works out
on the gymnastics equipment there but is spending most of her time
having fun: playing on the bowling team, taking up golf,
rollerblading. She started running to strengthen the bad ankle; she
has family in Houston and thought it would be a low-key place to
try her first marathon after a couple of 10Ks and and two 18-mile
runs. ``I'm sick of doing serious stuff,'' she told the Chronicle.
``I want to do cool stuff.'' Her goal was to finish in under five
hours.
</P>
<P>
   --Laila Ali, 21-year-old daughter of none other than Muhammad
Ali and herself a boxer, has announced that she will turn
professional this year. ``It's in my blood,'' she said. ``My father
is cool with it. He's given me his blessing to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   --In a CNN/SI poll, 59 percent of the 1,311 responding said
that, even with the demise of the ABL, the WBNA should stick to its
summer schedule, while 41 percent said the league should switch to
playing in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   --Plans for Wsports, a new women's sports magazine that was to
launch in April, have been put on hold indefinitely, after
publisher and editor-in-chief Nancy Levin, who once captained the
Harvard women's soccer team and now lives in the San Francisco Bay
area, was unable to raise the capital needed to start the magazine
this spring by her Jan. 1 deadline. ``I am keeping the door open
for new possibilities,'' she said, adding that if investors
materialize, she would be eager to pick up right where she left
off.
</P>
<P>
   --Meanwhile, Amy Love's Real Sports magazine hit the stands in
December with an inaugural issue that was uneven but promising,
ranging from an article on the ABL that was outdated even before
the league folded to an insightful piece on Pat Summitt and
Tennessee basketball (overlooking for a moment an unfortunate
reference to Monica Lewinsky) and a comprehensive college softball
preview that has the University of Massachusetts Minutewomen at No.
6 in the country. The reception by both readers and advertisers,
Love said Tuesday, has been so good that the publication date of
the next issue has been stepped up from June to March, with the
magazine scheduled to go bimonthly in June. For subscription
information, call 1-800-650-0122.
</P>
<P>
   --Mimi Murray, professor of physical education and former
gymnastics coach at Springfield (Mass.) College, will be given the
Luther Halsey Gulick Award on April 22 in Boston. The honor is the
highest awarded by the American Alliance of Health, Physical
Education, Recreation, and Dance (AAHPERD). Murray, a specialist in
sports psychology who has been a consultant to several Olympic
teams, has been on the Springfield faculty since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from wire reports, personal interviews and the Internet
were used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
