<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BABY-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      01-20 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BABY-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY BRUINS PERFORMING MINOR MIRACLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ The picture Peter Laviolette held in his
hands Tuesday was from Causeway Street, but its roots traced all
the way down Route 95, right here to Laviolette's office inside the
Civic Center. Andre Savage scored his first NHL goal with Boston
Monday at the FleetCenter, and a day later, Laviolette couldn't
take his eyes off the newspaper photo of the jubilant rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what makes me smile,'' said Laviolette, the
34-year-old head coach of the Providence Bruins, who only recently
put Savage on the shuttle to Boston. ``This is what makes me smile
_ a lot. What a great thing for Savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years removed from wearing a Baby B's uniform,
Laviolette now is the man in charge of channeling goalies,
defensemen, forwards, and dreams from Providence to Boston. That's
job No. 1. Job No. 2 is making hay down on the farm, and right now
Laviolette and top aide Bill Armstrong have the crop running deep,
rich, and beyond anyone's wildest expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what I think's got us where we are,'' said
Laviolette, whose team ranks first overall in the AHL with 60
points in 42 games, an eye-popping .714 winning percentage. ``It's
been everyone who has pulled on a uniform. It has been everybody
every night. Be it Shawn Bates, be it Terry Virtue . . . Brandon
Smith . . . Andre Savage . . . I mean everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the key now is, they don't want to lose. Sometimes Bill
and I stand back there behind the bench, watch 'em, and we can't
believe how hard they're playing.''
</P>
<P>
   For 13 straight games, dating back to a 4-1 win at Springfield
Dec. 23, these Bruins have worked on deleting defeat from their
memory banks. A 2-2 tie at Worcester Saturday snuffed out an
11-game winning streak, but a 6-2 win over Lowell Monday pushed
their undefeated stretch to 12-0-1. The AHL mark is 27 games
(21-0-6), set by Cleveland in the 1947-48 season.
</P>
<P>
   Savage and fellow forward Randy Robitaille will represent
Providence in this weekend's AHL All-Star Game at Philadelphia,
along with winger Landon Wilson and goalie Jim Carey. Robitaille is
the club's top scorer (15-35_50), and Carey, the former Vezina
Trophy winner who is trying to find his way back to the NHL, has a
13-6-2 record and a 2.43 goals-against mark. He shares the
Providence net with John Grahame, whose numbers (15-6-0, 2.80) and
effectiveness have nearly matched Carey's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year Providence finished dead last in the AHL, collecting
only 50 points in 80 games. Head coach Tom McVie and assistant Rod
Langway were moved off the job in June, and within 72 hours,
Laviolette was offered the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed Anderson (Providence chairman-CEO) has to take much of the
credit for hiring Peter,'' said Bruins assistant general manager
Mike O'Connell. ``But I think everyone felt we needed to go with a
younger coach, someone who could identify better with what players
go through today _ someone who understood the process and speaks
the lingo. So much has changed through the years, almost
everything, to the point where a charley horse is a thigh contusion
and we've got terms like `doubling down' and `weak-side lock.'
Players identify with all that better than just telling 'em, `OK,
go out there and skate your lane.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Mann, the Bruins' fifth pick in the 1995 draft, spent
virtually all of last season here, laboring in the frustration of a
dismal season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to explain what happened last year,'' said Mann,
the club's No. 2 scorer this season with 42 points in 38 games. ``I
don't know, things just didn't jell together. What's clear this
year is, to be on a winning team, you have to be like brothers on
the ice. The guys here this year, they'll work their asses off
every game to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that credit, said Mann, has to go to Laviolette.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preparation he gives us before every game, it's just
phenomenal,'' said Mann. ``He's just really smart. Before every
game, he tells us what the other team is going to do, and he'll let
us know exactly how we should play against them.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Laviolette playbook says to play to the
strength of one's own team. He has a fast bunch of forwards, which
allows him to implement a strong forechecking game. The dreaded,
mind-numbing trap is there if need be _ and it has its place, says
Laviolette _ but most nights the Bruins press the puck forcefully
through the neutral zone and beyond their offensive blue line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go. We try to fly,'' said Laviolette, who spent 11 years
patrolling blue lines in the minors, called to the NHL for only a
dozen games with the New York Rangers in the '88-89 season.
``Defense is still a priority for us _ it has to be _ but our
strength is the forecheck, and we play to that strength. With our
speed, we can get in there, so my feeling is, `Let's go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And who can argue with the results? The wins keep coming and the
crowds are growing. Providence is averaging 6,544 per game, fourth
best in the league, and Friday's game against Fredericton
(Montreal's affiliate) looks as if it will be a sellout. From dead
last in 1997-98, the Bruins are now dead certain to return to the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be easy to get a big head when you've gone 13 without
a loss,'' said Grahame. ``But the big thing with (Laviolette) is
that he doesn't let anyone become complacent. He finds ways to keep
us motivated, so every guy in here wants to keep the streak
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the undefeated string, the Baby B's lost three
straight, the only really rough spot they've encountered this
season. The first practice after the last loss _ a 3-2 setback to
Hamilton with one second left in overtime _ had Laviolette
employing the old-school hammer, skating his club into the ice in
what he calls a torture practice.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened on the way back from the dungeon. The
coach woke up the next morning with a feeling that the old way
wasn't the right way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself, `This just isn't the answer,' '' recalled
Laviolette. ``I'd read Rick Pitino's book _ I'm always looking to
pick things up wherever I can _ and he'd made the point that when
the guys are down, you have to give 'em a hug. Instead of beating
the bejeezus out of 'em, it's time to lay off. When they've gone 13
without a loss, that's when you go at 'em a little harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the next day, we made it a fun day. We had an East-West
scrimmage _ guys born in Canada on one team, everyone else on the
other _ and then Bill and I met with guys one-on-one. I don't know,
seems like it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's refreshing, that's what it is,'' said Grahame, who also
spent the miserable 1997-98 season here. ``You show up the second
day, expecting another hard practice, and instead, you're right
back having fun _ it's just a very refreshing approach.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Step-by-step process
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half ago, after deciding his playing days were
done, Laviolettte packed up and moved to Wheeling, W.Va., to become
coach and director of hockey operations of the Wheeling Nailers in
the East Coast Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only show in town there,'' said Laviolette, who
played in two Olympics, '88 and '94, for the US, acting as the
captain in Lillehammer. ``If the Nailers did anything, it was on
the front page of the paper _ not just the front page of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Franklin, Laviolette now has the hottest team in the
AHL, less than a half-hour from where he grew up. As a player, he
was a little too slow afoot to think seriously about holding down a
long-term NHL job. As a coach, he may be on the fast track to the
big leagues. Worst-to-first reversals, no matter what the league,
cause people to inquire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love what I do,'' said Laviolette, sounding interested but
cautious about what could be ahead of him. ``And like anybody, I
guess, if you don't set your sights on getting to the top, you
probably never will.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not my main goal. My main goal is to win a
championship here, and having said that, I know that usually one
leads to the next. I tell that to Savage, to Bates, to Virtue, all
the guys who want to get to the NHL. All I say is, `Work hard,
because it's like anything else: One thing leads to the next.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
