<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVENT' SHOWS THE AFTEREFFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're never the same. Whenever an outstanding horse sustains
an injury, especially if it involves an operation on the knee, he
seems to lose just enough to take away that special quality.
Unfortunately, Event of the Year is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   A son of Seattle Slew, out of Classic Event, a Mr. Prospector
mare, Event of the Year was a juggernaut heading for the Kentucky
Derby last year until he fractured his knee while winning the Jim
Beam Stakes at Turfway Park in March. With the 5-length win in the
Jim Beam, he had won all four of his races, by a combined 20
lengths. There is little question that he would have been favored
in the Derby had he made it to Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Event of the Year, who is owned by the Golden Eagle Farm of John
and Betty Mabee, started his career at Bay Meadows and was trained
by Jerry Hollendorfer and ridden by Russell Baze, the top tandem in
Northern California. But his owners shipped him to high-profile
Southern California trainer Richard Mandella for what they hoped
would be a stellar comeback campaign.
</P>
<P>
   However, Event of the Year has lost both of his starts since his
return Dec. 26, and, while he has been in the money in both tries,
he hasn't come close to winning. That's not the Event of the Year
who looked like the real deal last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella picked the Malibu at Santa Anita for Event of the
Year's first start since the layoff. Off as the 7-5 favorite under
Corey Nakatani, Event of the Year dropped back, then came on, but
he could do no better than third, beaten a total of 3 1/2 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   He can be forgiven that one, but Event of the Year was defeated
again last Saturday in the San Fernando. He rallied from fifth to
easily gain second as the 6-5 choice, but he was 4 1/2 lengths
behind winner Dixie Dot Com, who was 5-1 under David Flores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our horse developed more this year than Event of the
Year did,'' said Bill Morey, trainer of Dixie Dot Come, who was
coming off a second-place finish in a turf stake.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with running second and third, but being
beaten a total of 8 lengths does not bode well for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Event of the Year will get another chance against Dixie Dot Com
in the $500,000 Strub Stakes Feb. 6. Mandella feels that
inexperience has caused Event of the Year's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that he's not good enough,'' said Mandella. ``It just
looks like he's got to get a little seasoning.''
</P>
<P>
   But if history is any guide, Event of the Year has lost a step
or two because of the knee, and that's a shame.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Muddy winner
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brian's Dancer, who is nicely bred for the mud, took advantage
of the sloppy going at Suffolk Downs Monday to score a hard-fought
neck victory in the $25,000 Collegian Stakes for 3-year-olds, the
feature race on the holiday card. Ridden by Harry Vega, Brian's
Dancer sat just off a speed duel between Abundant Deeds and Rapping
With Robb. Abundant Deeds, ridden by Freddy Castillo, shook off
Rapping With Robb and edged away in the stretch. But Brian's Dancer
came flying on the outside to get the nod at 3-1 ($8.20 to win).
Chance Spender, the 5-2 favorite with Henry Ma, charged up the rail
but could not gain on the top two and finished third, another 1 1/2
lengths behind. The time for the 6 furlongs was an honest 1:13.
Owned by John Tombarello and Kevin Joy, and trained by Joy, Brian's
Dancer was making just his third career start.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manistique was game
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manistique, an impressive 4-year-old filly who is 17 hands high,
captured her 1999 debut last Sunday, overcoming a bad break to win
the $150,000 El Encino at Santa Anita. Ridden by Gary Stevens,
Manistique stumbled out of the gate but grabbed the lead anyway in
the mile-and-one-16th affair. She held on gamely through a
stretch-long duel to win by a head over Gourmet Girl and Kent
Desormeaux, tallying at 2-5 in 1:43. A daughter of Unbridled,
Manistique has won five of six career starts. Her only loss came in
the Alabama at Saratoga Aug. 22 when she finished third after
displacing her palate. She was on the shelf until Dec. 6, when she
returned to win the Bayakoa Handicap at Hollywood Park. ``She broke
so hard, the ground just broke out from under her,'' said Stevens,
who still managed to control the race, which had only three
starters. ``I was a liitle concerned in the stretch because
Manistique is not the kind of horse that has a big closing
charge,'' said trainer John Shirreffs. ``They really made her dig
in.'' Next for Manistique will be the $200,000 La Canada at Sant
Anita Feb. 7 . . . The Groom Is Red, owned by Rick Pitino's Celtics
Pride Stable, continues to work forwardly at Gulfstream Park for
trainer Nick Zito. The late-striding son of Runaway Groom went 5
furlongs in 1:00 2/5 Sunday as Zito continues to get him ready for
the first major goal of his sophomore season, the Florida Derby
March 13 . . . Real Quiet, hero of last year's Kentucky Derby and
Preakness, zipped 5 furlongs in :58 4/5 at Santa Anita Saturday as
trainer Bob Baffert aims him toward the New Orleans Handicap at
Fair Grounds Feb. 7. General Challenge, an undefeated
California-bred in Baffert's hands, went 1 1/8 miles in 1:51 3/5 as
he readies for the Santa Catalina Jan. 31 . . . Baffert unveiled
another outstanding 3-year-old as Finder's Gold captured a $47,000
allowance race at Santa Anita Sunday. A son of Seeking the Gold,
Finder's Gold made a steady gain to overtake the front-runners and
score by 2 1/2 lengths at 4-5 under Stevens. The time for the mile
and one-16th was 1:43 3/5. Owned by the Golden Eagle Farm, Finder's
Gold had finished third in his Dec. 26 debut, behind the highly
regarded Cape Canaveral, and appears to be one of Baffert's most
promising young horses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
