<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON SHOW WAS NO KNOCKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a lot of hand-wringing over Mike Tyson these days. His
crude, often violent spasms demonstrate beyond a reasonable doubt
that civility is an unattainable goal.
</P>
<P>
   He will never be reasonable, much less classy, but Tyson
defenders are quick to bring up his difficult background to explain
away his curious displays of sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   His cursing at reporters, most notably WFAN's Russ Salzberg,
during a satellite feed designed to promote last Saturday's fight
against Francois Botha was not the worst thing in the world.
Aggressiveness is good in the world of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   No, the worst thing for Tyson would be to become boring. He
still has a punch; he proved that by knocking out Botha in the
fifth round with one strong right hand. And Tyson is still crazy.
He exploded at the end of the first round, trying to break Botha's
arms after the bell. The lunacy required police intervention.
</P>
<P>
   But his boxing skills, always dubious, are now glaringly
lacking. By all accounts, he looked aged and rusty. Botha had Tyson
beaten in the first four rounds before, by his own admission, Botha
got cocky and careless. A better fighter would have brought out the
worst in Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's ability to attract middle-of-the-road fight fans also
has diminished. When compared with some other Tyson fights, the
pay-per-view take for Tyson-Botha was off by more than 50 percent.
The first Tyson-Evander Holyfield fight attracted 1.6 million
pay-per-view buys; the second generated a staggering 1.99 million
buys. Tyson-Botha managed only 750,000.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the drop, Showtime vice president Jay Larkin said he was
happy with the numbers, saying this was still the most-watched
fight in the last 20 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I be happier with 800,000 or a million or 1.5 million?
Sure, I would be ecstatic,'' Larkin said. ``But no other fighter
can get 750,000, and we are very comfortable with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin said promotion for the fight suffered because of the
timing. The holiday season tapped out some potential viewers, and
the swirl of NBA news _ a settlement in the lockout, the retirement
of Michael Jordan _ knocked the fight off the front pages.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Tyson, in all his raw glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyson is who he is,'' Larkin said. ``Nobody goes to him for
Bible class or Miss Manners. He is the first one to tell you
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The sad part is that no one is really interested anymore. With
no one else to fight _ does anyone really want to see Andrew Golota
and Tyson kill each other in the ring, with a subsequent riot more
than likely? _ Tyson has become a textbook example of what not to
do in life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   High-scoring games
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Football ruled last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   National overnight numbers from 44 markets showed CBS and Fox
pulling substantial numbers for the conference championships. CBS
earned a 26.6 rating and 48 share for Broncos-Jets, a 6 percent
jump from last year's AFC game, which was televised by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Fox wasn't able to sustain such momentum from its coverage of
Vikings-Falcons. The NFC game received a 26.1 rating and 52 share
in the national overnights.
</P>
<P>
   The drop-off at the end of the game was staggering; viewers
switched to CBS almost immediately to watch Billy and the Jets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
