<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOUBLE COUP BY THE KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can almost hear them chuckling at Madison Square Garden. Not
only do the Knicks have Latrell Sprewell. Even better, Pat Riley
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   There is unrelenting hatred between the Knicks and Heat,
personified by Riley and spreading from boardroom to benches. We
saw that last spring when Alonzo Mourning and Larry Johnson squared
off in the playoffs, Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy swung from
Mourning's leg like a Skip-It, and players took turns delivering
throat-cutting signals.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Knicks are adding the talented if volcanic Sprewell to
an already-interesting mix. And Riley, the man who stiffed the
Knicks to head south to Florida leaving a trail of faxes and broken
promises, the man who vigorously pursued Sprewell and spent more
effort and time on the matter than anyone else, ends up with
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   As they say in hockey, this was a 4-pointer for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think Warriors general manager Garry St. Jean will get a
little something in the mail from the Knicks? He should. St. Jean
has been a veritable juggler the last six months, tossing about
various offers for his coach-strangler. He could have sent him
almost anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But he couldn't get what he wanted from Miami, Indiana, or San
Antonio. Salary-cap rules or differences of opinion got in the way.
The Knicks agreed to part with two players, small forward Chris
Mills and shooting guard John Starks, neither of whom was starting
at the end of last year. They'll survive. And smirk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Riley really wanted him,'' said Celtics GM Chris
Wallace. ``He put the most work into this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic Division just got a little tougher. Sprewell and
Allan Houston will form a dynamic 1-2 punch to balance the inside
game of LJ and Patrick Ewing. We may see New York go to a
three-guard spread the way it did much of last year. The Knicks
also have added underachiever Marcus Camby, who, we all know, has
talent there somewhere. They still need to address their point
guard situation, but they will be a better team than they were last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' window may be closing, but Sprewell's arrival will
keep it open for another year or two or maybe even raise it. Yes,
he's a handful. Yes, he's volatile. Yes, he's playing in Tabloid
Country, where there will be unbelievable scrutiny. Yes, the folks
at Page 6 are salivating. Yes, he hasn't played in more than a
year, having served a suspension for a choking P.J. Carlesimo, his
coach at Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has been one of the game's top shooting guards this
decade, maybe even second to You Know Who. (He was a first-team
All-NBA selection at the spot in 1993-94, the full year Jordan
played baseball.) He's only 28.
</P>
<P>
   He has averaged 20.1 points over his six-year career, including
a career-high 24.2 in 1996-97. He's an excellent defender. He gives
the Knicks some of the toughness they lost when Charles Oakley was
traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He adds some oomph to them,'' Wallace said. ``The thing they
lacked was a guy who could get off his own shot, and he can do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And in New York, he'll also be just one of many stars in the
Knicks' firmament, not merely the most notorious. This is a team,
after all, that had Anthony Mason and now has Johnson, neither one
a choir boy. This is just a hunch, but you may see Sprewell turn
into George Sanders before your eyes, given the unprecedented
attention he'll get. He can afford little else.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of interest in Sprewell showed conclusively that the
NBA is a league in which people forgive and forget, moreso if the
individual is a 20-point scorer who can get you closer to a
championship. Sprewell had no shortage of suitors. Larry Bird would
love to have him; what does that tell you?
</P>
<P>
   It tells you that however repulsive and sickening the events of
15 months ago were _ and there were two within a half-hour _ a team
such as New York will take a chance and take the inevitable heat.
It tells you that for every coach who decried Sprewell's despicable
behavior, there was another willing to rehabilitate the recidivist.
</P>
<P>
   It tells you that there's a whole new Jordan-free landscape out
there and New York, already a contender, immediately becomes a more
viable one with Sprewell. And it tells you that revenge is still
very much alive in the NBA, in the boardrooms as well as on the
court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
