<SLUG> BC-TV-PROFILE-DEVANE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV COP DRAWS ON HIS ROOTS IN `TURKS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARC McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ William Devane has based roles on the Kennedys
and suburban slime and other assorted guys good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   Now for inspiration he can turn to his family roots. In his
latest turn on television, ``Turks,'' Devane plays a Chicago police
sergeant, but in reality he is playing his uncle, a police officer
for more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Francis E. Devane died in August 1997 at the age of 88. He
started out as a patrolman in the Albany Police Department in 1941,
did a stint in the Navy during World War II and was a captain when
he retired in 1972. He was Bucky to friends, and, for some reason,
Uncle Bob to the other side of the Devane clan.
</P>
<P>
   As for incorporating real life experience into acting roles,
it's more of the little things, attitude mostly. ``You just draw it
out of yourself,'' Devane said.
</P>
<P>
   You may see snippets of Uncle Bob, or Bucky, Devane in his
nephew in ``Turks,'' a midseason CBS drama that premieres at 9 p.m.
EST Thursday (check local listings). As Sgt. Joseph Turk, Devane
plays the level-headed, good-hearted leader of a squad room and
family, both of which can descend into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   This is not new ground. Devane, whose name is the one in
Hollywood most often linked with ``straight-shooter,'' will tell
you himself we've seen a lot of this before. There is the
close-knit Irish Catholic family, the patriarch cop, his
religiously devout wife, his two cop sons and a third who may or
may not go bad. The guys even play hoops before dinner.
</P>
<P>
   But television doesn't have to cover new territory, although it
would be nice once in a while. What it does have to do is cover old
territory well, which ``Turks'' does.
</P>
<P>
   How do you know it's good? Because if it wasn't, Devane would
say so. He's that kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   In this season of the Irish we've seen ``Trinity'' (NBC) and
``To Have &AMP; to Hold,'' both Irish cop shows that debuted and sank.
In its pilot episode, ``Turks'' was able to cover a lot of ground
in both the characters' personal and professional arenas, and,
unlike ``Trinity,'' did not leave viewers spinning and confused.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Devane, the sister of the actor, said that she saw a little
bit of Uncle Bob/Bucky Devane in the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see his definite love and caring for his fellow human
beings,'' she said. ``He was a great guy. He was one who was loved
by his fellow members on the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``He watched out for all of us; not just his kids _ he had four
_ but the other Devanes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Bob was the one who helped oversee the four generations of
Devanes. He couldn't be there all the time to stop ``Willie'' from
getting into trouble, so much trouble, Pat Devane said, that two
neighborhood matrons told his mother that ``he will be the first
one executed in the electric chair.''
</P>
<P>
   Devane's Sgt. Joseph Turk is loved but troubled. He is in a
marriage that clings to comfort after passion has long left the
station. Two of his kids followed their father's path onto the
force, but one could be facing serious charges for sticking to his
values. The third brother is the brain at a fancy college, but even
though he's not patrolling the streets, he may be in the greatest
danger of all.
</P>
<P>
   Mom has retreated to the church, and dad to the local tavern
(don't miss a very funny opening scene in which two stickup men
could not have picked a worse bar to hit). Joe may or may not enter
into a relationship with Ginny the waitress. He warns her that even
if he does, he would never leave his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Seen all this before? Sure you have. But with ``Turks,'' it is
comfortable and good, and like a good CD, worth enjoying again.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
