<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-STARTREK-BOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOLDLY GO WHERE NO CHEF HAS GONE BEFORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Recipe included) 
 
By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is the Emeril of TV outer space.
</P>
<P>
   Each week on ``Star Trek: Voyager,'' chief cook Neelix prepares
meals for his fellow lost-in-space crew members _ Heart of Targ for
Lt. Torres, Borg Tricorder Pie for Seven of Nine, Welsh rarebit for
Capt. Janeway.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny Talaxian also serves as the ship's morale officer,
kickin' up a notch the moods of those on board the USS Voyager.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time before he, like Emeril, got a book
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek Cookbook'' (Pocket Books, $20), published this
month, was written in the persona of Neelix by Ethan Phillips _ the
actor behind the epicurean alien _ and William J. Birnes.
</P>
<P>
   In this 317-page paperback, Neelix shares recipes for the
Voyager crew's favorite dishes and offers trivia on the culinary
likes and dislikes of characters from the original ``Star Trek''
series, ``Star Trek: Next Generation'' and ``Star Trek: Deep Space
Nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Recipes for their much-loved meals are included, too.
</P>
<P>
   Learn how to make Capt. Kirk's Plomeek Soup, his version of the
Vulcan delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   And Azna, a dish frequently eaten by ``Deep Space Nine's''
Jadzia Dax.
</P>
<P>
   For a behind-the-scenes look at the ``Star Trek'' realm's
cuisine, Neelix turns to Alan Sims, property master for ``Voyager''
and ``Next Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims tells all about food props, revealing that the Klingon food
``gagh,'' which is supposed to look like live worms, is actually
udon noodles dyed with soy sauce. He also offers tips on how to
re-create Quark's Bar, the popular watering hole on ``Deep Space
Nine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek Cookbook'' will surely be a hit with die-hard
Trekkers. While a few of the recipes are pure sci-fi fantasy, like
the one for Tricorder Pie, most are earthly adaptations of dishes
found in the ``Star Trek'' realm.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at Helena Rozhenko's Rokeg Blood Pie. Rozhenko, who
adopted Worf and raised him on Earth, learned how to make blood pie
the old-fashioned way for her Klingon son. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HELENA ROZHENKO'S ROKEG BLOOD PIE &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 pound veal kidneys &QL; 
2 pounds top round or sirloin beef roast &QL; 
1/4 cup (1/2 stick) salted butter, melted &QL; 
4 garlic cloves, minced &QL; 
2 cups flour &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon garlic salt &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon celery seed &QL; 
2 cups beef gravy or 2 cups beef stew with veggies removed &QL; 
1 pie crust &QL; 
Hot pepper sauce, cayenne pepper or paprika to taste &QL; 
1 12-ounce bottle dark beer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Skin, then wash kidneys. Slice very thin and set aside. Slice
beef very thin. Save any blood. Saut kidneys briefly in a skillet
with melted butter and garlic until kidneys just begin to turn
color, about 2 minutes. Set aside. Roll beef in flour seasoned with
garlic salt and celery seed.
</P>
<P>
   In a greased deep baking pan, arrange meat and kidney slices,
making sure to mix them so flavors blend. Cover with gravy or stew
and any reserved blood. Add hot pepper sauce. Pour in beer.
</P>
<P>
   Cover pan with aluminum foil and bake for two hours at 375
degrees. Remove from oven, let pan cool slightly and replace foil
with pastry crust. Increase oven temperature to 400 degrees. Return
pie to oven and cook an additional 15 minutes, just enough to brown
the crust.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with Klingon bloodwine or ale.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
