<HEADER>
A1029 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MEXICAN-GOD-REVI     01-20 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MEXICAN-GOD-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LIFE OF A MESOAMERICAN GOD: STORY OF QUETZALCOATL TOLD IN
DETAIL 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  ``Legends of the Plumed Serpent: Biography of a Mexican God''; by
Neil Baldwin; (PublicAffairs, $37.50.) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over in e Chichen, a in Itza, second a in
Yucatan, a in Hernan, e in Cortez, a in Duran and e in Jose.) 
 
By DAVID D. MEDINA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writing a biography of a mere mortal is hard enough. Imagine
piecing together the life of a god whose staying power has lasted
5,000 years and whose images continue to animate art in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Author Neil Baldwin completed this daunting task after reading
300 books in 10 years, and his effort has paid off. He has produced
an elegant and poetic account of the most important mythological
figure in Mexico and Central America _ Plumed Serpent
(Quetzalcoatl).
</P>
<P>
   The legend of Plumed Serpent began several thousand years before
the birth of Christ and evolved through time as different cultures
adopted the myth to meet their needs. ``This book is the mosaic
mural depicting that vast myth,'' writes Baldwin. And indeed, his
coffee-table-size book is a handsome display of illustrations,
maps, poems and personal observations as well as a concise history
of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Aztecs, it was Plumed Serpent who set the wheel
of history in motion, thus starting a long series of repetitious
cycles. Plumed Serpent was also the namer of all things and gave
humans a new life, blessing them with music, art, science, crafts
and time. ``Plumed Serpent was the performer of miracles, the
supreme magician, the ruler of sorcerers, holding the secret of all
enchantments,'' explains Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   But like many heroes, Plumed Serpent experienced a fall from
grace. In his incarnation as prince of the Toltecs, Plumed Serpent
was tricked by his evil twin into getting drunk and sleeping with
his own sister. Feeling guilty for his transgressions, he began his
``pilgrimage of purification,'' leaving Tula in Central Mexico and
moving east to Cholula and as far as Chichen Itza in the Yucatan
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally reached the sea, Plumed Serpent set sail on a
raft made of snakes that burst into flames and became the planet
Venus. But before he left, Plumed Serpent promised to return in the
year named One Reed, which happened to coincide with 1519, the same
year Spanish conquistador Hernan Cortez arrived in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking Cortez was their beloved god returning, the Aztecs
embraced the invaders, who destroyed the Aztec world within two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin deftly takes us on this odyssey, showing us how Plumed
Serpent influenced the civilizations of Mesoamerica: Olmec, Toltec,
Zapotec, Mayan and Aztec. The author examines, through works of art
(some engraved on pyramids and holy relics), how the image of the
protean Plumed Serpent changed. Sometimes he appeared as a snake
and eagle, at other times as a jaguar and monkey.
</P>
<P>
   The myth of Quetzalcoatl did not end with the Spanish conquest,
despite the Catholic Church's effort to eliminate all
manifestations of Indian belief. ``The next incarnation of the
Quetzalcoatl story was refracted through a Catholic prism,''
Baldwin writes.
</P>
<P>
   Some colonial friars considered Plumed Serpent a devil; to
others he was a mere mortal and a false god. Dominican priest Diego
Duran theorized that Quetzalcoatl was really the apostle St.
Thomas, who had been sent to spread the gospel to all nations.
Duran asserted that St. Thomas and Plumed Serpent had lived similar
lives as holy men, performers of miracles, artists and leaders of
disciples.
</P>
<P>
   Like the phoenix, Plumed Serpent has risen again and again in
the course of Mexico's history. During the Mexican Revolution of
1910, indigenous peoples viewed rebel leader Emiliano Zapata as a
reincarnation of Quetzalcoatl, their symbol of hope and renewal.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s Mexico sought to find a national identity by
glorifying its ancient past. The government employed three great
muralists, Diego Rivera, Jose Clemente Orozco and David Alfaro
Siqueiros, to paint Mexico's history on public buildings. Each of
the artists rendered his version of the Plumed Serpent myth.
</P>
<P>
   The legend took on an international appeal in 1925 when English
writer D.H. Lawrence published his novel ``The Plumed Serpent.''
Lawrence became so enthralled with the myth that he declared
himself to be Quetzalcoatl.
</P>
<P>
   As Mexico progresses through the modern world, the vision of
Plumed Serpent persists. New artists continue to explore the
meaning of Quetzalcoatl, and the Maya in southern Mexico still
perform ancient rituals celebrating him. Every tribute can be
likened to a snake shedding its skin in continual acts of renewal.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his book, Baldwin confesses that the many twists
and turns of the legend confused him. But he kept the faith, he
says, and managed to find a way. Readers should be thankful that he
persevered; through his engaging book he brings us closer than ever
to the fantastic legend of Plumed Serpent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
