<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVY-DEPARTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY TO TAKE OVER BAY AREA'S LAST NAVAL FACILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Calif. _ The Navy, once the dominant military presence
in the San Francisco Bay area, will fold its sails here later this
year, turning its last base in the region over to the Army.
</P>
<P>
   The transfer of the 13,000-acre Concord Naval Weapons Station,
already downgraded to a detachment of a another base, is scheduled
for Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear whether the move would cost more
jobs. The base's civilian work force was halved last year when it
lost its independent base status and was made a detachment of the
Naval weapons station at Seal Beach in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Some 250 military personnel are stationed at Concord and a much
smaller number of civilians work there.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the base would continue to be a transfer point
for spent nuclear fuel rods from research reactors in Asia. The
transit of the spent radioactive fuel to storage dumps in Idaho has
sparked protests here.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Defense Department said Concord is not now on any
list of bases to be closed, the inter-service transfer increases
the likelihood of its eventual demise as a military post.
</P>
<P>
   Local government officials have long eyed the site for
recreational and commercial development. With its deep-water port
and three rail lines, the site is ideal as a regional
transportation hub.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Flood, a Defense Department spokesman, said such transfers
between services have been relatively common following the
military's last rounds of base closures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually it's done with smaller activities. If a service has a
mission that can be done by another service, then between them they
come up with solutions,'' Flood said. ``It's not out of the
ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen approved the transfer for
financial reasons, according to Pentagon officials. Since
ammunition shipments have declined, Pentagon planners say the Seal
Beach ordnance depot meets the Navy's needs.
</P>
<P>
   The mission of the Concord site _ supplying ammunition _ will
remain the same under the Army. Base officials said the majority of
the work currently done there is for the Army and Air Force rather
than the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy will retain ownership of the land and port on Suisun
Bay. The Army, already a tenant, will have a long-term lease on the
base, which will be renamed the Military Ocean Terminal Concord.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's 834th Transportation Battalion was relocated to
Concord last year from the closed Oakland Army Base.
</P>
<P>
   Although some Navy personnel will remain at Concord, the October
transfer essentially eliminates the Navy's once-mighty presence in
the San Francisco area. Mare Island closed in 1996, and Alameda
Naval Air Station and Treasure Island Naval Station shut in May
1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
