<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, Jan. 21,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH_ Coverage of the President's defense in the Senate.
(Carr/Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HALLWAYS _ WASHINGTON _ Talk behind the scenes at the
Senate trial centers on how much of the voting and discussions set
to begin Monday will be behind closed doors. Tom Harkin is leading
an effort to make it all public. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-BUMPERS _ WASHINGTON _ The man who will wind up the
Clinton defense was chosen not only becuase of his cclose ties to
the president. In the eyes of his former colleagues, Dale Bumpers
was one of the greatest speakers in recent Senate history.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ President Clinton, accompanied by Vice President Al
Gore and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, will visit Buffalo,
N.Y., and Montgomery County, Pa., on the day after his State of
Union address in order ``to amplify on the themes and policies of
that speech,'' White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Clinton speaks in Philadelphia at 6:30 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ Follow on State of the Union
address, and comparing it with inaugural and state of the state
addresses by the nation's governors. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SENATE _ WASHINGTON _ Former President George Bush
addresses the Senate on Wednesday as part of a speakers series
sponsored by Majority Leader Trent Lott. (Harlan, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   GOP _ WASHINGTON _ The Republican Party's search for the next
Ronald Reagan begins Thursday with two important gatherings of the
GOP faithful. The nuts-and-bolts Republican National Committee
holds its winter meeting, with an eye on victory in the 2000
presidential election. But the party's most fervent conservatives,
the heart and soul of the GOP since Reagan, will get its first
up-close look at the most conservative presidential candidates. And
CPAC's chairman, David Keene, warns: ``No pale pastels.'' Only true
Reaganites need apply. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-PREGNANCY _ WASHINGTON _ Teen pregnancy in the United
States has declined to a rate of about 4 in every 10 girls becoming
pregnant in their teens, the national Kids Count survey reported
Wednesday. Critics say the improved rate is still too high, with
the United States trailing most of the world in this social
indicator. (Schultz, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Continuing spot coverage of the federal
antitrust trial against Microsoft Corp. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   STEEL _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. Mike DeWine joins 3,500 Ohio
steelworkers in a DC rally to highlight the current import steel
crisis. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POPE _ MEXICO CITY _ With all due respect, John Paul II
is fast becoming known here as the Potato Pope. To the chagrin of
many faithful, corporate sponsors of the Pope's trip to Mexico have
used images of the pope and the Virgin Mary in big advertising
campaigns anticipating his arrival. Sabritas, a Pepsi-owned potato
chip maker has wrapped its bags in yellow ribbons promoting the
pope's fourth visit. Those who purchase the chips produced by the
``official collaborator'' are treated to a card inside each bag
that bears the image of the pope or another religious figure. Pepsi
has erected huge billboards declaring ``Mexico. Always Faithful.''
And a television station that will air the pope's visit is running
commercials featuring fictional people -- a man with a flat tire, a
soccer player -- remembering to keep the faith. The church has
defended the use of corporate sponsors and the mass media, saying
it needs to use modern means to raise money and reach its flock.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the International and Lifestyle categories by 5
p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   POPE-SKED _ MEXICO CITY _ A schedule of the Pope's visit to
Mexico City. (Ferris, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-RIFT _ MIAMI _ The $7.8 billion Everglades
restoration plan is creating a rift among environmental groups.
Some, including the Sierra Club, say the Army Corps of Engineers
contains fatal flaws and needs a top-to-bottom review by
disinterested scientists _ even if that means missing the July 1
deadline that Congress set for finishing the plan. Others, such as
the Florida and National Audubon societies, say they trust the
corps to fix the problems. The divide will come into play this week
at a national Everglades conference in Miami, where Sierra will ask
more than 40 other enviro groups to join its call for a scientific
review. The National Park Service isn't supporting Sierra's plea,
even though park scientists had some harsh words for the corps plan
in a recent review. (King, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   TEX-ABUSE-TRAINING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Only about half of Texas
professionals who regularly come in contact with children say they
are required by their employers to learn the signs of child abuse
or neglect. But 83 percent of the teachers, police officers, social
workers, doctors and other professionals surveyed say they have
been trained to recognize signs of trouble, a new report released
Tuesday said. (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
