<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEAT-COOKBOOK-TEX     01-20 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-COOKBOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING REAL MEAT BACK ONTO THE TABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Remember when you could cut into a
succulent, well-marbled slab of meat _ we're thinking 2-pound
porterhouse _ without any guilt feelings?
</P>
<P>
   Saddled up to the side was a baked potato the size of a
newborn's head, only this baby was loaded with enough real butter
and high-fat sour cream to gag a goat. Next to this was a salad
with full-fat dressing and sprinkled with a fistful of rich cheese
and a half pound of crumbled bacon, the real kind.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's still not exactly OK unless you're on Death Row
already, but sausage maker/cookbook author Bruce Aidells is doing
what he can to put real red meat back on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Just when we were feeling that life itself had gone ``lite,''
Aidells has come through with ``The Complete Meat Cookbook''
(Houghton Mifflin, $35), a handsome, 600-page, user-friendly volume
with color photos good enough to eat.
</P>
<P>
   It's got it all, from the meat-grading system to information on
how to select, buy, store, prepare and eat beef, veal, pork and
lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Although the book focuses primarily on American cuts of meat and
contains many all-American favorites, Aidells also features ethnic
dishes from Mexico, Islamic countries, the Caribbean, South
America, Africa, Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Each meat type is paired with a ``master recipe,'' from which
spring many recipe variations.
</P>
<P>
   But even more than a manual of all things meat, this is a meaty
manifesto that aims to dispel the myths, to help us shun the guilt
and to help us again enjoy what we've really wanted all along.
</P>
<P>
   In some quarters, meat is the big bugaboo. High in fat and
cholesterol, some see meat as death on a plate. If that isn't
enough, some also have been programed to believe that simply
craving a big ol' steak is socially incorrect. Let us not even get
into the whole veal thing.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, a chunk of juicy red meat is one of the tastiest,
most satisfying things you can eat.
</P>
<P>
   And meat producers have kowtowed to these feelings and
perceptions, producing a leaner meat, which itself produces
preparation problems.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps red meat is back.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude is it never went away,'' said Aidells, who started
making sausage in his kitchen 20 years ago. He now has a company in
California that churns out 100,000 pounds of gourmet sausage a
week. (Locally, his sausage is available at Sam's stores.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Meat eaters are a huge group. I've got some numbers from the
Beef Board. About a quarter-billion Americans (that's pretty much
America's population) eat some beef at least every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what you're talking about is the fashionable crowd
getting back to the pleasures of a porterhouse,'' said Aidells, now
on a nationwide tour promoting ``The Complete Meat Cookbook.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the book are many.
</P>
<P>
   Many people never learned how to select and prepare meat. Some
knew how, but forgot.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in about the past 20 years, the grading of meat has
changed. It's generally leaner (remember the ``lite'' thing?). And
with less fat, meat is less forgiving for the sloppy cook or for
the good cook who makes a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Good meat cookery today requires more science.
</P>
<P>
   Aidells trained as a scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life doesn't always follow a straight path,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   He has a Ph.D. in endocrinology, which very, very basically is
the study of glands that secrete hormones.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 years ago, Aidells found himself doing cancer research
in London, where high cuisine is ``bangers and mash,'' a repast of
mashed potatoes with sausages that taste like sawdust.
</P>
<P>
   ``So one night, I thought it would be nice to make a batch of
sausage. I already was an inspired amateur cook. In England it was
a survival technique,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not much later, back home in Oakland, Calif., the cancer
research money was drying up and Aidells started moonlighting
making sausage for a friend who had just opened a charcuterie.
</P>
<P>
   From there he became chef at an all-chicken restaurant in
Berkeley, a place called Poulet (what else?).
</P>
<P>
   He continued to make sausage for a few friends and small
restaurants. It grew, and his company now makes more than two dozen
varieties of gourmet sausage sold nationwide. Generally, it goes
for about $5 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Aidells, 52, grew up in Los Angeles. He said the food he was
reared on was just like the stuff most baby-boomers endured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom was a convenience cook,'' he said. ``Dad was just
frightening.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me what kind of smells we had in the kitchen when I
was a kid,'' he said. ``The smell I remember from life as a kid was
dry onion soup mix. It went into everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with that, boxed macaroni and cheese dinner was one of the
basic food groups, and pork chops were cooked to the consistency
and the taste of hockey pucks, lest anyone get the dreaded
trichinosis.
</P>
<P>
   Aidells said that overcooking meat continues to be the most
common mistake of home cooks. Most recipes cook by time, but there
are too many variables: the type and size of pan, the stove, the
thickness of the meat and the temperature of the meat before
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   He believes that no meat cook should be without an instant-read
digital thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's indespensable,'' Aidells said. They are widely available
for $10 to $20.
</P>
<P>
   Aidells has written or collaborated on nine books, primarily
about meat, including ``Flying Sausages,'' ``Real Beer and Good
Eats'' and ``Hot Links and Country Flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a contributing writer/editor for the meat and chicken
sections in a recent update of the ``Joy of Cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Major sections of his latest book detail the history of meat in
the human diet, meat grading, how to shop, the differences in meat
today and how to cook various cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Helpful tips include: overlooked but delicious cuts; a lexicon
of meat lingo; how to read meat labels; and salting, also known as
koshering, which makes many meats more flavorful and juicy. The
book also contains recipes for more than 30 meat rubs and 30 meat
marinades.
</P>
<P>
   There are extensive cooking charts and diagrams detailing
cooking techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes are clear and well-detailed.
</P>
<P>
   Each recipe includes tells you how many it serves. It also tells
you if this recipe is good if you're on a budget, in a hurry,
looking for something low fat, something fit for company, or to
serve a crowd, if it rewarms well, or is comfort food, makes for
great leftovers or is a ``two for one'' recipe, which is something
designed to be turned into something else the next day.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
