<HEADER>
A1069 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PAXTON-PROFILE-H     01-20 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PAXTON-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAXTON'S AN ACTOR WITH `A SIMPLE PLAN' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The day after ``A Simple Plan'' screened for critics
at the Toronto Film Festival, Bill Paxton was hopeful but concerned
about how the movie was being received by critics.
</P>
<P>
   It's an unwritten law that actors and film makers don't directly
ask interviewers how they liked a picture. It avoids awkward
situations. But there is obviously plenty of plain-spoken Texan
left in Fort Worth-born-and-raised Paxton, so he just up and asked
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The positive response pleased him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie's got a lot of great themes in it,'' said an
enthusiastic Paxton, who was wearing oval, rose-colored sunglasses,
even though we were in his hotel room. ``It's definitely a
cautionary tale. I feel like we really milked the root about as
much as we could. The movie is almost as much Eugene O'Neill as it
is `Deliverance.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's not all exaggeration. ``A Simple Plan`` has the body of a
thriller and the mind of a deeply introspective morality tale.
</P>
<P>
   Paxton plays Hank Mitchell, a respected, responsible family man
in a classic small town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of George Bailey-esque,'' Paxton said, referring to
the hero of `It's a Wonderful Life.'``
</P>
<P>
   Out in the woods with his ne'er-do-well brother, Jacob (Billy
Bob Thornton), and Jacob's low-life alcoholic pal Lou (Brent
Briscoe), Hank stumbles across a crashed plane with a dead pilot
and a bag of money. A big bag.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming they will turn the money in, Hank is surprised when
Jacob and Lou insist on keeping the boodle. Hank ultimately relents
_ a decision that leads him, his wife (Bridget Fonda) and Jacob
into an ever-deepening whirlpool of danger and moral compromises.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood doesn't trust thrillers that make people think, and
Paramount has been concerned about the potential of ``A Simple
Plan'' from the beginning. The movie went through several actors,
directors and budget cuts before it got made.
</P>
<P>
   After the well-received Toronto screenings in September,
Paramount played hide-and-seek in releasing the movie. It came out
in a few cities in mid-December and did well, reaching box office
top-20 status even though it was in just 80 theaters nationwide.
After weeks of waffling, the studio is finally releasing it to the
rest of the country Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the fuss over what was once considered a hot property?
After all, the book, a dark thriller by Scott B. Smith, became a
fast best seller in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio wanted to keep the budget way down on this picture
because it's a high-risk movie for them,'' Paxton said. ``They
wanted to make just a taut thriller but got kind of more out of it.
But I think now they feel they have what could be a real commercial
movie.``
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the studio was smart to hold back. ``A Simple
Plan'' appeared on many critics' 1998 top 10 lists and has been
nominated for a number of awards _ most for Thornton's supporting
role.
</P>
<P>
   The Broadcast Film Critics named it Best Picture of the Year,
and it has a good chance of picking up some Oscar nominations Feb.
9. Because of its late release, it's likely that ``A Simple Plan''
still will be in theaters then, able to benefit if those
nominations come through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Billy and Brent are both Academy Award performances,''
Paxton said of his co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   But because his role is less showy _ an ordinary man _ it is
really Paxton who has the tougher part that carries the film. He
has to play a smart guy making some, in retrospect, dumb
mistakes.Yet they can't seem so dumb at the time. The character
does some terrible things, but he must remain sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hard part,'' he acknowledged. ``He gets in this
congress with these confederates who are `Oh my God.' He thinks he
can control them, and he can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon Hank finds his whole life out of control, and he feels like
fate, or at least the law, is sure to close in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one point where I think my character almost wants to
go, `I did it, I did it,'' Paxton said, raising his voice. ``
`Please, God, help me, take me away, I don't want to go through
this anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   He grinned over his impromptu performance.
</P>
<P>
   Paxton seems as unpretentious and laid-back as movie stars come.
On this day it was partly the blue jeans, work shirt and brown
boots. But it has more to do with his easygoing attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is just incredible,'' Charlize Theron said in an
interview last month. She co-stars with Paxton in ``Mighty Joe
Young.'' ``He's probably the nicest guy you'll ever meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aside from being extremely talented and creatively bringing so
much to table, he's a regular guy. And yet he's kind of this
prince. He's like the cowboy on the white horse. He's just a
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   (Paxton was also impressed with Theron's talent and sex appeal.
``She'll make you do the monkey dance, that's for sure,'' he said
in apparent awe.)
</P>
<P>
   Paxton, 43, has been a long time coming to stardom. He was still
in his teens _ during which he was known as Wild Bill Paxton
despite often being sickly and bedridden _ when he left Texas for
New York and then Hollywood, trying to break into acting.
</P>
<P>
   He got his film start 25 years ago, working as a set dresser on
such Roger Corman films as ``Big Bad Mama.'' As late as 1981 he was
a set decorator on a movie.
</P>
<P>
   He became an increasingly familiar supporting player, slowly
getting better roles in better films. A breakthrough role came in
``Aliens'' (1986), in which his borderline-hysterical performance
as a trooper feeling doomed by yuckie aliens made the line,
``That's it, man, game over'' part of cult-film lore.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was almost another decade before he was getting star
billing in big films.
</P>
<P>
   Although he enjoys doing the big flashy films like ``Twister,''
small, thoughtful films like ``A Simple Plan'' are much closer to
Paxton's heart. As an actor, he finds the characters much more
interesting, and feels such films have something to say. Among his
favorite movies are the 1992 character-study thriller, ``One False
Move'' (in which he starred with Thornton), and 1997's
``Traveler,'' a portrait of backwoods con men that he also
produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like making entertaining movies,'' he said of the big-budget
films. He quickly added, ```A Simple Plan' is a very entertaining
movie. Pound for pound, you get a lot of bang for your buck.''
</P>
<P>
   The studio didn't want to include some of the dark events from
the ending of the book in the film. But Paxton believed sticking to
the story was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the point,'' he said. ``You have to take an idea to
its conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxton read the book five years ago when his dad, John Paxton,
who has a bit part in the movie as a confused farmer, told him he
should play the role of Hank. At that time, before his starring
role in ``Twister'' and major supporting roles in ``The Evening
Star,'' ``Apollo 13'' and ``Titanic'' finally gave him star
recognition, Paxton figured there was no way he would ever get the
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed I would get to play this part,'' he said.
``Only in my wildest dreams. I knew it was a perfect part but I'd
never get to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``A Simple Plan'' had gone through the familiar
Hollywood pre-production hell, including other directors and
actors, years had passed and Paxton was a star. Still, after he was
signed to do it (with director John Boorman), the film was canceled
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, the cruelness of fate. I got set to do it, and now
they are not going to make the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paxton pushed, and with a greatly cut budget ($16 million)
and new director, Sam Raimi, the film was finally made.
</P>
<P>
   Paxton hopes ``A Simple Plan'' will add to the respect audiences
have for his abilities. ``Twister,'' ``Titanic'' and ``Mighty Joe
Young'' are not the films for which he wants to be remembered, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell ya, for me, when I got to do `A Simple Plan,' I said,
I've finally got my boxed set now. I'd like to one day put out a
box of `A Simple Plan,' `One False Move' and `Traveler.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to have three. Three means it wasn't a fluke; you
had enough in you to go the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   After a quarter-century and 40-plus films, maybe Paxton can stop
worrying about that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
