<HEADER>
A1072 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEAT-RECIPES-TEX     01-20 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-RECIPES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME RECIPES FROM THE `COMPLETE MEAT COOKBOOK'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some sausage recipes from Aidell's ``Complete Meat
Cookbook.'' People intimidated by the idea of making sausage should
remember that sausage is nothing but chopped-up meat and spices.
</P>
<P>
   Also it should be noted that there is no hard and fast recipe
for sausage. Anything and everything goes. It is a personal thing.
Be daring. Experiment. Have fun. It's unlikely that you will fail,
but if you do, you can always give it to the dog or an ex-spouse.
</P>
<P>
   SAGE AND PEPPER PORK SAUSAGE (MASTER RECIPE)
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3-4 pounds
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 pounds lean pork butt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound fat trimmed from pork butt and/or pork back fat, which
the butcher probably has in the back
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons coarsely ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried sage
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon light or dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped onions, blanched for five minutes and
drained
</P>
<P>
   1 cup drained and cooled cooked wild rice (optional filler)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   Using a food processor: Cut the meat and fat into 3/4-inch to
1-inch cubes, spread out on a tray or roasting pan and place it in
the freezer for about 10 minutes to firm it up and make it easier
to chop. Put the food processor bowl and blade in the freezer as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Set up the processor and add about one pound, or about
one-third, of the meat. Pulse to form a coarse grind, about
3/8-inch or about the size of a garbanzo bean. Refrigerate each
batch after processing.
</P>
<P>
   Process the fat the same way, only smaller, about 1/4-inch, or
about the size of petit pois peas.
</P>
<P>
   Toss everything into a large bowl and mix with your hands. The
idea is to get all the spices distributed, but do not overmix to
the point that the fat begins to melt.
</P>
<P>
   Make a small patty and fry it over medium heat. Taste and make
necessary adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   Sausage can be stuffed into casings or formed into breakfast
patties.
</P>
<P>
   The flavor will mellow and improve if tightly wrapped and
allowed to rest in the refrigerator for a day. It will keep for 2
to 3 days and freezes well for up to three months.
</P>
<P>
   Using a meat grinder: The process is basically the same,
although it's sometimes easier if the meat is cut into finger-size
strips to feed it into the grinder.
</P>
<P>
   A grinder is particulary helpful if you plan to stuff your
sausage into casings.
</P>
<P>
   Casings should be soaked, rinsed, soaked and rinsed again to
remove the brine in which they are packed.
</P>
<P>
   Sausage horns, a funnellike device that fits over the grinder
plates, are available at most kitchen ware outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Simply slide several feet of casings over the horn. For 3 pounds
of sausage you will need about 8 feet of casings. Tie the end. It's
good to have some help, to have one person feed the mixture into
the grinder while the other catches and twists the sausage as it is
pushed into the casing.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per 4-ounce serving without rice: 230
calories, 18 grams fat, 1 gram carbohydrates, 14 grams protein, 41
milligrams cholesterol, 1,142 milligrams sodium, 72 percent of
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHWEST CHORIZO
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 3 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean beef, preferably chuck
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds lean pork butt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound fat trimmed from pork butt and/or pork back fat
</P>
<P>
   2 dried New Mexico chilies, soaked in water, stemmed and pureed;
or 2 tablespoon ground chiles
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coarsely ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno pepper, seeded and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 peeled and finely chopped green bell pepper; or 2 Anaheim or
poblano peppers, fresh or canned
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cumin seed
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped onion, blanched for 5 minutes and drained
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked and cooled long-grained rice (optional filler)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup beer, peferably Mexican
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Follow the instructions in the previous recipe for making the
sausage.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per 4-ounce serving without rice: 333
calories, 27 grams fat, 3 grams carbohydrates, 18 grams protein, 65
milligrams cholesterol, 74 milligrams sodium, 74 percent of
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Finding equipment
</P>
<P>
   Sausage casings are available in Fort Worth at Klein Meat Co.,
2525 Cullen St. 817-332-4155. Klein sells 60 feet, or enough to
make 20 to 25 pounds of sausage, for $3.75. All-natural hog casings
are packed in a brine and must be washed thoroughly before using.
Kept refrigerated in the brine they will keep for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Hog casings also can be purchased mail-order via the Internet.
Do a search for ``hog casing'' or ``sausage making'' and several
companies will come up.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Meat cooking tips
</P>
<P>
   Salt meat before cooking. It will be much more flavorful and
juicy.
</P>
<P>
   Pork should be slightly pink, not white. It is not necessary to
overcook pork to prevent trichinosis. Trichinae are killed at 137
degrees, or medium rare.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to tenderize a tough cut of meat is to braise it to
stew it slowly. Do not use chemical meat tenderizers or buy
``tenderized steaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Do not baste a roast. It doesn't keep the meat moist and it
washes away the seasoning. The trick is not to overcook the roast.
</P>
<P>
   USDA is the only federal grading system for meat. Terms like
``Butcher's Prime,'' ``Market Choice'' are misleading fantasy meat
grades invented by retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Don't buy precut meat for stew. It is more expensive and you
never know what kind of cut it was. Buy a piece of chuck and cut it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Do no parboil spareribs. Parboiling toughens the meat and drains
it of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring lamb'' is available year round.
</P>
<P>
   Pan-broiled lamb chops are better than those broiled in the
oven. Home broilers don't get hot enough and cause the meat to
steam.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
