<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEMINISTS21-COX     01-20 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEMINISTS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feminist ideal breeds unhappiness, author says
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've gone too far, baby.
</P>
<P>
   Women who bought into the feminist ideal _ that they could have
sex with whoever they wanted, pursue any career they wanted and put
childbearing on hold as long as they wanted _ were sold a bill of
goods, says author Danielle Crittenden.
</P>
<P>
   In her new book, ``What Our Mothers Didn't Tell Us: Why
Happiness Eludes the Modern Woman'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23),
Crittenden says women should be seeking happiness in the family,
not just equality in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are freer and more equal than any women in history,
you still see a lot of unhappiness,'' Crittenden argues. ``Women
want work, children and family, but have no idea as to how to make
it fit together.''
</P>
<P>
   Crittenden, 35, is part of a generation that's grappling with
women's place in a world that was partly shaped by their feminist
mothers. She's founding editor of the Women's Quarterly, a
conservative newsletter published by the Independent Women's Forum
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Her post-feminist ideas, though conservative, may not be that
far right _ considering that even feminist-aligned President
Clinton, in his State of the Union address Tuesday, advocated tax
subsidies for families when one parent stays home with the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Clinton's tax break never becomes reality, women should
swap their briefcases for baby bottles if they want to lead
fulfilling lives as wife and mother, Crittenden thinks.
</P>
<P>
   Women's troubles began when they bought into the feminist notion
that they could do anything a man could, she says. With that belief
came liberal attitudes about sex, which enabled men to sow their
oats without the commitment of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few men who want to take on the responsibility when
there are so many women who are giving it away,'' Crittenden says.
</P>
<P>
   But if women would adopt more traditional attitudes about
premarital sex, like their grandmothers did, it would give couples
a greater incentive to get married.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men can be corralled into marriage. They are guided in this by
women,'' the author says.
</P>
<P>
   Once the knot is tied, Crittenden thinks starting a family, not
a career, should be the priority. For one thing, that avoids the
fertility problems some women experience when they try to have
children after 35.
</P>
<P>
   More than 61 percent of married women with children younger than
3 worked outside the home in 1997, compared with 33 percent in
1975, according to the Census Bureau. But many of those working
mothers feel guilty and would stay at home if they could,
Crittenden asserts.
</P>
<P>
   But they're afraid to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aside from the devaluation we've done of women who stay home
and take care of their kids, marriage today is so insecure. Women
feel it's very dangerous to quit your job if you cannot count on
your husband to stay with you,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   They should stay home anyway, the author argues, for the sake of
the kids. At least until the youngest child enters school.
</P>
<P>
   Crittenden admits she would never discourage her 7-year-old
daughter from pursuing her dreams. But she would give her some
heartfelt advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a woman wants an enormous career like a surgeon, maybe you
shouldn't have kids. Right now, we're not taught to think in those
terms,'' she says. Decisions lead to consequences.
</P>
<P>
   As for her 5-year-old son, Crittenden says she will raise him to
understand that he must support his family on his income, like her
husband, journalist David Frum, does, so his wife won't have to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Crittenden says she lives the life she is espousing. She married
Frum when she was 25. They had their first child three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Although her newsletter has gained public attention during its
four years in publication, causing Crittenden to appear as guest
and commentator on television and radio programs, she says she
maintains a part-time work schedule, 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. five days a
week.
</P>
<P>
   She also cooks dinner every night and doesn't seek an
egalitarian relationship with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sitting there with pen and paper taking note of what
he does,'' Crittenden said. ``He does take out the garbage _ with
some nagging.''
</P>
<P>
   Alma Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
