<HEADER>
A1126 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPIRITUAL-RECONSIDER-     01-20 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIRITUAL-RECONSIDER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K: A TIME FOR SPIRITUAL RECONSIDERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The world is not going to end on January 1, 2000 AD.
 &HT;    If God planned to end the world on the 2,000th anniversary of
the birth of Jesus, you would not be reading this column. Luke's
Gospel says Jesus was born ''in the time of Herod, king of Judea,''
who died in 4 BC. Experts think Jesus' life began in 6 or 7 BC and
that we are really in the year AD 2006.
 &HT;    However, assume the world will end in less than a year. What
would you do differently? How would you use this brief time that is
left?
 &HT;    Last year I faced two life-threatening illnesses and literally
had my life saved twice by surgery. I felt the brush of eternity's
wing on my cheek. So I find myself thinking more about how to best
use the limited time I have left, whether months or years.
 &HT;    My mind goes back to 1983 when my father died of lung cancer at
age 66. He was not a religious man. He never went to church. For
years he had fought verbal battles with each of his three adult
children over matters that seem trivial as I look back.
 &HT;    Yet he wanted to make peace with each of us. Before he died, he
gave each of us part of our inheritance. He had never been more
loving as he was in those last months. His deteriorating body led
him to return to a kind of pure love for each of us.
 &HT;    I traveled across the country to spend some days with him, and
tried to lead him to make a reconciliation with God, as well. But
he resisted: ''It's too late, Mike,'' he said to me in a hoarse
whisper the last time I saw him.
 &HT;    We hugged and I left with a joy about our personal
reconciliation, but with sadness over his attitude toward his
maker.
 &HT;    How can one who is now lost to God, become found?
 &HT;    It's not enough to return to churchianty. There is something
superficial about most religious services. They reach only a layer
or two down, particularly to a troubled soul.
 &HT;    What I recommend is an extraordinary workbook and course that
has now been taken by 2.5 million people: ''Experiencing God:
Knowing and Doing the Will of God'' written by Henry Blackaby and
Claude King. Here is how it begins:
 &HT;    ''Jesus said, `This is eternal life: that they may know you, the
only true God, and Jesus Christ, whom you have sent' (John 17:3).
The heart of eternal life and the heart of this study is for you to
KNOW GOD and to KNOW JESUS CHRIST whom He has sent. Knowing God
does not come through a program or a method. It is a relationship
with a Person. It is an intimate love relationship with God.
 &HT;    ``Through this relationship, God reveals His will and invites
you to join Him where He is already at work. When you obey, God
accomplishes through you something only He can do. Then you come to
KNOW GOD in a more intimate way by EXPERIENCING GOD at work through
you.''
 &HT;    This is an immensely encouraging concept -- that it is possible
to actually know the creator and what his plan is for our life.
 &HT;    ''Experiencing God'' is a course that has had a catalytic force
in the lives of millions. It is laced with Scriptural quotes and
practical, step-by-step exercises that lead one into a deeper
relationship with God. It says, ''The Bible is God's Word for you.
Scriptures will be your source of authority for faith and
practice.''
 &HT;    It is broken up into 30 to 60 minutes of study each day and
participants are encouraged to join a small group of 6-10 people
who take the 13-week course together. The workbook has space to
write answers to draw out one's reflections on Scripture.
 &HT;    For example, we read Jesus saying to Peter and other disciples,
''Follow me.'' He gave no detailed map, but asks people to trust
him. Read John 5:17 and 5:19-20, and write answers to these
questions: Who is always at work? How much can the Son do by
himself? What does the Son do?
 &HT;    To order ''Experiencing God'' for $11.95 call 800 458-2772.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Mike McManus
