<HEADER>
A1103 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DARWIN-NYTSF     01-20 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DARWIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MR. DARWIN'S SHOOTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Roger McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   365 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Monthly Press. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; UNNATURAL SELECTION
</P>
<P>
   BY EMILY BARTON
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IN his engaging novel ``Mr. Darwin's Shooter,'' the Australian
writer Roger McDonald imagines the life of Charles Darwin's
assistant, Syms Covington, an ordinary sailor who provided the
scientist with much of the evidence on which he based his work.
Through Covington's view of Darwin, McDonald examines the
ramifications of the theory of evolution, thus allowing the reader
to reconsider how much Darwinism has influenced the modern
worldview.
</P>
<P>
   When the novel begins, in 1828, Covington is the 12-year-old son
of a Bedford horse butcher. His primary religious text has been
``The Pilgrim's Progress,'' which the young Covington takes ``with
the seriousness of a promise and a passion of loyalty in his
bones.'' The boy soon falls in with a charismatic sailor and
preacher, John Phipps, who persuades him to explore the seas in a
kind of Victorian imitation of Bunyan's Pilgrim. When Phipps's band
of boy sailors boards their third ship, the Beagle, Covington
recognizes that the best position would be to work for the ship's
``gentleman,'' Mr. Darwin. Covington takes on his responsibilities
as Darwin's servant without comprehending the nature of Darwin's
work, and over the next five years makes copies of the notes that
will become ``The Origin of Species.'' More important, he prepares
many of Darwin's specimens, a task McDonald describes in all its
complexity: ``With every specimen he ever packed away in its bed of
cotton he hung over it this moment of saying farewell; he dressed
the feathers that were well dressed before; perfected every curve;
finished caressingly and put his bird tenderly down, as he hoped to
be shriven himself when his time came.'' It is no small irony that
a man of faith should be ``after a year the match of his master in
this regard -- a meticulous plunderer.''
</P>
<P>
   As a counterpoint to the journey to the Galapagos, McDonald
interweaves chapters in the late 1850's and early 1860's, when
``The Origin of Species'' was first published and when Covington,
gone deaf from proximity to his bird gun, has settled in Australia.
Mirroring his own apprenticeship to the gentlemanly Darwin, the
gruff, middle-aged Covington takes a delicate young doctor, David
MacCracken, under his wing. Like Coleridge's Ancient Mariner, he
forces MacCracken to listen to his tale of betrayal -- of Darwin's
failure to recognize Covington's contribution to his work, and of
Covington's concern that Darwin's project has been, all along, to
disprove the existence of God.
</P>
<P>
   These chapters yield some of the novel's strongest philosophical
moments. Covington, too nervous to approach the book himself, asks
MacCracken to read the first copy of ``The Origin of Species.'' The
reader experiences an almost visceral thrill in MacCracken's
anticipation: ``His finger went to the tip of his tongue. Wetted,
</P>
<P>
   it returned to the corner of a page. Gripped the paper. Raised
the page to a small curve. Rustle of the page turning, scraping
over. A feeling of sinking through time as the next raft of words
rose up. He felt part of time with a deep contentment and
understanding -- all times past and future as well as this very
particular moment of his lying in this room . . . given the poetry
of existence in such a form.'' Darwin's words appear to the
contemporary audience with the full weight of revelation they must
have held for their first readers.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's prose is uniformly well turned, and even his minor
characters are observed with accuracy and humor. (``Standing in his
blood-brown boots,'' he writes of Covington's father, ``he rocked
back and forth as if hammered to the ground and twanging slightly
with the force of his opinions.'') The ending, in which Covington
makes peace with the differences between his life's project and his
master's, is somewhat pat; but the novel as a whole is so fully
imagined and imbued with intellectual curiosity that one forgives
the momentary oversimplification in its final pages.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Emily Barton's first novel will be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
