</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1104 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MUSIC-NYTSF     01-20 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MUSIC-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE MUSIC LESSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Katharine Weber.
</P>
<P>
   178 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Crown Publishers. $21.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; STEAL THIS PAINTING
</P>
<P>
   BY SYLVIA BROWNRIGG
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WHEN John Hume and David Trimble won the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize,
some expressed concern that the award had been given prematurely,
that this peace might not stick. On both sides of the divide in
Northern Ireland, there will always be those for whom ``peace at
any price is no peace at all.'' Such, at least, is the view of the
members of the I.R.A. splinter group in Katharine Weber's affecting
and elegant new novel about the dangerous subterfuges of politics
and the healing truths of art.
</P>
<P>
   Set during one of the region's many fragile cease-fires, ``The
Music Lesson'' brings together two incongruous worlds: the rarefied
environment of art-historical scholarship and the extremities of
terrorist politics. Selected -- unknowingly -- as the link between
the two is 41-year-old Patricia Dolan, a specialist in Dutch
painting at the Frick Art Reference Library in New York. Since the
tragic accidental death of her young daughter and her subsequent
divorce, Patricia has been living ``in a permanent state of
anesthesia, a highly functional but sealed-over kind of
detachment.'' Her only remaining emotional tie is to her aging
father, Pete, a retired Boston policeman who raised her on
anti-British sentiment and pride in her Irish roots.
</P>
<P>
   We learn these facts gradually, as Patricia narrates her story
in a series of journal entries written during a stay in a remote
cottage on Ireland's West Cork coast. ``She's beautiful'' is the
novel's arresting opening line, and it turns out that the woman
into whose face Patricia stares with such fascination -- ``Her gaze
catches me, pins me down, pulls me in'' -- is in a painting by
Vermeer called ``The Music Lesson.'' Patricia has been recruited by
an Irish cousin, Mickey O'Driscoll, to take part in an elaborate
plot to ``kidnap'' the painting, which is owned by the Queen, and
hold it for ransom. The law-abiding Patricia has been led into this
adventure by two simultaneous awakenings: of her political ideals
and of a deep passion for fiery young Mickey.
</P>
<P>
   Once the group has seized the painting, Patricia's task is to
guard it in the cottage and await Mickey's further instructions.
Though she has been told to keep to herself, she must have a few
friendly encounters with the neighbors in order not to arouse
suspicion. Weber has a nice touch with these passages, depicting
American-Irish misunderstandings with wry, subtle humor and
portraying the eccentric locals without making them seem overly
cute or quirky. Above all, Weber offers sparely sensual
descriptions of the land itself, and of Patricia's deep response to
it.
</P>
<P>
   As in her highly praised first novel, ``Objects in Mirror Are
Closer Than They Appear,'' whose central character was a
photographer, Weber astutely explores the gap between perception
and reality, both in relationships and in works of art. Patricia
offers reflections on authenticity and reproduction (quoting
liberally from Walter Benjamin) and on the glories of Vermeer,
about whose realism she is rapturously eloquent. Yet Weber's
admirable ambition -- to integrate these complex ideas about art,
politics and love -- is not fully realized, partly because the
political-thriller element sits uneasily with the delicate tone of
the rest. Patricia's account of her passion for Mickey also remains
somewhat sketchy, so that her falling for this rebel 16 years her
junior, although plausible, seems self-consciously naive. When
Patricia finally realizes that ``Mickey was someone I had invented
for my own needs,'' this does not come as a revelation to the
reader.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the transformation Patricia goes through seems
real -- and moving. She may gain and lose Mickey, along with her
brief belief in the rightness of a violent solution to the
Troubles, but she acquires something much more important in the
process. And, in a satisfying twist, it is the Vermeer that guides
her through these changes. Initially, Patricia feels pale in
comparison with the woman of ``The Music Lesson'': ``I look at my
face in the mirror and it seems far away, indistinct, less real
than hers.'' By the novel's suspenseful, adroitly constructed
close, Patricia is making her own choice of art over politics. ``I
am grateful for her lesson, for what she has taught me about
integrity, and constancy. Through her, I have come to know myself,
and I have begun to understand the world a little better, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing (HENRIK DRESCHER)
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Brownrigg's novel, ``The Metaphysical Touch,'' will be
published in June.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
