NYT-01-20-99 1504EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF     01-20 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME 
 BY MARILYN STASIO
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jonathan Kellerman's singular touch with wounded children pays
off royally in BILLY STRAIGHT (Random House, $25.95), a brisk
suspense thriller unburdened by his smug shrink hero, Alex Delaware
(who makes the briefest of cameo appearances here). By comparison,
Kellerman's new protagonist, a Hollywood homicide detective named
Petra Connor, might seem bland, but she is blessedly free of
affectation. She is also warmhearted enough to identify with, as
she frantically scours the city in search of a runaway 12-year-old
boy who witnessed the vicious stabbing of a woman in Griffith Park.
This case quickly draws the media carrion crows when it comes out
that the victim was recently divorced from the popular star of a
television series.
</P>
<P>
   Like Connor, the investigation is competent but strictly by the
book -- and not the reason you're turning the pages so fast. That
distinction goes to the winsome title character and frequent
narrator, a self-taught street kid with an artless affection for
books. Despite having been used and abused most of his life (``Why
do I keep meeting evil, gross, sick people?'' he wants to know),
Billy has developed a sharp intellect and a keen code of ethics,
along with the survival skills that are keeping him one short step
ahead of the press, the murderer and the other creeps on his trail.
The kid is irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   You like hot? The homicide case in Michael Connelly's police
procedural ANGELS FLIGHT (Little, Brown, $25) is so incendiary, the
city of Los Angeles has to call in the F.B.I., Internal Affairs,
the riot squad and the Fire Department to put out the racial flames
when an opportunistic black lawyer who makes a career out of suing
the police is murdered on the eve of a controversial trial. Harry
Bosch, the Hollywood detective in charge of the case, wouldn't wish
it on his worst enemy -- which is O.K., because the guy is already
on his team, assigned by the big brass who would like to see Bosch
go up in smoke himself.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone keeps telling Bosch he's being paranoid; but that,
indeed, is what makes him such a terrific hero. Unlike the
self-promoters on both sides of the racial divide, he has no time
for pretense and no stomach for covering up the realities of race
hatred, whatever the source. ``Deep down, you know it was the
truth,'' he says in a standoff with a black colleague. ``How come
the moment the truth might be uncomfortable people raise the race
card?'' Granted, the case doesn't have to be quite as convoluted as
Connelly makes it. But as the conscience of a city that has not got
over (and how could it?) the naked rage of the 1992 riots and the
O. J. Simpson trial, Bosch is a wonderful old-fashioned hero who
isn't afraid to walk through the flames -- and suffer the pain for
the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a blue moon, a new writer speaks up in a voice that gets
your attention like a rifle shot. Jenny Siler, the 27-year-old
author of EASY MONEY (John Macrae/Holt, $24), has that kind of
voice: clean, direct and a little dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Kerry, the unconventional heroine of this lethal
thriller, is a drug courier schooled in the trade by her father, an
alcoholic social dropout who runs dope out of Key West. (``In the
Keys smuggling has always been a kind of family business, like
farming in the Midwest.'') Allie is making a routine pickup in
Seattle when she gets word of her father's death; but before she
can drive home for the funeral, things start going very wrong. Her
contact is murdered after passing her a computer disk in a sailors'
bar, and Allie, who has no idea that the disk contains secret
information about Vietnam War crimes, finds herself set up for the
murder.
</P>
<P>
   In an intensely vivid piece of writing, Siler sends Allie on a
mad dash in which the visceral thrills of a cross-country manhunt
dissolve into painful reveries about a father's death and a lover's
betrayal. Mind and body racing through scenes of Colorado
mountains, Montana pit stops and Texas bars, Allie looks out on
this alien landscape and sees the sword swallower in a sideshow on
the Coney Island boardwalk, the luminous underwater creatures of a
night dive off Key West. Prodded by the author's seductive voice,
we see it all, too.
</P>
<P>
   Connoisseurs of serial killers will appreciate the gorgeous
imagery of the playwright Gardner McKay's macabre first novel,
TOYER (Little, Brown, $24), in which an ``unimaginable'' lunatic
performs the gruesome surgical procedure of spinal cordotomy on his
victims, cutting off their higher brain functions and leaving them
neurologically drained. The comatose women are arranged like living
corpses, their ruined bodies described as glass figurines, as pale
and broken flowers; one, eerily, as ``a sloop at anchor on a still
night, none of her riding lights lit, swinging slightly on the
tide.'' Unfortunately, McKay is so carried away with the bizarre
beauty of his own writing that he dispenses with the customary
trappings of a logical plot and a believable protagonist. Like the
vacant victims, this one is stunning at first glance but hollow at
the core.
</P>
<P>
   James Sallis is an acquired taste, and, at that, more of an
appetizer than a main course. So long as you read his idiosyncratic
novels about a black private eye from New Orleans named Lew Griffin
as ruminations on an interesting life well lived, you're getting
good value. In BLUEBOTTLE (Walker, $22.95), for instance, Griffin
suffers a temporary loss of sight and memory from the trauma of a
gunshot wound; so, besides the poetic scenery of the city, with its
throbbing music bars and vibrant local characters, there are
thoughtful passages (by way of Malraux, Bob Dylan et al.) on the
ambiguity of time and the lonely terror of being disconnected from
one's identity. Just don't go expecting anything like a coherent
plot, because Sallis's novels aren't really about anything except
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1504EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1106 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-KEROUAC-1000&AMP;     01-20 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-KEROUAC-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 JACK KEROUAC, KING OF THE BEATS
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Portrait.
</P>
<P>
   By Barry Miles.
</P>
<P>
   332 pp. New York: Henry Holt &AMP; Company. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; ON THE ROAD, AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   BY ANN DOUGLAS
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Biography at its best involves a love affair, even a marriage,
between author and subject, an arduous, lengthy collaboration in
which the biographer both discovers and receives meaning. As
practiced by Barry Miles in ``Jack Kerouac, King of the Beats,''
however, biography is more like a one-night stand, an act of
exploitation in which the subject loses much of the value that
presumably made the book worthwhile in the first place. Miles, who
has written a good biography of Allen Ginsberg, acknowledges
Kerouac's gift for ``word portraits'' and for capturing the
American experience in prose, crediting him as well with starting
the back-to-nature ``rucksack revolution'' of the 1960's. But the
highest praise a biographer can offer his subject is extensive
research, a commodity in short supply here. Nor does Miles display
much understanding of the life or the work he is examining.
Instead, he frequently trivializes the risks Kerouac took with his
vagrant life style and his writing. ``King of the Beats,'' as the
book's title has it, was an epithet bestowed on Kerouac by a
hostile press, one Kerouac loathed and used only ironically.
Indeed, it is hard to see what motive Miles may have had for this
undertaking, beyond cashing in on the Kerouac revival now under
way. (All of Kerouac's books are back in print; The Atlantic
Monthly and The New Yorker recently featured long excerpts from his
unpublished journals and correspondence.)
</P>
<P>
   Kerouac's life is an intensely American story. Born in 1922 in
Lowell, Mass., to working-class, immigrant French Canadian parents,
he grew up speaking joual, a dialect often unintelligible to
natives of France. He didn't feel altogether comfortable with
English until his late teens, and he spoke joual with his mother
until the end of his life; his later audacious experiments with
language depended on his constant awareness of a different, yet
parallel linguistic universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ti Jean,'' as he was called at home, excelled in school and in
sports, winning a football scholarship to Columbia and arriving
there in 1940, though he dropped out in 1942. In New York in 1944,
he met the other members of the earliest Beat circle -- Ginsberg,
William S. Burroughs, Lucien Carr and Herbert Huncke. Even as he
joined their explorations of the Times Square underworld of
hustlers and junkies, Kerouac remained close to his mother,
Gabrielle, then living in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the publication of his little-remarked debut
novel, ``The Town and the City'' (1950), Kerouac discovered what he
called spontaneous prose, a technique requiring exhaustive,
interminable practice in journal writing and on-the-spot
``sketching'' in words to ready himself for the climactic act of
writing a final draft. ``On the Road'' (1957), written in 1951, was
the first of his experimental works to find a publisher after years
of rejection. Taking bebop as his model, Kerouac labored to perfect
a voice, a style, rather than a particular work; once unleashed,
the style produced its own narrative forms. He felt little more
free to revise his writing than a musician would to replay a gig,
except by way of future performances. Like Charlie Parker, Jackson
Pollock and Marlon Brando in their respective media, in his ``true
story novels'' Kerouac attempted to create an explosively lyrical,
charismatic style, to capture all that the reigning cold war
pieties censured or distorted -- ``the speed and tension and
ecstatic tomfoolery of the age.'' Uncomprehending reviewers
dismissed him, one calling him ``a slob running a temperature.''
</P>
<P>
   Painfully shy, helpless before the media onslaught ``On the
Road'' precipitated and seldom sober, Kerouac tried in vain to
explain that he was ``an artist, old-fashioned, devoted.'' He wrote
out of an abiding romantic identification with America itself,
expressed first as a consuming ambition to explore and record it,
and finally, in the last years before his death of alcoholism in
1969, as a determination to rage, deteriorate and die in its
shelter. He stayed on the job, as Robert Creeley remarked, long
after anyone seemed to be listening.
</P>
<P>
   Kerouac's tragedy is of little interest to Miles, who offers a
fairly perfunctory account of the writer's life and no real
explication of the spontaneous prose ethos, which to Miles means
simply ``not correcting'' one's work. The book also includes
several errors and interpretive misreadings. Pollock and Kerouac
did not hang out at the Cedar Tavern together in 1958, since
Pollock died in 1956. Miles writes that Kerouac's scattings
(``google giggle'' is the example) were typographical errors that
he childishly refused to erase, though, in fact, Kerouac
deliberately expanded vowel sounds, a homage to his native joual.
Nor is it a ``strange switch'' on Kerouac's part to turn to the
third person at the close of ``Maggie Cassady'' (1959); the first
three chapters are in the third person, too.
</P>
<P>
   For Miles, the most important fact about Kerouac is his moral
turpitude. He holds Kerouac directly responsible for the troubled
life of his only child, Jan, who was raised by her mother, Joan
Haverty. By initially denying his paternity, Kerouac ``allowed Jan
to become a junkie at 13.'' When Neal Cassady leaves his wife and
child to go on the road with Kerouac, it is Kerouac's fault as much
as Cassady's. ``The Subterraneans,'' Kerouac's still shockingly
honest novel about his love affair with Aileen Lee, an
African-American, falls short, according to Miles, because Kerouac
did not mention ``the fact that 10 million black people were living
under segregation in the South,'' a sociological point, however
important, utterly at odds with the subjective mood of the
narrative.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-KEROUAC-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: of the narrative.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, unlike Ellis Amburn, another recent, still more
irresponsible biographer, Miles does not treat Kerouac as a
closeted homosexual, despite the obvious conflicts and confusion of
his love life. Miles is right that Kerouac sustained few
relationships and failed many obligations, though he seems unaware
that this failure, revealed in its harshest light, forms a
dominant, agonized theme in all of Kerouac's work. In his own words
a ``strange solitary crazy Catholic mystic,'' Kerouac was a member
of the spiritual underground that formed the counterpoint to the
official religious revivalism of the churchgoing 1950's. Coupledom
was not part of his mission. Like Genet, a writer he admired, he
undertook his adventures the way someone else might enter a
convent.
</P>
<P>
   In his later years, Kerouac did, as Miles charges, revert to the
ugly anti-Semitic prejudices of his parents, but there is no sense
in this book of how extreme, chronic alcoholism brings out the
worst, but not necessarily the truest, aspects of the drinker's
personality, a fact Kerouac repeatedly acknowledged, describing
himself in the mid-1960's as ``a maniacal drunkard,'' a ``scared .
. . dumbhead loudmouth.'' Nor can Miles explain why so many of
Kerouac's friends and lovers remained loyal to him despite the
abuse they sometimes suffered at his hands. Although a number of
Kerouac's intimates are still very much alive, Miles didn't
interview any of them, relying instead on the interviews he did for
the Ginsberg biography a decade ago. He has never interviewed the
musician David Amram or the writer Joyce Johnson, both Jewish, who
have stated that they experienced no hint of anti-Semitism in their
relationships with Kerouac. Ginsberg saw Kerouac's anti-Semitism at
first hand, yet until his own death in 1997, he held to his
earliest, excited realization about Kerouac: ``If I actually
confessed the secret tenderness of my soul, he would understand
nakedly who I was.'' Kerouac seldom judged; by all accounts,
deliberate malice was foreign to him. In middle age, bitterly
disappointed and drunk, he spewed prejudices the way some people
use profanity. The one pledge he kept was, as he wrote in a letter
of 1961, to be ``free of hypocrisy,'' to tell his readers, in a
language as expressive and fresh as he could make it, everything
about himself and his times.
</P>
<P>
   In his last years, Kerouac realized that his kind of
confessional, all-defenses-dropped, sacrificial romanticism had
been decisively eclipsed by a new mood of skepticism, mockery and
facetiousness, what we today call the post-modern style. Yet in
1965 he predicted that ``some great catastrophe is going to make
people wake up again''; his ethos, based on a love of the
``suffering heart,'' would outlast the ``sneerers'' and
``divisionists.'' It is ironic and unfortunate that his most recent
biographer belongs to the sneerers' party, but Kerouac speaks with
increasing power to all those who read, as he said he wrote, for
``companionship,'' who search for ``the key /
</P>
<P>
   out this dark corridor, /
</P>
<P>
   the effulgent door, /
</P>
<P>
   the mysterious knob, /
</P>
<P>
   the bright room gained.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Ann Douglas, the author of ``Terrible Honesty: Mongrel Manhattan
in the 1920's,'' is writing a book on cold war American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
