<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1107 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CREEPING-NYTS     01-20 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CREEPING-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 EVERY CREEPING THING
<TEXT>
<P>
   True Tales of Faintly Repulsive Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Conniff.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 256 pp. New York: Henry Holt &AMP; Co. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; WHY GRIZZLIES LOVE TWINKIES
</P>
<P>
   BY ANN FINKBEINER
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   My stepdaughter, when she was younger, wept bitterly over the
horrid bulldozer in the city park -- ripping up the home of Mr. and
Mrs. Bunny, in her words. With the years and a doctorate in
entomology, her rhetoric and outlook have changed. Last time she
expressed her views on wildlife, she was focusing a high-powered
microscope on an aphid eating a plant while itself being eaten from
the inside out by a tiny parasitic wasp. Through the aphid's
greenly transparent body, we could see the wasp's buggy little
eyes. I remembered Stephen Jay Gould writing that 19th-century
theologians regarded parasitic wasps as ``the greatest challenge to
the concept of a benevolent deity,'' which I thought put it mildly.
My stepdaughter shrugged: ``The aphids just go right on eating.
They're awfully dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   My stepdaughter will like ``Every Creeping Thing.'' Richard
Conniff, a nature writer, begins by saying that Bunny-izing is
possible only when people are at a remove from nature and don't
know much about it. Nature up close evokes more complicated
feelings. ``Despite the efforts of many earnest and life-affirming
people to persuade me that the vampire bat is our friend . . . I
have never quite overcome the gut feeling that fear of nature is
normal,'' he writes. Then he qualifies that sentiment, ``or perhaps
I should say that fear and love are thoroughly tangled together.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is a series of case studies of the fear/love tangles
between various creatures -- bats, cormorants, porcupines, moles --
and people who, for commercial or academic or personal reasons,
live closely with them. The best case studies are small
self-contained stories. One is about a couple, Steve and Marilynn
French, who observe, from a distance, grizzly bears in Yellowstone
National Park. About 30 years ago, the park closed its garbage
dumps, from which the grizzlies fed, and then shot the grizzlies
that wouldn't stop raiding tourists' Twinkies. Ever since,
naturalists have argued over whether Twinkie-independent (Conniff's
phrase) grizzlies will survive and return to more natural habits,
and the Frenches say they have. Not only did the grizzlies become
better hunters, but the local elk got better at outsmarting them.
Conniff describes a hunt: ``In hot pursuit, the grizzly's mouth was
also open, with a look of pure joy. He flew up the slope and
hurtled in among them, spinning one way and then the other. . . .
The cows were all around him, confusing him, and the calves danced
away just out of reach.'' Steve French says, ``One of those dump
bears woulda had a heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Another story is about a conservation officer, David Wingate,
who has single-handedly reconstructed Nonsuch Island in Bermuda,
which after 350 years of settlement had been ``a desert'' of rats,
goats and ``the skeletal remains of the old forest.'' Over the last
40 years Wingate got rid of the rats and goats, restored the forest
and its undergrowth and brought back herons and land crabs. His
reason is personal: he wants a petrel called the cahow -- native to
Nonsuch, thought to be extinct since 1620, but now found in small
numbers -- to come back to live. If he restores their home, maybe
they'll return.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the chapters, however, aren't stories but loosely joined
descriptions of humans and animals; the parties are well matched
for charm, talent and repulsiveness. Grizzlies in Wyoming spend
August eating only moths. The first four-inch baby sandtiger shark
that escapes its embryonic capsule swims around the uterus, rips
open all the other capsules and eats its siblings. Sloths are so
lethargic that they are green with algae; once a researcher who
kept one as a pet smelled ``something like a burning sloth,'' and
found it ``half-asleep on a large electric bulb, with its rear
going up in smoke, and . . . it wanted to stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   On the human side, one researcher who studies the social systems
of mice says he ``spent a sizable part of his career in a darkened,
windowless room,'' occasionally sitting still ``for an extra 20
minutes while a mouse 'had a nap between my trouser leg and me.' ''
Another, before he was killed flying into a cloud-forest
mountaintop, had memorized the songs of over 4,000 bird species.
Another runs a charter service for people who want to catch sharks
with the object of cutting out their jaws and tails as trophies.
The man preparing the home for the cahow loved nature so much that,
as a child, ``he once took a jar of spiders to bed with him, and
his mother found him asleep, covered with webs.''
</P>
<P>
   The last chapter is another story, about the author and a dog he
didn't know. Conniff was in a pasture above the western Irish coast
and saw a sheepdog tearing toward him ``with a crazy, bucketing
speed, and it leaped up at me almost before I had spotted it.'' The
dog, an energetic breed with spookily intelligent eyes, began a
chasing-game with Conniff, drawing him by degrees down toward the
coast, then to the water, then onto the rocks out in the water.
Conniff, only a little afraid, followed, wondering what the dog was
up to. The dog stopped at the last rock, waited for Conniff to
catch up, then plopped down and watched the sunset. Conniff watched
too. When it was over, the dog led Conniff back over the rocks and
up the pasture, and then took off without a goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's a perfect ending to the book, I'm not sure why.
Conniff is a splendid writer -- fresh, clear, uncondescending, and
with never a false step; one can't resist quoting him. His message
is urgent: ``We are in danger of turning what's left of the planet
into a petting zoo,'' and so we must learn that ``the world is full
of life-forms that are too strange, too beautiful, too powerfully
disturbing to let merely vanish.'' But though the message is
explicit in the introduction and illustrated in each chapter, it's
never developed into an argument: 16 chapters of anecdotes don't
add up to a convincing case. So the reader leaves still hungry.
How, in the history of the relations between humans and animals,
did we get to this petting-zoo stage? Where in those relations does
the sheepdog fit? What do those spider-loving and shark-hunting
humans say about these relations? And if the human reaction to
animals is a tangle of fear and love, will we always relegate
animals to either extinction or the petting zoo?
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Ann Finkbeiner, a freelance science writer, teaches in the Johns
Hopkins University's writing seminars.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
