<HEADER>
A1109 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WARNINGS-NYTS     01-20 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WARNINGS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 SMALL CRAFT WARNINGS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stories.
</P>
<P>
   By Kate Braverman.
</P>
<P>
   180 pp. Reno: University of Nevada Press. Paper, $16.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; SQUALL LINES
</P>
<P>
   BY BILL GOLDSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HALFWAY through Kate Braverman's new collection of stories, a
character looks across San Francisco Bay and sees hills that remind
her of ``brown discarded flesh. Or abandoned women . . . exiled, of
no use anymore. Some man sent them away.''
</P>
<P>
   This observation seems a ``startlement,'' as the King of Siam
might say if he were a character in this book (in which that
memorable and unusual word unfortunately appears twice). But the
reader of the stories that precede ``A Conjunction of Dragon
Ladies'' will already have concluded that Braverman's relentless
focus is on abandoned women -- and that her characters'
observations are easily read as the author's self-conscious
summations of her aims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Craft Warnings'' is Braverman's second book of short
fiction (she is also the author of three novels and four books of
poetry), and in it we meet these protagonists: a 13-year-old girl
periodically abandoned to her grandmother's care by an
irresponsible mother; a 12-year-old girl who at long last meets her
one-legged Vietnam veteran father; a drug addict mother with an
infant she fantasizes about abandoning to nature (whence, too, she
gets the names she also fantasizes about giving him: Forest, Sky,
River, Wind). And then there is the photojournalist, rejected by
her parents when she gives birth out of wedlock, who senses that
she is ``part of an enormous midnight circle of women alone in
winter.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a numbing lineup in place of what ought to be an array of
individuals -- a weakness exacerbated by Braverman's excessively
lush language, which blurs her characters' identities and dilutes
the urgency of the harsh reality they appear to be living through.
Many of these women go unnamed, though other people almost always
are named -- which is confusing and seems another unnecessary
reminder of the protagonists' abandoned states.
</P>
<P>
   The stories also share an annoying repetitiveness of moods, even
of fleeting thoughts. ``We are all barbarians,'' one woman
concludes (echoed by another's idea that ``we are barbarians with
lace panties, machine guns and charge cards''). Vanilla candles
appear in one story; a perfume of ``corrupted vanilla'' pops up
later. One woman notes that ``nobody thinks about . . . placing a
shell to your ear. Everyone knows there are no answers.'' Three
stories later, another discovers that ``roots . . . have dug in.
They know. . . . This is what you must hold to your ear . . . not
the shell, which is empty, and tells you only its name.'' It's
probably hard to believe that the second, incidental appearance of
a porcelain teacup (its violet flowers changed to rosebuds) can be
a major annoyance, but if you read these stories in order you may
have the same reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Frustratingly enough, ``Small Craft Warnings'' is also filled
with beautiful language studded with sharp observations. The
daughter of the Vietnam War vet thinks, ``He was my father by
marginal technicality, a spasm and a shudder.'' The drug addict who
hears the laments of abandoned women also notices a ``gray-haired
woman who looks like you think your grandmother should look before
all the old women got face lifts and started playing tennis.''
Unfortunately, Braverman doesn't give us enough of these guideposts
to her characters' thoughts, apparently not minding that the
luxurious prose of her interior monologues reflects more about her
style than it does about her people in extremis.
</P>
<P>
   When the photojournalist concludes that she ``had been diligent
with her observations. She had courted the brutally intense,'' it's
hard not to think that we have found another of Braverman's
footnotes about herself. But the ``brutally intense'' is always
deflected here by overripe phrasing. The reader of ``Small Craft
Warnings'' is likely to think of Braverman when the Vietnam vet's
daughter wonders, at one point, whether she ``had invented a
paradox, how something could be exquisite and simultaneously torn
and suffocating.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Bill Goldstein is books editor of The New York Times on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
