<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1110 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ANGELS-NYTSF     01-20 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ANGELS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ANGELS &AMP; ALIENS
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Journey West.
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Morris.
</P>
<P>
   258 pp. New York: Picador USA. $23.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; FEAR OF FLYING
</P>
<P>
   BY KAREN KARBO
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NO woman is razor sharp during the first year of her first
child's life. Heroic, yes. Capable of weighing in with clear-eyed
opinions on anything much beyond disposable versus cloth diapers,
no. My inner feminist wishes it weren't so, but every now and then
the publication of a book like ``Angels &AMP; Aliens'' confirms it.
Subtitled ``A Journey West,'' this disappointing memoir of the year
Mary Morris spent as a writer in residence at the University of
California, Irvine, while singlehandedly raising her infant
daughter, Kate, is not so much a journey as a compilation of
cliched observations about California that are so obvious no one
bothers to make them anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Morris suffers in a bungalow overlooking the ocean in Laguna
Beach, an address most Californians would give their capped
eyeteeth for: ``In the morning I wake to a stream of relentless
sun. Outside, my neighbor (a woman I will never meet), dressed in a
string bikini, zinc oxide on her nose, wears a cordless Walkman
that projects two antennae from her head, and I know that I have
come to Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   The author of four novels, three short-story collections and two
marvelous ravel narratives, Morris is normally a wise and
meticulous observer. Here, however, she falls back on the sweeping,
portentous pronouncement that is too all-inclusive to be true: ``In
this city, catastrophe lurks everywhere. From the ooze in the
earth, the brush fires that sweep the canyons, the earthquakes, the
mud slides that, gathering momentum, take million-dollar homes out
in Malibu.'' This is the sort of take favored by the evening news.
Unless you're one of the handful of people who own those
million-dollar homes, the main calamity the rains may bring is
getting stuck somewhere in open-toed shoes without an umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   The journey of the title also encompasses Morris's desultory
spiritual dabbling. Her first stop is the gloriously tacky Crystal
Cathedral and its overblown Christmas pageant, in which grown women
vie for the part of ``angels'' who ``fly'' over the congregation
with the aid of invisible wires. Morris is curious enough about the
angels to pose as a journalist for an East Coast newspaper in the
hope of getting an interview. ``Each angel has her tale to tell --
divorce, betrayal, loss. Not so different than mine, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a scene that surely ranks a place in the Instant Karma
Files, Morris is railroaded into taking a test flight herself.
After a rocky start, she begins flapping her arms and ``I soar and
dive, catch the wind, my wings flapping, hands flowing. I dip and
climb . . . as close as I've ever come to God.''
</P>
<P>
   She drifts through further encounters with crystal healers, a
U.F.O. abductee support group and a woman named Wanda Joy, who
channels an alien being called Ashtar, without deconstructing,
dismissing or embracing any of them. Her bizarre interactions with
Wanda Joy, who is involved in Project Evacuation (which will allow
all of Ashtar's believers to transcend their earthly vessels and
beam to the fourth dimension, where new planets await them),
somehow fail to impress Morris one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   By page 9, the reader knows Morris's problem is not the
relentless sun of California or the traffic or the brainless bigots
she encounters at every turn. It is her faltering relationship with
the father of her baby daughter. A renowned professor of
international law, he had originally planned to move to California
with Morris; in fact, it was he who had been offered an important
post and declined it at the last minute. Having refused to sign an
affidavit acknowledging his paternity, he fails to provide money
for Kate's care. ``We had not married. . . . We had been together
five years. I had seen him through his divorce. But he was
ambivalent about marrying again. He was older than I by almost 20
years, and he had so many responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a crystal ball to see where all this is headed.
Fortunately, by the end of her journey, Morris does too.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Karen Karbo is the author of two novels. Her latest nonfiction
book, ``Notes From Ex Isle,'' will be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
