<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1111 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-GLAMORAMA-100     01-20 1603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-GLAMORAMA-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 GLAMORAMA
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Bret Easton Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   482 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; LESSER THAN ZERO
</P>
<P>
   BY DANIEL MENDELSOHN
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's a mystery to me why some people are complaining that Bret
Easton Ellis's latest novel is nothing more than a recycling of his
controversially graphic ``American Psycho'' (1991). ``American
Psycho,'' after all, was a bloated, stultifyingly repetitive,
overhyped novel about a fabulously good-looking and expensively
dressed Wall Street sociopath who tortures and dismembers beautiful
young women, whereas ``Glamorama,'' as anyone can see, is a
bloated, stultifyingly repetitive, overhyped book about an entire
gang of fabulously good-looking and expensively dressed sociopaths
who torture and dismember both women and men -- and lots of them.
Clearly, Ellis's authorial vision has grown broader and more
inclusive over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis made his name in 1985 with the cult best seller ``Less
Than Zero,'' a short, moodily effective morality tale about despair
among rich, unhappy young L.A. types; his subsequent fictions have,
with increasingly heavy-handed satirical intent, treated pretty
much the same theme and occasionally the same characters. The
nominal plot of ``Glamorama'' traces the disintegration of a young,
gorgeous, ``semi-famous'' model-cum-club-promoter called Victor
Ward, a United States senator's son who's so ennui- and
Xanax-ridden that he doesn't realize he's got involved in a group
of international model-terrorists until it's too late. Like its
predecessors, ``Glamorama'' is meant to be a withering report on
the soul-destroying emptiness of late-century American consumer
culture, chichi downtown division; but the only lesson you're
likely to take away from it is the even more depressing classic
American morality tale about how premature stardom is more of a
curse than a blessing for young writers.
</P>
<P>
   The new novel does provide Ellis with a vehicle for his
strengths, which are essentially reportorial rather than
novelistic. He has an uncannily keen eye for the tiny details of
the lives of the
</P>
<P>
   label-obsessed yuppies and would-be celebs he's sending up: much
of his prose consists of (intentionally) numbingly long lists of
his characters' clothes and accouterments, the Nokia cell phones
and Bang &AMP; Olufsen stereos and Prada handbags and Armani suits and
Ermenegildo Zegna ties out of which his loft-dwellers somewhat
hopefully attempt to assemble something like an identity. Even
better, he has perfect pitch for the way in which the denizens of
his upscale, downtown worlds have internalized, to deadening
psychological effect, the banalities of advertising and marketing:
his characters talk to one another and about themselves in what
sounds suspiciously like ad copy. (At one point Victor describes
himself as ``coolly disheveled in casual Prada, confident but not
cocky.'' )
</P>
<P>
   Ellis is less a novelist, in a way, than a kind of conceptual
artist in print: he likes to describe and mimic and juxtapose
things, in hopes that the juxtapositions will speak for themselves.
``American Psycho,'' with its many descriptions of rich Wall
Streeters' outfits -- relieved by the occasional disemboweling or
an authorial disquisition on the ``art'' of Whitney Houston -- was
apparently meant to suggest that corporate greed and consumer
culture were producing a generation of affectless ``killers'' to
whom everything had pretty much the same (low) value. Similarly,
the modishly thriller plot of ``Glamorama'' throws together a
madcap club opening, various fashion shows, a trans-Atlantic
crossing on the QE2, acrobatic sex scenes and many sequences in
which terrorists blow up trains and planes and automobiles and
torture their disloyal associates in extremely unpleasant ways,
thereby affording Ellis opportunities to gross you out with his
trademark affectlessness (``The device shreds his leg at the knee
and when I turn around I see his leg slide across the floor,''
etc., etc.).
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the morass of incident and body parts lurks the
point. The terrorists use a computer program (``PhotoSoap for
Windows 95'') to alter photographs and thereby control reality.
``You can move planets with this,'' one of the evil models says.
``You can shape lives.'' In a culture in which image -- and,
therefore, images -- is all-important, the author wants to say,
meaningful identity is obliterated and everyone becomes soulless
and interchangeable. (A running joke in both ``Glamorama'' and
``American Psycho'' is that characters are always getting confused
by their friends with other people, with no noticeable
consequences.)
</P>
<P>
   But Ellis's satirical message is, essentially, a one-liner, and
hardly an original one at that -- celebrity culture is vapid, yes,
and? -- and isn't remotely worth the endless pages in which his
vacuous and inconsequential characters talk vacuously and
inconsequentially about vacuous and inconsequential things: ``I'm
seeing Emily Lloyd maintaining remarkable poise while eating a
giant grilled shrimp.'' And the pretentious, halfhearted narrative
device, introduced a third of the way into the book, of suggesting
that the novel's action is actually part of a film that's being
made -- there are occasional references to ``the director'' or to
the fact that this or that scene is a ``flashback'' -- only
underscores how desperately the author is trying to impose,
retroactively, some shape and meaning on his rambling narrative.
Ellis goes to an awful lot of trouble to make sure you know how
disgusted he is by the superficiality of contemporary culture, and
the result is fiction that is -- well, disgusting and superficial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-GLAMORAMA-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: disgusting and superficial.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's odd that Ellis's books are so little fun, given how ripe
their subjects are for parody. Even at its blackest, truly
devastating social satire -- you think of Evelyn Waugh's ``Loved
One'' -- has a certain gleefulness about it: if you really disdain
those awful people and their empty pretensions, you can't help
enjoying impaling them on their own vanities. But as you slog your
way through ``Glamorama,'' with its clumpy, dissertation-length
references to the first-name-only celebrities, to the expensive
clothes, the hair salons and gyms du jour, to the empty, rococo
sex, the high-tech gizmos and copious, casual drug-taking, you
can't help thinking that Ellis knows far more about all this than
mere journalistic curiosity requires; he reminds you of those
Southern judges who simply had to watch hours and hours of dirty
movies in order to determine that yes, they were pornographic. I
suspect that the relentless dreariness of Ellis's recent books --
the sense you get as you read them that you're somehow being
punished -- is a kind of authorial projection, the product of a
certain conflictedness. People who really abhor celebrity, and who
are truly offended by the way that the media and the market have
eroded privacy, generally don't allow themselves to be the subjects
of celebratory promotional films. ``This Is Not an Exit,'' the
forthcoming documentary about Ellis's life -- he's 36 -- will,
according to Alfred A. Knopf publicity material, be ``available for
bookstore events.''
</P>
<P>
   One documentary that came to mind as I read ``Glamorama'' was
``Unzipped,'' the 1995 film about the fashion designer Isaac
Mizrahi; it trod much the same territory that Ellis's novel claims
to explore but showed you, delightfully, that along with the
silliness and vanity and pretentiousness rampant in the fashion/
</P>
<P>
   celebrity crowd, there's fun and passion and, often, talent.
(Some people become celebrated for a reason, after all.) Ellis
doesn't give you the whole picture because he does the safe thing:
he sticks to descriptions of what his dull characters are wearing
rather than considering what they might be thinking or, God forbid,
feeling. But Ellis's recent books aren't so much novels as
advertisements -- for his knowing attitude, for how hip he is to
the scene. Sadly -- given its author's abilities -- ``Glamorama''
is itself just another artifact of the culture it pretends to
criticize: it's little more than a pose, a soulless, empty thing
that's dressed to kill, the literary and rhetorical equivalent of
standing around at some club in black Prada and wearing sunglasses
after midnight, trying to cow those even more insecure than
yourself into thinking you're interesting and even important. I
can't imagine that anyone actually enjoys these torturous novels --
except, perhaps, the people whom the books clandestinely celebrate,
the actor-models and model-writers and celebrity-editors and their
gang. But then, Ellis has become a sort of hip brand-name label in
the publishing world, and people go in for him precisely for the
reasons they might go in for a $300 Helmut Lang plain cotton shirt:
It's so outrageous they assume there has to be something to it. But
there isn't. The emperor has no clothes, designer or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Mendelsohn's ``Elusive Embrace,'' a memoir of family
history and sexual identity, will be published this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
