NYT-01-20-99 1505EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1113 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LOUSE-NYTSF     01-20 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LOUSE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 LOUSE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By David Grand.
</P>
<P>
   255 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Arcade Publishing. $23.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; THE BOSS FROM PURGATORY
</P>
<P>
   BY DAVID SACKS
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bad employers can make for good fiction. The subject's a
natural: many readers have been unhappy employees, and wellsprings
of reader emotion -- resentment, embarrassment -- await an author's
skillful uncorking. Which is just what happens in ``Louse,'' a
delightfully eerie and angry first novel by a young New Yorker
named David Grand.
</P>
<P>
   With crazy but apt distortions, ``Louse'' mirrors the plight of
real-life workers in an era of job insecurity, video surveillance
and shameless corporate euphemisms. Yet Grand has even larger
aspirations: the novel's hallucinatory world suggests a religious
allegory (apparently sincere) posing questions about God's will or
presence in the universe. Although not every part of this ambitious
agenda succeeds, ``Louse'' is often provocative and hilarious,
occasionally stunning.
</P>
<P>
   The chapters alternate between two voices. Some are assembled
from ``official'' corporate sources -- staff memos, logbook
entries, public relations bulletins -- that give the reader
tantalizing scraps of information while exercising the author's
gift for parody. The rest are the personal observations of Herman
Q. Louse, a fly-on-the-wall character who is the obedient valet of
the man he's been instructed to call Poppy, the billionaire Herbert
Horatio Blackwell.
</P>
<P>
   By far the novel's best-drawn character, Poppy is a bedridden,
dying monster modeled on the aging Howard Hughes. Like Hughes,
Poppy owns a manufacturing, investment and gambling casino empire,
and it is based in a state that resembles Nevada. Like Hughes,
Poppy is a former daredevil pilot and Hollywood playboy, and he is
now addicted to prescription codeine. Poppy also shares old
Hughes's most notorious trait: a pathological fear of germs. Afraid
of most human contact, afraid to have his hair or nails clipped,
afraid of bugs, fresh air and fresh food, Poppy lives secluded in a
sanitized bedchamber. Louse and others tend him amid elaborate
hygienic precautions and social rituals.
</P>
<P>
   Lovingly, the author describes the meticulous duties required of
the domestic staff. Thus a conscientious worker prepares Poppy's
meal: ``Ms. Lonesome leans over the kitchen wash basin. She lifts a
scrub brush and applies it to the can of peaches. . . . She scrubs
the metallic container until all remnants of the adhesive once
holding the wrapper are gone. She scrubs until the canister is
shining. She wipes. She polishes with a fresh paper towel and
places the can on the tray.'' It is an image of diligence wasted.
But such scenes also point the way to the novel's higher ground --
a brooding on the futility of all human endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   The real Howard Hughes lived in hotels, with a whole floor
sealed off for him and his attendants. ``Louse'' chooses a more
imperial scenario: Poppy inhabits the penthouse of his corporate
headquarters, a cylindrical glass-and-chrome building ``with the
girth of a lake'' rising from the desert resort town of G., which
Poppy also owns. The ground floor is a public gambling casino with
a secret purpose. The rest of the building holds thousands of
corporate employees -- accountants, lawyers, clerks -- who toil day
and night.
</P>
<P>
   Poppy controls his company as insanely as he does his
bedchamber. Work and conversation are governed by voluminous,
stultifying rules. A huge security staff watches everything (an
idea the author plays with slyly, as in Louse's impression of the
attractive Ms. Lonesome: ``The pulse of red lights from the
surveillance cameras spreads across the pale pink pallor of her
lips'').
</P>
<P>
   We soon suspect that nearly everyone, Louse included, has been
drugged and brainwashed. ``Though you will find your long-term
memory impaired, you will find your short-term memory fully
functional,'' a perky indoctrination memo states. ``Your motor
skills should be impeccable and your energy level appropriately
blissful, as well as suitable for all required duties.'' Poppy's
dazed employees lack the presence of mind to quit or blow the
whistle. They'll stand for anything. The author takes this funny
notion and deftly, with self-restraint, turns it nightmarish.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we hear rumors of one free spirit. An executive named
Mortimer Blank has diverted company funds and is at large -- an
outlaw in the corporate forest, hunted fiercely by Poppy's
henchmen. This shadowy antagonist (blank  &QC;  mort  &QC;  death?) provides
much of the novel's suspense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louse'' often seems reminiscent of other satirical fables,
from George Orwell's ``Nineteen Eighty-four'' to Donald Antrim's
black-comic ``Elect Mr. Robinson for a Better World.'' The master,
of course, is Franz Kafka. Certainly the little people in Grand's
fiction are caught in a Kafkaesque system of guilt and obligation,
a kind of corporate purgatory. Louse receives no salary; instead,
like other employees, he owes the company money, a debt perpetually
renewed by disciplinary penalties. Similarly, a much-heralded
building called Paradise is under construction for occupancy by a
few select staffers -- which keeps everyone appropriately anxious
and motivated. The book's best scene -- a public ``correction'' of
a junior sales rep accused of abetting the rebel Blank --
chillingly combines elements of a staff luncheon, a television game
show and a 16th-century auto-da-fe. Throughout, ``Louse'' nicely
lampoons the bad employer's mandatory cheer, the phony equality of
office colleagues, the exploitative appeals to team spirit and high
standards.
</P>
<P>
   FLAWS there are, too. The novel's symbolism sometimes dampens
the storytelling, so that Blank's sedition seems less thrilling
than it should be. A related problem is Louse's passivity. We keep
waiting for the worm to turn. ``We were complicit. We could have
defied a little. Done something extraordinary,'' Louse says
regretfully at the end, and the reader is forced to agree. The only
real player is the supine boss, Poppy. The novel's larger message
also remains fuzzy: is the author saying that organized religion is
the ultimate corporation, or that corporate employers manipulate
the human thirst for expiation and salvation?
</P>
<P>
   Still, this ``Louse'' sticks to you, for its wit and imaginative
vision. Amid the twists and revelations of the closing chapters,
the old schemer's master plan finally comes into view -- yet
imperfectly. We see most of the how's but few of the why's. Which
is exactly the way David Grand seems to want it.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   David Sacks is the author of the Encyclopedia of the Ancient
Greek World.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1505EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1114 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LAWS-1000&AMP;ADD     01-20 1522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LAWS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ALL THE LAWS BUT ONE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Civil Liberties in Wartime.
</P>
<P>
   By William H. Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   254 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $26.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; ALL'S FAIR?
</P>
<P>
   BY JEREMY WALDRON
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the early hours of May 25, 1861, a Maryland state legislator
named John Merryman was arrested in connection with an attempt to
disrupt the transport of Union troops from Baltimore to Washington.
Merryman was held at Fort McHenry, under the command of Gen. George
Cadwalader. The day after his arrest, Merryman's lawyer obtained a
writ of habeas corpus, directing General Cadwalader to produce the
prisoner so that a Federal court could examine the case for his
detention. The general instead sent one of his officers to say that
he was authorized by the President of the United States to suspend
habeas corpus during the present emergency in Maryland. (What
President Abraham Lincoln had actually commanded was that the
resistance in Maryland was to be counteracted by ``the most prompt
and efficient means . . . even, if necessary . . . the bombardment
of their cities and, in the extremest necessity, the suspension of
the writ of habeas corpus.'') The judge responded by ordering that
the general himself be brought by force to the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   A United States marshal went to Fort McHenry to serve the writ
of attachment, but -- not surprisingly -- he returned empty-handed.
General Cadwalader would not receive him. The judge considered
whether it would be worth forming a posse to bring the general into
court but decided against it, fearing that the posse would be
resisted with superior force. Instead, he delivered an opinion
stating that the President did not have the authority to suspend
habeas corpus. He sent a copy of his decision to the White House,
reminding the President of his sworn duty ``to take care that the
laws be faithfully executed.'' Lincoln made no direct response to
the court, nor did his Administration appeal the decision. (And the
Army certainly did not release Merryman.) But in a speech to
Congress on July 4, the President presented his critics with a
challenge. The laws as a whole were being resisted in this
rebellion, he said. Are ``all the laws, but one, to go unexecuted,
and the Government itself go to pieces, lest that one'' -- habeas
corpus -- ``be violated?''
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Justices of the Supreme Court sometimes sat as
Federal circuit judges. The judge in the case of Merryman was Roger
Taney, Chief Justice of the United States, and the author of the
infamous Dred Scott decision (which in 1857 had held that
African-Americans could not be citizens). Needless to say, Northern
opinion was as outraged by Taney's decision in Merryman as it was
by the earlier infamy. The New York Times thundered that the case
presented ``the ungracious spectacle of . . . the soldier eager to
punish, and the jurist to exculpate a traitor.'' Nevertheless, five
years later (after the Union victory and with a Lincoln appointee
-- Salmon P. Chase -- as Chief Justice) the Supreme Court reached
essentially the same conclusion as Taney in a case called Ex Parte
Milligan. ``The Constitution of the United States is a law for
rulers and people, equally in war and in peace. . . . The
Government, within the Constitution, has all the powers granted to
it, which are necessary to preserve its existence.'' Habeas corpus
could be suspended, but only by Congress; and even then, the
majority said, civilians could not be held by the Army for trial
before a military tribunal, not even if the charge was fomenting an
armed uprising in a time of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Rehnquist is 16th in the line of Chief Justices that
includes Taney and Chase. With ``All the Laws But One: Civil
Liberties in Wartime,'' he has written a book that explores
Lincoln's situation, not primarily through legal or philosophical
analysis but by taking us through the variety of cases, from the
1860's to the 1940's, in which civil liberty issues in time of war
have arisen.
</P>
<P>
   The book is mainly narrative history, giving us an account of
the Civil War cases, the cases that arose during and immediately
after World War I and the cases that challenged the imposition of
martial law in Hawaii and the removal and internment of
Japanese-Americans in the Western states during World War II.
Actually, that summary is a little misleading. There are 13
chapters on the 1860's and only five on the 20th-century cases:
indeed, there are fewer than 30 pages on the World War II
internments, compared with more than 60 on the Milligan case alone.
That makes the book a little lopsided, the more so because the
disparity is never explained by the author.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rehnquist presents full and fascinating human profiles of
the major participants in these cases -- the statesmen, the
soldiers, the suspects, their lawyers and the judges -- and a level
of detail about the hearings and the decisions that provides the
reader with some understanding of what it must have been like to
grapple with these issues in a time of crisis. Not least is the
sense that we get, in a case like Merryman, of what a clash between
the executive and the judiciary is actually like: this provides a
healthy reminder of how much we usually rely, in the last resort,
on executive submission in upholding the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   In places, perhaps, there is a bit too much detail: at times it
seems Rehnquist wants to write like J. Anthony Lukas in ``Big
Trouble,'' giving us a history of everything that is mentioned in
the history and a background to everything that is furnished as
background. Do we really need to know that the author of the
majority opinion in Milligan went to stay with his uncle, an
Episcopal rector, when he was 5? Or to be reminded, at the
beginning of the chapter on Japanese internments, about ruinous
inflation in Germany after the Kaiser's abdication in 1918? Readers
will find themselves flipping rather impatiently through some of
these pages.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-LAWS-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: these pages.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if they are looking for provocative opinions or predictions
-- what this Chief Justice will do if a case like Milligan or
Korematsu (the most famous of the World War II Japanese internment
cases) ever comes before his Court -- they will be disappointed.
Rehnquist is quite sparing in his commentary. He criticizes the
Supreme Court majority in Milligan for holding that Congress had no
power to permit trials of civilians by military tribunals in time
of war, but mainly because that issue was not presented on the
strict facts of the case. And the courts, he says, should not
decide constitutional questions unnecessarily. He does speculate
that maybe ``Congress should be able to provide for trial of
defendants by a judge without a jury'' -- something like the
Diplock courts in Northern Ireland -- ``in a carefully limited
class of cases dealing with national security in wartime.'' But
this is not a suggestion he explores in any detail. He agrees with
Judge Learned Hand's insistence in one of the World War I cases
that the courts should resist any attempt by the Government to
equate strongly worded criticism of conscription with advocacy of
resistance to it. And he offers a helpful analysis of the
Japanese-American cases by suggesting, first, a distinction between
discrimination against groups of citizens and discrimination
against aliens, and second, a distinction between a policy of
evacuating people from coastal areas and a policy of continuing
detention.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Rehnquist expresses concern about the alacrity
with which the Roosevelt Administration accepted the military's
advice about the dangers posed by Japanese nationals and citizens
of Japanese ancestry. The President's approval of internment was
``perfunctory,'' given in the course of a telephone conversation.
As Attorney General Francis Biddle said later: ``I do not think he
was much concerned with the gravity or implications of this step.
He was never theoretical about things. What must be done to defend
the country must be done.''
</P>
<P>
   A nation that prides itself on the principle of civilian control
of the military should recognize that concern for civil liberties
is as much the job of the President as the courts. If it is, as
Rehnquist suggests, the task of public opinion to insure that both
branches take these issues seriously, then he can be congratulated
for providing in a very readable form some of the material they
will need for the responsible fulfillment of that duty.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Waldron is the Maurice and Hilda Friedman Professor of
Law at Columbia University. His latest book is the forthcoming
``Law and Disagreement.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
