</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1115 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CONVERSION-10     01-20 1627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CONVERSION-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE CONVERSION
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Aharon Appelfeld. Translated by Jeffrey M. Green.
</P>
<P>
   228 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Schocken Books. $22.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; BIRTHRIGHT FOR SALE
</P>
<P>
   BY LARRY WOLFF
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you feel that the empire is disintegrating?'' Karl, the
apostate protagonist of Aharon Appelfeld's novel ``The
Conversion,'' asks. The declining empire in which he lives is the
Hapsburg empire of Austria-Hungary, one that in fact would
disintegrate at the end of World War I. In the opening chapter Karl
converts from Judaism to Roman Catholicism, intending to advance
his career in municipal public service in his provincial Austrian
hometown, remote from the metropolitan sophistications of
fin-de-siecle Vienna. In church at Karl's conversion are the many
other converts who have preceded him, and who welcome him into his
new identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spell of the ceremony gradually faded, and everyone grew
hungry. A ceremony like this is no more than a tonsillectomy, one
of his childhood friends had told him. But Karl now felt
differently: as if his legs were weighed down.'' There is a
reception afterwards, with pastries to satisfy everyone's hunger,
but nothing to quell the inner uneasiness, the postoperative
trauma, that Karl now experiences and that will haunt him for the
rest of the novel. Appelfeld's drama of a distintegrating identity
in the context of a disintegrating empire confronts the reader with
the force of a familiar nightmare, akin to those of Kafka, himself
a bureaucrat in Hapsburg Prague, who actually lived through the
imperial collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Appelfeld was born in Czernowitz, in the former Hapsburg border
province of Bukovina. The city belonged to Romania after World War
I, to the Soviet Union after World War II, and today is part of an
independent Ukraine. Yet Czernowitz remained a Hapsburg town even
after the fall of the Hapsburgs, and the city's German-Jewish
culture was powerful enough to produce perhaps the greatest
midcentury German poet, Paul Celan. In fact Appelfeld was born on
the same street in Czernowitz where Celan lived in the 1930's.
Deported as a child to a concentration camp in Transnistria,
Appelfeld survived, escaped and went to Palestine after the war; he
has lived in Israel for the past 50 years and writes in Hebrew. He
has been well known to an international literary public since the
translation into English in 1980 of his brilliant novel ``Badenheim
1939,'' about an Austrian resort where Viennese Jews frivolously
delude themselves as they await deportation to Poland. ``The
Conversion,'' like ``Badenheim 1939,'' pursues the themes of
self-delusion and inevitable disaster, envisioning a world of
Austrian Jews who can not clearly recognize the fact that in
Austria they have no choice but to be Jews, who fool themselves
with the semblance of assimilation or the expedience of conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Appelfeld, together with Gregor von Rezzori, the author of
``Memoirs of an Anti-Semite,'' who also came from Bukovina, may
count as the last of the great Hapsburg writers. Robert Musil, who
may have been the greatest of all, scatologically called the empire
``Kakania'' in his epic masterpiece ``The Man Without Qualities''
and reflected on the violence of national rivalries there: ``It was
nothing more than the fact that every human being's dislike of
every other human being's attempts to get on -- a dislike in which
today we are all agreed --in that country crystallized earlier,
assuming the form of a sublimated ceremonial that might have become
of greater importance if its evolution had not been prematurely cut
short by catastrophe.'' In Appelfeld's novel the ceremony of
conversion appears as a futile attempt to evade the crystallized
dislike between Jews and Christians in Austria, and to escape the
imminently catastrophic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon there won't be any Jews left,'' an anonymous Christian in
the town says. ``Father Merser is baptizing them one after the
other. But I don't trust them. A Jew, even after he's been
baptized, is still a Jew.'' An unidentified Jew from another town
comments to Karl: ``Many Jews lived there once. Now only my wife
and me. All of them converted. It's difficult to live among
converts. They stare at you all the time.'' The double choruses of
Christians and Jews are similarly perplexed, unpersuaded and
repulsed by the religious gesture of the converts, who are left
with an awkward sense of their own alienation. ``At first the other
converts were pleased that Karl had converted. But over the years
he observed that they seldom showed themselves in public,
preferring to lead their lives in seclusion. They were never eager
to meet with childhood friends.'' The good-natured Christian madam
of a brothel disapproves of conversion, and tells Karl: ``Jews
should stay Jewish. That's the right thing for them.'' Translated
from the Hebrew by Jeffrey M. Green into terse, precise, sometimes
oracular prose, Appelfeld's fiction has some of the solemn tone of
biblical parable.
</P>
<P>
   Karl's conscience and imagination are provoked by the figures of
his old Aunt Franzi, once a scandalous cabaret singer, and her
friend Elsa Ring, once a glamorous actress of the demimonde. These
two women had belonged to the wider world of theatrical culture
centered on Vienna. Aunt Franzi had charmed an aristocratic
relative of the Emperor, while Elsa Ring had been admired on the
stage by Stefan Zweig. Karl attends the funeral of his Aunt Franzi,
and remembers uncomfortably that, in spite of her worldliness, she
always despised apostate Jews: ``Her love for her tribe was a
fierce love, quirky perhaps, but constant. She had changed her
lovers like dresses, but her love for her people was solid and
unwavering. If anyone spoke ill of the Jews or made accusations
against them, she would immediately rise up like a mighty
fortress.'' Elsa Ring had been no less proud, but in extreme old
age she began to receive visits from Father Merser, and eventually
she succumbed to his ineluctable invitations and insinuations. One
day the church bells rang: ``Then the truth struck like lightning:
it was Elsa Ring, or rather what was left of her, sitting in the
narrow wheelchair wrapped in a brown blanket. She was being pushed
by Father Merser along the street that led directly to the great
Church of St. George.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-CONVERSION-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: St. George.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the novel takes place in the claustrophobic setting of
Karl's provincial town, where church bells keep announcing new
conversions. In the final chapters, however, Karl deludes himself
into thinking he can find refuge in his mother's native village,
somewhere in the Carpathian mountains, maybe in Bukovina, though
the novel's Hapsburg geography remains vague. He discovers some of
the simple virtues of village Judaism, but also, in the end, in a
scene of apocalyptic siege, the savage violence of village
anti-Semitism. The fictionally elaborated Hapsburg empire sometimes
takes on some of the semimythological resonance of the embattled
empire in J. M. Coetzee's ``Waiting for the Barbarians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Conversion'' is at once a historical novel about the
Austrian past and an allegorical analysis of the significance of
religious identity, addressing issues that Appelfeld sees as still
relevant at the end of the 20th century. Written for the Israeli
public, and perhaps for the American public as well, his novel
seems to endorse the argument of the emphatic madam, ``Jews should
stay Jewish.'' The profoundly insightful essays of the intellectual
historian Carl Schorske suggest a more intricate concept of
relations between Jewish and Catholic cultural perspectives in
Austria at the turn of the century, illuminating also the case of
the empire's most renowned convert, Gustav Mahler. His baptism
helped make it possible for him to assume the post of director of
the Vienna Opera in 1897 but did not protect him from the nasty
denunciations of anti-Semitic reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   Magnus Dawison was in the cast when Mahler was conducting
Wagner's ``Lohengrin'' in Prague in 1899, and Dawison, who had
trained to be a synagogue cantor before becoming an opera singer,
took the opportunity to sing something in Hebrew for Mahler. ``I
sang with all my heart and soul,'' Dawison recalled. ``I put in all
the Jewish Weltschmerz, but also all the meaning of the words. The
master listened. And as I came to the end . . . he whispered in a
dry voice: 'Yes, that is religious! That's how I heard it as a
child, sung by the old prayer-leader in the village synagogue.' He
sat silent for a while, lost in thought. Suddenly he sat down at
the piano and began to play. To improvise. I heard phrase for
phrase the melody I had used. . . . And I sat spellbound, thinking
only how much our religious worship would have gained if only he,
the great man, had not turned away from it and from all that he
regarded as a frustrating burden.'' This account suggests that
Mahler felt he had lost something in his alienation from Judaism.
Appelfeld's novel, however, seems to say that the convert, cut off
from his own childhood, has lost everything.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Larry Wolff, a professor of European history at Boston College,
is the author of ``Postcards From the End of the World: Child Abuse
in Freud's Vienna.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
