<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1116 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NY     01-20 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
 BY SCOTT VEALE
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 A STONE OF THE HEART
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Tom Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Methodist University, $12.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   An overweight 14-year-old boy, starved for affection and trying
to stay afloat in a dysfunctional Irish-American household in
Queens in 1961, seeks refuge in Roger Maris's pursuit of the
home-run record. In 1990 our reviewer, Hilma Wolitzer, called this
a ``compact and affecting first novel.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEHIND THE OVAL OFFICE: GETTING REELECTED AGAINST ALL ODDS
</P>
<P>
   By Dick Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance, $16.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's former adviser tracks the arc of his own
career, giving plenty of attention to the mechanics of polling and
policy making, as well as the overwhelming influence of money and
television in Presidential politics. This curious artifact has been
updated with a new introduction and the weekly briefing papers
given to the White House by the author and other political
consultants during the 1996 campaign (and later subpoenaed by the
Justice Department). Morris ``has written an account that future
historians of the Clinton Presidency will not be able to ignore,''
James B. Stewart wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HEALING
</P>
<P>
   By Gayl Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon, $12 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Narrated by a faith healer and former rock star manager, this
funny novel leans on free association to explore the power of faith
to banish violence and paranoia. Last year in these pages, Valerie
Sayers praised the ``gradual building of connections and insights
that culminates in a giddy outpouring of language.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A PRAYER FOR THE CITY
</P>
<P>
   By Buzz Bissinger.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage, $15 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   A journalist with extraordinary access tells the inside story of
Philadelphia's remarkable Mayor, Ed Rendell, whose drive and
honesty helped restore hope and fiscal soundness to a city on the
edge of collapse. Last year our reviewer, Robert Fishman, said this
``full-scale portrait of a struggling metropolis . . . brings to
mind such classics of urban reportage and analysis as J. Anthony
Lukas's 'Common Ground.' '' Miami, by Joan Didion (Vintage
International, $12), is a more impressionistic account of an
American city, dwelling on the Cuban exile community and the
shadowy links between the Bay of Pigs disaster and events like
Watergate and the Kennedy assassination. ``The world Miss Didion
describes in beautifully evocative prose is . . . a world of menace
and elliptical connections,'' James Chace wrote here in 1987.
Dallas Public and Private: Aspects of an American City, by Warren
Leslie (Southern Methodist University, $14.95), was first published
after John F. Kennedy's murder and seeks to explain a city whose
mix of extreme conservatism, religious expression and political
excess made it a place where nasty things were bound to happen.
This study, which includes a new foreword and preface, ``is a good
deal more than a revealing, a valuable and a careful book,'' George
Fuermann said here in 1964. ``It is also a courageous one.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PERON NOVEL
</P>
<P>
   By Tomas Eloy Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Helen Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage International, $14 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   This Argentine novel imagines the life of the strongman Juan
Peron, particularly his 18 years in exile and his ill-fated return
to power in 1973. The book ``is a brilliant image of a national
psychosis,'' Jay Cantor wrote here in 1988. Tales From the Blue
ArchiveS, by Lawrence Thornton (Bantam, $13.95), is the last of
three dream-driven novels by the author revolving around
Argentina's ``dirty war.'' It focuses on a woman's search for her
grandsons, who were among the ``disappeared,'' and on what happens
when she finally finds them. The tale ``blends the mundane violence
of recent Latin American politics with the high tragedy of
Elizabethan drama,'' Robert Houston wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COUNT ME OUT
</P>
<P>
   By Russell James.
</P>
<P>
   Foul Play/Norton, $10 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   When one of the robbers of an armored car takes off with all the
loot, the mastermind of the heist tries to track him down through
the crook's ex-boxer brother and his 8-year-old daughter. In 1997
our reviewer, Marilyn Stasio, admired this British mystery for
``the depth, as well as the darkness'' of its insights.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HISTORY OF JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   By Ted Gioia.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford University, $15.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   This concise, accessible overview covers jazz from its roots in
slavery through jazz-rock fusion and beyond. In 1997 our reviewer,
Peter Keepnews, said that despite its occasional omissions and
lapses, ``the book is peppered with pithy and thoughtful
observations.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRESPASSING: MY SOJOURN IN THE HALLS OF PRIVILEGE
</P>
<P>
   By Gwendolyn M. Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $11 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   A well-off black lawyer tells how she rode the fast track to
success in corporate America, and how the pressures of racial
tokenism finally caused her to hop off. In these pages in 1997,
Deborah E. McDowell called this an ``engagingly written and fluidly
paced'' memoir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME AND AWAY
</P>
<P>
   By Joanne Meschery.
</P>
<P>
   University of California, $13.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   During the gulf war, a California woman struggles to balance her
growing political awareness with a troubled marriage and other
personal crises. The novel ``manages to deal sensitively with
serious issues,'' Constance Decker Thompson wrote here in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
