<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BR     01-20 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cover of POSADA'S BROADSHEETS: Mexican Popular Imagery,
1890-1910 (University of New Mexico, cloth, $50; paper, $24.95)
shows an engraving of a crazed man savagely chewing on a baby's
body while a winged dragonlike creature looks down menacingly from
the air. This surreal image was but one of many such gruesome
pictures designed by the Mexican artist Jose Guadalupe Posada
(1852-1913) and created for Antonio Vanegas Arroyo, a leading
publisher of broadsheets -- single-page periodicals -- that
reported on lurid crimes, executions, bullfights, cultural events
and politics. A precursor of today's tabloids, broadsheets were
cheaply printed and widely distributed as news and entertainment to
Mexico City's urban masses. They were the most ephemeral of printed
matter, bought, read and tossed away -- even Posada did not save
the majority of his works. But ``taken together, they form a
'people's history' of life in Mexico City during the years
bracketing the turn of the 20th century,'' writes the book's
author, Patrick Frank, who teaches art history at the University of
Colorado, Boulder. Posada was a hugely prolific commercial artist,
designing newspaper advertisements, product labels and magazine
illustrations; his work and import were rediscovered in the 1920's
by the Mexican political muralists Diego Rivera and Jose Clemente
Orozco and the French printmaker Jean Charlot. Posada, whose
imagery is reminiscent of Goya, is now considered one of Mexico's
most acerbic commentators and satirists. Although the prints are
mistakenly reproduced in halftone, which diminishes the strength of
the artist's powerful black line, ``Posada's Broadsheets''
nonetheless offers an insightful analysis of both the art and the
history of the time when it was created. _ STEVEN HELLER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ORDINARY PARADISE
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Furman.
</P>
<P>
   Winedale, $22.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   When Minnie Furman died at the age of 47 of ovarian cancer, she
left behind a husband and three daughters. The family had coped
with her impending death by pretending she was not seriously ill.
Laura Furman, then 13, and her sisters were never allowed to
express their grief. But ``Ordinary Paradise'' shows how a
devastating loss, acknowledged or not, can seep through the family
psyche. Furman, whose novels include ``Tuxedo Park,'' responded to
her mother's death and her new stepmother's theatrical indifference
by trying to sleep away her depression, cutting her finger with a
razor blade, attempting suicide after a failed romance; a disease
contracted from another lover left her unable to bear children.
Furman writes a dreamy, imagistic prose. By turns emotionally muted
and fiercely angry, she is forthright about the possible
distortions of memory. However, for all its honesty and heroic
appeal, the memoir feels muffled, as if a layer of story lies
hidden. How did she lead herself from loneliness to a happy
marriage, from numbing depression to stories that would earn a
Guggenheim fellowship and publication in The New Yorker? _ ANDREA
COOPER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEONARDO'S NEPHEW
</P>
<P>
   Essays on Art and Artists.
</P>
<P>
   By James Fenton.
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Reading James Fenton's essays is not unlike being taken on a
tour by an erudite but idiosyncratic guide, where detour is not at
all unusual and never beside the point. A fascinating, multilayered
essay on the sculptor Aristide Maillol, for example, offers a brief
history of the Cour Napoleon -- that is, the space at the heart of
the Louvre -- as well as Fenton's thoughts on what currently
occupies it, I. M. Pei's pyramid. ``Nobody who has glanced at this
space can possibly feel that this solution will last forever,'' he
writes. ``To believe this would be to subscribe to some theory of
the death of the history of taste.'' Fenton, the Professor of
Poetry at Oxford, is also a first-rate sleuth. In ``Seurat and the
Sewers'' he investigates, among other matters, the art historian T.
J. Clark's charge that the boys in Seurat's painting ``The
Bathers'' were bathing at a place in the Seine where undiluted
sewage was emptied (they were not). Other subjects in ``Leonardo's
Nephew'' include Freud's collection of antique statuettes, Egyptian
funerary portraits and Joseph Cornell. These essays educate,
enlighten, surprise and thrill, unfailingly.'' _ ROBIN LIPPINCOTT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANIEL DEFOE
</P>
<P>
   The Life and Strange, Surprising Adventures.
</P>
<P>
   By Richard West.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll &AMP; Graf, $26 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   This lively book rambles across the England of Daniel Defoe
(1660-1731), that realm of fops, rogues, merchants, sailors,
unctuous divines and fugitive pamphleteers. Richard West, a British
journalist, tracks Defoe's career by the books that he left
scattered along the way. Sometimes, West points out, Defoe's
imagination betrayed him. He squandered his wife's dowry and lost
heavily in the business ventures he undertook ``as wholesaler of
stockings, trader in wine and tobacco, breeder of civet cats,
promoter of diving bells or maker of bricks and pantiles.'' Defoe's
Protestant loyalties embroiled him in nasty religious quarrels. His
satirical pamphlet ``The Shortest Way With Dissenters,'' with its
straight-faced proposal for jailing and hanging Nonconformist
congregations, was taken seriously; the government hunted down the
author. The clearest surviving portrait of Defoe comes not from an
engraved frontispiece but from the notice placing a price on his
head. After pleading guilty to charges of ``seditious libel,''
Defoe spent time in Newgate Prison, the same grim jail frequented
by Moll Flanders. Hailing Defoe's travelogue ``Tour of Great
Britain'' as his masterpiece, West maddeningly devotes 84 pages to
a town-by-town precis, while shoehorning ``Robinson Crusoe'' into
one short chapter. Without posturing, this traditional
life-and-times approach raises critical questions about a writer
who packed his books with partisan judgments but whose own life can
only be reconstructed from asides in those same books. _ ALLEN D.
BOYER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEARNING A TRADE
</P>
<P>
   A Craftsman's Notebooks, 1955-1997.
</P>
<P>
   By Reynolds Price.
</P>
<P>
   Duke University, $34.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The novelist, poet and playwright Reynolds Price laments that
through four decades of cultivating novice writers at Duke, he has
failed to convince them of ``the absolute necessity of discovering
one's own best self-tailored means of working daily.'' Try not to
write, he has famously counseled wannabes; ``if you can not do it,
don't do it.'' A living lesson in vocational compulsion, Price has
published his working notebooks from 42 years to illustrate how
``satisfactions'' can arise from incalculable time spent ``in a
harmless (and conceivably benign) form of making.'' Price has
worked out countless fictions within his ``handy debating room,''
where a given page may echo the anxiety of influence (``I burn to
do as fine a thing'' as Joyce's novella ``The Dead''), recall a
talk with Eudora Welty at Schrafft's or appoint his own
self-spurring tasks like ``Spin a sequence -- any sequence -- just
to see where you go,'' or wrestle with the problem of ``how to
suggest that life keeps on'' between scenes ``without giving the
impression that everybody simply slept or was unconscious.''
``Learning a Trade'' moves along appealingly because, while Price
pulls deep and often from his own memories, he never confuses a
notebook with a journal or diary -- forms he finds to be ``a
repetitive bore at the end of a day.'' Rather, his life is ``all in
the work,'' he once claimed. ``Not a secret spared.'' _ RENEE TURSI
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
