<HEADER>
A1118 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEF     01-20 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: FICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 CONFESSIONS OF A LATE NIGHT TALK SHOW HOST
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Autobiography of Larry Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   By Garry Shandling with David Rensin.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The publicity over the final curtain of ``Seinfeld'' unfairly
obscured the simultaneous exit, after six seasons, of ``The Larry
Sanders Show,'' a comedy series so funny and risque as to make
``Seinfeld'' look positively bland. A glimpse behind the scenes at
an imaginary talk show, ``Larry Sanders'' starred its own creator,
Garry Shandling, as the neurotic host and featured celebrities
playing themselves as his guests in a mind-bending mixture of
fiction and reality. Now Larry, predictably bored and depressed in
retirement, has written an ``autobiography.'' We are told all about
his childhood -- lots of abuse, natch, but at least not of the
sexual variety. ``I had to wait until my first marriage to
experience sexual abuse,'' Larry confesses, ``and then there was
plenty of it.'' That marriage, by the way, went nowhere fast. ``If
only I could have loved her as much as I loved the audience,''
Larry mourns. ``Or maybe if there could have been 200 of her.''
Larry also reveals how he clawed his way to the top, lists the many
famous women he has slept with and gossips about the show's guests.
Sadly, the Larry who narrates this book is not the ``real''
backstage Larry -- whiny and passive-aggressive -- but merely Larry
the stand-up monologist, so the autobiography lacks the dimension
and bite of the television show. Still, for ``Larry Sanders'' fans
who haven't stopped craving that old Sunday night fix, even
watered-down Larry is a treat, and a lot better than no Larry at
all. _ BROOKE ALLEN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RING AROUND THE MOON
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Burnett Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow, $24 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Mary Burnett Smith's second novel is, at least in part, a
meditation on fatherhood as seen through the eyes of her narrator,
a black woman named Amy Beale, who is looking back to her childhood
and particularly to the year when she turned 11 and witnessed the
meltdown of her parents' marriage. Young Amy is a precocious tomboy
living with her family just outside Philadelphia on the eve of
World War II. Initially, her days are consumed with adolescent
concerns: the nappiness of her hair, her budding friendship with a
white girl, her affection for her brothers, her mother's weariness
and the increasingly meddling attitude of her aunts. Race and class
conflicts erupt regularly between neighbors and extended family
members in Amy's small town, but as time passes she discovers that
the most volatile member of the community is her own father.
Smith's strength as a writer lies in the relaxed complexity of her
characters: the bad aspects of good women and the wise thoughts of
foolish men are utterly plausible. Smith also succeeds in capturing
the psychology of children: Amy views every event in her life as a
direct response to her own thoughts and actions. In this way,
``Ring Around the Moon'' is transformed from a sketch of a father
to a portrait of the daughter who reluctantly bears witness to his
failings. _ MAGGIE GALEHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOOK OF MEMORIES
</P>
<P>
   By Ana Maria Shua.
</P>
<P>
   University of New Mexico, cloth, $32.50; paper, $16.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The notion of memory as ``not only cerebral but emerging from
the heart'' is ``a rabbinical creation,'' writes Ilan Stavans,
editor of New Mexico's Jewish Latin America series, in the
introduction to its latest volume. Ana Maria Shua's eccentric comic
novel concerns a family of Polish Jews who emigrate to Argentina
during World War I. As translated by Dick Gerdes, ``The Book of
Memories'' gives a fictionalized account of Shua's own family's
life in Buenos Aires, drawing on the recollections of its many
members. Yet it is Grandfather Gedalia who takes center stage
through most of the narrative, whether we're hearing his own views
or merely hearing about him. In this, the novel draws on a classic
Yiddish convention, which Stavans describes as ``the unfolding of a
story while two guys talk.'' Here the voices belong to two
anonymous descendants who contradict each other about virtually
everything. ``I've . . . heard that one Sunday afternoon he took
Silvester on the trolley and then bought him a ham sandwich,'' one
reports of the patriarch. To which the other replies, ``Grandfather
Gedalia never ate pig's meat because it was against his religion.''
Back and forth the conversation flies: ``Grandfather Gedalia never
ate pig's meat in public.'' ``Grandfather Gedalia was a pig.'' At
times, though, Shua tries too hard to justify such contradictory
viewpoints, putting a strain on her lively characterizations. _
PAULA FRIEDMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NECESSARY FICTIONS
</P>
<P>
   By Barbara Croft.
</P>
<P>
   University of Pittsburgh, $22.50 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in this curiously unaffecting collection of short
fiction is unhappy, and the reasons are always very clear. While
set in the present or near-present, the world of ``Necessary
Fictions'' is an oddly retrograde one in which men are held
accountable for the happiness of women and children, and women are
unable to assume responsibility for their own lives. We meet women
who studied art, but settled for money; a woman who wanted to teach
English, but married a self-absorbed workingman. Men are unhappy
because they lack education or because their fathers had no respect
for their education or because they are alcoholics or because they
are Vietnam veterans. Women who try to be strong die of cancer.
While technically proficient, the stories are unconvincing because
their plotting relies so frequently on such cliches. _ GLORIA
ROHMANN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ESSENCE OF THE THING
</P>
<P>
   By Madeleine St. John.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll &AMP; Graf, $22 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   When Nicola's lover suddenly asks her to vacate the London
apartment they have (she thinks) happily shared, she falls into an
emotional maelstrom most readers will recognize. Very quickly, her
initial disbelief turns to self-accusatory scrutiny, then grief, as
Jonathan abruptly declares, ``This relationship is getting us
nowhere. I don't love you.'' Predictably enough, time, work and
friends are the crucial elements in Nicola's recovery. And it is
only after she has secured a glamorous new job in a different town
and reconciled herself to her loss that Jonathan realizes how empty
his life has become and asks to be taken back. In this novel, which
was a finalist for the 1997 Booker Prize, Madeleine St. John shapes
what might have been a bathetic story into a brisk, sophisticated
and artful narrative buoyed by an ironic use of the religious
imagery of hell, salvation and resurrection. (A friend likens
Nicola's failed affair to ``an Act of God in its suddenness, its
comprehensiveness, its magnitude.'') Through these associations,
St. John convincingly illustrates that ``nothing is as serious as
love,'' even when the misunderstandings and discord between the
sexes appear to be God's little joke on the human race. _ GARDNER
MCFALL
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
