</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1134 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIGHT-MOVIE-LADN     01-20 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIGHT-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW YOU SENSE IT, NOW YOU DON'T
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; If, as the philosophers say, eyes are the windows
to the soul; and if, as many actors say, their job is to project
their innermost feelings onto the screen, imagine how tough it was
to make a movie like ``At First Sight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First Sight'' examines the difficult relationship between a
New York architect played by Mira Sorvino and Val Kilmer as a blind
masseur who temporarily regains his sight. Based on a true story by
Oliver Sacks, the doctor-writer who also provided the source
material for the film ``Awakenings,'' ``Sight'' keeps its focus on
the couple's problems rather than the more clinical aspects of the
blind man's condition.
</P>
<P>
   That established, falling in love without the requisite longing
gazes into one another's eyes was quite the acting challenge.
</P>
<P>
   For one of them, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of work, very difficult,'' says Chatsworth native
Kilmer, who has impersonated everyone from rock demon Jim Morrison
to Batman to Moses (in the animated ``Prince of Egypt''). ``I had
to make his whole persona, his whole vibe, seem effortless, because
there are a whole lot of things that take effort when you're blind,
but people like Virgil don't want people to know are an effort for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilmer did have expert help. A longtime neighbor in Santa Fe,
N.M., is a blinded Vietnam veteran. A blind masseur from the New
York suburbs also provided invaluable technical advice (``he was
always lobbying for more scenes with the dog,'' Kilmer notes. ``As
you can imagine, it's a very important relationship''). And Shirl
and Barbara Jennings, the real-life couple on whom the film's story
is based, visited the New York location both before and during
production last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bulk of the work was necessarily internal. And
sometimes traumatizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took months of practice,'' Kilmer reveals. ``I spent a lot
of time with my eyes closed in my room, or out on the street with
opaque contacts on so I couldn't see. I'd do that alone and with
friends, and it was actually more frustrating with friends. They'd
say, `Watch out!' They don't say watch out for what.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I was out alone, I'd find people would help, but they
also didn't. It's a very deep experience to just stand there on a
street and say to someone you know is near to you, `Excuse me, can
you point me uptown?' and they don't answer. They just don't want
to bother.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilmer's hard work made things easy for Sorvino ... at least up
to the point where her well-meaning Amy convinces Virgil to undergo
radical sight-restoring surgery, which leads to a whole new set of
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really seemed like Val was blind when we were playing the
scenes,'' Oscar winner Sorvino (``Mighty Aphrodite'') reports.
``His face responded to what I was saying, but his eyes would not
give me any flicker of response when I was looking right into them.
It must have been very hard for him, but it was great for me. If
you look, you'll see that my physical behavior is very different in
those scenes. I act like a person who's not being watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a certain way, the character is most vulnerable at those
points. All of her defenses are down because she's not feeling
judged or observed or anything. She's just feeling listened to.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's a powerfully seductive notion. And exactly what
director Irwin Winkler was aiming for, at least in the first,
falling-in-love part of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to present a blind man who was somebody an
audience might, in some way, feel pity for,'' says Winkler, a
successful producer (``Rocky,'' ``Raging Bull'') who lately has
turned to directing (``The Net,'' ``Guilty by Suspicion''). ``Also,
we're doing a romance, so I had to cast somebody that women in the
theater could consider having an affair with. I think doing that
with a blind man takes a bit with most women; but if he looks like
Val Kilmer, it might not take that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Winkler had heard the stories, though. Several directors,
including ``Batman Forever's'' Joel Schumacher and ``The Island of
Dr. Moreau's'' John Frankenheimer, publicly have accused Kilmer of
wanton misbehavior on their sets. But Winkler checked with his
close friend and Kilmer's ``Heat'' co-star Robert De Niro, who
vouched for the younger actor's talent and professionalism. Ditto
``Heat'' director Michael Mann, another Winkler pal.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I spent some time with Val and we got along great,''
Winkler says. ``He has been terrific, and we've become very close
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordial as the atmosphere on the set may have been, the movie
had to chart the deterioration of Amy and Virgil's relationship
after he regains his vision and finds it almost impossible to
function in a world of assaultive new sensations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have only been 20 cases recorded in the last 200 years
of somebody having gone from sightlessness to sight,'' Winkler
explains. ``And most of the time it ended up tragically. There are
several cases cited in the Oliver Sacks piece where people
committed suicide. They just couldn't deal with a world that was so
violent to them, so difficult to suddenly be thrown into.''
</P>
<P>
   That, fortunately, was not the case with Shirl Jennings, whose
vision gradually faded away again after his operation. Naturally,
the interim was marked by unique stresses, and they formed the core
of ``At First Sight's'' drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was even harder after Virgil gains his sight,'' Kilmer
explains. ``The premise of this story couldn't be more simple and
complex: What if you fall in love at first sight and you can't see?
This is a true story, and a true love story. But even though it's
her love and belief that leads him through this experience of
seeing, at the same time she's trying to make him something that
he's not. That's one of his points of view; he's right and he's not
right about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Telling this fascinating medical story, but with the emphasis
really on the human relations between the two people, appealed to
me,'' Sorvino adds. ``And on their flawed personalities, rather
than a kind of ideal, Hollywood-esque situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to make a special effects movie; I always felt
this was a very personal story,'' Winkler confirms. ``I didn't want
to make a movie where, every time when it's Virgil's point of view,
something is out of focus or the dimension is different or
something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he was cured from the eye disease that he had, I wanted
Virgil to see normally. He sees exactly what we see; the difference
is, he doesn't know what he's seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad metaphor for troubled relationships everywhere. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
