A1135 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKS-TV-LADN     01-20 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKS-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TURKS` A COP FAMILY WITH ONE BAD APPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; If you watch tonight's premiere of ``Turks,'' you
are more than likely to have this reaction: ``Haven't I seen this
before?''
</P>
<P>
   The CBS police drama about a Chicago family is predictable and
often cookie-cutter.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be surprised if your second thought is: ``This isn't
half-bad.''
</P>
<P>
   What separates this from many like it, including ``Trinity''
(which already has been taken off the fall schedule), is William
Devane (``Knots Landing''). The television veteran is undoubtedly a
star of the medium. He oozes with charisma, and in this vehicle,
with a close-cropped hairdo, Devane grounds the show.
</P>
<P>
   He spends a lot of time working and drinking with the boys after
work, leaving his wife lonely. This causes her to turn to the
church for companionship. Their three children are Joey, a
no-nonsense cop paired with an African-American partner; Mike, a
husband and father who is struggling to make sergeant; and Pauly,
the brainy college kid who gets mixed up with some bad characters.
</P>
<P>
   The writing is loaded with cliches and the show is predictable.
One of the story lines was almost lifted directly from the
``Trinity'' opener. Pauly not only gets mixed up with the wrong
crowd, he drives the getaway van at a warehouse robbery only to be
caught and given a stern warning by his own brother, Joey. This
comes back to haunt Joey.
</P>
<P>
   The best scene of the pilot episode comes before the credits,
when two thugs learn the hard way that you don't rob a cop hangout.
</P>
<P>
   At its core, ``Turks'' smoothly shifts from a family drama to a
police drama. This is an emotional brood, who all live on the same
block and yell at one other constantly. (Their poor neighbors.)
</P>
<P>
   They all get together at the end of the first episode for a
pickup game of basketball (which, incidentally, is how the first
episode of ``Trinity'' started).
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you've seen it before. But, hey, you've seen worse. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1507EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
