<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALKIN-RADIO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH-LANGUAGE STATION CONTINUE TO DOMINATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Three Spanish-language stations took the top
places in the latest quarterly ratings, illustrating the continued
dominance of Spanish programming in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican regional music KSCA-FM (101.9) placed first with 6.9
percent of the listening audience ages 12 and over. In second place
for the ratings period covering Sept. 24 to Dec. 16 was Spanish
adult-contemporary radio KLVE-FM (107.5) with a share of 6.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tied for third place with a 4.1 percent share was Mexican
regional music station KLAX-FM (97.9), which nearly doubled its
audience share in one year, and hip-hop KPWR-FM (105.9). The latter
station _ known as Power 106 _ grabbed the highest ranking among
English-language stations, although its audience consists largely
of English-speaking Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   Among talk stations, KFI-AM (640) is tops by far, moving up to
fifth place and a 3.9 percent share in the fall, while KABC-AM
(790) dropped to 14th place with a 2.4 percent audience share, its
lowest position in nearly a decade. The retooled KABC tied with
increasingly popular talk outlet KLSX-FM (97.1).
</P>
<P>
   Newly revamped Glendale-based talker KIEV-AM (870) jumped to
28th place and a 0.8 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   In the early hours, KFI's Bill Handel is circling KLSX's Howard
Stern, the top English-language morning personality. Handel edged
up from a 3.8 percent share to a 4.3 average quarter-hour rating.
Stern dropped from a 5.1 to a 4.7 audience share.
</P>
<P>
   But the numero uno morning personality in the area was KSCA's
Renan Almendarez Coello, who extended his lead and gained a
stunning 10.5 percent share in the fall, while KLVE's Pepe Baretto
placed second with a 7 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   Top-40 KIIS-FM (102.7), meanwhile, continues to dominate as the
top station for cumulative listening, a position the Burbank
station has held for six consecutive Arbitron quarterly surveys.
</P>
<P>
   In the sought-after 25-to-54 ratings race, KLSX afternoon-drive
talker Tom Leykis is No. 1 with a 3.0 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   EXIT THE NASTYMAN: Overnight host the Nastyman exits KLSX while
ex-Power 106 promotions director John Boyle and assistant Jeff
Carroll take over the shift. ... Ex-San Diego pop-alternative disc
jockey Greg Simms succeeds Larry Morgan middays at KYSR-FM (98.7).
... Sports talk KXTA-AM (1150) hires radio newcomer Derrick Hall as
John Ireland's morning co-host. Hall was previously public
relations director for the Dodgers. ... KABC afternoon driver Larry
Elder will soon be syndicated by the ABC Radio Network. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
