A1149 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAREERS-HNS &LR;      01-20 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO COPE WITH LOSING A JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last year was the most brutal year of the decade
for job cuts nationwide, according to the outplacement firm of
Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas. Last year's 677,795 cuts surpassed
the worst previous carnage, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   If you have been laid off for the first time _ assuming you
don't work in the high-tech sector _ you may feel a sense of
foreboding. Take heart and try these steps:
</P>
<P>
   _ Take time to grieve, but not to wallow. Losing a job is one of
the most stressful things in life. It's perfectly natural to feel
hurt and angry, to think you were cheated out of something you
deserved.
</P>
<P>
   So cry, scream, get counseling, take a vacation, do whatever it
takes (within those darned moral and legal boundaries, of course).
Then move on. Otherwise those negative feelings will come across in
a job interview.
</P>
<P>
   _ Open the wound. Understand why you lost your job and what it
means for your future. Don't be too quick to let yourself off the
hook.
</P>
<P>
   If your plant closed or your company went out of business, you
might be in a dying industry. If you stay in it, be prepared to be
laid off again.
</P>
<P>
   If you were wiped out in a merger, was everyone in your company
dumped? The industry is consolidating; expect more cuts. Were all
the people in your classification let go? Maybe your skills are
becoming obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part. If some peers didn't get dumped, why
did you? If you made a mistake, that's all right. We all do. But if
you don't acknowledge it, you won't learn from it.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful about falling back on excuses like:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My boss was a jerk.'' That boss is history, so it doesn't
really matter if he was a jerk or Mother Teresa.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A lot of middle managers got dumped.'' Yeah, but some were
kept. What did they have that you didn't? Be objective. Would you
have kept the job if you had an MBA or better technical skills?
Were you too tough or too easy? Is your area of expertise too
narrow? If you don't get more training, will it be impossible to
land another middle management job?
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It was age discrimination.'' Then sue. But before you call a
lawyer, ask yourself one question: Do you have skills that a person
10 years younger doesn't have? Forget what the law says and apply
some common sense. If you're 45 and you can't offer an employer
more than a 35-year-old can, something is seriously wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to be out of work for six months. This is for strategic
purposes only. You'll probably get hired long before the six months
are up.
</P>
<P>
   But assume you are out of work the whole time. If all you've
done is hunt for a job in those six months, you'll look less
attractive and more desperate.
</P>
<P>
   You've been given a gift here. Take the six months to build up
your skills and to examine other careers.
</P>
<P>
   Are there consulting projects you could do? How about a
temporary job that expands your skills? Could you do an internship
to help you into a new field? Would a couple of college classes
help? The first thing I would do is learn enough to design my own
Web page. You can teach yourself, it's not rocket science and it
would impress any employer who is not a complete moron.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of businesses are establishing Web pages, but often they
can't or won't spend money on consultants. Don't you think they'd
love a self-starter who knew their field _ whether it's personal
finance or medicine or auto mechanics _ and could also spend a few
hours a month on their Web page?
</P>
<P>
   But that's just my strategy. What's yours?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
