<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1174 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGIOUS-TRUTH-ANSWE     01-20 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGIOUS-TRUTH-ANSWERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THERE'S ONLY ONE TRUTH, WHY ARE THERE SO MANY ANSWERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I recently attended an academic conference where a well-known
neo-conservative historian spent nearly an hour chastising the
audience for being post-modern relativists.
 &HT;    She implored the scholars to seek ``truth'' -- which appeared to
mean recovering a unified and coherent past invested with Christian
theological meaning.
 &HT;    While some of her remarks were interesting, she also appeared
angry and bitter. Without personally knowing her audience, she
attacked the work of some present. She presumed to know the motives
behind their ideas and dismissed them as people without religious
convictions.
 &HT;    Throughout, she urged us to pursue the Truth -- a singular and
objective reality that she obviously understood and we did not.
 &HT;    After her bad-tempered tirade, I returned to my hotel room and
wearily called home. My husband and I chatted and, to cheer me up,
he put our one-year old daughter on the phone.
 &HT;    ``Hi, Emma. This is Mommy.''
 &HT;    ``Hi Omma,'' came the gently tentative reply.
 &HT;    My heart melted. Truth? All the truth I needed to know was in
the sound of that tiny voice.
 &HT;    Unfortunately for most people, truth -- especially religious
truth -- is construed as a set of intellectual propositions. Truth
is ``out there'' waiting to be discovered through science or
philosophy or history. Once found, it will be logical, orderly,
and, above all, clear. Truth will answer all our questions, ease
our doubts and erase all ambiguity.
 &HT;    So it seemed for the speaker. Although she knew nothing of my
faith, I know a little of hers through her written testimony. Once
a secular Marxist feminist, she converted in mid-life to a
traditionalist form of Roman Catholicism. Like many converts, who
take their new faith with a kind of intensity often lacking in
cradle believers, she appeared more Catholic than the pope.
 &HT;    Her life's journey had taken her from one radical truth to
another. She appeared to live in a black-and-white world where
truth is Truth and all else falsehood.
 &HT;    She, of course, is not alone. Around the globe, people are
seeking -- and perhaps finding -- the answer. The impulse to find
the Truth lies behind many political and social crusades as well as
various religious movements termed ``fundamentalism.''
 &HT;    The most obvious question rising from this worldview is: If
there is only one truth, why so many answers? Which truth is
correct if so many people believe different things?
 &HT;    These questions began to trouble Europeans in the 16th century
when a number of Protestant groups split off the medieval Catholic
church. The conundrum of religious diversity led some to reject
truth altogether and ultimately led to relativism and
privatization.
 &HT;    Thus, in the waning years of our century, those of an undogmatic
nature are unwilling to even address truth. ``Many ways to God,''
they insist, ``faith is a personal thing.''
 &HT;    I suspect many people are uncomfortable with either dogmatism or
relativism -- the two options most obvious in our culture or
churches.
 &HT;    There are, however, other ways of understanding truth.
Non-western religions construct truth in non-linear ways. Hence,
most forms of Hinduism and Buddhism avoid these problems. Perhaps
this accounts for their current popularity.
 &HT;    However helpful, most Americans are schooled in western
religions -- particularly Christianity and Judaism. Both faiths
were deeply affected by European ideas of truth and struggle
between dogmatism and relativism.
 &HT;    Although I cannot speak for Judaism as a whole, one Jewish
rabbi, Jesus, proclaimed: ``I am the truth.'' This odd statement
undermines much of what western Christians have thought about
truth. For Jesus, truth was a person -- not an idea, precept, or
doctrine.
 &HT;    Truth is a person?
 &HT;    Jesus pointed out that truth exists in relationship. To know
truth is to embrace another and embark on what theologian Martin
Buber called an ``I-Thou'' relationship. Truth, therefore, is like
all relationships: neither logical nor orderly on strictly
intellectual terms. Truth flourishes in community. Truth is messy,
fluid, and organic.
 &HT;    Truth does not demand intellectual conformity from her audience.
Truth is when people bump up next to each other, live and create
together.
 &HT;    Truth happens when a one-year old recognizes mommy's voice,
acknowledging an intimate connection beyond herself. With her
``hi,'' Emma reached toward a person who was both familiar and yet
unseen in an embryonic act of faith. Such faith is that which
carries us all toward God.
 &HT;    Religious truth is neither dogmatism nor relativism. It exists
outside those categories. It believes many things -- like love and
justice -- to be absolutely true. But it also thrives in life's
jumble of uncertainty and embraces its own limited vision. Therein,
faith is born. It raises questions, creates doubts, and fuels
ambiguity.
 &HT;    And the conference? Throughout, I wished I was with Emma
watching ``Teletubbies'' and learning something really important.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
