<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-STOCKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AIRLINES RIDING HIGH, WHY ARE WALL STREET VIEWS MIXED?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN REED 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jerry Tims doesn't know much about airline
management, but he thinks he knows why U.S. carriers are preparing
to report that they made more money as a group in 1998 than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen the planes so crowded,'' said Tims, chief
executive of Dexide, a Fort Worth-based maker of surgical devices,
who has logged more than 100,000 miles annually for years.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. carriers are flying more paying passengers than at any time
since World War II. And demand, Tims figures, is driving the record
$4.8 billion in profits that major airlines are expected to report
for 1998, excluding onetime events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The planes are so crowded it's getting hard to see the real
benefits of being a Platinum member,'' Tims said, referring to his
elite status in American Airlines' frequent-flier program. ``You
can't hardly buy a coach seat and expect to get bumped into first
class any more, because all the first-class seats are already
filled.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors are jittery about airline stocks, and many
analysts are talking about them in relatively negative terms.
</P>
<P>
   Airline stocks have been bouncing up and down like a plane
flying through turbulence over the past several months. Two weeks
ago, stocks soared 14.6 percent, but they dropped most of those
gains last week.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, some analysts believe, is that the industry is at a
cyclical high and is poised to slip. Labor costs are rising, they
note. And Asia's economic crisis has triggered discounting on
Pacific routes that were once highly profitable.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Northwest and TWA, two carriers struggling for
business, are keeping the lid on domestic leisure fares even though
many airline executives believe they could increase prices 10
percent to 15 percent without running off passengers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it appears as if scheduled capacity increases will
slightly exceed the expected increase in demand this year for the
first time in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Starkman, an analyst for SBC Warburg Dillon Read in New
York, is one who is concerned about a potential squeeze on airline
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that times are going to be bad for the
airlines,'' Starkman said. ``We've just hit a peak. ... And while I
think the downside potential in the event of an economic softening
is not as great as it used to be with this industry, it's still
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Airline executives expressed worries about a potential slowdown
as recently as last fall. They say they are still concerned, but
they are more confident.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Carty, chairman of American Airlines and its parent AMR
Corp., admitted to ``some mild concerns'' last week about increased
capacity and softening demand in some international markets.
</P>
<P>
   But ``demand, especially domestically, continues to be very
strong,'' said Carty, whose Fort Worth-based company is expected to
announce this week that it beat its 1996 profit record of $1
billion by several hundred thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Big corporations that had taken steps to reduce their travel
last fall have regained their confidence in the economy, Carty
said, and are back on the travel bandwagon. Meanwhile, the nearly
insatiable demand for leisure travel continues, at least
domestically, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, U.S. carriers _ when the numbers are tallied _ are
expected to have filled nearly 71 percent of their seats with
paying passengers in 1998, up from 70.35 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The only time that U.S. airlines reported higher load factors
was around World War II, when 88 percent of all seats were filled
at a time that demand was artificially stimulated by government and
military travel.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the industry is reaping the benefits of tough decisions
it made this decade. After the industry's worst downturn in
history, when airlines lost $13 billion in four years, most
carriers sought to regain control of the supply-and-demand equation
by slowing the growth of capacity to below the growth rate in
demand. Last year was the fifth straight that the industry's
capacity grew less than demand for air travel.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the airlines are paying less, adjusted for
inflation, for fuel than at any time in the four decades of jet
travel. The major carriers, which save about $160 million a year
for every 1 cent drop in the average price of fuel, paid about 54
cents a gallon in 1998, down nearly 18 percent from 1997. In the
fourth quarter, jet fuel on the spot market fell as low as 33 cents
a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Mullin, chief executive of Delta Air Lines, which employs
about 5,000 people in North Texas, echoed Carty's sentiments in
public comments last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much better about the economic outlook than I did back
in September,'' he said. This week, Delta reported a record $194
million fourth-quarter profit and a record $1.1 billion profit for
1998, exceeding analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions of airline stocks vary on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts expect a jump in airline stocks this year,
probably after first-quarter figures are released in April, and
they are advising clients to buy now at what they see as relatively
cheap prices.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts are worried.
</P>
<P>
   Candace Browning and Michael Linenberg, who follow airlines for
Merrill Lynch, project a 12 percent decline in 1999 industry
profit, largely based on their belief that capacity will grow 5.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Starkman, the Warburg analyst, said he is concerned about labor
costs and a softening economy that might force the airlines to
increase discounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If fuel prices had not fallen in 1998, if they had simply
remained flat, operating profits for the airlines would have been
down,'' Starkman said. ``In fact, the airlines' operating profits
for '98 will be up maybe $500 million, but the airlines saved $1.9
billion to $2 billion from the fuel price drop. The rest of the
savings were eaten up by higher costs.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Reed covers aviation for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call him at (817) 390-7874, or e-mail:
danreed(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
