<SLUG> BC-PIE-THROWERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY SPLITS VERDICT IN PIE-THROWING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MACKENZIE WARREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When it came to pie crimes and misdemeanors,
jurors returned a bittersweet verdict in the case of three people
accused of tossing pies at San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown: The
jury convicted them of battery, but cleared them of the more
serious charge of assaulting a public official.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who testified against the defendants last week, expressed
regret about Tuesday's verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume the jury thinks it's OK to punch an elected
official,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The three defendants, all members of the loosely organized
Biotic Baking Brigade activist group, said the verdict was a
victory for their cause and for free speech. Defense lawyer Mark
Vermeulen called the acquittal yet another pie in Brown's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope he takes this with a little more grace than the
last one,'' Vermeulen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the moment the pie hit his face,'' said defendant
Justin Gross, 27, of Berkeley. ``We got our message out.''
</P>
<P>
   Never denying that they threw the pies at Brown in the Nov. 7
attack, Gross and the other two defendants _ Rahula Janowski, 27,
and Gerard Livernois, 34, both of San Francisco _ said they had
wanted to draw attention to the mayor's policy on homeless people,
which they criticize as inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   They face six months in jail for misdemeanor battery, but they
could have received a one-year sentence had they been convicted of
the more serious charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Superior Court jury deliberated for more than nine hours
before returning the verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important to be careful how you choose to be an
activist,'' said juror Susan Cassidy. ``I support and appreciate
(activism) and empathize with these young people who are wanting to
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy, a teacher, said she and the other jurors were not
convinced that the act was retaliating for the mayor's policies or
was meant to prevent him from carrying out his official duties,
essential ingredients in convicting for assaulting a public
official.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy District Attorney Maria Bee had grilled the defendants on
the stand last week about whether they would have carried out the
attack had they agreed with Brown's policies. They all said they
probably would not have. These admissions, Bee said in her closing
arguments, should lead to a verdict of guilty of assault on a
public official.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict came after a three-day trial last week. Judge Ernest
Goldsmith set sentencing for Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was hit with pies during the Great Sweep III, the mayor's
annual community street cleanup. The defendants said they had
targeted him on that occasion because they felt it symbolized what
they termed ``the great homeless sweep,'' the results of what they
call a heavy-handed attempt to rid the city of homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   Janowski, who left the courtroom wearing a Biotic Baking Brigade
T-shirt, said ``Operation Free Willie'' was a success, despite the
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a pastry uprising,'' she said. ``There's a lot of
militant bakers out there. This isn't going to deter them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
