<HEADER>
A1206 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-BEARS-NYT &LR;      01-20 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-BEARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY WAY TO FACE DOWN A GRIZZLY: ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Meriwether Lewis, the moment of truth between human and bear
occurred on June 14, 1805, one day after he had discovered the
Great Falls of the Missouri. (Lewis and Clark's bear lore, along
with their other exploits, can be followed on line at
www.lewis-clark.org.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Having entirely forgotten to reload my rifle,'' Lewis wrote in
his diary, ``a large white, or rather brown bear, had perceived and
crept on me within 20 steps before I discovered him.'' Lewis tried
to walk slowly toward a tree 300 yards distant. ``I had no sooner
turned myself about but he pitched at me, open mouthed and full
speed. I ran about 80 yards and found he gained on me fast. I then
ran into the water.'' The grizzly bear abruptly turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cause of his alarm still remains with me mysterious and
unaccountable,'' Lewis wrote, and many have echoed his words since
then.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the grizzlies of the Great Plains, so plentiful in Lewis
and Clark's diaries, have been wiped out or driven into the
mountains, but environmentalists, students, hikers and anyone who
wants to feel a sense of deep respect can go bear trekking on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   The Bear Den (www.nature-net.com/bears) is a home page for all
things ursine, including pandas, which have traditionally been
lumped with the raccoon family but are actually closer relatives of
the bears, according to recent DNA evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Bear Den is run by Don Middleton, a school psychologist in
Portage la Prairie, Manitoba, which is near a big black bear
population in Riding Mountain National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Middleton's site has descriptions of the eight bear species,
including the sloth bear of Asia, sun bear, spectacled bear and
giant panda, all of them rare; Asiatic black bear, and the more
familiar brown, black and polar bears. It also has reviews of bear
books, videos, CD-ROMs and gear.
</P>
<P>
   Various links explore such controversial questions as the
usefulness of bear bells (are they a warning device or just noise
pollution) and pepper spray (you don't want to get close enough to
find out).
</P>
<P>
   ``Media, including the recent movie `The Edge,' usually portray
bears in unrealistic and anthropomorphic ways,'' Middleton wrote by
e-mail. ``I hope that people extensively studying my site will see
bears for what they are _ majestic pinnacle predators who should be
left alone for the most part, only studied from a distance and also
harbingers or sentinels of the sustainability of our last remaining
wilderness areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bear Den also pays homage to the need to talk about one's
bear feelings. A sample from the Quotes About Bears page comes from
John Muir, the pioneer: ``Bears are not companions of men, but
children of God, and His charity is broad enough for both.''
Another is from John Murray: ``Those who have packed far up into
grizzly country know that the presence of even one grizzly on the
land elevates the mountains, deepens the canyons, chills the winds,
brightens the stars, darkens the forest and quickens the pulse of
all who enter it. They know that when a bear dies, something sacred
in every living thing interconnected with that realm ... also
dies.''
</P>
<P>
   That verges on religion, but something meaningful often does
happen in bear encounters. John W. Uhler has put together a Bear
Story site on the Total Yellowstone Page
(www.Yellowstone-Natl-Park.Com/bearstor.htm), a selection of
up-close-and-personal accounts.
</P>
<P>
   James Musgrove's recently updated site on the American grizzly
bear (home.att.net/jrmusgrove/index.htm), provides a look at
current legal disputes and government action regarding the often
lopsided battle between friends of the bears and the logging,
mining and ranching interests.
</P>
<P>
   A sad but important part of his reporting is a running death
count (23 grizzlies were killed in and around Glacier National Park
in 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd W. Hofmann, creator of a short guide called Bear Fact
(www.planet.eon.net/homac/bear.html), wrote: ``I spend every second
weekend in Jasper National Park mountain biking. I was startled to
find people actually avoiding this national park due to the
perceived danger.'' He added, ``You honestly have a better chance
of being struck by lightning than suffering from a bear attack.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to cut the odds even further, the Bear Den's
offers important advice in its Guide to Backcountry Wisdom, as does
the North Cascades National Park site (www.nps.gov/noca/bear.htm)
and Bears and Glacier National Park
(www.nps.gov/glac/bearpage.htm).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a rich Eastern site is Bear Manners: Getting Along in
the Backcountry (patc.simplenet.com/bearman.html) by Dean Ahearn,
an homage to the black bear in Shenandoah National Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1541EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1209 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ENCARTA-AFRICANA-     01-20 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ENCARTA-AFRICANA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANET AFRICA: BLACK HISTORY ON DISK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Wash., R.I., Pa., Tenn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1995, Henry Louis Gates Jr., a Harvard professor and perhaps
the most widely recognized African-American scholar today, cast
himself in the role of fast-talking encyclopedia salesman. Gates,
who had begun dreaming of creating a comprehensive encyclopedia of
the black world two decades earlier, found himself in New York
presenting his proposal to executives from the giant publishing
company Random House.
</P>
<P>
   But before he could finish his pitch, the company's chief
executive, Alberto Vitale, asked him if the encyclopedia could be
done as a multimedia CD-ROM, rather than in the conventional
print-only manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' was Gates' response. The only hitch: He had no
idea what a CD-ROM was.
</P>
<P>
   But Gates, who is popularly known as Skip, is a famously quick
study. And the result is the Encarta Africana, a new electronic
encyclopedia that attempts to distill the black experience into two
honey-hued CD-ROM disks.
</P>
<P>
   The disks _ crammed with 2.5 million words and more than 2,500
pictures, maps, graphs, sounds and video clips on practically all
things of African descent _ reverberate with their subject. A mouse
click can launch users, even those with modestly powered personal
computers, on a cinematic voyage along the Swahili coast, or permit
them to retrace centuries of slave routes between the ``dark
continent''and the New World, or simply watch, in stunningly stark
video clips, haunting scenes of civil rights marchers being
attacked with fire hoses and police dogs.
</P>
<P>
   A keystroke can call up a 1929 performance of Bessie Smith
belting out ``Saint Louis Blues,'' Duke Ellington's elegant
redesign of jazz, The Temptations crooning in their Motown glory
years in the 1960s or sounds from hip-hop's humble birth in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have finally a technology that can explore and explain the
expressive features _ music and dance, art and cinema, literature
and story-telling _ that are the heart of cultural achievements of
people of African descent,'' Gates enthuses in a three-minute video
clip in the encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other CD-ROM collections of some of the sights,
sounds, words and deeds of blacks, like last year's Encyclopedia
Britannica Profiles Black History. But most of them have been very
limited in scope and imagination.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Encarta Africana, officially released Monday by
Microsoft to mark the celebration of Martin Luther King Jr.'s
birth, had from its inception the audacious task of chronicling
black history and culture stretching back to the first Africans
and, for that matter, the first humans, some 4 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Almost for its ambition alone, the project has attracted an
enormous amount of attention and some controversy. For Gates and
his co-editor, Kwame Anthony Appiah, a Harvard colleague, the
struggle to create the encyclopedia had been taken many paths.
</P>
<P>
   Some led to deadends and crushing disappointments. Others met
with debate over whether the project was taking an Afrocentric or
Eurocentric perspective, and over who actually had the rights to
the idea of a black encyclopedia, long a reoccurring dream among
some African-American intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of creating the Encarta Africana, Gates and
Appiah called on more than 400 scholars to research and write more
than 3,000 articles that could appeal to everyone from grade-school
students to graduate-school students. Gates also persuaded noted
figures like Wole Soyinka, the Nigerian-born recipient of the Nobel
Prize in literature, and Secretary General Kofi Annan of the United
Nations, to participate in the project.
</P>
<P>
   Gates even called upon his friend, the basketball great Michael
Jordon, to preview the encyclopedia. Jordan's endorsement _ ``a
reference work which every family should own'' _ is stamped on the
encyclopedia's packaging.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing some of the most popular features from Microsoft's
Encarta series, Africana was designed, its makers say, to show as
much as tell. Some officials at Microsoft have been describing the
encyclopedia, which costs $49.95 after a $20 mail-in rebate that
expires at the end of this year, as a groundbreaking marriage of
content and technology.
</P>
<P>
   One feature, for example, offers users six virtual tours that
include the slave castles of Goree island off the coast of Senegal,
West Africa and the Egyptian ruins at Medinet Habu, using
360-degree photographs that rotate with the nudge of a computer
mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people in the United States are not going to
have a chance to make it over to Africa, so we really try bring you
the sights and sounds in a stimulating format,'' said Evette Gee, a
Microsoft project manager for Encarta Africana.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest dream of a comprehensive black encyclopedia
belonged neither to Skip Gates nor to Bill Gates, but to a man
whose life ended long before the advent of personal computers, the
Internet and CD-ROMS. In 1909, W.E.B. Du Bois, the first black to
graduate with a PhD from Harvard University, and who went on to
become the grand American intellectual, writer, social scientist
and Pan-African activist, called for the creation of a black
encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted this work, which he called the Encyclopedia
Africana, to tell the complete saga of Africa and its diaspora in
Europe, Asia, the Caribbean and the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Du Bois thought in 1909 that the principle cause of racism was
ignorance,'' said Gates in an interview, who is the director of the
W.E.B. Du Bois Institute for Afro-American Research at Harvard.
``And if he could marshal `scientific evidence' _ that was his
phrase, that we could defeat racism. And the best way to marshal
scientific evidence was through an encyclopedia.''
</P>
<P>
   While his belief would change over the years, as he came to the
conclusion that racism was rooted in economics, Du Bois nonetheless
pursued his dream of producing an encyclopedia of the black world
until his death in 1963 in Ghana, at age 94.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years of his life, Du Bois was living in Ghana
at the invitation of its president, Kwame Nkrumah, and was at work
leading the creation of the Encyclopedia Africana. Since then, his
work has slowly continued in Ghana, with three volumes published so
far.
</P>
<P>
   While a student at Cambridge University in 1973, Gates said, he
dreamed of completing the vision of Du Bois, whose brilliance and
self confidence, he acknowledged, still stagger him. At Cambridge,
he met a young philosophy major, Kwame Appiah, whose uncle is an
Asante chief in Ghana. They became friends and collaborators in
trying to make real what Appiah calls Du Bois' ``noble idea.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Gates, then an assistant professor at Yale University,
approached Encyclopedia Britannica with the idea. But the company
was not convinced that the project would make money. If Gates could
raise the millions required to create the encyclopedia, the company
told him, Britannica would produce it
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1995, after having taught at Harvard for four
years, that Gates felt secure enough there to try once again to
resurrect the idea. He had gotten pledges of development money from
Quincy Jones, the composer and media entrepreneur, and Martin
Payson, a high-ranking executive at Time-Warner, for the project.
It was then that he met with Random House officials and was asked
to consider making a CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, after working with Dynamic Diagrams, a Rhode
Island-based design group, Gates had a CD-ROM prototype of his
encyclopedia. But when he returned to Random House with it, he was
told that the bottom had fallen out of the CD-ROM market. The
company was no longer interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said that they were only doing games,'' Gates recalled
recently. ``I could have cried. I was devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, the ``edutainment'' CD-ROM market is rapidly
shrinking as more users turn to the vast, ever-changing resources
of the Internet, rather than the static data on disks, said L. Butt
Jr., director of entertainment and technology strategy at Forrester
Research, a Cambridge, Mass.-based research firm. There are some
exceptions, however, for CD-ROM encyclopedias like Encarta, Butt
said.
</P>
<P>
   After his rejection by Random House, Gates shopped the project
around New York, making presentations to numerous companies,
including, the Voyager Co. and Simon &AMP; Schuster. Still no deal.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Spring of 1997, while approaching Prodigy, the
Internet provider, to set up an online version of the encyclopedia,
Gates was also talking separately with Perseus Books and Microsoft.
The day after Gates finalized a deal with Perseus to produce a
single-volume text version of the encyclopedia _ scheduled for
publication in November _ Microsoft agreed to produce the CD-ROM
encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and Persesus quickly reached an agreeement to split
the costs. No one will say how much the compendium cost, but a
source close to the project said the research budget was about $2
million.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gates had finally found publishers for the
encyclopedia, he learned that the original name he had in mind,
Encyclopedia Africana, would have to be dropped. The group still
working in Ghana to complete Du Bois' project, it turned out, owned
the rights to that name.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars say the Ghana-directed scholars who have so-far
produced three volumes of what some believe may be a 20-volume
Encyclopedia Africana: Dictionary of African Biography
(www.ulbobo.com/eap) are the inheritors not only of the project's
name, but of its true spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is a commercial product for the white
buyers,'' said Dr. Molefi Kete Asante, a widely published author
and former chairman of the African Studies department at Temple
University in Philadelphia. ``It is a project that is flawed,
because the people who created it, even though they have strong
credentials in the white academies, do not understand the African
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Asante is a leading proponent of Afrocentricity, which holds as
its chief tenet that black history must be seen from what he calls
an ``African center.'' Encarta Africana, he said, takes a more
Eurocentric approach to explaining the black world.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he points to the encyclopedia's passages on Egypt,
passages that, Asante said, work to confirm some historians views
that, despite its place on the African continent, Egypt's
civilization is somehow more akin to the Middle East, rather than
having evolved from from core African cultural and historical
roots.
</P>
<P>
   Asante and Raymond A. Winbush, a professor and director of the
Race Relations Institute at Fisk University in Nashville, also say
that Gates and Appiah asked few, if any, Afrocentric scholars to
join the more than 400 scholars who contributed articles to Encarta
Encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just disappointed that some of our great scholars, like on
slavery in America, were not invited,'' said Winbush, who is an
advisor to the Ghana-based project. He said the electronic
encyclopedia was not the ``definitive view of Africa.'' He
acknowledged, however, that it was ``a good first step, a baby
step.''
</P>
<P>
   The encyclopedia has drawn strong praise from Dr. Robert L.
Douglas, a noted African studies scholar. ``The sheer magnitude of
its size, scope and chronology (from four million B.C. to the
present) is magnificent in itself,'' said Douglas, professor of art
history and pan african studies at the University of Louisville in
Kentucky. ``Only with the coming years of its use in the multitude
of educational forums and the research potential that it promises
for teachers and scholars will its successes and failures be
realized.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates concedes that Encarta Encyclopedia is ``mainstream, very
mainstream.'' But that does not devalue its scholarship, others
agree. Any potentially controversy passage in the encyclopedia is,
he said, clearly labeled so. And often, he says, his group of
scholars, which he described as ``ideologically diverse,'' tried
hard to include opposing arguments on controversial interpretations
of black history and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a God complex,'' Gates said. ``We are not saying
that this is the Bible.'' he noted that this week he launched an
Internet site (www.africana.com) inviting anyone to send in ``ideas
and opinions'' regarding the encyclopedia's content. ``The more the
merrier,'' Gates said, suggesting that the encyclopedia may be
revised over time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the CD-ROM is not yet for everyone. It does not come in a
Macintosh version (or a single-disk DVD version). And there are no
immediate plans for a Mac Encarta, either, said Microsoft's Evette
Gee. This could present a problem, some educators say, for poor,
inner-city school districts that may be more likely to have
Macintosh computers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft announced that it plans to donate 2,000 copies of
Encarta Africana to urban schools, part of an overall donation of
8,000 copies of the encyclopedia to other schools, including
historically black colleges and universities and selected public
libraries in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said that he is immensely proud of the encyclopedia, and
he is pleased with the thought that Du Bois might be pleased as
well. Last month, when Encarta Encyclopedia was being shipped, he
received a letter from David G. Du Bois, 71, the son of W.E.B. Du
Bois.
</P>
<P>
   In part, it read, ``Anthony Appiah and Henry Louis Gates Jr.,
inspired by Father's original idea, have made a magnificent, state
of the art contribution to African and African American Studies and
Humanities with Encarta Africana. Dr. Du Bois would have been
proud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
