u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-RINGS-SITES-N     01-20 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-RINGS-SITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RINGS STEER WEB EXPLORERS TO BACK ROADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the most obscure and most fascinating sites on the Web
can be found almost exclusively sticking to its soft underbelly, in
Web rings. Take, for example, Tales of Fur and Fiber
(members.aol.com/daknits/index.html), run by Rachel Hecht, which
includes a page of superstitions about knitting.
</P>
<P>
   With the Webmaster's Himalayan cat, Firkin, and Maltese dog,
Oliver, as guides, we learn: ``Knitting for children you may have
in the future, but before you are pregnant, is bad luck.'' ``If you
knit one of your own hairs into a garment, it will bind the
recipient to you.'' ``Don't knit a pair of socks for your boyfriend
or he'll walk away from you!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hecht, who lives in North Miami Beach, Fla., joined her site
with the Free Knitting Patterns Web Ring
(www.geocities.com/Paris/9197/knitring.htm), part of Webring.org.
It includes material from the Knit List, an online knitting group.
</P>
<P>
   Someone desperate to find superstitions about knitting (and
isn't everyone, at one time or another, during this brief time on
earth?) would be out of luck in all but one of the major search
engines. Alta Vista picks up the Fur and Fiber site. But other
search engines turned up uninspiring results or nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   The searches produced many hits on the ``Innuendo'' album by the
rock group Queen. The album includes ``knitting'' and
``superstition'' in its lyrics, and the occasional mention of
Madame LaFarge, the knitter from Dickens' ``Tale of Two Cities.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the Web Ring site, there was just one ring devoted to
knitting, and the superstitions were easy to find by browsing
through the list. So where else could one learn this crucial
information: ``Stabbing your needles through your yarn balls brings
bad luck to anyone who wears something made from that yarn''? Let
the wearer beware.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1543EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-REAL-ESTATE-2TAKES     01-20 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REAL-ESTATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO AGENTS' DAYS: A REAL ESTATE DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The customer walked into the $1.5 million duplex
maisonette on Park Avenue and zeroed in on the decorative grilles
on the first-floor windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'd like to live in an apartment with bars on
it,'' Carlene Condon said, barely noting the ornate wrought-iron
balustrade, the swagged tapestry draperies, the Ionic columns and
the patterned marble floors. She shook her head. ``I mean,  &UR; Rikers
Island &LR;  has bars!''
</P>
<P>
   John Foreman, her real-estate agent, sighed. The day was not
getting off to a great start.
</P>
<P>
   In what has become one of the fastest-moving winter markets in
years, Manhattan real-estate brokers are hustling, trying to make
up for the third quarter, when buyers hesitated because of the
stock market's roller-coaster ride. Now, the agencies report, the
clients are back _ and buying. According to a Real Estate Board of
New York survey due out in early February, total sales volume in
the last quarter of 1998 rose 7 percent over the same period last
year. And according to a most year-end statistics, prices also
rose, well into the double digits for the larger apartments.
</P>
<P>
   So what is a day of selling real estate really like these days?
Is it a dawn-to-dusk frenzy, selling million-dollar duplexes as if
they were Volkswagen's New Beetle?
</P>
<P>
   To find out, a reporter tagged along with agents from two of the
city's most fiercely competitive companies, spending a day with
each.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman, a former architectural historian who has worked for
Halstead Property Co. for seven years, is so soft-spoken, the
reporter's back muscles hurt after spending a day leaning forward
to hear him.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Julie Gordon, a former Ford model turned co-op and
condominium saleswoman (why  &UR; do &LR;  real-estate agents always begin
their working lives in completely different occupations?), is
lively and outspoken. When desk mates at the Corcoran Group, where
she has worked for four years, were asked to characterize her, they
chanted in chorus, ``She's the one with the mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps there is a certain symmetry that Foreman is working
with a woman who boldly compares the window grates in a Park Avenue
maisonette to those at the city prison. And that Ms. Gordon is
working with Robert McVeety, a record company manager who is as
reserved as Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what did you think of the apartments?'' Ms. Gordon asked
McVeety after viewing two one-bedroom apartments in a postwar
building on East 56th Street. ``OK,'' he replied, without passion.
</P>
<P>
   She pressed him: ``Which did you like better?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, life is full of compromises,'' he said. After a good 10
minutes of fruitless interrogation, Ms. Gordon thought she might
have unearthed a clue to his diffidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' she said a bit wearily. ``Let's look at some apartments
on the West Side.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 a.m., there's a message on the reporter's answering
machine from Julie Gordon: ``Oh, my God, it's snowing! It looks
like school is going to be canceled, and I don't have anyone to
take care of the kids, so I'll have to give up my appointments.
We're trying to get the Snow Patrol on the phone, but they're not
awake yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus the day begins for Ms. Gordon, a 40-year-old divorced
mother of two who is trying to carve out a life selling real estate
while juggling her family responsibilities. She is not as well
known as her colleagues who are photographed in their Rolls-Royces
with celebrity clients: she walks to showings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gordon is a vice president at the Corcoran Group, a title
won because of the money she's earned. She once had a bulletin
board with a handful of her ribbons, each attesting to a sale of
more than $1 million; one day, she tossed them all out. ``I just
wasn't into the ribbons anymore,'' she said, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   At 7, she calls back. ``We called the class mother and woke her
up. There's school.''
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour later, she throws open the door of her six-room
apartment at 141 E. 88th St., a prewar co-op that she rents. She's
still wearing a gray sweatshirt and sweatpants. Her daughters,
Laura, 9, and Kelly, 11, are already dressed for school. ``I feel
like we're in Montana _ and we're going off to kill that moose,''
their mother says, as they head out.
</P>
<P>
   Walking along Lexington Avenue at a rapid clip, Laura and Kelly
fight over who will get their mother's left hand. ``It's a better
hand,'' Laura insists, looking daggers at her older sister. A few
minutes before 8, the children are delivered to the
Nightingale-Bamford School, and Ms. Gordon speeds back to her
apartment. ``After the first time my clients go out with me, they
know to wear sneakers,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   At 9, she's changing into her basic-black work clothes,
listening to messages: ``Oooh!'' she shrieks. ``I just found out
this guy who just bought an apartment from me the first day we went
out had looked at 37 other apartments with another broker. I feel
 &UR; so &LR;  bad for her!''
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour later, at the office on Madison Avenue, she calls
Bob McVeety, who wants to find an apartment for himself and his
wife. ``He's looking at one-bedrooms,'' she says. ``They're the
hardest to please. They're always trying to squeeze, to get more
bang for the buck. They want to see every 750-square-foot apartment
in Manhattan before they decide. It's not my niche, but I like him,
so I make an exception.''
</P>
<P>
   And if she  &UR; doesn't &LR;  like a client? ``I call 911,'' she says
referring to an extension at the office for just such
eventualities. ``I say, `I want to get rid of this buyer.' They can
take them over. Oh, sure, they'll give me a referral fee _ 10
percent. You go up to the broker and give her a kiss. Better her
than me!''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Across town, John Foreman is just getting started. His first
appointment is at noon. At 9:30, he leaves the giant postwar
complex on East 66th Street, where he sublets. He is bound for his
office on Madison Avenue to check out the ``show sheets'' (who in
his office is showing what), to return calls and to put together
his own schedule, which includes deciding whether he's ``going to
show somebody a piece of garbage just because you have to show them
 &UR; something &LR; .'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foreman, 53, looks dapper in a camel's-hair coat and a
taupe-colored slouch hat. He grabs a cup of squash soup at E.A.T.
``How much could it cost?'' he asks, without checking. He soon
finds out: ``$8!'' Reeling, he takes the soup back to the office.
He is meeting Carlene Condon, a corporate lawyer, at a seven-room,
$1.4 million co-op on East 68th Street.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Condon, who has been looking for an apartment for more than
six months, had requested this particular building, if something
became available; it is a prewar doorman building with a fine Old
English courtyard garden seen through leaded-glass french doors.
But the apartment, freshly renovated, gets only a lukewarm ``nice''
from Ms. Condon. She is looking for something more dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop is the idiosyncratic Park Avenue maisonette, with
hidden marble shower and a kitchen with a balcony. Drama, yes, but
those bars on the windows just won't do. The broker and his client
shake hands. ``I'll call you,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman heads back to the Halstead office to check messages and
to track down a missing commission check for $8,000 (he found it).
At 1:30, he zips off to meet a well-known basketball player and his
wife, who want to buy on the Upper West Side, either a large
apartment in a prewar doorman building (her choice) or a town house
filled to the rafters with original details (his choice). Like some
other clients on this random workday, the basketball player
insisted that his name not be used for reasons of privacy.
Tactfully, Foreman is showing them three apartments and two
brownstones.
</P>
<P>
   They are disappointed in the first apartment, at 100 Riverside
Drive, listed as having ``5-6rms/riv views'' for $1.175 million.
``So where was the river?'' the basketball star asks, as he drives
away.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop is a magnificent brownstone that, alas, was almost
gutted years ago and renovated to a modern stuccoed sheen. ``It was
in several magazines,'' Judy Osten of Brown Harris Stevens, the
listing agent, says brightly. Foreman will split the commission if
the couple buys the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a shame!'' the basketball player says. ``How much do you
think it would cost to restore it to the way it was?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Osten leads the group to another brownstone at 44 W. 91st
St. Right away, the customers see a drawback: the house is right
across the street from an elementary school. ``Yes, but they're
little children,'' Ms. Osten says gamely. Inside, though, the
couple are enthralled. They roam from room to room, floor to floor.
They admire for the cherry kitchen, which leads out to a back
garden. He exclaims over the huge den at the rear of the first
floor, which opens to a tiny deck. ``See, what you'd have to do is
maybe just stain these boards darker,'' he says to no one in
particular. The house is $2 million. ``They'd have to come down a
lot _ like to $1.5,'' he says afterward. ``Then it'd be a good
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple then visit two elegant prewar buildings on West End
Avenue: an eight-room apartment at No. 924, the Clebourne, is
listed at $1.075 million and a seven-and-a-half room fixer-upper at
No. 875 is priced at $765,000. They are still leaning toward an
apartment they saw on their first outing with Foreman. ``There's a
bathroom situation,'' the basketball player explains. ``Yes, a
 &UR; situation &LR; ,'' his wife says with a laugh. They explain: there is
an old-fashioned shaving closet _ just a single sink _ which they
want to make into a third bathroom, but the board has already said
it would not allow the change. (Nonetheless, the couple has asked
Foreman to schedule an appointment to see it again.)
</P>
<P>
   His next customer is a banker named Aashish Kamat, a friendly
but taciturn man whom he shows a series of two-bedroom co-ops,
priced at $400,000 to $600,000. Kamat is very quiet the whole time.
``I am always quiet,'' he says, ``when I know I am going to spend a
very great deal of money.''
</P>
<P>
   At 1:15, Ms. Gordon walks the five blocks from her office to
meet McVeety at 136 E. 56th St. On the way, she explains her
strategy for the McVeetys. ``See, this couple's tough. I'd like to
see them go into a top-notch building. But his wife, Chris, is just
out of law school, so the boards might say: `Yeah, fine, she's
 &UR; going &LR;  to make a lot of money. Come back in a few years.'''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McVeety says: ``We're trying to make up our mind
whether to live in Westchester or the city.'' he says. They are now
living in a Brooklyn sublet. He carefully examines two
1,000-square-foot one-bedroom apartments, both with dining areas.
Both are priced at just under $300,000. ``I would like Chris to
look at both of these,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   After her last showing, Ms. Gordon heads back to pick up her
daughters at school and to make some calls from her apartment. It
is 2:30. Her day of showing co-ops is over.
</P>
<P>
   Six hours later, Foreman shows a small $269,000 one-bedroom in
the Schwab House, a postwar building at 11 Riverside Drive.
Afterward, he sinks into a sofa in the lobby and pulls out his cell
phone. One last call, and his day is done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither broker has ended up with a signed contract _ or anything
close to it _ but that's hardly unusual, both say.
</P>
<P>
   Before making a sale, an agent often shows a customer 30 or 40
apartments, Foreman says. ``And sometimes you have dry spells, when
you don't make any money for a very, very long time. I've got an
ex-wife and a kid at boarding school. That's why I do so many
rentals; they're quick. Sometimes you can wrap up a deal in a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Foreman sold one town house and 11 apartments, but he
rented 12 apartments, each with a hefty commission: usually 15
percent of a year's total rent. (With sales, the commission is
normally 6 percent, which gets divided with the agency and with any
other broker involved.) ``It's not an easy living,'' he continues.
``You have to work hard. I came to this job when I was 45, and I've
learned to live with the uncertainty. I like being my own boss.
Some big-time brokers rake in a lot of money.'' He chuckles. ``And
frankly, I aspire to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Both agents refuse to say exactly how much they make. They get
no salary; they live on their commissions. Ms. Gordon says she has
to bring in at least $120,000 to keep her desk at the agency.
Foreman makes in the low six figures. ``Emphasize the  &UR; low &LR; ,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gordon has adopted a devil-may-care attitude. ``Hey, I only
sold five apartments last year,'' she says. ``And when I sold the
fifth, I said: `Whoa! That's it. That's all the money I need for
this year. And I headed off to St. Bart's.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, she says, she already has five apartments that will
close in the next few months. ``And then guess what? It's off to
St. Bart's again!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
