<SLUG> BC-ELECTRICITY-FACE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEX THAT FACE: NEW ELECTRICAL TREATMENT TOUTED AS ALTERNATIVE TO
FACE LIFTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ I stare intently into the mirror, squint my
eyes and stretch my face into various contortions _ pursing the
lips, lifting the eyelids, poking out the chin, elongating the
mouth, sucking in the cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I can definitely see a slight difference.
</P>
<P>
   I'm studying the effects of a session at Fort Worth's European
Skin Care Institute, one of several salons in the area offering a
new nonsurgical alternative to a face lift. Facial muscular therapy
rests on the premise that as facial muscles weaken with age,
wrinkles form and skin sags. To relieve and reverse those
inevitable signs of aging, say proponents of the theory, the 101
muscles that cover the face and neck need to be exercised and toned
with controlled contractions _ but without stretching the skin.
Exercise, they say, renourishes and revitalizes the tissue that
bonds the skin to the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was hatched eight years ago by a Florida woman who
wanted a face lift but learned that because of her medical history,
she was not a candidate for surgery. Working with a biomedical
engineer, she came up with the Belisle Systems' Facial Muscular
Therapy, a battery-operated device designed to stimulate facial
muscles electrically, contracting them and then releasing them.
</P>
<P>
   The technology for FMT is similar to that used for
transcutaneous electrical stimulation (TENS) units to relieve pain,
except that the face is given a full workout with the resistance
necessary to tighten and tone muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can compare this to working out your body muscles, only I
work out the facial muscles for you,'' says Diana Denton, a
registered nurse who worked at Cook Children's Medical Center in
Fort Worth before joining the staff at European Skin Care
Institute. ``This is very different from a facial massage, even a
deep facial massage. It literally exercises and tightens the
muscles that are at the root of the aging process as far as the
face is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Sessions take about an hour and a half and involve placing
electrodes dipped in a heavy ultrasound gel on specific points of
the face to deliver electrical waves to the interconnected facial
muscles. Denton says that friends and relatives are likely to
notice the difference and comment after five or six treatments. The
folks from Belisle recommend an initial series of 20 treatments,
which can run as much as $3,500. After that point, one treatment
every one to three months is suggested to maintain and further
improve the face and neck uplift. Without the follow-up
maintenance, facial muscles will begin to loosen and sag again
after a couple of years, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a time machine,'' says Alexander von Illyes,
president of the European Skin Care Institute, ``but the technique
is refined to the point now where we can achieve significant
results in as few as 20 sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you improve the underlying structure,'' he says,
``everything else improves with it _ especially loose skin on the
neck and around the eyes and on the jaw line.''
</P>
<P>
   Denton, 42, not only gives the treatments but also gets them.
She says the treatments she began while training for her new job
were a godsend.
</P>
<P>
   ``A surgical face lift was not an option for me,'' she says. ``I
could not afford the downtime or the cost of surgery, but my face
has always been a little lopsided. The left jaw hangs down a little
lower than the right, and my eyes had started to sag a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the right place at the right time,'' she says. ``I
think this could help a lot of people look better.''
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of the therapy depends on the way the muscles
of the face are interconnected, exact placement of the electrodes
and the order in which the muscles are worked, Denton says. In
addition, people with pacemakers or metal implants in their face or
neck are not candidates for the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   My own experiment in FMT lasted an hour and a half (twice as
long as expected because I apparently tend to ask a lot of
questions). For purposes of comparison, I offered only one side of
my face as a testing ground. I felt a tingling sensation, and
sometimes pulling with quick little jerks as a current passes from
one electrode to the other. If the pull becomes uncomfortable,
Denton said, it can be decreased immediately. If you can't feel it
at all, the charge is increased.
</P>
<P>
   As Denton worked just below my right cheekbone, I could see my
left eyebrow twitching. As she worked around the right outside
corner of my lip, I could feel the left side quiver. She delivered
six to 10 pulses of electricity, repeated 10 to 12 times each, to
about 20 sites on the right side of my face.
</P>
<P>
   When we're done, I carefully study the results. The bag under my
right eye is less puffy, the smile lines on the left side more
pronounced. There is even an extra crease under my left eye. Wasn't
there a matching one on the right side before my one-sided facial
workout?
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, most of the people I asked said the effects of
the therapy had, predictably, vanished.
</P>
<P>
   But I could see the difference. I believed it was there.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7687. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
