<HEADER>
A1227 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUXURY-DOGS-ART-HNS &LR;      01-20 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUXURY-DOGS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPPING UP LUXURY: WOMAN'S BELOVED `GIRLS' LIVE THE HIGH LIFE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ People are always telling DeAnne Doane that if they
should ever die and come back to life, they want to come back as
one of her dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon us, one of her ``girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Doane owns two miniature red dachshunds named Inga Marie and
Gretta Anne. To say these canines are pampered is like saying the
Titanic was a large boat.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs _ make that ``the girls,'' which is how Doane and all
her friends refer to them _ take naps in a bed lined in
animal-print fabric in their Houston condominium. They share a
second bed in a swank, upper East Side apartment in Manhattan. They
own matching leopard-print scarves. They vacation in exotic
locales, where they hobnob with celebrities. They dine in the
finest New York restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   They have their own Easter dresses. They have their own polo
hats. They have their own custom-made lederhosen, which they wore
to a dachshund costume party in New York, where they won first
place.
</P>
<P>
   When they fly _ and they do, frequently _ it's always
first-class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the flight attendant,'' says Doane, when asked
if the pups ever get released from their big Sherpa bag while en
route to New York, the Caribbean or some other exciting
destination. ``If he or she is a dog lover, then out they come.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that Doane loves her dogs. Lots of people love
their dogs. Doane cherishes her dogs, darn near worships them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no parents, no children, no siblings, no aunts,'' says
Doane, relaxing on a couch inside her elegant Houston condo,
decorated in burnished beiges, browns and golds _ the colors of
dachshunds. ``They're my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Petite, svelte and stylish, wearing an animal-print scarf that
matches those around her dogs' necks, Doane is a self-confessed
workaholic, a hopeless Type A. She spends more than half the year
in New York on business. As vice president of national business
development for Fidelity National Title Insurance Company, she
brokers billion-dollar deals in a high-pressure job that involves
long hours, extensive travel, enormous stakes and the occasional
bunking-out on a conference room floor.
</P>
<P>
   She's go-go and big-time. Her dogs, she says, are her serenity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I could have the job I do without them, without
the endorphins they give me,'' she says, stroking Inga's forehead,
making the dog's eyes blink sleepily. ``It's so nice to come home
and have them there to nurture me. They give me balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The dogs nestle beside her on the sofa, curling photogenically
and burrowing their snouts into the cushions. Gretta, 15, is the
oldest (``that's 120 in dog years,'' says Doane), with a
silver-tinged muzzle and slightly clouded eyes. Several years ago
she had a disc removed from her spine _ back problems are common
among dachshunds, says Doane _ and she must take daily arthritis
medication. But she's still peppy, shamelessly begging for petting
by sitting up over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   Inga, 6, is ``my tomboy, my athletic one,'' says Doane, who
inherited the dog when her mother died of cancer four years ago.
Inga is obsessive about her little blue ball and unabashedly
attached to Gretta. Whatever Gretta does, Inga does. The two are
inseparable: they won't sleep unless they're touching. At night,
they sleep with Doane in her bed, at the foot of which she has
rigged a series of stair-step suitcases so that Gretta can ascend
painlessly. Inga has her own stuffed toy from FAO Schwarz, which
she must have to fall asleep.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the dogs have the run of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not very good with boundaries,'' admits Doane, smiling
down tenderly at her two little weiners.
</P>
<P>
   Doane (who is divorced) says in the past male suitors have had a
hard time understanding her relationship with her dogs. They get
jealous. But any man who would love her must also love her dogs,
she attests. She believes dogs are a good filtering device in this
regard: People who love dogs tend to be inherently nice; dogs,
conversely, can often ferret out bad apples. In the past, Doane has
brought home certain blind dates to meet the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would bristle, they wouldn't settle down,'' says Doane of
the dogs. ``It would turn out the men had some character flaw, and
the girls picked up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   She takes the girls everywhere (except her office.) When she
can't, they are left in the care of Juan, the dog walker, who is
equally doting. Doane rises from the sofa (the girls following her
with their eyes, in unison) to fetch photo albums documenting their
many exploits together. Here are pictures of a recent vacation at
Carmen del Playa, where she and the girls met actor Jerry van Dyke
on the beach and subsequently enjoyed Christmas dinner at his
Mexican hacienda (van Dyke and his wife used Inga and Gretta as
stand-ins for their own missing pooches, she explains.) Here are
the girls relaxing in the sand, looking chic in sun visors and
sunglasses. Here they are dining in an upscale New York eatery,
where an enchanted Burt Bacharach (a dachshund lover) decided to
join them for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the girls in Central Park, at the founding party of a
singles' group that seeks to unite unattached people who share a
love of dogs. (Doane plans to form such a group in Houston, with a
kickoff this March.)
</P>
<P>
   Doane estimates she spends more than $200 a month on film and
processing for pictures of the girls. She sends some of these to
dachshund magazines _ in which the girls have often been featured
as ``centerfolds'' _ and to friends in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people they're my little nieces from Houston, Texas,''
says Alexandra Linden, a treasury service employee at a Japanese
bank in Los Angeles who has a framed photo of the girls in their
beach regalia on her desk.
</P>
<P>
   Some may think Doane goes a little overboard with her doggies.
Not Jodie Tanner, a co-worker at Fidelity Title who owns a
miniature dachshund named Spooker.
</P>
<P>
   ``DeAnne and I have bonded because of our animals,'' says
Tanner, who keeps a framed portrait of her own dog on her desk.
``My husband passed away a year ago last September, so I can really
understand how she has that feeling for her animals. With my
husband being gone, my little dog is even more special. He doesn't
even know he's a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Every year, Spooker and the girls exchange Christmas gifts, she
says. Last Christmas, he gave them a doggie snack jar; they gave
him a tasty bone. They've never met in person, but it's a ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Doane's dachshund love affair began when she was a teen-ager in
Houston, when she acquired her first one as a stray. For the past
25 years, she has taken her dachshunds (she's on her third
generation) to Houston-area nursing homes at Christmas, so that
elderly residents can stroke and cuddle them. One woman insisted
that Inga be placed in her bed as she went to sleep, and so in Inga
went.
</P>
<P>
   Gretta, Doane says, ``kissed my tears away'' when her mother
died, when her father died, through countless other heartaches as
well. Dogs, she says, are simply the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't care what you produce, they don't care what you
look like. All they want is to be with you. What more can you ask
for?''
</P>
<P>
   Doane ``can't even think about'' the day when Gretta dies, a
looming inevitability. Several years ago, Gretta experienced renal
failure and came close to dying. With the care of Dr. Robert Sweet,
the girls' veterinarian, as well as a canine kidney specialist, she
survived, although today she is permanently incontinent. To protect
her hardwood floors, Doane bought a pair of ``piddle pants'' for
Gretta, hot pink with black accents. They are stylish, almost
jaunty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took them off her, though, for the interview,'' says Doane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
