<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GOP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY 2 GOP REACTION TO CLINTON SPEECH: GRUDGING ADMIRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: SUBS lede; Republican sted Republicans; pickup2ndgraf, ``it
was))  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after Bill Clinton's State of the Union
address, some Republicans governors expressed grudging admiration
for the impeachment-embattled president's ability to deliver the
speech that prompted high approval ratings for him in overnight
polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quintessentially Bill Clinton,'' said Oklahoma's
Republican Gov. Frank Keating in a conference call with reporters.
Keating called Clinton's laundry list of priorities on Social
Security, health care, education and defense a combination of ``New
Deal and shining city on the hill,'' references to speech imagery
favored by Presidents Franklin Roosevelt and Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's commendable that the president wants to use the surplus
for Social Security,'' Keating said. ``Now it's time to get down to
details, to make sure this is a long term solution and not
rhetoric. If Republicans and the president can come together and
resolve the Social Security crisis now, all Americans will
benefit.'' Keating stressed that ``the public wants a bipartisan
fix.''
</P>
<P>
   But he criticized Clinton for not offering Republicans ``more of
an olive branch. We make it a point to compliment Democrats who
make governance possible. It was Republicans who balanced the
budget, and the president made no mention of that. The recovery
started in 1991 (under President George Bush), and no mention was
made of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. Ed Schafer of North Dakota, joining the
conference call, said, ``The president is a great deliverer,'' and
added that in the speech ``there was something for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schafer criticized Clinton for not including a tax cut among
his proposals and said he was relying too heavily on government
solutions in areas such as Social Security. ``He's reinstituting
the era of big government,'' Schafer said.
</P>
<P>
   In his Social Security rescue plan, Clinton said the government
should invest a quarter of the budget surplus funds that he would
divert to the Social Security trust fund over the next 15 years and
called for setting up federally subsidized savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. Jim Geringer of Wyoming, who also took part in
the conference call, said Clinton's speech ``showed a mastery of
politics. There is no more truth, only perception. Clinton used the
weapons of mass distraction in his address.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said in an
interview on ABC's ``Good Morning America'' that since Clinton
``probably will'' survive Republican efforts to remove him from
office, ``we need to move forward. We can't leave these wounds
open.''
</P>
<P>
   And conservative activist Gary Bauer, a possible Republican
presidential contender, told reporters he admired Clinton's ability
to ``compartmentalize'' his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure most people in public life in Washington facing
the sort of charges he's facing would have quite had the
performance he had last night,'' said Bauer, a former Reagan
administration official who has been a leading critic of Clinton.
``It's an incredible phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls released Wednesday by ABC, CBS and NBC showed the public's
approval of Clinton's job performance is still high at the same
time that the Senate is hearing evidence on whether he should be
removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   His job approval rating was 66 percent in the ABC poll, 72
percent in the CBS poll and 76 percent in the NBC poll. In the CBS
poll, six out of 10 said his actions are not serious enough to
warrant his removal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
