<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: PREPARING TO HANG A LARGE MIRROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: How-to drawing is being sent to both NYT photo and NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hanging large mirrors can be a problem because they are heavy,
difficult to maneuver and require adequate wall support.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find a ready-made large mirrors that fits your
specifications, you can order one custom cut to almost any
reasonable size and shape. Look in the Yellow Pages under
``Mirrors, Retail'' to find a shop that will cut a mirror to your
specifications. Before ordering a mirror take the time to
accurately measure the space where you intend to hang it.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to mount the mirror in the middle of a large wall
that has ample space on either side, then your measurements need
not be precise. If, however, you want to place the mirror in a
recess with little clearance, it is essential to take accurate
measurements so the mirror will fit properly.
</P>
<P>
   Measure the width of the area in at least three different
places, top, midpoint and bottom. Take the narrowest measure and
subtract at least 3/4 inch to find the width needed for the mirror.
The extra 3/4 inch will allow room so you can position the mirror
without scratching the adjacent walls.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a mirror that's at least 1/4-inch thick. Thinner 1/8-inch
mirrors are less expensive, but they are not as sturdy and are apt
to be wavy. That can cause distortions in the reflected image.
Usually, the mirror will have smooth, ground edges on all sides.
You can, if you wish, order the mirror with beveled edges, but
there will be an additional cost for this.
</P>
<P>
   After you purchase the mirror, you are faced with the task of
maneuvering it into place. This may not be easy because large
mirrors are heavy and they can break under their own weight if they
are not gripped and supported correctly during transport. Remember
also that mirrors are not usually made of safety glass _ unless
they are made for closet or shower doors. If a mirror breaks, it
can split into a number of sharp and dangerous pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Do not try to move a large mirror by yourself. Enlist the aid of
an able-bodied assistant to help you. Wear heavy-duty work gloves.
The gloves will provide a better grip and protect your hands. In
addition, the gloves will keep the oils on your skin from getting
on and damaging the silver coating on the back of the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   It will be easier to carry the mirror if you use glazier's
handles. These handles have large suction cups that attach directly
to the surface of the glass. They are especially useful when you
have to maneuver the mirror into a tight space where it may be
difficult to get a good hand-hold around the edges of the mirror.
Unfortunately, these suction-cup handles are often difficult to
rent _ not all equipment rental stores have them. If you have to
carry a large mirror up winding stairs or navigate through narrow
spaces, it may be safer to pay the mirror store to move it for you.
</P>
<P>
   Secure the mirror to the wall with two lengths of extruded
aluminum ``J- channel'' _ so-called because the cross section of
the bracket looks like the letter ``J.'' The channels come in two
configurations, one for the top and one for the bottom. They look
similar, but the top channel has a wider lip than the bottom
channel.
</P>
<P>
   Use a hacksaw with a fine-tooth blade to cut each channel to
length, then file all the ends smooth. Mount the channel onto the
wall with drywall nails driven into the studs. You may have to
drill new holes if the existing holes in the channel do not line up
with the studs. Be careful when you hammer the nails; if you miss,
you could dent the channel.
</P>
<P>
   Attach the bottom channel first, then position the top channel
so it is 3/8 inch higher than the height of the mirror. This gives
you enough clearance so you can slip the mirror into the top
channel and then lower it into the bottom one.
</P>
<P>
   Large mirrors need additional support, in the form of mastics,
to hold them in place. Mastics are adhesives that are applied to
the back of the mirror. It is important to only use mastic
specifically formulated for mirror mounting. Other types of
mastics, like construction or panel adhesives, may damage the
silver coating on the back of the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Place a few large globs (about 3 inches in diameter) in the
center of the mirror about 12 inches apart. Do not put any mastic
within 6 inches of the mirror edge; it could ooze out when you
press the mirror in place. Position the mirror in the channels,
then press firmly on the surface of the mirror to spread the
mastic. The mastic will dry in about 24 hours and hold the mirror
tight against the wall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
