<HEADER>
A1255 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV26-     01-20 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV26-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RAVAGES OF AFGHANISTAN'S GENDER APARTHEID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, Jan. 26)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which is worse?
</P>
<P>
   Not being able to go to a doctor because he is a man and you are
a woman and there are no longer any women doctors?
</P>
<P>
   Or having your thumb chopped off because you are wearing nail
polish?
</P>
<P>
   One is life threatening, but the other is such a ridiculous
prohibition that it is almost more chilling.
</P>
<P>
   Both are happening to women in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   It always seems easier to dismiss brutality when it happens on
the other side of the world, in a place you'll never go. You can
say it's their madness. Their way.
</P>
<P>
   But in Afghanistan it is not as convenient as madness.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two years now, members of the Taliban militia have
been killing and humiliating the women of Afghanistan. The whole
society is under siege, but it is the spirit of women and girls
that leaders seemingly most want to destroy.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the world community know and condemn this, but
not enough to make it stop, and so the petitions continue to show
up in mass mailings on the Internet. People like Hillary Clinton
and Madeleine Albright express their outrage. International
feminist groups keep gender apartheid in Afghanistan as a priority
interest. Individuals wear small lapel pins of mesh fabric to
announce their solidarity with Afghan women and girls.
</P>
<P>
   The mesh represents the eye piece in the burqa, the required
head to toe body wrap that marks and imprisons all females under
Taliban rule.
</P>
<P>
   Corey Hale is a Sonoma State University student who leads
vigils, sits at information tables, talks to classes and carries
petitions calling for the United States to condemn the Taliban's
acts.
</P>
<P>
   She once tried on a burqa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really suffocating. You feel very vulnerable. The screen
in front of your eyes leaves you blindsided, so you can't walk
upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   You also can't use your hands for balance, or anything else, she
said, because the garment is designed to be held closed. So all you
can do is walk in it.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a woman in Afghanistan you must be accompanied every
time you leave your house by a male relative - husband, father,
son, brother. If you walk with someone who is not your relative you
can be charged with adultery and publicly whipped, unless you are
married and walking with someone who isn't your relative and then
you can be killed.
</P>
<P>
   Corey, a full-time student, single mother and president of the
Feminist Majority Leadership Alliance on campus, which would all be
considered incredible luxuries or crimes by someone living in
Afghanistan, makes the connection between her world and theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Taliban took over less than three years ago women
worked in the professions, next to men in the fields, served in
parliament, dressed as they wanted, gathered freely. Little girls,
like boys, grew up with possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Students ask Corey if her petition, which will go to President
Clinton, Secretary of State Albright and U.N. secretary general
Kofi Annan, is ``religious interference.'' She shows them where
other Muslim countries have disassociated themselves from the
Taliban which inappropriately uses religion as its excuse. Informed
discussion has followed with Muslim women students explaining the
difference between choosing to wear a veil and women being forced
to be totally concealed.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Smeal, president of the Feminist Majority, asks, ``How
can women be safe anywhere if some governments can carry out gender
apartheid with impunity?''
</P>
<P>
   In the global community, if your neighbor is beating his wife,
you need to do something about the screams.
</P>
<P>
   So, imagine yourself in their place. Suddenly, you must give up
your job and take your daughters out of school. You cannot meet a
friend. You cannot wear shoes that make noise. Your windows must be
painted black so that you can't be seen. You cannot even pluck your
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the claustrophobia inside the burqa that you are now
forced to wear. There is no air on your skin. Journalist Jan
Goodwin reports that women are so poor that they can't even afford
their own burqa but must share one with the neighborhood. Each must
then wait days for her turn in order to go out to buy food.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the shame. You are hooded and shunned like you have some
communicable disease, which they explain is that the sight of you
causes men to lose their self control.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, even the men who do not agree with the leaders start
to treat you poorly in order to protect themselves. And then it
becomes part of male thinking, and even, worse, female thinking,
that women are truly inferior.
</P>
<P>
   The bullies win.
</P>
<P>
   But not so fast. In December the California-based oil company,
Unocal, withdrew its plans to build the trans-Afghanistan pipeline.
It cited pressure from feminist groups for it to stop doing
business with the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if women know, and if they shared any satisfaction
behind their burqas.
</P>
<P>
   They wouldn't laugh. In Afghanistan it's illegal to laugh in
public.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
