<HEADER>
A1259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TULIKIVI-FIREPLACE-AR     01-20 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TULIKIVI-FIREPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLS-ROYCE OF HEARTHS, A HIT IN THE ROCKIES, HEADS EAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By JIM ROBBINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOZEMAN, Mont. _ The fire had burned down to a heap of coals.
With a gloved hand, Randy LaFerr opened the oven door of his
monumental Tulikivi soapstone fireplace from Finland and with a
long-handle rake pushed the coals out the back and into the stove
below. The soapstone bricks that line the oven were around 750
degrees, the perfect temperature, LaFerr said, to start the hors
d'oeuvres. He placed a plate of goat cheese and cured olives with
marinara sauce in the oven. In five minutes, it was bubbling gently
behind the glass door.
</P>
<P>
   ``The taste of food cooked in a Tulikivi is unlike anything else
I know of,'' said LaFerr, who owns the Enterprise Fish Company
restaurants in Santa Monica and Santa Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The use of wood-burning stoves and fireplaces, which boomed in
the 1960s and '70s, has waned because of the danger of chimney
fires and the nonstop work involved in sawing, chopping and
carrying wood. There are also regulations, especially in the West,
that govern new wood stoves and fireplaces because they are a major
source of air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Tulikivi, a company based in Jukka, Finland, says it has solved
many of those problems by using an old technology. Tulikivi _
``fire stone'' in Finnish _ has rekindled the art of making huge
heaters out of native gray soapstone. The company has found a way
to mass-produce a four-ton product that is both esthetic and
efficient (though as expensive as a new car and almost as big).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm attracted to functional art,'' LaFerr said. ``Things that
are beautiful and at the same time have a superior function.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is l8 years old and has been operating in this
country for 12 years, though much of that time it has been plagued
with organizational problems. The North American sales department
has been reorganized, however, and Heikki Vauhkonen, the son of the
founder, Reijo Vauhkonen, has moved to New York with his wife, Anu
Vauhkonen, to oversee operations.
</P>
<P>
   Tulikivi sold 17,000 units worldwide last year, mostly in
northern Europe. Just 250 of those were in the United States,
making Tulikivis rarer than Ferraris. (In the spring, the company
will open a large new showroom in Cold Springs, N.Y.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet the beauty of the Tulikivi, its price (as much as $16,000)
and the freedom it affords from hourly trips to the woodpile have
made it revered in the Western states. ``There's some kind of
hearth magic about this soapstone,'' said Tom McGuane, the
Montana-based novelist, who has a small Tulikivi in his bedroom.
``It's comforting to lie in bed in the winter and watch the
flames.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rocky Mountains, with their cold winters and omnipresent
wood piles, have become home to scores of Tulikivis. Add to that
the trend toward self-sufficiency, spawned by the belief that a
Year 2000 computer apocalypse will cause wide power disruptions,
and interest multiplies. ``I've had five or six installations lined
up at the beginning of each year for the last few years,'' said Ron
Pihl, a mason who is the Tulikivi distributor and installer in much
of the West. ``This year I have 20, and many of those are because
of Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tulikivi principle is simple. Make an extremely hot fire of
well-seasoned wood with the damper wide open for two or three
hours. Once the embers die down and the dampers are closed, the
stone gets even hotter. For the next 12 to 24 hours, heat from the
Tulikivi radiates into the house, all without any further feeding
or stoking.
</P>
<P>
   I was skeptical of the claims but invested in a modest Tulikivi
to heat my home outside Helena, Mont. Even on the coldest days, the
Tulikivi gets so hot during our ritual evening fire that we can
slow-cook a stew in its oven the following day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like most is that you don't have to get up in the
morning and light a fire,'' said LaFerr's wife, Shelley. ``It's
still warm.''
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the Tulikivi is its gray soapstone, shot through
with spidery white veins. It is quarried next to the factory at
Jukka and has a talc content ideally suited for the high
temperature of the stove. Soapstone conducts 8 to 10 times as much
heat as brick fireplaces and holds the heat longer. Yet it is soft,
which makes it easy to saw and carve. When polished, it has a silky
smooth feel, similar to marble.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the Tulikivi is a home appliance with a stirring
history. In the mid-1500s, during what has been called the Little
Ice Age, the population of Europe was growing, and firewood was
scarce. Most homes were heated with a simple fireplace. The first
patent for a more efficient stove was granted in 1557. Primitive
masonry stoves, some with sleeping platforms on top, spread through
Europe. Germans still use a wood stove covered with ceramic tiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedes were credited with developing the modern masonry
stove in 1767, when Baron Carl Johan Cronstedt, an architect, came
up with a more efficient design. The Finns took the Swedish unit,
with its baffles to trap gases and heat, and added heat-absorbing
soapstone, from the mountains of Karelia in Finland. In the early
1900s, the Finnish architect Eliel Saarinen designed some masonry
stoves; later, Tulikivi used some of those designs.
</P>
<P>
   With central heating, masonry-stove-design waned. But in the
last decade, the heaters have made a comeback. Tulikivi builds its
stoves by hand in Finland, then breaks them down for shipping. The
13 standard models, from four to six feet in size, are capable of
heating 750 to 1,500 square feet on one level (more if there are
two levels).
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drawback to a Tulikivi is the price. While a
conventional wood stove sells for a few hundred dollars, Tulikivis
range from $4,500 to $16,000 and more. Custom units _ one had
carved animal figures and soapstone tiles inlaid with jasper and
onyx _ can reach $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the start. The stoves must be professionally
installed by a mason, which adds $1,000 to $3,000. Figure $1,000 to
$3,000 more if it is to go into an existing home.
</P>
<P>
   No one puts a Tulikivi in the trunk of the car and installs it
on a Saturday afternoon. Buying the stove requires a serious
commitment. It is best if an architect plans the unit's place in a
new home; a retrofit requires engineers. The Tulikivi also has to
have its own foundation, and because it burns so hot, it may need a
particularly high chimney.
</P>
<P>
   Some will say that they are worth it. ``I've seen units that are
100 to 150 years old in Finland,'' said Dale Hisler, a mason who
works with Pihl. ``And they increase in value.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
