<SLUG> BC-CIR-SCIENCE-JOURNALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS ARE PUBLISHING MORE ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga., Conn.)   (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Print versions of scientific journals could soon be a thing of
the past, as the Internet gives rise to thousands of electronic
journals and helps usher in a new era for scientific publishing,
according to an article published Wednesday in the journal Nature. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Much evidence suggests that maintaining a plethora of
high-price, low-circulation journals as the primary means of
scientific communication is no longer the best way to meet the
needs of users,'' said the article, written by Declan Butler.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years or so, as traditional publishers have
put electronic versions of their journals onto the Web, the rise in
the number of so-called E-journals has been meteoric.
Reed-Elsevier, the largest commercial publisher of scientific
journals, now has more than 1,200 of its titles on line,
Springer-Verlag has 360, and Academic Press has 174. ``A journal
without a Web version is now rare, and probably endangered,'' the
Nature article said.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of E-journals has yet to help lower the high price of
subscribing to scientific journals. Many traditional print journals
now on the Web charge a surcharge for the electronic edition, in
addition to the basic subscription fee, or restrict access to
subscribers. A few publishers offer lower rates for an
electronic-version-only subscription to a journal.
</P>
<P>
   But many scientific researchers and research librarians say they
hope that E-journals will eventually alter the economics of
scholarly publishing. In several scientific quarters, electronic
journals are springing up to compete with expensive print titles.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Association of Research Libraries' Scholarly Publishing
and Academic Resources Coalition, for example, recently announced
the debut of PhysChemComm
(www.rsc.org/is/journals/current/physchemcomm/pccpub.htm), an
electronic journal from England's Royal Society of Chemistry, to
compete with print journals that cover chemical physics and
physical chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the entire editorial board of the high-priced journal
Evolutionary Ecology, published by Wolters Kluwer, based in the
Netherlands, left in protest over the journal's subscription price.
Led by the journal's former editor in chief, Michael Rosenzweig, a
professor at the University of Arizona, the group has just begun
producing Evolutionary Ecology Research, a lower-priced alternative
in both print and electronic form (www.evolutionary-ecology.com).
</P>
<P>
   Research libraries, many of which struggle to pay for expensive
print journals, generally welcome the change. At Denmark's national
Technical Knowledge Center and Library in Lyngby, outside
Copenhagen, print journals are being phased out altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most significant savings when you go from print to
electronic only is the fading away of the staff-intensive work
procedures connected to handling the print editions,'' said Lars
Bjoernshauge, the director of the library. By shifting away from
handling paper, the Danish library expects to increase its titles
by 25 percent by the end of this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some research librarians are less sanguine about the rate at
which scientific publishing is changing. ``It should happen
faster,'' said William Loughner, physical sciences bibliographer at
the University of Georgia. ``I could come up with a list of real
science journals that are new and independent and it would be a
very short list.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle to faster change is concern among librarians over
how electronic materials will be preserved for posterity. ``We're
not sure electrons are stable enough to withstand the test of
time,'' said Ann Okerson, an associate university librarian at Yale
University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
