<SLUG> BC-CIR-HDTV-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOWER END OF `HIGH DEFINITION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American consumers set a record last year. They
bought more projection televisions than ever before, just over one
million of them. And with that, these mammoth sets captured the
largest share they have ever had of the nation's television market:
a whopping 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With those numbers, it may seem odd that since digital
high-definition television went on the market a few months ago,
every manufacturer in the world has chosen to manufacture and sell
huge rear-projection, high-definition sets. Every manufacturer but
one.
</P>
<P>
   Alone in the industry, Sony recently began selling a 34-inch
HDTV, the traditional sort with a picture tube. Sony sells the set
with its own stand, but you can also set it on a table, though you
had better select the table carefully. This set weighs 205 pounds.
And a look at it helps explain why Sony chose this path _ and why
everyone else chose the other.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction is important because just about everyone will
have to buy a digital television receiver sooner or later, as the
nation makes the transition to digital television in the next 10
years or so. Most people will probably choose to buy televisions
that are like the ones they already have, and more than 95 percent
of all televisions sold today are the tabletop sort with picture
tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's wide-screen HDTV looks quite nice _ and it should,
considering the price: $9,000. Still, it's a product whose life
span is likely to be short, at least at that price, because several
manufacturers have announced their plans to begin selling similar
models at half that price or less later this year.
</P>
<P>
   So for many people, a look at the Sony television may serve
largely as an instructive exercise as they look toward the day when
they can buy HDTVs at prices that do not exceed the credit limits
on their charge cards.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing a seasoned viewer notices when watching HDTV on
Sony's television is that while the picture is far clearer than
anything available on a conventional set, it just does not reach
the level of clarity that the big projection televisions can offer.
</P>
<P>
   Picture clarity is largely a matter of resolution, and that is
determined by the number of picture elements, or pixels, on the
television screen. The best of the big-screen HDTVs can display
1,080 horizontal lines and 1,920 vertical lines. That gives a total
pixel count of a little more than two million.
</P>
<P>
   But it is extraordinarily difficult to squeeze two million tiny
phosphor dots onto a 34-inch television screen _ even a wide
screen, like Sony's. When Sony first made its product announcement
in September, the company said the set would provide 1,080
horizontal lines but refused to specify the vertical number.
</P>
<P>
   Later, however, a company spokesman said the screen would have
900 vertical lines, which means that Sony's screen has a little
less than one million pixels. That's three times as many as a
conventional analog set, but only half as many as a full-resolution
HDTV.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced HDTV viewers quickly discover a phenomenon that
helps explain the seductive nature of this new medium. When the
resolution of a television reaches a certain level, the viewer's
perception of it changes. The image seems three-dimensional, real _
like looking out a window. As a result, viewers respond to the
programming in a new way.
</P>
<P>
   An HDTV set offering two million pixels easily reaches that
level, and so does one with 25 percent fewer pixels. But the
threshold lies somewhere between that level and the resolution
offered by this Sony set. The Sony offers a sparkling, clear
picture, but watching it is like watching a beautiful picture. It's
not like looking out a window. Still, that is not the whole story
of HDTV.
</P>
<P>
   Keiichi Kubota, a senior engineer with NHK, the Japanese
television network, who helped design that nation's high-definition
system, explained in a recent discussion why NHK had named the new
medium ``high definition'' television instead of ``high
resolution'' television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because resolution is only one part of it,'' he said.
HDTV also offers greater brightness and contrast, he noted. The
color palette is richer and broader. The sound quality is higher.
In fact, for those people who have the requisite audio equipment,
the American system offers six-channel surround-sound audio.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, because the transmissions are digital, they are
generally free of the ghosts, snow and other interference that
hamper conventional television broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   So even if this Sony set and future tabletop HDTVs cannot match
the resolution of their monster-size brethren, they do offer all of
these other advantages. And this set also includes what Sony calls
``digital reality creation'' circuitry, which enhances the
resolution of conventional broadcasts and videotapes, vastly
improving the picture quality.
</P>
<P>
   In the new digital age, that becomes important because once
viewers see HDTV, most of them never want to go back. And for many
years to come, only a minority of the television programming will
be high-definition. Several companies are offering special
circuitry with their HDTVs, conceptually similar to Sony's, that
enhances regular programming. But Sony's is particularly effective.
</P>
<P>
   While Sony eventually revealed the full resolution numbers for
its set, many other manufacturers have not been so forthright. At
the Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas, Nev., early this month,
several companies showing tabletop HDTV sets said those televisions
each offered two million pixels of resolution when it was obvious
that they could not. When challenged, the companies acknowledged
the exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the consumer-electronics industry decided that a set
had to have 1,080 horizontal lines to qualify as an HDTV. But the
manufacturers decided not to specify the number of vertical lines,
leaving the door open for misleading advertising. Given the
important differences in picture quality _ the resolution
``threshold'' _ that problem is likely to haunt the industry once
HDTV becomes a mainstream product.
</P>
<P>
   But for many people, it may not matter. HDTV is meant to be
watched by viewers who are fairly close. But in most homes, viewers
sit on a sofa 10 to 15 feet away from the television. At that
distance with a tabletop set, it would be hard to tell the
difference between HDTV and regular television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1622EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
