<HEADER>
A1290 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-KOSOVO-BOS &LR;      01-20 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO'S JOB IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a pattern to the crimes of Serbian strongman Slobodan
Milosevic. By exploiting historical memories of Serbian suffering,
he has stoked animosities against Croats, Bosnian Muslims, and now
Kosovar Albanians. When his aggressions lead to catastrophes for
Serbs and he confronts a countervailing military power, Milosevic
dons the mask of a diplomat to sign cease-fires and peace
agreements. As soon as he believes there is no credible threat of
force to restrain him, he breaks the agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's massacre of Albanian villagers in Kosovo confirms
the Milosevic pattern of bellicose action, diplomatic accords, and
broken pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Unarmed monitors were supposed to preserve the cease-fire
negotiated last fall by Richard Holbrooke, the US special envoy.
But Serb soldiers or special forces and the militiamen of the
Kosovo Liberation Army have been ambushing each other all winter,
leading to the Serb atrocities Friday in the vicinity of a village
called Racak.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran US diplomat William Walker, chief of the 700
monitors from the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, witnessed the mutilated bodies in a gully near the village
and called the massacre a crime against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Now Milosevic has expelled Walker, blatantly violating his
agreements with NATO, the OSCE, and the UN Security Council. Even
Milosevic's supporters in Moscow have counseled him to reconsider
and honor his promises of last October.
</P>
<P>
   To revive the cease-fire in Kosovo, NATO must confront Milosevic
with an ultimatum: Stop the carnage or Serb military targets will
be bombed. But the massacre in Racak also demonstrates that the
unarmed OSCE monitors are not able to keep the peace. They ought to
be replaced with a large force of armed NATO troops, a contingent
potent enough to deter both the Kosovo Liberation Army and their
Serb antagonists.
</P>
<P>
   NATO should not, however, make any effort to prescribe the terms
of a political settlement of the conflict. It should stop the
killing and leave it up to the belligerents to negotiate a mutually
acceptable solution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
