<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1296 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GREAT-BOOKS-ART-N     01-20 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GREAT-BOOKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVER OF DETAIL SERVES LITERARY SEARCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Utah, Mich.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William A. Williams Jr. is a former member of the Mormon Church,
which is known for its detailed collection of genealogical
information, and a former actuary, familiar with small but vital
details about populations. So perhaps it figures that he has become
the Internet's sovereign of citation and ruler of reference, the
man who posted the Concordances of Great Books, an online
searchable index of 86 authors and 200 full texts.
</P>
<P>
   Dickensians as far away as Japan send him kudos for his Web
site, at www.concordance.com. And they are far from the only
intense users of Williams' works. If you care to find out where in
the works of Shakespeare the word incardine appears, want to know
how many times Hamlet or Job cursed their stars or wonder where
exactly Walt Whitman sang the body electric, you can plug in a word
to search his index.
</P>
<P>
   The site, which first appeared on the Web in June 1998, grew out
of an electronic conversation Williams had with a man on the
alt.religion.mormon newsgroup. The man wanted to study the
occurrence of various words in the Bible, the Book of Mormon and
several other texts to see if one of those books had evolved from
others.
</P>
<P>
   It took Williams a few months to teach himself the Perl
programming language and write a program for creating concordances.
(Created primarily for searching religious texts, concordances are
also used for legal depositions and in business.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to process files to create index files, several for
each book,'' Williams said. ``And they kind of reference each other
in such a way that you can pull out the occurrences of words very
quickly, 500 references in a second or two. The biggest job is
getting the text files into a form where you can use it. A lot have
junky stuff in it, like hyphens at the end of lines. That's a big
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the works indexed on his page are no longer under
copyright and were obtained from the Project Gutenberg and Books on
Line electronic libraries. Williams got permission from publishers
to put up some of the Mormon-related texts he offers that are not
yet in the public domain. His Web-site host, Primegen Internet
Labs, is generous with space on its server and charges him about
$500 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't do this to make money, but to have something
to do, and hopefully create something to benefit others,'' said
Williams, 61, who is retired and lives with his wife, Ruth, in
Bloomfield Hills, Mich., north of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Williams himself favors English authors, particularly Austen,
Dickens and Shakespeare. Still, his favorite book is ``Les
Miserables,'' by Victor Hugo. Books by all four authors appear on
his site.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the average number of hits per day, the most popular
stops on the site are Mark Twain (about 18 hits), Charles Dickens
(24), Jane Austen (11), the LDS (Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints) Research page (13) and the Bible (5). Euripides
has also racked up many visits. Kenneth W. Starr has fared less
well, and Williams is thinking of dropping his report for lack of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   The page also provides visitors with links to the North American
Kant Association and the Sherlockian Holmes pages, among other
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Williams' collection, concordance software turns up on an
eclectic variety of Web sites. Bleary-eyed college students can
find both mentions of the word peach in the collected poems of T.S.
Eliot (www.missouri.edu/enggf/tsebase.html).
</P>
<P>
   Recovering alcoholics can search for heartache, hangovers,
holidays and havoc in ``The Big Book,'' published by Alcoholics
Anonymous (www.royy.com/concord.html). Dungeons and Dragons players
can search rule books for spells, magic items and enchantments at
Effie Rover's Fantasy Role Player's Library (www.effierover.com).
</P>
<P>
   All of the ``Wheel of Time'' books, by Robert Jordan, can be
searched by using a Yahoo-style directory of categories
(www.d.umn.edu/knovek/wotc/wotcToC.html).
</P>
<P>
   A concordance of Arthur Miller's ``Death of a Salesman,''
including a list of all the words used in the play, by frequency,
is available at www.konbib.nl/dutchess.ned/18/06/info-0289.html.
And in a surprising nod to technology, the Mennonite hymnal is also
ready to be searched at the click of a mouse, not on line but on
disk. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
