<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1302 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-CLINTON-BOS     01-20 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONIAN CONTRADICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are contradictory times. The president of the United
States is disgraced, impeached, and his trial is underway. One
might have expected a national gloom, but there is none. President
Clinton stood before Congress and the nation Tuesday night in a
time of unparalleled prosperity and well-being with an address that
boosted his already high approval ratings even higher. The union
has seldom been in a better state.
</P>
<P>
   There is the usual carping from the right that Clinton is trying
to insert big government into places it doesn't belong and from the
left that he isn't pushing government intervention enough. But the
American people are satisfied with his performance, and just as his
lack of discipline and avoidance of the truth got him into this
mess, so have his political instincts and his capture of the
political center saved him time and again. He has successfully
poached many of the issues the Republicans considered their own,
and he is the only Democratic president in this century not to face
a challenge from a candidate on the left.
</P>
<P>
   His big themes _ the economy, Social Security, education, and
health care _ are all safe, poll-tested products put forth by this
most poll-conscious president in history. But that doesn't mean his
positions are wrong or that these issues are not worthy of the
nation's attention. Far from it. When all else is going so well,
these are areas in which things might go wrong if left unattended.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the president's men began three days of defense of
Clinton's outrageous untruths. Yet there is little indication that
the public is riveted by these proceedings. The press does its duty
by reporting them, as it must. But to most Americans, it is as if
the goings-on in Washington really don't matter _ and in a sense,
they matter less than they have in 70 years. From the stock market
crash of 1929 to the coming down of the Berlin Wall in 1989, the
United States was in a continual state of crisis. The Great
Depression, World War II, and the Cold War followed closely on one
another, and Americans looked to Washington for the answers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, by almost every yardstick, the nation's health is good.
Employment is high; inflation is low. The American economy has
emerged much stronger from a painful period of readjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Crime statistics are down, real wages and the stock market are
up. So far, the United States has avoided the economic storms that
have battered so much of the rest of the world, and instead of
megatyrants such as Hitler and Stalin, Americans now face
mini-tyrants such as Saddam Hussein and Slobodan Milosevic, who are
dangerous and need watching but are not comparable to the foes of
yore.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Americans no longer look to Washington as they did
before. We are in an era where the unbridled forces of market
globalization can sweep smaller governments aside, and Fed chairman
Alan Greenspan and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin arguably have
more say over the well-being of Americans than the president.
Clinton, with no great domestic or foreign crisis, has contracted
government's role in ways that were both realistic and necessary.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean that there are not still problems. As Senator
Edward M. Kennedy said Monday, civil rights remain the nation's
unfinished business. This doesn't mean that dangers and hard times
won't come again, and when they do, Americans will look toward
Washington again for answers. But for these blessed years _ may
they last _ the role of Washington and the presidency is not as
central to the lives of citizens as in the dangerous years. The
greatest contradiction is that President Clinton, with so much to
offer, should have brought down such discredit on the office he
holds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1637EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
