u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSEWARES-SHOW-2TAKE     01-20 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSEWARES-SHOW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELLS AND WHISTLES FOR THE `HEALTHY HOME' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ill, Mich.)  (js) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ If your home is like mine, it is an imperfect thing,
resistant to most efforts to make it a sanctuary, even a little
tyrannical in its dogged inconveniences. The bookcase shelf isn't
quite within arm's reach of the desk chair, the toaster won't
release an imperfectly sliced bagel, the bathroom vent mysteriously
funnels in rap music from some other apartment in the building. (I
assume it's in the building.)
</P>
<P>
   It was with this in mind that I visited the International
Housewares Show at the McCormick Center here last week, where one
of the themes, according to the National Housewares Manufacturers
Association, which sponsors the show, was the ``healthy home.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, apparently, are becoming more concerned with the
dangers inherent in the world at large _ ``They're hearing a lot
about things like stress, carbon monoxide, E. coli, tainted meat,''
said Lisa Casey Weiss, a ``lifestyle consultant'' for the
association _ and therefore are eager to create a safe haven in the
living room and the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The show, from Jan. 10 through 13, was huge _ more than 2,000
exhibitors, vast tracts of floor space taken up with the
awe-inspiring evidence of enterprise and ingenuity _ and it wasn't
hard to find the theme illustrated. There were a lot of new
products designed to make the house and its accouterments not just
nicer for you, but nicer to you.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting to note that the Europeans, no matter how
celebrated for expensive facial cleansers and $800 Miele vacuum
cleaners, are amused by the American obsession with cleanliness.
</P>
<P>
   As Suellen Hoy points out in her book ``Chasing Dirt: The
American Pursuit of Cleanliness'' (Oxford University Press, 1995),
the ideal of cleanliness in this country has shifted from
preventing disease to becoming a way of being irredeemably
American. If the products at the International Housewares Show
reach the masses, homemakers will soon fight disease (or at least
allergies and asthma) by attacking dust mites and will take
temperatures without being invasive. But they will also find ways
to make the house odor free (not just for cleanliness, but for the
appearance of cleanliness) and to cook pizzas in microwaves without
reading the instructions.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Philips, for example, is introducing a battery-operated
thermometer (about $80) that is just wiped across the forehead. The
marketing angle is that you can check sleeping infants without
waking them. ``It's as accurate as a rectal reading,'' Lori
Intetssano, a company representative, explained brightly.
</P>
<P>
   Adobeair, a maker of electric heaters, was promoting
``safe-sense technology'' with a portable heater ($149) that sets
off warning lights and beepers if anyone gets within three feet and
shuts off entirely if the invader gets to within a foot.
</P>
<P>
   From my walk around the convention, I learned that our homes are
not as safe as we thought. Why else would Bissell, a company famous
for carpet cleaners, let conventioneers know, in a large display,
that ``95 percent of American households are infested with dust
mites''? Fortunately, Bissell's new allergen removal formula, used
with its new line of upright steam carpet cleaners, ($229 to $299,
available this spring) addresses the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Eureka has a way of fighting not only dust mites but E. coli and
salmonella _ in this case on bare floors _ with the Enviro Steam
Cleaner, a sanitizing $99.99 mop replacement. Evidently, the
companies that make floor cleaners and vacuums (``dirt suckers'' in
industry parlance) feel it's good to know as much as possible about
the filth in our homes. Most new bagless vacuums, for instance,
feature dirt collectors made of clear plastic. ``The consumer has
the perception she's cleaning better because she can see the dirt
right in front of her,'' said Bruce Gold, executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   These days, vacuum manufacturers boast features like ``cyclonic
action'' to separate what the vacuum sweeps up into smaller and
larger particles (I'm not sure why), and ``Hepa filters'' and
``true Hepa filters'' that scrub the vacuum's exhaust before
shooting it back into the room. Hepa, a current industry buzz
acronym, stands for ``high-efficiency particulate air.'' ``True''
Hepa filters, according to the Eureka Co., which has several
machines featuring them, are the most hard-working, removing
``99.97 percent of all particles from the air, down to three-tenths
of a micron.''
</P>
<P>
   Air purifiers employ Hepa technology, too. Once a medical
product, air purifiers are now so in demand for the odor- and
grit-sensitive among us that they are marketed by shape. One has a
flattened side so the machine sits unobtrusively against a wall.
Decorative.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the most striking example of niche marketing was in the
air-clearing category; a man named Daniel Antepenko, president of
Classic Tool, of Spruce Pine, Ala. _ an aptly named home for an air
purification business _ was there promoting a single product, an
exhaust system that hooks up to your toilet. Vac-A-Way, it's
called, ``a revolutionary new way to remove commode odors'' ($120,
plus shipping).
</P>
<P>
   After a while I began to feel lucky to be out of the house,
where so many unseen threats apparently lurk. So I began searching
for new ways to make myself more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Ease at home _ that's the ticket. Samsung, the electronics
company, is behind the Imwo _ the intelligent microwave oven _ a
product with a built-in computer and data base, developed by
Rutgers University scientists, that relieves the burden of having
to read the instructions on the back of microwavable food packages.
The Imwo reads the bar code on the frozen pizza box, taps into its
data base and cooks the pizza according to the maker's own
directions.
</P>
<P>
   Wine with that pizza? Never good with a corkscrew? Try the
Winemaster, a foolproof device from Vacuvin, a Dutch company, which
sells for $65. It snaps down over a bottleneck and with a couple of
deft tugs on its various levers, bingo! With its 49 moving parts
it's a little heavy and overdesigned (and kind of
sinister-looking), but if your aim is wine and not esthetic ritual,
it's perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers are clearly hip to the urge for immediate
gratification. Microwavable socks (from New Product International)?
A toilet night light (from Prestige Line)?
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago we showed our blood-pressure products here,'' said
Harvey S. Cohen, vice president of Lumiscope, a 75-year-old medical
appliance company in Edison, N.J., that has expanded into massage
therapy implements. In the last five years, he said, the company's
line of vibrating wands and slippers and such has expanded to 20
percent of its sales.
</P>
<P>
   Conair, known for hair dryers, has also been exploring the
self-indulgence market. Its new products include foot massagers, an
aromatherapy lamp and a Water Jet Bath Spa that drapes over the rim
of the tub and rhythmically churns the bath water _ instant
mini-Jacuzzi ($59.99 to $69.99, depending on the retailer).
</P>
<P>
   Another obvious trend is home massage without the masseuse. I
tried portable back massagers and platforms with vibrating balls
for the feet. I wore a mask that made the bridge of my nose
vibrate. I sat in several elegant chairs (up to $3,000) that I
swear had hard-knuckled midgets living inside them. I ended up
quite loose, even a little jiggly.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite device, though, was the Back Maestro, a product
developed by Homedics, of Keego Harbor, Mich. The Back Maestro
($99.99) is a cushion that drapes over an office chair or a car
seat and, with a hand control, allows you to prescribe where on
your body, and in what rhythm, you wish to be pummeled. Here's the
amazing (or ridiculous) thing: If plugged into the stereo, the
cushion will respond to the music, massaging to the beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really smart,'' said Paulette Abraham, the company's
director of marketing. Oh? Could I hook it up to my bathroom vent
and put that mysterious rap music to good use?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
