<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BARBIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANTED: F.O.B.'S (FRIENDS OF BARBIE)  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been many years since I felt even the slightest envy for
my cousin Mary Ann's collection of Barbies.
</P>
<P>
   I can barely remember how her white doll case smelled of new
plastic. Or how its cunning little gold clasp opened so smoothly to
reveal dozens of matching outfits and hats and shoes, all lined up
by color on hangers and in tiny cardboard drawers. Or how the Midge
doll was held snugly in place by an elastic strap. Or how _ if
anyone had bothered to ask _ I would have recommended against
dressing Skipper in the culottes combination with the flowered
headband.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one asked me. I was six years younger than my
cousin so I did not join her and the Hinchey girl from next door
when they played with the dolls. Could this have been the root of
the aching suspicion that my own Barbie was inferior because she
did not possess such essential accessories as a head scarf and
cat's-eye sunglasses? If so, I got over that, too. Years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what I told everyone until the other day in the
car, when my 7-year-old daughter, Ella, piped up from the back
seat. ``I saw on TV that on the Internet you can make a custard
Barbie,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customized, Ella,'' corrected Zoe, her older sister. ``There
was this commercial about how you can make a doll who is a friend
of Barbie. You pick how she looks. They mail her to you.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounded like an expensive proposition, I muttered from the
front seat. But inside, I was thinking: Yesssss. How many times had
I stood in front of Barbie displays, frustrated because none of the
zillions of available dolls were adequate substitutes for my
cousin's? But now I had hope.
</P>
<P>
   I know it's not fashionable in these days of rampant
Barbie-bashing to admit a fondness for a doll who once declared
that she preferred shopping to math. As a mother of three
daughters, I might be expected to frown on a toy whose original
theme song included the lyrics, ``Barbie's small and so petite/Her
clothes and figure look so neat. . . . Someday I'm going to be
exactly like you.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at my own childhood, I can't say that exposure to
Barbie harmed me. Perhaps it even toughened me. After devouring
such old-fashioned books as ``Cheaper by the Dozen,'' ``Life With
Father'' and ``All-of-a-Kind Family,'' I was familiar with the
concept of outdated sex-role stereotypes at a very young age. I did
not want Barbie's life style. I just needed her as a prop in
elaborate make-believe plots that involved her and Midge not
inviting my cousin along when they went to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, my daughters and I gathered expectantly at my
computer.
</P>
<P>
   A blond Barbie in a tight miniskirt appeared on the opening
screen of www.barbie.com. Clearly, we had come to the right place.
Clicking on My Design revealed the details of the customized
Barbies. Drawbacks: Each doll costs $39.95 _ plus $7.95 for
shipping _ and might not arrive for up to eight weeks. Benefits:
You are able to name your own doll, then click to choose the color
of her eyes, skin and hair, facial features, clothes, accessories
and such sexually nonspecific interests as ``community work,''
``geology'' or ``running a company.''
</P>
<P>
   At each step, the site helpfully displayed the doll in progress.
So if you made a ghastly mistake by, say, pairing the ``pulled back
and pretty'' hairstyle with the ``open mouth smile,'' it was easy
to fix with a few quick clicks.
</P>
<P>
   For Ella, the exercise turned out to be a kind of online
Rorschach test. She created a Barbie who reflected her own
personality, a doll who ``lives in the suburbs,'' ``is interested
in books'' and ``loves to play the piano.'' Ella's most agonizing
decision was choosing a hairstyle resembling her own. Since ``bangs
in the eyes and a crooked part'' was not an option, she settled for
``long and wavy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Zoe? As usual, my oldest child tried to balance her own
interests with mine. Her doll ``spends a lot of time at the beach''
but also ``loves to surf the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Did I order the dolls for them? Why even ask? The bigger
question for a Barbie addict like myself was, Why didn't I create
my own custard doll, the one I had yearned for since childhood: a
Midge with messed-up hair and a line of blue ink on her cheek?
</P>
<P>
   I would not have hesitated but my expectations had been too
high. At least that's what Lisa McKendall, Mattel's director of
marketing communications, told me when I phoned to complain that
the customization options were too limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midge got married and disappeared _ she hasn't been in the
line since the 1960s,'' Ms. McKendall explained.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. McKendall said she understood my quest. ``One time I met
a woman in New York who had this little Barbie sweater,'' she said.
``Her neighbor made it for her 35 years ago, and she felt compelled
to bring it to a meeting to show me. So sometimes it's not about
the doll so much as it is about the relationships that people had
with her.''
</P>
<P>
   My daughters will pester our mail carrier daily for the next
eight weeks. But I am patient. In my heart I believe www.barbie.com
will someday offer a Skipper in culottes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
