<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VERSION CONFUSION THE CUSTOMER LOSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The more things change, the more they drive us insane. At least
that's the way it seems in computer technology, where products have
the life spans of insects.
</P>
<P>
   The frantic pace of innovation in the computer industry is a
mixed blessing. On one hand, we benefit from a torrent of newer,
faster, better and cheaper products, creating value for the
consumer at a speed unmatched in any other industry in history.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, rapid advances in technology condemn us to a
treadmill of rapid obsolescence. It is frustrating to buy version
1.0 of something, knowing that version 1.1 is already in
development and that version 2.0 is just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   But more vexing are the phantom upgrades that we often don't
know about, midcourse corrections and improvements that are not
widely publicized by either the manufacturers or the dealers.
Sometimes the changes are subtle, while others are significant.
</P>
<P>
   The harm comes when consumers think they are buying the newest
technology, only to discover later that they purchased yesterday's
product. It is as if you went shopping for a butterfly and wound up
with a caterpillar.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, for example, the Intel Corp. introduced the Celeron
processor as a low-cost alternative to the Pentium II chip. The
Celeron was basically a Pentium II chip stripped of a high-speed
memory subsystem called Level 2, or L2, cache. Without the cache,
the enervated Celeron chip was such a dog that many major PC makers
refused to build systems around it.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Intel introduced a significantly improved Celeron
with 128 kilobytes of L2 cache. It called the new chip the
300A-megahertz Celeron, to distinguish it from the 300-MHz Celeron
chip with fleas.
</P>
<P>
   The result, however, is that Intel now offers two different
300-MHz Celeron processors. Unless the shopper is up to speed or
has a knowledgeable salesperson to help point out the right one,
there is a risk of going home with one of the original bow-wow
Celerons.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Intel's newer and faster Celerons all have the L2
cache, and all offer impressive performance for the price. Just be
aware that the 266-MHz and non-A 300- MHz chips are caterpillars.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months after it introduced the iMac computer last
summer at $1,299, Apple Computer made it better. For the same
price, Apple added a better graphics card and more video memory,
and made some other minor improvements.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid hurting sales of the original iMacs that were already
in retail stores or the distribution pipeline, neither Apple nor
the stores publicized the fact that newer and better iMacs were
available at the same price as the old ones. The only clue was a
model number that ended in B instead of A.
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling how many unsuspecting customers bought the
box containing the old A model when the revision B model could have
been sitting on the shelf right next to it or being held in the
back room until the A models were sold out.
</P>
<P>
   The transition was not prolonged because the iMacs sold so
quickly, although that is little comfort to people who bought the A
iMac when the B was already in the stores. Apple has since
introduced a new and further improved generation of iMacs and cut
the price on the older ones.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft released the Windows 98 operating system upgrade on
June 25 last year and within a week announced that a ``multimedia
enhancement'' was in the works. The upgrade to the upgrade, which
Microsoft insisted was not a bug fix, was made available in August
to customers who knew enough to check Microsoft's Web site
periodically.
</P>
<P>
   But six months after the ``enhancement'' was offered on line,
customers who buy the Windows 98 upgrade package at retail stores
are getting the same original and presumably unenhanced program
that Microsoft shipped back in June.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Microsoft includes a clever Windows Update link
under the Windows 98 Start button that automatically scans the
user's computer to determine whether there are any updates
available on line that might be helpful. The user then has the
option of downloading the latest enhancements and bug fixes.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the Symantec Corp. released a new version of its
popular Norton Systemworks utility package for Windows computers
(reviewed favorably in this space on Dec. 31). The new version
added a fifth utility to the package, an excellent program called
Cleansweep.
</P>
<P>
   The company called the new version 1.1 and labeled the disks
1.1, and the installation screen identified the software as 1.1,
all signaling that it was an update of the original, four-utility
version 1.0.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sarah Hicks, a Symantec group manager, the unusual
decision was made to call the upgraded product 1.0 because
relabeling it 1.1 might have caused dealers to pull the old
versions off the shelf. Symantec might have lost sales of the older
version, and, Ms. Hicks said, there was also a risk that harried
dealers might be too busy during the hectic holiday shopping season
to restock with a new version.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So the new version was stacked alongside the old version, and
the only difference on the box is that the new 1.0 has an added
line on the front listing five utility programs instead of four. On
the back, there is a paragraph of information about Cleansweep. The
price stayed the same. Only those customers who knew details of the
new release got the better version.
</P>
<P>
   Symantec now says that people who bought the older version can
return it for a full refund within 60 days of purchase or, if they
bought it before Nov. 30, upgrade to the new version for $9.95.
</P>
<P>
   Angry yet? Ready to quit going to computer dealers and to start
shopping on line? Not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   PC Connection (www.pcconnection.com) is still promoting the
older version of Systemworks 1.0 for the original list price of
$69.95, with no mention that it is the discontinued and inferior
version. The promotional material on the PC Connections Web site
describes the older version.
</P>
<P>
   The new version (which Symantec has now decided to call Norton
Systemworks 1.0 With Cleansweep despite the 1.1 label on the disk)
is not offered. But a spokeswoman for PC Connection said that if
Symantec was sending the new version, that is what people would
get.
</P>
<P>
   Another major online software dealer, PC Mall (www.pcmall.com),
was featuring a picture of the old Systemworks box on its front
screen this week as a ``Web-only special for a limited time only!''
The cost was $58.99, ``plus, take an extra $10 off with mfr mail-in
rebate!'' the advertising copy read. ``Norton Systemworks gives you
the current version of four powerful Symantec utilities in one
convenient box.'' But the version shipping since Nov. 30 has five
utilities, not four.
</P>
<P>
   The problem goes beyond these few products, of course. Even if
you did not buy an A-series iMac, a non-A-series Celeron 300 or
Norton Systemworks 1.0 without Cleansweep, the increasing disdain
for consumers is cause for concern. Shopping for computers and
software is hard enough these days without such cavalier treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Stores often stock thousands of products, and it is virtually
impossible to keep track of all product upgrades. Sometimes the
dealers are not told about the changes. Sometimes they are, but the
stores are too busy to swap out the older products or to pass the
word to all the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Seymour Merrin, a consultant in Santa Fe, N.M., who publishes a
newsletter on trends in computer retail, notes unhappily that big
computer stores are cutting staff and eliminating staff training
programs as competition and price pressure increase.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Harrington, editor of Computer Retail Week, says that
ultimately consumers bear the burden of thoroughly researching the
products they are buying, whether they are shopping for computers
or any other type of electronics.
</P>
<P>
   For those who lack time to do so, he advises them to seek
reputable dealers and bond with any clever and trustworthy
salespeople they encounter. Another tip, he said, is to wait six
months before buying any newly released product, to give the
companies (and less patient consumers) a chance to find and fix
early glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers appreciate the chance to buy older products,
either because stores cut the prices of trailing-edge products to
the point they are great bargains or because they own older
computers than cannot meet the newer software requirements. But if
the stores do not cut the prices, and do not tell the buyers that
the products are not current, well, that bugs me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
