<HEADER>
A1323 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-LIFE-GAME-700&AMP;ADD     01-20 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LIFE-GAME-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING SOME OF THE FUN OUT OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Product notes are at the end of article.) 
(js) 
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life was much simpler 40 years ago, when all you had to do was
spin the wheel, drive down the road, get a job, get hitched, buy a
house, take out an insurance policy, have a couple of kids, maybe
play the stock market and retire with as much money as possible.
</P>
<P>
   That was the Game of Life, first published by Milton Bradley in
1960. Times change. So do board games. Life is more complicated
now. It's a CD-ROM published by Hasbro Interactive (Milton Bradley
was bought by Hasbro midway into President Ronald Reagan's first
term). The new game is stored on a flat piece of plastic rather
than a flat piece of cardboard. These days, Life is played in front
of a computer monitor instead of around a table.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spinning a wheel, you click on an icon marked
Spinner. And instead of pushing a miniature car, you watch a
computer-generated convertible cruise through a theme-park
landscape filled with animated landmarks _ it looks like a
miniature golf course. The car radio shifts from doo-wop to
psychedelic pop, rock, disco, new wave and techno as you drive
through the decades between 1950 and 2010, past the giant drive-in,
the towering coffee cup, the monumental mortarboard, the church,
numerous vacation resorts and onward to senescence.
</P>
<P>
   The object remains: whoever retires with the most money wins.
But the means to that end have altered considerably. In the old
game, there were five careers for someone with a bachelor's degree:
doctor ($20,000 per year), lawyer ($15,000), journalist ($10,000),
teacher ($8,000) and physicist ($10,000). Or you could skip college
(meet future spouse, pay $500 for diamond ring, take a
correspondence course, pay $500) and start working for $5,000 a
year. Whatever it was, you were going to do it for the rest of your
life, then retire to Millionaire Estates or, barring that, to a
cottage in Countryside Acres.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward to 1999. The job options have expanded
considerably. You can be a doctor or a teacher. But you can also be
a travel agent, a salesperson, an athlete, an artist or a superstar
(an official job designation _ blame People magazine). Not only
that, but your salary bears no relationship to the amount of
training your job requires. Your salary comes up on a slot machine.
You could be a $30,000-a-year doctor or a $100,000-a-year athlete,
or vice versa. There are also the Lose Your Job and Mid-Life Crisis
squares to contend with _ if you land on them, you switch careers
and change salaries.
</P>
<P>
   But financial success requires more than just cruising past Pay
Day. It also depends on how often other players land on your Career
Spaces. (Have Tattoos Removed, Pay Doctor $100,000.) ``Whether
anyone lands on your Career Spaces is pure luck,'' the manual
informs us, ``so choose any career you like!''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, work is not the only way to accumulate the mountain
of cash that defines success in Life. There's also luck. But
notions of luck have changed a lot since Kennedy-era kids played
Life on rainy afternoons. In 1960, luck had a lot to do with
gambling. Lucky Day squares told you that it had been a good day at
the races or that you'd had a great weekend in Vegas. And there
were lots of chances to risk what you had. Keep the $10,000 or go
for $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those risks have been removed from the new version,
which is much more wholesome. The gambling references have gone the
way of the three-martini lunch. Instead, good luck consists of Life
Tile spaces where you are allowed to do a good deed. Learn sign
language. Support the Special Olympics. As an outward sign of
inward grace, all these activities involve a large cash payoff.
Help the homeless; earn a five-figure bonus. It looks like a
utopian dream world next to the 1960 version of Life, where every
social commitment had a cost. (``Give to charity, pay $5,000.'')
There were lots of burdensome family obligations: ``Father-in-law
needs money, pay $10,000.'' You forked over the cash. These
trade-offs were built into the game, and the object was to retire
as a millionaire despite them. You spent $500 to bail your uncle
out of jail. You didn't earn $25,000 for fishing with your kid.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The CD-ROM's goody-goody stance is somewhat hypocritical,
however. The disk runs on a home PC, which occupies the least
social space in any house. To play, you literally have to turn your
back on your family, although you can play it on the Internet,
sending chat messages back and forth to strangers.
</P>
<P>
   And for all its digital enhancements, Life on CD-ROM is actually
less interactive than its cardboard counterpart (from any era). In
a game that lasted more than an hour, my participation took 2
minutes and 11 seconds. If you're playing against the computer,
this game is pretty pointless and text messages on the Net are a
poor substitute for actual social interaction.
</P>
<P>
   The real fun in Life, or in any board game, is what happens
among the players between turns. It's not just what they say. It's
the faces they make, the laughter, the moments of spontaneous
cruelty. All of that is possible because of the space a board
creates. The game board defines a circle, a circumference of people
facing one another. The whole point of the game is to sustain that
sense of inclusion. That's why the rules of most board games are so
simple. Concentrating too hard on the rules would rob players of
the fun _ the interpersonal shenanigans that occur two feet above
the board. Those are the real games. The cardboard and plastic is
just an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Digital versions of cardboard games often miss the mark because
they don't create the right kind of space. Board game players face
in. Computer game players face out. When you sit in front of a
monitor, you're facing out, and the vista is a synthetic world
waiting to be explored. Even if it's a networked world and lots of
people are playing, the individuals are all facing out. They just
happen to be facing out toward the same thing. They're separate,
but looking in the same direction. They're linked, but they're not
connected.
</P>
<P>
   Circa 1999, that's Life.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCT NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   Game of Life
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro Interactive
</P>
<P>
   $29.95, ages 8 and up
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
