<HEADER>
A1335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICHAEL-MARKETING-NYT     01-20 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHAEL-MARKETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING LIKE MIKE
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving from muscle power to brain power is never easy. That's
the task that faces Michael Jordan, now that he has decided to
leave behind burning glycogen in favor of generating marketing
electricity. He's changing from shorts to a three-piece suit. A
Nike advertisement from last year shows him as a chief executive,
wearing a suit and sitting at a desk. And he's already on the board
of another company: Oakley, best known for its sunglasses.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the products he endorses for Oakley, and whose marketing
he has helped plan, is the $1,500 Time Bomb watch, which also
converts mechanical energy to electricity. Using a tiny flywheel,
the Time Bomb employs the wearer's natural movement to generate
electricity. The power is stored in a lithium capacitor so it never
needs a new battery. Self-winding mechanical watches have long been
around, but they stopped when at rest. By linking mechanical and
electronic, the Time Bomb can sit up to two weeks on a dresser
without stopping.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But $1,500? A gold watch, sure, a jeweled watch, but who would
buy a $1,500 watch like the Time Bomb? How many watches and the
batteries to run them could you buy for the same money? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You have your Cartiers and your Rados and your Rolexes,'' said
Colin Baden, Oakley's head designer, ``but there's a whole new
consumer group becoming affluent. They don't know what Rolex is,
but they sure know Oakley.'' The demographic group described
sounded as ifit consisted chiefly of early-round NBA draft choices.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Time Bomb's name has already resulted in Oakley getting
calls from nervous postal inspectors; its style is no more
reticent. The effect is a combination of Rube Goldberg and H.R.
Geiger, designer of sets for films like ``Alien,'' with a dose of
Groucho Marx's Professor Flywheel thrown in. It could be a prop
from some cartoony sci-fi movie like ``Space Jam,'' say, starring
Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   It's a blobby chunk of a metal the company calls X metal, a
light titanium alloy used in its frames for sunglasses. Hard metal,
hard edge _ the Time Bomb takes the shape of the Oakley ``O'' logo
and turns it into what looks like some obscure part from Jordan's
Ferrari.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The esthetic, Baden said, is ``mechanical sculpture,'' and the
company's design is called Splayed Logically Offset Geometry: SLOG
is the acronym used at Oakley. On the back of the watch is a little
glass window through which you can see its mechanism _ a glimpse
into its mystery, a courtside seat on its performance. What you see
are tiny flywheels and springs, escapements and gears, that might
seem quaint and old-fashioned in the electronic era of chips and
liquid crystals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's about showing off, of course, which is not always bad.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unlike what Jordan has done all his career: turn a
physical game into a high theatrical event.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So the Time Bomb is a warning: get ready for Michael Jordan,
designer and marketing executive. Jordan not only appears at
publicity events wearing the Time Bomb, but also is involved in the
design and marketing of it and other Oakley products, notably a
line of sunglasses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He has an innate sense of style that is very valuable to this
company,'' Baden said. ``He's an active participant in our design
department. He helps in development and hangs out in the studio.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to be skeptical of these claims, but at Nike, Jordan
has long had an active part in designing shoes and other items. The
Air Jordan line has prospered, while sales of other Nike products
have lagged.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jordan left the game, he said, because there were ``no mental
challenges left.'' But he is not so much retiring as narrowing his
focus, addressing what the business schools call his core
competence: stardom. Jordan made just $33 million a year for
playing basketball, versus $40 million for his endorsements. Like
the writer who enjoys everything about his trade except the
paperwork, he's set to enjoy all the benefits of athletic stardom
without the sweat. My 9-year-old approves. Now, he says, Jordan
will have more time to make movies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And he will have time to help design products like the Time
Bomb. But flashiness that works on the court is not necessarily
what works on the street or in the office. Converting Jordan style
into products has its limits. Being like Mike is fine up to a
point, but most of us would no more try to carry off watches and
glasses that look fine on Jordan than try to dunk from the paint.
Who said man was meant to fly, much less flywheel?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
