<HEADER>
A1346 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLET-BRITISH-COLUMB     01-20 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLET-BRITISH-COLUMBIA-2TAKES-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGINATION THAT TRANSCENDS EXPECTATIONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM LITTLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ George Bernard Shaw once described
Vancouver as ``the pick of Canada,'' and even his caustic fellow
wordsmith Dylan Thomas, in a letter to his wife, called it ``a
quite handsome hellhole.'' But a metropolis of dance? Home to an
internationally ambitious ballet company? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1985, when the latest of a series of West Coast balletic
phoenixes rose tentatively from the ashes of Pacific Ballet
Theater, nothing so ambitious as a passport appeared on the agenda
for the new Ballet British Columbia. It was to be a Vancouver-based
company with a regional mission, to bring ballet to the various
centers of its home province. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Less than a decade later, the company was dancing at Whitman
Hall at Brooklyn College, where it was characterized by Anna
Kisselgoff in The New York Times as ``a handsome group of 16
classical dancers whose bold demeanor evokes the tough, frank
manner of contemporary ballet troupes in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, John Alleyne, the company's artistic director for
the past seven years, regards that New York debut as premature, and
his associate artistic director, Marquita Witham-Lester, goes even
further: ``We were on a subscription series, and the audience
didn't know who we were. They saw ballet in the title and seemed to
expect `Giselle' or `Romeo and Juliet.' Instead, we gave them a
program of contemporary Canadian work. They left up the aisles like
lemmings.''
</P>
<P>
   So what has the company decided to offer the audience in its
return one-week New York engagement starting Tuesday at the Joyce
Theater? A program of contemporary Canadian work. Only this time,
Alleyne insists, ``We have the right theater, the right public, the
right repertory and the right dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Giselle'' and ``Romeo and Juliet'' were never in the cards for
Ballet British Columbia. Early on, its artistic directors, whether
the retired Grands Ballets Canadiens ballerina Annette av Paul or
her successors, Reid Anderson, Patricia Neary and Barry Ingham,
recognized that Vancouver lacked the resources to support a
large-scale company.
</P>
<P>
   Not that dance itself was unable to thrive. Today, Canada's
third largest city boasts 27 professional companies. But their
seasons are short, their dancers are few and their competition
includes some of the most beautiful natural scenery known to keep
people out of theaters. ``Many of the dancers who come here also
love the outdoors,'' says Ms. Lester, herself native born. ``We
have a lot of layoff time; our season is only 30 weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   A company of sybarites? Alleyne laughs at the notion. Most of
its 14 members are Canadian born and trained; some come from the
United States, Japan, China and Poland, but all are expected to
perform as soloists and contribute to the creative life of the
company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why we seek out mature dancers,'' Alleyne says. ``The
men are mostly in their early 30s, the women in their late 20s.
They came here from other companies with a clear objective: to be
part of an ensemble of individuals who can participate actively
with choreographers in the creation of new work.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, works by major international figures like John
Cranko, Jiri Kylian and William Forsythe have turned up among the
newly commissioned pieces. Through its Dance Alive series, Ballet
British Columbia also sponsors visits to Vancouver by major
domestic and foreign companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it is those specially commissioned works, literally dozens
of them over the last decade and virtually all of them Canadian,
that have given Ballet British Columbia its special identity. As a
choreographer himself, Alleyne has deliberately cultivated a
dance-making environment in the company's two modest studios. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Born in Barbados, Alleyne immigrated to Canada with his parents
at the age of 5 (his 39th birthday precedes his Joyce Theater
opening by one day). He trained at the National Ballet School in
Toronto and spent his dancing career with the Stuttgart Ballet and
the National Ballet of Canada, eventually becoming the latter's
resident choreographer before taking up his Vancouver appointment
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``John isn't just a choreographer,'' says Trisha Baldwin,
executive director of the ballet company. ``He is a leader. He
understands dancers. He knows how to talk to audiences. He draws
everyone into the process of creation.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is often part of Alleyne's own process of creation to
give the dancers ideas and have them work out some of the actual
steps. For someone reared in a strict environment of balletic
classicism, he champions a surprising amount of invention in the
studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inviting the dancers to work this way can make getting to the
end result a longer journey,'' he says. ``The reward is seeing them
develop as creative beings. I'm a huge lover of classical ballet,
but I want it to remain a creative art form.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although Alleyne clearly chooses his dancers, he likes to say
that they also choose him, and in large measure because of his way
of working. The company he took to New York last time was
different: he had inherited most of those dancers. ``They were good
dancers, but they weren't really my dancers,'' he says. ``I didn't
want to go back to New York until I felt the company had an
opportunity to develop a new repertory that we had worked on
together. Only one of the works is mine, but I'm not really that
magnanimous. The three others all appeal to my admiration for craft
and refinement in movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The other works include ``There, Below,'' a dance for five
couples exploring James Kudelka's fascination with the art of
partnering; ``The Fall,'' a duet by Serge Bennathan lamenting man's
self-destructiveness, and ``Conversation Piece,'' Mark Godden's
portrait of forbidden love inspired by 18th-century genre painting
of fashionable people.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these choreographers has enjoyed a close association
with another Canadian company: Kudelka with the National Ballet, of
which he is currently artistic director; Bennathan with the Toronto
modern-dance ensemble Dancemakers, which he directs, and Godden
with the Royal Winnipeg Ballet, for which he functioned for several
years as resident choreographer. In fact, Alleyne's own ``Sex Is My
Religion'' is the only work on the Joyce program to have been
created for Ballet British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its title (which comes from a play by the Canadian
dramatist Colin Thomas), Alleyne's ballet has less to do with
either sex or religion than with the lifelong impact of the
relationship between a mother and child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things rarely happen in a linear way in my ballets,'' he
explains. ``Everything is highly textured. Phrases break up and
continue two minutes later. The work shifts very rapidly in its
emotional intent. I used to say I do 20 minutes of bombardment and
5 minutes of pleasure. I guess I still do that, but I think now
that it is sometimes important to show not what is but what one
hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly an idealist, Alleyne has let his capacity to hope mellow
the anger sometimes found in his earlier work. ``My parents were
brought up in a time when they were regarded as lesser beings in
the Caribbean,'' he says. ``And I experienced some of the same
feelings in my life in North America and Europe. But if I had
allowed tradition to win, I would never have come to where I am
today. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognized this particularly when Arthur Mitchell invited me
to do a work for Dance Theater of Harlem,'' says Alleyne, who has
also choreographed for the New York City Ballet's Diamond Project.
The work in Harlem, he adds, ``was one of the best experiences of
my life, being in the studio with his dancers and realizing that
their stories were my stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Home is nonetheless the far-from-Harlem studios on Vancouver's
west side, where Alleyne and his dancers do their primary work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided,'' he says, smiling, ``that there is no point
competing with the incredible beauty of the mountains and the
ocean. A lot of artists can't bear to work in such an environment.
They feel inessential. But because Vancouver is relatively small
and isolated, there is a real feeling of community among the
artists who do work here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in Europe for eight years in an environment in which
tradition had been written and no one was expected to diverge from
it. In Vancouver, we are still writing our tradition, and that is
why I find it one of the most exciting places to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
