<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TURKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG `TURKS' CARRY IRISH BANNER INTO SWEEPS BATTLE FOR CBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the last shall be first.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seems with ``Turks,'' the last morsel in the 1998-99
stew of Irish-flavored programming, and possibly the tastiest.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, ``Turks'' may need the luck of the Irish to survive its
midseason tryout. It will air Thursdays at 9 p.m., a slot owned by
NBC for much of this decade, thanks to the strength and quality of
``Seinfeld.'' Perceiving a chink in NBC's ``Seinfeld''-free armor
now, CBS hopes to make inroads by sending ``Turks'' over the
battlements in a quest for more Thursday night viewers,
particularly during the February ratings sweep, which begins next
Thursday. (ABC recently did the same thing, albeit with the god of
love, ``Cupid.'')
</P>
<P>
   CBS's move is risky, because ``Diagnosis Murder'' has been a
shrewd piece of counterprogramming that earned CBS a loyal audience
on Thursdays at 9. The problem is that it's an older-skewing
audience, a demographic not coveted by Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turks,'' which is appealing despite a reliance on timeworn
cliches, is aimed at the lucrative 18-to-49-year-old demographic,
and if CBS can attract the same number of viewers that it attracts
to ``Diagnosis Murder,'' the network can actually make more money
because advertisers are willing to pay more for a younger audience.
One problem: People who like ``Diagnosis Murder'' for its light,
formulaic approach in the manner of ``Murder, She Wrote'' aren't
likely to warm to ``Turks,'' a darker, character-driven endeavor
with continuing story arcs from week to week. This means CBS may
have to bring an entirely new group into the tent. (``Diagnosis
Murder'' switches to 8 p.m. Thursdays for the time being, while
``Promised Land'' takes a breather.)
</P>
<P>
   Joe Turk would never put up with such shenanigans, but,
unfortunately, he's only make believe and he has no say in how long
``Turks'' will stay on the air, or where it appears in the
schedule. For better or worse, William Devane plays Sergeant Turk
with the firm jaw and steely gaze you'd expect of a tough Chicago
policeman who wouldn't hesitate to pull over a network exec on
suspicion of DUI _ decision-making under the influence (of
advertisers).
</P>
<P>
   Turk has two sons who are also cops, and another whose gambling
habit puts him at odds with the family code of honor, not to
mention on the wrong side of the law. Turk's marriage is rocky, and
his relationship with his sons, while close, wouldn't exactly
qualify as warm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turks'' is from executive producer Robert Singer, who has
plumbed both the lighter drama (``Lois and Clark: The New
Adventures of Superman'') and the weightier stuff (``Midnight
Caller'') with some success. Thursday night's effort is notable for
its subtle melding of humor and drama into a mixture that is
pleasing, though numbingly familiar.
</P>
<P>
   As dramas go, ``Turks'' is no ``EZ Streets.'' The scripts honor
the time-tested police-drama banalities: the ethical cop forced to
make the tough choice, the question over whether a ``good shoot''
was justified, the inevitable wounding of a principal character.
The latter happens to Mike Turk (David Cubitt) in episode three,
and if I were a betting man like Mike's brother Paul (Michael
Muhney), I'd plunk down some serious folding money on odds that
Mike will pull through, maybe after a close brush with the
hereafter.
</P>
<P>
   The cliches are annoying, but the writing is solid enough and
the characters compelling enough to make a viewer put his feet up
on the ottoman and sit for a spell. Devane is especially fun to
watch, as is Ashley Crow, who plays a waitress who helps Turk deal
with his loveless marriage. The plots run a little deeper than the
sort of programming CBS does best, but if ``Turks'' works, CBS will
have begun a monumental revision of its Thursday night diagnosis _
from murder to money.
</P>
<P>
   Turks. Hourlong police drama about a close-knit Chicago family.
Starring William Devane, David Cubitt, Ashley Crow, Matthew John
Armstrong, Helen Carey, Michael Muhney and Sarah Trigger. Premieres
Friday night on CBS. Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
