<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRIBUTE TO JUDITH: A SUCCESSFUL ARTIST, MOTHER AND WIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the flower bed below the deck, where she could
delight in their color, promising green daffodil shoots nudged
through the winter leaf mulch. And the woman who in many columns
you've come to know as ``Wife Person'' allowed as how it seemed a
tad early for spring in Seattle, but that she was anxious to have
me uncover them so she might see them by Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hahn, my wife and partner for 36 springtimes, won't be
asking me to pick her a fresh bouquet of her very own daffodils. My
Judith died suddenly, of a heart attack, last Friday in Evergreen
Hospital Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was very comforting that several of her doctors cried when
they later talked to me. Most everyone who met Judith liked her,
and we can all take her untimely death a little personally. I
shared her with you in columns because she was very, very special.
</P>
<P>
   You often read that someone died ``after a courageous battle.''
And Judith never ceded so much as an inch or a minute of precious
time to the chronic progressive form of multiple sclerosis that
took a little bit of her energy and capabilities every year. After
20 years learning to play the rotten hand she was dealt, she was on
her way out of the hospital, after her second successful surgery in
a month, and downright enthusiastic about life.
</P>
<P>
   She had repeatedly rejected professional advice about going into
``a facility,'' and opted, instead, to live and work at home. An
overwhelming number of friends and health care professionals knew
we could handle it. If you are a caregiver, you know.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a whole lot we couldn't do, even considering the
physical limitations that put her in a wheelchair. She could be
hell on wheels once she powered-up her new electric wheelchair and
zipped down the sidewalk or through a shopping mall. But she was a
gentle, refined and very sensitive woman who gave much more to
life, and to those around her, than ever she asked or expected. And
while she did not suffer fools lightly, neither was she a snob. She
loved to share and to teach as much as she loved to learn.
</P>
<P>
   She was beautiful, my wife. A dazzling smile, twinkly blue eyes
and lovely blonde hair. We grew up about a block from one another
in Chicago, and went to the same grade school and high school, the
same church, etc., but never dated. Eventually we both went to the
University of Illinois, where she was an art student and I was one
of those perpetual college drop-in-and-outers. The minute I saw the
cute little blonde from the old neighborhood walk out of the
college dorm as a beautiful young woman, my heart went into my
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   She had me framing paintings two days later. Two years later, we
married while still students. We followed her academic work to
Michigan State University, where she earned a master of fine arts
degree. Judith was winning professional art competitions before she
was graduated. Her work is in the Brooklyn Museum, the Smithsonian,
and many major collections.
</P>
<P>
   About the time we followed my work here, far from our respective
families, she was diagnosed with this crippling disease that
eventually made it difficult and then impossible to water ski,
garden, walk or drive. She had to give up physically demanding
printmaking and became a painter. A Northwest painter.
</P>
<P>
   Her eye delighted in the patterns of forest ferns or water
waves, and she was excited at seeing row upon row of daffodils in
the Skagit Valley or dahlias in the Sammamish Valley below our
home, or the sea of bobbing heads at Bumbershoot. Lord, did she
love Bumbershoot, and the Folklife Festival, and the University
Street Fair. She knew I disliked these crowds, but she came home
exhausted and utterly happy at having been out in the moving tide
of people.
</P>
<P>
   She fell in love with Puget Sound and insisted we travel down
the county roads and blacktops that took her close to the fields
and the farms and rivers. She saw, and later captured in her
paintings, the simple elegance of ferns and fences and the
rough-cut beauty of sunlight on river rocks. People in Pioneer
Square and boats at Port Angeles. She even made the Ballard Bridge
look good.
</P>
<P>
   And she tried _ oh, how she tried _ to make me look good. As I
would dress quietly every weekday morning in the dim light of our
closet, trying hard not to wake her, I would turn to leave and
hear: ``You're not going into Seattle dressed like THAT, are
you?!'' But she was my best editor and fairest fan. And I think,
despite the rolling of her eyes, that she was pleased to be known
as ``Wife Person'' as much as Judith Hahn, signature member of
Northwest Watercolor Society.
</P>
<P>
   She never complained how unfair it was; neither did she feel
sorry for herself, or let anyone else do so. She was not a
``handicapped artist,'' she insisted, but simply an artist who
happened to be in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   And a very active and caring wife and mother. She made it to all
those wet, cold soccer games, to all the school concerts, to all
the Scout ceremonies. And, to our great joy, our son's wedding
aboard the old ferry Skansonia last spring. Judith painted the
portrait that Stefan and Christie used for their wedding
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   She was a remarkable woman, My Judith, not for what she endured
so much as for her daily victories, and for the way she could light
up a room. Her light never dimmed till the very end.
</P>
<P>
   It is really hard writing of Judith in past tense. As I busied
myself with cleaning away those medical supplies and equipment that
had become part of our daily homelife, I paused at a simple
disposable paper cup on the sink. It was rimmed with her lipstick
impressions. And I cannot yet discard it.
</P>
<P>
   I know that's sorta silly. There are all her prints and
paintings, all those album photographs. Everything in our home
reflects her touch, her vision. When my older sister died not long
ago, Judith felt my hurt and bought me a lavender rose plant to
remind me of my sister.
</P>
<P>
   And just now, in the flower bed below the deck where she loved
to look down on them, the daffodils are coming to life again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
