<HEADER>
A1370 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-GAMBLERS-&AMP;GANSTE     01-20 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GAMBLERS-&AMP;GANSTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR RELISHES THE BAD SIDE OF THE GOOD OLD DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In the 1940s and '50s, Fort Worth was
renowned for its Cats baseball team, its pioneer status in the TV
industry, civic icon Amon Carter and a slew of illicit sin palaces
where gangland types knocked one another off in real-life imitation
of Dashiell Hammett's bloody private-eye fiction. Although the
Cats, early TV and Carter have been woven into modern-day versions
of city history, the shady stuff, like an embarrassing relative's
snapshot in a stuffy family's photo album, has been pointedly
overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't see why,'' says Ann Arnold, a Fort Worth
educator and activist. ``When I first moved to the city in 1949,
there was so much of that going on _ gambling, gangland slayings _
that to me the interesting thing was the dichotomy between us
normal folks and the gamblers and gangsters. I mean, it wasn't like
today, with drive-by shootings and nobody safe in their front
yards. It was a completely separate, fascinating culture.''
</P>
<P>
   After a fruitless search for books about Fort Worth history that
included material about those wild-and-woolly days, Arnold decided
to write her own. Two years later, the result is ``Gamblers &AMP;
Gangsters,'' published by Eakin Press of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing the book turned out to be very easy,'' says Arnold,
66. ``I started by going to the (Fort Worth) public library, where
they had a folder with some newspaper clippings about gamblers who
had been indicted in 1951. From there, I studied other newspaper
accounts and got some names of people to contact. I talked to them,
and most of them would say, `You've got to talk to so-and-so, too,'
and it just spread from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Arnold's sources included veteran area journalists
such as Carl Freund and Madeline Williams, former Fort Worth Cats
manager Bobby Bragan and Gerald Saxon of the University of Texas at
Arlington's Special Collections Division. But most of her best
material came from descendants of Jacksboro Highway hooligans and
even, in the case of 90ish George Wilderspin, straight from the
lips of one of the participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just loved George,'' Arnold says, laughing about the
colorful gangland character. ``He's such a crusty old fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   As ``Gamblers &AMP; Gangsters'' relates, in the 1940s and '50s much
of the Jacksboro Highway became a haven for illicit gambling
joints, prostitution rings and strong-arm financial shenanigans
that would never have passed muster in a court of law. Much of the
dirty dealing went on, however, with area law enforcement carefully
looking the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Even the area's leading newspaper was a conspirator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amon Carter didn't want anything in the `Star-Telegram' that
detracted from the image he wanted his city to have,'' Arnold says.
``If we find today that most of these gangster stories have been
swept under the rug for decades, well, Amon Carter had a lot to do
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, however, makes up for anyone else's attempts to pretend
that the bad things didn't happen. ``Gamblers &AMP; Gangsters'' begins
Nov. 22, 1950, when all-around nasty fellow Nelson Harris and his
pregnant wife were killed by a car bomb. It took the death of
Juanita Harris and her unborn child, Arnold writes, to make
upstanding Fort Worth residents ``realize crime and corruption were
serious problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite lengthy accounts of other gory deaths, ``Gamblers &AMP;
Gangsters'' also provides its share of chuckles. Elmer Sharp, an
enforcer so tough that he wrestled his own pet bear, is recalled as
someone who still could be beaten up by his mother. Reporters for
an evening paper are depicted trying to talk a police chief into
timing his raids to fit their deadlines and not those of their
morning competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to be a fun book,'' Arnold says. ``I guess that's
because I still see myself as a teacher who tries to make history
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   She evidently has. Eakin Press has ordered a second ``Gamblers &AMP;
Gangsters'' printing, and Arnold has had requests for the book from
as far away as Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``That surprised me, because I thought it would be only of local
interest,'' she admits. ``But people just seem to like it. Even
surviving relatives of people who were not treated too kindly in
the book _ treated objectively, I hope, but not kindly _ have said
they liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold's plans for her next book projects include a look at
local law schools and courts, and a novel based on real-life Fort
Worth crime. The latter is already written; Arnold is shopping for
a publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like writing, and when you work on one book you hear
something that can lead to another project,'' she says. ``I'm glad
`Gamblers &AMP; Gangsters' is pleasing people. It's about things that
are part of what made Fort Worth what it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
