<HEADER>
A1378 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-COMEDY-2TAKES-     01-20 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-COMEDY-2TAKES-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE NEW RUSSIA, COMEDY LACKS BITE  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It's not hard to make fun of what is happening in
Russia these days. New jokes about the new rich (now the new poor
after last summer's financial crisis) are posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin's fumbling speech is always an easy
laugh. There may be more comedy routines about bank failures than
there are solvent banks in Russia. But real humor _ the deep,
biting, funny-sad satire that makes Russians laugh, usually at
themselves _ has become rarer, or at least so says Mikhail
Zhvanetsky, the country's premier stand-up comedian and humor
writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In prison, without freedom, humor is much more interesting; it
is nobler somehow,'' he said on the eve of his most recent one-man
show in Tchaikovsky Hall, Moscow's biggest concert hall. ``It
carries with it the idea of protest, of a struggle against the
regime. And everybody is in agreement. In fact, that was the great
achievement of Soviet power: people were unanimous, everyone
thought the same. Just try to achieve something like that in a free
society. Never. You'll fail.''
</P>
<P>
   People may have laughed in unison in the old days, but that
doesn't make Zhvanetsky nostalgic for censorship. It just means he
has had to adjust to a new reality, to audiences that are more
distracted, more divided, more diverse _ and smaller. Tchaikovsky
Hall was only two-thirds full on the night of his big concert (in
part because ticket prices averaged $10, too high for the average
Zhvanetsky devotee), and the bond between comedian and audience,
once strung tight with the tension of political risk, seemed at
times to go flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``All information is available; a satirist cannot discover
anything new,'' said Zhvanetsky, 64, ``so humor doesn't play the
role it played before. Now is the time for satirists to show off
their talent. Before, it was enough to prove they were brave.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Zhvanetsky _ a short, balding man who, with glasses
perched on the end of his nose, reads his material from typewritten
sheets, legs apart and chest thrust forward _ makes people laugh.
Sometimes they laugh so hard they cry.
</P>
<P>
   When NTV, Russia's largest private television station, recently
broadcast a 16-part series of pure Zhvanetsky, showing him reading
through a collection of work written over the last 30 years, it was
at the top of the ratings, except for one night when another
station tried to fight back with Peter Falk in an old ``Colombo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Zhvanetsky is No. 1, both in the Soviet Union, now in Russia,
and in all points of the world where Russian-speakers live,'' said
Gennady Khazanov, another well-known comedian who, like Zhvanetsky,
had his heyday in the ``perestroika'' years of the 1980s. ``For the
majority of thinking people, he is the symbol of humor in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis here is on the word ``thinking.'' Zhvanetsky and
others are quick to point out that the general level of humor in
Russia has sunk as the country has emerged into the bright light of
freedom. ``Before, humor was aimed at the level of the head, then
it went down to the heart, then we had jokes about health,'' said
Zhvanetsky. ``Now it has slipped even lower, with most of it at
about the urogenital level. It is not even about sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the language of humor has changed, coarsened by the
criminal jargon that has crept into Russian speech. ``I sometimes
get advice,'' he said. ``People say, `Misha, you should spend some
time in prison, a year or two.' They say, `You would see such
interesting things there, and it would make your humor so
understandable to the people.' That's why we have this exchange:
the satirist amuses the public by mimicking what he or she has seen
or heard watching the public. So he is amused watching them, then
they are amused watching him.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so with Zhvanetsky, who now as before manages to infuse his
sketches with philosophical insights and literary touches. His work
is in the same class as the books of Ilf and Petrov, writers of the
1930s who, like Zhvanetsky, were from Odessa, the Black Sea port
known as the crucible of Russian-Jewish humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a classic,'' said Leonid Parfyonov, general producer at
NTV. ``He writes about the national character with a kind of
philosophical lyricism. It is literature, and such things don't
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhvanetsky, who worked for a while as a mechanic at the Odessa
port, began as a writer of monologues for a local satirical
theater. In the 1960s, his work attracted the attention of Arkady
Raikin, a legendary Russian comic actor. But Zhvanetsky's notoriety
as a performer as well as a writer peaked later, when he began to
appear behind closed doors at Russia's elite establishments. There,
his listeners _ sometimes scientists, sometimes high-ranking
bureaucrats, once even cosmonauts out there circling in space _
were trusted to keep his jokes secret.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they eventually leaked out, and like the bitter songs
of Russia's beloved bard, Vladimir Vystotsky, circulated widely on
scratchy recordings.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Zhvanetsky returned to the public stage in the
mid-80s, his monologues, like Vysotsky's songs, had already been
committed to memory by legions of fans from all walks of life,
dissidents and Communist party members, workers and physicists,
anybody who found the daily burdens of Soviet life both unbearable
and unbearably funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zhvanetsky personified deep perplexity,'' Yuri Bogomolov wrote
in a review in the newspaper Izvestia about the Zhvanetsky classics
after they were broadcast on NTV. ``He didn't lash out, or skip
around. He simply tried to figure out the logic of what was
happening to us. Having found it, he understood that this logic was
absurd. That was the essence of his satire. Step by step, sketch
after sketch, he created an encyclopedia of Soviet absurdity that
eventually turned out to be, unintentionally, the true history of
the Soviet state.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, much of that absurdity continues today in the new
Russia. The sketch that got the biggest laugh at Tchaikovsky Hall
was about a befuddled Russian Everyman who is told to sit still and
keep quiet as former leaders of the Young Communist League turn
their wagons around and become young capitalist bankers, only now
to change signals and turn around again. Somehow, the Everyman is
always left bringing up the rear.
</P>
<P>
   Some old Soviet themes _ like that of the endless queuing up for
scarce goods _ have been replaced by more modern Russian ones about
cars queuing up to inspect prostitutes. There are more topical
jokes, about homosexuals who are released from the usual
obligations on International Women's Day, about Jews who are
ashamed to be Jews, and about sex.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these might not pass muster in the United States, but
then Zhvanetsky _ who makes regular trips to appear before
audiences of Russian immigrants _ freely confesses to not
understanding modern American morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the part of America I like the least,'' he said, ``the
relations between men and women, all this business about sexual
harassment. People don't know where to look, what to touch. It
makes me worry about where the next generation of Americans are
going to come from.'' Like most Russians, he finds the Clinton
scandal baffling, but above all ``ungentlemanly'' on the part of
the congressional investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Although he still mocks politicians, Zhvanetsky says he wants to
move away from attacks on the government, and take a closer look at
Russians themselves. ``Finally I realized that it is not the
government we should focus on but ourselves,'' he said, ``that is,
those of us who don't want to work. It has been described before:
people sit in a cage, the cage opens, and they are unwilling to get
out. It's ridiculous, but there is a strong desire of Soviet people
to work on a collective farm. There, you can steal and you can
drink, calmly.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most other comedians, Zhvanetsky has little time for the
ever-circulating jokes about the new Russians, as the
gold-bedecked, Mercedes-driving new rich in Russia are called. ``It
is a huge sphere of humor for everybody but me,'' he said. ``I also
touch upon it, but since I try my best to improve life, I prefer to
prod those who do nothing. In fact, everyone is a bit sick and
tired of new-Russian jokes. They are too primitive, both the jokes
and the new Russians themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
