A1390 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TURKS-BOS &LR;      01-20 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TURKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TURKS' OFFERS NOTHING NEW IN COP SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TURKS 
Starring: William Devane, David Cubitt, Michael Muhney, Sara
Trigger, Helen Carey, Matthew John Armstrong, Ashley Crowe 
On: CBS, Thursday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pity TV's poor cop-show writers, having to churn out scene after
scene in a genre that truly has been there, done that, and revealed
some serious rear end along the way. After two decades of ace crime
dramas like ``Hill Street Blues,'' ``NYPD Blue,'' and ``Homicide,''
all of which spent years breaking new ground, there just isn't much
fertile territory left to explore. And so we find recent
urban-police series _ last year's ``Brooklyn South,'' for instance,
and now a midseason replacement called ``Turks'' _ simply going
through the motions, with the cops racing up tenement stairs to
round up perps and pimps, or dodging the well-manicured hand of
internal affairs, or falling into bed for affairs of a less
criminal nature. And don't forget to add plenty of street-poetic
cursing. Formerly an adjective used to mean fresh and real,
``gritty'' now connotes little more than tired and cliche.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turks,'' which premieres Thursday at 9 p.m., has the great
advantage of William Devane, the rubber-faced actor best remembered
from his 10-year stint on ``Knots Landing.'' With his downturned
mouth and piranha teeth, he brings the weight and ease and
distinction that a cop show like ``Brooklyn South'' sorely lacked.
He's sort of a small-screen Jack Nicholson. But even Devane, who
plays the police-sergeant father of three sons, two of whom are
cops, can't rescue ``Turks'' from the TV vacuum. By the time, in
episode 2, that Devane must talk a jittery kid out of a drug-store
hostage situation, it's clear the series is going to make no effort
at originality, content to become nothing more than a police-drama
parallel to the medical regurgitations of ``L.A. Doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago family at the center of ``Turks'' is Irish, a newish
TV gimmick that was the much-noted glue of three fall series, the
similar ``To Have and to Hold'' and ``Trinity'' as well as the
sitcom ``Costello,'' all of which have been canceled. ``Turks'' is
less offensive in its stereotyping than those other shows, although
the boys do spend a bit too much of their time at Emmit's Tavern,
doncha know. We quickly learn the undiscussed Turk family problems,
mainly that Devane's Joe Turk is married to a bitter church-going
woman who can't bear his touch. Of the two sons on the force, Mike
is the married father of one who will undoubtedly be paired with a
comely female partner at some point, and Joey is the younger
hothead who explodes when a sloppy older cop insults Joey's mother.
Both of them struggle with unfavorable comparisons to their heroic
dad. The third son, Paul, is a compulsive gambler whose part in a
heist triggers a chain of only-on-TV coincidences that put Joey
under investigation by internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Could ``Turks'' develop into something worthwhile? The signs
don't point that way, even as Devane's very presence does battle
with the mediocrity around him. The dialogue creaks from the
opening moments of the show, when a waitress delivers an obscenity
to a lewd customer with the help of some word play involving a
hockey disc. And the action scenes are clothed in painfully
familiar trappings, with crimes set in abandoned warehouses, bad
guys who seem to have acne and bad noses, and shooting that lapses
into oh-so-stylized slow-mo. It's all very . . . gritty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
