<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT &LR;      01-20 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT AGE THING 
TRIXIE HELPS OUT 
A LOSING BET
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you question someone who asks questions for a living,
choose your words carefully.
</P>
<P>
   After a talk Jan. 14 by LESLEY STAHL, a correspondent on the CBS
News magazine ``60 Minutes'' and the author of the just-published
autobiography ``Reporting Live'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), a woman in the
audience at the National Press Club in Washington tried to ask a
question about television's reputation for pushing women aside as
they age. Fumbling for words, she said something about, ``Now that
you're in your golden years. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd gasped and giggled. Ms. Stahl, 57, smiled. ``I can't
say the word that's come to mind,'' she said, apparently referring
to her questioner, ``but it _ in the words of Barbara Bush _ it
rhymes with witch.''
</P>
<P>
   There was laughter as Ms. Stahl said, ``Go ahead, go ahead, tit
for tat, tit for tat.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she mentioned several other women who have had long careers
in television news, including BARBARA WALTERS, DIANE SAWYER and
CONNIE CHUNG.
</P>
<P>
   A little while later, Ms. Stahl apologized, saying that she had
intended the remark to be funny but she feared that it had not come
across that way. She also invited the woman to come up to the
platform and shake her hand.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that she misquoted Mrs. Bush, whose 1984 remark
about GERALDINE A. FERRARO was, ``I can't say it, but it rhymes
with rich.'' Later Mrs. Bush said the word she had had in mind was
``witch.'' (Ms. Stahl, whose office said she was traveling Tuesday,
did not return a call for comment.)
</P>
<P>
   TRIXIE HELPS OUT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the speedy one,'' said the actress JOYCE RANDOLPH, who
played Trixie on ``The Honeymooners'' in the 1950s. Now, wearing
comfortable shoes and a fur coat, she was talking about a friend,
the restaurateur JEAN-CLAUDE BAKER.
</P>
<P>
   He had recruited her for an unusual assignment: walk at a
leisurely pace from his restaurant, Chez Josephine, on West 42nd
Street near Ninth Avenue, to every theater in the neighborhood.
Baker would walk at a faster pace. Both had stopwatches to see how
long each trip took.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to quiet theatergoing customers who worry about how
long they can stay at Baker's restaurant without being late for a
performance. He was tired of having customers worry that they were
lollygagging over the lobster cassoulet.
</P>
<P>
   Synchronizing stopwatches, he and Ms. Randolph set out.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at the Westside Theater, a block away at 407 W. 43rd
St., in 1 minute 59 seconds. She arrived in 3 minutes 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   They walked back to the restaurant and headed for the theater
where ``The Lion King'' is playing, the New Amsterdam, at 214 W.
42nd St. near Seventh Avenue. Baker recorded his time as 6 minutes
35 seconds, Ms. Randolph's as 9 minutes 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   As they left for the next destination, the Nederlander Theater
on West 41st Street, where ``Rent'' is playing, Baker seemed
pleased. ``People behave like children, panicking at 7:15, when we
all know you have 50 minutes because the show will never start
before 5 minutes past,'' he said.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A LOSING BET &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, NINA TOTENBERG, a correspondent for National Public
Radio, made a bet on the air. She bet two broadcast-booth
colleagues, NEAL CONAN and DANIEL SCHORR, $1 each that President
Clinton's lawyers would forgo their scheduled Tuesday presentation
at the impeachment trial to avoid competing with the State of the
Union Message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost, right?'' Ms. Totenberg said by telephone Tuesday,
having all but forgotten the wager.
</P>
<P>
   Did it prove anything?
</P>
<P>
   ``It proves that when you've been covering the same story for
months and been live on the air for in one case 15 hours straight
filling as much as an hour and a half at a time,'' she said,
``you'll say almost anything.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POPE-0121-COX     01-20 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-0121-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POTATO CHIPS DEVOTED TO THE POPE AND OTHER VENTURES STIR DEBATE
IN MEXICO
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins 600 words.
 &HT;    With POPE-SKED-0121.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ With all due respect, John Paul II is fast
becoming known here as the Potato Pope.
</P>
<P>
   The not-so-holy nickname is derived from a debate that's broken
out in Mexico over the unusual level of marketing to promote Pope
John Paul II's fourth visit to Mexico, which begins Friday.
</P>
<P>
   To help finance or publicize the pope's tour, Catholic officials
in Mexico approached Sabritas, a popular Mexican potato chip
company, and about two dozen other corporations seeking donations.
</P>
<P>
   Sabritas, a division of the U.S.-based Frito-Lay -- a subsidiary
of PepsiCo -- took up the clergy's invitation by churning out
special commemorative bags of chips wrapped in a yellow ribbon
emblazoned with the Vatican's coat of arms.
</P>
<P>
   Inside each bag, buried among the salty fare, is a tiny
photograph of the pope or one of nine other religious figures
revered by Mexicans. Sabritas is also selling a separate
card-holder for two pesos -- about 20 cents -- so that the faithful
can collect all 10 photographs and display them.
</P>
<P>
   Not lost on Mexicans is the fact that, in Spanish, the word
``papa'' means both pope and potato.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's purely coincidental,'' said Tod MacKenzie(CQ both), a
spokesman for Frito-Lay in Plano, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie said the chips, which have the full blessing of the
Catholic church, are selling well at three pesos a bag (about 25
cents) despite media reports here that some Mexicans think the
pope's visit has been over-commercialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The archdiocese (in Mexico City) approached Sabritas and a
number of other companies and asked them to help spread the word,''
MacKenzie said. ``They were looking for non-traditional ways to
reach Mexicans in every corner of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabritas, he said, was ``frankly, quite honored to be approached
for such a worthy cause.'' With 90 million photographs inside the
bags and some 400,000 Sabritas distribution points around Mexico,
MacKenzie said, the church will be able to reach ``an awful lot of
the faithful.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated $200,000 in profits from the sales of the
card-holders will be donated to the Pilgrim Aid Foundation, a fund
for the construction of a house to host pilgrims visiting Mexico
City's famed Our Lady of Guadalupe Basilica.
</P>
<P>
   One of those pilgrims who was visiting the Basilica this week,
however, said she didn't really appreciate the potato chips
dedicated to the pope, who has frequently spoken out against
materialism and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have distributed those photos for free, without
putting them inside bags of chips, couldn't they?'' said Teresa
Duran of Ciudad Juarez, a city on the Texas-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   A cartoon in the Mexico City newspaper La Jornada lampooned such
business ventures celebrating the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many commercial messages, will I have time for the
divine word?'' the pope wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Cardinal Norberto Rivera, speaking to Mexico City's
Reforma newspaper, defended the potato chips venture and other
corporate publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in an era of publicity, and we are men of this era,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other corporations contributing services or money
include Mexicana Airlines, which will fly the pope to St. Louis,
Mo., and Hewlett Packard, which contributed high-tech know-how.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi, the soft drink giant, has erected a number of huge
billboards in Mexico City promoting the pope's visit and declaring,
``Mexico, Always Faithful,'' a slogan with the same hip ring of the
``Pepsi Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Azteca television station, which promises saturation
coverage of the pope, has been running commercials designed to stir
faith -- and, some people say, attract viewers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the commercials features a fictional truck driver who
becomes incensed when a tire blows out during a rain storm. He
slams the door of his truck so hard his rosary beads fall from his
rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   A hand in vestments calmly retrieves the rosary beads, a
ubiquitous decoration in Mexican vehicles. The camera cuts to the
back of a bent, almost ghostly figure that's obviously supposed to
be the pope walking along the road.
</P>
<P>
   An opinion poll of 400 Mexico City residents conducted by
Reforma found that among those who had seen the commercials 63
percent thought they were publicity for the station while only 25
percent thought they were a ``spiritual message.''
</P>
<P>
   But the same poll found that 50 percent of Mexico City residents
believed that the commercialization of the pope's image would be
``positive'' for the promotion of Catholicism in Mexico. Only 37
percent said the marketing would have a negative impact.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City resident Florentina Caudillo, 76, a devout Catholic
who was also at the Basilica is among those who are not offended by
the marketing flurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the way businesses want to express their faith,
that's OK with me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1731EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1424 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WISDOM-NYTSF &LR;      01-20 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WISDOM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE TOO SURE OF A `MARRED' LEGACY FOR CLINTON -- THE
UN-REAGAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By JIM CASTELLI  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The conventional wisdom -- the consensus among politicians and
media personalities -- has been consistently wrong about the
scandal surrounding President Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
 &HT;    Those who create such ``wisdom'' have been more concerned with
what they want to happen, or what they think is supposed to happen,
rather than what is actually happening.
 &HT;    That's more than enough reason to question the confident
statements that Bill Clinton has been weakened anddisgraced and his
legacy permanently marred.
 &HT;    Put another way, there is reason to believe that Clinton has, in
fact, been strengthened by the scandal and that his legacy will be
far more positive than anyone now imagines.
 &HT;    To be sure, future historians are hardly likely to talk about
Clinton without referring to his impeachment following a full year
of headlines about a sexual scandal. But that won't be the whole
story.
 &HT;    Andrew Johnson was impeached, but historians now generally agree
that his impeachment was highly partisan and that it was Congress,
not Johnson, who was disgraced.
 &HT;    Historians also generally agree that Richard Nixon would have
been impeached and convicted over Watergate-related offenses, and
would have deserved to be, if he had not resigned.
 &HT;    But Nixon's legacy is far bigger than Watergate. His conduct of
the Vietnam War, detente with the Soviet Union, opening of
relations with Communist China, and his domestic policies -- many
of which would be regarded as dismayingly liberal by today's House
Republicans -- are also part of a very mixed legacy.
 &HT;    Bill Clinton was impeached on virtually a straight party-line
vote in the House, but no one beyond a handful of anti-Clinton true
believers think that the Senate trial will result in conviction. At
worst Clinton will receive a censure, at best (for him), nothing
more than impeachment by the House. If Clinton is still president
when all this is over, he will have won.
 &HT;    The notion that he has been weakened by the scandal ignores
public opinion, which has been consistent and resistant for a year.
The more Republicans attack Clinton, the more the public thinks
positively of Clinton and negatively of the Republicans.
 &HT;    In polls taken after Tuesday's State of the Union address,
anywhere from 66 percent to 76 percent of Americans approved of
Clinton's job performance -- three times the approval rating Nixon
had when he resigned. The president is the most admired man in
America and his wife the most admired woman.
 &HT;    Clinton's party is fresh from a surprisingly strong showing in
the mid-term elections, and while the Republicans still control
Congress, Clinton is within reach of what Nixon used to callan
ideological majority. The Republicans have already lost two
speakers of the House over the Lewinsky affair, and the Republican
Party has its lowest approval rating in a generation.
 &HT;    The claims that the public won't trust Clinton on other issues
because he lied about Lewinsky don't hold up. Even amid all the
references to ``Wag the Dog,'' the public overwhelmingly believed
that Clinton ordered the bombing of Iraq for the right reasons, not
as a distraction from impeachment.
 &HT;    The public doesn't believe Clinton when he talks about things
they don't want to hear about, but they trust him when it comes to
doing his job.
 &HT;    The public also seems to trust Clinton and the Democrats more
than the Republicans on the issues likely to occupy Congress for
the next two years -- Social Security, Medicare, Medicaid, HMOs and
education.
 &HT;    And that is the irony behind the likelihood that Clinton's
legacy will be positive: Because of Bill Clinton, the American
people once again want government to work for them.
 &HT;    Clinton is the un-Reagan. Ronald Reagan spent eight years in
office downgrading government. He left the sense that government
shouldn't try to do anything, and he left a gigantic deficit that
made it almost impossible to think about government doing anything
new.
 &HT;    George Bush was somewhat less opposed than Reagan to government
trying to do things for people, but he lamented in his Inaugural
Address that America had more will than wallet.He never tried to
find either will or wallet, and the result -- in the face of a
recession -- was a feeling of national despair and 62 percent of
voters throwing Bush out of office.
 &HT;    Clinton came in arguing that there was nothing wrong with
America that couldn't be fixed by what's right with America.He
believed, in effect, that America could find both will and wallet;
he balanced the federal budget while adding new social programs.
 &HT;    Clinton's push for one big program -- a massive health-care
reform -- failed, but he has made major changes in America through
dozens of smaller changes.
 &HT;    Today, people can't lose health insurance because they change
jobs or have pre-existing conditions, and millions more children
have access to health care. Clinton has succeeded in his goal of
making two years of college or technical school affordable for
virtually every American. The controversial welfare reform bill he
signed has -- so far, at least -- moved people from welfare to work
without forcing people into the streets.
 &HT;    Clinton made it intellectually and financially possible, even
desirable, for Americans to once again look to government to do
good things for people. That's why so many conservatives loathe
him. But it's a heck of a legacy.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    Jim Castelli is the author of ``A Plea for Common Sense:
Resolving the Clash Between Religion and Politics'' (Harper &AMP; Row).
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Jim Castelli
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
