<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, January 21, 1999,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ As a result of the recent currency devaluation in
Brazil, BellSouth Corporation (NYSE: BLS) said today that it
expects to record a foreign exchange impact on earnings for the
first quarter of 1999. The amount is yet to be determined, but
based on the floating rate of the Brazilian real as of Jan. 19 and
BellSouth's share of the US dollar debt of its Brazilian
investments of about $1 billion, it would be approximately $172
million, or 9 cents per share. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GM-EARNINGS _ General Motors Corp.'s strong performance in North
America overcame the effects of last summer's strikes and weak
results overseas to generate a record fourth-quarter profit of $1.8
billion, up 8 percent from the same period a year ago. The world's
largest automaker reported today that it earned $2.61 a fully
diluted share, compared with $1.7 billion, or $2.33 a share, in the
last three months of 1997. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News). 12.
</P>
<P>
   NCR-EARNINGS _ NCR Corp. exceeded analysts expectations by
posting strong fourth-quarter and full-years earnings Wednesday.
The Dayton-based computer equipment and services company said it
earned $49 million, or $0.49 per diluted share, during the fourth
quarter, compared with $36 million, or $0.35 per diluted share, in
the comparable period last year. (Dayton Daily News). 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   BEST-TECHTOWNS _ Atlanta is the third best place in America for
information technology workers, according to Computerworld
magazine's annual ranking. (Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SMALLBIZ-AUSTIN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As the Texas Legislature
cranks up for another session, it means a swath of new business
comes to town that benefits small businesses all over the Austin
area. (Tyson, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
