A1441 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX     01-20 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyday Tao''
</P>
<P>
   By Deng Ming-Dao
</P>
<P>
   HarperSanFrancisco/$15
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who follow Tao learn an inner direction in their lives.
They accept who they are, and they ascertain and then accept the
details of their lives. They take advantage of who they are and do
not try to be someone they are not. They accept that they were
born, they accept that they will die, and they take the distance
traveled between those two points as their personal path.''
</P>
<P>
   Deng Ming-Dao writes not another translation or academic's
reflection on classical works, but a clear, down-to-earth guide
toward gaining spiritual awareness for our day-to-day journey.
Everyday Tao examines the Chinese word/picture in its most
primitive style (the Small Seal Script), a language in which a
picture is truly worth many words. Each ideogram provides the
starting point for a Taoist lesson on nurturing an intimate
relationship with nature, others and ourselves. Fundamental Taoist
thought is delivered in savory bite-size pieces; easy to digest,
deliciously sustaining.
</P>
<P>
   Deng Ming-Dao, author of ``365 Tao: Daily Meditations,
Chronicles of Tao: The Secret Life of a Taoist Master'' and
``Scholar Warrior: An Introduction to the Tao in Everyday Life,''
has shown, once again, that rare ability to convey core principles
in universal context (without scaring off the novice).
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Becky Brandenburg
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs From the Heart''
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Adams
</P>
<P>
   Verity Records
</P>
<P>
   Along with Kirk Franklin, Yolanda Adams is of one Texas' most
successful gospel artists, having earned several Grammy nominations
and also Top 5 spots for several releases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs From the Heart,'' which has ascended to the Top 10 on
the national gospel charts, is another worthy release from the
Houstonian, chock-full of good songs and the woman's amazing
vocals. Adams is probably gospel's Whitney Houston, in that she
specializes in big, soaring ballads that display those vocal
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, though, one can't help but be a tad
disappointed by ``Heart.'' The songs (by a variety of writers;
Adams co-wrote three) are good, and the trips into traditional
gospel _ such as ``Lord, I Want to Be a Christian'' and a
three-song ``Jesus Medley'' _ are well-chosen and well-arranged.
</P>
<P>
   But there are, quite simply, too many slow ballads here, and
several of the songs (including the medley) are sweetened too much
by unneeded string arrangements. It's a relief when she dips into
gently funky stuff such as ``God Will Take Care of You,'' but she
never quite does that enough. Adams has an enormous amount of
talent, but now and then ``Heart'' is just too gauzy and mellow for
its own good.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
