<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE BOTTLE TO STAY, GIANTS OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco Giants officials won't back down
from a plan to erect a giant Coke bottle in their new China Basin
baseball stadium, but they have once again promised to shield it
from view outside the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will effectively screen the Coke bottle,'' team spokeswomen
Staci Slaughter said Tuesday at a City Hall hearing.
</P>
<P>
   And if that doesn't happen, neighbors who oppose the plan have
vowed to sue in an attempt to remove it, said South Beach activist
Jeffrey Leibovitz, who is leading the fight against the project.
</P>
<P>
   The Coke bottle, which will rise 80 feet, is part of a
children's play structure to be located behind the left-field
bleachers. Kids will be able to climb on it, and when a Giants
player hits a home run, the cap will pop off and the bottle will
spit out celebratory bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   The project won the OK from the planning and redevelopment
commissions, and from a neighborhood citizens advisory task force
after the Giants scaled back the original plan that called for a
110-foot structure. Still, there are some neighbors wary of a huge
pop bottle in their back yard and others who just plain don't like
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Brodkin, who heads Coleman Advocates for Children &AMP;
Youth, called the Coke bottle a ``permanent monument for bad
taste'' that is intended to seduce children into drinking ``an
addictive substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Stephen, dental director for the San Francisco Health
Department, called the bottle ``a public health hazard'' because it
promotes a soft drink that contributes to tooth decay.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giants representatives said the Coke bottle is a go, noting
that Coca-Cola is a major sponsor of the privately financed
ballpark. Slaughter said the plan is to shroud the structure from
outside view with trees and other foliage, or another screening
device. The bottle, of course, will be quite visible from within
the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano, who requested the
hearing, said he ``personally is not happy with the Coke bottle,''
but conceded there is nothing the city can do at this point to stop
it.
</P>
<P>
   Coke, the second-largest sponsor of the new stadium, contributed
about $20 million of the total $306 million ballpark cost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
