<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, Jan. 21. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
QUAYLE (Phoenix) - After launching an attack on ``liberal
Republicans,'' Dan Quayle is taking his first formal step toward
running in 2000. Quayle will file exploratory campaign papers
Thursday in Washingon, and then make a public declaration on
``Larry King Live,'' the same TV show that Ross Perot used to
launch his presidential campaign. Quayle discusses this and other
things _ like his thinly-veiled jab at George Bush _ in an
interview with ``The Arizona Republic.'' By MICHAEL MURPHY. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
IMPEACH-AZNOTES (Phoenix) - Hundreds of people have called or
e-mailed ``Arizona Republic'' reporter Julie Amparano in response
to her columns gauging the public's response to Bill Clinton's
impeachment trial over the last week. Some have confessed their own
affairs and wondered what's so bad about cheating, anyway. Another
compared Bill and Hillary to MacBeth and Lady MacBeth, saying they
will never wash the `'blood'' of scandal from their hands. Here are
the personal stories and sentiments of those who have responded to
the column. By JULIE AMPARANO. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CORDBANK (Phoenix) - When Karen Williamson delivered twins in
November, she fortified their financial futures with savings
accounts and college funds. But that wasn't enough for the Phoenix
mom. So she banked a little of their blood just to insure their
longevity. Drawn painlessly from their umbilical cords moments
after their Cesarian births, blood from each child was quickly
whisked by courier to a cord blood bank at the University of
Arizona campus in Tucson. And, after being processed, it will
remain there indefinitely, preserved in liquid nitrogen at 400
degrees below zero Fahrenheit until one of the twins needs it for a
life-saving cure. By LINDA HELSER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AMWEST (Phoenix) - America West announced record earnings of for
the fourth quarter and year-end. Fourth quarter net income was
$22.4 million, and it topped $108 million for the year, up 45
percent from last year's record of $75 million. By PETER CORBETT.
Story will move in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) - An atomic bomb exploded in Rep. John
Shadegg's face about 30 seconds into the president's State of the
Union speech, and he didn't even flinch. The fallout wasn't strong
enough to penetrate Shadegg's thick shield of arrogance. By E.J.
MONTINI Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Someone's knocking at my door. I have a
feeling it's Jerry.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, I liked Jerry when he came to my house several weeks
ago and pulled out a semi-dead orange tree from my front yard,
using nothing but his bare hands and a whole lot of angst. But
apparently I was Jerry's gold mine, and though he eventually
stopped asking for work, he just started asking me for outright
cash. I said no and felt really bad for him. I kept on feeling
really bad about it until my husband did the math, figured out that
in the two days that Jerry had done work for us and our neighbors,
he had made more than we both did in a week. By LAURI NOTARO. Story
moved in the ``L '' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
