<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Warm and increasingly moist air will flow north from the Gulf of
Mexico, eventually encountering a mass of cooler air from the
northern Mississippi Valley to the Middle Atlantic States. A front
separating the two air masses will be the focus for abundant clouds
and an expanding area of wet weather. Meanwhile, the unsettled
conditions will persist in much of the West where a moist flow from
over the Pacific remains vigorous.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will become locally heavy at times in the Ohio Valley as
strengthening winds from the south bring humid air into the region.
Farther south, bands of showers and thundershowers will develop
from the Tennessee Valley to the central coast of the Gulf of
Mexico. Later Thursday over the southern Mississippi Valley, a
potent jet stream disturbance will incite strong, gusty
thunderstorms, heavy rain and perhaps a few tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will thicken over most of the Northeastern States as high
pressure moves off the New England Coast. Patchy light rain and
drizzle will develop near a wavering front from the Middle Atlantic
States to extreme southern New England. Meanwhile, sunshine will
gradually yield to clouds over eastern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Colder air will spread south through the interior West. Showers
will occur near the Northwest Coast and a few interior valleys
while intermittent snow will fall along west-facing slopes in the
northern and central Rockies. Most of the Southwest will be partly
to mostly sunny and dry. However, low clouds and fog will linger in
the Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Snowy January
</P>
<P>
   So far this month, 24.4 inches of snow have fallen at La Crosse,
Wisconsin, marking the town's fourth snowiest January on record.
Snowfalls across a large chunk of the upper Middle West continue to
stay ahead of the normal pace for snow this winter. The upper
Middle West has been favorably positioned to the north and west of
a beaten track of storm systems, which have cut a path from the
southern Plains to the eastern Great Lakes. Later Thursday and
Thursday night, another storm will take a similar path, but the
lack of a deep Arctic air mass will result in a mix of wintry
precipitation at La Crosse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0341 </DOCNO>
