<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: ARGENTINE ART IN AUSTIN; GENIUS OF THE SHAKERS;
REMEMBERING BURROUGHS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ariz., N.Y., Argentina)    (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contemporary art from Argentina takes the spotlight beginning
Friday at the Jack S. Blanton Museum of Art at the University of
Texas in Austin, where about 75 large-scale works of painting,
sculpture and assemblage by nine of that country's artists parody
middle-class Argentine ideas of good taste.
</P>
<P>
   The artists include Antonio Berni, Jorge de la Vega, Alberto
Heredia and Victor Grippo. Most of the works have never been
exhibited in the United States, and the display will be accompanied
by complementary exhibitions, lectures, symposiums and films on the
campus.
</P>
<P>
   After it closes on March 7, the exhibition, ``Cantos Paralelos:
Visual Parody in Contemporary Argentinian Art,'' is to travel to
the Phoenix Art Museum, where it will remain from July 24 to Sept.
26. Next year it will travel to museums in Bogota, Colombia, and
Buenos Aires, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   A Certain Style
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly 400 objects, from fragile bonnets and
woodworking tools to rocking chairs and drawings that record
spiritual visions, go on display Thursday in an exhibition at the
Paine Webber Art Gallery, at 1285 Avenue of the Americas between
51st and 52nd Streets.
</P>
<P>
   The show, ``Shaker Gifts, Shaker Genius: The Collection of the
Shaker Museum and Library,'' celebrates the history and artistic
and cultural legacy of the American Shakers, a sect established in
1774 by Ann Lee and eight followers who came to the Colonies in
search of religious freedom. Continuing through April 21, the
exhibition was organized by the Shaker Museum in Old Chatham, N.Y.,
a leading center for study of the Shakers.
</P>
<P>
   Novel Occasions
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William Burroughs, author of ``Naked Lunch,''
``Queer'' and ``Junky,'' would have turned 85 on Feb. 5, and he
will be remembered in literary fashion with a weekend's worth of
events.
</P>
<P>
   Concurrent with the publication by Grove Press of ``Word Virus:
The William S. Burroughs Reader,'' the provocative author will be
the subject of ``A Tribute to William S. Burroughs,'' a panel
discussion and multimedia presentation at Tishman Auditorium of the
New School, 66 W. 12th Street in Greenwich Village, at 7:30 p.m. on
his birthday. The next day, at 1 p.m. at the Poetry Project in St.
Mark's Church, 131 E. 10th St. in the East Village, readers ranging
from the actor Steve Buscemi to the publisher Barney Rosset are to
take part in a reading of favorite passages from his works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
