   CALIFORNIA -- Reaction from Contra Costa County representatives
and California's U.S. senators to President Clinton's State of the
Union address Tuesday night. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA -- MAX. Before spending Wednesday afternoon at President
Clinton's impeachment trial, Georgia's two U.S. senators introduced
bills on education and defense issues. (Working.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- STEEL. Thousands of steelworkers from the Ohio Valley
rallied before the U.S. Capitol and White House today, protesting
what they believe is the illegal dumping of foreign steel in the
United States. Lawmakers from steel-producing states introduced
bills that would impose restrictions on foreign companies. Also, a
strict quota bill will be introduced by Rep. Peter J. Visclosky,
D-Gary, early next month. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA -- Reaction from Southwestern Louisiana's two
representatives to President Clinton's State of the Union address
Tuesday night. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- STEEL. Sen. Mike DeWine and Rep. Jim Traficant of Poland
joined thousands of steel workers in a Capitol Hill rally to
pressure Clinton to take tougher action to stop the flood of
foreign steel. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   -- STEEL-NEY. Rep. Bob Ney walked up to the gates of the White
House, literally backed by thousands of steel workers, and demanded
a response from the administration about what they would do about
the steel crisis. And that's what he got. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- STEEL. Three thousand steel workers and industry
officials traveled to the Capitol to call for an end to the
``dumping'' of foreign steel. Pennsylvania steel workers say
foreign countries are selling their steel product so cheap, that
domestic companies can't compete. Sen. Arlen Specter and other
lawmakers announce legislation. Fine
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN ISLANDS -- UNION. V.I. Delegate to Congress Donna
Christian-Christensen reacts to President Clinton's State of the
Union address. Williams
</P>
