<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1467 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WINS-NYTSF &LR;      01-20 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WINS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TOO SURREAL TO BE REAL HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;     (EDITORS: On Jan. 22 Flora Lewis will be honored in New York by
the OVERSEAS PRESS CLUB, with its coveted ``Lifetime Recognition
Award.'') 
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ It's so ``surreal'' some editors have ruled out
further use of the word as tiresomely banal. But nobody is
restraining the use of the word ``historic,'' and that is just what
it doesn't feel like. The sense of this epoch is really more an
outlandish farce or melodrama, exciting but of no essential
significance.
 &HT;    The president of the United States is charged with such grave
dishonor that he must be removed from office. At the same time,
that same president appears before both houses of Congress in
solemn assembly to tell them of his plans for the country, which
stretch as far as a half century ahead.
 &HT;    Of course, if President Bill Clinton is convicted of perjury and
obstruction of justice and expelled, it would be historic because
that has never happened before in the United States. But it seems
too far-fetched, considering the miserably pointless circumstances.
What's more, the partisan arithmetic seems too impervious to
argument _ enough Republican votes (a majority) in the House to
impeach and in the Senate to try, but not enough (two-thirds) to
convict.
 &HT;    Clinton's State of the Union address was glowingly upbeat, full
of confidence and promise. It focussed on the medium and long term,
five to 50 years ahead, with no reference at all to the immediate
attempt to cut him down. His lack of embarrassment, contrition or
malaise clearly infuriated his Republican opponents all the more.
 &HT;    The two young congressmen chosen to respond on TV for the
majority party, Jennifer Dunn of Washington and Steve Largent of
Oklahoma, had nothing to offer but their claims of personal virtue
and dedication, all delivered in overly familiar political
windbaggery.
 &HT;    When it comes to public issues, rather than his personal
misbehavior, Clinton doesn't provide them with much of a target,
while his easy, cheerful style, without a hint of discomfort, is
masterly.
 &HT;    Still, one of the two mysteries about the whole Clinton scandal
is why the hard-line right hates him so much. They do. They refer
to him as Evil Incarnate.
 &HT;    One analysis is that he has co-opted a lot of conservative
issues _ such as crime, middle-class problems with child care, poor
education standards _ and they feel he has stolen their birthright.
But that doesn't explain enough. After all, in a way it is a
repudiation of the left they abhor. There is also a rebound, a
revenge, against those who epitomized the counterculture rebellion
of the late 1960s and early 1970s, a kind of grim and satisfied
conviction that so much defiance could only come to a bad end.
 &HT;    The polls confirm the fact that the public at large doesn't
share the indignation at all. Why? _ that is the second mystery.
The questions that pollsters usually ask don't help much. The
answers tend to brush the surveys aside much more than to reveal
the underlying thoughts of either the hard-liners or the general
public.
 &HT;    The drama in the atmosphere all seems artificial, generated by
media and prosecutors, while the typical ordinary reaction is ``Oh,
leave him alone.''
 &HT;    Surprisingly, Dunn began her rebuttal to the president's speech
by saying it was wrong to talk so much about crisis. ``There isn't
any crisis, Americans are sound.'' But that's the president's first
point. ``The state of our union is strong,'' he said.
 &HT;    So what is the fuss about? Probably most congressional
Republicans are no more intense about it than their constituents,
but the militant leadership has achieved a capacity for
intimidation that keeps them from risking the charge of being
``soft'' or defecting.
 &HT;    The situation has been compared to the period of Sen. Joe
McCarthy's fierce campaign against the Communists he professed to
smell everywhere. It was enough to silence even Dwight Eisenhower.
 &HT;    But the McCarthy era, which finally blew up in ridicule, was
ABOUT something, an ideological crusade. It is very hard to say
what the Monica Lewinsky scandal is about, except by sniggering.
Still, it has taken on a momentum of its own that makes the next
weeks hard to predict.
 &HT;    The longer term is easier. As Clinton said in his speech, it has
to be about Social Security, education and public debt, and nothing
that is argued in his trial will make any real difference. It was
noticeable that he dwelt almost entirely on domestic social issues,
with only a brief passing reference to foreign affairs and
America's role in the world.
 &HT;    He was defending himself naturally, but he was also reflecting
what is predominantly on the mind of Americans as the country
enters the new century. Just getting on with life, nothing for the
rest of the world to get upset about.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1999 Flora Lewis 
<TEXT>
