<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A Tough Choice: Bowlgame or Baby &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The folks at babycenter.com, which offers advice and products
for expectant and new parents, want to help expectant parents
answer one of life's most important questions: will the birth of
our baby interfere with a major sporting event?
</P>
<P>
   To avoid possible conflicts, the site's creators have conceived
the Sports Event Conflict Catcher and Conception Blocker. Through
the magic of databases, the site (www.babycenter.com/conflicts)
allows parents to enter in the anticipated arrival date of their
bundle of joy, and determine which of three thousand sporting
events they are likely to miss as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Or, for a digital age twist on the phrase ``planned
parenthood,'' you can choose an event you do not want to miss, say,
the National Rodeo Championships (Dec. 3-12, Las Vegas), and the
``Birth and Labor Conflict Catcher'' will tell you that the week of
Feb. 26th is one which requires contraception, not attempted
conception.
</P>
<P>
   And, for those facing an imminent conflict, the site includes a
function that will give you directions from sporting sites, say,
the Orange Bowl, to your hospital. But no guarantees implied:
thanks to the vagaries of due dates, the site warns you that there
is only a 5 percent chance of it being completely accurate, still
better than the odds of Michael Jordan returning to basketball.
</P>
<P>
   BabyCenter.com's chief executive, Matt Glickman, said his
daughter, Emma, was born last March during the Final Four.
``Truthfully, I'm not the biggest basketball fan,'' he said. ``I'm
a Cleveland Browns fan. I was lucky to have a baby when the Browns
weren't even in existence.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Napoli &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Wristwatch Tells The Time, and the Place &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new wristwatch from Casio Computer will tell its wearers not
just the time, but where they are.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced this month at the Consumer Electronics Show in Las
Vegas, the Casio Global Positioning System Watch communicates with
satellites to continuously find its longitude and latitude. The
screen of the watch also shows on a crude map the position of the
watch relative to some established point of reference, say, where
you left your car before you started hiking.
</P>
<P>
   But like most consumer electronics that come in condensed form,
the watch-bound GPS device is more expensive than many similar
handheld models. When it comes out this summer, it is expected to
cost $500 to $600, several hundred dollars more than basic handheld
versions.
</P>
<P>
   While outdoor types use the GPS watch to find their way home,
they can field pages on their other wrist with a second high-tech
timepiece, the Beepwear Pro, introduced at CES. The Beepwear Pro
can receive paging messages up to 104 characters long via the
Skytel system.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $179 cost for the watch, the paging service
can cost from $7.95 to $49.95, per month, depending on the
geographic coverage. The Beepwear Pro is on its way to stores this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The watch, made by Beepwear Paging Products, a joint venture of
Timex and Motorola, can also 150 telephone numbers and addresses.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suit to Cut Web Access At Library Is Dismissed
</P>
<P>
   In California, library patrons of all ages still are free to
check out the Internet. Last week, a state court in Alameda County
dismissed a lawsuit that charged that a public library violated the
constitutional rights of a 12-year-old boy who last year walked
into a library in a San Francisco suburb and used the Internet to
view and download pictures of naked women.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother, referred to as Kathleen R. in court records,
filed the suit saying the government had violated its
constitutional responsibility to protect the boy from harm by
permitting him access to content deemed ``harmful to minors.'' The
woman asked the court to suspend use of the Internet at the
Livermore Public Library, in a San Francisco suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Public libraries across the country were closely watching the
case because they are struggling with whether and how to restrict
access of minors to the Internet. And further muddying the waters,
last year, a federal court ruled that the use of Internet software
filters, those that attempt to prevent access to pornographic Web
pages, by the Loudon County public library in Virginia was a
violation of patrons' First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   In the California case, Judge George Hernandez of the Alameda
County Superior Court, dismissed the suit last Thursday without
comment. In October 1998, he dismissed a suit brought, by the same
woman, that had said the library's Internet policy violated state
law, not the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the American Civil Liberties Union, which
supported the city of Livermore's open-access policy, said the
plaintiff and her lawyer were ``long on rhetoric and short on case
law.'' The woman said she would appeal the ruling. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another Portable Way To Access Your E-Mail &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E-mail users who cannot bear to be without the service when they
leave the office now have another way for messages to follow them
around. Research In Motion, a wireless modem maker, and BellSouth
introduced a new e-mail ready pager called Blackberry this week.
Unlike other wireless systems, this one does not require a separate
e-mail account for messages.
</P>
<P>
   The software instantaneously forwards e-mail addressed to a
users' regular desktop computer account to the pager, which is
roughly the size of a credit card and the thickness of a AA
battery. Users can send replies which, in turn, are stored in a
sent items folder back in their office machine.
</P>
<P>
   But the pager's itty-bitty keyboard, however, will discourage
long-winded messaging. Also stuck in the pager are several personal
digital assistant functions _ calendars and the like _ that can be
synchronized with the big brother computer.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackberry sells for $399 and flat-rate monthly service
costs $39.99. The system works only on desktop computers connected
to a network running Microsoft Exchange software.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ian Austen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Long Arm of the Law Shuts a Source of Lyrics &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The International Lyrics Server (www.lyrics.ch), a popular Web
site containing the words to more than 100,000 songs, was closed
last week after music publishers accused the site's Swiss operators
of copyright violations and police officers seized their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Pascal de Vries, a network consultant in Basel who started the
site in 1997, said the police responded to a criminal complaint
filed by lawyers for the licensing arm of the National Music
Publishers' Association (www.nmpa.org) in New York, which says it
``is dedicated to the protection of music copyright across all
media and across all national boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lyrics Server received an average of a million hits per day
from visitors seeking the words to chart-topping songs by bands
like the Rolling Stones and Aerosmith, as well as to show tunes and
obscure ditties. Most of the lyrics were contributed by the site's
users.
</P>
<P>
   _ Matthew Mirapaul &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strange Bedfellows Join To Sue a Porno Group &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do Pamela Anderson, Dr. Laura Schlessinger and the
Archdiocese of St. Louis have in common? As of Jan. 8, 1999,
they've all sued Seth Warshavsky and his Seattle-based online
pornography company, the Internet Entertainment Group. The
archdiocese is suing IEG for posting sites tied to the pope's visit
to St. Louis next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the Internet's most thorough and complete site on the
pope's visit,'' Warshavsky said after a federal judge from the
Eastern District of Missouri shut down two IEG sites Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The sites did look and feel like official church content,
complete with a biography of Pope John Paul II and detailed
information on his visit. But a closer look revealed one section
titled ``Unholy Sex,'' which described medieval sex scandals in the
Catholic church, plus links to IEG's more typical fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We quoted from a dozen scholarly works, including William
James,'' explains IEG executive editor Evan Wright, who says he has
a degree in Medieval and Renaissance Studies from Vassar College.
``It's really much milder than the history of the church I studied
in school.''
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese, of course, was not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the goals here was to confuse people who thought it was
a legitimate site,'' says archdiocese spokesman Steve Mamanella.
</P>
<P>
   IEG intends to appeal the ruling and to relaunch the original
sites under a new address.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Romano &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1806EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
