<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1484 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-0121-COX     01-20 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-0121-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS REPUBLICANS MEET, POLITICAL GHOST OF REAGAN HOVERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican Party's search for the next Ronald
Reagan begins anew Thursday with two important gatherings of the
GOP faithful.
</P>
<P>
   The nuts-and-bolts Republican National Committee begins its
three-day winter meeting with an eye toward victory in the 2000
presidential election. Private strategy sessions are expected to
focus not only on the White House race, but also on halting the
erosion of the GOP majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the party's most fervent conservatives, the
heart and soul of the GOP since Reagan, will get their first
up-close look at the most conservative presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``No pale pastels'' are invited to the annual conference of the
26-year-old Conservative Political Action Committee (CPAC), warned
David Keene, its chairman. Only true Reaganites need apply for the
GOP's 2000 presidential nomination, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after he left office, ``the GOP is still looking for
the next Ronald Reagan, and no one has a lock on that,'' said
Dennis Goldford, a Drake University expert on political parties and
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Among those slated to address CPAC are former Gov. Lamar
Alexander of Tennessee, Family Research Council founder Gary Bauer,
magazine publisher Steve Forbes, House Budget Chairman John Kasich
of Ohio, former Vice President Dan Quayle and Sen. Bob Smith of New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The current front-runners for the GOP nomination, Gov. George
Bush of Texas and former American Red Cross President Elizabeth
Dole, declined invitations to appear before CPAC. So did Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, who is running a distant third in public opinion
polls of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions by Bush and Dole to forgo an appearance before
CPAC affords other possible candidates an opportunity to snipe at
them and their credentials as heirs to the Reagan legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect George W. Bush will run as a Bush Republican and
Elizabeth Dole will run as a Dole Republican,'' said Bauer, a
former Reagan domestic policy adviser who next week will announce
his decision whether to run for the GOP nomination. ``If I run, I
will run as a Reagan Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that the GOP, in gearing up for the next
presidential contest, is harkening back to the glory days of
Reagan, said Haley Barbour, the former RNC chairman who helped
mastermind the GOP's takeover of Congress after 40 years of
Democratic dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the spending proposals outlined by President
Clinton in his State of the Union speech, ``we may very well be on
our way to a great debate over the next couple of years on the
proper size and scope of the federal government,'' Barbour said.
``And if I were running for president, I'd be standing with Ronald
Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Democratic contest, which seems to be shrinking into
a one-on-one scrimmage between Vice President Al Gore and Bill
Bradley, a former U.S. senator from New Jersey and pro basketball
great, the Republican presidential primary is expanding in spite of
Bush's and Dole's high standings in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GOP race has no previously tested front-runner, and other
candidates think it is now or never for them,'' said Merle Black, a
political expert at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is the compressed calendar of presidential
primaries next year. By the end of March 2000, 35 states will have
held caucuses or primaries, selecting nearly two-thirds of the
delegates to the parties' nominating conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The election calendar puts a premium on early campaign funding.
Many believe a candidate must raise at least $20 million this year
in order to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the invisible primary,'' said Ed Gillispie, who is
assembling Kasich's campaign apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
