<SLUG> BC-POCONOS-ARTS-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE CENTER IS PLANNED FOR CONCERTS IN POCONOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (lb) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Poconos have been famous for decades for resort hotels with
heart-shaped beds and bathtubs, but if Elliot Rosoff and Nat
Gliserman have their way, those Pennsylvania mountains will soon
become as well known for culture as for kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   Rosoff, a concert violinist, and Gliserman, an engineer who has
designed food and housing areas for two World's Fairs and several
Olympics, are planning a kind of Tanglewood of the Poconos called
the Keystone Center of Music and the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The center, on 675 acres near Stroudsburg, Pa., is a two-hour
drive from New York or Philadelphia. It is scheduled to open on May
25, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rosoff, the president and artistic director of the venture, and
Gliserman, its general manager, have received a letter of
commitment from the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, which hopes to
make the center its summer home, much as the Boston Symphony
summers at Tanglewood and the Philadelphia Orchestra takes up
residence at Saratoga, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The Tisch School of the Arts at New York University has signed
on to stage student productions of musical theater works there as
well as cabaret shows and children's performances. Discussions are
under way with the New York Pops and the Northeast Pennsylvania
Philharmonic for concerts, and East Stroudsburg University has
agreed to open a culinary school on the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been after a summer home for a long time,'' said Gideon
Toeplitz, the managing director of the Pittsburgh Symphony. ``We
used to spend the summers at Ambler, a college outside Baltimore,
until state funding ceased. Then we went to Great Woods, Mass.,
which was wonderful for two years, until one of the owners decided
that they could make more money with rock concerts, and we were
phased out. Since then, we have been using part of the summer for
domestic tours, but our long-term project was always to find a home
for the summer, and we certainly hope this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the plan is for the Pittsburgh Symphony to be in
residence for four weeks and to offer four programs each week.
Rosoff is talking to other orchestras about filling the rest of the
summer weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Rosoff happily promotes the center's relationship
with the Pittsburgh Symphony, he says he is thinking in broader
musical terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole philosophy,'' he said, ``is that we are not an
elitist organization. We'll have all kinds of music there, and only
35 percent of it will be classical. We expect about 40 percent to
be Broadway and pop. About 12 percent will be country, and we'll
have jazz and dance as well. We have so many places to present
performances on the property that we can have several things going
on at once.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a certain amount of faith involved. Rosoff
and Gliserman have budgeted $20 million for the first phase of the
project, which includes the cost of the land for the center and the
renovation of its existing buildings and lawns. Another $15 million
is budgeted for the second phase, the centerpiece of which is a
4,000-seat concert pavilion with lawn seating for 15,000. Gliserman
expects the pavilion to be completed in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the center has been promised a $7.5 million state grant,
although bureaucratic squabbles _ mainly over funds for proposed
sports complexes for Philadelphia and Pittsburgh that are part of
the same grant package _ have held it up. But beyond the state
grant, the center's board has raised only $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rosoff points out that the center has just started seeking
donations, and indeed, he and Gliserman have accomplished a lot in
a relatively short time.
</P>
<P>
   They saw the site of the proposed center for the first time last
March. Since then, they have established the nonprofit corporation
that will run the center, assembled a board, negotiated the
purchase of the property and started negotiating with the
orchestras and schools that would be resident at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Rosoff, who lives in New York, has worked as a freelance
orchestra player and recording-session violinist and founded and
ran Opal, a recording studio, until he sold his interest in 1985.
He was drawn into the arts-center business almost by accident. Four
years ago, he became intrigued with a bridge partner's proposal to
start a summer arts complex in the Catskills, and became the
artistic director of the project.
</P>
<P>
   When the original plan fell through, Rosoff and his partner
began looking at land in Pike County, Pa. They were about to buy a
piece of land when the partnership split because of what Rosoff
describes as ``philosophical disagreements'' about the function of
the center.
</P>
<P>
   Rosoff and his former partner had been working with Gary Boam,
the executive director of the Pike County Industrial and Commercial
Development Authority, and when he called Boam to say the
partnership had been dissolved, Boam asked if Rosoff was interested
in restarting the project on his own. When they met last March to
begin searching for sites, Rosoff brought along Gliserman, also a
New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at four pieces of land,'' Rosoff said. ``This was
the fourth, and when we got there I took one look and said, `Wow,
this is it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gliserman added: ``You're looking at 675 acres, lawned and
wooded, with an 88-acre glacial lake and a nature walk. You know
that expression about contemplating one's navel? The lake is the
optimum place to do it; it has that kind of serenity. And over the
full area, you could have 10,000 people there, and they would not
be tripping over each other.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The property had been owned by the International Ladies Garment
Workers Union, which ran it as a retreat called Unity House. The
union stopped using the property in 1989 but had kept
groundskeepers on its payroll. The cost was $8.5 million _ $4.5
million in cash (Rosoff is currently negotiating a mortgage) and $4
million in free tickets to union members.
</P>
<P>
   Already in place was a handful of buildings that will become the
spine of the Keystone Center, as well as 33 cottages and other
buildings, 244 rooms in all, to house performers and the staff.
</P>
<P>
   A large administration building dating from 1973 will become the
Cultural Arts Center. It has a 1,500-seat dining room, a kitchen
and a vast food-storage area as well as a large performance space.
A separate theater built in 1959 will have 1,200 seats when it is
refurbished; it already has rehearsal space and full theatrical
backstage facilities. There is also a boathouse that would be
transformed into a theater for cabaret performances.
</P>
<P>
   A big lawn to the south of the Cultural Arts Center will be used
for outdoor chamber concerts and jazz, and a lawn near the lake for
children's concerts. The largest of the three lawns, west of the
Cultural Arts Center, will be the site of the concert pavilion,
planned for 2003. Until it is built, the center will hold concerts
in a large tent, like the one the New York Philharmonic uses for
its summer concerts in the parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the center at maturity _ say, five years out _ bringing
in upward of 600,000 people a year,'' said Boam of the Pike County
development authority. ``Currently we serve many millions of people
a year. As you know, the Pocono Mountains used to be characterized
as the honeymoon capital of the world, but now we have a more
diverse crowd, and it's difficult to get a handle on exactly why
they're coming. We see this as something that will bring people
into the market and provide entertainment for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Boam does have some concerns. Traffic, for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rural community,'' he said, ``and we want to support
the environment we have. We don't have massive four-lane
expressways, so moving 15,000 to 20,000 people in and out for
concerts will be interesting. But there are solutions. A bypass is
being built for other reasons nearby. And there is a proposal for a
rail line, in the next five years, to connect Scranton with points
in New Jersey and New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The center's neighbors seem to be fully behind the project: one
nearby resort, Tamiment, lent the board money to make its down
payment. Together, three resorts within 10 miles of the center _
Tamiment, Pocomont and Fernwood _ are undertaking about $50 million
of renovations. All told, there are 18,000 to 20,000 hotel rooms
within a 50-mile radius of the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be a place where people come at 7:30, go
to a concert and leave,'' Rosoff said. ``That's not the premise of
what we're doing. We're offering an environment, a destination.
It's an incredible piece of property _ you walk in there, and
you're in another world. That's very important to us. It's what
attracted me to it in the first place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1811EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
