<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      01-20 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: PEN IN HAND? MAYBE NO MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the final graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a genre, the literary letter is like many a dramatic romance.
One always predicts that its soliloquy will end, but often it
doesn't. The form has survived the telephone and the typewriter and
the personal computer. Will it survive e-mail?
</P>
<P>
   The maxim for the literary letter was very likely set by Cicero,
whose craving for publicity was so consuming that he inadvertently
laid down the principle that has endured for more than 2,000 years.
It was the simple phrase ``a letter does not blush'' _ or anything
goes _ and it dates from the shameless request he wrote in 56 B.C.
to Lucceius not only to commence the writing of his biography
immediately but also ``to embellish,'' indeed ``to put aside the
rules of historical composition and grant a little more of your
love for me than the truth might allow.''
</P>
<P>
   From Cicero's time (he was a prolific letter writer) to now,
what has made the somewhat subterranean art of literary letter
writing important has been the intimacy and passion and sometimes
ebullient honesty that authors have felt free to express in their
letters. Stuff they often couldn't or wouldn't put into their other
work.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, for instance, Emily Dickinson wrote to her sister-in-law,
Susan Huntington Dickinson: ``Dearer you cannot be, for I love you
so already, that it almost breaks my heart _ perhaps I can love you
anew, every day of my life, every morning and evening.'' (``Open Me
Carefully,'' Paris Press, 1998.) Or Simone de Beauvoir to Nelson
Algren: ``I work well, I wait for spring, I think of you first
thing in the morning when I open my eyes and last thing at night
when closing them. I kiss you as well as I can and as long as you
want.'' (``A Transatlantic Love Affair,'' the New Press, 1998.) In
neither collection are the pages reddening.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill left behind about 5,000 letters. Hemingway, Faulkner and
Steinbeck churned them out, Steinbeck often as a morning warm-up,
like a pianist's finger exercise, before starting the day's work of
story writing. Think van Gogh. After the paintings, it's the almost
nightly letters to his brother Theo that pop into your mind.
Raymond Chandler, writing to his publisher, described his letters'
importance this way: ``So I suppose in my letters I more or less
revealed those facets of my mind which had to be obscured or
distorted in what I wrote for publication.''
</P>
<P>
   For serious writers, nothing was too trivial or too personal for
their letters. Nothing else allowed for such joyous ego
exploration. And without such indulgences, future biographies would
certainly be patchy things at best.
</P>
<P>
   The latest presumed threat to the form is e-mail. For many it is
difficult to conjure someone's pouring out emotions to a recipient
who will almost certainly not save the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Carol Oates, a voluminous letter writer, said: ``I don't
know if I could write anything intimate on e-mail. I didn't grow up
with e-mail. My students at Princeton did, so it's intimate for
them.'' She added: ``I still type out a letter. I don't have a word
processor. I can sit and look out the window at the rain,'' she
said. ``It's easier psychologically than using a word processor,
let alone e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have written thousands of letters; if I haven't much to say
I send postcards to friends and editors,'' she said. ``John Updike
and I write letters to each other; he sends me postcards.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1961, Ms. Oates has had a prodigious correspondence with
Robert Phillips, author, poet and director of the creative writing
program at the University of Houston, whom she met when they were
undergraduates at Syracuse University. ``It's very old-fashioned
letter writing _ lots of gossip, literary information, personal
news,'' she said. ``He and I have written thousands of letters, and
we still mail them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have love letters because I married my first serious
love,'' she said. Phillips said: ``What we write about is mutual
friends, what's going on in our groups'' _ Ms. Oates teaches
creative writing at Princeton _ ``reviews of things we think will
interest each other. I send her poems. When I don't have a clear
writing project in mind, I use the letters for warm-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   Writers feel often that their work is not real unless they can
touch it and see it on paper. ``My primary mode of communication is
the old manual typewriter,'' John Updike said. ``It has the breath
of life to it; it's not plugged in to something.'' He doesn't write
letters ``in the grand old sense of them,'' he said. ``Joyce writes
a very good letter, very old-fashioned sort. Mine are more terse; I
send a lot of postcards.''
</P>
<P>
   In at least one way, however, Updike is in the literary
tradition of letter writing. He most often communicated by letter
with Judith Jones, who edits him at Alfred A. Knopf, and William
Maxwell, who formerly edited him at The New Yorker. ``Those
letters, hundreds of them, have probably been kept,'' he said.
``They show me in a professional mode worrying about details. I
wouldn't say they are highly emotional or confiding. One's letters
sometimes creep into the public domain, and it makes one a little
uncomfortable to have them out there when you are still out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Updike's letters have been given by Maxwell to the
University of Illinois, where they can be read. (Writers, or their
estates or heirs, own the content of letters so they cannot be
quoted at length without permission, but the recipient owns the
physical objects and can show them.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Updike doesn't reveal much of himself in his letters,
he says he would be very sorry if e-mail wiped out the genre. ``It
is sad to think there wouldn't be things like the letters of Byron
_ his best writing was his letters _ and Keats,'' he said. ``Or
Henry James, dashing off letters just to keep his social life in
order.'' A phone call or e-mail could be used for this, ``but
there's something about the act of typing and seeing words on
paper,'' Updike said. ``It allows the writer to ever so slightly
preen and polish.''
</P>
<P>
   For the biographer, the threat of what e-mail will do to the
literary letter is too terrible to consider. Gioia Diliberto, whose
biography of the crusading Jane Addams will be published by
Scribner in July, said that much of the research involved letters.
``The collection of her letters comprises more than 75 reels of
microfilm, a great deal of it in handwriting that is illegible,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-mail is not the same as mail; people don't use it for
contemplative purposes,'' Ms. Diliberto said. ``People used letter
writing to figure out how they felt about things. You usually use
e-mail for business purposes, not venting your feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Letters also tell history. Broadway Books had a recent trade
paperback success with ``Letters of a Nation,'' a collection of
letters by extraordinary Americans and obscure ones, and its sister
imprint, Dial Press, plans a book that will tell the history of
20th-century America through letters.
</P>
<P>
   So the loss of letters on paper can be a serious thing indeed.
And can anyone really imagine: sjohnson(AT)therambler.com?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
