<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1496 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-WARCRIMES-AR     01-20 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-WARCRIMES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIA'S FOOT SOLDIERS OF GENOCIDE: CRIMINALS OR PAWNS?
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHUM THMEI, Cambodia _ ``If I killed anyone, you can kill me
back,'' said Neang Kin, her hair matted and her clothes stained
reddish-brown from her work in the flooded rice fields. ``I swear
to God and swear to die in front of my children. I faint at the
sight of blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Khmer Rouge personnel files at Tuol Sleng prison and Mrs. Neang
Kin's own confession 20 years ago tell a different story. According
to these records, she was one of many thousands of functionaries
who carried out the brutal policies that led to the deaths of more
than a million Cambodians from 1975 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Neang Kin, who guesses her age at 48, once confessed to
assisting in the torture of 300 people at the prison and even to
taking part in administering electric shocks. A subsistence farmer
now, she desperately denies that confession.
</P>
<P>
   As Cambodia and the outside world prepare for the possibility of
trials for perhaps a dozen Khmer Rouge leaders, a large unanswered
_ and generally unasked _ question is how to deal with the people
who actually took part in the torture and the killing, or even how
to think of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people like her on file,'' said Youk
Chhang, the director of the Documentation Center of Cambodia, a
private agency that is collecting evidence of Khmer Rouge crimes.
His investigators have talked with Mrs. Neang Kin three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a very classic case for the lawyers to
determine who should be responsible,'' he said. ``Even though I
personally believe only the leaders should be brought to justice,
we need to clarify this for the younger generation to understand.
This woman is like a first-hand killer. Why should only the the top
leaders take responsibility?''
</P>
<P>
   The documents show that Mrs. Neang Kin spent 18 months in prison
after her confession in 1979. She said the recent surrender of two
Khmer Rouge leaders has filled her with mixed emotions: anger at
their apparent impunity but fear that if trials are held, she may
once again be a target.
</P>
<P>
   She said she resented some former Khmer Rouge colleagues who
have done well for themselves in recent years, buying motorbikes
and televisions or emigrating to the United States. Abandoned years
ago by her husband, Mrs. Neang Kin grows rice, beans and corn to
support her parents and teen-age daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Her file at Tuol Sleng prison, in Phnom Penh, describes her as
having been a ``group chief,'' though it does not specify her
duties. Like similar files, it includes an expressionless portrait
that is indistinguishable from those taken of the 14,000 prisoners
who passed through the torture house en route to their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Her confession to the Vietnamese-backed government that ousted
the Khmer Rouge says she assisted and sometimes administered
torture, including electric shocks. ``We used the shocks until
people died,'' she is quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The stories she now tells, in conversations last August and this
month in this tiny riverside village 30 miles south of Phnom Penh,
have become more complex.
</P>
<P>
   Though she admits setting up and cleaning the interrogation
rooms _ sweeping, arranging chairs, putting out glasses of water _
she stops short of her earlier confession that she took part.
</P>
<P>
   And though she insists on her personal innocence, she describes
in knowledgeable detail the nighttime departures of large dark
trucks, ``very quietly, with a small flashing light,'' that carried
the stripped and handcuffed prisoners to their deaths in a killing
field.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever her actions, it seems clear that she, like many of even
the cruelest Khmer Rouge executioners, was a young, barely literate
farmer who was recruited, indoctrinated and terrorized into
unquestioning and even enthusiastic obedience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had political meetings, but I didn't understand anything
they said,'' Mrs. Neang Kin said. ``Wherever they asked me to go, I
went. They were OK, but they were brutal when you did something
wrong. Sometimes I spilled rice and the group leader hit me with a
flashlight. He hit, and hit, and hit.''
</P>
<P>
   She was asked the question that is key for those who have
performed atrocities throughout history: Why did she not simply
refuse?
</P>
<P>
   ``They would kill you,'' she replied. ``You would say one word
against them, and they would kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the leading pursuers of those responsible for the
Khmer Rouge atrocities, Youk Chhang wrestles with questions of
culpability, responsibility and humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just an uneducated peasant girl living on a farm,'' he
said. ``Suddenly she was working in the prison system, part of the
machine that was killing people. She was a human being caught up in
events, but what she was caught up in was inhuman. She is legally
responsible for what happened there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for ignorant people to understand what is humane and
what is inhumane. Her conscience was dulled by the government; who
was she to object?''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, ``she still seems to be very proud of
her discipline, of her ability to carry out orders without
question.''
</P>
<P>
   He said cases like hers could challenge any tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all say they didn't kill anybody,'' he said of the former
cadres. ``But what if there is a living witness, a victim of hers?
What if someone comes forward and says, `I want you to arrest this
person; she killed my sister.' How will the court respond?''
</P>
<P>
   And how will the nation respond?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that even a carefully limited tribunal could set
off nationwide recriminations and score-settlings _ even fighting _
worries some.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Khmer Rouge are bad and are criminals, but there are
too many to convict, and some remain strong,'' Pin Sisovann, an
editor, wrote in The Cambodia Daily this month. ``The international
tribunal will never be able to make it fair and just.''
</P>
<P>
   To safeguard the living, he wrote, ``it is better not to find
justice for the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Youk Chhang's response is: ``If people begin pointing fingers at
their neighbors, perhaps that will be bad. But it will be to a good
end. To cure pain, you have to go through pain.''
</P>
<P>
   There are countless people like Mrs. Neang Kin all around
Cambodia, living quiet lives among their victims, their backgrounds
often well known to their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Neang Kin may simply have been, in Youk Chhang's phrase,
``a human being caught up in events.'' But she was one of the
thousands of people whose failure to say no made the atrocities
possible.
</P>
<P>
   She was the daughter of a peasant landowner with a high school
education. She said that despite her parents' pleas, she was forced
to work for the communist insurgents of the Khmer Rouge beginning
two years before they seized power.
</P>
<P>
   At first she was a laborer, working on irrigation projects and
carrying rice. When the Khmer Rouge seized Phnom Penh in 1975 and
expelled its 2 million residents, she said, she helped collect gold
and other goods from the abandoned shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of cakes and biscuits,'' she said. ``They
were delicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, she said, she was assigned to prison work. ``I don't know
why.'' After a beating for some infraction, she said, she ran away
and returned home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got me and took me back to the prison even though I was
sick and my parents begged them not to,'' she said. ``They tied me
up in the sun for two days.''
</P>
<P>
   She learned to obey without question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever they put you, you stayed there,'' she said. ``You
didn't go searching into something that wasn't your business. You
didn't even tell your own relatives what you saw. Maybe for our
society today that is not a good system, but back then there was
discipline. And you have to live according to the rules of
society.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``They trained us to follow the path of the
revolution correctly. If you didn't believe, they killed you.''
</P>
<P>
   There were happy moments, too.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Neang Kin remembers with pleasure the New Year's parties
where the prison staff, dressed as always in spectral black, danced
the slow, traditional dances of Cambodia. They even had meat to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the guards were handsome, she said, but there was no
flirting as the men and women swayed their hips and hands in
separate dance circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't even ask permission to marry when you were
working at the prison,'' she said. ``You were afraid even to have a
feeling like that. The feeling could be seen and you could be
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   These are harsh memories to live with. So were Khmer Rouge
functionaries like Mrs. Neang Kin victims too?
</P>
<P>
   No, Youk Chhang said: ``They are not victims, but they are human
beings like us. They are not dragons or crocodiles or tigers. That
is what is so frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   One Cambodian-American researcher from his office said she was
charmed, and confused, by Mrs. Neang Kin and her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are wonderful people,'' said the researcher, Kalyanee
Mam, who visited them last summer. ``I just fell in love with the
family. She even cooked food for me. She didn't seem nervous or
hiding anything. She seemed very honest and direct. She said the
accusations were all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I said, `We have your photo from Tuol Sleng.' She said
she was forced to take the photo, that they just chose some people
for pictures so they wouldn't have to take pictures of the real
people. When I heard that, I didn't know what to say. I couldn't
just say: `You're lying.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She said: `Look at me. Do I look like a killer?''' Miss Mam
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same question the Khmer Rouge leader, Pol Pot, asked
an interviewer shortly before he died in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
