<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1498 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTEXHIBIT-NELLIE21-C     01-20 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTEXHIBIT-NELLIE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Folk artistry of a maid from Vinings finds national recognition
17 years after her death
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nellie Mae Rowe's doctor told her to chew gum for
headaches. So she took her leftover wads of Wrigley's and Beechnut
_ ``I don't want nobody else's, just mine'' _ and molded them into
sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   A widow with no children, she made dolls and set them out to
keep her company. Fashioned from old clothes, wearing wigs and
sunglasses and perched, sometimes, on little plastic lawn chairs,
they often bore a strange resemblance to Rowe herself _ portraits
of the artist as a young doll.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 20 years, the late Nellie Mae Rowe has become
something of a cult figure in Atlanta, revered by its community of
folk art aficionados, contemporary artists and museum officials.
Now, in a meticulously researched, lovingly assembled show at the
Museum of American Folk Art, the tale of this self-taught artist
from Vinings, who died of cancer in 1982 after a remarkable
two-year burst of creativity, is being revealed to a larger public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's a long time in coming, but here she is, and I think
she deserves every bit of it,'' says curator Lee Kogan. ``She
should be recognized because she is, in her way, a genius. Without
qualification, she is a significant American artist of the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   All this week _ and at a reception Wednesday night attended by
dozens of Atlanta followers _ this city has fallen under the spell
of Nellie Mae Rowe.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, those chewing gum sculptures and bespectacled rag dolls are
amazing. But among the 96 works in this retrospective, it's the
pictures that really pop.
</P>
<P>
   Saturated with color, throbbing with sensuality and informed by
the accumulated symbols of Africa and America, Rowe's vision is
near-mythic in sweep. Yet this is not always self-evident.
</P>
<P>
   Using a deceptively simple vocabulary _ trees and flowers, fish
and fowl, men and animals _ she captures something that is both of
her time and beyond time's larger frame. Plugged into a primordial
subconsciousness, yet fully cognizant of her exterior world, Rowe
encodes her landscapes with icons of life and death, fertility and
barrenness, strength and vulnerability, pleasure and pain. She is
both mesmerized by the progress of man (TVs, freeways) and
terrified of it. She is eroticized by the lushness of the physical
world and seduced by the promise of heaven. Like Phoenix Jackson,
the character in Eudora Welty's ``A Worn Path,'' she is on a
metaphorical journey of life, with all of nature spread out in
front of her, creating both beauty and chaos.
</P>
<P>
   For some, Nellie Mae Rowe's big moment is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she is a major player in the field of self-taught art,
and I think she has not yet achieved the recognition she
deserves,'' says High Museum (Atlanta) folk art curator Lynne
Spriggs, who came to New York to see the show, which goes on view
at the High's downtown branch in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's always hurt me about Nellie Mae Rowe is that
she had to work so hard,'' says Atlanta artist Susan Loftin, who
traveled 22 hours by train to see the show. ``One of the greatest
artists we had in the country had to work as a maid for 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta collector Marianne Lambert says that if you'd gone to
Rowe's funeral, you would have never known she was such a creative
force. ``They never once mentioned that she was an artist. They
just talked about her good deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   That's changing now.
</P>
<P>
   But the story of Nellie Mae Rowe might never have gotten out,
had it not been for Judith Alexander. After first seeing Rowe's
pictures in 1976, Alexander became her dealer, best friend and most
tireless advocate. By 1978, at Alexander's urging, Rowe had created
enough works to kick off the inaugural exhibit at the Alexander
Gallery, Atlanta's first folk art house.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe was 78, and her art career had just begun. Over the next 10
years, she would realize her preternatural impulse to make art,
turning out the wildly incandescent pictures that are now coveted
by museums.
</P>
<P>
   Born on a Fayette County (Ga.) farm to a former slave, Rowe was
possessed of a tenacious will to draw. Her father was a basket
maker, and her mother stitched quilts, so making things seemed like
her birthright. A bride at 16, twice widowed by the time she was
48, Rowe worked as a domestic servant. When she wasn't decorating
her own house and yard with her play pretties, she was rearranging
her employers' furniture. To her surprise, they liked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she had this affinity for all living things,'' says
Lee Kogan, the show's curator at the Museum of American Folk Art.
``I think she really understood and believed in the unity of every
living thing. And you feel it _ you just feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander _ a visionary in her own right who opened Atlanta's
first abstract gallery in 1956 _ says she was drawn to Rowe's work
simply because it didn't bore her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It excited me,'' says Alexander, 67, sitting in her New York
apartment, which is hung almost exclusively with Rowe's art. ``This
was art that did not make me think of anything else. It did speak
to me, and it was amazing. It just delighted me. It nurtured. It
just made me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   As Alexander says this, she sounds like the Geraldine Page
character in the movie ``A Trip to Bountiful.'' It is the tiny,
wholly sweet voice of an old woman who is still a little girl at
heart, a quality that must have endeared her to Rowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Nellie's spirit lives on with her in a way,''
Spriggs says. ``She's just been an incredible advocate of Nellie's
work.'' Though Alexander closed her gallery in 1989, she has
continued as the keeper of the Rowe repository, dispensing pictures
only to those who meet her exacting criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Nellie Mae Rowe was fortunate in finding a
collaborator like Judith Alexander,'' says Gerard C. Wertkin,
director of the Museum of American Folk Art. ``This was a true
partnership based on mutual respect and affection. That
unfortunately is not always the case. . . . She (Alexander) has
nurtured the legacy and has gone about it with tremendous
commitment. I would even use the word `love.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Brown Sr., Rowe's nephew and closest relative, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people would come by here, and they would try to beat
her out of stuff, but Miss Judith didn't do that,'' says the
85-year-old Smyrna resident, who was too ill to make the opening.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander won't say how many Rowe works she owns, nor what they
are worth on the market. But she is clearly determined to see that
they get into the hands of careful custodians. She worries over
whether the paintings should stay in Georgia or be sent to museums
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so proud to have been given archival works and some
major works of Nellie Mae Rowe and hope in time that we may have
more,'' says Kogan, who traveled to Atlanta numerous times to
research the show. She dedicated the handsome coffee table volume,
the first major treatise on Rowe, to Brown and Eleanor Shropshire,
a Rowe niece from Fayetteville (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Brown says he's gotten the catalog and thinks the show is
wonderful. ``I know that Aunt Nellie would love it if she could see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the final pictures is one of a tiny, big-eared dog looking
sad and perplexed, as if it is nearing the end of a very long
journey. In Rowe's inimitable hand, she has scrawled the words: ``I
won't be back.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in these hauntingly beautiful images of joy and hope,
she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of Nellie Mae Rowe: Ninety-Nine and a Half Won't Do''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Through May 16. Free. Museum of American Folk Art, Eva and
Morris Feld Gallery at 2 Lincoln Square, Columbus Avenue at 66th
Street, New York. 212-595-9533. The show travels to the National
Museum of Women in the Arts (June 3-Aug. 15) in Washington, the
High Museum of Art's downtown Atlanta gallery (Nov. 20-Feb. 26,
2000) and the African American Museum in Dallas (March 18-May 14,
2000).
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
