<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stars Allen, Richardson ask to pull plug on `Home'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Tim Allen says this is absolutely, positively
the last season for ``Home Improvement.'' The sitcom star, who
wants to work on his film career (``The Santa Clause''), says no
amount of money can make him return, even though there are reports
ABC might offer him $2 million per episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many ways I can say this,'' says Allen. ``I'm
not going to do this any more. As far as I'm concerned, it's the
end of the road.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC programming execs are playing the decision close to the
vest, saying they'd like to have the show back if a deal can be
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about them, it's about us,'' says Allen, who says he
learned from Jerry Seinfeld and Michael Jordan how not to overstay
one's welcome. ``There is nothing ABC can do to bring us back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Improvement'' co-star Patricia Richardson, who also wants
to call it quits, said the stars and the producers have already
mapped out an approach to a finale that would run in May.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Taylor Thomas, who played their son Randy but has now
left the show for college, has been approached to come back for
that finale, but hasn't answered yet, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Although never on hipsters' radar, ``Home Improvement'' was one
of the biggest hits of the 1990s, earning hundreds of millions for
ABC and parent Disney in eight seasons, especially in syndication.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
