<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NELLIE-BIO21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A brief bio of Nellie Mae Rowe
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Personal: Born July 4, 1900, in Fayette County (Ga.). The
artist's father was an emancipated slave. She died of cancer in
1982 and is buried at the Flat Rock African Methodist Episcopal
Church, Fayetteville (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The playhouse: From 1937 until her death, she lived in a
four-room house at 2041 Paces Ferry Road in Vinings (Ga.). She
called it her playhouse and decorated it with dolls, drawings,
chairs, Christmas ornaments and all kinds of found objects. She
pruned the shrubbery to look like sheep, roadrunners, elephants and
ostriches. The site is now occupied by the Wyndham Gardens Hotel,
but there is a marker commemorating Rowe.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting recognized: Rowe was discovered by Atlanta collector
Judith Alexander in 1976. In 1982, she was one of 20 artists chosen
for a landmark exhibit on African-American folk art at the Corcoran
Gallery of Art in Washington. Her work is in the collections of
Atlanta's High Museum of Art, the Morris Museum of Art in Augusta
(Ga.), the Milwaukee Art Museum, the Museum of American Folk Art in
New York and the Studio Museum in Harlem, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Her legacy: Says Gerard C. Wertkin, director of the Museum of
American Folk Art: ``This is an artist who has risen above local
interest, to be sure. The interest is now national. I have a
suspicion that now after the exposure here in New York, it will be
international.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
