<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-1STLD-2TAKES-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A NEW FOSSE VEHICLE, A HEADLONG JOY RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of members of the cast of ``Fosse'' is being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
(af) 
 (Eds: Please use this version.) 
By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as their budgets and, occasionally, their aspirations have
ballooned, Broadway musicals give the impression of having grown
smaller in recent years, at least in part because of the
near-disappearance of dance from the American musical theater.
</P>
<P>
   Dance is still there, but it's either nondescript, as in
``Footloose,'' or solemnly obligatory, almost instructive, as in
``Ragtime.'' The sense of excitement and discovery has disappeared.
If you have any doubt about what has been lost or, better yet, if
you just want to have a terrifically entertaining night of Broadway
theater, then you can't afford to pass up ``Fosse,'' now at the
Broadhurst.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a very particular, epic-size musical revue. In its
consideration of the career of Bob Fosse as dancer, choreographer
and director on Broadway, in Hollywood and on television from the
late 1940s into the 1980s, it celebrates the art, high spirits and
dazzling inventiveness of a theater now known only through
revivals.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned, however. ``Fosse'' is an anthology composed mostly of
climaxes for which there are no build-ups. Some numbers are
presented in their entirety, while others are spliced into medleys
and not always easy to identify. Yet the elegant-looking production
is given cohesion by the dynamic character and the restless mind of
Fosse himself.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the pure exhilaration that comes only rarely these
days, when watching a cast of 32 talented performers dancing and
singing with an energy that, from time to time, threatens to raise
the roof.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Fosse'' looks back over approximately 40 years of dance in
theater and movies, it inevitably prompts the question: What
happened?
</P>
<P>
   It may be Jerome Robbins who forever confounded our expectations
for dance in the Broadway musical. His contributions still
astonish: think of his role in transforming ``Fancy Free,'' the
Robbins-Leonard Bernstein ballet, into ``On the Town'' (1944), of
his priceless Keystone Kops ballet for ``High Button Shoes''
(1947), of ``The Small House of Uncle Thomas'' ballet for ``The
King and I'' (1951) and of those balletic gang rumbles in ``West
Side Story'' (1957). He led us to believe that it would be the
classically trained choreographer, skilled also in modern dance,
who would bring new life and meaning to the American musical
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins was as much at home in a Broadway house as in Ballet
Theater. He brought a breadth of vision to musical shows that was
unique and, by comparison, called attention to what some people saw
as the limitations of such Broadway-bred choreographers as Fosse,
Michael Bennett and Gower Champion.
</P>
<P>
   An unfair comparison, really. Robbins was not just a great
choreographer. He was a genius. He was one of a kind, without
compare. He wasn't someone next to whom anyone else can be measured
without the help of a large footstool.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographers of the stature of Fosse, Bennett and Champion
were masters of their own class of entertainment. No wonder they
became directors: Broadway was then a dancing place.
</P>
<P>
   If you have seen the work of the choreographers from ballet and
modern dance who have recently been corralled by the musical
theater, you might have noticed that there haven't been any Jerome
Robbinses among them. You might also have realized that these
recruits can be even more limited in their vision than the earlier
generation of hoofers who went on to become superlative Broadway
choreographers. (The one possible exception: Garth Fagan, the
modern dancer and choreographer whose work is integral to the
success of Julie Taymor's vision of ``The Lion King.'')
</P>
<P>
   The problem facing contemporary Broadway choreographers is not
only training but also experience. As the number of musical shows
produced each year has dwindled, and as dance has come to look like
an afterthought in the operettas that have dominated the scene, the
choreographic gene pool has all but dried up.
</P>
<P>
   No more that opportunity for Broadway gypsies to move from one
show to several others within a single season, to survive flops,
hits and road tours, to be hired and fired and to know that there
is another show casting around the corner, if not this week, then
next. No time to acquire the itch, not simply to dance well but to
create one's own idiosyncratic dance vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   If you saw Fosse's film ``All That Jazz'' (1979), a gorgeous but
self-absorbed Fellini-esque examination of the life of a director
very much like himself, you already know that he was a man given to
excess. The air he breathed was filtered through his cigarettes. He
drank too much, ate amphetamines for breakfast, loved his wife and
mistress and was faithful to neither. The film's most flamboyant
conceit: Fosse's foreseeing his own death, which was to come in
1987 when he was 60.
</P>
<P>
   Except for his fine screen version of ``Cabaret'' (1972) and
``Lenny,'' his comparatively disciplined biographical film about
Lenny Bruce, all of Fosse's movies reflect the tendency toward
excess that marked his life, though not his shows. He went a little
mad in the movie studio, like the kid who decides he is able to fly
with a parasol.
</P>
<P>
   Note ``Sweet Charity'' (1969), the first film he directed. Among
other things, the manic cross-cutting from one image to the next
and the use of gigantic real-life locations, from Lincoln Center to
Wall Street and the Brooklyn Bridge, all but swamp the adaptation
of his hit Broadway show of 1966. He effectively upstages not only
Shirley MacLaine, the star, the book by Neil Simon and the Cy
Coleman-Dorothy Fields score, but also his own distinctive
choreography.
</P>
<P>
   There is something infectiously cheeky and bold about Fosse's
movies as well as his shows. Yet his singular strength is his
choreography, which, when seen in the theater at its best, cuts to
the quick. It can make us laugh, and sometimes, without warning, as
in the final moments of ``Chicago,'' it can become unaccountably
moving. These are the gifts of the man whose work is now being
recalled on the stage of the Broadhurst.
</P>
<P>
   As a choreographer, Fosse is a satirist. He is cool, spare of
detail. At his best, he is also a brilliant caricaturist, someone
who uses a minimal number of precisely drawn lines to express the
essence of a single character, of several characters, of a whole
raft of characters, in a specific time, place and circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   I remember (I hope accurately) the initial image in the Broadway
production of ``Sweet Charity'': Gwen Verdon, seen alone in
silhouette against an orange-lighted cyclorama, her weight on one
leg, her hip thrust to the other side, one arm akimbo _ a Broadway
taxi dancer waiting for a customer and waiting, maybe forever, for
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet Charity'' provides ``Fosse'' with two of the show's most
elegant sequences: the marvelously comic ``Rich Man's Frug,'' in
which Manhattan nobs, as ferret-faced as Maurice Sendak characters,
sweep around a nightclub as if untroubled even by gravity (as
choreographed by Fosse, the dancers appear to float), and ``Big
Spender,'' wherein Charity's taxi-dancer pals stand at the bar and
face the audience, alternately wheedling and intimidating their
would-be customers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other memorable numbers recalled: ``Steam Heat''
from ``The Pajama Game'' (1954), ``Mr. Bojangles'' from ``Dancin'
'' (1978), ``Take Off With Us _ Three Pas de Deux'' from ``All That
Jazz,'' in which three nearly nude couples, one heterosexual, one
homosexual and one lesbian, make love, going as far as a standard
modern balletic vocabulary allows, and the foot-stomping grand
finale, ``Sing, Sing, Sing,'' also from ``Dancin'.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   My favorite: a sly, spirited take on the old standard ``Me and
My Shadow'' from Fosse's last show, ``Big Deal'' (1986), in which
Eugene Fleming, Kim Morgan Greene and Dana Moore add a sexual
dimension to the song so languidly and sentimentally sung by Ted
Lewis from the 1920s into the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat less effective, in part because they can be seen in
context next door at the Shubert Theater where ``Chicago'' is
playing: Fred Ebb and John Kander's ``Razzle Dazzle'' and
``Nowadays.'' ``Shoeless Joe From Hannibal, Mo.,'' from ``Damn
Yankees'' (1955), also isn't helped by the fact that the number was
better done in the 1995 Broadway revival, choreographed by Rob
Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Maltby Jr. is the director responsible for coordinating
the many talents involved, including Gwen Verdon, Fosse's widow,
the show's artistic adviser, and Ann Reinking, Fosse's companion,
who is the co-director and (with Fosse) co-choreographer. Note that
the spiffy production was initiated and is being presented by
Livent Inc., the bankrupt Canadian company (which is also
presenting ``Ragtime''), founded by the besieged, deposed
entrepreneur Garth Drabinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Note also two other expert performers who help to make this
enterprise work: Valarie Pettiford, who is both an accomplished
Fosse dancer and a singer to shake the rafters, and that superb
dancer Scott Wise, who also sings the elegant though abbreviated
``Razzle Dazzle.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing so much of Fosse's extraordinary work, in such a
condensed form, also provides clues as to the identity of those who
may have influenced him. Fosse himself acknowledged his debt to
Jack Cole, the Broadway and Hollywood choreographer sometimes
credited for having created ``jazz dancing.'' ``Fosse'' also brings
to mind Charlie Chaplin, an association I had never noticed before.
If Charlie Chaplin had been a choreographer, he might have created
dances like Fosse's.
</P>
<P>
   The resemblance is remarked on not because of Fosse's fondness
for derby hats and gloves. Rather, it's because the singular
fashion in which Fosse uses the dancer's body, at rest and in
motion, so frequently evokes Chaplin mannerisms, everything from
the way the Tramp walks and stands to the way he controls his
hands, even his elbows.
</P>
<P>
   One big difference: Chaplin depends on close-ups of the Tramp's
face to verify what has already been made clear. Fosse appreciates
the full figure. The costumes he favors for his dancers, including
black leotards, have a way of deflecting attention from individual
features to allow movement to become the principal expression of
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fosse,'' you should understand, is a rich, bewitching show. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Art,'' Yasmina Reza's superbly funny French play, is clearly a
theatrical phenomenon both in this country, where it is being seen
in Christopher Hampton's English translation, and abroad, where it
is playing _ or has played _ in more than 40 countries. It seems to
be unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   At the Royale Theater in New York, Judd Hirsch, Joe Morton and
George Wendt have replaced the English cast, which earlier replaced
Alan Alda, Victor Garber and Alfred Molina, who opened the show at
the Royale last March. That company has just opened at the Ahmanson
Theater in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Another company is at the Royal George in Chicago. London, where
the play opened in 1996, is on its ninth company. Meanwhile,
``Art'' continues in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other places it has been seen: India, Peru, Belarus,
Japan and Serbia. Remember, this is a comedy about three Frenchmen,
members of the bourgeoisie, whose longtime friendship is about to
dissolve in acrimony over the acquisition by one of the friends of
a white-on-white painting. Does wit suddenly sell like kung-fu
movies? In some places, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   A return visit to the Royale to see the new cast confirms my
original reaction: ``Art,'' directed in New York as well as in
London by Matthew Warchus, is an exceptionally wise and
sophisticated work. It succeeds in being stylishly contemporary
without ever dropping brand-names or references to any celebrity
born after Seneca. Further, it is a play that seems to fit with
ease any number of good if quite different actors.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt, who is still best remembered as Norm in the long-running
sitcom ``Cheers,'' easily slips his large frame into the role of
Yvan. It's a part actors might die for: the harried friend who
helps precipitate the crisis by becoming engaged and rebelling
against his position as the comedy relief for the two other men.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch is furiously, seriously comic as Marc, the full-time
control freak. Morton is splendidly condescending as Serge, the
divorced doctor who embarks on a life as a collector by buying the
painting for a price his pals find ludicrous, 200,000 francs, or
approximately $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art'' is a delight in the economy of its construction. Running
90 minutes and played without an intermission, it never seems to
hurry but, by the time it ends, a friendship has been analyzed in
the kind of minute psychological detail you are more likely to find
in a well-written short story or novel. ``Art'' breathes as if it
had a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   There is something mysterious about writing so firm and true: it
is infinitely adaptable. After watching each of the three casts I
have seen play it, I have been convinced that no one else did it
better, or even quite the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
