<HEADER>
A1505 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHANGEL-BOOK-REVIEW     01-20 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHANGEL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ARCHANGEL': STALIN'S SECRET NOTEBOOK BURIED IN BERIA'S GARDEN
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review) 
(bl) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You could hear the howling of caged wolves'' in the Moscow
zoo, says a character who is both describing a location and setting
the atmosphere at the outset of Robert Harris' powerful new
thriller, ``Archangel,'' which, like the author's previous novels,
``Fatherland'' and ``Enigma,'' makes clever imaginative use of an
actual historical detail.
</P>
<P>
   The character is Christopher Richard Andrew (Fluke) Kelso, a
former lecturer on Russian history at Oxford who was once described
by a newspaper as ``a battered Byron,'' which wasn't bad, the
narrator says: ``if Byron hadn't died on Missolonghi but had spent
the next 10 years drinking whiskey, smoking, staying indoors, and
resolutely avoiding all exercise, he too might have come to look a
little like Fluke Kelso.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelso is in Moscow to attend a conference on newly opened Soviet
archives. One night, after delivering a paper on Stalin, he is
approached by one Papu Rapava, an old NKVD officer who was once the
bodyguard of the secret-police chief Lavrenti Beria. In Kelso's
hotel room, over many bottles from the minibar, Rapava tells a
story about the night of March 2, 1953, when he accompanied Beria
on an emergency call to Stalin's dacha just outside of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   There they found the general-secretary lying in one of his
bedrooms, immobilized by a stroke. Making sure that he was not
conscious, they found the key that he always kept on him, drove
back to the Kremlin and from a safe in his office removed certain
personal papers, including an oilskin-covered notebook thought to
contain some testament to the Soviet people. They then took the
papers to Beria's residence on Vspolnyi Street and buried them in a
toolbox in the garden. Three days later, Stalin died.
</P>
<P>
   When Kelso tells Rapava the notebook could be worth a fortune
and asks him if he can produce it, Rapava slips away without
leaving Kelso any way of getting in touch with him, except for a
few personal details and a matchbook advertising a bar. Kelso's
colleagues at the conference assure him that Rapava's story is a
classic setup for a scam like Hitler's forged diaries, which the
author of ``Archangel,'' a former television correspondent for the
BBC and a columnist for The Sunday Times of London, happens to have
written a book about, ``Selling Hitler.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kelso, already an expert on Stalin, plays hooky from the
conference to check out the details of Stalin's death and learns
that Rapava's story is completely plausible. More ominously,
Kelso's research quickly attracts the interest of several
mysterious parties, including Vladimir Mamantov, an old KGB officer
who leads a broad extremist movement calling for the revival of
Stalinist communism. Kelso soon gets caught up in an intrigue that
delivers the thrills of a Graham Greene entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing ``Archangel,'' when you think about what
happens, you find it so outlandish as to defy credibility. But
Harris makes you believe it as it's happening. What he does
particularly well is evoke the atmosphere of contemporary Russia,
not only the physical sense of it but also its threat of violent
instability, the howling of its caged wolves.
</P>
<P>
   As one character, R.J. O'Brian, an American television
journalist, explains, parroting Kelso's own views: ``Weimar
Republic, that's how I see it. Like you see it. Six things the
same, okay? One: you have a big country, proud country, lost its
empire, really lost a war, but can't figure out how _ figures it
must've been stabbed in the back, so there's a lot of resentment,
right? Two: democracy in a country with no tradition of democracy .
. . Three: border trouble . . . Four: anti-Semitism _ you can buy
SS marchin' songs on the street corners, for Christ's sake. That
leaves two.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All right,'' says Kelso.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic crash, and that's coming, don't you think?''
</P>
<P>
   ``And?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it obvious? Hitler. They haven't found their Hitler yet.
But when they do, it's watch out, world, I reckon.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course what Kelso believes is that they haven't found their
new Stalin yet, the old one having been, in his view, ``the most
alarming figure of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   As he explains in a talk to the conference: ``I say this not
merely because Stalin killed more people than Hitler although,
clearly, he did _ and not even because Stalin was more of a
psychopath than Hitler _ although, clearly, he was. I say it
because Stalin, unlike Hitler, has not yet been exorcised. And also
because Stalin was not a one-off like Hitler, an eruption from
nowhere. Stalin stands in a historical tradition of rule by terror,
which existed before him, which he refined, and which could exist
again. His, not Hitler's, is the specter that should worry us.''
</P>
<P>
   In another talk to the conference, Kelso recalls an image that
always occurs to him when he thinks of Stalin. After finishing
work, Stalin would go to the Kremlin movie theater to watch a film.
``Often, it was one of the Tarzan series,'' Kelso says; ``for some
reason Stalin loved the idea of a young man growing up and living
among wild animals.''
</P>
<P>
   After the film he and ``his cronies in the Politburo'' would
drive out to his dacha at Kuntsevo for dinner, and after dinner he
would go over to his gramophone and put on a record. ``His
particular favorite, according to Milovan Djilas, was a song in
which howling dogs replaced the sound of human voices. And then
Stalin would make the Politburo dance.'' One night, Stalin's
daughter, Svetlana, ``drawn, we might speculate, by the peculiar
noise of grown men dancing to the baying of hounds,'' put her head
around the door, and Stalin, seeing her, ``made her start dancing,
too.'' When she got tired and protested, Stalin _ and here Kelso
says he is quoting Khrushchev's description _ ``grabbed her like
this, by the hair, a whole fistful, I mean by her forelock, as it
were, and pulled, you understand, very hard . . . pulled, jerked
and jerked.''' It is this image of Stalin yanking his daughter by
the hair to the sound of howling dogs that is the key to the secret
of ``Archangel.'' From that image Harris has fashioned an adventure
that will keep you on edge until its bizarre conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ARCHANGEL'
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Harris
</P>
<P>
   373 pages. Random House. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
