<SLUG> BC-RENEE-FLEMING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA SUPERSTAR IS A MOM FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American soprano Renee Fleming first came to Fort Worth on the
Cliburn Foundation's recital series three years ago as an
undisputed star of the operatic world.
</P>
<P>
   She has moved up a level, to superstar. Already a regular
performer at the leading opera houses in Europe and America, she
has added a whole new dimension of name recognition as the star,
last fall in San Francisco, of the premiere production of Andre
Previn's opera ``A Streetcar Named Desire.''
</P>
<P>
   She has become such a big name, in fact, that 60 Minutes filmed
her during a Fort Worth recital this week for a segment to be aired
soon. But for Fleming, 39, operatic superstardom is balanced with
her more treasured role of motherhood. Separated from her husband,
actor John Shore, Fleming has refocused her career around her
relationship with her two daughters, ages 3 and 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty wonderful,'' she said last week. ``The children
ground me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she often travels with both children _ ``They love
planes, and we have a wonderful time'' _ their entry into school
years will slow the travel for all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have modified my career,'' Fleming says. Because operatic
productions require several solid weeks of work at one site, while
a recital can be accomplished with an overnight trip, she'll be
doing more recitals and fewer operas.
</P>
<P>
   But Fleming is certainly not totally tied down: The family has a
live-in nanny at its Connecticut home, the children's father is
close, amicable and involved, and Fleming has a brother and sister
who live nearby, making for an active extended family.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of high school voice teachers, Fleming grew up with
intense musical training. She trained at the Eastman School of
Music while still in high school, which perhaps pushed her a little
early, she thinks. She returned to Eastman for graduate study after
completing a degree in music education at Potsdam College in New
York. Additional graduate study followed at Juilliard and in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But Fleming's big break came in Texas in 1988, as the Countess
in a Houston production of Mozart's ``The Marriage of Figaro.'' By
1991, she was at the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mozart has been at the heart of her repertoire, she has
become well-known to Texas audiences for Slavic roles, including
Dvorak's ``Rusalka'' in Houston and Janacek's ``Jenufa'' and
Tchaikovsky's Tatiana (from ``Eugene Onegin'') in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming continues her own studies with Beverly Johnson in New
York; she believes that a singer can never really know what he or
she sounds like. As for her own daughters, who show musical talent,
Fleming is willing to let things take their course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't push them,'' she says. ``I want them to be able to
explore.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
