<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1509 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOWN-VS.-MEGABUSINESS     01-20 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWN-VS.-MEGABUSINESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINY TOWN STONEWALLS ROCK CRUSHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHUACANA, Texas _ Small-town pride and the interests of a
billion-dollar corporation have collided in a hilly stretch of
Limestone County, triggering a legal match that has shaken this
Central Texas hamlet of 322.
</P>
<P>
   Vulcan Materials Co., which employs 6,697 people and does $1.57
billion in sales a year, is suing Tehuacana. The town has this on
its side: an abandoned 19th century college campus, a tiny post
office and a general store.
</P>
<P>
   When Vulcan was told that it couldn't blast limestone within the
city limits, it hired one of the state's most powerful law firms,
Fulbright &AMP; Jaworski, and sued in federal court for $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama-based Vulcan is the nation's biggest supplier of crushed
stone for road paving.
</P>
<P>
   Tehuacana (pronounced Tuh-WAW-kuh-nuh), once a contender as a
site for Texas' capital, is a residential community bounded by
farms, ranches and a cutting horse operation, about 40 miles
northeast of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take pride in being a quiet peaceful town, and the rock
crushing is breaking their hearts,'' said Betty Shelton, 44, owner
of the Tehuacana General Store. ``A lot of them have tears in their
eyes when they discuss Vulcan. It's like a schoolyard bully pushing
you around.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vulcan believes that it is the underdog and Tehuacana the
oppressor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a government entity here telling us we can't work,
can't use our property,'' Tom Ransdell, 56, Vulcan's Southwest
region president, said in a telephone interview from San Antonio.
``They're the government making the laws and using powers to put us
out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Vulcan accuses the town of violating its constitutional rights.
The corporation has sued under the Fifth and 14th Amendments, which
guarantee due process.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are 160 acres _ 50 within the city limits _ of quality
limestone that would fetch roughly double the price of medium-grade
aggregate stone, Ransdell said. Shutting down would cost the firm
$25 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ransdell argues that Tehuacana allowed quarrying in the 1960s
and that Vulcan for years has safely operated in small and large
Texas cities, sometimes just a few hundred feet from homes.
</P>
<P>
   He has swayed practically no one in Tehuacana.
</P>
<P>
   Vulcan bought the operations of Smith Crushed Stone in October
1997 and acquired its mining lease. At the time, Ransdell said, he
was unaware of written assurance by Smith's Dallas attorney that it
would not quarry within the city limits. Those assurances were made
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Vulcan wants to be a good corporate neighbor, Ransdell said,
adding that his firm has repaired roads and sponsored a Halloween
health fair.
</P>
<P>
   But Tehuacana's Community Action League, a grassroots group
opposed to Vulcan, organized a boycott of the health fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only two residents from town showed up,'' David McCartney, a
retired school superintendent, gleefully reported.
</P>
<P>
   The adversaries are expected to meet in federal court in Waco in
July.
</P>
<P>
   It may not help Vulcan's case that its lawyers misspelled
Tehuacana at every mention in its 10-page lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But then, if Tehuacana's own past is any guide, the outlook is
dim. Its history is littered with disaster and disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   The town was first called Tehuacana Hills after the small
Tehuacana tribe, which lived in the area but whose members were
massacred by a rival tribe in the early 1830s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1849, the town finished third in balloting to be the capital
of Texas, after Austin and Palestine. Tehuacana nearly disappeared
after Trinity University moved to San Antonio in 1902 after 33
years. A Methodist school, Westminster College, moved in, but
closed in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   The high emotions of the new legal fight have transformed the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had factions before with petty politics, bitterness and
people butting heads,'' Shelton said, standing outside her store
after cooking chicken-fried steaks for noon diners. ``The town has
come together like you wouldn't believe _ like glue dropped on
Tehuacana. It's heartwarming watching them band together.''
</P>
<P>
   The standoff began Dec. 8, when city leaders voted unanimously
to prohibit mining and rock blasting inside city limits.
</P>
<P>
   The vote followed rock-blasting explosions by Vulcan, which
upset nearby residents such as Henry ``Banjo'' Johns, who lives
about a quarter-mile from the operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved here because it was a quiet place,'' said Johns, 80,
whose wife, Ruby, also 80, is recovering from two strokes. He said
blasts in October rocked their mobile home and deeply upset her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting so close we won't be able to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   When Smith held the mining lease, a May 1996 explosion sent
rocks the size of small boulders into a resident's yard and onto a
county road used by school buses. The community was outraged.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Vulcan indicated that it would extend operations into
Tehuacana proper, the town decided to take no chances, said its
attorney, H. Fred Neale of Mexia, who wrote the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, any city is entitled to pass an ordinance intended
to protect citizens from operations that could constitute a danger
to people or property, or constitute a nuisance to a residential
area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the $25 million in damages Vulcan is seeking, Neale said,
``I think they're confusing limestone with gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is that the figure was meant for shock value _ an
attempt to intimidate the city and the citizens,'' he said.
``They're so big they think they can just run over this little
city. But, frankly, they've bit off the wrong little town.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
