<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIO ADS PRESS SENATE ON IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A battle in the airwaves and cyberspace between
pro- and anti-impeachment groups shifts into high gear Thursday as
the Senate resumes the trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   People for the American Way, a liberal public policy
organization here, plans a radio advertising campaign urging
senators to end the impeachment trial. The 60-second spot begins on
the third day of testimony from Clinton's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   This joins other recent advertising and Internet efforts in an
ideological tug-of-war over how senators should handle the Clinton
case.
</P>
<P>
   The People for the American Way said its new ad ``is designed to
give voice to the majority of Americans who oppose impeachment and
feel growing frustration over Congress' continued pursuit of a
partisan goal that is not supported by the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lux, the organization's senior vice president, said the
spot is targeted at Republican senators in Maine, Rhode Island,
Vermont and Washington state. The ads will run in the major markets
of those states and in Washington, D.C., on Thursday, Friday and
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking people to call and get those senators to vote
yes'' when the Senate considers a motion to dismiss the case
against Clinton. Such a motion could be heard in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The same group last month waged an unsuccessful advertisement
blitz to sway the House against impeaching the president.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved two articles of impeachment against Clinton
Dec. 19. The president is charged with perjury and obstruction of
justice in trying to conceal his affair with Monica Lewinsky, a
former White House intern, during the course a sexual harassment
lawsuit brought by Paul Jones, a former Arkansas government worker.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Dart, a Republican who has advised Presidents Reagan,
Bush and Clinton on disability policies, also began airing
60-second anti-impeachment ads this week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``has made the same hurtful mistake as many presidents
and millions of Americans, including me, who were not impeached,''
Dart begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building on the good work of George Bush, Bill Clinton has
empowered people with disabilities as never before,'' Dart says in
the radio spot. ``But in spite of real gains, too many Americans,
including millions with disabilities, are still shut out of the
good life. We need Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Dart's spot ran for three days in the Washington area, and he
said the ad may soon run in other markets around the country.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum is Steve Vaus, a conservative
San Diego songwriter whose spots, while they don't expressly call
for the president's removal, are anti-Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   One ad features the voice of a child caught fibbing who asks the
president for help. ``Mr. President, could you call my mom? Maybe
get her just to censure me? I know you can explain lying better
than anybody,'' the child says.
</P>
<P>
   An announcer then adds, ``If it takes a village to raise a
child, the leader of that village must lead by example _ children
must know that facts matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaus' spots have aired in Atlanta, Denver, Los Angeles, New
York, San Diego and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The spots follow a pro-impeachment radio campaign last month by
Steve Forbes, the publishing magnate and Republican presidential
aspirant, as the House deliberated charges against the president.
In those spots aired in major markets, Forbes said that ``turning a
blind eye to presidential felonies'' poses a grave danger to the
republic.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Rosenberg, a Forbes spokesman, said Forbes had not decided
whether he will renew the ads sometime during the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to radio ads, the Internet has become a favorite
tool of groups seeking to influence the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   An organization called Move On allows a visitor to sign an
on-line petition urging senators to ``censure President Clinton and
move on to pressing issues facing the country.'' The group also
warns senators that they will pay a political price at the polls if
the trial isn't ended.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Web site of the Christian Coalition, a
conservative political organization, lets visitors sign a petition
directing senators to press ahead with the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the President does not resign, Congress has a moral and
constitutional obligation to act swiftly and remove the President
from office,'' the petition says.
</P>
</TEXT>
