<HEADER>
A1525 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOGS-KAN &LR;      01-20 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOGS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
[HEAD MISSOURI LAWSUIT ACCUSES HOG PRODUCER OF POLLUTION KANSAS
CITY, Mo. _ Accusing Premium Standard Farms of a long history of
polluting Missouri streams, state officials on Tuesday sued the
company, which is the state's largest hog producer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in Jackson County Circuit Court, asks that
the company be ordered to cease its hog breeding operations until
the court approves a new system to manage hog wastes.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accuses the Kansas City-based hog producer, the
nation's third largest, of repeated hog-waste spills, failing to
report many spills and spraying excessive amounts of hog wastes
onto farmland.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit asks for $10,000 in fines for each day that the
company operated in violation of state law. The facilities cited
for pollution are located in Mercer, Putnam and Sullivan counties.
</P>
<P>
   Premium Standard Farms ``has failed in its obligation to obey
the law, to not despoil the environment, and to be a good neighbor
to those Missourians whose families have been farming this land for
generations,'' said Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   A Premium Standard Farms' spokesman declined Tuesday to comment
on the specific allegations in the lawsuit but pledged to cooperate
with state officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premium Standard Farms accepts responsibility for our
environmental performance, and we're going to cooperate fully with
the attorney general and the Department of Natural Resources,''
said Charlie Arnot, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Arnot added that the company has initiated significant
improvements in its operations. The most important, he said, was
the recent decision to hire an outside engineering company to
conduct annual pollution audits of its operations.
</P>
<P>
   The company will respond in legal filings to the specific
allegations in the lawsuit, Arnot said.
</P>
<P>
   Premium Standard Farms has 18 hog farms and 131 hog waste
lagoons in north Missouri. By state permit, the company can spray
or inject each year more than 750 million gallons of hog wastes
over 45,000 acres of north Missouri farmland.
</P>
<P>
   If the court were to uphold the state on all counts and impose
the maximum fines, Premium Standard Farms could face hundreds of
thousands of dollars in penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Sierra Club cheered the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company, a chronic and habitual polluter, has run out of
time,'' said Ken Midkiff, the Sierra Club's program director.
</P>
<P>
   Rolf Christen, a Sullivan County farmer and director of Citizens
Legal Environmental Action Network, said his group was ``encouraged
that this action will bring about fundamental and lasting change in
the attitude and management of this corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   Christen's group has filed federal lawsuits against Premium
Standard Farms and its majority owner, Continental Grain Company,
accusing the company of water and air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Several specific violations of Missouri law were cited in the
state's lawsuit filed Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   - Thousands of gallons of hog wastes were spilled into Spring
Creek in May and December of 1997. The May spill wasn't reported to
the state for more than 16 hours.
</P>
<P>
   - At least 11 other hog waste spills in 1996 and 1997 were not
reported to state officials until December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   - As recently as last year, the company was applying hog wastes
onto farm lands at rates in excess of what is allowed by its state
permits. Excessive rates, which can lead to pollution of nearby
streams, were applied on at least 145 separate sites.
</P>
<P>
   - The company's irrigation system is poorly constructed and in
violation of its approved construction permits, which may have led
to spills.
</P>
<P>
   - The company's nursery, known as Summers Multiplier, is in
violation of state permits, housing more pigs than the state
authorized. It also operated for two years without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleges that waste spills and the frequent and
intense odors from the Premium Standard Farms facilities constitute
a public nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   For their neighbors, Premium Standard Farms' hog operations have
produced a ``profound negative impact on the quality of their lives
because of the uncontrolled stench that comes from tens of
thousands of pigs whose manure and urine are unreasonably
handled,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's office had been negotiating with Premium Standard Farms
for at least a year. But talks broke down last month, Nixon said,
when his office learned that company had continued to spray hog
wastes on farmland in violation of its permits, even as
negotiations continued.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Missouri environmental leaders were gathering
evidence that they said showed that the company's facilities were
``an environmental mess,'' an allegation that Premium Standard
Farms disputes.
</P>
<P>
   After the Missouri Sierra Club and the Citizens Legal
Environmental Action Network gave state regulators copies of
videotapes made at Premium Standard Farms, state officials pledged
last week to inspect the company's facilities with a special team
of state experts, including engineers, geologists and biologists.
</P>
<P>
   That team's inspections are expected to begin soon, said Nina
Thompson of the Missouri Department of Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Continental Grain Co. bought controlling interest in
Premium Standard Farms. The new operation, still called Premium
Standard Farms, includes Continental's farms in three other
northern Missouri counties.
 &LR; tag1:To reach Michael Mansur, The Star's environment writer, call
(816) 234-4433 or send e-mail to mmansur &LR; kcstar.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
