<SLUG> BC-PRAYER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
[HEAD CHAPLAIN'S PRAYER CRITICIZING CLINTON CAUSES RUCKUS IN KANSAS
SENATE TOPEKA, Kan. _ A guest chaplain's prayer that criticized
President Clinton touched off a minor controversy in the Kansas
Senate on Tuesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of the objections to the Senate prayer by Gene Price,
pastor of Word of Hope Church in Larned, came from Senate
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every citizen is entitled to express their opinions,'' said
Senate Democratic leader Anthony Hensley of Topeka, ``but a prayer
is offered to give spiritual inspiration, not political
agitation.''
</P>
<P>
   In his prayer, Price said: ``Lord, we stand before you, a nation
in need, with a president in need. I'm interceding to see the
floodgates of deception, unfaithfulness, lies, broken oaths and
covenants stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interceding on behalf of those disappointed, disillusioned
and discouraged: those destined to be future leaders of our land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely, the power and influence of leadership is our ability
to reproduce what we are in others. Heaven help us, as our children
become the mirror image of what we see in our land.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Dick Bond, an Overland Park Republican, did not
defend the content of the prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wouldn't have given that prayer,'' he said. ``It
sounded somewhat critical of the president. I'm not sure the prayer
is the appropriate place to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, however, added that he had no intention of prescribing the
day's Senate prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry Salmans, a Hanston Republican, invited Price as a
guest chaplain. The Senate's regular chaplain, Fred Hollomon, will
return to his post today. Each Senate session traditionally opens
with a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Price said he had no idea his prayer would generate
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just asked to come and pray my heart,'' he said, ``and
my heart has been broken by the situation we find ourselves in.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tag1:To reach John L. Petterson, Topeka correspondent for The
Star, call {(785) 354-1388} or send e-mail to
{jpetterson &LR; cjnetworks.com}
</P>
</TEXT>
