u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-FIBER-NYT &LR;      01-20 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-FIBER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RINGS STEER WEB EXPLORERS TO BACK ROADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for CIR-WEB-RINGS-SITES)  
 (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the most obscure and most fascinating sites on the Web
can be found almost exclusively sticking to its soft underbelly, in
Web rings. Take, for example, Tales of Fur and Fiber
(members.aol.com/daknits/index.html), run by Rachel Hecht, which
includes a page of superstitions about knitting.
</P>
<P>
   With the Webmaster's Himalayan cat, Firkin, and Maltese dog,
Oliver, as guides, we learn: ``Knitting for children you may have
in the future, but before you are pregnant, is bad luck.'' ``If you
knit one of your own hairs into a garment, it will bind the
recipient to you.'' ``Don't knit a pair of socks for your boyfriend
or he'll walk away from you!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hecht, who lives in North Miami Beach, Fla., joined her site
with the Free Knitting Patterns Web Ring
(www.geocities.com/Paris/9197/knitring.htm), part of Webring.org.
It includes material from the Knit List, an online knitting group.
</P>
<P>
   Someone desperate to find superstitions about knitting (and
isn't everyone, at one time or another, during this brief time on
earth?) would be out of luck in all but one of the major search
engines. Alta Vista picks up the Fur and Fiber site. But other
search engines turned up uninspiring results or nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   The searches produced many hits on the ``Innuendo'' album by the
rock group Queen. The album includes ``knitting'' and
``superstition'' in its lyrics, and the occasional mention of
Madame LaFarge, the knitter from Dickens' ``Tale of Two Cities.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the Web Ring site, there was just one ring devoted to
knitting, and the superstitions were easy to find by browsing
through the list. So where else could one learn this crucial
information: ``Stabbing your needles through your yarn balls brings
bad luck to anyone who wears something made from that yarn''? Let
the wearer beware.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1838EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-0121-COX     01-20 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-0121-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITNESS: A MICROSOFT MONOPOLY WOULD CHARGE $2,000 FOR WINDOWS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If government theories about Microsoft's monopoly
power were on the mark, the software giant would be selling its
Windows operating system for 40 times its current price, or $2,000
a copy, an economist appearing for the company testified Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Schmalensee of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
made what he called ``this reasonable inference'' near the close of
a tough four-day cross-examination by Justice Department lawyer
David Boies at the Microsoft antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been retained to perform an economic analysis, and I'm
giving that estimate because I believe it,'' Schmalensee told an
incredulous Boies. ``I value my reputation very highly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really think that (estimate) makes sense?'' Boies
persisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' the witness answered. ``But that's because
Microsoft faces long-term competition and isn't free to charge
whatever it wants for Windows.''
</P>
<P>
   When Boies asked the witness what share of Microsoft's profits
came from Windows' sales, the economist said the firm's accounting
system does not distinguish between the money it makes from Windows
and from its various applications programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since both software streams share lots of common costs,''
Schmalensee said, ``that data doesn't exist.'' Besides, he added,
``Microsoft's accounting system isn't all that modern. They enter
sales of their operating system by hand on sheets of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Boies had focused on how Microsoft limits the freedom
of personal computer makers to change how Windows appears when it
first boots up on about 90 percent of all machines begin sold
today. Windows licensees, for example, are barred from hiding or
removing access to Microsoft's Internet browser.
</P>
<P>
   If a computer maker ``gets unhappy with Microsoft, does it have
anywhere to go?'' Boies asked Schmalensee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short run,'' the answer is no, the witness said. But he
added, ``I was just five feet away from Michael Dell a few weeks
ago when he said: 'We sell what our consumers want. And if
consumers don't want Windows, then we won't sell Windows.' ``
</P>
<P>
   But the benign view held by the founder of Austin-based Dell
Computer Co. wasn't reflected in an indignant e-mail to Microsoft
from an executive at Hewlett-Packard Co., the world's second
largest computer company, complaining about the licensing limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a choice of another supplier, based on your actions
in this area, I assure you you would not be our supplier of
choice,'' wrote John Romano, a manager at Hewlett-Packard. He
maintained that Microsoft's restrictions caused ``significant and
costly problems'' for his firm.
</P>
<P>
   Shown the message, Schmalensee called Romano ``clearly an angry
person.'' However, he said ``channel conflict'' is a fact of life
in the business world whenever a manufacturer's rule rubs a
distributor the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be surprising ... if Microsoft, in reducing the
freedom of action in some respects, didn't cause them upset,''
Schmalensee said.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony from Paul Maritz, Microsoft's vice president of the
platforms and applications group and a key decision maker in the
browser wars with Netscape Communications Corp., is now due to
begin Monday. Through e-mail messages entered into evidence
throughout the long trial, Maritz has already emerged as a key
figure in the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
