A1550 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-GERRYMANDERING-     01-20 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-GERRYMANDERING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT STRUGGLES OVER THE ROLE OF RACE IN DRAWING VOTING DISTRICTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court took up an issue Wednesday that
has bedeviled it several times in this decade: whether a state
legislature's redrawing of a congressional district was an attempt
at racial gerrymandering or merely an exercise in plain old
politics.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was North Carolina's 12th Congressional District,
containing parts of Winston-Salem, which critics have said was
drawn with racial factors as the predominant consideration _
something the high court has ruled unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   A group of white plaintiffs filed a suit in federal court
alleging that the North Carolina legislature drew the district's
boundary lines in 1997 in an effort to get minority candidates
elected, violating the equal protection clause of the 14th
Amendment, which bans racial favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina argues that it was trying to draw a congressional
district where Democratic voters would be in the majority. The fact
that the new district was heavily African American was merely a
coincidence, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Last April a U.S. District Court ruled 2-1 that the 12th
District was unconstitutional primarily because the legislature had
excluded many adjoining precincts that were heavily Democratic but
not largely African American.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time in seven years that the high court has
examined the North Carolina district. Over the decade it has ruled
on similar cases from Texas, Louisiana and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th District case offers the justices an opportunity to
clarify their position on how large a role race can play _ or
whether it can play any role _ in drawing congressional districts.
State legislatures around the country will begin the process of
redistricting their states after the 2000 Census.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the court has limited itself to saying only that race
cannot be the ``predominant factor'' in drawing a new district.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's oral argument, Robinson O. Everett, the lawyer
for the whites who claim they were discriminated against in the
drawing of the district, told the justices, ``If you look at the
precincts around the 12th district, it's obvious that race was the
motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The legislature drew a district where African
Americans would be elected and then gave reasons after the fact to
cover their real motivation,'' Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David Souter asked him to explain why a top state
statistician in North Carolina concluded that statistically, the
legislature's decision was just as likely to be based on political
affiliation as race.
</P>
<P>
   Everett seemed perplexed at first, then said, ``I believe his
conclusions are beside the point, since I'm trying to argue that
the state is using politics as a cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Solicitor General Walter E. Dellinger, arguing for
the state of North Carolina, said, ``The 12th district wasn't drawn
on the basis of race but on fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the legislature was trying to create a
Democratic-leaning district in a ``sea of Republican'' voters.
</P>
<P>
   Dellinger also addressed Everett's contention that adjoining
Democratic precincts with white majorities were kept out of the
12th District. He said these precincts, while appearing heavily
Democratic because a majority of voters were registered Democrats,
were, in fact, evenly split between the parties and, at times, were
Republican strongholds. The reason, he said, was that in these
precincts, registered Democrats routinely voted Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Everett and the (U.S.) District Court relied only on
registered voter numbers, but if they had bothered to look at the
voting records of these areas, they'd know that they were not
Democratic precincts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department attorney James Feldman argued that the case
against North Carolina has little merit because the redrawn 12th
District is not majority African American.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how best to deal with past discrimination has
deeply divided the court's nine justices who remain at odds over
the role race and ethnicity should play in crafting remedial
measures ranging from affirmative-action programs in schools and
the workplace to efforts to create voting districts where
minorities predominate in order to help Congress better reflect
America's ethnic diversity.
</P>
<P>
   During much of the 1990s, the justices have often split 5-4 over
these issues in favor of more conservative approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The slim conservative majority, emphasizing the 14th Amendment's
equal protection of all Americans regardless of race, has ruled
repeatedly that if any race-based formula is used in redistricting,
it must be narrowly tailored to serve a compelling state interest.
</P>
<P>
   In none of the major redistricting cases that the court decided
in this decade has a state met that standard.
</P>
<P>
   During Wednesday's arguments, one of the court's most
conservative members, Justice Antonin Scalia, appeared to pushing
for an end to any consideration of race in redistricting. ``If a
legislature decided to keep a couple of black precincts out of a
district to make sure a white person was elected and then said,
`Well, race was just the final factor,' that wouldn't be allowed,''
Scalia said. ``That type of stuff isn't allowed in the workplace,
so why should it be all right here?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
