A1555 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH21-COX     01-20 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brazilian currency crisis causes earnings decline for BellSouth
Corp.
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. warned Wednesday that its earnings
will sag by about $172 million during the current quarter as a
result of the Brazilian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that first concrete sign the exchange crunch is hitting
home, BellSouth again vowed to stick with a multibillion dollar
strategy aimed at exploiting Brazil's huge economy as it
modernizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are convinced our Latin American investments will continue
to be a growth engine for us as we enter the new millennium,'' said
BellSouth Chairman Duane Ackerman in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   However, the dramatic fall in the value of the Brazilian real is
making payment on a $1 billion debt much more expensive for BCP,
the Brazilian subsidiary that is 46 percent owned by $23
billion-a-year BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   With several Brazilian partners, BellSouth has licenses to offer
wireless service in two regions. The service has racked up more
than 1 million subscribers _ most in Sao Paulo, a city of
approximately 18 million.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth and its partners were lucky to have spent much of the
money needed to build those systems _ hundreds of millions of
dollars on switches and cell sites _ before the currency crisis
hit. Still, BellSouth estimates the currency crisis' impact on
first quarter earnings at 9 cents per share. An average of analyst
predictions made before Wednesday's announcement put first quarter
earnings at 45 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Marten, analyst at Edward Jones &AMP; Co., said the currency
crisis appears to be a short-term problem for BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real value of those investments is the high population
growth in Brazil and Latin America. What we are really looking for
are the earnings from ongoing operations, because that is more
indicative of operations going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, whose economy is twice the size of Mexico's, is seen as
the key to the economic health of the region. The country is also
the flagship of BellSouth's international strategy, which includes
eight other Latin countries, as well as several properties in
Europe. BellSouth and its partners spent more than $2.5 billion
just winning the licenses needed to provide service in Brazil,
betting it can recoup far more than that by satisfying a pent-up
thirst for telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   And while analysts expect Brazil to go through some rough months
_ perhaps even years _ few predict a calamitous downturn. Short of
a full-scale depression, analysts believe BellSouth's wireless
business will keep growing.
</P>
<P>
   A series of devaluations have barely slowed down BellSouth's
wireless business in Venezuela, said BellSouth spokesman Al
Schweitzer. ``What that tells us is to hang in there, provide
quality services, satisfy the marketplace and it's going to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth will report earnings Monday for the fourth quarter of
1998. An average of analyst projections puts those profits at 41
cents per share for the quarter and $1.63 a share for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
