</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fortune looks at cause of 'finished at 40' culture
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Experience may be the best teacher, but if Fortune
(Feb. 1) is right it doesn't count for much any more in U.S.
business. ``Today, for many people, the longer you've been at one
company, the more disposable you are,'' senior writer Nina Munk
says.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on technology, on pressure to produce, on demographics
_ whatever the cause, ``in the new economy, experience and the
skills that come with age now count for less and less.'' One New
York employer is quoted as saying he can hire ``a smart, raw kid
right out of undergrad'' for $40,000 to $50,000, who will work
seven days a week for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative, he says, is to pay twice as much money to
``some 40-year-old who does half the amount of work, has been
trained improperly and doesn't listen to what I say.'' This
attitude is creating what Fortune calls a ``finished at 40''
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund scorecards
</P>
<P>
   It's mutual fund analysis and ranking time in the business
press:
</P>
<P>
   Smart Money (February) reminds us 1998 was the worst year for
mutual funds in this decade, with just 12 percent of domestic stock
funds outperforming the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation is that, like professional baseball, there are
so many more funds now than in 1990 there isn't enough management
talent to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Money (February) makes a case that 1999 may be the year that
funds come out of their slump and outrun the indexes. Analyst
Michael Sivy says managers will catch up with stocks of smaller
companies and emerging markets, which have trailed blue chips.
</P>
<P>
   Ho-hum, more stocks?
</P>
<P>
   Tired of those dull stocks, bonds and mutual funds? Why not add
some spice to your portfolio by investing in alpacas, llama-like
South American animals highly valued for their wool? That's a
suggestion from P.O.V. (February), which notes that conventional
investments are necessary, but just aren't as much fun as offbeat _
but profitable _ items.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggestions? Race horses, vintage wine, antique musical
instruments, Broadway (or off-Broadway) plays, classic cars.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ This is a good time for a career change, Working Woman
(February) says, listing 20 ``hot careers.'' The opportunities come
from recent cutbacks due to economic turmoil in 1998, which created
a shift in demand for labor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
