<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1576 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-PREVIEWS-SPI &LR;      01-20 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-PREVIEWS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD GETS READY TO SET OSCAR-MANIA IN MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't long ago that the Hollywood Foreign Press
Association's Golden Globe Awards were considered the most
irrelevant and tarnished of all the annual movie awards _ the one
prize that a shrewd producer could actually ``buy'' by wining and
dining the right journalists.
</P>
<P>
   But in the '90s, that has changed. Ever since some pundit first
noticed that the Globe nominations tended to be an uncanny
bellwether for the Oscar nominations, they've steadily grown in
credibility _ and importance. So when they take place Sunday night
at the Beverly Hilton Hotel, Hollywood definitely will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   And attending. Since the ceremony takes place five days before
the polls close for Oscar nominations, the Globes also have become
the major campaign platform for the Academy Awards. It's accepted
now that an especially gracious or charming showing by a winner _
or presenter _ on Sunday night can well be the deciding factor that
sways the vote of an undecided Academy member.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Globes also have come to unofficially mark the
opening of the 1999 Oscar campaign season: one that picks up speed
the next day, when the Screen Directors Guild announces its
nominations (which usually match four out of five of the Oscar
nominations); and on Tuesday, when the Screen Actors Guild and the
American Society of Cinematographers announce their nominations.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the Writers Guild of America nominations on Feb. 3,
the American Cinema Editors ``Eddie'' Awards nominations on Feb. 5,
and, of course, the Academy Awards nominations, which will be
announced at a nationally televised news conference on Feb. 9, at
the ungodly hour of 5:30 a.m. Pacific Standard Time.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the Oscars really switch into high gear, and the
battalion of critics, pundits, soothsayers, Wall Street analysts
and Las Vegas oddsmakers who follow every beat of the competition
will be scrutinizing the results and readjusting their predictions
when the various guilds announce their awards: the writers on Feb.
20; the cinematographers on Feb. 21; the directors on March 6; and
the screen actors on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for the next two weeks, the television networks, CNN, E!
Entertainment Television and the various classic-movie cable
networks will all join in a frenzy of Oscar-mania and predictions
that will last right up to the moment the Oscar parties start and
the little gold statues of the 71st annual Academy Awards are
handed out at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion on March 21.
</P>
<P>
   After all the analysis and backslapping, can there possibly be
any suspense left by the time Oscar night rolls around? And don't
we already know that ``Saving Private Ryan'' is going to be the big
winner? (As Variety quoted one Academy member last July, ``Should
we just FedEx the Oscars over to Spielberg's house now and save
everybody the trouble of voting?'')
</P>
<P>
   Actually, yes, there should be a considerable amount of suspense
nine weeks from now _ maybe as much as in any Oscar night of the
'90s. And no, while it's still the clear best-picture front-runner,
Spielberg's ``Ryan'' no longer seems to have the lock on the
evening that ``Titanic'' did last year or ``Schindler's List,''
``Forrest Gump'' or ``The English Patient'' did in their years.
</P>
<P>
   The year-end critics awards _ the most important pre-Golden
Globe Oscar indicator _ gave decidedly mixed signals this time. The
New York Film Critics and L.A. Film Critics handed their best
picture honors to ``Ryan,'' but the National Board of Review picked
``Gods and Monsters'' and both the Boston Film Critics and the
National Society of Film Critics chose the quirky caper picture,
``Out of Sight.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong critical showing and likely best-picture nomination
of Terrence Malick's ``The Thin Red Line'' (released in January but
officially a '98 film) also diminishes the Spielberg movie's air of
invincibility, based on the theory that Academy members inclined
toward World War II movies will split their vote between the two
very different epics.
</P>
<P>
   If they do, it could leave the door open to one of the underdog
pictures that will be fighting it out for the other three
best-picture slots, in the same way ``Chariots of Fire'' upset
``Reds'' in 1981. Based on the Golden Globe nominations, this could
be ``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``Elizabeth,'' ``Gods and Monsters,''
``The Truman Show'' or perhaps even ``Bulworth'' (which was more
popular in Hollywood than it was in the rest of the country).
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Spielberg seem to have his name engraved on his second
directing Oscar. He won the L.A. Film Critics prize in that
category, but the New York Film Critics gave their directing nod to
Malick for ``The Thin Red Line'' (indicating another split could
occur here), and the National Board of Review gave the honor to
India's Shekhar Kapur for ``Elizabeth.'' Not to be counted out are
Steven Soderbergh for ``Out of Sight,'' John Madden for
``Shakespeare'' and Peter Weir for ``Truman.''
</P>
<P>
   The front-runner for the best-actor Oscar is no longer Tom
Hanks, who was blanked by the critic associations for ``Ryan,'' but
Ian McKellen, who took the L.A. and several other critics' prizes
for ``Gods and Monsters.'' Nick Nolte won the New York Film Critics
award for ``Affliction,'' and got the best notices of the all-star
cast of ``The Thin Red Line.'' So he has momentum, and a long track
record that deserves recognition. Also in the running are Jim
Carrey for ``Truman'' and Warren Beatty for ``Bulworth.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the best-actress race, for which ``Ryan'' has no
candidate, may be as wide open as it's been anytime in Oscar
history. Fernanda Montenegro (``Central Station''), Ally Sheedy
(``High Art''), Cate Blanchett (``Elizabeth'') and Cameron Diaz
(``There's Something About Mary'') have all won major
critic-association awards, and Emily Watson (``Hilary and
Jackie''), Gwyneth Paltrow (``Shakespeare'') and Meg Ryan (``You've
Got Mail'') also seem strong contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the air of suspense come March 21 is the fact that the
Academy is presenting an honorary award to director Elia Kazan,
who, despite his legendary career, has never been forgiven by much
of Hollywood for naming names in the McCarthy communist witch-hunt
era. When he won his last best-directing Oscar in 1954 (for ``On
the Waterfront''), he accepted it from New York. This time he'll be
in person. Will he be booed?
</P>
<P>
   There also is the matter of the Oscar-night host, an honor that
fell this year to Whoopi Goldberg after Billy Crystal turned it
down several weeks ago. In her two previous outings, Goldberg
proved to be competent but a pale second to Crystal, whose quick
wit and self-deprecating humor has made him the natural successor
to Bob Hope and Johnny Carson in the Oscar-host Hall of Fame. Will
this third time be the charm for Whoopi? Or the curse?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the greatest suspense of all about Oscar '99 may be
over how the public responds to its change of day, from Monday to
Sunday night. On the surface it seems like a great idea: allowing
an earlier start (5:30 p.m.), and a whole day for the networks to
build the audience with lead-in shows. ``But you never know,'' one
Oscar publicist confided to me. ``Since 1959, Oscar has been handed
out 32 times on Monday night. People have been programmed to think
Oscars and Monday and rush home from work. Let's just hope they
remember to turn back their watches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
