<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-DELAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA REPORTS DELAYS IN SPACE STATION, OBSERVATORY SCHEDULE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ NASA expects an additional delay of at least two
months in Russia's scheduled late July launching of the third
component of the U.S.-led international space station, agency
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency also disclosed another round of difficulties
with its giant new Chandra X-ray space telescope, a setback that
will force at least a five-week postponement in the anticipated
April 8 launching of the observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the developments pose a significant disruption to
NASA's plans to launch a half-dozen space shuttle missions this
year, four of them linked to the construction of the new space
station. Three of the four depend on the Russian service module
launching first.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-foot-long service module is taking longer than initially
anticipated to complete ground tests of its hardware components and
computer software at its Moscow production facilities, said James
Hartsfield, a spokesman for NASA's space station program office.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian contribution to the station will furnish the
life-support equipment and living quarters for the first crew of
three astronauts and cosmonauts. They are expected to become the
first residents of the new outpost sometime in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's chronic financial difficulties since joining the United
States, Europe, Japan and Canada in the station project in 1993
have stalled construction of the module. It was initially scheduled
for launching in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The first components of the new station were successfully
launched by the Russians and Americans in November and December.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
arranged for an unscheduled $60 million payment to the financially
ailing Russian space agency to ensure it could complete the
assembly at the Khrunichev State Research and Production Center in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an issue of getting the module built,'' Hartsfield
said Wednesday. ``The schedule has been pretty aggressive. The
testing will require additional time in Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   Engineers tentatively plan to ship the module to Russia's
Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan in March rather than February.
Additional launch site preparation will push the service module's
liftoff from late July to late September, though the schedule will
be reassessed by NASA in March.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled August launching of a U.S. shuttle crew to prepare
and equip the service module for occupancy will slip into the fall
of the year as well. It is too soon to judge how much shuttle
station assembly flights planned for October and December will be
affected, Hartsfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, newly discovered problems with electronic circuit
boards in NASA's $1.5 billion Chandra X-Ray Observatory will delay
plans for the year's first shuttle mission.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandra observatory had been scheduled for an August 1998
launching aboard the shuttle Columbia when computer software
difficulties forced a long delay.
</P>
<P>
   The four-story spacecraft appeared to have cleared those
obstacles earlier this month as TRW, its California-based
manufacturer, announced the observatory was ready for shipment to
NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida and an April 8 liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   However, late last week the company discovered faulty copper
circuitry in the electronics components of another satellite. The
circuit boards were similar to those installed aboard the Chandra,
said Ken Ledbetter, who heads the spacecraft development division
of NASA's office of space science.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency directed TRW to replace some boards and
evaluate others for potential replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This potentially was very critical to our mission,'' Ledbetter
said. ``We are very pleased we found this problem before we got any
further along.''
</P>
<P>
   Evaluations of circuit boards in six electronics components
aboard the observatory are under way. As of mid-week, one of the
boxes has two of the potentially faulty boards that merit
replacement. One box has been cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially, 22 boards in five boxes may require replacement,
warranting an even longer delay in the Chandra launching, Ledbetter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chandra is the third of NASA's great observatories, which
include the Hubble Space Telescope launched in 1990 and the Compton
Gamma Ray Observatory launched in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The new telescope was designed to give ground-based astronomers
their best views yet of the activities associated with mysterious
black holes and other high energy celestial objects.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member crew of the shuttle Columbia that will launch
Chandra is led by veteran astronaut Eileen Collins, who would
become the first woman of any nation to command a spaceflight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
