<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-IMPEACH-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans an 8-page package, including 5 pages of
text, on the aftermath of the State of the Union address and the
second day of President Clinton's defense in the Senate impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 7:30 p.m. Eastern time &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-SURPLUS (Washington) _ After a transition year in
which both parties struggled to shift from an era of crippling
federal budget deficits to an anticipated age of fiscal plenty, the
battle has at last been joined over how the country should allocate
the flood of excess money streaming into Washington. In short, the
debate is whether nearly all the surplus will be needed for the
twin pillars of the social welfare system, Social Security and
Medicare, as Democrats assert, or whether there is plenty to take
care of those looming problems and still return much of the surplus
to the people in the form of tax cuts, as Republicans say. By
Richard W. Stevenson. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-VOICES (San Francisco) _ The day after the State of
the Union speech. What one liberal neighborhood thinks. By Evelyn
Nieves. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-BUFFALO (Buffalo, N.Y.) _ Digging out of the snow
to see Clinton. A scene story, by Joseph Berger. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8:00 p.m. &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-REPUBS (Washington) _ Prominent Republicans around
the county said Wednesday that President Clinton's State of the
Union message was an unsettling reminder that the party cannot
compete with the president's political skills and that the
impeachment trial could only further endanger their electoral
prospects in competitive states. By Richard L. Berke. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-GREENSPAN (Washington) _ In testimony before a
House committee today, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan said that he
supported the president's notion of putting 62 percent of the
government budget surpluses over the next 15 years into Social
Security reserves, but he said that the plan to have the government
invest part of the money in the stock market could threaten the
economy. By David E. Rosenbaum. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ The Senate in the morning, when
senators have a chance to orate on absolutely anything they please
a full two hours before President Clinton's impeachment trial
resumes. It is Senate business time _ non-combative potpourri hours
for individual lawmakers to reserve time and speak on the record
before a nearly empty chamber. By Francis X. Clines. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8:30 p.m. &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ A White House lawyer rejected the
charge that President Clinton lied before a grand jury as nothing
more than ``arguments over semantics'' and accused House
Republicans of drawing conclusions more extreme than those of
Kenneth Starr. By R.W. Apple Jr. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ The House Republicans prosecuting
President Clinton are sharply divided over whether to seek to offer
new evidence that some managers say shows a pattern of obstruction
of justice by Clinton and his aides. By Eric Schmitt. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-CHICAGO (Chicago) _ Not so long ago, Chicago's
Public Schools were considered the worst in the nation. But in
Tuesday's State of the Union address, President Clinton held them
up as a model. Specifically, Mr. Clinton singled out the school
system's elimination of the practice of promoting students even if
they don't meet their grade's academic standards, just so they can
stay with their age group. But, as with most issues in education,
the reality is not as simple as it sounds. By Pam Belluck. (850
words)
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-TOBACCO (Undated) _ Folo on Clinton's announcement
of a federal suit against the tobacco industry: a history of the
backroom maneuvering that led to the government's action, the legal
theories involved and the effort to bring a new round of pressure
on the tobacco industry. By Barry Meier. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 9 p.m. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-CLINTON (Norristown, Pa.) _ An exuberant President
Clinton, showing no signs of the weight of impeachment, starred in
two foot-stomping rallies today, where he amplified the themes of
his State of the Union address and attacked Republican proposals
for across-the-board tax cuts. The president has attended few such
mass events over the past year, and he was rewarded with a
rapturous response. By John M. Broder. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-BUSH (Washington) _ Former President Bush addresses a
meeting of Republican senators. Developing. By Frank Bruni. (750
words)
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column: More
about the Clinton Social Security investment plan. By Michael M.
Weinstein. (950 words)
</P>
