<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RALLY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CONFRONTS REPUBLICANS ON SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ President Clinton rebutted Republican criticism
of his Social Security rescue scheme Wednesday at a jubilant
campaign-style pep rally staged by a venerable Democratic machine
to buoy the embattled chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by Vice President Al Gore, first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton and Tipper Gore, the president touted the centerpiece of
his State of the Union address to an enthusiastic audience in an
industrial, working-class city that supported the Clinton-Gore
ticket in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this one hell of a party or what?'' Erie County Executive
Dennis T. Gorski shouted at the boisterous crowd of 21,790
ticket-holding guests in the hockey arena used by the National
Hockey League's Buffalo Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton disputed GOP criticism of his Social Security plan that
he announced Tuesday night, cautioning Americans against GOP
suggestions that the projected 15-year, $4.4 trillion federal
budget surplus ought to be used for tax cuts rather than diverted
to bailing out the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound good if somebody says, `This is your surplus and
we ought to give it back to you,''' Clinton said. ``But you ought
to ask yourself ... how are families going to deal with the
retirement of the baby boom generation?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton conceded his proposal ``is not as popular as what others
can tell you,'' cautioning: ``Others can say, `We've got this
surplus now, I just want a tax cut. I'll give it back to you,
you'll figure out what to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before a House committee in Washington, Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan trashed the president's plan to
invest government funds in the stock market in order to produce
more revenue for the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said the proposal could hurt the economy and said it
was risky to allow government money to be invested in the stock
market because there was no way to insulate investment decisions
from ``political forces.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton respected
Greenspan's concerns, adding: ``We are committed to working with
Congress to make sure that any Social Security investments are made
by independent, private-sector managers without political
interference.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said if the White House and Congress could strike a deal
to use $2.7 billion of the projected budget surplus for Social
Security, it would spare the next generation the burden of
underwriting the retirement of the 76 million Americans born in the
post-World War II baby boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot afford to squander this moment,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his fellow White House travelers were visibly moved
by the enthusiastic reception in chilly Buffalo, the first
campaign-style rally in months that involved both the Gores and
Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, praising her husband's focus on the nation's
challenges during his presidency, said she didn't care ``what the
weather forecasters say, there isn't any warmer place in the United
States than this community right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The president opened his 46-minute address, saying the audience
had gotten so excited that it had ``melted the snow for a mile
around this arena.'' Clinton thanked the audience at the conclusion
``for one of the great days of my presidency, here.''
</P>
<P>
   The president made only an indirect reference to his struggle to
combat threatened Senate conviction on two articles of impeachment
lodged by the House. He began speaking here in Buffalo about 25
minutes after White House counsel Gregory Craig who opened the
second-day of the president's three-day defense before the
100-member Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was ``flattered'' by Gore's suggestion that he
had deflected GOP proposals with the same knack that Sabres' goalie
Dominik ``The Dominator'' Hascek uses to turn aside shots.
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``those flying hockey pucks in Washington,'' Clinton
quipped: ``I just wish one day they would give me a mask and a few
pads when I dodge that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton struck a wistful note at another point, noting that the
six years since his Jan. 20, 1993, inauguration ``have been _ to
put it mildly _ quite eventful.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the audience said they obtained tickets through ties
with the Democratic Party, Democratic politicians, labor unions and
political organizations with ties to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, Clinton flew to Norristown, Pa., to address
another rally.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Buffalo audience left the arena with the same
opinions of Clinton that they came with. Gloria Elmer, a retired
kindergarten teacher from East Aurora, N.Y., who is active in the
League of Women Voters, said Clinton remains ``a great leader who
has done what's right.
</P>
<P>
   Added Elmer, who was wearing a straw boater hat wrapped in a
banner that said, ``The will of the nation is for Bill'': ``How
could people get so worked up about all that foolishness of a young
woman going after a married man? Nothing new about that!''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Kovaka, a homemaker from East Aurora, N.Y., who called
herself a Democratic activist, said Clinton has done more for women
than all the presidents before him. ``If Mr. Starr thinks that the
women of America could be fooled, he's wrong. Leave the president
alone. We love what he has done; we love what he wants to do. Let
him get back to the business of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   It was independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report on Clinton's
conduct that prompted the House impeachment of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Judson, a computer analyst from Buffalo, said he attended
the rally to show his support for Clinton. ``This is where Buffalo
stands _ with the president,'' Judson said. ``An attack on this man
is an attack on the presidency. We're tearing down our country from
within.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sandra Schintzius, 54, a Georgia-born mother of five who has
lived in Buffalo for 31 years, said she was a Republican who
attended out of curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he did in his State of the Union was hand out lollipops _
how tough can that be?'' said Schintzius, who said she voted for
the Republican presidential candidates over Clinton in 1992 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Schintzius said she wanted Clinton to resign or to be removed
from office by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's clean house for the new millennium,'' Schintzius said.
``Our nation cannot afford not to make a statement about the
insidious spirit of lying from the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Clinton paraded their opposition outside the arena.
Several held signs aloft, demanding: ``Resign now.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights organizations, however, staged a large show of
support. An abortion doctor who was slain in his home last year
lived in nearby Amherst.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
