<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-MARKETPLACE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NISSAN WELCOMES ALL BIDDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Japan, Germany)  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ For sale: A piece of the world's sixth-largest car
company. Excellent engineering and technical capabilities. Some $20
billion in debt, but a fixer-upper with promise. Interested parties
may apply to Yoshikazu Hanawa, president of Nissan Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   Hanawa has embarked on a sales campaign never before seen in
Japan and perhaps in the world. Nearly every day for more than a
week, Nissan's leonine president has been hawking his company,
welcoming one and all to make a bid.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly the subtle tap on the shoulder one would expect
from a Japanese executive, but then, these are not subtle times for
Nissan. The company's predicament _ carrying a staggering amount of
debt at a time when it has lost ground in its two major markets,
Japan and the United States _ is glaringly obvious, and the
stronger yen and rising Japanese interest rates have only increased
pressure on the company to act.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Renault SA, the rejuvenated French car company that is
reaping the fruits of a corporate overhaul, is the only potential
partner that has publicly acknowledged an interest in the company.
After Nissan's operation in Britain leaked news of the overtures,
Renault confirmed that it was indeed talking to Nissan _ and other
carmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Renault embarked on an extended fact-finding mission
on several Japanese vehicle manufacturers, according to bankers,
including Suzuki Motor Corp. and Fuji Heavy Industries, a Nissan
affiliate. ``Clearly, they're interested in Japan, but what in
Japan, no one knows for sure,'' one banker said.
</P>
<P>
   After subtracting debt, Renault has cash of about $1 billion,
according to analysts, which would buy it a little more than 10
percent of Nissan at current market prices. (Shares of Nissan here
have edged up 3.5 percent this week. In New York, its American
depository receipts _ each representing two shares of the company _
closed Wednesday at $7.25, down 25 cents.)
</P>
<P>
   Under Japanese law, a shareholder must own at least 33.4 percent
of a company to win board representation and veto power, and given
Nissan's well-documented history of foot-dragging, a potential
buyer would presumably want that kind of control at the minimum.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean a purchase is out of the question. Renault
could, of course, use new shares as currency, but that would not
help Nissan pay down debt and would dilute the holdings of
Renault's shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler AG and Ford Motor Co. have also been rumored to
have an interest in Nissan. Speculation that Juergen Schrempp,
chairman of DaimlerChrysler, is taking an offer with him to Tokyo,
where he is attending an exhibition of Daimler technology at the
end of this week, is rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Neither DaimlerChrysler nor Ford has sought to dispel such
speculation, but Nissan has said it has yet to receive any offer.
Indeed, the company has quite directly said that it has as yet had
no concrete discussions about any kind of equity purchase with
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler clearly has designs on the global market, and
Asia remains a huge gap in its plans. Mercedes-Benz cars continue
to sell well in Japan despite the recession, and Chrysler has built
test models of slimmed-down minivans that would be perfect for the
Japanese market. Conceivably, some of Nissan's excess capacity,
currently at about 35 percent, could be switched to production of
Mercedes and Chrysler vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler has been negotiating with Nissan since May over
the disposition of Nissan Diesel Motor Co., a troubled truckmaker
in which Nissan owns a 39.8 percent stake. The negotiations have
dragged on and on _ first, because DaimlerChrysler wanted more
detailed financial information and, second, because the information
it obtained made it wary.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler is now more comfortable with the numbers, but it
has asked Nissan Diesel's bankers, led by Industrial Bank of Japan
and Fuji Bank, to forgive some of the truckmaker's debt. Debt
forgiveness is not unheard of in Japan, but it is unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan is expected to hold a news conference on Friday, but it
has no plans at this point to announce a sale of Nissan Diesel to
DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ford already has a relationship with Nissan. It produces some
Nissan vehicles in the United States in an alliance that has been
so-so for both partners, and it rents Nissan's shuttered Zama
production plant southwest of here and uses it as an inspection
site for its cars.
</P>
<P>
   But it also owns 33.4 percent of Mazda Motor Corp., a company
once caught in the same bind that now grips Nissan, but on a much
smaller scale. Ford won the right to install its own executives and
has managed to cut costs without layoffs, which are anathema in
Japan. Mazda has cut procurement costs, frozen wages and paid down
debt, making more gross profits per car now than it did a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Having gone through such an exercise, does Ford now want to do
it again on a much grander scale? Does it need to?
</P>
<P>
   Hanawa has some goodies to sell that would be attractive to any
buyer. For starters, Nissan presents a golden opportunity to
establish a rather large beachhead in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   And despite its problems, Nissan is still respected for its
engineering prowess and technological skills. Nissan boasts some
150 alliances with carmakers around the world that have sought its
engineering expertise. Its strained budget has been most apparent
in the design of its cars, which has been, in a word, boring. But
their quality and performance is still among the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the company owns big chunks of real estate that
were acquired decades ago and are still carried on the books at
more or less their original prices. It also has a hefty stock
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Woodworth, an independent auto analyst, has scoured the
company's Japanese financial statements. He believes the company
values its total fixed assets and real estate at about $7.5
billion, which he regards as being well under their present value.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take a lot of sales to put a dent in Nissan's debt,
which ranges between $24 billion _ excluding potential leasing
liabilities _ and $39 billion if those liabilities are included.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Redl, an analyst who follows auto-parts makers at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in Tokyo, has a novel suggestion for
potential buyers. ``If people are interested in Nissan's
technology, they should consider buying one of its parts makers,''
he said. ``That's where the technology resides anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
