<HEADLINE>
U.N. IS RELEASING FUNDS TO IRAQ FOR ELECTRICITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United Nations is releasing more than $81
million to Iraq to buy equipment to increase its supply of
electricity, the director of the Iraqi relief program said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq, which suffers frequent power shortages as power plants
fail and demand for electricity rises, had applied to buy the
necessary generating equipment last year, when the ``oil for food''
program was expanded to allow Iraq to begin rebuilding its
crumbling public services. Sanctions and a more limited oil-sales
program had earlier prevented the Iraqis from replacing old
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the purchases, $74.9 million in gas turbines, will
come from China, said Benon Sevan, director of all nonweapons
projects for Iraq. Last year Iraq bought $70 million in
power-generating equipment from a Russian company.
</P>
<P>
   Under a separate program, the Security Council sanctions
committee approved $6.5 million worth of contracts for oil-industry
spare parts to upgrade pumping equipment, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week President Clinton announced that the United States
would speed up approval of contracts for spare parts so Iraq could
pump more oil and be able to buy more food, medicine and other
goods for a civilian population that has lived under tight trade
sanctions since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, under pressure in the Security Council, opposes
calls from France, Russia and others for a lifting of the embargo
on Iraqi oil sales so Baghdad would be free to buy what it needs,
although with international supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has had difficulties in recent months raising enough money
through permitted oil sales, since the international price of oil
has plummeted. Money earned on oil sales goes into a
U.N.-supervised escrow account.
</P>
<P>
   Under the expanded oil-sales program, even with prices low, Iraq
has been able to buy equipment to repair its telephone system and
place computers in schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the Iraqis have not yet used $17 million set aside last year
for fortified biscuits and milk for malnourished children and
mothers, Sevan said Wednesday. And millions of dollars in medicine
remains in warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release on Jan. 14, Iraq did not deny that it was
stockpiling medicine, but blamed the United States for holding up
contracts for purchases, which must be approved by the Security
Council's committee on Iraq sanctions. U.S. diplomats deny this
allegation.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, Iraq also repeated its accusations, for which
no evidence has yet materialized, that U.S. and British air strikes
in December destroyed ``Iraq's infrastructure, schools, hospitals
and grain warehouses.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Washington on Wednesday, the Clinton administration took
another step toward giving more support to Iraqi opposition groups.
In a report to Congress, the White House designated seven
organizations as permitted recipients of U.S. financial support.
</P>
<P>
   Among the groups is the Iranian-based Supreme Council for the
Islamic Revolution, led by Mohammed Bakr al-Hakim, a Shiite Muslim
clergyman. The organization is considered most influential in the
largely Shiite Iraqi south, where opposition to President Saddam
Hussein is widespread.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, U.S. administrations have been wary of backing
Shiite groups, because of their links to Iran. But relations with
Iran are beginning to thaw slightly, making a gamble possible.
Shiite Muslims account for about two-thirds of the Iraqi
population, although Saddam's government is dominated by Sunni
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups eligible for U.S. aid under a $97 million program
created last year by Congress are the Iraqi National Congress, a
coalition of opposition organizations; the Kurdistan Democratic
Party and the Popular Union of Kurdistan, both based in the
autonomous Kurdish north of Iraq; the Movement for Constitutional
Monarchy, led by the pretender to the Iraqi throne; the Iraqi
National Accord, and the Islamic Movement of Iraqi Kurdistan.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi Communist Party, long a foe of Saddam, was not on the
list.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday 47 exiled Iraqi opposition leaders _ but not the
major Kurdish parties in northern Iraq _ asked Arab foreign
ministers who are planning to meet on Sunday in Cairo, Egypt, to
lend their support to a campaign to overthrow the Saddam
government.
</P>
</TEXT>
