President Clinton's proposal to deal with Social Security, and
Republicans in Congress called the plan unacceptable. But while
some influential Republicans said the plan announced in the State
of the Union message on Tuesday night was so off base it left no
room for compromise, many others saw the president's offering as an
opening bid that could lead to fruitful negotiations. By David
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-CLINTON (Norristown, Pa.) - An exuberant President
Clinton, showing no signs of the weight of impeachment, starred in
two foot-stomping rallies on Wednesday, where he amplified the
themes of his State of the Union address and attacked Republican
proposals for across-the-board tax cuts. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-WARCRIMES (Phum Thmei, Cambodia) _ As Cambodia and the
outside world prepare for the possibility of trials for perhaps a
dozen Khmer Rouge leaders, a large unanswered _ and generally
unasked _ question is how to deal with the people who actually took
part in the torture and the killing, or even how to think of them.
``Why should only the the top leaders take responsibility?'' said
Youk Chhang, director of the Documentation Center of Cambodia, a
private agency that is collecting evidence of Khmer Rouge crimes.
By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FIBER-CANCER (Washington) _ It has been nearly three decades
since Dr. Denis Burkitt, a British missionary surgeon who studied
the differences in diseases between poor Africans and affluent
Westerners, postulated that the Africans' high-fiber diet protected
them against colon cancer. He spread his thesis as dietary gospel,
prompting millions to change their diets. Now the largest study
ever to examine Burkitt's theory has found that, at least when it
comes to preventing colon cancer, all those fruits, vegetables and
cereals don't do any good. By Sheryl Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   Possible reefers:
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-BOMB (New Delhi, India) _ Police here say they have foiled
a plot to bomb American consulates in Madras and Calcutta with the
arrest of a Bangladeshi man. American counter-terrorism experts
arrived here Tuesday to further investigate the case, a spokeswoman
for the American embassy said. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ Under pressure from President
Slobodan Milosevic to show resolve against his violence in Kosovo,
NATO announced Wednesday that warships were being dispatched to the
Adriatic Sea and fighter jets were being placed on a higher state
of alert. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-LABOR (Undated) _ The NBA lockout was officially settled on
Wednesday, opening the way for training camps to begin at 2 p.m. on
Thursday. At that point, teams can officially complete the trades
and signings that they have tentatively concluded over the last two
weeks. Still unclear, though, is when exactly the season will
begin. By Mike Wise.
</P>
