r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONCERT-HALL-MANNERS-     01-20 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCERT-HALL-MANNERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUELL THAT COUGH _ AND OTHER GUIDELINES FOR POLITE CONCERT-GOING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of the grand moments you look forward to all year.
</P>
<P>
   All evening long in Bass Performance Hall, the orchestra and
200-voice chorus had been building, irresistibly, through one grand
choral movement after another, to the final ``Amen'' of Handel's
``Messiah.'' Wave after wave of majestic counterpoint rolled toward
that ultimate climax, where Handel, that master of musical drama,
inserts a moment of silence _ just before the last ecstatic
cadence, bespeaking a universe at peace under the reign of
triumphal God.
</P>
<P>
   Well, except for that hacking cough.
</P>
<P>
   All human beings make a certain amount of noise just by being
alive. Your chair squeaks, you sneeze, you sigh or sniff when
Violetta dies. It's not those occasional small noises that are the
problem, says conductor John Giordano, the music director of the
Fort Worth Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any extraneous noise can be disturbing to the performer,''
Giordano says. And, on occasion, he admits, ``There have been
instances when it was difficult to carry on.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he continues, it's not those little noises that are the
real problem. It's that insensitive, controllable noise that could
be stopped. The cougher who keeps coughing. The chair that keeps
scooting or creaking. The people with the noisy child who just
don't understand that they should leave.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rodzinski, executive director of the Cliburn Foundation,
grew up seeing his father, renowned conductor Artur Rodzinski,
conduct in the great opera houses and concert halls of America and
Europe. He says that Fort Worth audiences are noisier than those
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, and even in Moscow, where the air quality is very
poor and many more people smoke than in America, there is
absolutely no coughing during a performance,'' Rodzinski says. ``It
is considered as unacceptable as other offensive bodily sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   But even New York, the center of the classical music world,
takes its knocks. Anyone who listens to radio broadcasts knows that
New Yorkers are more apt to clap between movements of a large work
than Fort Worth audiences. Worse still, New York Philharmonic
conductor Kurt Masur recently stopped a performance and walked off
stage because of coughing from the audience, according to a report
from The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason that you may be more likely to cough in a
concert hall than, say, at a basketball game or a movie, where you
have more freedom to move around.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the absence of other stimuli, the stimulus to cough becomes
more prevalent,'' says Jack Hardwick, a doctor who is also
president of the Fort Worth Opera Association and a devoted
concertgoer. Hardwick says that coughing is no more prominent in
Fort Worth than at any other place in the world, in his experience.
</P>
<P>
   However, the highly refined acoustics of Bass Performance Hall
make audience discretion even more important, simply because
individual audience noise is more obvious in this room.
</P>
<P>
   Don't go home and die of shame if you happen to cough or sneeze
during the slow movement of Mahler's Fifth. Music was written to be
performed for a live audience. Everyone knows the basics: Arrive on
time; wear decent, clean clothes; don't even think about taking
photographs or carrying food or drink into the concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, it's really fairly easy: Just remember to mind your
manners, and Fort Worth can preserve its reputation as a center of
fine music and good home-training.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RULES TO LISTEN BY
</P>
<P>
   1. In general, don't clap between movements of multimovement
works. Don't applaud while music is being played, even at the opera
or ballet; the experience is even better if you hear all the music.
Once the music is over, by all means, whoop, yell, whistle, stamp
your feet _ if the performance merits it. Booing is reserved for
those extremely rare occasions when a performer or stage director
has actually insulted the audience _ or for opera houses in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   2. If you have a bad, uncontrollable cough, stay home. If you
arrive at the concert and need to cough or sneeze, stifle it if
possible. Carry lozenges with you, but ``please don't rattle the
wrappers.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're at a concert and can't stifle your cough, be as quiet
as possible. Cough when the music is over; if you must cough, try
to do it between movements or, as a last resort, quietly during a
loud passage. Covering your mouth can help to soften the noise. If
the cough persists, leave. (At Bass Hall, you can watch the
performance on the TV screens in the lobby.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Small children, and adults who have developmental
disabilities that make it impossible for them to remain quiet for
extended periods, should not be brought to concerts. When in doubt,
follow the ``Moynihan Rule:'' Would you take this person to a
lecture by Daniel Patrick Moynihan and expect him or her to sit
quietly and listen? If not, he or she is not ready or able to
attend a standard classical music concert, opera or ballet.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, certain events that small children and
other people who may not be expected to be totally quiet may
reasonably attend _ such as special children's concerts, certain
park concerts and performances aimed specifically at family
audiences, such as ``The Nutcracker.'' A 5-year-old dancing with a
light stick at a symphony concert at the Botanic Garden has a
certain charm, so long as the urchin doesn't step in your potato
salad. One hopes that a 6-year-old might ooh and aah at ``The
Nutcracker,'' so long as he or she stays in his or her seat and
limits the exclamations to about 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   4. Any thoughtful person will think twice before wearing
fragrances in the close quarters of a concert hall. Many people are
sensitive to artificial and natural chemicals in perfumes.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
