r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX     01-20 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
 
The Tractors pull together a memorable CD 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In rock 'n' roll, four years is not a long time _ major bands,
such as U2 or Aerosmith, can take that long between releases and
nobody really thinks too much about it.
</P>
<P>
   In country, however, it's an eternity. The big acts, the Garths
and the Alan Jacksons, release a new CD (or at least a best-of)
every year, or at least every two.
</P>
<P>
   Then we get to the Tractors, Tulsa's finest
country/roots-rock/soul/New Orleans R&AMP;B outfit, the guys who scored
big-time with ``Baby Likes to Rock It'' way back in 1994. ``Rock
It'' won the band two Grammy nominations and a Country Music
Association award for Video of the Year, and ``The Tractors'' sold
2 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Then they went away _ right back to Tulsa and leader Steve
Ripley's studio. For months and months. And months.
</P>
<P>
   You'd never know it by ``Farmers in a Changing World,'' which is
the result of all those months, but which also sounds for all the
world like a bunch of guys batting out a handful of songs for
grins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's the idea,'' says Ripley, an amiable sort who
actually grew up driving a tractor in Oklahoma and went on to play
with Bob Dylan, J.J. Cale and Leon Russell, and build guitars for
Eddie Van Halen and Ry Cooder. ``That's the exact goal and that's
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Only _ not the way you'd think. The Tractors' recording process
is an odd one that says much about Ripley, who confesses a love of
the warmth and looseness of nailing down a song quickly (the way
guys like Elvis Presley and Hank Williams used to do it), yet a yen
for endless tinkering to get just the right guitar or drum sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony people might not believe is when I listen to Hank
(Williams), I'm astonished by the sounds and the recording as much
as the songs and the performances,'' he says. ``Also, there's a
thing about Tulsa musicians; we all live in the studio. If you
don't go to one, you've got one in your home.''
</P>
<P>
   What Ripley would do is lay down a guide vocal and guitar track
and then have the different players (keyboardist Walt Richmond,
guitarist Ron Getman, bassist Casey Van Beek and drummer Jamie
Oldaker) come in and lay down their parts quickly _ one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times it's `Here's the song, it's in G, here we go,' and
we roll the tape,'' he says. ``The first take is always the best.
That's as good as it's gonna get. The analogy I like is how movies
are made _ they're shot with one camera at a time, and then some
guy makes sense out of it and it ends up seeming larger than
life.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tractorland, that one guy is Ripley, who assembles the songs
out of the band's playing, stitching together their work into a
coherent whole.
</P>
<P>
   He says it's ``like putting together a jigsaw puzzle and making
it as you go.'' And there's where the years in the little room come
in.
</P>
<P>
   But the result _ well, the result was well worth the wait.
``Farmers'' shows the Tractors to be one of the very few even
semimainstream country bands whose members sound as though they'd
be as comfortable playing a smoky club in New Orleans or Memphis as
in Nashville. Snappy, sinuous horn lines grace several songs, as do
funky rhythms that would have sounded at home on a 40-year-old Ray
Charles record. Old pal Bonnie Raitt throws in some tart slide
guitar on several cuts, and former Presley sidemen James Burton,
Scotty Moore and D.J. Fontana help out on Ripley's tribute to the
King, ``The Elvis Thing,'' which concludes with him throwing in a
snippet of the classic ``Mystery Train.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, both the long wait and the band's
country/roots/R&AMP;B hybrid sound have meant that ``Farmers'' has not
taken off like ``The Tractors'' did. It currently sits at No. 53, a
neither great nor horrible showing. A round of dates in the spring,
which Ripley has dubbed ``The Tractors' Great American Get Off Your
Butt and Dance Tour,'' may well help, but ``Farmers'' most probably
won't be the huge success that ``The Tractors'' was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in a way, because of course we'd like it to
be in the Top 10,'' Ripley says. ``You do have expectations. But
it's hangin' in there and sold about 3,000 copies last week, and
the company's happy with it. And really, we're beating a lot of
records. Things are actually great _ we're not getting impeached.''
Dave Ferman, (817) 390-7839 ``dfer\Nstar-telegram.com''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
