<HEADLINE>
BUSH, STILL UNDECIDED ABOUT PRESIDENCY, HAS EYE ON 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Wednesday that
his best shot at winning the Republican presidential nomination
would be in 2000, although he insisted that he had not decided
whether to run.
</P>
<P>
   A day after being sworn in for a second term, Bush faced another
barrage of questions about the upcoming presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   While he expressed some reluctance about dragging his family
into the national spotlight, he also spoke of ``moments in
history'' and ``windows of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I choose not to run for the presidency, I understand
the window probably will be closed, because one can't control their
fate in the political process,'' Bush told a news conference at the
Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that this could be a very unique moment. But
you've got to understand me: I didn't wake up when I was
14-years-old wanting to be president of the United States. When I
was 21, I didn't want to be president, and I don't wake up every
morning saying, `How can I position myself to be president?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is in the position of being the undeclared front-runner in
the Republican race.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential Republican candidate, New York Gov. George
Pataki, announced Wednesday that he had created a political action
committee to finance campaign trips.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush appears to be leaning toward running, he and his
wife, Laura, said they were concerned about the loss of privacy for
themselves and their 17-year-old twin daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reluctant, absolutely,'' Mrs. Bush said. ``I just think
it's a major life change. We have a very nice life in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the son of the former president, said that while he is
taking his family's feelings into account, the decision ultimately
is his to make.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 52, said he was not concerned about scrutiny of his life.
He has admitted he was ``young and irresponsible'' but learned from
his mistakes, which he has repeatedly declined to discuss in detail
except to say he drank too much alcohol and quit when he was 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had done anything in the past that would've disqualified
me for being in public office, you would have found it,'' Bush
said. ``When I put my hand on the Bible and swore to uphold the
laws of the land of the state, I also implicitly said I'd uphold
the dignity of the office that I was elected to, and I have done
so.''
</P>
<P>
   As he works his way toward making a decision, Bush has been
meeting with various policy experts and other interested parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't surprise you that I'm listening to policy people
because I intend to make an informed decision. It's not only a
decision of heart, which is the primary reason,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to meet Thursday with a group of national fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I decide to run for the presidency, I'm going to have
to raise a lot of money quickly, and it's important to listen to
the concerns of money-raisers as well as to listen to different
policy folks. And that's what's going to happen between now and
when I make my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to decide by the end of the state's legislative
session in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
