</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AN ACTIVIST ENCLAVE, PRAISE FOR A GUTSY PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Calif., N.J.)  (See also: STATEOFUNION-CLINTON, STATEOFUNION-SURPLUS,
STATEOFUNION-REPUBS, STATEOFUNION-GREENSPAN, STATEOFUNION-BUFFALO,
STATEOFUNION-CHICAGO) 
(DW) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Alison Levy heard the word ``Republican'' and
her eyes narrowed and body tensed in one reflexive motion. ``It's
just so frustrating,'' she said, as she sorted titles at Phoenix
Books, the new and used bookstore she manages in this neighborhood
called Noe Valley. ``The Republicans are wasting all this time and
energy and money and resources for something they shouldn't. It
just shouldn't be happening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' is the trial of the president on the charges of
impeachment, of course, and Ms. Levy, one disgusted Democrat among
many she knows, has barely been able to bring herself to watch it.
But like most of about 30 people interviewed in Noe Valley this
morning, she did watch President Clinton's State of the Union
address and she, like many others, thought it a brave, gutsy
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see him continue to do his job,'' she said.
``After all that is happening, he doesn't let it stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Noe Valley, a liberal Democratic neighborhood in a
liberal Democratic city, little that the house managers prosecuting
the president have said has mattered. The president's impeachment
and trial has been a political act. Period. The Conservative
Republicans have been out to get him. No question. Nothing that
happens in the Senate will convince them that the impeachment, or
even a conviction, is anything else.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the attitudes in Noe Valley, a diverse
neighborhood of long-time, working-class residents, struggling
artists, middle-class professionals and new, wealthier arrivals who
work in Silicon Valley, correlate with the national polls. But in
this bastion of political activism _where residents worried about
the gentrification of the neighborhood successfully lobbied for a
law banning new coffee bars and juice bars here _ people are even
more defensive of the president than the polls indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Only two people approached are registered Republicans, and both
of those said they plan to switch parties as a protest against the
president's impeachment. Only one person interviewed (a Democrat)
wants the Senate to remove the president from office _ ``for
lying'' _ while everyone else said the president's sex life is his
business and none of ours.
</P>
<P>
   Most people interviewed said they think the president's affair
with Monica Lewinsky was ``slimy,'' ``sleazy,'' ``plain wrong.''
But even those who have found the president's policies too
conservative for their liberal philosophy are rallying behind
Clinton against what they perceive as a politically driven vendetta
orchestrated by the right-wing. To people here, it's as if the
president is Bugs Bunny and the Conservative Republicans are Elmer
Fudd, throwing tantrums each time the wascally wabbit has slipped
past their traps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think going after Bill Clinton is stupid, idiotic _ and I
wish the whole thing was over,'' said Nancy Ford, a clerk at the
24th Street Cheese Shop, barely able to contain her venom. ``Bill
Clinton just keeps doing his job and the Republicans are trying to
keep him from doing anything. Just make them leave him alone and
I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bacik, co-owner of Accent on Flowers, a neighborhood
fixture for 29 years, said that while he is a life-long Republican,
he's ``tired of all this crap the Republicans have been dishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacik is re-registering as a Democrat. ``They're spending
millions of dollars prosecuting the president for his sex life,''
he said. ``That's something between him and Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tully's Coffee, four Clinton supporters talking over the
predicament in Washington, expressed unanimous contempt for the
Republicans spearheading the attack on the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just feel like throwing something at the television, or
leaving the country,'' said Phyllis Ehrenfeld, a New Jerseyan
visiting her sister here.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Sylvain Ehrenfeld, was just as disgusted. ``To me,
it's all highly politicized, just part of the culture war,'' he
said. ``The polls show that what they are doing to Clinton is
likely to hurt them but they still do it. Why would they continue
on a course that is so self-destructive?''
</P>
<P>
   Their friend, Harry Stern, who lives in Noe Valley, said the
whole course of events of the last year have a surreal quality.
``The whole thing is like a Norman Rockwell painting. It's all
technically correct but there's no there there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is one of total, absolute distate for what is
happening,'' said Eunice Rosenberg, the fourth member of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Disgust at the impeachment proceedings has not clouded Jan
Lagerhof's criticisms of the president. ``He's been too
conservative for me,'' said Ms. Lagerhof, a criminal defense lawyer
whose office is in Noe Valley. ``But the important thing is to
defend the office of the presidency. He hasn't done anything to
abuse the office of the president, which is what they're saying.
Make them stop. Make them stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Her views were echoed by Harriet Beinfield, a licensed
acupuncturist who is co-owner with her husband of Chinese Medicine
Works, an herbal pharmacy. Ms. Beinfield blames the president for
``doing in Welfare'' and for allowing crime bills to go forward
that she says demonized black youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, he wears the face of the people,'' she said.
``On the other hand he caves in to the will of the right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
