<HEADER>
A1660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-1000(2TAKES)-N     01-20 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 HIGH COURT HEARS ABOUT BIZARRELY SHAPED CONGRESSIONAL DISTRICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (fe) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The long and skinny North Carolina congressional
district that drew the Supreme Court's ire six years ago is barely
half as long now. Redrawn by the state Legislature after the Court
declared it to be an unconstitutional racial gerrymander, it no
longer has a majority of black voters, although it is still
represented by a black Democrat, Melvin Watt.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court heard arguments on Wednesday about whether the
12th congressional district of North Carolina is still
unconstitutional. The court's answer and how the justices arrive at
it are very likely to set the ground rules for the next round of
congressional redistricting, after the 2000 census, when legal
challenges to districts drawn with race in mind are likely to pour
into the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time the North Carolina district has been
before the Supreme Court. In 1993, it was the subject of a case
called Shaw vs. Reno, in which a bitterly divided court held by a
5-4 vote that districts drawn with ``bizarre'' shapes for the
purpose of electing black representatives were presumptively
unconstitutional. A three-judge U.S. District Court in North
Carolina, applying the new standard, upheld the district
nonetheless, in a decision the court overturned by the same 5-4
vote in a 1996 case called Shaw vs. Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina Legislature then redrew the district, as part
of a state-wide redistricting, shaving off 89 of its 191 miles and
reducing its black population from 57 percent to 47 percent. The
primary goal, the legislators told the District Court, was no
longer racial but political, preserving the even split of six
Democrats and six Republicans in the state's congressional
delegation by insuring that reliable Democratic voters were carved
out of the Republican Piedmont region and bunched into an urban
district running along Interstate 85 from Charlotte to Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling last year in a lawsuit brought by white voters allied
with the plaintiffs in the original Shaw vs. Reno case, the
District Court in Raleigh rejected the legislature's explanation
and ruled that the district was still impermissibly ``race
driven.'' Granting summary judgment to the white voters, the court
found that race was still a predominant factor and declared the
12th District unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The argument on Wednesday, an appeal by the state, brought
familiar personalities before the Supreme Court, as well as
familiar questions and answers. But for the first time there was
some indication that justices who supported Shaw vs. Reno might be
growing concerned that the doctrine, at least in the hands of the
lower federal courts, has gone too far and been interpreted too
rigidly.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident from the response of Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor, the author of Shaw vs. Reno and the critical fifth vote
in subsequent redistricting decisions, to the opening statement by
Robinson O. Everett, the lawyer who has represented the white
plaintiffs in all the North Carolina cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am back again with a map show,'' Everett said, referring to
the maps of the current and previous district perched on easels
behind him. Similar props had proved useful tools for him in his
previous arguments. ``Maps are very important,'' he observed this
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, they are,'' Justice O'Connor said. ``But at least
speaking for myself,'' she continued, ``there may well be enough
evidence here'' on the state's behalf to mean that the District
Court made a mistake in ruling at this point for the plaintiffs, by
awarding summary judgment without conducting a trial. The argument
then turned to the facts and theory behind Everett's case, and he
never referred to his maps again.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the question of whether the District Court
properly entered judgment for the state is a technical one, the
justices' interest in it suggesting that a ruling on the merits
might be put off until still another appeal. But it was evident
from the argument that the question of summary judgment is
inextricably bound up with how the court views the role of race in
legislative districting. What had the appearance of a technical,
procedural argument in fact approached the heart of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   A summary judgment is a ruling on the purely legal issues in a
lawsuit and is appropriate only if no relevant facts are in
dispute. But the dispute in this case, several justices suggested,
was the core question of whether the asserted goal of political
balance was just a pretext, with race actually the predominant
factor in drawing the 12th district's lines. At what point does a
factor become predominant, the justices wanted to know. Can a
legislature that once drew an unconstitutional district ever be
assumed to be acting in good faith?
</P>
<P>
   Walter E. Dellinger, an acting solicitor general earlier in the
Clinton administration, serving as counsel to his home state in
this case, Hunt vs. Cromartie, No. 98-85, told the justices that
maintaining a partisan balance was a ``constitutionally legitimate
goal.'' He said the ``overlap'' between including Democrats and
including black voters, most of whom vote Democratic, was not in
itself sufficient to invalidate the district. Political balance
``could have been a pretext, but there was no evidence that was the
case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That raised the question of which side in such a case has the
burden of proof: the plaintiffs, to show that the district lines
were impermissibly based on race, or the state, to show that,
despite some ambiguous evidence to the contrary, they were not. The
plaintiffs' lawyer, Everett, argued that once a district had been
invalidated on the basis of race, the state should have the burden
of proving that later modifications were untainted.
</P>
<P>
   While preserving an incumbent's district has often been accepted
as a valid purpose for drawing particular district lines, Everett
said this presumption should not apply when the incumbent was
elected from a ``race-based, race-skewed district.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Watt's election in 1992, there had been no black member of
Congress from North Carolina since 1901.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration argued in support of the state. While
``legislators are commonly aware of race,'' James A. Feldman, an
assistant solicitor general, told the justices, the court's
precedents did not go so far as to make a district unconstitutional
simply because it reflected the ``mere desire'' to take account of
its racial makeup.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to hearing this case, the court also decided a
redistricting case on Wednesday, ruling 8-1 in a case involving
state judicial districts in Monterey County, Calif. that local
jurisdictions must abide by the Voting Rights Act even when the
challenged district lines were drawn at the state level rather than
the local level.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Lopez vs. Monterey County, No. 97-1396, applied to the
obligation of jurisdictions covered by the law to seek advance
permission _ ``preclearance'' _ from the Justice Department or the
U.S. District Court in Washington before making a change that
affects voting. In California, as in New York, only parts of the
state are covered by this section of the law, raising the question
of whether actions taken at the state level are immunized from
Voting Rights Act review even when they affect a ``covered''
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. District Court in San Francisco had ruled that the law
did not apply in such a case. The court today disagreed, in a
majority opinion by Justice O'Connor. Justice Clarence Thomas
dissented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1926EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
