<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1662 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-HEBERT-LADN     01-20 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HEBERT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEBERT BACK IN FORM AFTER TOUGH YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Family life is agreeing with Guy Hebert, and so is
the current NHL season.
</P>
<P>
   After enduring a year of team and personal turmoil, the Mighty
Ducks goalie can't help but laugh and smile. Not even the pressure
of becoming an unrestricted free agent at the end of the season can
bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days, you take for granted what you do,'' Hebert said.
``Not every day is going to be rosy, but I wanted to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun isn't the word Hebert would use to describe the 1997-98
season. He and the Ducks struggled the year after the team had made
its first playoff appearance, and Hebert's wife, Sarah, suffered a
troubled pregnancy and required six weeks of bed rest.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter, Madeline, was born prematurely on Dec.22, 1997,
and she spent the first two weeks of her life in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps you set your priorities,'' said Hebert, who was on
the road when Madeline finally came home. ``We (have) a
high-pressure lifestyle and are under a microscope. But you see
something like that, see what my wife went through, and you step
back and say, `Well, it's a lot more enjoyable than you think, and
you should get back to thinking it's enjoyable.'''
</P>
<P>
   So far, this season has been enjoyable for Hebert. After last
Wednesday's loss to Calgary, Hebert was 14-14-7 with a 2.22
goals-against average, a .928 save percentage and had already
equaled his career high in shutouts with four.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has given us a chance every night to win games, and he has
won some by himself,'' Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg said. ``It's
tough to ask anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   After suffering through a sub-par first half and not playing a
minute for the United States Olympic team in Nagano, Japan,
Hebert's 1997-98 season officially ended April 9, when he had
surgery on his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But after a summer of rehab, the 32-year-old Hebert returned in
top shape. He is playing like he did when he led the Ducks to the
playoffs in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing as good as that, or maybe better,'' teammate
Teemu Selanne said. ``He's older, smarter, more confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, he's back to the same old keeper, and that's huge
for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert was not named to the North American All-Star team, but he
said it really didn't matter if he made it or not, even before the
squad was announced. There is little reason to doubt him,
especially now that he has a daughter waiting for him at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it changes everyone,'' Hebert said of becoming a
father. ``If it doesn't, I think there is something wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to the rink and have a bad day, there is nothing you
can do. You go home, enjoy the family and show up the next day and
try to be better. Not every day is great, but so far, so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert said he is trying not to take himself so seriously
anymore, and he has become somewhat of a dressing room cutup, even
joking he was going to dye his thinning, dark hair blond, as
several players have done throughout the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert may not take himself as seriously as he once did, but
Hartsburg says he's serious once he is stationed between the pipes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people underestimate how competitive he is,'' he said.
``When you talk to him, he's very laid-back and he's got a good
sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've noticed, when he pulls that mask over him, there is a
competitive edge that comes over him as well. In a game, he fights
and battles and does everything he can to stop the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a trait his defensemen also have noticed. Hebert plays a
simple style -- he does not flop and dive much -- but Jason
Marshall said looks can be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can make the flashy save; I've seen him do it time and time
again,'' Marshall said. ``Even when it looks like an empty net,
he'll never give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, the only Duck to play all six years in Anaheim, will be
able to shop himself on the open market after the season. He
insists, however, that he will not let himself get caught up
worrying about signing a big free-agent deal. He saw firsthand what
Curtis Joseph went through when they played for St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``A contract is going to take care of itself,'' said Hebert, who
is making $2.6 million this season. ``But it became everything
every time he stepped out on the ice. I saw how miserable he was,
and I didn't want to be that miserable this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make great money. If I never make another dime, I'm pretty
lucky. If you play well, you'll be rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert has made it clear he'd like to finish his career in
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here six years and really put a lot of blood, sweat
and tears into trying to make the Mighty Ducks grow,'' he said.
``We've had our bumps in the road, but I think we are really taking
off now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, it would end with me picking up the (Stanley) Cup
at center ice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1926EST &QL; 
