<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1664 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      01-20 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNUBBING WIDOWS AND HEROES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - An atomic bomb detonated in Rep. John Shadegg's face
about 30 seconds into the president's State of the Union speech
Tuesday night, and he didn't even flinch.
</P>
<P>
   It happened just after Bill Clinton said, ``Let me begin by
saluting the new speaker of the House, and thanking him for
extending invitations to two special guests who are sitting in the
gallery with Mrs. Hastert. Widows of the two brave Capitol Police
officers who gave their lives to defend freedom's house.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then _ as Lyn Gibson, widow of Special Agent John Gibson,
and Wei Ling Chestnut, widow of Officer Jacob J. Chestnut rose to
accept the wild applause of every person in the chamber _ Shadegg's
decision to boycott the event went up like a mushroom cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad there wasn't enough fallout to penetrate a politician's
hard ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stands by his decision not to attend,'' Shadegg's press
aide told me Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By skipping the speech, the Arizona congressman wasn't there to
applaud the widows of two officers killed last July trying to
protect him and his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg and other Republicans who refused to attend the speech
wrote a letter saying, ``The president is demonstrating his lack of
respect for Congress. We will not play a role in facilitating his
disrespect.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that what Capt. Jeffrey B. Taliaferro was doing? Facilitating
disrespect?
</P>
<P>
   Taliaferro is a pilot who flew B-1 bomber missions over Iraq
during Operation Desert Fox. He, too, was greeted with a standing
ovation after being pointed out by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   What about Ashley Dumas, the AmeriCorps volunteer working with
single mothers in South Boston? Or Loc Truong, the former
Vietnamese refugee who mentors boys in San Luis Obispo?
</P>
<P>
   They, too, were singled out by Clinton. Were they demonstrating
their lack of respect for Congress by agreeing to attend?
</P>
<P>
   Is that also true of Officer Chris Lonsford, who received a
medal of valor from the Fontana, Calif., police department last
March and was another guest of the president?
</P>
<P>
   Is it true of Suzann Wilson, whose 11-year-old daughter was shot
and killed by schoolmates in Jonesboro, Ark., and who now works to
keep firearms out of children's hands?
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows that the first objective of a State of the Union
address is making the president look good. Mostly, this is done by
having the big guy make promises he knows he can't keep. Nobody's
fooled.
</P>
<P>
   We put up with it because the State of the Union is also a pep
rally, a nationally-televised excuse to celebrate the country and
point out some of our best people.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the president finished Tuesday night, Shadegg was
on a Phoenix talk radio program saying Clinton has ``no class.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Sammy Sosa?
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs star attended the speech. The president praised
Sosa for helping to bring relief to hurricane victims in the
Dominican Republic. The crowd cheered.
</P>
<P>
   What about Rosa Parks?
</P>
<P>
   She was also there. When Clinton declared her a living icon of
the American civil rights movement, all of the Representatives and
Senators stood up and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, Shadegg told me he meant no offense to anyone
honored by Clinton. ``My only concern here was, Is it appropriate
in the midst of the impeachment proceeding for this speech to go
forward?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I leveled that criticism both at our leadership, with a
letter I sent to the speaker before I made my decision not to
attend, and also by my decision not to attend. Which was a personal
decision of conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   You make the call:
</P>
<P>
   On one side are Shadegg and his buddies. On the other side are
the police widows, the young volunteers, the mother, the cop, the
bomber pilot, Sammy Sosa, Rosa Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Which group has no class? &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1927EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
