<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEOFUNION-BUFFALO-     01-20 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-BUFFALO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND SOCIAL SECURITY PLAN WELCOMED IN A DEMOCRATIC
STRONGHOLD
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ When President Clinton on Wednesday gave his
folksy version of his State of the Union Message to the blue-collar
and middle-class residents of Buffalo and its environs, he got an
ardent response from people like Beverly Brigantia, for whom Social
Security, the centerpiece of the president's message, is no
academic matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be one of those women on Social Security that
he's talking about,'' she said, listening to Clinton's speech on a
small television propped up on a satellite truck outside the Marine
Midland Arena here. ``I'm single and currently unemployed and
there's $6,000 in my pension in the teachers retirement system. I'm
probably going to have to work until I drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brigantia, a 55-year-old former community college writing
instructor, said Clinton's plan to reserve 62 percent of the budget
surpluses over the next 15 years _ $2.7 trillion _ for Social
Security ``sounded reasonable to me,'' and at least put the issue
squarely on the national agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to generate excitement after his State of the Union
address, the president could scarcely have picked a more receptive
audience than the one in this heavily Democratic city of 325,000
people. Buffalo's mood Wednesday was as bright as the sunshine that
ended a week and a half of snow, with accumulations of 60 inches.
</P>
<P>
   This Lake Erie city, where Grover Cleveland was mayor in 1881
and where President William McKinley was assassinated in 1901, has
made a slow and somewhat mixed economic recovery since the 1970s,
when Bethlehem Steel closed its plant in neighboring Lackawanna and
chemical and automobile companies downsized. Unemployment is at 7
percent or 8 percent, said Vincent Lovallo, chief of staff to Mayor
Anthony Masiello. That is almost twice the national average, but
far less than the double-digit rates that Lovallo said prevailed
before Clinton's election in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The president was delighted with the long ovation he received
after a fiery introduction by Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got so excited you melted the snow for miles outside the
arena,'' Clinton told the crowd of 15,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The warmth was by no means unanimous. Fifty demonstrators stood
across from the domed arena, the home of the Buffalo Sabres hockey
team, with signs saying ``Jail to the Chief!'' and ``Can You Trust
a Liar?''
</P>
<P>
   One of the protesters, Andrea Tice, a 30-year-old mother of two
from the suburb of Marilla, said she had not watched Clinton's
speech Tuesday night _ ``I prefer to go to sleep at night without
rage in my heart,'' she said _ but she disliked his Social Security
plan anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security is fine, but he should give the hard-working
people a tax cut,'' Ms. Tice said, echoing a proposal made by
Republicans in Congress on Tuesday that called for a 10 percent
across-the-board cut in income tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly the crowds outside and inside the arena seemed
impressed with a president spunkily going on with his job despite a
Senate impeachment trial that could remove him from office. Even
the baby boomers who doubt that the government will have surpluses
for the next 15 years were glad Clinton enunciated something to
shoot for that may protect them when they retire. And many were
simply tickled at glimpsing the president and his wife, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, and by his casual colloquial delivery Wednesday,
with lines about Social Security like this one: ``Seniors today
have no sweat unless they live to be 120 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Nellie King, who had trouble getting into the arena even though
she is superintendent of the Lackawanna City School District,
described the Social Security plan as ``excellent.'' She said she
did not want to end up in the kind of poverty she was born into as
a sharecropper's daughter in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am 56 and I hope to retire in the 21st century, and I hope
the Social Security system will be there for me,'' she said. ``It
was through education that I was able to rise above the poverty
level, and when I retire I don't want to go back into poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she liked the State of the Union picture of a President
``totally in charge.'' ''I think the president is a role model
because he's a caring president,'' she said. ``All have sinned, and
I don't think what he did should have been exposed to the American
people.'' Some of the approbation came from registered Republicans
like Beverly Huber sprinkled through the arena crowd who have been
disenchanted with their party's harping on scandal surrounding the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't vote for him in either of the last two elections, but
I don't like the lynch-mob mentality in Washington right now,''
said Ms. Huber, a self-described baby boomer from Tonawanda. ``I
think he's a good president. His policies are for the middle class
and the common people, and the Republicans seem to be for the upper
classes and the radical right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
