<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1670 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS &LR;      01-20 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALSH GREAT, BUT MUST BE BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There is nothing new about Bill Walsh, believe
you me. He's been introduced, re-introduced, crowned, defrocked,
recrowned, analyzed, worshipped, annoyed, understood, misunderstood
and combed over until there is little new to say about him.
</P>
<P>
   None of which is his fault, necessarily. He is a 67-year-old man
who has been doing his work in the San Francisco area for nearly 40
years now, as public a figure as this neck of the woods has
produced in years. He sneezes, and a thousand people want to know
how it affects the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Now we know. He sneezed, and the 49ers begin a new era. And
every 49ers fan is thrilled beyond measure by the very prospect.
</P>
<P>
   All well and good, then. Everyone gets what they want _ except
maybe for those wonderfully misguided souls who don't see the
wonder in a story about a front office that literally never ends.
</P>
<P>
   There is unadulterated worship for Walsh now just as there was
in 1992, when he was reintroduced at a news conference as the head
coach of Stanford University. The '92 press conference was a
combination pep rally and ``This Is Your Life'' episode, the likes
of which Stanford had never seen, nor will see again.
</P>
<P>
   The theme remains the same _ the master returns.
</P>
<P>
   There is, though, a fundamental difference this time. Walsh
returned in 1992 to do mortal combat with the idealized Walsh, the
one who sent Stanford to bowl games in 1977 and '78 and revitalized
the football operation, and the one who took the 49ers from
junkyard dogs to best in breed in almost record time. That he was
coming back to Stanford direct from a disappointing engagement as
NBC's lead NFL color man was irrelevant _ we knew he knew football
in ways that few men ever match, and even at 60, he would surely
maintain Dennis Green's standard of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   As we know now, he didn't. He won 10 games with Green's senior
class, then lost touch with his players and didn't replenish the
roster, put up two consecutive losing seasons, and resigned to
pursue his muse. He went into what can best be called private
practice, surfacing for the odd motivational speech and an
ill-fated tourlet being ignored by the deposed 49ers front officers
Dwight Clark and Vinny Cerrato, but mostly he was out of sight, if
not out of mind.
</P>
<P>
   People still longed for his leonine silhouette, his bright
silver hair, his erudition and his plain old Walshness.
</P>
<P>
   And now the image and its owner are back. He is in an unfamiliar
place _ general manager. He is working in an unfamiliar arena _ cap
ball. He is working for an unfamiliar owner _ Eddie DeBartolo with
cash concerns, as opposed to the sky's-the-limit Eddie he knew in
the '80s. Not only that, he comes back to confront a checking
account that is $28 million in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   This would cause concern to 49ers fans who have found as much
enjoyment in watching the organization go nuts this past year as in
watching them win 13 games without satisfying anyone. It should,
too, but it won't. Because the one thing that has endured when all
other things have not is Bill Walsh's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   He has outlasted DeBartolo, in concept and in execution. He has
outlasted Joe Montana, and Dwight Clark, and Ronnie Lott, and Fred
Dean, and Wendell Tyler, and George Seifert, and Carmen Policy, and
all the other 49ers who have come and gone since 1979 _ everyone
save, of course, John McVay, who puts a face on the dictionary
listing for ``survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Issues remain, of course. Will he succeed at re-ordering the
franchise on the old specs? If the old specs don't work, will he
have new ones ready? Will he stay on the job long enough for the
organization to be fully re-freshened? Will DeBartolo allow him the
freedom he did in 1985, and took back from him in 1988?
</P>
<P>
   Can he outdo the romanticized version of himself?
</P>
<P>
   Again, logic says no, because going home again is a lot harder
than it looks, especially in this racket. It can't be this easy,
can it?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes it can, the acolytes tell you, because he is Bill Walsh,
and Bill Walsh is enough.
</P>
<P>
   And there's nothing new about that, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
