<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEOFUNION-SURPLUS-     01-20 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-SURPLUS-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO USE THE SURPLUS: THE GREAT DEBATE BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Texas)  (Eds: See also STATEOFUNION-CLINTON, STATEOFUNION-BUFFALO,
STATEOFUNION-REPUBS, STATEOFUNION-GREENSPAN, STATEOFUNION-VOICES,
STATEOFUNION-CHICAGO, STATEOFUNION-TOBACCO) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a yearlong transition in which both parties
struggled to shift from an era of crippling federal budget deficits
to an anticipated age of fiscal plenty, the battle has at last been
joined over how the country should allocate the flood of excess
money streaming into Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In an immediate sense, the debate is whether nearly all the
surplus will be needed for the twin pillars of the social welfare
system, Social Security and Medicare, as Democrats assert, or
whether there is plenty to take care of those looming problems and
still return much of the surplus to the people in the form of tax
cuts, as Republicans say.
</P>
<P>
   In a broader sense, though, it is about the size and role of the
federal government, a familiar ideological issue but one that has
been seen for most of the last two decades through the prism of
deficit reduction.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton changed that on Tuesday night in his State of
the Union address. The headlines were about his proposal for
shoring up Social Security, but Clinton was setting out to do
something more than deal with the retirement system's future.
</P>
<P>
   The president said the government is going to take in $4.4
trillion more than needed to pay for current programs over the next
15 years, a previously undisclosed and staggeringly big windfall
that, if it materializes, would be unlike anything the country has
ever experienced. Roughly 60 percent of the money would come from
excess payroll tax revenues that are earmarked for Social Security.
The rest would be a true surplus, the difference between general
tax revenues and what the government would spend to maintain
current programs at their existing levels.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than just repeating his demand from a year ago that the
projected surpluses be left untouched until Social Security's
future is assured, Clinton laid out exactly how he would spend the
money. Social Security was at the top of the list. But Clinton also
proposed using hundreds of billions of dollars for Medicare,
unveiled a plan under which the government would subsidize
retirement savings accounts for low- and middle-income workers, and
said he would set aside big sums for the Pentagon, education and
other domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   In setting out his priorities, Clinton was moving into a policy
vacuum that he had created last year with his ``Save Social
Security first'' strategy. But Republicans, who last year had been
shy about advancing any big ideas because of their well-founded
fears that they would be accused by Democrats of endangering Social
Security, immediately made clear that they would be far less
inhibited this year.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking an issue as potent as Social Security to claim as their
own, they turned to the one idea that unites their fractious party,
tax cuts, and proposed a plan that they say combines good economic
policy with strong political appeal, reducing income tax rates by
10 percent across the board.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that _ to the degree it is not consumed with
Clinton's impeachment trial _ Washington will see a wide-ranging
ideological debate this year over fundamentally different views of
how the country should capitalize on its good fortune.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The president essentially made the case that we should use
this period of extra resources and prosperity to invest in the
future and save to solve future retirement challenges,'' said Gene
Sperling, the White House economic policy director. ``The
Republicans seemed to respond by suggesting we should go to
across-the-board consumption. That's a good solid policy debate for
the nation to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's view of an activist government shoring up the social
safety-net programs played to the liberal wing of his party, but
with a twist: He portrayed himself as the champion of austerity,
dedicated to paying down the national debt to levels not seen since
World War One.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they were energized to make the case for a
smaller federal government once again, a task they admitted would
be more difficult now that the discipline of reducing the deficit
can no longer be the backbone of their argument. They said tax cuts
would not only put more money back in the hands of the people out
of whose paychecks it is coming, but would help strangle the
federal bureaucracy and push power out of Washington back closer to
the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Ronald Reagan extended spending and borrowing a great
deal in the 1980s, the deficit was a forced limit on the growth of
government,'' said Rep. Nick Smith, R-Mich., who would once have
been known as a deficit hawk. ``Now that damper is sort of off, and
we're going to have to make an upfront philosophical decision
whether we want to reduce taxes and slow the growth of the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're faced with a situation where there's still a political
advantage to coming up with programs that do new things for more
people and spend more money,'' he said. ``It's going to be a huge
challenge even in the Republican ranks not to take advantage of
spending some of that money on programs they think are important.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains unclear is whether the debate will lead to
bipartisan deals on issues like Social Security, or whether it will
simply allow the two parties to define what they stand for heading
into the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Having the debate serve as an electoral platform ``is the more
probable outcome, but that's not inconsequential by itself,'' said
Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas. ``To frame the issue for debate and
consideration in the election is worthwhile, and maybe some
progress can be made toward resolving the issue in some way this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The optimistic scenario is that the surplus is so big, and the
options for dealing with issues like Social Security so fluid, that
there is plenty of room for a legacy-minded president and a
Republican leadership eager to prove it can pass legislation to
come to some accommodation this year.
</P>
<P>
   The pessimistic scenario is that the battle over Clinton's
impeachment has so poisoned the atmosphere in Washington that the
two parties will never trust each other enough to join together in
addressing politically sensitive issues. And without any consensus
on how to use the surplus, it could gradually be eaten away by
politically popular tax-and-spending programs from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have paid the price for running up huge deficits, and we
have finally, with the help of good economic times as well as hard
work by politicians, gotten past that,'' said Martha Phillips,
executive director of the Concord Coalition, a fiscal watchdog
group. ``Now we have to find a way for politicians to do their
thing without going too far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
