<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-STEEL-PA </SLUG>

 &HT;        PENNSYLVANIA STEEL WORKERS TRAVEL TO THE CAPITOL TO STAND UP
FOR STEEL   By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Jan. 20, -- Laid-off steel worker Jeff Dellenbaugh
looked at his sleeping son before leaving in the middle of the
night on a bus with other steel workers to attend a rally Wednesday
at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be able to say I did this for him,'' said the
Washington County, Pa., resident. ``I did this to fight for my job
back and for his future in this steel town and steel family. My
father worked in a steel mill.''
</P>
<P>
   Dellenbaugh was one of nearly 3,000 steel workers and industry
officials from Pennsylvania, Ohio, and West Virginia who attended a
``Stand Up for Steel'' rally urging President Clinton to put an end
to a surge of cheap foreign steel imports. On the front porch of
the Capitol, steel workers heard speeches from lawmakers and
industry leaders calling for a curb on foreign imports. Most of the
workers traveled all night by bus from the headquarters of Weirton
Steel Corp., in the Northern Panhandle of West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The event was sponsored by the Ohio Valley Stand Up for Steel
Committee, which is made up of Weirton Steel Corp.,
Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel, and the Independent Steelworkers of
America.
</P>
<P>
   Steel industry officials say a flood of cheap foreign steel
imports have caused 10,000 layoffs and forced several companies to
make cutbacks or go bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic steel officials charge that foreign companies are
``dumping'' their product - or selling it for below market value.
Companies and unions have lodged trade complaints against Japan,
Russia and Brazil, seeking to impose duties. ``We don't want
handouts, we just want a fair and level playing field,'' said
Dellenbaugh, who had worked for nine years as an overhead crane
operator at Weirton Steel. President Clinton recently proposed
giving $300 million in tax breaks for steel companies. But
Clinton's plan did not set quotas or force nations to adopt
voluntary limits on their exports, two measures backed by the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who chairs the Senate Steel Caucus,
and lawmakers from other steel producing states, announced
legislation to lower standards for proving injury in trade disputes
which would make it easier for the industry to obtain quotas and
broad tariffs against the dumping of foreign steel. At the rally,
Specter called upon the president to act further.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has the power to put tariffs and duties today,''
Specter said, a comment which was met with cries from the crowd of
``Let's do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about Russia's economy, but I'm more concerned
about Pennsylvania, Ohio and West Virginia,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Murtha, D-Johnstown, vice-chair of the House Steel
Caucus, co-sponsored a bill that sets up an import monitoring
program for steel.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha said it was his first priority in Congress to help the
nearly 2,000 steel workers who live in his district and commute to
steel mills.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha said he urged White House officials, whom he met with
Wednesday in a briefing, to take action that would have an
immediate impact on the steel crisis.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the Capitol police asked the rally participants
not to use blow-horns or whistles so they wouldn't disturb the
business going on inside the Capitol. The request was met with
little cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the people's business,'' yelled one woman,
referring to President Clinton's ongoing impeachment trial in the
Senate. ``This out here is the people's business.''
</P>
<P>
   After the rally, workers streamed down Pennsylvania Avenue
holding white picket signs that said ``Stand Up for Steel,'' to
Lafayette Park, across from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked, West Virginia steel worker Bill Stephens, said he
feels like he has two jobs.
</P>
<P>
   One, said the 55-year-old, is working as a machinist at the
Weirton Steel Co. The other, is trying to keep that job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we made a point today,'' said Stephens, who had
left for the rally after finishing a full shift at the steel
company. ``Now I can go home and go to sleep knowing I did this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
