<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1679 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-20 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE LAWYERS ATTEMPT TO TEAR DOWN IMPEACHMENT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House lawyers on Wednesday challenged the
facts and legal interpretations undergirding the impeachment case
against President Clinton, hoping to convince senators that there
is enough doubt to warrant acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapping up the second day of President Clinton's defense in the
Senate impeachment trial, White House lawyer Cheryl Mills gave an
emotion-laden appeal for exoneration, telling senators ``those
stubborn, stubborn facts'' favor the president.
</P>
<P>
   In a slow, deliberate voice, Mills invoked her status as an
African-American and a woman to attack the Republican case against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a lawyer, as an American, and as an African-American, (the
rule of law) is a principle in which I believe to the very core of
my being,'' she said. ``If you love the rule of law, you must love
it in all of its applications. ... If it is applied equally, the
rule of law exonerates Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, she sought to undermine the prosecution theory that
Clinton's actions were rooted in his effort to undermine Paula
Jones' effort to pursue justice in her civil rights lawsuit
alleging sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about civil rights because this president's
record on civil rights, on women's rights ... is unimpeachable,''
Mills said. ``The house of civil rights is strong because its
foundation is strong. And with all due respect, the foundation of
the house of civil rights was never at the core of the Jones
case.''
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Gregory Craig said Clinton ``has a strong
and a compelling case, one that is based on the facts, on the
record, on the law and on the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig took aim at the first impeachment article charging Clinton
with lying under oath during his Aug. 17, 1998, grand jury
appearance about his affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky, as well as his testimony in his Jan. 17, 1998, deposition
in the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In the deposition, Clinton denied having ``sexual relations''
with Lewinsky under the terms of a definition handed to him by
Jones' lawyers. In his grand jury testimony, he acknowledged
``inappropriate intimate contact'' with Lewinsky, but defended his
deposition statement as technically accurate under the definition.
</P>
<P>
   Craig accused House Republican prosecutors of trying to pin
their perjury case on Clinton's deposition, even though the House
specifically rejected an impeachment article based on that
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you believe president crossed the lines in the Jones
case, you cannot conclude that he should be removed for it,'' Craig
said. ``He wasn't impeached for it. This case is about the grand
jury and the grand jury alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig also defended legal hairsplitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``In defending the president of the United States, we intend,
and we will use, all the legal defenses that are available to us,''
Craig said. ``Legalistic though some of these legal defenses may
be, these are the respectable and respected, acceptable and
expected defenses available to anyone charged with this kind of a
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The allegations of lying by Clinton are ``frequently trivial,
almost always technical, often immaterial and always
insubstantial,'' Craig said. ``We are the ones who must cry
`foul.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mills defended Clinton against the accusation that he obstructed
justice when he allegedly conspired with his secretary, Betty
Currie, to hide gifts he had exchanged with Lewinsky at a time when
they had been subpoenaed by the lawyers for Jones in her sexual
harassment lawsuit against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors argued that in their final White House meeting
Dec. 28, 1997, Lewinsky and Clinton discussed the possibility of
Currie taking charge of the gifts. Clinton, Lewinsky testified,
replied ``I don't know'' or ``let me think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills argued that Clinton was unconcerned about gifts because he
gave Lewinsky new gifts during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those stubborn, stubborn facts,'' Mills said. ``They show that
this was not obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   She also defended Clinton's conversation with Currie on Jan. 18,
1998, the day after the Jones deposition, in which Clinton picked
Currie's brain about Lewinsky in what House prosecutors
characterized as an effort to enlist her backup in a false account
of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wasn't trying to coach Currie about what to say if she
were asked about his relationship with Lewinsky, Mills argued.
Rather, his intent was to ward off ``a looming media firestorm.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, a conservative Clinton critic, said
Mills' presentation had been effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone pretty much all the way through was riveted on what
she had to say,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The White House case is expected to conclude its case Thursday
with Clinton's private lawyer, David Kendall, addressing elements
of the second impeachment article alleging that Clinton obstructed
justice in hiding his affair with Lewinsky. Kendall will be joined
by former Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., an old political ally of
Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Senators then can submit written questions through Chief Justice
William Rehnquist to lawyers for the White House team and the House
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Senate is expected to take up a motion to dismiss
the case. If the motion fails, the lawmakers are likely to take up
the volatile issue of whether to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., said there are ``still a lot of
conflicts members have questions about. My sense is it would be
helpful to have witnesses'' to resolve them.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, suggested that momentum to call witnesses
was slowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be more fluidity than it appears,'' said Sen. John
Kerry, D-Mass. ``I've had a number of conversations with
Republicans... some Republicans may be finding that witnesses may
not be helpful to their case.''
</P>
<P>
   To convict Clinton and remove him from office requires the votes
of 67 senators, a two-thirds majority. The Senate is divided 55-45,
with Republicans in the majority.
</P>
</TEXT>
