<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING NEWCOM TO LAY OFF 40 WORKERS, CUT EXECUTIVES' PAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- High-speed communications product maker NewCom
Inc. has announced a sweeping restructuring that includes laying
off nearly 30 percent of its employees, hiring an interim president
and a pay cut for executives.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of NewCom fell 56.25 cents, or 22 percent, to $1.96875 on
Wednesday on volume of 386,600 shares. That's about seven times the
30-day average volume.
</P>
<P>
   The changes at the suburban Westlake Village-based company came
five days after it reported a $15.7 million third-quarter loss.
</P>
<P>
   James M. Curran, an outside board member who was an executive at
IBM for 21 years, becomes NewCom's interim president. Meanwhile,
the company is looking for a permanent replacement for Sultan Khan,
who had filled that job.
</P>
<P>
   Khan will remain NewCom's chief executive officer and chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last two years at NewCom, I have greatly appreciated
Mr. Curran's expertise and support,'' Khan said in a statement.
``In this time of rapid change in our industry, his help will be
invaluable in providing me an opportunity to step back from the
day-to-day responsibilities and work on the strategic positioning
of NewCom.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty employees, most involved in manufacturing, will lose their
jobs in the restructuring, the company said. It now has 104
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Six senior managers at NewCom have taken a 10 percent pay cut,
which puts their compensation at 1997 levels.
</P>
<P>
   NewCom also said Ed Stoltenberg, the company's chief financial
officer, resigned because his family did not want to relocate from
their Rhode Island home. He will provide financial consulting until
a replacement is found.
</P>
<P>
   NewCom said it is repositioning itself to take advantage of
emerging markets in the consumer field such as DVD digital cameras
and digital modes for high-speed Internet access and computer
networks.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
