<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA A FINE ONE TO PREACH TO NEWSPAPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An NCAA honcho named William S. Saum was minding other people's
business last week when he threw down a challenge to all
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Stop printing point spreads on games _ that's what Saum had to
say at the NCAA convention in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is one spread Mr. Saum won't be able to cover,
but it's a continuing theme for both him and the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only encouraging betting,'' Saum said. ``Unless a
newspaper is based in Nevada, where betting on sports is legal, a
point spread shouldn't be printed.''
</P>
<P>
   So Bill, bet this:
</P>
<P>
   For credibility, be it moralistic or Jerry Tarkanian, the NCAA
is one of the last institutions that should be placing itself upon
a pedestal. From the top of the organization down to member
schools, there is the ongoing question of just how do-right these
people really are.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, of course, there has been an outbreak of college
basketball point-shaving scandals, and one in football, involving
student-athletes. As director of gambling activity for the NCAA,
Saum is highly concerned, and should be. He is also hardly alone in
his concern.
</P>
<P>
   But if certain NCAA schools are giving the wink to
student-athletes on everything from under-the-table cash, entrance
exams, grades, cars, etc., then the next logical step was probably
predictable. Meaning, what's the harm in my team losing by 10
points, instead of nine, if the spread is nine.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, gambling is a major industry in this country,
legal or illegal, and the quest for an edge brings out the bandits.
</P>
<P>
   But what the heck does that have to do with point spreads being
printed in basically every sports section in the country, including
this one?
</P>
<P>
   This is the truth. Honest. And upon request, reliable witnesses
will be produced to verify the following:
</P>
<P>
   It's been at least 20 years since I placed a wager on a college
sporting event. Or professional, either.
</P>
<P>
   At Lone Star Park, however, I do believe strongly in pounding
the windows. It's just that my long-standing rule is don't risk
money on the athletic endeavors of any two-legged creatures,
although the Falcons plus seven is extremely tempting.
</P>
<P>
   But as a nongambler on football, basketball or baseball, one of
the first things I look for in the sports section is the point
spread or baseball odds. I don't think I'm alone, either.
</P>
<P>
   For a fan, the best indicator we have of how one team ranks
against another is how ``the line'' is set in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the apparent Sun Bowl mismatch between TCU and
Southern Cal. I had no idea how to handicap that game, but personal
opinion would have had TCU over a three-touchdown underdog.
</P>
<P>
   When Vegas put the line at 16, it was like a compliment to the
Frogs. And TCU's massive upset will always be remembered as a
gallant 16-point 'dog coming through. Vegas gave us that number,
which provided the predicted difference in the two teams, even for
those of us who didn't bet.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the betting line has its quirks. Handicappers
put up a number based on their opinion of how the legal money in
Las Vegas will flow. In the Cowboys' glory days of this decade, if
Dallas was favored by seven, you could usually assume the Cowboys
were actually a five- or six-point favorite. Since the Cowboys were
a team that normally drew betting action, points might be added.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers print the line for entertainment, information, and
opinion. Gamblers who are going to wager large sums obviously know
the line without having to turn to the sports section.
</P>
<P>
   Saum was not in his Kansas City office yesterday, or else I
would have asked him this:
</P>
<P>
   In North Texas, there have repeatedly been scandals involving
religious leaders, including pastors and priests. Should newspapers
discontinue religion sections?
</P>
<P>
   The medical community keeps telling us there are too many fat
people in this country. Since being overweight is a health problem,
are newspaper food sections to blame?
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the NCAA backed down after threatening to
withhold Final Four credentials for any newspaper printing the
point spread. There is some thought the NCAA will try to use that
muscle again.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for a Bill Saum is certainly real. It's just that
his solution is not realistic. \Ntagtop:Randy Galloway's Sports at
Six can be heard weeknights, 6-8 p.m., on WBAP NewsTalk 820.
\Ntagbottom:rgalloway\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
