<HEADER>
A1690 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEOFUNION-GREENSPA     01-20 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-GREENSPAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN AND REPUBLICANS FIND FAULT WITH CLINTON PLAN TO INVEST IN
STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Fla., N.H. Texas)  (See also: STATEOFUNION-CLINTON, STATEOFUNION-SURPLUS,
STATEOFUNION-VOICES, STATEOFUNION-REPUBS, STATEOFUNION-BUFFALO,
STATEOFUNION-CHICAGO, STATEOFUNION-TOBACCO.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in Congress and Alan Greenspan, the
chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, said on Wednesday that
President Clinton's proposal to have the government invest a
portion of Social Security reserves in the stock market would
endanger the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But while some influential Republicans said the plan proposed by
Clinton in the State of the Union message on Tuesday night was so
off base it left no room for compromise, many others saw the
proposal as an opening bid that could lead to fruitful
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before the House Ways and Means Committee on
Wednesday, Greenspan, whose views on economic matters carry
considerable weight in Congress and on Wall Street, said he
supported the president's notion of putting almost two-thirds of
the federal budget surpluses in the next 15 years into Social
Security reserves. But he said the idea of having the government
invest part of the money in the stock market could threaten the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The most pessimistic of the top lawmakers interviewed on
Wednesday was Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas, a Republican who is one of
the foremost authorities in Congress on Social Security. ``I was
profoundly disappointed in what the president proposed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said he feared that ``the whole thing is dead for this
Congress'' and that ``we may have to wait for a new president to
take office'' before the issue can be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   But asked about that view, Rep. Bill Archer of Texas, chairman
of the Ways and Means Committee, replied, ``I'm not that
pessimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president's opening shot ducks out on facing up to
the real issues,'' said Archer, whose committee will have first
crack in Congress at writing a new law, ``but I'm not sure this is
his final shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's plan to address the potential insolvency
of the retirement system when the baby boom generation retires, 62
percent of the projected surpluses in the next 15 years _ about
$2.7 trillion out of total surpluses of about $4.4 trillion _ would
be used to bolster Social Security's cash reserves. The Clinton
administration calculates that this would extend solvency to 2055
from 2032, protecting almost everyone who is now working.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this money would be used to pay off the government's
debt. Economists believe that lowering the debt, now about $5.5
trillion, would reduce interest rates, generate private investment
and stimulate economic growth, all of which would make it easier
for the children of baby boomers to pay their parents' retirement
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But the president would invest $700 billion of the $2.7 trillion
in the stock market, which over the long term has historically
produced substantially higher returns than the government bonds
where the Social Security reserves are now invested. The White
House says these higher returns would extend Social Security
solvency for about five years of the extended solvency, to 2055
instead of 2050.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insist that care would be taken to make
sure the investments were insulated from politics. But Greenspan
and Republicans in Congress are skeptical of government
participation in private financial markets, and this is where they
take strongest issue with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, for example, said he supported the idea of using most
of the surplus to shore up Social Security reserves. But as for
government investment in the stock market, he said, ``I do not
believe that it is politically feasible to insulate such huge funds
from government direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Political pressures, Greenspan said, could lead to inefficient
investments that, in turn, would result in a lower rate of return
for retirees and a lower standard of living for all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans took a similar stand. ``It amounts to
nationalization of American industry,'' said Rep. Jim Kolbe of
Arizona. ``It's scary. They haven't thought it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, almost without exception, favor investing
retirement money in financial markets, but they would have workers
invest the money themselves in their own private accounts rather
than having the investments placed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, with the support of most Democrats in Congress,
believes that such individual investments could breach the social
safety net and result in unsophisticated workers' risking their
retirement savings.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are not united behind any particular plan. Some,
like Kolbe, would allow workers voluntarily to invest a portion of
their payroll taxes. Their guaranteed Social Security benefits
would be reduced accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans would maintain the current Social Security tax
and benefit structure but would give workers an income tax cut if
they invested the money for their retirement. This would ultimately
cause the federal deficit to rise again if taxes were not raised or
government spending reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw of Florida, the new chairman of the Social
Security subcommittee in the House, said he was optimistic a
compromise could be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has opened the door toward investing in the
private sector,'' Shaw said. ``Republicans don't support the idea
of the government doing the investing, but it's a good thing the
president has opened the dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Judd Gregg of New Hampshire calculated the odds of finding
a consensus at 20 to 1. But before the president's speech, Gregg
said, he would have set the odds at 200 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, the Ways and Means Committee chairman, is retiring at
the end of this Congress, and he said that like Clinton, he would
like to leave a solvent Social Security system as a legacy of his
years in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do want to work something out and get this solved
during the last two years for Clinton and me,'' Archer said. Then,
referring to impeachment, he quickly added, ``Assuming he goes on
for another two years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
