<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS USE `RAPID RESPONSES' TO COUNTER CLINTON'S DEFENSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When White House Counsel Gregory Craig took a short
break in his testimony at the Senate impeachment trial Wednesday,
his GOP adversaries sprung into action.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after Craig stopped talking, several members of the
House Republican prosecution team were in front of the microphones
set up outside the Senate chamber trying to punch holes in the
White House argument.
</P>
<P>
   And later as Craig and his colleague Cheryl Mills were making
their case before the senators, staffers for the House managers
were roaming the Senate gallery where reporters work, passing out
response sheets, detailing where they believed the president's
attorneys had erred.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to influence lawmakers and shape public opinion during
the senate trial, Republicans may have stolen a page from President
Clinton's public relations machine.
</P>
<P>
   During his two presidential campaigns Clinton perfected a
rapid-fire response to his opponents accusations, often ensuring
that media coverage included both charge and countercharge.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McNulty, a spokesman for the House managers, said the
Republicans had not modeled their approach after Clinton's or any
other campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The managers want to be very quick to respond to what they
perceive as the mischaracterization of their positions,'' McNulty
said.
</P>
<P>
   Each day the House Republicans and their staffs prepare the
responses, which are not only passed out to media but to the
senators.
</P>
<P>
   One typical response:
</P>
<P>
   ``White House claim: White House counsel Gregory Craig today
stated that the articles of impeachment are unconstitutional
because each article contains multiple charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Truth: The articles do not improperly charge multiple
offenses in one article. Mr. Craig's arguments are factually
deficient, ignore Senate precedent and procedure, and are
constitutionally flawed.``
</P>
<P>
   However, the quick rebuttals have irritated some Democratic
senators, who believe that the House managers should be talking to
them, not the media.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said that
Democratic senators were ``generally grousing about'' the
Republican press conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have something to present they ought to present it to
the senators on the floor,'' said the aide.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when the Republican managers were making their case
before the Senate, White House officials opted to release a short
statement at the conclusion of each day.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had considered putting together a ``rapid
response'' effort to counter the presentations, but Democratic
lawmakers, including Sen. Robert Byrd of West Virginia, cautioned
against such an approach.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also considered having Democratic House members
who are on the Judiciary Committee respond to their GOP colleagues.
But that idea was also nixed.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign style response strategy is just one more way in
which the Senate procedure differ from courtroom proceedings, where
jurors are barred from considering evidence not presented during
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But most senators have long ago abandoned any pretense that they
are similar to jurors. While they pledged to be impartial and fair,
the senators have been eager to appear on television talk shows and
regularly grant interviews to reporters during breaks in testimony.
</P>
<P>
   They even joke about their new strange roles.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, walked by
Democratic colleague Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, who was
chatting with a half-dozen reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't believe a word'' she joked to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As she walked away, Dodd, laughed and responded, ``nice jury we
have here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
