<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1700 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-1100     01-20 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, UPSTATE PROSECUTORS ARE MORE LIKELY TO SEEK DEATH
PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Iowa, Texas)  (fe) 
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The return of capital punishment has reinforced the long-held
suspicion that New York is not one state but two. There is New York
City and its suburbs, with the bulk of the state's murders but a
fraction of its death-penalty cases. And there is the rest of the
state, where prosecutors seek the death penalty twice as often as
their downstate counterparts, and homicide defendants have been 10
times more likely to face possible execution.
</P>
<P>
   This striking imbalance accounts for what may be a more
surprising trend. Some opponents had worried that under the new
law, enacted four years ago, death sentences would fall
disproportionately on minority defendants. But because most upstate
counties are predominantly white, a defendant in a New York
death-penalty case is far more likely to be white than black.
Though whites make up only 21 percent of the state's murder
defendants, they are 55 percent of the defendants in capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the death penalty usually concentrates on
whether it is a useful and appropriate tool to reduce crime. It is
hard to measure what impact, if any, capital punishment has had on
New York's murder rate, which has declined sharply for nearly the
entire decade. But it has changed the criminal justice system, in
ways both subtle and startling and often unforeseen.
</P>
<P>
   The most pronounced disparities involve geography and race.
There have also been an unexpectedly small number of capital cases.
Thirty-four murder defendants _ less than 2 percent _ have faced
possible execution. Only two have been sentenced to death, and no
one has been executed. Proponents had predicted that prosecutors
would seek the death penalty in 15 percent to 20 percent of murder
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these trends underscores the ultimate source of power on
the death penalty in New York and other states: local prosecutors
who have broad discretion in deciding who will face execution and
who will not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death penalty in America is made by local officials,''
said George H. Kendall, a staff attorney at the NAACP Legal Defense
Fund, who works on capital cases around the country. ``Some
district attorneys use it, and some don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Geographic distinctions have cropped up in many of the 37 other
states with the death penalty. ``What you're seeing in New York is
typical, though not usually so stark,'' said David C. Baldus, a
professor at the University of Iowa School of Law. ``What you
usually see is that, in center city, there is relatively little
interest in capital punishment in the prosecutor's office.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government and most states do not keep detailed
death penalty statistics, including the racial breakdown of those
who become capital defendants, but academic experts have studied
geographic disparities in selected states.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Baldus examined all murder cases in which the
defendant was eligible for capital punishment in New Jersey between
1983 and 1991; he found that 10 percent of the potential capital
cases resulted in death sentences in the state's urban areas, while
24 percent resulted in death sentences in rural and suburban areas.
Political differences between urban and rural cultures account for
many of these distinctions, Baldus said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all states follow this pattern. In Texas, prosecutors in
Harris County, which includes Houston, have brought many capital
cases in the 1990s, while prosecutors in Dallas have brought
relatively few.
</P>
<P>
   And in Florida, prosecutors brought proportionately few capital
cases between 1973 and 1991 in Dade County, which includes Miami;
Palm Beach; Sarasota, and Broward County, which includes Fort
Lauderdale. But prosecutors in rural, northern counties and in some
Florida cities, including Pensacola, Daytona Beach, Orlando and
Tampa, sought the death penalty much more often, according to a
study by Michael Radelet, the chairman of the sociology department
at the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   While no two murder cases are exactly alike, there are enough
similarities to illustrate prosecutorial discretion in New York
state. In Buffalo, for example, Jonathan Parker was accused in 1997
of fatally shooting a police officer who was trying to question him
on a city street. District Attorney Frank J. Clark of Erie County
sought the death penalty. A jury convicted Parker last October but
rejected execution in favor of life in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, District Attorney Robert M. Morgenthau did not
seek the death penalty against Scott Schneiderman, who was accused
of killing a police officer as he fled from a botched attempt to
rob his own father in a Chelsea apartment in 1996. Morgenthau
instead pursued a sentence of life without parole and, like
virtually all prosecutors, would not discuss his reasons publicly.
A jury convicted Schneiderman last month, and he was sentenced last
week to life without parole.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the reasons for the disparities between upstate and
downstate _ which includes New York City and the counties of
Nassau, Suffolk, Westchester and Rockland _ are obvious. Four of
New York City's five district attorneys personally oppose capital
punishment. Two of them _ Morgenthau and Robert T. Johnson &UR;  &LR; of the
Bronx _ have never brought a death penalty case.
</P>
<P>
   But neither have two district attorneys who support the death
penalty: Jeanine F. Pirro of Westchester and William L. Murphy of
Staten Island. Nor has District Attorney Denis Dillon of Nassau,
who is opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pirro said the state's death penalty law was so restrictive
that very few murders qualify. ``There is not a lot of discretion
in the law,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But many other prosecutors and defense lawyers said that while
prosecutors had limited discretion in seeking first-degree murder
indictments, they had broad powers to decide which first-degree
murder defendants should face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In reinstating the death penalty, state legislators expanded the
definition of first-degree murder to include 12 categories. Among
them are multiple murders, the killing of police or corrections
officers, contract killings, those that involve torture and those
that take place during the commission of another serious crime like
robbery or rape.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,500 people have been arrested on murder charges
statewide since September 1995. About 190 people were indicted on
first-degree murder charges, and only 34 _ one-sixth _ have faced
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Upstate prosecutors have brought 24 of the 34 capital cases,
with 10 sought by downstate prosecutors. More than 80 percent of
the state's homicide arrests occurred in the city and its suburbs.
That means that someone arrested for murder upstate had a 5 percent
chance of becoming a capital defendant, while someone arrested for
murder downstate had a chance of one-half of 1 percent of becoming
a capital defendant _ making an upstate person arrested for murder
10 times more likely to face execution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many factors are part of the death penalty equation.
Prosecutors, for example, must decide if there were mitigating
factors in a defendant's background, like child abuse or serious
emotional problems, that could make it inappropriate to seek
execution. They must weigh aggravating factors, like the
heinousness of a homicide.
</P>
<P>
   District attorneys declined repeatedly to discuss how they had
decided individual cases. But speaking generally, many prosecutors
said they had created panels of senior aides to sift through
first-degree murder cases and weigh whether to seek execution. The
final decisions, the district attorneys insisted, were their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will never be a science, and quite frankly I think it
shouldn't be a science,'' said Clark, the Erie County district
attorney. ``That's why we're elected, to use our judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he had no formal committee to advise him, but often
conferred with senior aides. The first consideration in a potential
capital case, he said, is whether there is enough proof to win a
conviction..
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think about the impact on the community, whether or not
I feel this is the kind of case the Legislature had in mind when it
passed the statute,'' Clark said. ``Does this case really shock the
conscience of the community?''
</P>
<P>
   He also talks with the victim's family, he said, ``but in the
end I make the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said these decisions were difficult and personal. ``I
suppose there are a lot of different philosophies that people might
have or considerations they have to make in deciding which way to
go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The result statewide has been a strange hodgepodge. In Queens,
George Davis Bell was accused of killing an off-duty police officer
and a businessman as they were opening a check-cashing business in
1996. Richard A. Brown, the Queens district attorney, sought the
death penalty against Bell, who is awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Across the East River in the Bronx, Michael Vernon was charged
with killing five people in a shooting rampage in a shoe store in
December 1995. But Johnson, the Bronx district attorney, decided
not to pursue the death penalty. Vernon was convicted in 1997 on
five counts of first-degree murder and sentenced to life in prison
without parole.
</P>
<P>
   And in Rochester, Angel Mateo faced the death penalty in two
separate cases. Mateo was accused of having kidnapped a mentally
ill man on the street while on a frenzied search for his estranged
girlfriend. When the man could not help find her, Mateo shot him in
the head and suffocated him with a plastic bag, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   A jury convicted Mateo last month and sentenced him to die,
rejecting arguments that his life should be spared because he had
been physically abused as a child. Mateo is also awaiting trial in
an unrelated capital case, in which he is accused of killing three
people.
</P>
<P>
   The repeated decisions by Johnson, Morgenthau and other
downstate prosecutors not to seek the death penalty have been
harshly criticized by proponents of capital punishment, including
the relatives of some murder victims. In the most hotly disputed
case, Gov. George E. Pataki intervened two years ago when he became
convinced that Johnson would not seek the death penalty against
Angel Diaz, who was charged with killing Officer Kevin Gillespie.
Diaz committed suicide in jail before the case could be tried.
</P>
<P>
   After Diaz's death, a divided state Court of Appeals upheld the
governor's authority to intervene, ruling that legislators had not
intended to allow any of New York's 62 district attorneys to
sidestep the law by adopting a ``blanket policy'' against the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson insisted that he was following the law by exercising his
discretion case by case. ``There is no civil disobedience here,''
he said. ``We're complying with the law, and we're allowing other
people to go forward with what they've had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Some defense lawyers have seized on the governor's stand in the
Diaz case and the court's ruling, saying that the state's goal
appears to be that the death penalty should be applied uniformly
and that there should not be counties where it is never invoked.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Doyle, the state's capital defender, who runs the office
created by legislators to coordinate the defense of capital cases,
has hinted broadly that he would like someday to challenge capital
punishment in New York on the basis that it has been applied
arbitrarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is the earliest prophetic voice on that issue,''
Doyle said. He was referring to Pataki's comment, after the Court
of Appeals upheld his intervention in the Bronx case, that he would
not ``allow certain areas of the state to become death penalty free
zones.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents have raised legal challenges to death penalty laws in
at least four states by arguing that geographic imbalances show
capital punishment to be arbitrary and, thus, unconstitutional.
None of the lawsuits succeeded, said Baldus of the University of
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, most capital cases involve felony murders and
multiple homicides. Thirteen of the 34 capital cases have been
settled through plea bargains, with nine of the 13 defendants
getting life sentences without parole.
</P>
<P>
   Six death penalty cases have gone to trial; two defendants were
sentenced to die and three were sentenced to life without parole.
The sixth trial is in progress in Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, the Diaz case ended with the defendant's suicide.
In another case, in upstate Schoharie County, the prosecutor
withdrew his intention to seek the death penalty before trial.
Thirteen capital defendants are awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a great revelation to people to see how few
times district attorneys have chosen the death penalty,'' said
Charles J. Hynes, the district attorney in Brooklyn. ``There is an
awesome responsibility connected to this thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
