<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SPEECH, SOME IN GOP FEEL DAUNTED BY CLINTON'S POLITICAL
ACUMEN
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wis., Ga., S.C., Mont., Okla., N.D.)  (See also: STATEOFUNION-CLINTON, STATEOFUNION-SURPLUS,
STATEOFUNION-VOICES, STATEOFUNION-GREENSPAN, STATEOFUNION-BUFFALO,
STATEOFUNION-CHICAGO) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prominent Republicans around the country said
Wednesday that President Clinton's State of the Union Message was
an unsettling reminder that their party cannot compete with the
president's political skills, and that the impeachment trial could
only endanger their prospects in competitive states.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Washington attacked Clinton's plan to channel
some of the budget surpluses to domestic programs, asserting that
tax cuts were more important. And some Republicans were skeptical
about the president's proposal to invest Social Security money in
the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But, without disagreeing, Republican governors and party
officials in several states focused their comments _ and their
concerns _ more on Clinton's ability to win over the public than on
what they viewed as flaws in his programs. They sounded almost
awestruck by his political prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``He touched on every subject except his dog and the homeless _
and he promised everybody something, so you've got to like it,''
said Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson. ``He sounded like a super
governor up there, hyping all these individual programs. But over
all, you'd have to give him a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the speech made clear that his party faced quite a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans have to compete by coming up with a very
aggressive agenda, a very aggressive position on Social Security;
they have to have a tax cut and pass it, then have an HMO overhaul
bill,'' the governor said, adding, ``The only thing he missed was
talking about tax cuts _ that's what Americans really want.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Republican state chairman Rusty Paul said: ``He gives a
doggone good speech. It's extremely difficult to counter. And I
don't know that you can directly counter it. The great thing about
Clinton is the ability to finally buy into our ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   After the president's speech and the generally positive
reception to it, Paul said, he was even more worried about how the
impeachment trial could damage Republican chances in the 2000
elections. ``I don't think the country or the Republican Party
benefits from a protracted, long trial in the Senate,'' he said.
``People are going to get more and more frustrated and angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating, the chairman of the Republican
Governors' Association, said Clinton's speech was a ``candy store''
for lawmakers that offered ``caramels for conservatives,'' in the
form of initiatives to bolster education, and ``lemon drops for
liberals,'' with a pledge to increase the minimum wage. Keating
added: ``There was something for everyone. The only person who was
missing was Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans who remarked on Clinton's speech were so
effusive in their praise that they sounded as if they were
Democrats backing their leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president should receive high marks for his style and
presentation of the remarks,'' said Montana Gov. Marc Racicot. ``He
lived up, as he typically does, to an expectation of a polished
presentation. He embraced a lot of congressional proposals that
have been part of the Republicans' agenda for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Racicot did have a few misgivings, such as with Clinton's
proposals about Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a concern about the investment of funds in the stock
market and involving the government to a significant degree in
making decisions in what could be a fairly dominant presence in the
stock market,'' the governor said. ``And we didn't hear as much as
I would have liked to hear about tax relief.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Republican chairman Henry McMaster , said he
worried about the electoral consequences of the president's
popularity, which is underscored by his successful speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in a popularity contest with someone who's giving
away money, it's hard to win _ and that's all he does,'' McMaster
said. ``But he makes a great speech for the type of thing he's
trying to do. He very carefully says all the right things. It's so
obviously patronizing and attempting to appeal to folks who want to
feel good. It's a lot of spending more of our money.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many Republicans said Clinton's speech sounded like a
return to big government.
</P>
<P>
   ``More programs, more bureaucracy, more expenditures _ binding
our future generations to government costs _ and that is the
most-focused thing that we saw come from the president's speech,''
said Gov. North Dakota Edward Schafer. He described Clinton as the
``great deliverer _ he said something for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Goodman, a Republican speechwriter who helped draft the
response to Clinton's speech by Rep. Jennifer Dunn of Washington,
said the good news was that the battleground between the parties
Tuesday night was over an agenda, and not impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Republicans stray into uncharted territory, as they
are with this trial, and they come off message, it hurts them more
than it hurts Democrats,'' Goodman said. ``When there's a sense of
inertia, Republicans more than Democrats take the brunt of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
