<HEADLINE>
BUSHES SAY PERSONAL CONSIDERATIONS PLAYING ROLE IN POSSIBLE
PRESIDENTIAL RUN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Laura Bush expressed reluctance Wednesday to
surrender her privacy to a national political audience, while her
husband, Gov. George W. Bush, said he views a possible bid for the
2000 GOP presidential nomination as a once-in-a-lifetime
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure on Bush to run continued to build as Republican-elected
officials in California and Massachusetts praised him Wednesday as
a possible national party leader and president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reluctant. Absolutely. It's a major life change,'' Mrs.
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not particularly worried about safety. Privacy. I'm very
worried about privacy. That's really the main theme of it,'' Mrs.
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush expressed similar fears, but said he also believes that if
he does not run next year, history will pass him by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand there are windows of opportunity and there are
tides of history and moments of history,'' Bush said. ``Should I
choose not to run for the presidency, I understand the window would
probably be closed.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after being sworn in for a second term of office, Bush and
his wife were surrounded by state and national reporters during a
news conference at the Governor's Mansion. Only a few questions
dealt with state policy instead of his possible presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said if he does not rule out a presidential bid he will
take some action, such as forming an exploratory committee, before
the Legislature ends May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bushes said personal considerations are playing a major
role in whether to take the next step. Bush's father is
ex-President Bush, and both said they know what a presidential run
does to a family's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very nice life in Texas,'' Mrs. Bush said. ``I have
a really great time as first lady of Texas traveling around our
state. I see wonderful programs in every town, all over our state.
To do that on a national basis is just a step beyond. It's a much,
much bigger step.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush said she is worried about giving up her privacy as
well as that of her twin 17-year-old daughters, Jenna and Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   The governor added, ``Our daughters are normal. They don't want
to be put through the meat grinder of national politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is moving forward with personal explorations. He has
met with policy advisers in the past several weeks and Thursday has
a meeting scheduled with potential money-raisers from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't surprise you that I am listening to policy
people, because I intend to make an informed decision,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I decide to run for the presidency, I'm going to have
to raise a lot of money quickly,'' Bush said. ``It's important to
listen to the concerns of money-raisers as well as to listen to
different policy folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci, the only U.S. governor to
attend Bush's inaugural Tuesday, returned home praising Bush as a
potential national Republican leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party needs the kind of leadership that he's
demonstrated in Texas,'' Cellucci said. ``He's shown he can get
things done. He's also put a very high emphasis on high standards
in the classroom, on ending social promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   And in California, a majority of the Republicans in the state
legislature sent Bush a letter urging him to run for president. The
letter was signed by 22 of 32 Republicans in the state Assembly and
three of the 15 Republican senators signed the letter, including
all four Hispanic Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask for your favorable consideration to lead America as our
president, and we commit to you our support,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was considered to be a reproach to California Gov.
Pete Wilson, who is considering a White House run himself after an
unsuccessful try in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans believe Wilson cost the party support for
fostering racial divisiveness with his stands against aid to
illegal immigrants and against affirmative action. Bush has argued
against Republican rhetoric that is racially divisive.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was asked whether he thought there should be any kind of
limits on raising money for presidential campaigns. His father's
1988 campaign set up a system to funnel large contributions through
the Republican National Committee. Campaign finance scandals grew
out of the 1996 election when President Clinton all but turned
large donations to the Democratic National Committee into an
extension of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we ought to have full disclosure on campaign
contributions. If I choose to take a large contribution, you need
to know about it, and I can pay the political price if there is one
to be paid,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed criticisms from potential presidential rivals Dan
Quayle and Lamar Alexander about his use of the term
``compassionate conservative'' to describe his philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, who was vice president under Bush's father, recently
sent a letter to the staff of his presidential exploratory
committee banning the use of the phrase ``compassionate
conservative.'' Quayle called it a ``silly and insulting term that
was created by liberal Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander called the term ``weasel words'' and said Bush should
just call himself conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people choose to campaign based on what they believe, and
some people choose to campaign talking about the other person,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I choose to run for the presidency, I will talk about
what's in my heart and what I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
