<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-VENDING-ART-950(     01-20 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-VENDING-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTLERS BECOMING RIVALS TO VENDING-SALES MERCHANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Texas, Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic showing
market share of Coca-Cola Enterprises is being sent to NYT graphics
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One morning in October, Mike McGee stopped to inspect the
Coca-Cola vending machines that he had installed in a new student
recreation center at Harvey Mudd College in Claremont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   To his dismay, he found a brand-new one standing there, too _ a
machine installed by Coca-Cola Enterprises, the world's biggest
Coke bottler and the supplier to the $5-million-a-year McGee &AMP; Sons
family business. And the rival machine was charging 45 cents for a
12-ounce can of Coke _ 10 cents less than McGee was charging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the old days, they came around here saying, `Sell our
product,''' McGee, whose father started the business in 1961,
recalled. ``Now that we need their product, they say, `We'll still
sell it to you, but we're also going to be in business against
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, McGee pulled his machines from Harvey Mudd,
just as he took machines out of nearby Scripps College and two
accounts serving California city buildings a few months ago.
``There's just no way I can compete,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vending machines, a highly profitable market, have become an
important new battleground in the soft-drink business, and
Coca-Cola Co., through its bottlers, is by far the biggest and the
most aggressive competitor. ``We're in a period of intense
competition between bottlers and full-line vending operators for
the control of soft-drink vending machines,'' Elliott Maras, editor
of Automatic Merchandiser, a trade magazine, said.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the battle has led to greater availability of
soft drinks at somewhat lower prices. But many Coke-vending-machine
owners and distributors across the United States complain that the
fight is not fair. They say that Coca-Cola, which owns 44 percent
of Coca-Cola Enterprises and all the rights to popular brands like
Coca-Cola, Diet Coke and Sprite, is using its dominant position to
take business away from them.
</P>
<P>
   The power of Coca-Cola bottlers over distributors, they say, is
further enhanced by a 1980 federal law that gives local bottlers
exclusive rights to sell soft-drink brands in a certain territory.
More often than not, in Coke's case, the local bottler is Coca-Cola
Enterprises, which did $3.2 billion worth of business last year,
according to an earnings report on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints have led to investigations and lawsuits in
several states, people involved in the inquiries said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Coca-Cola Enterprises said the company played by
the rules. ``We deal with our customers in a fair and equitable
manner,'' said the spokesman, John Downs Jr., ``creating value for
them and satisfying the refreshment needs of our consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It is our policy to fully comply with all laws and
regulations applicable to our business operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Distributors who are accustomed to selling Coca-Cola products _
which have a 43.9 percent market share in the United States _ but
are troubled by the presence of Coca-Cola Enterprises as a rival
say that they cannot simply switch to selling other brands: Their
investments, market demand and other competition prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they have no choice but to buy from the local
bottler because Coca-Cola will penalize any bottler that sells to
customers from outside its designated territories. As a result, say
many smaller vending-machine owners and distribution companies, a
bottler can raise prices at will and otherwise dictate the terms of
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is, they overprice us in order to keep us in a less
competitive position than they have,'' said Ladd Little, who runs
L.C. Vending, his family's company in San Antonio. Like McGee, he
is a customer of Coca-Cola Enterprises, which controls the Coke
bottling business in most of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Little says that the price Coca-Cola Enterprises charges him is
higher than what he can find elsewhere. ``I buy a truckload a
week,'' he said. ``I can buy it for less at the grocery store. But
they won't allow that grocery store to sell it to me in quantity,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Several New York distributors say they are trying to organize to
resist the competition from Coca-Cola Enterprises. ``We just want
them to sell us the product for the same prices that they sell it
to themselves,'' one distributor, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said of the bottler. ``There's got to be something wrong
with being the wholesaler, and the retailer, and being protected by
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises declined to comment on its pricing.
</P>
<P>
   While Coca-Cola and Coca-Cola Enterprises are separate
companies, many analysts and accountants have said that their
business is essentially united. The bottler was spun off in 1986
from Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent annual report, Coca-Cola describes the
vending business as crucial to its sales growth. ``We're putting
ice-cold Coca-Cola Classic and our other brands within reach,
wherever you look,'' the report states, ``at the supermarket, the
video store, the soccer field, the gas station _ everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The investment in vending machines is costly, as debt-heavy
Coca-Cola Enterprises' fourth-quarter earnings statement shows. The
company reported a loss of 9 cents a share, in part because of
``capital and infrastructure investments,'' the chief executive,
Henry Schimberg, said in a statement. At the same time, though,
cash operating profit and case volume grew, mainly in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts applaud the company's push into vending
machines. ``It's really what I call the entrepreneurial spirit of
Henry Schimberg, that three or four years ago CCE recognized the
need to diversify out of lower-margin channels,'' said Andrew
Conway, an analyst with Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola and Pepsico, the nation's No. 2 soft-drink marketer,
have long flirted with the vendingbusiness, but both now seem
smitten with its potential. In Pepsico's prospectus for the initial
public offering of its bottling division, issued earlier this
month, the company calls vending ``one of the fastest-growing and
most profitable segments'' with ``gross margins that are
significantly higher than those from sales of products for
consumption at home.''
</P>
<P>
   As sales of 20-ounce bottles increase, they offer more reasons
for bottlers to pursue vending sales. They can charge more per
ounce. For example, according to one vending-machine owner, a
12-ounce can costs 22 cents apiece wholesale in one area of
southern California, while the 20-ounce bottle costs 53 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The big bottlers' drive for new business is being helped by the
unusual protection that Coke, Pepsi and other national brands
enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s the Federal Trade Commission argued that exclusive
bottling territories were illegal, because they inhibited
competition. But the Soft Drink Interbrand Competition Act of 1980
affirmed the rights of soft-drink companies to grant their bottlers
exclusive rights to sell a brand in a certain area, as long as
``substantial and effective competition between products of the
same general class'' exists.
</P>
<P>
   No other industry has a similar statute. Moreover, the
soft-drink companies essentially enforce the law on their own.
Citing the law, companies like Coke can charge bottlers a penalty
of $5 a case or more if their products turn up in bulk outside
their designated areas _ a breach of contract known as
``trans-shipping.'' The effect is to prevent distributors and
vendors from buying their soft-drink products from anyone but the
local bottler.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the legislation was being considered, proponents
said that a law was needed to protect bottlers from having their
business picked off by nearby rivals. The law also protected the
public interest, said Gordon Spivack, a partner at the law firm of
Coudert Bros. in New York who argued on behalf of Coca-Cola before
the Federal Trade Commission and on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every witness we called testified that the result of exclusive
territories was increased output and lower prices and better
quality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1980, the local bottler was probably a small,
independent, third-generation family business. Today, local
bottlers tend to be part of a conglomerate spanning many markets
and states. Industry consolidation has been in high gear for the
last several years. Coca-Cola Enterprises has acquired dozens of
smaller bottlers in the last few years, and now Pepsi is seeking to
match the Coke system.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the law shields small businesses hardly applies
anymore, said Allen Vestal, a professor at Washington and Lee
University Law School, who specializes in corporate issues and has
written about the soft-drink law.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say other arguments put forth in 1980 to support
the law, including the environmental benefit of refilling glass
bottles to the protection of a bottler's investment in those
bottles, have also lost their relevance.
</P>
<P>
   ``With those conditions gone, it's pretty hard to justify the
law,'' Vestal said. ``There are some natural constituencies who
ought to be interested in getting it repealed. Retailers could get
a better price if they had more than one person to deal with, and
so could Kmart and Wal-Mart.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises referred questions about the law to the
National Soft Drink Association, the industry's chief trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Davis, vice president for federal affairs at the
association, said that regardless of consolidation, the law remains
relevant for the industry. ``Size is a relative term,'' he said.
``You could have the smaller, efficient folks wanting to prey on
the larger bottlers' big accounts in certain areas.''
</P>
<P>
   And a spokesman for Pepsi-Cola, Brad Shaw, said, ``The law is
every bit as pro-competitive and relevant today as it was 19 years
ago.'' Trans-shipment ``is not a problem for us,'' he said, adding
that it amounts to ``a tiny fraction of our sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say that the law has been beneficial to consumers. The
territorial franchise system, said John Sicher, editor of Beverage
Digest, an industry newsletter, ``has enabled bottlers to make
products more widely available and at better prices than in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   That system, however, and the role that Coca-Cola Enterprises
plays in it, is drawing increased scrutiny. In addition to other
state investigations, the Ohio attorney general's office has begun
an investigation of its own, following a complaint from one
distributor.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman, Todd Boyer, said that the investigation was in its
early stages and added, ``We are aware that there are other states
that may be investigating similar allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Metzger, the Ohio distributor who complained, said
Coca-Cola Enterprises executives had pursued him after he told them
he thought he was being charged too much. He compared prices at a
nearby Sam's Club, owned by Wal-Mart Stores, and found that he was
paying 40 cents more per case than the giant retailer did; Metzger
sells about 170,000 cases of Coke products a year.
</P>
<P>
   When he complained to Coca-Cola Enterprises, he said, his prices
were raised another 70 cents, and the company began demanding
immediate payment. Metzger said he could not pay the $160,000 he
owed them.
</P>
<P>
   Downs, the Coca-Cola Enterprises spokesman, said he was aware of
Metzger's complaint, but had no further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer also said that Ohio investigators were ``keeping an eye''
on a federal lawsuit filed in Maryland, in which a distributor,
B.K. Miller Inc., accused Coca-Cola Enterprises of unfair pricing,
fraud and other illegal activities. Downs said that the allegations
in the B.K. Miller suit ``are false and totally without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as complaints mount, few expect the soda franchise system
to change its way of doing business. ``Every decision a bottler has
made has been predicated on the protection of territorial
integrity,'' said Drew Davis, vice president of federal affairs at
the soft-drink trade group. ``Without that certainty, your customer
could be anybody in America. Or it could be nobody in America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
