<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS 2000 MAY BE HIS ONLY SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush said Wednesday that the 2000
election is probably the only shot he'll get at capturing the White
House, but that his wife and children are reluctant to give up
their privacy for a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand there are windows of opportunity, and there are
tides of history and there are moments in history,'' Bush said
during a packed news conference at the Governor's Mansion. ``Should
I choose not to run for the presidency, I understand the window
would probably close.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was joined at the post-inaugural news conference by his
wife, Laura, who expressed reservations about a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reluctant, absolutely,'' she said. ``I just think it's a
major life change. We have a very nice life in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very worried about privacy. That's really the main thing,
I guess,'' she said in a rare extended exchange with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said the couple's twin 17-year-old daughters, Jenna
and Barbara, feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our daughters are normal,'' he said. ``They don't want to be
put through the meat grinder of national politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments from the governor and first lady are among their
most extensive to date.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will not decide definitively on a national campaign
before the 76th session of the Texas Legislature wraps up at the
end of May.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean he won't set up a federal exploratory
committee to allow him to raise money and lock up some key support
before spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the exploratory committee an option?'' said Bush. ``Yes,
it's an option ... should I decide to do so it will be set up prior
to the end of the legislative session.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently at or near the top in most presidential preference
polls, Bush has been meeting with policy experts and potential
donors in recent weeks to help him make up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has a meeting scheduled Thursday with ``potential
donors, helpers.'' Neither he nor his office would release the
names of those attending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I decide to run for the presidency, I'm going to have
to raise a lot of money quickly, and it's important to listen to
the concerns of money raisers as well as to different policy folks
and that's what's going to happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush raised about $18 million on his re-election effort and,
should he run for president, is expected to have a formidable fund
raising machine that taps into an extensive national network
developed over decades by his father, former President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, Gov. Bush said the current limits on federal
fund raising should be raised. He said the Texas campaign finance
system, which has no cap on contribution size, works just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I choose to take a large contribution, you need to know
about it, and I will pay the political price if one needs to be
paid,'' Bush said. ``I'm for full disclosure, and I believe we
ought to raise the limits to give people a chance to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it would not be appropriate for him to talk about the
issues he would choose to campaign on, but he did find fault with
the GOP message on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have been great about saying let's roll back
welfare . . . which I thought was a good reform,'' Bush said. ``But
there is a corollary to that, and that is, we must do our own part
in our own neighborhoods in our own communities to help people in
need. That's sometimes part of the message that is missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush passed up an opportunity to criticize potential Republican
primary opponents, including Lamar Alexander and former
Vice-President Dan Quayle, who have been taking shots at the
``compassionate conservatism'' slogan the governor has used to
convey his philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I choose to run for the presidency, I'll talk about
what's in my heart and what I believe,'' he said. ``They can talk
about what they believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Root, (512) 476-4294
</P>
<P>
   jroot\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
