</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-PROFITS-INCREASE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM REPORTS UNEXPECTEDLY ROBUST 4TH QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors Corp. announced Wednesday an
unexpectedly large increase in profits during the fourth quarter of
last year, as the very strong American auto market and the
company's continued recovery from last summer's strike more than
offset losses in Latin America and East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   GM's profits rose 7.7 percent, to $1.77 billion, during the
fourth quarter, but fell 53.2 percent, to $2.96 billion, for all of
last year, because of a 54-day strike in June and July at two
auto-parts factories in Flint, Mich. The strike forced the world's
largest automaker to close almost all of its assembly plants in
North America.
</P>
<P>
   The company's fully diluted earnings per share reached $2.61 in
the fourth quarter, up 12.0 percent. Excluding a long list of
one-time losses, GM's earnings were $3.25 a share, easily beating
the Wall Street analysts' average estimate of $2.65 a share,
according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of GM rose to an all-time high after the earnings were
announced. It closed at $88.9375, up 93.75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   GM's robust fourth-quarter results reflected exuberant sales of
high-profit sport utility vehicles and pickup trucks in the United
States and continued profits in Europe. Because Ford Motor Co. also
depends heavily on the American and European markets, GM's results
make it likely that Ford will also report healthy profits when it
releases its earnings on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regions of the world that are strongest happen to be where
we are strongest,'' J. Michael Losh, GM's chief financial officer,
said in an interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The North American auto market produced $1.58 billion in profits
for GM in the fourth quarter, while European car operations
generated another $146 million in profit, allowing the company to
prosper despite economic troubles in emerging markets. By contrast,
GM's East Asian automotive division lost $213 million in the fourth
quarter while its operations in Latin America, Africa and the
Middle East, previously very profitable, lost another $212 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's strike reduced GM's full-year, after-tax profits
by ``at least $2 billion,'' Losh said. While GM had declared
strike-related losses totaling $2.5 billion during the second and
third quarters of last year, John Smith Jr., GM's chairman and
chief executive, had predicted in August that the company would be
able to reduce that to $2 billion by the end of the year by
building extra cars and trucks in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Losh said GM had not been able to catch up as much as
expected during the fourth quarter because Americans bought cars
and light trucks at a torrid pace. Indeed, last month had the
highest seasonally adjusted annual rate of new auto sales in the
United States since December 1986.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, GM factories in North America will continue to
produce cars and trucks at a brisk tempo in the first quarter,
usually a slow season, Losh said. Whether the strike cost GM $2
billion or even more, it still remains easily the most expensive
strike in U.S. history, before adjusting for inflation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Maryann Keller, an auto analyst at ING Baring in New York, said
GM's strong fourth-quarter profits were likely to spill over into
the first quarter because GM will be catching up on full-size
pickup truck production, which is very profitable. Unlike in past
periods of prosperity, GM is also continuing to cut costs
aggressively, Ms. Keller said, adding that she had raised her
estimate of GM's 1999 profits to $8.75 per share from $8.25 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   GM earned $4.18 per share in 1998 and $8.62 per share in 1997.
GM's sales also fell last year, to $161.32 billion from $171.18
billion.
</P>
<P>
   GM, which had cash reserves of $14.1 billion on Dec. 31,
announced Wednesday that it would resume a $4 billion share buyback
program soon and finish it this year. GM had suspended the program
last summer because of the strike, after spending only a third of
the $4 billion. GM also said Wednesday that it would soon redeem
its Series B 9-1/8 preference stock, which has a face value of more
than $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   GM's fourth-quarter earnings included $420 million in one-time,
after-tax charges. These mostly reflected early retirement
programs, but included a $97 million charge in GM's East Asian
automotive division that was caused partly by the need to replace
equipment at a new factory in Thailand. GM had planned to produce
one of its popular European car models there, but switched to van
production because of the economic problems in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi Automotive Systems, GM's wholly owned auto parts
subsidiary, earned $88 million in the fourth quarter, compared with
a $508 million loss in the period a year earlier, as smaller
one-time charges more than offset a deterioration in operating
results. Delphi plans an initial public offering of a 17.7 percent
stake in itself this spring, and to become completely separate from
GM by the end of this year through a distribution or exchange of
shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
