<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTRO-DELAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUNCHING OF WORLD'S LARGEST X-RAY TELESCOPE IS DELAYED AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.M.)   (sw) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NASA announced on Wednesday another delay in
launching the world's largest X-ray telescope, saying that the
discovery of possibly flawed circuit boards in the $1.5 billion
craft would delay its trip into orbit at least five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the flight of the Chandra X-ray Observatory, a
cousin to the Hubble Space Telescope that is to examine the
universe's X-ray emissions, will come no earlier than mid-May and
could be delayed further. The shuttle Columbia was to have lofted
the five-ton observatory on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   National Aeronautics and Space Administration officials said
during a telephone news conference on Wednesday that the potential
problem arose Friday, a day after the telescope's manufacturer,
TRW's Space and Electronics Group, of Redondo Breach, Calif., held
a ceremony to declare the craft ready for delivery to NASA.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandra observatory has taken more than 20 years to develop
and build. It was to have been launched last summer but was delayed
because of troubles during hardware testing and problems with
software.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth W. Ledbetter, director of mission development in NASA's
Space Science Office, said discovery of the circuit board problem
was disappointing, particularly with the craft so close to launch.
However, he added, ``We are very pleased we found the problem
before we got further along.''
</P>
<P>
   The circuit boards were made by an Albuquerque, N.M., company
acquired by B.F. Goodrich in 1997 and now part of its Davis Systems
Division. The company found during routine tests that copper
tracings that carry electrical current along the surface of some
boards were cracking and separating from the surface. Ledbetter
said delays over the past six months already have cost NASA an
additional $39 million, but he said he did not know what the latest
postponement would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Chandra is named after the late University of Chicago
astrophysicist and Nobel prize winner Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar.
It will examine X-rays, which are produced by the most violent
processes in the universe, including exploding stars, quasars and
black holes. They can be observed only from outside the Earth's
atmosphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2007EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1727 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT &LR;      01-20 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUE MEANING OF FREE SPEECH IN THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.C., N.M.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-TRIAL) 
(mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There was a certain pleasure for the few listeners
on hand Wednesday morning when senators began orating in the
chamber about absolutely anything they pleased a full two hours
before President Clinton's impeachment trial resumed.
</P>
<P>
   It was Senate morning business time _ noncombative potpourri
hours for individual lawmakers to reserve time and speak on the
record however they cared to _ before a nearly empty chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, as each senator entered for a scheduled
slot, then left without listening much to the next lawmaker, the
exercise resembled individual oratorical aerobics much needed after
all the flabby trial hours of having to listen in silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a gifted man, gifted as few individuals are,'' Sen.
Richard Durbin, D-Ill., was saying at one point to the cavernous,
sparsely attended chamber, earning the ear of early wanderers as he
talked of the ``premature retirement'' of someone. (Of whom? Of the
president?)
</P>
<P>
   ``All net,'' the senator continued in a sports metaphor for
success. (The president's polling ``bounce'' after his State of
Union speech?) ``He developed a new fade-away jump shot,'' Durbin
went on and, of course, it was another tribute to Michael Jordan
the basketball master, not to the president and his patented
triangulation move in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, as the separate senators went about their talkative bits
of preferred business, the now familiar trial bustle began outside
the chamber. Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., wheeled quickly around a
corridor corner in his motorized wheelchair and almost collided
with the hand-powered wheelchair of Charles Ruff, the White House
counsel arriving for another day of the momentous trial.
</P>
<P>
   Great mutual amusement ensued, as if at a friendly village
crossroads and the two went their separate ways. Just so, witnesses
could imagine ordinary life going on beyond the trial,
unimpeachable mishaps, small encounters, not grueling struggles.
</P>
<P>
   In the chamber, the speechmakers still went about their
non-impeachment workouts, promising fresh tax cuts and other boons
to the cameras and to the lone senator doing president pro tem duty
up in the chair.
</P>
<P>
   They did so to within a close few minutes of the arrival of
Chief Justice William Rehnquist and the resumption of the trial
with the ``Hear ye...'' and the rest of the new Senate routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to spend it all,'' Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., was
declaring in complaint of the president's clashing with Republican
tax-cut proposals for the budget surplus. The senator seemed
thoroughly delighted to be plainly talking of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In a minute the proceeding was gaveled closed. Free speech was
over, and Domenici metamorphosed once more into a member of the
impeachment court. Other senators hurriedly arrived, one wiping
lunch crumbs from his lips.
</P>
<P>
   The trial routine settled back in. David Kendall, the
president's personal counsel, once more neatly aligned and
realigned his two pens, red and black, at the defense table for
another day's careful note-taking.
</P>
<P>
   It was the turn of Gregory Craig, special counsel to the
president, to address the court and attack the charges of the House
Republican prosecutors. ``You will have had much more than 100
percent of your minimum adult daily requirement of lawyering,'' he
lightly apologized at the outset, drawing laughs from senators who
were in no position to debate the point.
</P>
<P>
   The court listened closely, taking notes, following the
exhibits, including a 14-minute clip from Clinton's videotaped
deposition in the Paula Jones suit. The man the senators studied
warily talking a year ago about his private life delivered the
State of the Union message only the night before, with all the
confidence in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, like the nation, seemed threatened by time warp, by
the oft-told tale of the president and the intern. During 15-minute
breaks in the trial the House prosecutors took to television to
offer counter-rebuttal, as if their case were in the hand of some
national jury rather than the Senate court. They admitted that, of
course, the public was hearing nothing new since both sides were
working from a now all too familiar record.
</P>
<P>
   In the corridors, the question in the air, as ever, was when
would this all end. The threat of a fresh, time-consuming muddle
was hinted at by some Senate staffers pointing to a complex series
of contentious votes and debates, some behind closed doors, to come
next week. After that, according to many expectations, a period of
witness deposing is likely to follow as something new is searched
for.
</P>
<P>
   Out beyond the debating chamber, sunshine bathed the Capitol as
the country moved inevitably closer to spring. Craig ended his
defense of Clinton with a simple narrative description of the
political event that projected him into the presidency, election
day when millions of Americans go to firehouses and schools to
personally choose their national leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing _ almost miraculous _ that so powerful and
transforming an event can occur so quietly in a great and populous
nation,'' said Craig, and the silent court of elected politicians
seemed to listen with professional savor. ``The act itself is
almost invisible to outside eyes,'' the president's defender gently
noted, pleading against removal of the people's choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
