<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1729 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-SENATE21-COX     01-20 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SENATE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former President George Bush, in a special lecture
to U.S. Senate members Wednesday evening, expressed concern over a
``deficit of decency'' that he said has engulfed the nation's
capital in the six years since he departed the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush continued to refrain from commenting on the
impeachment and Senate trial of President Clinton, his successor,
the former president lamented ``the lack of civility'' in politics
today as well as ``sleaze'' and ``excessive intrusion into private
lives'' of public figures.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed not only the politicians for the ``bitter rancor'' of
today but also the ``once great news organizations that seem to
resort to tabloid journalism, giving us sensationalism at best and
smut at the worst.'' He said ``the times cry out for more
credibility'' from the press.
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged ``some of the ugly happenings'' of his own
presidency, including the Senate fights over the nomination of John
Tower as defense secretary and Clarence Thomas to the Supreme
Court. But for the most part, ``a spirit of compromise'' prevailed
between his White House and the Democratic majority in Congress, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting current events with Washington's preoccupation with
the mushrooming budget deficit of his administration, Bush said,
``All in all, it seems to me, that whereas the problems looming
over this town dealt more with budget deficits in times past, today
we're confronted with kind of a deficit of decency, one that
deepens by the day.''
</P>
<P>
   He made only a fleeting mention of the impeachment trial,
thanking the senators for attending his lecture during a ``terribly
traumatic time'' in their deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was the fourth person invited to address senators in a
special lecture series sponsored by Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott of Mississippi. Bush delivered his lecture in the old historic
Senate chambers in the U.S. Capitol. Among the special guests in
the balcony was Colin Powell, who was chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff during Operation Desert Storm, the Bush-led war to expel
Iraqi troops from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in a brief review of his administration, said the narrow
52-47 Senate vote backing the Gulf War against Saddam Hussein was
``the key vote'' of his presidency. And while he insisted that he
was not obligated to seek such a vote, he noted it was important to
have the Senate's backing before sending U.S. troops into combat.
</P>
<P>
   Bush recalled that after the vote, he received a warning from
Sen. Dan Inouye, D-Hawaii, that he might be subjected to
impeachment ``if things go wrong'' in the military intervention in
the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who resides in Houston, told the senators that while he
rarely visits Washington anymore, he is still interested in events
in the capital. But he said he did not want to involve himself in
those events because of the political careers of two sons, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas and Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``My politics today ... relate only to the two sons,'' he said.
``Time has moved on. And in our family, the torch is passed to two
boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the lecture, Bush displayed his hallmark
self-deprecating humor. Noting, for example, that his lecture fell
on the 10th anniversary of his being sworn in as president, he also
pointed out that it was the sixth anniversary of his being ``sworn
out ... receiving what Winston Churchill called the order of the
boot.''
</P>
<P>
   Promising not to filibuster the senators, he added, ``speaking
of filibusters, Barbara is sorry she could be here this evening.''
The former first lady did not accompany the former president to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bush singled out former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole for
special praise. Despite their intense and bitter political fight
for the 1988 GOP presidential nomination, ``not once did he (Dole)
let me down'' during his presidency, Bush added.
</P>
<P>
   end
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
