<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K glitches showing up in politics, too, but America `will go
on'
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Y2K glitches or no Y2K glitches, the nation is
working itself into a millenial mood.
</P>
<P>
   This is the season of broad visions and long reaches, of
inauguration and state of the state and nation speeches, when new
leaders take office with great hopes for the future and more
weathered ones try to put a fresh spin on their administrations.
The added incentive of being in office at the beginning of the new
millenium seems to have inspired those politicians who've had a
platform in the past week or so to stretch themselves in the vision
department.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, taking office for the second time,
called for ``armies of compassion'' to rise up and solve the
state's problems, while newly elected Gov. Jim Hodges of South
Carolina spoke of a 21st century ``children's crusade.'' Gov. James
Gilmore of Virginia vowed to make that state the Internet capital
of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   In line with the millenial rhetoric, two things distinguish this
year's crop of speeches from those of recent years: a much stronger
itch for governmental activism, from the president on down, and a
sweeping acknowledgement of the nation's increasing diversity.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Bush spoke a sentence in Spanish and extolled values
``upheld by boot-tough old cowboys and brand-new immigrants.'' In
Alabama, civil rights attorney Fred Gray declared the ``line in the
dust'' drawn in 1960 by Gov. George Wallace had become ``the tie
that binds.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was the shift in the approach to government more evident
than Alabama, where former Georgia Gov. Zell Miller administered
the oath to Democrat Don Siegelman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone was any attack on big government and out-of-control
courts and any expressions of concern over a society gone haywire
that constituted nearly half of (Former Republican Gov. Fob) James'
1995 inaugural speech,'' wrote Tom Gordon of the Birmingham News.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman and Hodges are both exponents of Millerism, that
coinage being safe now that he's out of office: a sharp focus on
what Miller calls ``kitchen table issues,'' laced with the pizzazz
of a lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Millerism is a style which has evolved in response to the
Republican Southern surge. To the GOP's critique of Big Government
at both the national and state level, Millerism concentrates on
government programs that demonstrate very obvious payoffs for
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The First Governor, Bill Clinton, has studied Millerism
carefully, but it would be too understated to define the agenda
described in his State of the Nation address as a litany of kitchen
table issues.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe kitchen table and kitchen sink. Beyond the mere fact of
his showing up to give the speech, what must have most galled the
Republicans who sat on their hands watching Clinton on Tuesday
night was his appropriation of huge chunks of the century they
thought was theirs. Clinton's plan to save Social Security would
lock the Republicans out of the chance for a surplus-produced tax
cut for 15 years, while his plans for Medicare would set policy for
that program out to 2020.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to this sweeping 21st-century horizon, the
Republican response began with Rep. Jennifer Dunn's cheerful
assurance that ``no matter what the outcome of the president's
situation, life in America will go on.'' True enough, but not very
Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
