<HEADER>
A1731 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BUMPERS21-COX     01-20 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BUMPERS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Final arguments presented by Bumpers expected to be personal,
`entertaining'
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a lengthy interview with the Los Angeles Times
shortly before he left office, former Arkansas Sen. Dale Bumpers
predicted the House would never impeach President Clinton and, if
it did, the Senate would filibuster it to certain death.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the veteran Democrat will stand before his former Senate
colleagues to defend his longtime friend against charges that
Clinton lied and obstructed justice and should face the ultimate
consequence: removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers, who retired from the Senate last year after 24 years,
will deliver the final arguments in Clinton's defense. White House
lawyers haven't spelled out what Bumpers will say, but several
Democratic senators said they expect their former colleague to draw
heavily on his personal friendship with Clinton, understanding of
the Senate and deep knowledge of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the substance, senators on both sides of the aisle
predict a fiery summation from a man many consider to have been one
of the Senate's finest orators.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't get any better,'' said Sen. Ron Wyden (D-Ore.).
``He's one of those people who in this age of sound bites brings a
real dignity to the Senate body. It would not be possible to find a
better person on the planet to represent the president.''
</P>
<P>
   A liberal Southern Democrat who lived and fought through the
civil rights movement, Bumpers retired from the Senate at 73
feeling very much disillusioned. He is now the director of the
Center for Defense Information, a military policy organization in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He fought many losing battles in the Senate, but became known
for his persistence and dedication to the issues he believed in. He
fought funding for the NASA space station, a host of expensive
defense projects and legislation and regulations he believed tilted
too much in favor of mining companies.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Atlanta Constitution in October,
Bumpers said, ``The ordinary person in the coffee shop in Arkansas
will say I don't agree with old Dale, but at least he stands up and
does what he thinks is right. That is the quality, that people not
just in Arkansas, but all across the country are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion piece appearing in the New York Times earlier this
year, Bumpers lamented the ``meanspiritedness'' and loss of
collegiality that had infected Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is rarely consensus even on the most practical and
ideologically neutral matters,'' he wrote. ``And issues that go to
the heart of the values we hold as a nation have become so partisan
that the imperative to win subsumes the necessity of governing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers' former Senate colleagues invariably refer to his
captivating oratory when describing their former colleagues
</P>
<P>
   With his booming voice and penchant for roaming the Senate floor
while he speaks, Bumpers' oratorical style harkens back to the
``golden age'' of Senate oratory when senators spoke to real
crowds, not radio microphones or television monitors, said Ron
Ritchie, associate Senate Historian.
</P>
<P>
   Senators such as Daniel Webster, John Calhoun and Henry Clay
were seasoned orators, Ritchie said, who depended on the power of
their lungs and gesture of their hands to engage their listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clearly came out of that background,'' said Ritchie. ``He
could really speak to a crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers, the son of a hardware store owner in the West Arkansas,
honed his speaking skills as a Southern country lawyer in his
hometown of Charleston, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   He ran for governor in 1970, beating out seven other candidates,
including Arkansas' segregationist governor, Orval Faubus. He ran
for Senate in 1974 with the intention, later abandoned, of running
for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he ran for governor, no one had heard of a country lawyer
from Charleston, but he was such a great speaker,'' said Ralph
Shelby, a boyhood friend from Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has had a remarkable ability to connect with the people,''
said Skip Rutherford, former chief aide to senator David Pryor,
another former Arkansas Democrat. ``He's one of these individuals
who is a scholar, but also a communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   A passionate constitutional scholar, Bumpers carries around a
copy of the Constitution in his pocket and frequently has copies on
hand to give away.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers also knows Clinton, who views the senior Democrat as a
mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have a grasp of what went on down there in Arkansas
and that would add to his credibility,'' said Sen. Ernest Hollings
(D-S.C.). ``It'll certainly be a lot of better than what we've
heard so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tim Hutchinson (R-Ark.) acknowledged that Bumpers was well
liked, but noted that he had also ``championed a lot of lost
causes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be very entertaining,'' said Hutchinson. ``There will be
a lot of stories. He'll be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
