</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HALLWAYS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate divided on public coverage of trial
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's impeachment trial could vanish
from television screens as early as Monday if the Senate doesn't
change the 131-year-old rules governing the trial.
</P>
<P>
   When senators switch from passive audience to participants in a
debate, the rules require that they exclude the public. Any
proposal, or motion, to dismiss the charges, subpoena witnesses, or
vote on Clinton's fate can be discussed only in secret session,
although the votes themselves would be held in public.
</P>
<P>
   The trial schedule sets Monday as the day to consider a motion
to dismiss the charges against Clinton, followed by another
proposal to subpoena witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In a legislative body as fond of tradition as the Senate, there
is considerable support in both parties for retaining the secrecy
rule. Sen. Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) spoke for many of his colleagues
when he praised the Senate's ability to work in a bipartisan
fashion, particularly when no television cameras are present.
</P>
<P>
   Senators ``are more reasonable'' in a private setting, McConnell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many senators said their private meeting in the old
Senate chamber nearly two weeks ago allowed them to agree on
procedures for the trial in large part because they did not have to
worry about how reporters would assess their comments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not all senators want to retain the old rule. Two
Democrats, Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa and Sen. Paul Wellstone of
Minnesota have sponsored a proposal to open deliberations to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that unless we open this trial up, we are going to
sow the seeds of confusion, misinformation, suspicion and
unnecessary conflict,'' Harkin said Wednesday on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said senators would quickly tell reporters what had
transpired, but insist on not being quoted. Competing versions of
events would create conflict, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's two senators, both strong supporters of open
government when they were state elected officials, said they likely
would be on different sides of the issue. Democratic Sen. Max
Cleland said, ``I tend to favor the Harkin resolution to open up
the deliberations of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell said he is leaning against
voting to open the proceedings to the public. Coverdell said he is
still working through the issue, but added that he fears open
deliberations could disrupt the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't know to what public good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Chief Justice William Rehnquist's ruling last week that
the senators are not, strictly speaking, jurors, Coverdell said
their debates on the articles of impeachment are akin to jury
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause and other government watchdog groups are working in
support of open deliberations. ``If the Senate deliberates in
secret, there will forever be lingering questions about what
happened and why,'' Common Cause President Ann McBride wrote
senators.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin and Wellstone intend to modify their proposal so that it
would apply only to the initial motion to dismiss the charges. If
that motion fails, and senators see how painless public
deliberations are, they would support changing the rest of the
process, Harkin said.
</P>
<P>
   But he may be a tad optimistic. Rule changes require a
two-thirds vote, meaning 67 senators must vote for open
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to get two-thirds on anything,'' Coverdell said.
``I just don't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
