<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1733 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DREXLER-PIPPEN-HN     01-20 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DREXLER-PIPPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
When Clyde Drexler retired from the NBA, he left some pretty big
shoes to fill. It was almost as if the Rockets lost three players.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They lost a guy who could play the point and distribute the
ball, a small forward who could post up and rebound, and a big
guard who could shoot from the perimeter and push the ball on the
break.
</P>
<P>
   Filling those gaps would require signing three players. Or they
could try to get the one player who could do all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Houston, Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler, now the basketball coach at the University of Houston,
can easily see the similarities between his game and Pippen's.
Getting him to admit that, however, is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for me what's different or what's similar,'' Drexler
said. ``I never compare myself to anybody or compare people to me.
I just think he's a good player, and he's been a good player for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Drexler can see where Pippen is a huge addition for a team
trying to milk another title or two out of Hakeem Olajuwon's last
three years in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to winning is that you need a real team,'' Drexler
said. ``The Rockets are trying to piece together a team. For the
last three years of Hakeem's career, the Rockets are trying to put
people around him that will give him a chance to go back and win
another title. That's admirable. By bringing in Scottie, I think
they're going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, signed by Chicago to a five-year deal that could be
worth up to $82 million with incentives before being dealt to the
Rockets for Roy Rogers and a second-round draft pick, won six NBA
championships with the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, playing with Michael Jordan helped Pippen amass those
rings, and Drexler pointed out that by coming to Houston, he will
be playing in an entirely different system than the one to which he
was accustomed in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie was a good complementary player to Michael Jordan,''
Drexler said. ``He had a tremendous career. I like his game. He
plays hard, but I think that fitting into a new system, one with a
center, is going to be an adjustment for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he has to give the ball into the center, because that's
where your offense starts. That's different from the motion offense
he had in Chicago, or when they just gave it to Jordan and spotted
up. It's going to be an adjustment, but I think Pippen can make
that adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if the 6-8 swingman continues to play the kind of
game that made him so successful with the Bulls. Drexler feels the
reason Pippen flourished in Chicago was because he was content to
play a complementary role rather than try to upstage Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie never was the type of guy who wanted to put up big
numbers just to make you notice him,'' Drexler said. ``He just
tried to play the all-around game. That's probably good, because if
he tried to put up big numbers, we don't know if he could. That
year that Jordan was not there (the 1993-94 season), we saw that he
couldn't, basically. (Pippen averaged a career-high 22 points, but
it was far off the 32.6 Jordan put up the season before.)
</P>
<P>
   ``So Scottie just plays his game, and he does that very well.
He's going to have pretty much the same job description on this
team _ play the all-around game, distribute the ball and just do
what he's capable of doing. He's not going to be asked to do
anything special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the question becomes, Does he want to spend his whole life
being a secondary player? Is he happy with that? I don't know.
Those are issues he has to face. From what I've seen, Hakeem is
still the franchise player. If Scottie does what he did in Chicago,
they'll be in great shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Drexler hopes the same can be said of the Rockets when the
abbreviated season is finally finished. Because of the lockout, the
league is putting together a compressed schedule to squeeze 50
games into three months, which Drexler feels will be a challenge to
veteran-laden teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets fall into that category since they will feature
Olajuwon, 36; Barkley, 35; Pippen, 33; and Eddie Johnson, 39, all
of whom had surgery last season or during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question whenever you have a bunch of veterans like
Charles and Hakeem, and I'm just assuming they're going to re-sign
Charles, the question is that when they play three games in a row,
are they going to keep guys healthy?'' Drexler said. ``It's tough
enough to play two in a row, but now when you start talking about
playing three straight in a season where guys aren't really
healthy, that's when the veteran teams could get hurt. A format
such as this, where you have a lot of games in a short number of
days, hurts those veteran teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish them all the best,'' Drexler added. ``I'll be going to
a few of the games, but I'm just a casual fan right now. I have
worries of my own right here, but I wish them well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
