<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCSEC-ECONSCENE-NYT &LR;      01-20 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS NEW GOVERNMENT ROLE IN SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's proposal to shore up the financially shaky
Social Security system leans heavily on a leading Republican plan.
He would grab trillions of dollars of general tax revenues and
invest at least some of it in the stock market. The plan is
attractive since neither Clinton nor the Republicans would need to
propose higher payroll taxes or reductions in retirement benefits.
On this feature, Democrats and Republicans easily agree.
</P>
<P>
   But under Clinton's plan, the government would own stocks. The
leading Republican plan, proposed by Martin Feldstein of Harvard
and backed by Sen. Phil Gramm and others on Capitol Hill, would
turn the general revenue over to individuals for deposit into their
own investment accounts. Therein lie profound political and
financial differences.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement of the baby boomers early next century combined
with their increased longevity will throw Social Security into
deficit. The administration proposes to balance the books by
tapping future federal surpluses that it expects will total about
$4.5 trillion over the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aims to pump about $3 trillion of that amount into the
trust fund. About $650 billion of the $3 trillion would would be
invested in stocks. Under current law, the entire trust fund is
invested in low-yielding government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of new revenue and high return on stock
investments is expected to generate enough new revenue to eliminate
deficits in the program for the next 50 years or so.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal has the political virtue of closing the deficit in
Social Security without cutting retirement benefits. And by
preserving the central feature of the current system _ paying
benefits entirely out of public funds _ the proposal avoids certain
pitfalls of private accounts. The plan would pay retirees a benefit
based on their lifelong earnings, not on the vagaries of stock- and
bond-market returns.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would preserve the ability to transfer money from high-
to low-paid workers. And the costs of administering a single public
fund are very low compared with those of setting up 150 million
individual accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan solves these financial problems by creating a
severe political problem. The administration estimates that
government would come to own 4 percent to 5 percent of the value of
shares on Wall Street. The danger is that Congress would meddle,
for example steering federal dollars into environmentally friendly
companies rather than tobacco companies, which were a target of
Clinton's speech on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Alan Greenspan of the Federal Reserve Board added his
weight to the critics on Wednesday. ``I do not believe that it is
politically feasible to insulate such huge funds from government
direction,'' he told the committee. ``I am fearful that we would
use those assets in a way that would create a lower rate of return
for Social Security recipients.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Boskin, President Bush's chief economist, shares
Greenspan's concern and rejects the Clinton plan as ``politically
naive.'' He said, ``Congress will simply not stand by and let huge
surpluses accumulate without spending them. Congress is much less
likely to tamper with private accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists point out that investing security revenue in stocks
would not in itself affect the nation's saving rate or raise future
living standards. It would merely shuffle stock out of accounts of
private investors and into a public account.
</P>
<P>
   But, as a recent report from the National Association of Social
Insurance pointed out, the shuffle would still have an important
impact. Wealthy families, the report observes, need not care if the
public trust fund invests their payroll contributions in stocks,
because they can invest their private savings in stocks, reaping
the high rate of return that stocks have historically yielded.
</P>
<P>
   Most families, however, save and invest very little. The only
way their retirement income can reflect the value of investing in
stocks is if the government does the investing for them. Clinton's
proposal to invest some of the trust fund in stocks would bring the
benefit of stock investing to a larger number of American families.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the financial merits, the administration is left
with Greenspan's political demerit. Here the administration has a
plausible response provided by two economists at the Brookings
Institution. Henry Aaron and Robert Reischauer, a former director
of the Congressional Budget Office, outline safeguards that they
say would insulate stock purchases from political interference.
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea is to create a board that would turn the Social
Security money over to private managers of widely diversified
mutual funds. No government official would have any say over actual
purchase decisions. Boskin remains unconvinced. Congress can build
whatever fire walls Aaron and Reischauer want, he said, ``but in
the end Congress can tear them down.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton's Social Security plan was proposed in the context of
a larger budget plan that places other claims on future surpluses.
About $500 billion of the $4.5 trillion would be used to help
create individual retirement accounts that would be separate from
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The White House envisions contributing, say, $100 into accounts
for low- and middle-income families. Families that add more would
have their contributions partially matched by government.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious purpose behind the idea is to encourage families to
save more for retirement, the best way to boost future living
standards. But the administration also wants to use these
individual accounts to blunt the Republicans' fervor for setting up
private accounts as part of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The virtue of separate accounts, it believes, is that they would
not provide a ready excuse for cutting benefits under the Social
Security program, or lead to a cascading momentum to steer Social
Security increasingly away from a public plan to a private plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
