<HEADLINE>
KENNY WALLACE WANTS ON-TRACK HEADLINES IN '99
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kenny Wallace racked up his 15 minutes of fame last year with a
flippant remark about water and Turn 1 and Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   He can laugh about it now, and Wallace was doing exactly that
during the annual Charlotte Motor Speedway Media Tour last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said there was a lot of water gushing out of Turn 1 at
Texas,'' said Wallace, recalling an interview at Bristol Motor
Speedway that appeared in the ``Star-Telegram'' the Sunday before
the Texas 500 in Fort Worth. ``And of course, \RTMS owner\S Bruton
Smith and \RTMS general manager\S Eddie Gossage heard it and I
became the bad guy real quick. I called up and apologized that I
was sorry there was water gushing out of Turn 1. And Bruton chewed
my butt out, big-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny Wallace's tendency is to have shoelaces hanging out of
his mouth. But when the water came out and they canceled
\Rfirst-round\S qualifying, I just kind of walked back to my
motorhome.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, Smith and Gossage since have hissed and made up. And
Wallace is attempting to reinvent his so-called career. The younger
brother of 1989 Cup champion Rusty Wallace, Kenny Wallace believes
his alliance with longtime buddy Ken Schrader and team owner Andy
Petree will allow him to make headlines on the racetrack in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That would be different. Because the only stat Wallace led the
Winston Cup Series in during 1998 was the dubious category of DNFs.
Wallace logged a distressing 13 ``Did Not Finish'' results behind
the wheel of the No. 81 Square D Ford Taurus owned by Filbert
Martocci. Nobody grenaded engines with the panache of Wallace, who
announced in midseason that he and his primary sponsor planned to
join Petree's single-car Chevrolet Monte Carlo stable in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go on record that I don't have as much fun as I used
to,'' said Wallace, 35, whose highest finish last year was sixth at
the second New Hampshire International Speedway event. ``And I
think I see Mark Martin's and Rusty's point. They tell me how
miserable they are. Now I think I get it. To run up front, you have
to be a little bit ornery to get what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any ``little brother,'' Kenny Wallace wants to match his
brother's 15 minutes of fame on the racetrack. Kenny's career
to-date _ zero victories, two poles, one top-five and 17 top-10s in
151 starts _ is a bad joke when compared to his big bro's 48
victories and $18.7 million in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Winston Cup racing, the given things are your wins and your
poles,'' Wallace said. ``But that's not success in Winston Cup.
Success is being very competitive every week. If you're sitting
there running fourth through 10th and you blow up, then I was
successful last year. But the bottom line is the finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace acknowledged that both he and Schrader, who has not won
a Cup race since June 1991, will have to prove they are not just
the best comedy act in the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny and myself, we know the best and worst parts about each
other already,'' said Schrader, who will return to the No. 33 Skoal
Bandit Chevy. ``I keep saying I'd give him five bucks _ but it'd
probably only be two _ if he'd keep his mouth shut for five minutes
when we're at a restaurant or something. He could never do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But forget about that I know him and really like him and
stuff. Kenny Wallace can drive the race car and he's got the right
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said he and Schrader have tremendous chemistry, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing he's not a brother, because he's been family
friends forever,'' Wallace said of his fellow Missourian.
``Schrader races for a living and so do I. We're the first ones to
lay in bed at night with our gut tore out if we don't run good.
When business is done, we're probably the first ones to cut up a
little bit. 'Course, my loud laugh draws attention, and hell, I
can't help it. It's just the way I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've been real serious this winter. The biggest pressure
is that I promised Andy Petree that I would be successful with a
new team. I'm like anybody _ I'm a man of my word.''
THE BUZZ The 358-cubic-inch Ford V-8s run by Penske-Kranefuss
teammates Rusty Wallace and Jeremy Mayfield this season will be
provided by a new supplier _ Penske Engines of Concord, N.C. The
man in charge is Larry Wallace _ no relation to Rusty _ who built
some motors for the team last year. Rusty Wallace recorded only two
DNFs during 1998, a huge improvement from the nine engine failures
he experienced in 1997. ``I'm really excited about this year and
knowing that the engine company has been formed,'' said Rusty
Wallace, who posted the hottest hot lap during winter testing at
the Daytona International Speedway at 193.129 mph on Jan. 13. Team
co-owners Michael Kranefuss and Roger Penske each own 50 percent of
the engine shop. ...
</P>
<P>
   Pennzoil has announced a one-year contract extension with
National Hot Rod Association Top Fuel driver Eddie Hill of Wichita
Falls. The deal will allow Hill, the 1993 Top Fuel champion, to run
the entire 22-race schedule that begins with the AutoZone
Winternationals at Pomona (Calif.) Raceway on Feb. 4-7. Hill, 62,
was one of just six Top Fuel drivers to qualify for every national
event in 1998. ... Houston Raceway Park in Baytown is scheduled to
play host to the NHRA's Pro Stock Superbowl Challenge on Jan. 30.
The one-day nonpoints event begins at 8 a.m., with professional
trials at 10 a.m. and noon. Eliminations are set for 1 p.m. Tickets
are $18 for adults. Children $12-and-under will be admitted for $1.
...
</P>
<P>
   Pep Boys Indy Racing League team owner John Menard has announced
plans to field a team for Robby Gordon in the rival FedEx
Championship Auto Racing Teams series this season. Menard, whose
lone IRL driver is Greg Ray of Plano, is the first owner to become
involved with both the IRL and CART series on a full-time basis
since their split after the 1995 season. Menard and partner Mike
Held, who is Gordon's business manager, will field Gordon in a
Toyota-powered Swift for the 20-race CART schedule. Gordon also
will be Ray's teammate at the IRL-sanctioned 83rd Indianapolis 500
in May. ...
</P>
<P>
   Galles Racing and driver Davey Hamilton submitted a last-minute
entry on Jan. 14 for Sunday's IRL season opener at Walt Disney
World Speedway. Team owner Rick Galles originally planned to skip
the race to search for corporate sponsorship. ``We are still
searching for a major sponsor,'' Galles said. ``But we feel that
it's important to run Orlando and collect points and show support
for the series.'' Hamilton, who finished second to champion Kenny
Brack last year, will stand as the only driver to start in all 25
IRL events if he qualifies at the 1-mile oval. Hamilton shares that
distinction with former IRL champion Tony Stewart and two-time Indy
500 winner Arie Luyendyk, neither of whom is scheduled to run at
``The Mickyard.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   The Joliet (Ill.) City Council has approved plans to add a
1.5-mile oval track just north of the year-old Route 66 Raceway
drag strip. That facility drew rave reviews when it played host to
the inaugural NHRA Fram Route 66 Nationals last summer. Dale Coyne,
chief executive officer of Route 66 Raceway, has put a $100 million
price tag on the oval, which will seat approximately 75,000. And
naturally, track management already is on its knees, praying to
land a NASCAR Winston Cup race for the schedule.
LAST WORDS ``''I'm a Kyle Petty clone _ without the ear rings. I
can grow a ponytail, but the ear rings is out.''''
</P>
<P>
   _ NASCAR legend Richard Petty, sporting a goatee to match that
of his son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
