<HEADER>
A1740 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-T     01-20 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS RALLY TO CLINTON AFTER DEFENSE PRESENTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Democrats rallied to President Clinton's
defense Wednesday after White House lawyers launched a
point-by-point attack on the impeachment case against him.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling that they are ready to close ranks, several Democrats
said the White House presentation marked a turning point in the
Senate trial that will determine Clinton's fate. Their outspoken
support for Clinton is another sign that opinions are hardening
along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the last chapter is written on this entire impeachment
trial, I suspect that this day will be remembered as the beginning
of the end,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. ``Under no
circumstances is there going to be a vote of conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors dismissed the White House rebuttal as a
``Swiss cheese'' defense _ full of holes. But some Senate
Republicans acknowledged that White House lawyers did a good job in
arguing that Clinton should be allowed to finish his final two
years in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young lady at the end was very powerful,'' said Sen.
Robert Bennett, R-Utah, referring to deputy counsel Cheryl Mills.
``I think we made a mistake in not allowing for a rebuttal period
for the House managers.''
</P>
<P>
   Religious broadcaster Pat Robertson, one of Clinton's harshest
critics, contributed to the sense that momentum had shifted in the
president's direction by declaring the impeachment battle over.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a public relations standpoint, he's won ... Clinton's
won,'' Robertson said on his 700 Club program. ``They might as well
dismiss this impeachment hearing and get on with something else,
because it's over as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said Mills' summation left some
Democrats on the verge of tears. The 33-year-old lawyer, the only
woman and the only African American on either legal team, concluded
her presentation by defending Clinton's civil rights record.
</P>
<P>
   In calling for the president's ouster last week, House
prosecutors said his deceptions in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment case were, in effect, an assault on Jones' civil rights.
The president has acknowledged that he tried to hide his affair
with Monica Lewinsky from Jones and her lawyers, who felt that the
information would help their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand here before you today because Bill Clinton believed I
could stand here for him,'' Mills told the Senate. ``You should
acquit him on this record. And you must not let imagined harms to
the house of civil rights persuade you otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bulk of the White House presentation focused on the
details of impeachment articles accusing the president of perjury
and obstruction of justice. Clinton's lawyers said prosecutors
strained to find criminal intent in the understandable actions of a
man trying to ``protect himself and his family from embarrassment,
even destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Special counsel Gregory Craig attacked the perjury allegations
as trivial, baseless and vastly overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you convict and remove President Clinton on the basis of
these allegations, no president of the United States will ever be
safe from impeachment again,'' he told the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said the perjury allegations boil down to ``a classic
oath-on-oath, he-says-she-says, swearing match'' that would never
hold up in court. The illicit relationship exploded into a scandal
a year ago Wednesday with a story in The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Although Craig acknowledged that Clinton's sworn statement in
the Jones case was maddeningly evasive, he reminded senators that
the House rejected an impeachment article based on the civil suit.
Even some of Clinton's staunchest defenders have said that they
think he lied in the Jones case, which was later dismissed and
settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment article approved by the House is based on
Clinton's Aug. 17 testimony to a federal grand jury, when the
president admitted what he called an ``inappropriate intimate''
relationship with the former White House intern. In a reversal from
his previous testimony, Clinton also acknowledged that he had been
alone with Lewinsky on various occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you believe that the president crossed the line in his
Jones deposition, you cannot conclude that he should be removed for
it,'' Craig told the Senate. ``This case is about the grand jury
and the grand jury only.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills was equally scornful in challenging allegations that
Clinton obstructed justice by tampering with witnesses and trying
to hide evidence linking him to Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president had a relationship with a young woman. ... He
ended it not because he thought it would place him in legal
jeopardy. He ended it because he knew it was wrong. That is not
obstruction of justice,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to specifics, she said Clinton's secretary, Betty
Currie, helped Lewinsky hide gifts that Clinton had given her
without telling the president. She said Currie was motivated by
``motherly affection'' for Lewinsky, who feared that Jones' lawyers
would subpoena the trinkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Currie had no idea the gifts were under subpoena. And so
Miss Lewinsky's request hardly struck her as criminal,'' Mills
said.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors said Mills' account conflicts with Lewinsky's
testimony and demonstrates the need to call Currie and Lewinsky
before the Senate as witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the lawyers say is not evidence. It is just the opinion
of lawyers,'' said Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The White House will conclude its three-day presentation
Thursday with closing arguments from attorney David Kendall and
former Sen. Dale Bumpers of Arkansas. Senators will then have two
days to ask questions of both sides before opening deliberations on
the next step in the trial Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hutcheson, (202) 383-6101
</P>
<P>
   rhutcheson &LR; krwashington.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
