<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1743 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TOUR-SPI &LR;      01-20 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEW FROM TV CRITICS' TOUR: TRASH THE NEWSMAGS, ADD MORE
ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ As dozens of cable channels scramble in these
final days of the winter press tour to impress (the critics) and
impeach (the viability of the commercial networks), it may be
worthwhile to remember the words of Dick Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Wolf always says something interesting at these
California conclaves. For another, he's been around long enough to
know what he's talking about.
</P>
<P>
   At a session to promote the 200th episode of his riveting series
``Law &AMP; Order,'' slated to air May 5, Wolf was easily persuaded to
talk about other things, such as network programming strategy as it
pertains to the attraction and retention of viewers.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that, on Sunday, Nov. 8, the four major networks
grabbed 68 percent of the television-viewing audience in prime time
_ a noteworthy achievement in light of all the hand-wringing over
the erosion of viewership from network to cable. (One of the shows
airing that night was Wolf's ``Exiled,'' a TV movie based loosely
on ``Law &AMP; Order.'')
</P>
<P>
   On bad days, of which there are many lately, the Big Four share
less than 50 percent of the viewing public.
</P>
<P>
   If Wolf were running the networks, his response to this downward
spiral would be a simple _ and maybe simplistic _ brave new world.
He would trash the newsmagazines and put on some more
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a viewer,'' Wolf said, ``I don't know why I would be that
loyal to a network that has a great deal of news on it when it's
available in so many other places. ... The economics are kind of
self-fulfilling. If you give people an excuse not to watch the
networks, they won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf made his remarks the day after CBS unveiled its new
Wednesday version of ``60 Minutes.'' That brought to 12 the number
of newsmagazines now airing on the networks (five ``Dateline
NBCs,'' three ``20/20s,'' two ``60 Minutes,'' one ``48 Hours'' and
one ``Fox Files''). It's a number that has more or less held steady
for the past few seasons, but Wolf thinks it's completely out of
whack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The median age of a `60 Minutes' viewer is 62,'' Wolf said.
``This is not how you go to franchise products over the long term.
I think it really is a poison pill and I would love to see more
dramas on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   So would I, but most broadcasters want to be just that:
broad-casters.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Jamie Kellner at The WB, who enjoys
narrowcasting to a lucrative demographic with such youthful fare as
``Felicity'' and ``Dawson's Creek,'' every other programming
executive at the commercial networks believes in reaching the
widest possible audience with a balanced lineup. That means dramas
and comedies, movies and specials, news and newsmagazines, and,
sadly, even ``reality'' programming like ``World's Wildest Police
Videos.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf's point about the newsmagazines, of course, is that the
balance is way off, and he's probably right. Just this week,
``Dateline'' wasted an entire show on a jewelry-theft story that
could have been _ should have been _ reported in 10 minutes, tops.
It was journalistic padding of the worst kind, and it led the
viewer to conclude that ``Dateline'' doesn't have enough stories to
cover five nights, so it inflated the importance of a 10-minute
segment to fill an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is on target when he says such newsmagazine bloat will send
viewers scurrying.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sassa, the new president of NBC Entertainment, probably
agrees, but he'd never say so in public. Instead, his answer to the
question about the proliferation of newsmagazines is appropriately
diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has always been some form of programming that was not a
sitcom or a drama that filled the schedule of networks,'' Sassa
said. ``Whether it was game shows or variety shows, there was
always something (else) out there.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether he'd like to see more or fewer ``Datelines,''
Sassa is coy. ``We view `Dateline' as a tremendous asset in the
entertainment division. It's a great brand that's been built. ...
Our job is to find the schedule that gets the highest ratings in
the highest demographic categories with whatever programming we
have available to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, we may all be complaining less about newsmagazines
and more about animation in a few months. Most of Fox's comedies
will soon be of the animated variety, and The WB and UPN will be
getting into the game as well. First out of the gate was Eddie
Murphy's ``The PJs'' on Fox. Next will be ``Dilbert,'' premiering
Monday on UPN.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, it's the way the networks do things. If one is
good, one dozen must be be better. It may be annoying, but, as
Sassa points out, the networks retain a huge advantage over cable.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they're not pulling in as many viewers as they did 10
years ago, a quality show like ``ER,'' the most-watched drama on
network TV, still attracts 12 times as many viewers as the
most-watched drama on cable, ``Pacific Blue'' (an average of 27.8
million viewers vs. 2.3 million). Moreover, Sassa said, the
least-watched drama on the Big Four, Fox's ``Brimstone,'' pulls in
twice as many viewers as ``Pacific Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that ``Pacific Blue'' is dreadful, and that
most network fare is considerably better.
</P>
<P>
   But what's most encouraging about this press tour is the sense
that network executives finally believe that allowing these shows
to build an audience is preferable to canceling them after six
episodes because of small initial audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Networks are the only beachfront, Class-A real estate out
there,'' said Sassa, who spent a decade at Turner Broadcasting
before joining NBC in 1997. ``While I was at Turner, the whole time
we were there we were trying to buy a network, start a network or
merge with a network.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as the broadcast networks factor quality into their
quest for balance, their best shows should have a long stay at the
beach. And, as far as this midseason's entries go, keep an eye on:
``It's Like, You Know ...'' (March, ABC); ``Family Guy'' (March,
Fox); ``The PJs'' (Tuesdays, Fox); ``The Sopranos'' (Sundays, HBO);
``Strange World'' (TBA, ABC); ``Futurama'' (March, Fox) and
``Turks'' (Thursdays, CBS).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
