u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEOFUNION-CLINTON-     01-20 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON EXPOUNDS ON STATE OF UNION THEMES BEFORE ENTHUSIASTIC
CROWDS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: STATEOFUNION-SURPLUS, STATEOFUNION-VOICES,
STATEOFUNION-REPUBS, STATEOFUNION-GREENSPAN, STATEOFUNION-BUFFALO,
STATEOFUNION-CHICAGO, STATEOFUNION-TOBACCO.) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORRISTOWN, Pa. _ An exuberant President Clinton starred in two
foot-stomping rallies on Wednesday, where he amplified the themes
of his State of the Union address and attacked Republican proposals
for across-the-board tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, accompanied by Vice President Al Gore, First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Tipper Gore, received a rock idol's
reception at the Marine Midland Arena in Buffalo on Wednesday
afternoon, where 21,000 residents of western New York waited for
hours amid roof-high snowbanks to enter the hockey arena to see
him.
</P>
<P>
   The president has attended few such mass events over the past
year of scandal and investigation, and he was rewarded with a
rapturous response, after the crowd had heard more than an hour of
introductions from local dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton fairly glowed as speaker after speaker praised his good
works and glossed over his legal and political problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Bennett W. Smith, in an invocation, said that Clinton
has been ``the greatest president for our people of all time.'' He
called on the Lord to ``comfort him with Your word, that no weapon
formed against him shall prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton got a huge ovation when she rose to introduce her
husband. Several in the crowd held signs boosting her imagined
candidacy for the U.S. Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who appeared energized by the crowd, bellowed, ``We can
have the future we deserve because we already have the president we
deserve!''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said that the State of the Union marked a
turning point for the country and called on the huge audience to
help fight for the president's expansive policy agenda. The crowd
rose to its feet and roared.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Clinton made a swing through the Midwest after his
State of the Union speech , and the year before that he went south.
This year, aides said, he wanted to visit the Northeast. Further,
Clinton told his staff that he wanted to go to Buffalo because he
had not paid a visit there since 1996, when he did little more than
arrive at the airport before heading into seclusion to prepare for
an election debate with his opponent, Robert Dole.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House saw a further benefit to picking these
spots, Clinton aides acknowledged. As relatively small communities
that rarely receive presidential visits, they were more likely to
respond to the appeals of advance staff for big crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could hardly match the passion the preacher and the vice
president. He noted that he and Gore had taken the oath of office
for the first time six years ago on Wednesday and marveled at how
quickly the years had passed. ``They have been, to put it mildly,
eventful.''
</P>
<P>
   But policy, not nostalgia, was on his mind on Wednesday. So he
delivered a half-hour dissertation on the aging of America and the
importance of shoring up Social Security and Medicare for the baby
boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   He said that today's prosperity must be used to ensure a
financially secure future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot afford to squander this moment,'' the president
said. ``We have to make the most of it. We have to look at the
long-term challenges facing America.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeated his plan for reserving a large portion of the
federal budget surplus for Social Security and Medicare and argued
strenuously against Republican proposals to use the money for tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But 20 minutes into his remarks, people began pouring out of the
arena, an unusual spectacle at a presidential event.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who stayed were Tom O'Sullivan and his 8-year-old
son, Kevin. O'Sullivan, 39, an auto worker, said he came to show
support for Clinton. ``I think he's done a good job. And there's
not too many chances to see a living president.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan, who builds axles for light trucks, said the United
Auto Workers urged its members in the Buffalo area to attend the
rally. But he said he would have come anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky was
wrong, but that Republicans have gone overboard in bringing him to
the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with what he's done,'' O'Sullivan said, ``but
they should have censured him and been done with it. What people
fail to take into account was that we all have our faults. How many
people in the House and Senate did the same thing as he did and
just didn't get caught. Man's just trying to save his marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the overwhelmingly pro-Clinton crowd, Diana
Gaglia, 61, took a half-day of vacation time from her job at a
denture plant to attend the rally to show her support for the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he's being ostracized because of that stupid Linda
Tripp,'' Mrs. Gaglia said. ``I also feel, find me a man who hasn't
had an indiscretion. He didn't do right, but we shouldn't be put
through all this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
