<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALLY AN OLD FOSSIL, BUT NOT FEELING THAT WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now I have a greater appreciation for why my Uncle Jim was so
sensitive about the use of the word ``elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Jim, I need to explain, was managing editor of the
``Star-Telegram'' for more than 40 years. That in itself was
remarkable. I don't think anyone could take the pressure of that
job for that many years today.
</P>
<P>
   James Robert Record was a formal man. He ceased to be ``Uncle
Jim'' from the moment I went to work for the newspaper as a copy
boy on July 3, 1944. For the rest of my life, I always addressed
him as ``Mr. Record.''
</P>
<P>
   He also was ``Mr. Record'' to two other nephews who worked for
the newspaper: my brother, Tony, and my cousin Phil North.
</P>
<P>
   My dear mother could never understand why we couldn't address
him as ``Uncle Jim'' at family gatherings. If you had worked for
James R. Record, you would have understood.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Record (I still feel much more comfortable referring to him
that way, even though he has been dead for more than two decades)
could get agitated when a reporter referred to anyone near his age
as ``old'' or ``elderly.'' The reporter or his/her supervisor was
likely to get a memo reading: ``Hardly appropriate. JRR.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Record never considered himself to be old or elderly. Many
of us who worked for him did, but he was the man who called the
shots.
</P>
<P>
   To be safe, staff members adopted an unwritten rule to use the
words ``old'' or ``elderly'' only to describe those who were at
least five years older than Mr. Record. He didn't know about this
rule, of course.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. We wouldn't be chastised if we followed the unwritten
rule.
</P>
<P>
   I said I had a greater appreciation for Mr. Record's
sensitivity. That's because I turned 70 last week.
</P>
<P>
   I certainly don't feel ``old.'' Nor do I feel ``elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't even feel like an ``old fossil,'' although that is the
way my oldest son, Chris, described me in an invitation he prepared
for a gathering to mark the end of my seventh decade.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation read, ``Phil Record is officially an old
fossil.'' I promise you, he would never have written that had he
been the son of James R. Record.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure some of those young whippersnappers down at the
newspaper probably had some age rule they applied to me before I
retired as ombudsman a year ago. That's OK. To anyone in their 20s
or 30s, someone over 50 is ancient.
</P>
<P>
   I've truly been blessed during the past 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't have had better parents. I endured the ups and downs
of newspapering with colleagues whose dedication to serving the
public frequently went unrecognized and unappreciated. I have been
accompanied to the mountaintops and the valleys of life with
supportive friends deserving of the title ``beloved.''
</P>
<P>
   And I have reached that stage when I realize that many of the
travails of life have in fact been blessings.
</P>
<P>
   I have stated previously in this space how much I admire the
renowned spiritual author Henri Nouwen. I begin each day reading
from his book ``Bread for the Journey.''
</P>
<P>
   He had some interesting words for me on my 70th birthday:
</P>
<P>
   ``... to be grateful for all of our lives _ the good as well as
the bad, the moments of joy as well as the moments of sorrow, the
successes as well as the failures, the rewards as well as the
rejections _ that requires hard spiritual work. Still we are only
truly grateful people when we can say thank you to all that has
brought us to the present moment. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not be afraid to look at everything that has brought us
to where we are now and trust that we will soon see in it the
guiding hand of a loving God.''
</P>
<P>
   Too many who have reached my age have been cast aside _
especially by businesses _ as being of little value. That was not
my lot at this newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   When I decided it was time to retire a year ago, Publisher Wes
Turner and Executive Editor Jim Witt said they wanted me to
maintain ties to the paper as a consultant and columnist. I now
realize that to have completely cut my ties to the newspaper after
an association of more than half a century would have been
devastating.
</P>
<P>
   And now another blessing from that ``guiding hand from a loving
God'': This week I begin a new career.
</P>
<P>
   I am joining the faculty of the Journalism Department at Texas
Christian University, thanks to department Chairman Anantha Babbili
and his colleagues, as a teacher of ethics and a coach of writing.
</P>
<P>
   What an exciting venture for one entering his eighth decade.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure I will be sharing some of this new adventure with you
in future columns.
</P>
<P>
   Retired ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to the
Star-Telegram. He can be contacted at precord &LR; star-telegram.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
