<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1748 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRMA-P.HALL-TEX     01-20 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRMA-P. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS-BORN ACTRESS LOSES HERSELF IN CHARACTERS
</HEADLINE>
 HALL-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because she's so adept at character acting, to speak with the
real Irma P. Hall is a bit odd. It's almost hard to believe she
exists.
</P>
<P>
   Had this been a meeting with Minerva, the voodoo priestess from
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' or Big Mama from ``Soul
Food,'' it would have been different.
</P>
<P>
   Those are people one can identify. Irma P. Hall isn't. And
that's exactly how she wants it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I know to work is to get into character as quick
as I can,'' she says. ``As soon as I find enough about the
character for me to assume it, I stick my feet in and I stay there
for the duration of the project.''
</P>
<P>
   She so embodies her characters that her macho, weight-lifter son
cried when Big Mama died in ``Soul Food.'' ``I cried, too,'' says
Hall, a woman who speaks in italics. ``Because it wasn't `me.' I
cried when `that lady' died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm Lena,'' she says, referring to her role in the
Dallas Theater Center's production of ``A Raisin in the Sun.'' ``I
mean, I know I'm Irma P. Hall, but not right now. I'm Lena.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall was born in Beaumont and grew up in Chicago. She returned
to Texas and attended Texas College in Tyler. She taught in Dallas
at Booker T. Washington, James Madison, T.W. Brown and Zumwalt
Sarah schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother said that when I was a kid, as soon as I'd learn
something, I'd run out to show someone else. They knew I'd be a
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be a buyer for Marshall Field's. I wanted to
travel all over the world, picking out fashions and bringing them
back,'' Hall says with a sense of marvel that often fills her deep,
dark eyes.
</P>
<P>
   She was a precocious child with a curiosity that has carried her
through life. Her love for learning and doing new things led her to
volunteer as a writer for the struggling minority newspaper The
Dallas Express. Before she knew it, she was the black culture page
editor and the sports editor.
</P>
<P>
   And this is when her life changed course. In 1971, she wrote an
article about actor/director Raymond St. Jacques, who was going to
film ``The Book of Numbers'' in Dallas. He was so pleased with the
story that he asked her to be his interim publicist and to audition
for a role in the film.
</P>
<P>
   She landed a supporting role, and it was just the fuel she
needed for her future career. She soon co-founded the Dallas
Minority Repertory Theater, thinking her only role would be fund
raising. Her title, however, was executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was plunged into it,'' she says. ``I had to learn to act,
write, hang lights, run lights, run sound, make costumes ...
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Her stage debut was in the play ``Happy Endings.'' During the
next decade, she balanced her teaching and acting, trying to give
each equal time. In 1984, she decided to devote herself fully to
acting, and three years later, she moved to assist her ailing
mother in Chicago, where she now resides.
</P>
<P>
   So, how does a schoolteacher just get up and immerse herself in
the flighty world of acting _ especially during midlife and with
two grown children? For Hall, it all came easily.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that her parents _ her father was a musician who
played regular gigs at Chicago's infamous Rhumboogie Club, her
mother a hospital admissions clerk _ reared their only child on the
arts and letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my home, someone was always quoting something,'' she says.
``I was in third grade when I first heard my father quote `Above
all, to thine own self be true' (from Shakespeare's ``Hamlet).''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew that Shakespeare was supposed to be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, delving into the theater without any knowledge of its
machinery is not easy. ``When I started, I didn't know upstage from
outdoors,'' she says with a chuckle. ``Plus, being ambidextrous, I
don't think of things as left and right. But I've learned a lot,
and am still learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was doing `Funny Girl' with Carol Lawrence at Dallas
Summer Musicals, the stage manager said, `Watch out for the scrims'
(the opaque backdrop used in theaters),'' she says. ``I had no idea
what a scrim was, so I just made a big wide circle around
everything to make sure I missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her big film break came with Richard Pearce's 1996 film ``A
Family Thing,'' in which she co-starred with Robert Duvall and
James Earl Jones. Her role as the blind, peppery Aunt T earned her
a Best Supporting Actress award from the Chicago Film Critics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, she appeared in five films: ``Midnight in the Garden of
Good and Evil,'' ``Soul Food,'' ``Nothing to Lose,'' ``Steel'' and
``Buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was a role in the Oprah Winfrey/Jonathan Demme
movie ``Beloved,'' and the role of Joletta, the lovable nurse who
falls for Patch Adams' unorthodox medical philosophy. She also
released a self-published poetry anthology, ``I Can Deal With Black
and Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   She has performed in Lorraine Hansberry's American classic ``A
Raisin in the Sun'' several times, first playing Ruth and later
Lena, or Mama, the matriarch who holds the Younger family together.
She said she jumped at the chance to reprise the role of Lena at
the Dallas Theater Center.
</P>
<P>
   At 63, Hall isn't shying away from new ventures. She next wants
to tackle cinematography, having long had an interest in
photography.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as her acting goes, she doesn't know _ or worry about
_ what's next. ``When I wake up in the morning and say my prayers,
I say, ``Give us `this' day. And at the end of the day I say `Thank
you.'
</P>
<P>
   Film ``is a nebulous thing _ `chicken and feathers' I call it.
Chicken one day and feathers the next. I'm surprised my chicken is
still here.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several ideas in her head. Her dream is to play the
yet-unborn role of her personal hero, Mary McLeod Bethune, founder
of Bethune-Cookman College in Daytona Beach, Fla., and a friend of
Eleanor Roosevelt. ``I have put that (idea) out there in the
universe,'' she says furtively.
</P>
<P>
   She also makes no bones about whom she'd like to work with next:
``Don't you think I look like Whoopi Goldberg's mother?''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's her fantasy stage role. ``This is a far-fetched
thing, but I've always thought that a woman could play
Mephistopheles in `Faust,''' she says, thrusting her hands forward
and giving her fingers a mischievous wiggle. ``I could just see me
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering how Hall becomes the character she's playing at the
moment, that's a chilling thought.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
