<HEADER>
A1750 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANHEUSERBUSCH-AD-COLU     01-20 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANHEUSERBUSCH-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANHEUSER-BUSCH PREPARES NEW ICONS FOR THE SUPER BOWL  
 MILLER DUMPS DICK 
 (DW) 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mo., Minn., Calif., Ill., Texas)  By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like a tavern owner who feels expansive enough to buy
the house a round of drinks, Anheuser-Busch Inc. is spending a
record sum on the most commercial time it has ever bought during a
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch, the beer division of the Anheuser-Busch
Companies in St. Louis, has long been a mainstay Super Bowl
marketer, most notably with campaigns centered on mock football
games known as the Bud Bowl. For Super Bowl XXXIII, which the Fox
Broadcasting Company will show on Jan. 31, Anheuser-Busch, the sole
beer sponsor, plans to run 9 spots during 5 minutes and 15 seconds
of commercial time _ the most by far for any advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch executives outlined their extensive and expensive
Super Bowl strategy at a news conference Wednesday in Manhattan.
The Super Sunday spots will likely mark the beginning of the end
for the popular Budweiser beer campaign about talking frogs and
lizards, the executives disclosed, which may conclude in 6 to 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   As if not to be outdone, Anheuser-Busch's main rival, the Miller
Brewing Company in Milwaukee, made a surprising announcement of its
own later in the day: Fallon McElligott &UR;  &LR;  in Minneapolis, the
incumbent on the flagship Miller beer brand account, Miller Lite,
will keep the creative assignment _ with billings estimated at $150
million _ after a grueling two-month review that pitted the agency
against three other finalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Anheuser-Busch ad blitz for the Super Bowl comes as that
company, the world's largest brewer, celebrates 1998 as its best
sales year ever. Anheuser-Busch gained market share in an industry
that was otherwise flat to down as beer drinkers switched from
competitive brands and the so-called microbrew fad faded. Results
were paced by Bud Light, which outsells Miller Lite, with annual
sales increasing by a double-digit percentage for the sixth
consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a tremendous year,'' said Bob Lachky, vice president
for brand management at Anheuser-Busch, adding that an estimated
sales increase of 4 percent for all brands was ``our best since the
early 90's.''
</P>
<P>
   While Budweiser, the Anheuser-Busch flagship brand, suffered
another sales decline, falling about 2.6 percent, ``we expect to
turn that around this year,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has Anheuser-Busch, it seems, felt more positive about the
Super Bowl, regardless of which teams face each other in what has
become an annual midwinter festival of pigskin, parties and
pitching (not necessarily in that order).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Super Bowl is the No. 1-rated TV show every year,'' Lachky
said, ``with 60 percent more households tuned in than for another
comparable big event, the Academy Awards'' and tens of millions of
``beer drinkers, primarily men, primarily 21 to 34 and above.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest audience we can reach at one time,'' he
added, ``and that's why we're there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a unit of News Corp., is charging a record average of $1.6
million for each 30 seconds of commercial time during the game.
Trade publications reported that Anheuser-Busch paid more _ perhaps
as much as $2 million for each 30 seconds _ to guarantee
exclusivity in the beer category.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pricey,'' Lachky said, ``but it's not too much money when
you're the leader in your industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch has been the exclusive Super Bowl beer peddler
since Bud Bowl I in 1989. ``We don't intend to ever give it up,''
Lachky asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Back in St. Louis, his boss, August A. Busch IV, vice president
for marketing, announced that Anheuser-Busch had secured the beer
category exclusivity for three additional years by signing
agreements with the ABC unit of the Walt Disney &UR;  &LR;  Company for 2000,
the CBS unit of the CBS &UR;  &LR; Corp. for 2001 and Fox for 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Lachky and David English, group vice president for premium
brands at Anheuser-Busch, showed reporters finished and rough
versions of commercials being considered for the nine Super Bowl
slots.
</P>
<P>
   Two spots definitely in the lineup are new installments in the
Budweiser swamp-creature saga created by Goodby, Silverstein &AMP;
Partners in San Francisco, a unit of the Omnicom Group. In the
first spot, Louie the lizard tells the three croaking frogs they
all are ``canned,'' which causes the frogs to utter words other
than ``Bud-weis-er'' for the first time. In the second spot, the
frogs administer a tongue-lashing _ literally and figuratively _ to
Louie.
</P>
<P>
   The phasing out of the characters is attributable to a belief
that ``the lifetime of our icons is about two years,'' Lachky said,
rather than to widespread complaints by advocacy organizations that
they appeal to children.
</P>
<P>
   Four other Budweiser spots being considered for the game are by
DDB Needham Chicago, also part of Omnicom, as are two of three
commercials being considered for Bud Light; the third is by Fusion
Idealab &UR;  &LR;  in Chicago. Five commercials for Michelob and Michelob
Light are also under consideration, all by the Leap Partnership in
Chicago, a unit of the Leap Group.
</P>
<P>
   The final commercial being considered, about the role parents
can play in discouraging underage drinking, is by Kupper Parker
Communications &UR;  &LR;  in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Bud Bowl, the 11th annual edition will be played on a
Web site at www.budbowl.com during half time as part of a national
promotional giveaway of electronics gear.
</P>
<P>
   MILLER DUMPS DICK &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the Miller Lite review, Susan Henderson, a
spokeswoman for the Miller unit of Philip Morris &UR;  &LR; Cos., said that
the decision to keep Fallon McElligott, the creative agency since
December 1996, came after ``a thorough and disciplined evaluation
concerning the long-term vitality and performance'' of the brand,
which included consumer research.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon McElligott will replace its current campaign for Miller,
centered on unconventional vignettes meant to appeal to consumers
ages 21 to 27, with a revamped effort scheduled to start in early
March. Ms. Henderson declined to discuss how the ads would differ
from the current work, which has been widely castigated for
nontraditional imagery and jokes about the elderly, bodily
functions and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Miller executives had originally supported the campaign, which
was initially focused on an imaginary ad man named Dick. But last
fall, the ads were broadened somewhat and wholesalers were told the
overall approach would be changed.
</P>
<P>
   The other finalists in the review, which continued through
Tuesday with last-minute meetings in New York, were Publicis &AMP; Hal
Riney in San Francisco, a unit of Publicis &UR;  &LR; S.A.; Square One &UR;  &LR;  in
Dallas, and the New York office of Wieden &AMP; Kennedy. Media duties
for all Miller brands are handled by Starcom Media Services, a unit
of the Leo Burnett &UR;  &LR;  Co. in Chicago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
