<HEADER>
A1756 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEEL21-COX     01-20 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEEL21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Steel workers protest cheap imports, lack of action by U.S.
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than 80 bus loads of angry Ohio Valley steel
workers spilled out onto the steps of the Capitol on Wednesday to
rally against cheap imported steel that has flooded American
markets and forced layoffs in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Jabbing the chilly air with placards, a mass of men and women
from Steubenville and Weirton, W.Va., protested what they consider
to be the federal government's inaction during this latest steel
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Ten thousand steel workers have lost their jobs in the last
year, and workers for Weirton Steel Corp. said they're expecting
another wave of cuts because Japan, Brazil and Russia have ignored
trade laws and dumped cheap steel in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (another layoff) does come, I'll be gone,'' said Gary
Dennis, a crane operator for Weirton Steel. ``I'm not very far from
the bottom. It gives me a lot of mental stress, the idea of going
to work and wondering whether it's going to be there tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mark Dotson, 33, tomorrow already has come. The plant
electrician has been unemployed since Weirton Steel laid off more
than 800 workers in the first week of November. Dotson held a sign
over his head that said, ``Unemployed Because of Unfair Trade!''
with a series of arrows pointing down at him.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether U.S. officials will quickly enforce existing
trade laws that prohibit dumping large volumes of inexpensive
steel.
</P>
<P>
   The chief offender is Japan, but the United States has been slow
to punish Japan because its economy is in shambles and must recover
if the larger Asian economic crisis is to be resolved, according to
a White House report on steel.
</P>
<P>
   But that report, released earlier this month, seemed only to
have enraged the steel workers at Wednesday's rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you read it and dissect it, he has done virtually nothing
for the American steel worker,'' said rally speaker Mark Glyptis,
president of the Independent Steelworkers Union at Weirton.
</P>
<P>
   The report outlines a series of efforts by the Clinton
Administration to stem the flow of import steel, but doesn't
specify any direct action against countries that violate existing
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The report says next year's budget will include $50 million to
help laid-off workers and their communities cope with the pain of
global competition.
</P>
<P>
   The workers felt the same way about Tuesday night's State of the
Union address, which included a single sentence on the steel issue.
``I have already informed the government of Japan that if that
nation's sudden surge of steel imports into our country is not
reversed, America will respond,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But for these workers, many of whom live in Steubenville and
cross the state line into Weirton to work, that's not enough. No
talking is enough. When Sen. Jay Rockefeller (D-West Virginia) told
the crowd he was threatening to introduce legislation to establish
trade quotas in steel, Dotson had only one reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do it!'' he screamed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
