<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ White House lawyers challenge the
facts and legal interpretations undergirding the impeachment case
against President Clinton, hoping to convince senators that there
is enough doubt to warrant acquittal. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-PROSECUTORS (Washington) _ Minutes after White House
lawyer Gregory Craig finished his defense of President Clinton
before the Senate, House prosecutors were in front of the
microphones trying to punch holes in the defense arguments. It's
part of a coordinated effort to shape public opinion during the
trial. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ADS (Washington) _ As the Senate weighs President
Clinton's fate, ad campaigns designed to influence lawmakers are
going into high gear. The People for the American Way kicks off
radio spots Thursday asking senators to keep Clinton in office. A
San Diego songwriter, Steve Vaus, offers ads that feature children
asking the president for advice on how to lie. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-CLINTON (Washington) _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan trashes a key part of President Clinton's Social Security
rescue plan, saying the government could damage the economy by
investing large amounts of money in the stock market. By JENNIFER
CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GOP (Washington) _ A day after Bill Clinton's State of
the Union address, some Republican governors express grudging
admiration for the impeachment-embattled president's ability to
deliver the speech that prompted high approval ratings for him in
overnight polls. By DAN FREEDMAN. (1stld-writethru already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-GERRYMANDERING (Washington) _ The Supreme Court grapples
with the question of whether North Carolina's legislature was
motivated by race or politics in creating two congressional
districts. In past rulings, the high court has said race cannot be
used as the ``predominant factor'' in drawing a voting district. By
MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RALLY (Buffalo, N.Y.) _ President Clinton asks
supporters at a raucous pep rally here to help persuade the
Republican Congress to adopt his Social Security overhaul and other
measures to aid the elderly that he outlined in his State of the
Union address Tuesday. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-PRESIDENCY (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush says
that while he has not decided whether to run for the presidency in
2000, he believes this may be his only shot at the White House.
Polls show Bush as the front-runner among Republicans. By LAURA
TOLLEY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Austin, Texas) _ Texas first lady Laura Bush
expresses reluctance at waging a national campaign as Gov. George
W. Bush inches closer to a decision on running for the presidency.
Mrs. Bush says that while she has enjoyed traveling around Texas,
the thought of doing it nationally ``is another big step.'' By R.G.
RATCLIFFE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-DELAYS (Houston) _ NASA expects an additional delay of
at least two months in Russia's scheduled late July launching of
the third component of the international space station. NASA also
discloses new problems with the Advanced X-Ray Telescope that will
delay plans for an April 8 launch on the shuttle Columbia. By MARK
CARREAU. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ Last year, the Houston Rockets had a
lineup that featured three of the NBA's 50 Greatest Players, yet
the team still limped into the playoffs as a No. 8 seed and was
ousted in the first round. This year, the Rockets again will
feature a lineup with three of the NBA's 50 Greatest Players and
three future Hall of Famers. By MICHAEL MURPHY
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BKN-LOCKOUT (Undated) _ The NBA lockout is officially over, and
NBA teams will be able to open camps starting Thursday afternoon.
By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
