<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON21-1stLEDE-COX     01-20 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON21-1stLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NOTE: Updated in 5th graph
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ President Clinton took the blueprint for the remainder
of his term on the road Wednesday and got a thunderous expression
of heartland support from the Democratic faithful in this working
class town near the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   As his lawyers rolled out day two of his defense in the Senate
impeachment trial, Clinton fled Washington for the snow-covered
fields and factories of western New York and eastern Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   In speeches in both places, Clinton asked Americans of all ages
to get behind his plan to invest $4 trillion over the next 15 years
preparing for an aging population. He took aim at Republican plans
to use much of the money for an across-the-board income tax cut,
saying the country needs to harness its current prosperity to
confront future challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot afford to squander this moment,'' Clinton told some
21,000 supporters gathered at the Marine Midland Arena, home of the
Buffalo Sabres hockey team. ''We have to make the most of it. We
have to look at the long-term challenges facing America.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, addressing some 3,500 students, teachers and parents at
the Norristown Area High School in eastern Pennsylvania, Clinton
charged grown ups in the audience to look at the young people
present, ''and ask yourself, 'Do you really want to run the risk of
squandering this surplus?'''
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address to Congress on Tuesday,
Clinton called for investing $2.7 trillion over the coming 15 years
to shore up the financially-ailing Social Security program, which
provides retirement benefits to one American in every six; some
$600 billion to help bolster Medicare, the federal health care
program for retirees; and another $500 billion to set up subsidized
savings accounts for lower-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   Those proposals, Clinton said, could be paid for out of federal
budget surpluses projected to top $4 trillion over the coming
decade and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans regard the surplus as indicative of
over-taxation, not an opportunity to increase spending. They called
for a 10 percent cut in income taxes, an idea Clinton assailed on
Wednesday in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have a big argument about this...and I hope it
will be a good debate,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned his supporters, however, against being tempted by
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I said last night is not as popular as what others can
tell you,'' Clinton said. ''Others can say 'We've got this surplus
now; I just want a big tax cut; I'll give it back to you, you'll
figure out what to do with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   He further admonished his backers to gird themselves for
arguments against government spending, saying his plan is to set
aside the projected surplus to deal with the aging of America, a
demographic shift that will begin to kick in 15 years from now,
when baby boomers begin to retire en masse.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're going to have everybody say that government doesn't
know how to spend this money,'' Clinton warned. ''Look folks,
Social Security and Medicare work. I'm not talking about spending
this money, I'm talking about saving it.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President
Al Gore and his wife Tipper, the president was greeted by
thunderous applause from the largest crowd he's addressed since his
post State of the Union speech a year ago in La Crosse, Wisc.
</P>
<P>
   The mood was more campaign rally than policy discussion, with
handmade posters endorsing Gore in 2000, and one calling on Mrs.
Clinton to seek office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary for New York Senator,'' read one sign. Clinton
directed his wife's attention to it, and she smiled broadly.
</P>
<P>
   She has not commented publicly on speculation over whether she
would run for the seat to be vacated in two years by Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. She looked positively like candidate
material, though, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There isn't _ I don't care what the weather forecasters say _
any warmer place in the United States,'' Mrs. Clinton told the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   After speeches by both Gores and both Clintons, all four shook
hands. At one point, Mrs. Clinton was handed a bouquet of fresh
roses and mums by 8-year-old Peter Narby, a third-grader from a
Buffalo suburb. Appearing genuinely moved, Mrs. Clinton leaned over
a crowd-control rail and kissed the boy on the cheek, then told
autograph seekers to ''write me at the White House and I'll write
you back.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was clearly energized by the response.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thank you for one of the great days of my presidency,'' he
said, as his lawyers _ hundreds of miles away _ argued before the
Senate to save his office.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo, though, Clinton's backers were clear about their
views on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to tell those people that the people down in the
heartland don't want the president impeached,'' said Brian Grassia,
owner of Evergreen Construction, a home remodeling and repair
business in nearby Amherst, N.Y. ''That's pretty obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoed Darlene Boykins, a Buffalo mental health therapy
assistant: ''He's done a good job, leave him alone. His private
life is his private life. That don't have anything to do with us.''
</P>
<P>
   end
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
