<HEADER>
A1773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEOFUNION-TOBACCO-     01-20 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-TOBACCO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SURPRISES ALL PARTIES IN ANNOUNCING TOBACCO SUIT
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: 2ndtake will follow in 10 minutes.) 
(See also: STATEOFUNION-CLINTON, STATEOFUNION-SURPLUS,
STATEOFUNION-VOICES, STATEOFUNION-REPUBS, STATEOFUNION-GREENSPAN,
STATEOFUNION-BUFFALO, STATEOFUNION-CHICAGO) 
(sw) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When President Clinton announced on Tuesday that the government
planned to sue cigarette makers, he shocked not only tobacco
producers but also some Justice Department officials as well as
outside lawyers who had been lobbying the government to bring such
a suit.
</P>
<P>
   Only last Thursday, Justice Department officials met with
several plaintiffs' lawyers and law professors who had been
involved in the state lawsuits against cigarette makers that ended
in settlements costing the industry $246 billion over the next 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, the lawyers and professors gave department
lawyers a 100-page document outlining the legal strategies that the
government could use to sue the industry for the recovery of
federal funds spent treating smoking-related ills.
</P>
<P>
   But participants at the meeting said in interviews on Wednesday
that Justice Department officials were undecided about what
specific legal course to pursue. Many had been caught off-guard by
the president's announcement in his State of the Union Message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was caught by surprise,'' said Richard Scruggs, a
plaintiffs' lawyer from Pascagoula, Miss., who had been meeting
with federal officials for six months in an effort to persuade them
to sue cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   The filing of a federal lawsuit against the tobacco industry is
not likely to come for months. Lawyers involved in the effort said
its aim would be to win concessions not included in the recent
settlements between the tobacco industry and the states. Those
would include measures like federal regulation of nicotine,
cigarettes' addictive component, by the Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision by the administration to pursue the tobacco
industry in the courtroom comes after months of long and
contentious debate within the Justice Department over the wisdom of
such a suit and its legal prospects. Even on Wednesday, some
government lawyers expressed anger that the president would
announced a lawsuit well in advance of its filing.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce N. Reed, Clinton's chief domestic policy adviser, said he
believed the disclosure was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case of this scale where you are assembling a team of top
lawyers to take on a formidable industry it would be impossible to
wait until the minute you are filing to make such an
announcement,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Justice Department officials had considered
the possibility of suing cigarette makers to recoup federal health
care funds. But they had also been long concerned that federal law
did not give them the clear authority to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
