<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-BOMB-NYT &LR;      01-20 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-BOMB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLOT TO BOMB U.S. CONSULATES IN INDIA IS ALLEGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The police here say they have foiled a plot
to bomb U.S. Consulates in Madras and Calcutta, with the arrest of
a Bangladeshi man and three men the police say were his
accomplices.
</P>
<P>
   A team of U.S. counter-terrorism experts arrived here Tuesday to
further investigate the case, a spokeswoman for the U.S. embassy
said Wednesday. Officials from the embassy have interviewed the
suspect, Sayed Abu Nasir, 27, who has been in Indian custody for
more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   No information was available on the other three men, Mohammed
Gulab, Mohammed Nawab and Aga Khan, who were arrested in connection
with the case in Siliguri in the Indian state of West Bengal on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're working with the police and we take it very
seriously,'' Donna Roginski, the embassy spokeswoman, said. ``How
credible it is _ that's all being looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said Wednesday at a
briefing: ``We obviously regard with grave concern, and take very
seriously, any threats to our personnel, both American and Indian.
With respect to the question of involvement of other intelligence
services, Indian authorities are continuing their investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indian police did not make clear who it was they thought
might be behind any plots against U.S. targets.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. intelligence officials in Washington, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, said Wednesday that the reports from India
were overblown.
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence officials also made clear that despite some
press reports, there had been no threat to the U.S. Embassy in New
Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   New Delhi police said they arrested Nasir on Jan. 7 at the New
Delhi railway station and charged him with waging war on India, an
offense punishable by life in prison or death. He was carrying more
than 4 pounds of RDX, an explosive, and five detonators, according
to the police.
</P>
<P>
   The police said he had other accomplices who remain at large,
four from Egypt, two from Sudan and one from Myanmar, formerly
Burma.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Nasir and his accomplices crossed the porous
border between Bangladesh and West Bengal last October and
subsequently traveled to Madras and Calcutta to survey the U.S.
Consulates there for possible openings for an attack.
</P>
<P>
   The police reported that Nasir offered them one particularly
tantalizing, though inconclusive, tidbit during his interrogation:
He said that he met Osama bin Laden, whom U.S. authorities have
blamed for the bombings of U.S. Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, in
1995 at a terrorist training camp in Kunar, Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. intelligence officials said that there was no known
link between the arrested suspects and the bin Laden group.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that Nasir told them he had been associated with
organizations that proved to be involved in supporting terrorism.
He said that when he was in Afghanistan he was picked out by
Pakistani intelligence officials to be their agent, the Indian
police said.
</P>
<P>
   In Islamabad, the Pakistani capital, Zameer Akram, the senior
Foreign Ministry official for south Asia, told The Associated Press
that ``Indian authorities have not informed us about any arrests
and we don't have any information about the case.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pakistani diplomat in New York, speaking on condition of
anonymity, added, ``If this is a week old, why has the Pakistani
government not been informed?''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin of the State Department said, ``We have no knowledge of
the alleged involvement of Pakistan, and I don't care to speculate
on the various motives of an event that is being investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Nasir's account, late last year he and several
other men were sent across the Bangladeshi border into West Bengal
with the intention of blowing up the U.S. Consulates in Calcutta
and Madras.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian police did not make clear who sent the men or what
group they were working for. Nasir said he did not know why those
particular targets were chosen. The men spent a month in Calcutta
and then went on to Madras, but never carried out their plan, the
Indian police said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that while the other men stayed in Madras, Nasir
came to New Delhi with the intention of setting off some explosions
in public places but was arrested after he received explosives at
the railway station here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
