A1782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEOFUNION-TOBACCO-     01-20 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-TOBACCO-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: do so.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the issue was revived again by Scruggs and others after the
collapse last spring of a $516 billion Senate bill that would have
regulated nicotine and sharply increased the price of a pack of
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, tobacco litigation split in two directions. State
officials completed a round of settlements under which tobacco
producers agreed to pay out $246 billion over 25 years to resolve
lawsuits brought by a number of states to recover Medicaid expenses
spent treating smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The legal underpinnings of those lawsuits were never tested in
court. But the question still remained as to whether successful
claims could be brought to recover similar federal funds expended
by Medicare, the health care program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   One senior administration official, who spoke only on the
condition of not being identified, said that as part of the latest
plan, the White House and the Justice Department are considering
introducing new tobacco-liability legislation because of legal
impediments that make it difficult to beat the tobacco companies in
court.
</P>
<P>
   One major difficulty is a 1947 landmark decision by the Supreme
Court that sharply limits the ability of the federal government to
recover funds from any individuals or companies absent explicit
statutory authority.
</P>
<P>
   As a result Justice Department officials, when approached last
spring by Scruggs and others, were leery about the prospects of
taking on tobacco producers. Still, a round of discussions ensued
and advocates of such an action as a means of bringing added
pressure on the industry began to make headway
</P>
<P>
   In time, Justice Department officials also began to reach out
and seek the advice of plaintiffs' lawyers and law professors
involved in tobacco lawsuits filed by the states. Included in the
group were Lawrence Tribe, a law professor at Harvard University,
G. Robert Blakey, a law professor at Notre Dame University, and
Einer Elhauge, another Harvard University law professor.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, other plaintiffs' lawyers who worked for the
states also began promoting the idea with Justice Department
officials. Included among them were Fred Levin, a Florida lawyer
who helped that state's Medicaid lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, the White House official, also said he believed that
Justice Department officials contacted Michael Ciresi, a
Minneapolis lawyer who worked for Minnesota in its tobacco lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In the months of sporadic talks that followed, the Justice
Department began to slowly shift ground from concerns about
bringing a suit to increasing consideration of the issue, said
participants in those talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several months ago, my sense is that they had grave doubts,''
said one lawyer, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``But
they had not done a lot of analysis. Eventually, the doubt was not
about whether to bring the lawsuit but the best way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed, the White House official, said it was in December that
Attorney General Janet Reno made the decision to sue tobacco
producers. She communicated that decision at the time to him, Reed
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have kept this a secret if we had told everyone,''
Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   As for tobacco producers, an industry spokesman reiterated on
Wednesday that cigarette makers believed that Clinton's
announcement of the new lawsuit was a self-serving political
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a blatantly political move,'' said Scott Williams, the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The producers involved in the recent round of state lawsuit
settlements are the Philip Morris Cos.,; R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, a
subsidiary of the RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.; Lorillard Tobacco, a
subsidiary of the Loews Corp., and Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco, a
subsidiary of BAT Industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
