<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDRESSING SENATORS, EX-PRESIDENT BUSH LAMENTS LOSS OF CIVILITY IN
POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Texas)  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE) 
 (bl) 
By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Addressing scores of senators who had just finished
another long afternoon at President Clinton's impeachment trial,
former President George Bush warned of the collapse of decorum in
political debate and an ``excessive intrusion into private lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush declined to say whether he believed that Clinton's
impeachment was warranted and what the president's fate should be.
He has long been reticent to bring up the issue while his son,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, considers a bid for the 2000 Republican
presidential nomination. The younger Bush has expressed concern
about invasion of privacy as it affects political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But his father's words, rendered in a grave voice, seemed to
signal a degree of sympathy for Clinton and a desire for senators
to move the country past this tense, uncertain moment as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I confess that the lack of civility in our political debate
and official dealings with one another concerns me,'' said the 41st
president, who spoke in the Old Senate chamber as part of a lecture
series for senators. ``I worry, too, about sleaze _ about excessive
intrusion into private lives. I worry that once-great news
organizations resort to tabloid journalism, giving us
sensationalism at best, smut at worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all,'' he continued, ``it seems to me that, whereas the
problems looming over this town dealt more with budget deficits in
times past, today we are confronted with a deficit of decency, one
that deepens by the day.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who began the
lecture series last spring, said that the date for Bush's speech
had been set several months ago and that its timing in the middle
of the impeachment trial was coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-hour speech that constituted an extended political
reminiscence, Bush kept circling back to the observation that
Washington was a more civil place, and the political parties worked
together more harmoniously, when he was vice president from 1981 to
1989 and president from 1989 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democratic senators had different
interpretations of Bush's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said, ``He was trying to say to us,
`Calm down. You are the repository of deliberative thought.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said that Bush's appeal was the
kind almost any former politician, once removed from the fray,
tended to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they've lived through the process, they take a longer
view of things,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made a point in his speech of saying that the best
accomplishments of his administration were bipartisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a certain civility, a certain honor, less rancor,''
he said, recalling his days in office. ``I wouldn't say kinder and
gentler, but, then again, maybe I would.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
