<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDOCK OUT OF CLIPPERS PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Murdock only (begin ital)sounded(end ital) like
the name of someone who would be networking in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Murdock _ a Miami Heat free agent on the Clippers'
point-guard shopping list _ and the Nets reached an agreement
Wednesday that will return the five-year veteran to his native New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an agreement in principle,'' Keith Glass, Murdock's
agent, said on the day before such a deal can become official.
``Nothing is etched in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   And please continue to count the Clippers among teams have yet
to even scratch in this etching derby.
</P>
<P>
   With the Murdock option eliminated, New Jersey free agent
Sherman Douglas remains the favorite to land the role of Clippers
playmaker. But the Clippers may need the domino-delivery system to
bring Douglas to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   With his role of backup Nets point guard taken by Murdock,
Douglas only seems to be a lock for the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Washington Wizards free agent point guard Rod Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, don't expect this big-ticket item to become a Clipper.
According to a league source, Strickland has two offers on the
table from the Wizards, but had a deadline of midnight (EST)
Wednesday to accept one of them. If Strickland and the Wizards part
company, Douglas could be the answer _ and a starter _ in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Or he could sign with the Clippers and play for new coach Chris
Ford, who coached Douglas in Boston and Milwaukee. The Clippers
have played the Douglas issue close to the vest but may have tipped
their hand in dealing with Murdock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we really rejected the Clippers,'' Glass said.
``We really didn't get an offer from them. If we had, I'm sure
(Eric) would have been interested. Basically, though, it came down
to staying at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Fleisher, Douglas' agent, and Elgin Baylor, the Clippers'
vice president of basketball operations, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   If the Clippers don't sign Douglas, or trade for a point guard,
they may choose to re-sign their own free agent, Darrick Martin,
unless another team beats them to that punch.
</P>
<P>
   Two more alternatives are free agents Kevin Johnson of Phoenix
and Darrell Armstrong of Orlando. Johnson, in the twilight of an
All-Star career, figures to join one of the league's heavyweight
teams. Armstrong, who missed much of last season with a shoulder
injury, is expected to stay with the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Jolly Rogers: Clippers forward Rodney Rogers made an appearance
on the final day of voluntary workouts at Veterans Park Sports
Complex in Carson. Rogers, who appeared to be an onion ring or two
above his playing weight, spent most of his lockout time taking
care of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to make sure I could keep living if we didn't have a
season,'' said Rogers, who has business interests in real estate
and trucking in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be funny the first couple of weeks,'' said Rogers,
commenting on how a less-than-ship-shape NBA might look. ``A lot of
laughs. Playing as many as four games a week means a lot of wear
and tear on the body. But that's what guys say they want _ more
games and less practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Six other Clippers attended Wednesday's workout. Missing in
action were Pooh Richardson, Keith Closs, James ``Hollywood''
Robinson and Maurice Taylor. The team expects its 10 signed
players, rookie Brian Skinner, and five mystery free agents on hand
when camp opens tonight at College of the Desert in Palm Desert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
