<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1787 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH21-COX     01-20 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton lawyers argue ouster could set dangerous precedent
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The impeachment charges against President Clinton
are so frivolous, vague and politically motivated that to remove
him from office would set a dangerous precedent, White House
attorneys argued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers Gregory Craig and Cheryl Mills, in sometimes graphic
detail, told the president's side of how he concealed a sexual
affair with former intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you convict and remove President Clinton on the basis of
these allegations, no president of the United States will ever be
safe from impeachment again,'' said Craig, who concentrated his 3
1/2 hour presentation on the charge that Clinton lied to a federal
grand jury about his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to take the charges seriously when in each case
they boil down to arguments over semantics,'' said Craig.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is expected to conclude its defense of Clinton
today with presentations from Clinton's personal attorney, David
Kendall, and former Sen. Dale Bumpers. Senators will then have 16
hours to question attorneys on both sides before considering a
motion to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans alone already have compiled more than 70 questions,
although many of these will be consolidated or eliminated for
redundancy.
</P>
<P>
   Senators are also jockeying for position with several scenarios.
Sen. Tom Harkin (D-Iowa) and Paul Wellstone (D-Minn.) want a motion
to open up all the deliberations, which would ordinarily be secret.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry (D-Mass.) also is pushing a motion that would
lead to an immediate vote on the articles of impeachment themselves
before any consideration of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors, meanwhile, continued to press for an
opportunity to rebut the president's defense arguments. They also
continued to wrangle over a final witness list, but without
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   To make his case, Craig played 14 minutes of a video of Clinton
during his deposition in August where he sits red-faced as
attorneys debate what constitutes a sexual relationship. The oddity
of hearing the definition of sex explored on the Senate floor was
evident, with some senators shifting in their seats, and others
focusing their eyes on the ground instead of the video screen.
</P>
<P>
   Craig argued that Clinton did not perjure himself.
</P>
<P>
   It made no sense for Clinton to lie about specifics to the grand
jury after making the ``painful, difficult admission'' of a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said prosecutors had embellished their case since the
House voted, largely along party lines, to impeach the president
Dec. 19. He said the case included new charges that had not been
part of the report issued by independent counsel Kenneth Starr in
September.
</P>
<P>
   To the allegation that the president falsely testified about the
nature and details of his relationship with Lewinksy, Craig said
that the president admitted during the grand jury that he had a
relationship of a sexual nature with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Mills followed Craig's presentation on perjury by attempting to
cast alternate interpretations on two of the most damaging
allegations against Clinton: that he orchestrated the retrieval of
gifts from Lewinsky's apartment and sought to intimidate his
personal secretary, Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   Mills also sought to counter the argument, advanced by House
prosecutors, that acquitting Clinton will send a dangerous message
about the enforcement of sexual harassment laws and the ability of
someone such as Paula Jones to bring such cases against powerful
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had imperfect leaders in the past, and we'll have
imperfect leaders in the future,'' Mills said. ``But their
imperfections did not roll back nor did they stop the march for
civil rights and equal protection for all our citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of the president's gifts to Lewinsky, which Currie
collected and kept under her bed, Mills suggested that it was
Lewinsky, not the president, who was concerned about them. She
cited Lewinsky's statements to the FBI that she was worried that
the Jones lawyers would break into her apartment and steal them and
other statements to the grand jury when she said it was she, not
the president, who raised the subject of gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``was not concerned about the gifts because he gives so
many gifts to so many people,'' Mills said. ``No one claims that he
ordered, hinted or suggested'' that the gifts be removed from
Lewinsky's apartment, Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Mills also argued that House prosecutors introduced no evidence
to suggest that Currie felt intimidated by Clinton when he called
her to the White House the day after his Paula Jones deposition to
quiz her about what she knew about Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Mills argued that obstruction of justice can't be legally proven
without some evidence of intimidation. Far from coaching Currie,
Clinton instead was seeking to find out what she knew about his
relationship so he could manage a ``media firestorm'' that he knew
was coming, Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president was concerned that his secret was going to be
exposed,'' said Mills. ``He talked to her to see what she knew.''
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors were quick to fight back, issuing a series
of responses to the White House claims.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Craig said that it was insignificant that the
president said his relationship began in 1996, vs. 1995 when
Lewinsky said it began. Insignificant because the accounts differed
by a matter of months during which her age did not change.
</P>
<P>
   The president lied about the beginning of the date before a
federal grand jury in August, the House managers said, because he
had denied such contact with Lewinsky in an earlier deposition with
the attorneys for Jones.''To admit it in the grand jury would be
clear perjury,'' the prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The date is also important because Lewinsky was an intern and
therefore, a federal employee, in the White House when the
relationship began in 1995, but not in 1996 when the president
testified the relationship began.
</P>
<P>
   ``In sum, the president's lawyers have presented a classic Swiss
cheese defense. It is full of factual holes, and twists the law
into contortions so strange they are scarcely recognizable,'' the
House managers said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers generally praised the White House
presentation but some scoffed at the notion that the charges
against Clinton were not supported by the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say there is no proof,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah).
``What about the dress?'' One of Lewinksy's dresses was found to
contain DNA from the president, the FBI found.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic senators, however, said they found the arguments
persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow is the way I felt when I left,'' said Sen. Max Cleland
(D-Ga.). ``Ms. Mills was, quite frankly, incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
