<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-STOCKS-660(     01-20 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-STOCKS-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN HINTS RATE CUT IS UNLIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also STATEOFUNION-GREENSPAN, EDIT-GREENSPAN) 
(js) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, said
Wednesday there is little evidence that the economy is slowing. But
he warned for the first time since the stock market's most recent
run-up that equity prices might be getting excessive.
</P>
<P>
   His comments, analysts said, suggested that the central bank
would leave interest rates unchanged for some time to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there are risks going forward,'' Greenspan told the
House Ways and Means Committee, ``to date domestic demand and hence
employment and output in the United States certainly has remained
vigorous. Though the pace of economic expansion is widely expected
to moderate as 1999 unfolds, signs of an appreciable slowdown as
yet remain scant.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the risks, Greenspan suggested, is that stock prices may
again have become unrealistically high. One of the reasons that
Wall Street has rebounded so smartly from its brief but sharp dip
last summer is Greenspan himself, who engineered a series of three
interest-rate cuts in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of equity prices would appear to envision
substantially greater growth of profits than has been experienced
of late,'' the Fed chairman said, restating a theme he has sounded
on and off for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   The markets, which have come to expect some low-key jawboning
from Greenspan, largely shrugged off his comments. The Dow Jones
industrial average, which had advanced well over points during the
day, retreated to end with a 19.31-point loss, at 9,335.91. Broader
market indicators closed modestly higher, including the Nasdaq
composite index, which set another record. Bond prices fell.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has not directly addressed stock market valuations in
public since the market tumbled and then recovered. But he has
warned in general terms about what happens when investors fail to
make appropriate judgments about risk, whether on Wall Street or in
emerging markets. And the minutes of the Fed's policy-making
meeting on Nov. 17, when Greenspan and his colleagues cut rates by
a quarter of a percentage point, show that some members of the
committee were worried that pushing rates down would send the stock
market to unjustifiably high levels.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have assumed for several months that the Fed is
likely to hold rates steady at least the next few months unless the
global financial turmoil that has unsettled markets and economies
flares anew.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan reinforced that view Wednesday, though he acknowledged
that Brazil's recent problems create uncertainty. He suggested that
the Fed is again concerned that stronger-than-expected growth could
rekindle inflation if the economy did not slow on its own. Growth
in the fourth quarter of 1998 may have been as high as 5 percent,
according to some estimates, ending a year in which the economy
grew nearly 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fed officials and many economists expect growth to slow to a
range of 2 percent to 3 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also discussed subjects including Social Security, tax
cuts and trade policy, saying that ``some moderation'' in growth
might be required to sustain the nation's long expansion. ``Through
the end of 1998, the economy continued to grow more rapidly than
can be currently accommodated on an ongoing basis, even with
higher, technology-driven productivity growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's testimony marked something of a return to his
customary views after the tumult of last fall, when the Fed cut
interest rates by a total of three-quarters of a percentage point
to calm anxious investors and insure that the financial upheaval
that began in Asia did not spread to the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   As it has for most of the last three years, the economy is
cruising along, defying predictions of a slowdown. The stock market
is regularly setting new highs. But even though unemployment is low
and demand is strong, there are almost no signs of inflation,
leaving policy makers, including Greenspan, pleased but wary.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A survey released Wednesday by the Federal Reserve System
provided much the same view of the economy's performance as
Greenspan's testimony. The survey found that ``most regions are
showing solid economic growth over all,'' with ``generally stable
or declining prices.''
</P>
<P>
   No element of the economy's performance draws more attention
these days than the boom in the financial markets, and Greenspan
used much of his prepared testimony Wednesday to explore the link
between Wall Street and the buoyancy of consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   He said there have been valid reasons for the jump in stock
prices over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lower inflation, greater competitiveness and the flexibility
and adaptability of our businesses have enabled them to take
advantage of a rapid pace of technological change to make our
capital stock more productive and profitable,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that the Fed has not sought to use monetary policy
to move stock prices up and down to reflect its view of appropriate
market valuations, adding, ``We need to react to changes in
financial markets, as we did this fall, but our objective is the
maximum sustainable growth of the U.S. economy, not particular
levels of asset prices.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, referring to last fall's rate cuts, he said,
``We were not attempting to prop up equity prices, nor did we plan
to continue to ease rates until equity prices recovered, as some
have erroneously inferred.''
</P>
<P>
   But the markets have a direct if complex effect on the economy
that must be factored into monetary policy, Greenspan said. The
rise in stock prices, he said, had clearly affected the personal
savings rate, which declined from almost 6 percent in 1992 to zero
last year. Instead of saving through traditional channels,
individuals are accumulating wealth through the stock market. There
is evidence, he said, that all or most of the decline in personal
savings is concentrated among the wealthy, who benefit the most
from capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   The wealth effect _ the theory that consumer spending rises
along with increases in the value of investment portfolios _ ``has
been real and significant,'' Greenspan said. But the wealth effect
could also work in reverse, he said, since ``a decline in equity
values, especially a severe one, could lead to a considerable
weakening of consumer demand.''
</P>
<P>
   The markets have stabilized substantially since the fall,
Greenspan said, but the forced devaluation last week of Brazil's
currency illustrates the tenuous nature of that calm. And he noted
that global economic crises continue to have an effect in the
United States, not least in leading to a growing trade deficit as
foreign markets for agricultural and industrial products dry up and
other nations look to this country to import their goods.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Greenspan said, central banks had to be careful that
interest-rate changes did not unduly unsettle the financial
markets, given their fragility. Policy makers, he said, ``are going
to have to be particularly wary of actions that unnecessarily sow
uncertainties, undermine confidence and interfere with the
efficient allocation of capital.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
