A1795 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO:AIRPORT-PRIVAT     01-20 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO:AIRPORT-PRIVATIZE-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVIATION: MODEL PLANS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By DOUGLASS STINSON 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Mexico's Planned privatization of 35 airports, including the
country's main international facility in Mexico City, has been a
surprisingly quiet affair. A consortium led by local builder
Tribasa recently filed a winning bid of US$116 million for a
50-year concession to operate nine airports in the country's
Southeast - the first of four such auctions that some say could
earn as much as US$ 4 billion.
 &HT;    The recent privatization of Argentina's 33 airports caused a
stir, mainly due to the relief by airlines and passengers alike
that a private, world-class operator would finally address the
desperate need for financing and the desperate operational and
safety concerns. But Mexico's airports are safe and well-run,
earning a profit of nearly $190 million over the first three
quarters of 1998, 29 percent better than the previous year.
 &HT;    So why sell at all? ``Who flies into our airports? The rich, the
top 1 percent of our society,'' says Jorge Silberstein,
privatization coordinator for the Ministry of Communications and
Transport. ``Every dollar we spend on airports, is a dollar we
can't spend on health care or schools. Our resources are scarce.''
 &HT;    There is one thing privatizers are looking to fix: the way
corporations are owned and controlled in Mexico.
 &HT;    Mexico has had problems in this department, notably in the
privatization of state banks and toll-road projects. In both cases,
new owners failed to fully disclose many risky ventures aimed at
recouping inflated privatization bids. Ministry officials have
pledged that their privatizations will be different. ``The thinking
is that this is a company that should be public,'' says
Silberstein. ``We are paving the way for the idea of a diverse
shareholder base and the protection of minority shareholders'
rights.''
 &HT;    To that end, the sale of equity stakes in the airports are like
no other privatization of its kind in the world, designed to create
a transparent public-company management structure that will run the
airport and contract for needed construction and development in an
open, free-market fashion. ``The equity structure they are using
makes it less eventful,'' says Steven Steckler, the president of
Infrastructure Management Group, a U.S.-based firm that advises on
airport management. ``In Argentina, there was the feeling that they
were really handing over the airport.''
 &HT;    Normally, airport systems are given in concession over long
terms or outright sale to a group of partners that includes a
strategic operator. Mexico's airports have been divided into three
regional groupings, plus the Mexico City airport, the largest, as a
solo offering. But instead of granting total control through
concession or sale, the government is only offering the sale of a
15 percent stake and concession rights to the winning bidders.
Additionally, bidders must consist of a partnership between an
international operator and a local partner each owning a quarter of
the holding company. Additional investors must fill out the
remaining ownership.
 &HT;    The remaining 85 percent of each airport group is slated to be
sold through an initial public offering at a future date.
 &HT;    The uncertainty has not kept many bidders away. Major operators
like U.S.-based Ogden Corp. and Holland's Schiphol International
B.V. have entered the first round of privatizations, the
Southeastern Group of airports. But others are waiting to see how
the first auction and the final negotiations for the concession
contract turn out.
 &HT;    ``This is not a normal concession privatization. Instead, the
operator is investing in a holding company over which it does not
have total control. You choose your partners in a concession, but
with Mexico's IPO, you are getting into bed with strangers,'' says
Cody Plott, a vice president in charge of airport development for
Airport Group International. ``This one is so unique that we
decided to see how the first one goes.''
 &HT;    Observers expect the terms of the first concession contract to
dictate the remaining three sales, with winning bidders allowed to
own one regional system and also bid on the Mexico City airport in
the final auction schedule scheduled for the end of this year. The
unorthodox privatization of the airport system is expected to draw
major attention from operators, even though Mexico does not sport
the growth potential that Argentina offers. But with airport
operators expecting big contracts coming up for bid in Europe and
Asia, they are looking for any opportunity that will give them a
track record. ``This is portfolio-building time'', says Steckler.
``Operators are thinking, `If we're not there, the rest of the
world will be asking `why?'''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
