<HEADER>
A1805 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PLAYINGBYHEART-T     01-20 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PLAYING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY CHARACTERS, TOO LITTLE COHESION
</HEADLINE>
 BY HEART-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Certain directors _ Robert Altman and Woody Allen, to name a
couple _ have a gift for movies with large casts and multiple story
lines. At their best, the films are seamless, their characters
inhabiting one world so emphatically that the world becomes a
character itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing by Heart'' would like to be a movie like that, but it
suffers from having its screenwriter as its director. Willard
Carroll, whose best-known credit to date is 1991's little-seen
``The Runestone,'' appears to have been too close to his script,
and his possessiveness diminishes a promising premise. Other hands
might have corrected the flaws by smoothing the movie's flow,
trimming its excesses and filming it in such a way that the
dialogue doesn't call attention to itself.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the film plays like a collection of duet-acting
exercises. It's no wonder it attracted such a marquee-value cast,
all of whom get to flex their performing muscles. But the actors
aren't playing individual characters so much as couples.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of couples. Sean Connery and Gena Rowlands are a
long-married pair bickering about an indiscretion he almost
committed 25 years ago; Gillian Anderson and Jon Stewart are
professionals embarking on a relationship but struggling with her
reluctance; Angelina Jolie and Ryan Phillippe are bohemian club
goers who connect but struggle with his reluctance; Madeleine Stowe
and Anthony Edwards, each married to someone else, are having an
affair that she wants to keep simple and he wants to complicate.
</P>
<P>
   For wild cards, there are Jay Mohr and Ellen Burstyn as a dying
AIDS patient and his compassionate mother, and Dennis Quaid as a
guy who goes to bars and tells his life story to anyone who will
listen _ only it's a different life story every time.
</P>
<P>
   All the characters interconnect in a ``surprise'' climax that
most viewers will figure out well ahead of time. Miramax sent a
note to journalists asking that the ending be kept secret, and
we'll oblige, but the movie's straining toward the revelation is
its central problem. If the connection had been revealed from the
beginning, we could see the characters as part of that one world.
Instead, the couples inhabit their own little worlds; they're so
segregated from anything outside their romantic problems that they
don't even have friends, apparently relying on their many pets for
some kind of emotional connection. The movie is set in Los Angeles,
but it could just as well have been set in Fort Worth or Cincinnati
for all the city plays into it; the many interior scenes inspire
not a sense of place but a sense of dislocation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the performances almost save the movie. Jolie steals the
film with a funny, touching performance as the disco dolly who, in
trying to break down Phillippe's walls, discovers that she has
walls of her own _ and that they're very fragile (it's tempting to
tag Jolie with the nickname Gepetto, because she's the only person
ever to make the wooden Phillippe appear to come to life). Her
theft is a bit by default, because the movie's best actors, Connery
and Rowlands, are wasted in their plot line; it's as if that's the
only conflict Carroll could possibly imagine older people having.
</P>
<P>
   Also good is Anderson, who gives an interesting, subtle
performance as the woman who has been so wounded that she can't
bring herself to look her charming suitor in the eye. And Quaid's
turn as the chameleonic barfly is his most confidently puckish in
years, but when his character's secret is revealed, the confidence
and puckishness vanish, because Carroll's screenplay has ceased
giving him anything to do.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's original title was ``Dancing About Architecture,'' a
phrase that Carroll borrowed and adapted from a Laurie Anderson
song, only in his case it's talking about love that's like dancing
about architecture (he's so fond of the metaphor, he uses it
twice). The inspired original title probably better represents the
heights that Carroll was aiming for; unfortunately, the more
mundane new title reflects the movie's reality. Except that these
characters talk so much about love, maybe it should have been
called ``Playing by Mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing by Heart'' is rated R for language and adult
situations.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
