<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-HI-LOCOUNTRY-TEX     01-20 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HI-LO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPWALKING THROUGH A DYING WEST
</HEADLINE>
 COUNTRY-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sam Peckinpah wanted to adapt ``The Hi-Lo Country'' for the big
screen more than 30 years ago. The book's elegiac tone and mixture
of courtliness and explosive instinct would have been suited to
Peckinpah's abiding interests, as well as his compulsion to track
the codes of machismo and the hardheadedness that can kill
friendships. Director Stephen Frears gets the courtly part right.
His film is measured, rapt and not one iota less than beautiful.
But the rambunctious energy is missing. We're always aware that
Frears carefully deposits his feet in the prints of those who've
come before him. Curiously, ``The Hi-Lo Country'' seems to be
yellowing before your very eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It's another of those westerns about the end of the West, in
which we watch a way of life dying. It even seems to be narrated by
a dead man, Pete (Billy Crudup). After the bullying, wide-awake
performance Crudup gave in ``Without Limits,'' he apparently became
mesmerized by the gorgeous vistas and sunsets of ``Hi-Lo.'' It's as
good-looking as a movie can be. The picture starts during World War
II and gets going just after the war ends. That's when Big Boy
(Woody Harrelson), a big man with a heart big enough to tame a land
too big for most, brings his big passions home and wants to start
ranching. Yup, there's a lot of big in ``Hi-Lo.'' Mostly, it's like
watching kids in clothes too big for them carrying pillowcases from
house to house on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Pete harbors a love for Mona (Patricia Arquette), but so does
Big Boy. Mona is supposed to pass through the town Hi-Lo like a
sultry breeze, and her humiliated husband (John Diehl) follows her
around while she's turning the head of every man in town. Arquette,
with the baby fat burned out of her cheeks, looks the part. But
she, too, seems to be sleepwalking through the movie. Which, I
guess, explains what Harrelson is doing screaming at people and
grabbing them by their lapels. He's trying to wake them up. (He'd
have better luck in a cemetery.) He begins to seem like he's Kevin
McCarthy in ``Invasion of the Body Snatchers,'' trying to wake
everybody up before the pods swallow 'em up whole. He's too late,
though. The striking Penelope Cruz, as the girl who loves Pete but
is never enough for him, is so badly used you'd think she never
acted before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi-Lo'' is peculiar because it's so dreary and moth-eaten that
it almost makes you forget the feel that Frears showed for American
low-lifes in ``The Grifters,'' and the brilliant way he handled
American actors in ``Dangerous Liaisons.'' He's not contemptuous of
the wild streaks in American actors; he revels in them. Not having
read the book, I can't say what attracted him to the material, but
movies like ``The Hi-Lo Country'' were made quite a few times
during the 1950s. ``(Giant'' was probably the peak.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi-Lo'' is supposed to be full of men who are men and sure
proud of it. It's certainly full of something. Harrelson works hard
to dominate the picture, but what he tries to force, Sam Elliott,
as the dastardly rancher who controls Hi-Lo, has by natural right.
Laconic and sure-footed, Elliott probably could have played Big Boy
20 years ago. Harrelson puts so much effort into the role that
we're not sure if we should take him seriously. Except the movie
seems to take him very seriously. It takes itself way too
seriously, too, dragging around its themes of doom and loss and men
hanging onto a way of life that's receding right in front of them.
A way of life isn't the only thing receding in this movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hi-Lo Country'' is rated R for adult sexuality, violence
(including a rape scene) and language.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
