<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-RIFT21-COX     01-20 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-RIFT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientists: No easy way to restore Everglades, Biscayne Bay
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Despite weeks of scrambling, scientists
working on a $7.8 billion Everglades restoration plan have found no
easy way to meet demands that they fully replenish Everglades
National Park and Biscayne Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they came up with proposed changes that could parch or
flood parts of the central Everglades and risk floods in some Palm
Beach County suburbs. The changes also would create a potentially
huge cleanup bill by steering billions of gallons of polluted
suburban drainage into otherwise unfouled sections of the
Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the likely results of the latest ``tweak'' of the U.S.
Army Corps of Engineers' Everglades rescue plan, state and federal
scientists said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They said they're still trying to design a restoration that
helps the entire region _ or at least doesn't hurt anyone. But the
final details will probably remain unknown until well after
Congress receives the corps' blueprint in July.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest example of the conundrum facing the restoration
effort: How do you revive one part of South Florida's shrunken,
shriveled ecosystem without trashing something else?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to damage one part of the Everglades to solve
problems in another part,'' said biologist John Ogden of the South
Florida Water Management District, the corps' partner.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden said it's still unclear how the proposed changes outlined
Wednesday will be included in the corps' report to Congress. They
may wind up in an appendix of ideas needing further review.
</P>
<P>
   Corps officials have long said their plan will need repeated
changes over the next two decades, with Congress doling out money
in stages only after the engineers finish the details.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the specter of harmful side effects could make the entire
restoration hard to sell to a skeptical public, one state official
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a real marketing issue,'' said Mary Ann Poole of
the state Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The park also has yet to endorse any of the proposed changes,
but Superintendent Richard Ring said: ``We're really encouraged. We
want a final plan that does the best it possibly can for all of
South Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   The $7.8 billion plan is supposed to replenish the Everglades,
which has suffered from decades of draining and development, while
providing water and flood control to farms and cities.
</P>
<P>
   In a draft that Vice President Al Gore unveiled in October, the
corps called for creating more than 300 wells and 251,000 acres of
marshes, reservoirs and deep quarries. They would store hundreds of
billions of gallons each year, capturing water that the region's
canals waste out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not enough, park officials said last month. They said
the plan would supply drinking water for suburban sprawl without
giving the park and Biscayne Bay the water they need to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for more water, scientists from the corps, water
district and other agencies turned to the urban drainage that
washes off lawns, parking lots, streets and rooftops along South
Florida's developed coast.
</P>
<P>
   They suggested corraling 89 billion gallons flowing out to sea
each year in Palm Beach and Broward counties. Pumps would move that
water into wells, reservoirs and filter marshes, much of it
ultimately entering the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Through that step and other drainage changes, the scientists
said they could pour an additional 112 billion gallons into the
park and Biscayne Bay each year.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes would have serious drawbacks:
</P>
<P>
   _ The change in drainage would flood parts of the central
Everglades during rainy seasons and parch them in dry times, game
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The rerouting of water could overflow canals in suburbs west
of cities from Lake Worth to Boca Raton unless the canals are
widened, drainage managers say. ``We're kind of upset because
nobody has talked to us about this,'' said Bill Winters, executive
director of the Lake Worth Drainage District.
</P>
<P>
   _ Urban runoff contains a host of pollutants, including
fertilizers, pesticides, oil residue and heavy metals.
</P>
<P>
   Already, taxpayers are financing a $763 million project to clean
farm and suburban pollution draining into the northern Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning that pollution could add an untold amount of money to
the price and require enlarging some of the filter marshes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
