A1816 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BISHER-COLUMN-COX     01-20 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BISHER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting to the SuperBowl is a (long) snap
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All right, class, we're going to start today with a
little test. Multiple choice: A long snapper is (a) a lawn mower,
(b) a fish, (c) a turtle or (d) a football player who spends most
of his time with his head between his legs.
</P>
<P>
   If you picked (d), you win. In this case, what you win is a few
minutes of Adam Schreiber's time. Adam Schreiber is a long snapper.
That's his line of work. Nobody ever notices a long snapper until
he makes a bad snap, then he becomes a headline. Even his family is
vilified.
</P>
<P>
   ``But never,'' he wanted it pointed out, ``have I ever made a
bad snap that lost a game'''
</P>
<P>
   It is now on record that Morten Andersen kicked the field goal
and booted the Falcons all the way to Super Bowl No. 33, thus
becoming the most popular Dane around here since Victor Borge.
However, the science of football tells us that it takes three
people to kick a field goal, and nobody can kick anything until the
long snapper snaps the ball to the holder, who then places it so
the kicker can kick it between the pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Before Andersen kicked, Schreiber snapped, Dan Stryzinski
fielded the snap and placed the ball in position. Ergo, three
points. Falcons win, Falcons win, Falcons win!
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not one of my best snaps,'' Schreiber said. ``The laces
were a quarter to the right.'' Then he went into a technical
discourse on the science of the field-goal snap. ``Accuracy is
everything snapping for field goals. Snapping for punts, you just
snap as hard as you can.'' Let the punter track it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get nervous snapping for field goals,'' he said. ``We
work on it 20 minutes every day. We've done, I'd guess, over a
thousand practice snaps this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, what course does a player take to get into this upside-down
profession? We turn back here to his career as an offensive lineman
at Texas, where he was part of one of the most magnificently
crafted front five you ever saw. Tall, straight backs, flat
stomachs, lean and rangy as Texans are supposed to look. Schreiber
played a little bit of everything, but Casey Smith was the center.
The others were Mike Reuther, who once was a Falcon, Doug Dawson
and a stout one so square they called Gene Chilton ``The Coke
Machine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great team. We went 11-and-0, but the saddest part
was, we lost to Georgia in the Cotton bowl by one point,''
Schreiber said with a curled lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father got me into football. One afternoon when I was in
the 4th grade, he dropped me off at the practice field. We were
lined up going out for passes. I dropped a pass and started crying.
I was a mama's baby. I decided right then I wanted to be an
offensive lineman.''
</P>
<P>
   Schreiber took up snapping at New Orleans, anything to hang on.
``Joel Hilgenberg had been the snapper, but he turned up sick as a
dog one day, and Bum Phillips called on me. I'd been practicing,
just in case, and I took over.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been more to his career than playing upside down. In
the 15 seasons he has been in the NFL, twice he has started 16
games, last with the Minnesota Vikings -- yes, those guys -- in
1993. He got in a few licks at guard in preseason here, but Bob
Hallen, the rookie, came through and that cut him loose for pure
snapping.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcon connection dates back to the three seasons Schreiber
spent with Dan Reeves and the New York Giants. The telephone rang
during preseason last year, and it was Reeves again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted me down here, and I wanted to be wherever Dan Reeves
was. So we made a two-year deal, and here we are, on the way to the
Super Bowl. How's that for the end to a story of the 4th-grader who
dropped his first pass and cried?''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be 39 next month, but long snappers have a different view
of the game than the other players. They're in a world of their own
and always in demand. The Falcons are Schreiber's seventh team. He
has seen the NFL from coast to coast, but that's how he grew up.
His father was in hotel management and the family saw a lot of the
country. He was born in Galveston, though, and that makes him a
Texan forever.
</P>
<P>
   Bisher writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
