<HEADER>
A1818 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-COX     01-20 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves talks about his pain in Denver
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves acted like a man who had left
the past behind when he was asked Monday the first of what will be
many questions about Broncos coach Mike Shanahan, quarterback John
Elway, and owner Pat Bowlen.
</P>
<P>
   When the subject came up again Wednesday, Reeves sounded like a
man who would never forget. He will meet them all face-to-face
again on Jan. 31 in Super Bowl XXXIII, when the Falcons (16-2) meet
Denver (16-2) in Miami. As coach of the Broncos from 1981-92,
Reeves occasionally had a strained relationship with Elway, fired
Shanahan after the 1991 season and was fired by Bowlen after the
'92 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I'll ever get over the full situation,''
said Reeves, who had a record of 110-73-1 in Denver, including five
AFC West titles and three losing trips to the Super Bowl. ``I think
any time you're fired and you've been in a place for 12 years and
had the success we had, that you really don't understand it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed an awful lot of people's lives,'' Reeves said
during a 70-minute news conference Wednesday. ``Just like me making
the decision about Mike ... changed a lot of people's lives. I
don't know that Mike will ever get over the hurt from that, and
what it cost his wife and children. Well, the same thing with me.
It caused a lot of pain for my wife, my children. It's something
that won't ever go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway came first, arriving in Denver in 1983 as a remarkable
talent after a standout career at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   In his first NFL game, Elway took over for current Falcon backup
Steve DeBerg during the fourth quarter of a preseason game against
Seattle and rallied Denver to a comeback victory. He went on to
become the starter.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves benched him a month into the season, then made him
the starter again in week 10 after DeBerg injured a shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, they had their first sideline argument. A few days later,
Elway and Reeves met in the coach's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him we're bad for each other,'' Reeves told the Rocky
Mountain News many years ago. ``We're both impatient. We made a
pact after that game. I told him I'd remind him to be patient if
he'd remind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway played pretty well the rest of the season, then was
stunned when DeBerg got healthy, and was tabbed to start in an AFC
divisional playoff game against Seattle _ a 31-7 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point,'' Elway's wife, Janet, said, ``he talked to me
about forgetting pro football and becoming an assistant for his
father (Jack at Stanford). I don't think deep down he was serious.
But I knew he thought about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowlen purchased the team in 1984, and in training camp DeBerg
was gone, traded to Tampa Bay, where he backed up Steve Young.
Shanahan had been hired as an assistant out of the University of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985, Shanahan was the offensive coordinator, although he
left in 1988 to become head coach of the Raiders, who fired him a
month into the '89 season.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was coaching his own quarterbacks at the time, a taxing
job for a head coach, and he couldn't talk backup quarterback Gary
Kubiak _ the current Denver offensive coordinator _ into being a
player-coach.
</P>
<P>
   So he and Bowlen hired Shanahan has the quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Raiders let Mike go, I was the first one to go to Pat
and say, 'This would be great if we could get him back,' `` Reeves
said. ``So I had tremendous respect for Mike. He was as good a
football coach as I've ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shanahan's relationship with Elway blossomed so much that
Reeves grew uncomfortable. Reeves didn't care for the idea of
Shanahan and his family vacationing with Elway and his family,
thinking that it wasn't what a professional relationship should be.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Reeves grew very upset with the relationship between
Shanahan and Elway. He started reading comments in the local papers
about Elway being unhappy with comments Reeves had made about him
in private. And there was talk of Shanahan and Elway scripting
plays without Reeves' knowledge. So Reeves fired Shanahan for
``insubordination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing to me was, the biggest problem I had (with Shanahan)
was,'If John Elway had a problem with me and you're coaching that
position and you know (it), why did I not know that prior to
reading it in the paper?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like if you were the position coach and you were
that close to the quarterback, why did you not say, 'Hey, this is
something you ought to sit down and talk about?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And you say things in a coaches' meeting as far as critiquing
a play of someone that you would never say to the player. If John
ever got any bad feelings about something that I said . . . it had
to be something coming from a staff meeting. Now, does that mean
Mike did it? You got a lot of people on your staff. Again, . . . as
I said, I have no proof of them, nothing. I did what I felt was
best for our football team. I didn't think Mike acted in my best
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Shanahan told the Rocky Mountain News in 1993, when he
was offensive coordinator of the 49ers, ``I think Dan is trying to
blame his relationship with John on somebody else. The fact is,
when I got there back in 1984, John and Dan weren't getting along
very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day our relationship soured was the day when (a column by
late Denver Post columnist Dick Connor in '91) came out with John
saying he and Dan didn't communicate anymore. Dan called me in his
office and said, 'Why did John go and do that?' And I said, 'Why
are you asking me? John's a big boy. Go and ask him.' Up until
then, Dan and I were fine. It all soured after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the distractions, the Broncos won the AFC West title
that year with a 12-4 record but lost in the conference
championship game to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The team went 8-8 in 1992, but Reeves already had begun to sense
that Bowlen was going to drop the ax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I coached in the Pro Bowl (after the '91 season) and was
promised a contract extension. I expected (Bowlen) to do it in
Hawaii,'' Reeves said. ``It never came up. I thought it was going
to happen in the offseason. It never came up. I didn't feel like it
was for me to go to him and say, 'When are we going to get this
done?' We went into the (1992) season, and he hadn't addressed
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Reeves was surprised and very disappointed that he
was fired, although he said he didn't argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stay in Denver the rest of my career,'' he said.
``Pat was born about a month after I was, and he used to always
say, 'We're going to finish our careers together.' I didn't ask
questions. I've been on the other side of that desk, with Mike, and
with players over the years, and that's not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   When Reeves underwent heart-bypass surgery last month, Shanahan
and his wife sent get-well wishes, and Elway and his wife made a
donation in Reeves' name to the Atlanta Youth Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves isn't about to invite Shanahan, Elway or Bowlen to
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have never been where we were without John Elway. I
always had a tremendous amount of respect for John Elway,'' he
said. ``And the whole thing with John is, I tried to address
everything we did, even in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of hurt that won't ever go away. You never
will forget those things. But am I a person that's not going to
speak to Pat Bowlen or Mike Shanahan or John Elway? I don't live my
life like that. I had a lot of great times with those guys. I can
be cordial to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play golf with them. I won't go out to eat with them, or
go socially to a function with them, but I would have no problem
carrying on a conversation. It' just part of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Winklejohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
