<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1819 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MIAMI-PROFILE-COX     01-20 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MIAMI-PROFILE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Before the big game, Miami battles image header
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Chamber of Commerce dream is perfect weather, 70
sunny degrees under a cloudless blue sky, happy dancers swinging to
a salsa beat in packed nightclubs while football fans spend gobs of
money.
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare is Miami's other side, the one that gets more
headlines than the pretty weather: thugs smack tourist rental cars
in fake accidents to set up robberies, ethnic tensions boil over
and city blocks burn, corrupt politicians get carted off to jail in
handcuffs as the cameras roll.
</P>
<P>
   Which Miami Super Bowl fans will find is anybody's guess. Just
this week robbers killed a winter resident from Canada and shot a
Panamanian woman, while a top parks department official was
suspended after $300,000 worth of mahogany trees came up missing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, movie stars and gorgeous cover-girls cruise the
vibrant nightscene on South Beach, while smugglers traffic in drugs
and immigrants, dumping cargo that sometimes washes up on the beach
next to posh waterfront mansions.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the spice and hint of something taboo that gives the
place some of its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, for most visitors and residents, Miami isn't like
living in the netherworld of some bad TV mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the main thing Super Bowl fans can look forward to is
probably gorgeous weather, which is largely what put this place on
the map in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's magic skyline still shimmers on perfect winter days
under a 70-degree sun, the blue Atlantic lapping at wide white
beaches, residents and tourists alike sucking in the glorious balmy
air and wondering why it can't be like this all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Rent a convertible if you can find one. Head to the beach,
cruise the lushly-landscaped streets of Coconut Grove or Coral
Gables, sip a Cuban coffee while you watch old men playing dominoes
in Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a one-day game,'' said Ginny Gutierrez, a
spokesperson for the Greater Miami Visitor and Convention Bureau.
``It's a whole week where you can take advantage of a wide array of
events. And mostly it's our weather. That's always been our number
one draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, you may want to keep your eyes and ears peeled for those
``Only-in-South-Florida'' gems that often make the news here.
</P>
<P>
   Last year it was the mayor's race. Xavier Suarez, dubbed ``Mayor
Loco'' by local pundits, was deposed from office after elections
officials found rampant absentee ballot fraud that included one
vote cast by a dead person.
</P>
<P>
   A city commissioner on the same ballot had been removed from
office on mortgage fraud charges, only to be re-elected by his
zealous supporters, only to be removed again weeks later for
alleged vote fraud.
</P>
<P>
   That pol now sits in jail, further humiliated by revelations
that his wife had an affair with his attorney during his trial.
</P>
<P>
   But political corruption is run-of-the-mill stuff, common, to
some extent, in many big American cities.
</P>
<P>
   More interesting are the characters who seem drawn to sunny
South Florida. The developer who wants to build an indoor
snow-skiing mountain so sweaty locals and visitors can trade beach
togs for the latest ski fashions. Airboat operators who like to
take tourists up-close and personal with toothy alligators. Or the
Indian gator wrestler who tried a dangerous trick one time too many
and had his face stitched up after the jaws of death clamped down
on his noggin.
</P>
<P>
   There's a tour of famous crime sites, including the South Beach
mansion where world-famous Italian fashion designer Gianni Versace
was gunned down two years ago. There's a police museum to warm any
Dragnet fan's heart. And even a live parrot show where trained
birds do tricks.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it does seem that South Florida gets more than its
share of headlines for crime. In the early 1990s, thugs were
targeting tourists, who could be easily identified by their
rental-car license plates. High profile murders of several foreign
tourists sparked an avalanche of page-one stories in Europe, and
tourism promoters felt the pinch.
</P>
<P>
   Officials responded by getting the license plates changed so
rental cars don't stick out, and by setting up a special police
task force that concentrates on the airport and tourism areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had our problems like any other big city, but we've
taken innovative steps that have reduced tourism crime by 86
percent,'' Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, local boosters shivered this week when a Canadian was
killed outside his winter home shortly after picking up a relative
at the Fort Lauderdale airport and a Panamanian woman was shot by
robbers outside a shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the height of the tourist season, with Super Bowl
coming,'' Miami-Dade County Manager Merrett Stierheim told local
reporters. ``Without question, this is a sensitive time for us.
We're concerned. We've been down this road before.''
</P>
<P>
   Police will work overtime shifts during Super Bowl week, looking
out for tourist-targeting bad guys. But the cops can can cause
problems, too, especially when they get pushy in poorer
neighborhoods: A police shooting in 1989 led to riots that marred
that year's Super Bowl. However, Super Bowl XXIX in Miami in 1995
was without serious incident.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope tourists won't be worried about crime, but also
won't take foolish chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visitors should bring their common sense just like they would
to any large city,'' Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
