<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tennessee's national title paying off
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer, reaping the rewards of the Vols'
national championship, is assembling one of the nation's top
recruiting classes.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers got commitments from defensive linemen Albert
Haynesworth (6-5, 285) of Hartsville, S.C., and Kevin Young (6-3,
240) of Duncanville, Texas, and offensive lineman Anthony Herrera
(6-3, 280) of Naples, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee also is expected to get defensive lineman Terriea
Smalls (6-3, 310) of Timberland, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the SEC, Florida got commitments from athlete Lito
Sheppard (5-11, 185) of Jacksonville; defensive back Daryl Dixon
(5-10, 188) of New Smyrna Beach, Fla.; linebacker Todd Pointer
(6-3, 190) of Deerfield Beach, Fla.; and defensive lineman Tony
Charles (6-3, 260) of Hyattsville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Alabama got tight end Michael Gaines (6-3, 255) and
defensive back Antonio Carter (5-10, 180), both of Tallahassee. ...
Tight end/quarterback Gary Godsey (6-8, 255) of Tampa, the younger
brother of Georgia Tech backup quarterback George Godsey, committed
to Notre Dame. ... Westlake's Detronn Harris is leaning to Arkansas
over Louisville and Auburn. ... Dunwoody's Jeff Womble favors
Florida State over Tennessee, Florida and Georgia. ... Middle
Georgia coach Randy Pippin says linebacker Kendrell Bell will chose
between Georgia and Mississippi State in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
