<HEADER>
A1823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN-CO     01-20 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no time like the first time
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Bradley
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is the first time. It might or might not be the
last time. It is absolutely the best time.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are going to the Super Bowl. Five months ago, five
days ago, who among us thought it possible? That's why this will be
the time of all possible times. No matter what happens 10 days
hence in Pro Player Stadium, no matter how many Super Bowls the
Falcons might _ or might not _ go on to win, this will be the one
we treasure, the one we highlight, the one that serves as our
psychic touchstone.
</P>
<P>
   The first time, by definition, comes once. The first time is all
innocence and bliss, all wide eyes and full hearts. Nobody is
jaded, nobody too consumed by what the outcome will be. (If the
Falcons beat Denver, great. If not, still great.) We're not yet
bottom-liners with these Dirty Birds. We're not yet where we are
with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   There was, you'll recall, another first time. The Braves won the
NL West in 1991, came from 3-2 down to beat Pittsburgh and thereby
qualified for _ the World Series! Hadn't happened before. For all
we knew, it might never happen again. And we, meaning all of us,
were, as they say, In The Moment. We bought our foam tomahawks and
grappled for tickets and thought of nothing else. Outside the old
stadium, guys took turns beating a tom-tom all day and all of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   It was the time of our lives, and not just ours. ``Ninety-five
was great,'' Steve Avery said, meaning the year the Braves finally
won it all, ``but '91 was the best.'' The Braves lost Game 7 in the
Metrodome, but we didn't much care. Half a million of us turned out
for a parade to salute the gallant runners-up, a parade that so
overflowed with good feeling it nearly became a riot.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lemke was our scruffy idol, Terry Pendleton our fearless
leader, John Schuerholz our guiding light. The Braves had taken us
where we never thought they would, and for that we all gave
heartfelt thanks. But the heart hardens with time. Atlanta has
hosted six more baseball postseasons, each less momentous than the
one before. Remember last October and the unsold seats? Back in the
giddy days of 1991, did anyone believe we could become so blase?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have given us a second chance at a first time.
Through them, we get to live again what was supposed to happen only
once. The Falcons have given us new heroes, new amazements. The
Falcons have overridden cynicism and negativity, have reminded us
that sports can be about something other than grousing about Bobby
Cox's lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   But with First Time, Take 2, there comes the built-in caveat:
Wring every drop of enjoyment from it now. If they beat Denver,
we'll demand that they do it again. If they lose, we'll wonder what
strengthening moves will be made. Sure, we'll buy more tickets for
their games and pay attention in a way we haven't, but nothing the
Falcons do will ever seem so sweet, so pure, so uplifting.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days until Super Bowl XXXIII. Ten days to drink in the
elixir we thought had been guzzled. Ten days to feel like a
5-year-old on Christmas morning. Ten precious days.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: markb(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
