<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS21-COX     01-20 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laettner is dealt to Pistons
 &HT;    By Jeffery Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA opens its doors at 2 p.m., but the Atlanta Hawks are in
desperate straits and apparently far from ready. They can't even
practice today.
</P>
<P>
   With the seven-year working agreement finally in place, player
signings can commence at 2 and teams can start practice at that
point. The 50-game schedule will be released today (NBA.com at 5
p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   But the Hawks have been turned down by important outside free
agents and are having a difficult time getting their own under
contract.
</P>
<P>
   When the bell rings they likely won't have enough players to
hold a scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks learned Wednesday that free-agent forward Rick Fox had
turned them down for the second time. His agent said he has elected
to remain with the Los Angeles Lakers with whom he will be eligible
for an early Larry Bird contract next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks had already lost forward Billy Owens, who goes from
Sacramento to Seattle in a sign-and-trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   They were foiled in a bid to complete such a maneuver with
Christian Laettner when he agreed to a three-year, $18 million deal
with Detroit. The Pistons must clear $2 million of cap room to make
that happen.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the Hawks are making no progress with young power forward
Alan Henderson after two negotiating sessions between general
manager Pete Babcock and agent Bill Strickland, who returned to
Washington, D.C., Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have six players, including holdovers Mookie Blaylock,
Steve Smith, Dikembe Mutombo and Ed Gray, plus rookies Roshown
McLeod and Shammond Williams.
</P>
<P>
   They are expected to tender forward Tyrone Corbin an offer at
the $1 million minimum, but Corbin said Wednesday afternoon he
would like a two-year deal and had not heard from the team. Corbin
does not have an agent but has asked Steve Smith's representative
Dr. Charles Tucker to look around for him in case the Hawks do not
come through.
</P>
<P>
   One ray of hope came in the form of a teaser. Charles Barkley, a
free agent, said he would decide among Houston, Seattle and Atlanta
by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, general manager Pete Babcock and scouting director
Gary Wortman were working the phones to line up players for camp,
if only on ``make goods.'' One of these, Ivano Newbill, declined
and headed to Washington, the only team to make him a firm offer.
The Wizards expect center Georghe Muresan to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Corbin and Henderson, the Hawks will only have eight
players until recruits come to town. They can't practice today
because Life University's court isn't available, so they will start
two-a-days at 9:30 Friday morning with a public practice Saturday
at 5:30 at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Hawks president Stan Kasten said Babcock was working to develop
a full roster as he attempts to bring in a contributing small
forward or power forward to fill the middle-class exception slot at
$1.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of Henderson, Kasten said, ``The important thing
is we want him and he wants to play here,'' but the two sides may
be as much as $3 million apart in salary for this season on a
six-or-seven year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a number of other teams have been doing business
successfully, for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the important deals in progress:.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Conference favorite Indiana will sign free-agent
center-forward Sam Perkins for two years, $3.7 million and may also
add veteran point guard Derek Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent forwards Loy Vaught and Laettner are going to
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   New York has landed troubled Latrell Sprewell from Golden State
for John Starks and Chris Mills after acquiring young forward
Marcus Camby for Charles Oakley in June. Meanwhile, and power
broker agent David Falk was trying to find a way to gift wrap
free-agent point guard Rod Strickland for them.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando will pick up free-agent center Ike Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte will sign forward Derrick Coleman, but lost centers
Matt Geiger (Philadelphia) and Vlade Divac (still unsigned).
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is bringing in defensive center Jim McIlwaine from
Seattle where he was known as Wally's Folly after being signed to a
rich contract by general manager Wally Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle reportedly has agreed to a sign and trade deal for Owens
and, after going $3 million under the cap and could go $5 million
under, using that to land Divac.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix has added free agent center Luc Longley, but has
apparently lost Antonio McDyess to Denver and is pursuing Tom
Gugliotta who wants to play there.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento wants Divac but would have to renounce power forward
Michael Stewart and forward Corliss Williamson to put a blockbuster
deal together.
</P>
<P>
   As for the agreement, the NBA yielded on one point Wednesday,
permitting six-year contracts for middle class exception players
after agreeing to three years. There was also disagreement over
several lesser details that were decided early Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
