<HEADER>
A1826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      01-20 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW FALLS 19.31 AMID PROFIT-TAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Minn., Mass., N.J.) (lb) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shrugging off the latest caution by Alan Greenspan,
the Federal Reserve Board chairman, stock prices marched higher
during the morning on Wednesday but then faded in the final hour or
so and ended mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, technology stocks supplied much of the lift, spurred
by the surprisingly strong profits reported by Microsoft after the
markets closed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But with the quarterly earnings season in full stride, investors
seemed inclined to take profits on upbeat reports, with General
Motors a prominent example. The auto giant's shares jumped as much
as 4 points, to 92 _ practically double their low on Oct. 8 _ after
announcing a big jump in earnings, only to slip back to 88 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   And several Internet stocks, which have dazzled for so long,
fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 19.31 points, or 0.2
percent, to 9,335.91, after rising nearly 125 points during the
day. Nineteen of its 30 blue-chip components posted losses. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index and the Nasdaq composite index
followed a similar pattern but hung on to small gains. Nasdaq edged
up 7.32 points, to 2,415.49, its second straight record, and the
S&AMP;P 500 rose 4.62 points, to 1,256.62.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market valuation level scares a lot of people,'' said
James Paulsen, chief strategist at Norwest Investment Management in
Minneapolis. Nonetheless, he added, the economy is strong and stock
prices relative to bond prices are still lower than they were last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan was less blunt in his appraisal of the stock market,
the subject of close scrutiny by policy-makers these days. He told
the House Ways and Means Committee on Wednesday that current
valuation levels ``would appear to envision substantially greater
growth of profits than has been experienced of late.''
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan, confirming widespread belief, also seemed to rule
out raising interest rates despite an economy still growing
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't have a global crisis, you'd be worried that the
guy is setting himself for a tightening stance,'' said Mark Lapman,
executive vice president of Independence Investment Associates in
Boston. ``But he can't do that at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that President Clinton's State of the Union
message, which included a proposal to invest Social Security money
in stocks, was a modest plus on Wednesday. Tobacco stocks, however,
tumbled because of the president's surprise announcement of a
federal lawsuit. Philip Morris fell 2 3/8, to 48 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft surged 7, to 162 5/8, while Dell Computer rose 3 3/16,
to 85 5/16. Texas Instruments rose 6 5/8, to 99 5/8, after
reporting improved profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong earnings seem to be carrying the market,'' Michael
Pendergast, managing director of HGK Asset Management in Jersey
City, N.J., said before the late swoon.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet stocks were weak throughout. Amazon.com skidded 27,
to 113, its biggest decline since Aug. 31. Ebay fell 16, to 213};
Yahoo was down 35 13/16, to 287 3/16; Broadcast.com dropped 17 3/8,
to 120, and Excite slid 13 3/8, to 96 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Airline stocks were also pounded, with U S Airways falling 6
5/16, to 51 1/8, and AMR, the parent of American Airlines, down 4
7/16, to 59 13/16, after both companies reported disappointing
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a bit of profit-taking coming in here,'' said
Joseph Battipaglia, chief strategist at Gruntal.
</P>
<P>
   As these groups faltered, some stocks that had been under
pressure of late rebounded. Among them were shares of drug
companies, with Pfizer up 3 13/16, to 119 11/16, Lilly and
Schering-Plough up more than 2 each and Bristol-Myers Squibb and
Merck each up more than a point.
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange volume picked up to 905 million from 787
million.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ending lower Wednesday held a slim margin over those
advancing, 1,587 to 1,478.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, stocks gained in nearly every major foreign market.
Brazil's Bovespa surged 3.98 percent; Mexico's Bolsa was up 4.77
percent, and Germany's DAX index rose 3.15 percent. Lesser gains
were 1.87 percent in Japan, 1.8 percent in France, 1.29 percent in
Britain and 0.2 percent in Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
