<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kirk gets help in BASS win
 &HT;    By Scott Benarde
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danny Kirk needs to send a thank-you card to one of the
lockmasters on the Kissimmee, Fla., Chain of Lakes. Along with his
last-minute fishing ability, she was a necessary ingredient in the
Bartow angler's win last weekend at the BASS Master Florida Top 150
bass tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The lockmaster reopened the lock at the last minute after Kirk
had caught two fish in his final 10 minutes that were big enough to
lift him past local guide Terry Segraves and well-known pro Shaw
Grigsby and earn him the first-place check of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really need to send her a card,'' Kirk said Tuesday. ``But I
don't even know her name.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the chain of more than 10 lakes are linked by canals and
a series of dams and locks, Kirk needed to pass through a lock to
get back to the weigh-in in time to avoid any penalties. The
weigh-in was on Lake Tohopekaliga, two lakes away from Lake
Hatchineha, where Kirk was fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk, 41, had planned to leave his spot on Hatchineha at 1:30
p.m. to make the 2:30 weigh-in, but at 1:27, he caught his fifth
keeper _ the limit is five fish _ out of a large school of fish.
With more fish nearby, he pushed the deadline and caught two more
to replace two smaller ones and left his spot at 1:37. He caught
the final two fish on a Carolina-rigged chartreuse/pepper centipede
Zoom soft plastic bait.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Kirk hadn't reached the lock, the lockmaster gave
him an extra minute or two. ``They heard me coming,'' Kirk said.
``They knew how many of us were down there, so they waited.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk's four-day total of 20 fish weighing 41 pounds was seven
ounces heavier than fish caught by Segraves and Grigsby, who both
caught 40 pounds, 9 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first major win for Kirk, who hopes the win will lead
to a berth in his second consecutive BASS Masters Classic this
summer, and the first major win for a Georgian since Kim Carver's
win in the Red Man All-American last year.
</P>
<P>
   The win lifted Kirk to 36th in the trail's points standings with
three tournaments remaining. The top 25 points winners advance to
the Classic. Kirk has 377 points; 412 is 25th place. However,
because the worst finish is thrown out in determining Classic
qualifiers, Kirk's 112th place in season's first tournament in
Maryland could disappear and move him up in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Bruce of Buford also had a top-10 finish, placing fifth
with a 38-6 total, earning him $14,000. Bruce is 39th in the points
standings. Canton's Mark Hardin was 13th with a 25-5 total for
three days; only the top 10 fished in the final round. That finish
earned him $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   New licensing system
</P>
<P>
   The Wildlife Resources Division of the state Department of
Natural Resources is installing its new electronic license system
for 1999. Pilot sites for field tests should be open by the end of
the week. Sites include regional WRD offices, Bass Pro Shops in
Duluth and the Sports Authority on Northlake Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   Show a success
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill Williams' fishing show last weekend at the North Atlanta
Trade Center drew compliments from patrons, exhibitors and the
producer. Producer Bill Winzinger was happy because ``all the
asphalt in the parking lot was covered.'' Exhibitors such as West
Point Lake guide Ron Savage were happy because they were booking
fishing trips from a crowd that, while not close to being as large
as a Fisharama, was in a spending mood.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
