<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0512 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1834 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ART-NYT &LR;      01-20 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS WEIGH MOVE FOR QUICK VOTE ON IMPEACHMENT ARTICLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., R.I., S.D., S.C., La., Calif., Fla., Ark.)  (ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo/graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds: See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Buoyed by the White House's impeachment defense and
hoping that Senate Republicans are starting to tire, several Senate
Democrats said Wednesday that they might propose voting on the two
impeachment articles early next week in another attempt to end the
trial without calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Some Senate Democrats, according to their aides, think it is
possible to muster enough Republicans to win a vote on a motion to
proceed to the articles. But under the impeachment rules adopted
unanimously by the Senate, a single senator could block such a
move.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed highly unlikely that all 55 Republicans would agree to
bypass witnesses. Many Republicans have indicated they want to hear
witnesses, though not very many and not for very long.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats have argued that witnesses are unnecessary, and
would only prolong a trial that is already unpopular with the
public. Even if they lost a motion, however, to vote on the
impeachment articles and thus avoid witnesses, they could still
claim a political triumph by painting the Republicans as dragging
out the proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think many senators at that point of time will have serious
reservations about whether additional witnesses or any witnesses
are needed,'' said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., who is a leading
advocate of an early vote on the impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   Many Senate Republicans dismissed Democratic predictions that
calling witnesses would push a trial into March or April, and
consume all other Senate business. ``I don't think it has to be a
mob scene,'' said Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I. ``They can do it
swiftly.''
</P>
<P>
   But some senior Republican aides acknowledged on the second day
of the White House defense that several senators were eyeing the
calendar and calculating how much time witnesses might take.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're sensing appropriate concern,'' said one top Republican
aide. ``The White House hasn't shifted anyone on the need for
witnesses, but the general fatigue of the process may be adding to
the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate agreement, senators are to debate and vote
early next week on whether to dismiss the case and whether to
depose witnesses. A separate vote would be required on which, if
any, witnesses would be called in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerry's plan, which has the blessing of Sen. Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., the Democratic leader, would substitute the vote to dismiss
with a vote to proceed to a vote on the impeachment charges _
perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., said he would offer Kerry's plan after
the vote on a motion to dismiss. ``If there are 40 or 45 votes on
the motions,'' he said, ``there is a clear indication there are not
sufficient votes to convict.''
</P>
<P>
   That would pave the way to a vote on the articles of
impeachment, Breaux said. But, again, under the Senate agreement,
any one senator could block such a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans prosecuting Clinton repeated their pleas
Wednesday that their case would be incomplete without calling
witnesses. The House managers want to call at least Monica
Lewinsky, Betty Currie and Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president's version is correct, why is he so afraid to
allow these witnesses to come down and just simply take an oath,
stand before the bar of the Senate and tell the truth?'' said Rep.
James Rogan, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Off the Senate floor, the managers fiercely rebutted the White
House's arguments, issuing 14 news releases Wednesday using the
format ``White House Claim'' and ``The Truth.'' The managers
challenged the White House's facts and interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate over witnesses intensifies, the House prosecutors
are sharply divided over whether to offer new evidence next week
that some managers say points to a pattern of obstruction of
justice by Clinton and his aides.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate would have to admit such evidence into the record by
a majority vote, and some Democrats and Republicans say they are
deeply skeptical of introducing material that is outside the scope
of the two impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether the House prosecutors, or managers, should
offer unsubstantiated evidence about Clinton's alleged encounters
with several women, some of whom denied those allegations under
oath in affidavits filed in the Paula Jones civil case.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the obstruction of justice charge, House prosecutors
accuse Clinton of encouraging Ms. Lewinsky to cover up their affair
by filing a false affidavit in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the prosecutors feel they can buttress that charge by
giving senators examples of other allegations of sexual misconduct
in which, the managers claim, women might have been pressured not
to disclose the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no interest in getting into any of the sexual
aspects,'' said Rogan. ``What I am very interested in are the
potential facts that may relate to false affidavits being filed.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of the other 13 managers fear that bringing up the
salacious material, which was not part of the impeachment articles,
would distract senators from the prosecution's core case, and give
appearance the prosecutors are desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't be going too far afield from the scope of our
presentation,'' said Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla. ``It is important
we stay focused on our presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the lead manager, indicated in an
interview that he is cool to the idea of introducing new material
at this late stage of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors say they will not settle their internal debate,
which was first reported in Wednesday's editions of The Hill, a
Capitol Hill semiweekly newspaper, until they gauge the impact of
the White House's defense and questions from senators.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans and Democrats were preparing for the 16-hour
questioning period at the end of this week, by culling and
organizing queries submitted by lawmakers to avoid repetition and
put them in a logical order.
</P>
<P>
   Among the women the managers might want to introduce is Kathleen
Willey, a former White House volunteer who accused Clinton of
groping her outside the Oval Office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the House managers, Reps. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., and Asa
Hutchinson, R-Ark., met last week with Ms. Willey and her lawyer,
and came away divided on whether she could strengthen the
prosecution's case.
</P>
</TEXT>
