<HEADER>
A1839 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     01-20 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPALDING GRAY SAYS WE AIN'T GOT BRAINS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Spalding Gray &LR; , whose ``Morning, Noon and Night'' received
mixed reviews when it played here New Year's week, gives his own
mixed reviews to the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   When performing here, he says in the latest issue of Elle,
``People get what I'm doing, they understand it, they know what
irony is _ but they won't let themselves indulge. Last time I
performed in Berkeley there was a lag between the lines and the
laughter. I realized it was the audience's inner censor, reviewing
it all in their heads: Is this PC? Is this spiritually correct? Is
it all right to laugh?''
</P>
<P>
   He describes the difference between Cambridge, Mass., and
Berkeley, ``which are, to me, similar towns on different coasts. I
remember asking a married woman in Cambridge whether or not she had
ever had an extramarital affair. And she said: `I'm not gonna
answer that.' I said: `Why?' She said, `Because I live here _ and
you're leaving tomorrow.' This is good, I thought. She knows how to
make boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out in San Francisco the tendency would be to go into a really
detailed confession. A woman there was talking about how she was
trying to do an art piece. ... She was having a real problem with
it. I said: `Why?' She said: `Because they're all controlled by
men, and ... well, I've never told anyone this before, but I'm gay.
And I have my lover here in the audience ...' The trumpets were
blowing, the audience was cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   The interviewer asks Gray why there's that difference between
Cambridge and San Francisco, and he cites the old saw: ``Someone
tipped the United States on its side and all the smart people held
on. ... There's definitely a different race out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MAKING OF A HIT FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Actor &UR; Val Kilmer &LR; , profiled in the latest issue of W, has less
than fine memories of some of the films he's made. In ``Top Gun,''
for example, Kilmer played a smaller part than stars  &UR; Tom &LR; 
 &UR; Cruise  &LR; and  &UR; Kelly McGillis &LR; , who was a college friend from
Juilliard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any scenes together in `Top Gun,' '' he said,
``but we'd hang together and she'd come over and cry, `I'm four
feet taller than him!' Believe me, that movie didn't feel like it
looked. I don't know how much movie there is if you take out the
second-unit flying stuff and the soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did an amazing job on all that stuff, but it just didn't
feel like we were really on  &LR; to something there. Then it made all
that money, and people still talk about it and revere it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ House Judiciary Chairman  &UR; Henry Hyde  &LR; was one of the
Republicans who didn't attend  &UR; President Clinton &LR; 's State of the
Union message Tuesday night because he ``doesn't like large
crowds,'' his press secretary told the Washington Post. Hyde said
he would ``leap to my feet in applause in the comfort of my living
room.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Still getting even for the president not having served in
Vietnam?  &UR; Steve Warren &LR;  forwards word that the movie broadcast just
before the State of the Union message by AFTRS, the Armed Forces
Radio &AMP; Television Service, was ``Devil in a Blue Dress.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Comforting news for you who have been trying to beat the
president's six-minute crossword record:  &UR; Jon Delfin &LR;  points out
that the crossword puzzle  &UR; Will Shortz &LR;  watched Clinton whiz
through in 1992 was not from the New York Times. It had been
specially prepared for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mailing several letters, &UR; Carole Terwilliger Meyers &LR; ' husband
inadvertently dropped a batch of 32-cent stamps into the mailbox.
The good news is that a few days after Meyers reached the
lost-and-found at the postal service's 800 number, the ``stamps
magically appeared in my mailbox.'' Congratulations to the ``Loose
in the Mails'' (a real department) staff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Michael Moore &LR; 's new show, ``The Awful Truth,'' starts
broadcast in England in March and in April in the United States (on
Bravo). The first show, notes  &UR; Gar Smith &LR; , features Christmas
carolers outside R.J. Reynolds' headquarters. The singers are all
former smokers who lost their voice boxes to disease.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Q: If you were offered the chance to play Bill Clinton in the
story of his life, would you take it? A: I can't even begin to
comment on my feelings about Clinton. If we're talking about
masculinity and tenderness, I don't look at Clinton. I think our
heroes have to be honest. You know,  &UR; Abe Lincoln &LR; ,  &UR; Gary Cooper &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Aaron Eckhart, who played the masculine villain in ``In the
Company of Men,'' praising the president who freed the slaves and
the actor who played cowboys.
</P>
