<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Golden West Profit up 20% In Hot Market  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Golden West Financial Corp., the giant Oakland savings and loan,
said yesterday its fourth-quarter profit rose 19.9 percent as it
took advantage of a sizzling housing market to make a record volume
of mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Golden West, which operates under the name World Savings,
reported net income of $112 million ($1.95 a diluted share) for the
quarter ended in December. In the 1997 fourth quarter, the thrift
earned $93.5 million ($1.62).
</P>
<P>
   The latest profit beat the average analyst forecast of $1.84 a
share, according to First Call Corp. The thrift's shares rose $1.50
to $89.50 on the New York Stock Exchange &LR;   &LR; yesterday. Golden West
specializes in adjustable-rate mortgages, or ARMs. It keeps ARMs in
its loan portfolio, and it originates fixed-rate loans and sells
them to investors on the secondary market.
</P>
<P>
   When interest rates are low, as they are now, borrowers
generally shun ARMs, instead favoring fixed-rate mortgages to lock
in cheap rates.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this unfriendly climate for ARMs in the fourth quarter,
Golden West made $2.5 billion in mortgages, up 27 percent from the
comparable period the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Although Golden West made more fixed-rate loans than usual, the
thrift still was successful selling its staple product. Almost
three of every four mortgages it originated during the period were
adjustable.
</P>
<P>
   That was down from the 93 percent ARM rate in the 1997 fourth
quarter but still was one of the highest percentages in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Golden West posted big gains on
secondary-market sales of the fixed-rate loans that it did make.
That helped push up noninterest income 72.8 percent during the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a much better quarter than expected,'' said Caren
Mayer, an analyst with NationsBanc Montgomery Securities in San
Francisco. ``They showed a real ability to stick to their strategy
and generate great earnings in this environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden West's total assets fell 2.8 percent during the year to
$38.5 billion because of its sales of fixed-rate loans.
</P>
<P>
   Golden West also benefited from falling interest rates on
deposits, which went down faster than rates on its mortgages. The
wider gap between what Golden West collected from borrowers and
what it paid to depositors helped boost net interest income 5.7
percent from the year-ago period.
</P>
</TEXT>
