<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1844 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON &LR;      01-20 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Apologetic Pac Bell Cuts Line to Telemarketing Firm  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pacific Bell said yesterday that it canceled its contract with a
telemarketing firm that was misleading customers about Caller ID
blocking, and will call back everyone who got the telemarketing
pitch to see whether they have the service they want.
</P>
<P>
   The phone company terminated the contract after learning that
Business Response Inc. of St. Louis was doing things ``that
shouldn't have been done,'' Pac Bell spokesman John Britton said.
</P>
<P>
   The company hired BRI to call Pac Bell customers and recommend
that they drop a free service called complete blocking of Caller
ID.
</P>
<P>
   Caller ID is a box that attaches to a phone and displays the
number of an incoming call. Complete blocking prevents a caller's
phone number from appearing in the Caller ID box of the person
receiving the call.
</P>
<P>
   Some Pac Bell customers who got the telemarketing pitch said
they were told that complete blocking no longer existed and that
they would have to switch to selective blocking, which requires
callers to dial 67 each time they make a call in order to block
their phone number from a Caller ID box.
</P>
<P>
   Others were told that a new law would soon end complete blocking
and that customers who did not take advantage of selective blocking
now would have to pay for it later.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those assertions are untrue.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires that all phone companies, including Pac Bell,
offer complete blocking and selective blocking free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Pac Bell suspended the contract with BRI and began
an investigation after getting inquiries from customers and The
Chronicle about the misleading calls.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said the company met with BRI yesterday and found that
some telemarketers were telling customers wrong information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that there were some things a couple of agents did
that were outside the parameters of the scripts we provided,''
Britton said. ``This is a company that's highly respected, and
we're not condemning them at all, but we have acknowledged there
were some things done that shouldn't have been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Britton said he was not sure why the telemarketers were
misleading customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes things happen with employees,'' he said. BRI's
telemarketers work on commission, but Britton would not say whether
that was an incentive.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said this was the first time Pac Bell used the firm,
which came ``highly recommended'' from SBC Communications of San
Antonio, Texas, Pac Bell's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   The phone company has been pushing for customers to dump
complete blocking because it has hurt sales of Caller ID. About 44
percent of California customers have blocks on their lines, meaning
that their phone numbers will not appear in Caller ID boxes. Only
12 percent of customers have subscribed to Caller ID, according to
Pac Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said BRI was supposed to ``recommend'' that a customer
drop the blocking, not force them to get rid of the service.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tyler, chief human resources officer with BRI, said the
company was ``working with Pac Bell on this very closely'' but
referred all inquiries about the contract back to Pac Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler would not discuss the calls some Pac Bell customers say
they received.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of newspaper articles on the misleading
telemarketing calls, Pac Bell engaged in some damage control
yesterday, instructing its service representatives to assure any
customer who called that Pac Bell is not doing anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   According to a script obtained by The Chronicle, Pac Bell
service representatives are supposed to tell customers: ``I can
understand how you might be concerned after reading an article like
that.'' And, ``We only offer our products and services in (an)
ethical and legal manner.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PACBELL2 (79034 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Britton said Pac Bell wants to make sure customers know that the
phone company is sorry for any confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really are committed to honest, ethical selling
relationships,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that at some point, Pac Bell may start calling
customers again to ``educate them'' about their blocking options.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell canceled the BRI contract just before today's hearings
at the Public Utilities Commission into whether Pac Bell engaged in
aggressive and misleading sales pitches in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
