<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1846 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PGE-SFCHRON &LR;      01-20 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PG&AMP;E Posts Glowing Profit  &HT;       
 By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
PG&AMP;E's earnings more than doubled for the fourth quarter, beating
stock analysts' expectations and signaling that the utility holding
company is learning how to capitalize on electric industry
deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E Corp., parent of Pacific Gas and Electric Co. and four
other subsidiaries, said it earned $196 million (51 cents per
share) on operating revenues of $5.5 billion for the quarter,
blasting past a lackluster profit of $94 million (22 cents)
recorded a year ago on revenues of $4.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1998, PG&AMP;E earned $719 million ($1.88) on revenues of
$19.9 billion, a 7 percent boost compared to per-share earnings of
$1.75 for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E stock rose $1 to close at $31.50 on news of the quarterly
earnings, which were one-third higher than Wall Street expected.
The company also announced yesterday that it will buy back 4 to 5
percent of its common shares, worth $570 million, on the open
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers were exceptionally good,'' said Daniel Tulis,
utility analyst for NationsBanc Montgomery Securities in New York,
who issued a ``strong buy'' recommendation on PG&AMP;E stock.
``Management is starting to get good results from the nonregulated
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to PG&AMP;E's future performance is U.S. Generating Co.,
PG&AMP;E's nonregulated power plant operator based in Bethesda, Md.
During the past year, while regulated utility Pacific Gas and
Electric has been selling off power plants, U.S. Gen has been on a
buying spree.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Gen logged revenues of $650 million for 1998, nearly half
of which came in the final quarter and stemmed from the purchase of
5,100 megawatts of generating capacity from the New England
Electric Sys tem. The fourth quarter was the first full quarter to
reflect revenues from that $1.59 billion acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PGE21 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Although U.S. Gen's contribution to corporate earnings still is
small compared with Pacific Gas and Electric's _ 28 cents per share
versus $1.82 per share _ it shows the dramatic growth made possible
by deregulation. Under deregulation, state and federal regulators
are requiring mainline utilities to sell off generating plants,
generally to multiple buyers, to prevent market dominance that
could permit price gouging.
</P>
<P>
   This creates opportunities for companies like U.S. Gen. Its 1998
profit looks especially good, analysts said, when compared with the
amount it lost in 1997, 10 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the unregulated operators are getting their
house in order,'' said Douglas Christopher, utility analyst for
Crowell, Weedon &AMP; Co. in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   There's the potential for even more striking growth this year.
Parent company PG&AMP;E wants to transfer Pacific Gas and Electric's
huge California hydroelectric system to U.S. Gen if it can do so at
the right price and is seeking regulatory approval from the state
Public Utilities Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The move _ being questioned by a growing consortium of consumer
groups, environmental organizations and water districts _ has the
potential to add another 3,850 megawatts of generating capacity to
U.S. Gen's system. In addition, U.S. Gen is expected to bid on
power plant divestitures by New York's Consolidated Edison and
others in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   By year's end, U.S. Gen's generating capacity could approach the
amount held by Pacific Gas and Electric prior to energy industry
deregulation which began nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The key difference, both to consumers and PG&AMP;E Corp., is that
the electricity is no longer being priced by regulators, based on
annual utility costs. Instead, deregulation means that commodity
prices are being set by a new electricity marketplace where prices
fluctuate _ sometimes wildly _ by the hour, day and season. Whereas
profits of regulated utilities are capped by regulators at 9 to 12
percent, there are no limitations on the profits allowed
unregulated generators in the commodities energy market.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of PGE21 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Although its power generation business appears to be doing well,
PG&AMP;E still is losing money on the marketing side. PG&AMP;E Energy
Services, an unregulated energy marketer, reported startup losses
that depressed corporate earnings by 14 cents per share for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to narrow losses as we leave the startup
phase,'' said David Kaplan, spokesman for PG&AMP;E Corp. in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E Corp. hopes to get more money out of Pacific Gas and
Electric this year. For 1998, the regulated utility had a return on
equity of roughly 8 percent. That's far less than the maximum
return _ 11.2 percent _ allowed by state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The company is seeking a rate hike for 1999 of nearly $1 billion
that would give it a greater shot at earning its maximum authorized
rate of return. Like the hydro transfer, it is being challenged by
consumer groups. A decision is expected from the PUC this spring.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of PGE21 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
