<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-ETHNICITY-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY OF CANCER AND RACES IS URGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif.) (lb) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Institutes of Health need to develop a
broader strategy for finding out why poor people and some ethnic
minority groups are more prone to certain cancers and less likely
to survive them than the rest of the population, an expert panel
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The NIH, the federal agency that sponsors most of the medical
research in the United States, needs to expand the study of why
ethnic and racial groups are disproportionately affected by cancer
and make certain that minority groups are adequately represented in
research trials, the panel said in a report.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-member committee of medical, health and research experts,
convened by the Institute of Medicine, said the effort to
understand the impact of cancer on subgroups in the population
would be helped by discarding traditional racial categories and
studying people on the basis of their ethnic and economic
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Use of the term ``race'' is scientifically inaccurate because it
implies fundamental biological differences, which do not exist,
among groups and masks the influence of ethnic background and
lifestyle differences that could be big factors in cancer, panel
members said at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alfred Haynes, former president of the Drew Postgraduate
Medical School in Los Angeles and chairman of the committee, said
studies within and between ethnic groups could not only help in
determining what affects their cancer risks but also provide
insights for the general population. Finding out why some ethnic
minority groups are less affected by certain cancers could lead to
ways to reduce risks for the majority, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This information will benefit all Americans and help the
medical community craft prevention strategies that work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel said African-American men, for example, have unusually
high rates of prostate cancer, while Asians are more likely to
develop stomach and liver cancer than whites are. Cervical cancer
is higher among Hispanic and Vietnamese-American women, while
African-American women are less likely than others to develop
breast cancer but also less likely to survive it. And while Alaska
natives have high rates of colon and rectal cancer, low-income
whites in rural areas such as Appalachia have some of the highest
rates of lung cancer and other cancers in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Having people in cancer studies in traditional racial categories
_ white, black, Asian or Pacific Islander, or American Indian _
makes it hard to pinpoint factors affecting incidence of the
disease and its treatment within subgroups, the panel said. Asians,
the report noted, include Vietnamese and other Southeast Asians,
Koreans, Japanese, Chinese, Indians and others who are ethnically
and culturally very different.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Congress asked the independent Institute of Medicine, part of
the National Academy of Sciences, to examine the government's
efforts to understand and deal with cancer as it affects poor
Americans, with little insurance and limited access to care, and
ethnic minorities. The committee said the NIH and its National
Cancer Institute were trying to address these issues, but needed to
devote more money and develop a government-wide plan to deal with
them.
</P>
<P>
   The panel said the cancer institute spends about $24 million a
year, or about 1 percent of its budget, on programs specifically
addressing cancer among ethnic minority groups and the poor. These
groups also are included in more general research studies, it said,
but more resources need to be devoted to programs targeted to
minority groups and the medically underserved.
</P>
</TEXT>
