<HEADER>
A1855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES21-C     01-20 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons focus on basic plays
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons practiced later in the season than
ever Wednesday, as they gathered for their first preparation for
Super Bowl XXXIII January 31 in Miami against the Broncos (16-2).
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves and his staff didn't begin installing the game
plan, per se, but they focused on Denver. That means the offense _
minus quarterback Chris Chandler, who was with wife Diane as she
prepared for childbirth _ lined up against Bronco defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons defense, meanwhile, faced Bronco plays.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of concentrating on specific ways to defend those
plays, the Falcons worked on basic schemes. The offense ran its
basic plays rather than those the coaches think stand the best
chance of working against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps the word ''concentrate'' is a poor choice.
</P>
<P>
   Players, perhaps distracted by three days of trying to take care
of ticket and hotel reservations for friends and family, had a hard
time focusing, and Reeves had to stop practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were times that we had things that didn't go the way
we'd like them to, and we . . . talked about it,'' he said. ''We
said, 'If we're going to be here . . . let's concentrate on what
we're doing.' We had a good practice after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, 0-3 as a head coach in Super Bowls with the Broncos in
the 1980s, is searching for the right formula to prepare for the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, he has tried installing the entire game plan the
week of the game, and he's tried installing the entire game plan
two weeks before the game. This time, he's trying a middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Coaches) are working on the game plan,'' he said. We're not
giving them to the players to where they're going to have to learn
them specifically. We'll try to start next week like a regular
week.''
</P>
<P>
   That means that although the Falcons will get a little more
specific in practice today and Friday, earnest preparation will
begin next week.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday and Thursday will be the most important days from a
technical standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Other plans
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has decided players will be allowed to have their
families stay with them at the Miami Airport Hilton and Towers if
they choose. Also, there will be a curfew on some nights, but not
all.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl baby
</P>
<P>
   Diane Chandler gave birth at about 2:30 p.m. Wednesday at North
Fulton Regional Hospital in Alpharetta to the couple's third
daughter. The baby girl, whose name is unknown, was 20 inches long,
and weighed six pounds and 20 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, backup quarterback Steve DeBerg, who turned 45
on Tuesday, worked with the No. 1 offense, and second-year man Tony
Graziani got much more work than normal with the No. 2 and even No.
1 offense.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler is expected to return to practice today.
</P>
<P>
   Coming back
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who underwent quadruple heart bypass surgery Dec. 14,
said he continues to get stronger, but still can't work quite as
long without getting tired. He has no doctor-prescribed limitations
on the sidelines (although he continues to stand back on punts and
kickoffs).
</P>
<P>
   He also re-iterated plans to continue coaching after this
season. ''There is no thought in my mind that I won't continue,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Going home
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will practice next week at the University of Miami.
The only former Miami player on the roster, rookie wide receiver
Jammi German, won't participate because he went on injured reserve
in November with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got mixed emotions because I want to play so bad,'' he said.
''But going back to the facility I was at for five years is
extremely exciting. I've just told the guys to bring shorts,
T-shirts, and flip-flops and they'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight redux?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised to see rookie receiver Tim Dwight line up in
the shotgun against Denver, like he did last Sunday against the
Vikings. He had two rushes for 22 yards in that game, and earlier
this season, he completed a 22-yard pass to Chandler off a reverse.
</P>
<P>
   He had eight rushes for 19 yards in the regular season before
strained knee ligaments reduced his role at midseason.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we got ready to play Minnesota, and saw some of the
things they did with (receiver/return man) David Palmer, we kind of
said, 'We don't need to save (Dwight) for next week,' '' Reeves
said. ''He's very versatile because he can run with it, throw it,
and catch it, and he's fearless.''
</P>
<P>
   Morten's the man
</P>
<P>
   Kicker Morten Andersen, whose 38-yard field goal gave the
Falcons their 30-27 overtime win over the Vikings, has worked
several prior Super Bowls as a commentator for European TV.
</P>
<P>
   The main station in his native Denmark, however, was not going
to televise this year's game because ratings have gotten so bad.
</P>
<P>
   It will be televised now.
</P>
<P>
   ''The station, TV2, bought the rights from Norway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So what current or former NFL great will do the commentary?
Former kicker Jan Stenerud?
</P>
<P>
   ''No,'' Andersen said. ''He's Norwegian.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Other than Chandler, the only player who did not practice was
left defensive end Lester Archambeau, who may not practice until
Wednesday because of a high ankle sprain. . . . Reserve safety and
nickel safety Devin Bush, who did not practice or play last week
because of a strained hamstring, practiced and said, ''It's good.
I'll be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Reeves opted to kick the game-winning field goal against
Minnesota on third-and-9 from the Vikings' 21 last Sunday in case
something went wrong. Atlanta could have called timeout, or, if the
snap was bad, holder Dan Stryzinski could have tried to recover the
fumble, down it, and then Atlanta would have lined up to try
another kick. . . . Also, the Vikings continue to be criticized for
having quarterback Randall Cunningham take a knee with 30 seconds
left in regulation rather than throw downfield on third-and-3 from
the Vikings' 27. Former Vikings offensive coordinator Brian
Billick, hired as the Ravens' coach Tuesday, said if he had it to
do again, he probably would have thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Strange questions
</P>
<P>
   You know the Super Bowl is coming when you hear questions like
those asked of wide receiver Tony Martin by a Denver TV station.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked who, between he and receiver Terance Mathis, who
would: Win a 40-yard dash? ''Me.'' A five-mile run? ''Terance.''
Fare better in a trash-talking argument with Denver tight end
Shannon Sharpe? ''Me.'' Win a comedy contest? ''Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember me?
</P>
<P>
   Reeves cut wide receiver Ed McCaffrey from the Giants in '94.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the 6-foot-5, 215-pound McCaffrey caught 64 passes
for 1,053 yards and 10 touchdowns and made the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I've ever made a mistake that bad,'' Reeves said
earlier this season. ''I've had guys go play somewhere else, but
not go on to the level where they could be an All-Pro and a major
contributor on a Super Bowl team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
