<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1856 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESCRIP-SFCHRON &LR;      01-20 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCRIP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Scrip Goes Electronic  &HT;       
 By Carolyn Said 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's a familiar sight to any parent of a school-age child: A card
table set up outside the cafeteria with PTA volunteers selling
scrip _ gift certificates to Safeway, Lucky's, Macy's, Costco,
Target and other stores _ as a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Now a San Mateo startup hopes to turn scrip sales into an
all-electronic transaction, eliminating the need for card tables,
paper certificates and volunteer time.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Scrip Inc. says it has signed up 120 California
school districts, half of them in the Bay Area, and a dozen
merchants for its program, which launches next month.
</P>
<P>
   It's also negotiating with many more merchants, but can't
identify them until contracts are signed. So far it's signed up
Andronico's, Draeger's and several smaller grocery stores; Payless
Shoe Source; Timberland; the Sharper Image; and Budget Rent a Car.
</P>
<P>
   Scrip is a big business. Schools and nonprofits buy about half a
billion dollars worth of the colorful vouchers a year from
merchants at a discount, usually about 5 percent. They resell them
at face value to parents and other supporters, who spend them in
stores just like cash. The schools keep the difference between
their purchase price and the face value.
</P>
<P>
   With the eScrip system, schools or other nonprofits sign up to
participate. Then, parents or other supporters register their
credit card and ATM card numbers with Electronic Scrip. Every time
they make a purchase at a participating vendor, a percentage of
their transaction is automatically donated to their designated
school.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Scrip, a 2-year-old profit-making venture, plans to
go national later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's electronic, we can spread it beyond just grocery
and department stores,'' said Ian Diery, Electronic Scrip's chief
executive and a former Apple Computer vice president. ``We intend
to reach to many types of merchants _ airlines, hotels, anywhere
you use a credit card. We can really enlarge the scope of scrip so &LR; 
 &LR; schools will have a tremendous opportunity to raise more money.``
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of ESCRIP21 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The company ( &LR; www.escripinc.com &LR; ) sends monthly reports to
schools summarizing how much they've received, to parents showing
how much they donated, and to merchants showing how many eScrip
customers patronized their store, how much they spent and where
they shopped.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit for parents is that they don't need to buy scrip
ahead of time, tying up their cash, or have it on hand when they're
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks can still get frequent flier miles or other benefits
that exist on their credit cards,`` said Joanne Remillard,
Electronic Scrip's executive vice president. ``That's a big plus.''
</P>
<P>
   One drawback is that many will be reluctant to turn over their
credit and ATM card numbers.
</P>
<P>
   And parents who participate in eScrip must pay the company a $10
annual fee. They pay no fee with paper scrip.
</P>
<P>
   The National Scrip Center, a 10-year-old Santa Rosa nonprofit
that is the nation's largest clearinghouse for scrip purchases, is
planning its own electronic version of scrip. But Edward Phillips,
its chief operating officer, is dubious about Electronic Scrip.
``They're a for-profit company that will have to report to their
investors,'' he said. ``They're taking a lot of fees out so the
school gets less.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Scrip Center, which works with 8,000 schools and
nonprofits and 220 merchants, takes 1 percent or less of each
transaction to cover its expenses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Scrip wouldn't disclose its fees, but said they will
be offset by its broader reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'd get a lower percentage with eScrip than we do by
selling paper scrip, but they might have many more merchants than
what we carry. The wider selection would make up the difference in
the percentage,'' said Joan Donovan, scrip coordinator for the San
Mateo/ Foster City Community Education Foundation, which sells
$100,000 of scrip a month to supporters of 20 public elementary
schools in the district. Her organization plans to have a dozen
board members try eScrip for a couple of months to evaluate it.
</P>
<P>
   Budget Rent a Car contracted with Electronic Scrip to be the
only rental car company represented. With paper scrip, Budget gave
schools 8 percent of the money parents spent. With eScrip, it will
still give schools 8 percent _ on top of a 2 percent administrative
fee it pays Electronic Scrip.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of ESCRIP21 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Why is it willing to pay more? ``We think the revenue potential
is greater,'' said Beth Murphy, consumer marketing manager at
Budget. ``It could work out to be a significant amount of
incremental revenue for us, as well as a way to make our customers
feel good about renting with Budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Paper scrip is a huge hassle for schools, which have to front
the money to buy it, figure out a secure place to store it, and
employ an army of volunteers to sell and deliver it. It's also a
bother for merchants.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a retailer, (eScrip) is far less work for me, because they
are using the standard electronic fund transfer network,'' said
Peter Draeger, chief financial officer of Draeger's Market, a chain
of food stores on the Peninsula that sells scrip.
</P>
<P>
   The eScrip system ``would be great for us because it would
release us from a lot of the manpower _ really womanpower _ of
selling scrip,'' said Linda Okamoto, who co-chairs the scrip
committee for two schools in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   But she hasn't yet signed on with eScrip because its merchant
selection is still limited. ``We would really want to have
Safeway,'' she said. ``They're going to have to get the big guys:
Target, Mervyn's, Macy's. If they get a whole lot of merchants and
they're widespread, then it would be great.'' She also said the $10
annual fee per consumer could be a stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Diery, who oversaw Apple Computer's launch of its Power
Macintosh line, said Electronic Scrip has taken every precaution to
safeguard consumers' privacy and their credit cards' security.
</P>
<P>
   But a big draw for merchants will be the opportunity to tap into
the millions of customers Diery hopes to sign up. ``We have the
opportunity to drive tremendous communication with the customer,''
he said. ``But we will be very sparing about things like doing
inserts with our (monthly reports to customers) because we don't
want to invade privacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
