<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1865 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEOFUNION-CLINTON-     01-20 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFUNION-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON EXPANDS ON STATE OF THE UNION THEMES BEFORE ENTHUSIASTIC
CROWDS
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Pa., Wis.) (Eds.: Subs for inserts and extensive rewriting throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORRISTOWN, Pa. _ An exuberant President Clinton starred in two
rollicking rallies on Wednesday where he amplified the themes of
his State of the Union message and attacked Republican proposals to
use the federal budget surplus for across-the-board tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, accompanied by Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President
Al Gore and Tipper Gore, received a rock star's reception at the
Marine Midland Arena in Buffalo on Wednesday afternoon from 21,000
residents of western New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, he addressed several thousand spirited
students and parents in a packed high school gymnasium in
Norristown, a suburb northwest of Philadelphia. The city is in a
moderate swing district whose seat in Congress has changed parties
three times since 1992. The Democrats won it back in 1998, after
two terms in Republican hands, with the election of Joseph M.
Hoeffel.
</P>
<P>
   The president has attended few such mass events over the past
year of scandal and investigation, and he was rewarded with a
rapturous response from campaign-style crowds drawn by White House
advance teams distributing thousands of free tickets through local
unions, churches, schools and political offices.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no mention in either of his appearances Wednesday
of the Senate impeachment proceedings, where two White House
lawyers delivered extensive rebuttals on Wednesday afternoon to
charges of perjury and obstruction of justice against the
president. No one in Clinton's entourage nor any of the local
officials who introduced them raised the subject of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo, Clinton fairly glowed as speaker after speaker
praised his good works and glossed over his legal and political
problems. At the end of his half-hour speech, he called Wednesday
``one of the great days of my presidency.'' White House aides said
that Buffalo had been chosen for Wednesday's rally because it is a
Democratic stronghold of working-class families. Officials said the
Buffalo throng was the largest American crowd Clinton had addressed
since an appearance in LaCrosse, Wis., last January, the day after
his last State of the Union speech.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Bennett W. Smith, who is black, said in an invocation
that Clinton has been ``the greatest president for our people of
all time.'' Smith called on the Lord to ``comfort him with Your
word, that no weapon formed against him shall prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton received a huge ovation when she rose to introduce
her husband. Several in the crowd held signs in support of her
imagined candidacy for the U.S. Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who appeared energized by the rally, growled lustily to
the crowd, ``We can have the future we deserve because we already
have the president we deserve!''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said that the State of the Union speech
marked a turning point for the country and called on the huge
audience to help fight for the president's expansive policy agenda.
The crowd rose to its feet and roared.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could hardly match the passion of the preacher and the
vice president. He noted that he and Gore had taken the oath of
office for the first time six years ago on Wednesday and marveled
at how quickly the years had passed. ``They have been, to put it
mildly, eventful,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But policy, not nostalgia, was on his mind on Wednesday. So he
offered a half-hour dissertation on the aging of America and the
importance of shoring up Social Security and Medicare for the baby
boomers.
</P>
<P>
   He said that today's prosperity must be used to insure a
financially secure future, not to satisfy momentary urges for
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot afford to squander this moment,'' the president
said. ``We have to make the most of it. We have to look at the
long-term challenges facing America.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeated his plan for reserving a large portion of the
federal budget surplus for Social Security and Medicare and argued
strenuously against Republican proposals to use the money for tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I will say again, it may sound good if somebody says, this
is your surplus and we ought to give it back to you,'' he said.
``But you ought to ask yourself, what's America going to look like
10, 20, 30 years from now? How are all the families going to deal
with the retirement of the baby boom generation?''
</P>
<P>
   But 20 minutes into his remarks, people began streaming out of
the arena, an unusual spectacle at a presidential event. Many had
waited for hours amid towering snowbanks to enter the arena and
preliminary speeches lasted more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who stayed were Tom O'Sullivan and his 8-year-old
son, Kevin. O'Sullivan, 39, an auto worker, said that he came to
show support for Clinton. ``I think he's done a good job. And
there's not too many chances to see a living president.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan, who builds axles for light trucks, said the United
Automobile Workers had urged its members in the Buffalo area to
attend the rally. But he said he would have come anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Clinton's relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky had
been wrong, but that Republicans had gone overboard in bringing him
to the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with what he's done,'' O'Sullivan said, ``but
they should have censured him and been done with it. What people
failed to take into account was that we all have our faults. How
many people in the House and Senate did the same thing as he did
and just didn't get caught. The man's just trying to save his
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the overwhelmingly pro-Clinton crowd, Diana
Gaglia, 61, took a half-day of vacation time from her job at a
denture plant to attend the rally to show her support for the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he's being ostracized because of that stupid Linda
Tripp,'' Mrs. Gaglia said. ``I also feel, find me a man who hasn't
had an indiscretion. He didn't do right, but we shouldn't be put
through all this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0528 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1877 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-1STLD-W     01-20 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYERS CHIP AWAY HOUSE PROSECUTORS' ARGUMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS 7th graf, Ms. Mills ..., to drop reference to race.) 
 (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-BUSH, IMPEACH-SCENE) 
(bl)  
By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A White House lawyer Wednesday accused House
prosecutors of resorting to ``word games'' and ``legal
mumbo-jumbo'' in their efforts to prove President Clinton guilty of
impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed the charges as ``frivolous,'' often based on
``utterly meaningless'' conflicts in testimony and fundamentally
flawed from a constitutional perspective.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of the president's defense in his Senate
trial, the lawyer, special White House counsel Gregory Craig,
appealed to the senators not to ``throw our politics into the
darkness of endless recrimination'' and not to ``inject a poison of
bitter partisanship into the body politic which, like a virus, can
move through our national bloodstream for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If you convict and remove President Clinton on the
basis of these allegations, no president of the United States will
ever be safe from impeachment again.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig challenged every Republican accusation of perjury, which
forms the basis of the first of two articles of impeachment voted
by the House. Whereas Rep. Bill McCollum of Florida, one of the
Republican managers, had urged the Senate to concentrate on ``the
big picture'' and not to lose the forest in the trees, Craig homed
in on the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule of law depends on the details, because it depends on
the facts,'' said another White House lawyer, assistant counsel
Cheryl Mills, who followed him. She began the rebuttal to Article
Two, which charges Clinton with having obstructed justice in an
effort to conceal his illicit sexual relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mills made a striking presentation, dropping her voice to a
melodramatic murmur as she sought to demolish the case constructed
by the managers last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those stubborn facts,'' she said, after describing
discrepancies in the account of presidential actions assembled by
the Republicans. ``They won't go away. They keep pounding, like the
telltale heart.''
</P>
<P>
   In his summing-up, Craig echoed the point made by the White
House counsel, Charles Ruff, in his address to the Senate on
Tuesday, arguing that only the most heinous of crimes could justify
steps ``to undo the result of a national election and remove the
man chosen by the American people to be their president.''
</P>
<P>
   But he went further, suggesting that such a step could be taken
only if the American people approved it, presumably through a
referendum or in a public-opinion survey. The Senate ``dare not''
convict the president, Craig insisted, ``unless the people who
spoke agree that such drastic action is justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Current polls show the American public strongly opposed to the
removal of Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   There was another unusual aspect to the presentation by Craig,
who has known the Clintons since their days together at Yale Law
School. Replying to months of charges that the president and his
lawyers have engaged in hair-splitting and tortured constructions
in an effort to wiggle off the legal hook, he commented:
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that we have relied on overly legal or technical
arguments to defend the president from his attackers, we apologize
to him, to you and to the American public. We do the president no
earthly good if in the course of defending him we offend both the
judges, the jurors and the American public. And Mr. Ruff had it
just right when he expressed his concern to members of the
Judiciary Committee that our irresistible urge to practice our
profession should not get in the way of a just result.''
</P>
<P>
   But allegations of crimes ``invite _ indeed, they call out for _
legal defenses,'' Craig added, and he and his colleagues intended
to use ``all the legal defenses available.''
</P>
<P>
   He himself surely did so. He mounted an across-the-board attack,
with each line of argument ending with the conclusion that no
perjury had been committed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Craig complained that the perjury article was much too loosely
drawn, ``with a stunning lack of specificity'' which had forced
White House lawyers to try to hit ``a moving target.'' It would be
thrown out of any federal court on that ground alone, he contended.
He also said that the House managers had improperly attempted to
revisit the president's statements in his deposition in the Paula
Jones case, even though an article covering that matter had been
rejected by the House.
</P>
<P>
   The House rejected by a vote of 229-205 the article dealing with
alleged perjury in the president's Jan. 17 Jones deposition. But
the House managers have included in their allegation that Clinton
committed perjury in testifying to the Lewinsky grand jury in
August a charge that he had lied when he said he sought to tell the
truth in the deposition. This is a technique known in legal circles
as ``bootstrapping.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff and Craig said that should not be permitted, but McCollum
argued last week that the House rejection of the Jones article
``does not keep you from considering the lies in that deposition.''
He went on to list many questionable statements made by the
president, notably his statements that he could not remember if he
had ever been alone with Ms. Lewinsky or exchanged gifts with her.
He testified much more truthfully on those matters before the grand
jury six months later.
</P>
<P>
   Craig made much of the fact that many of the charges voiced by
the House managers had not been included in the referral by the
special prosecutor, Kenneth W. Starr. And he made extensive use of
videotapes of testimony before the Judiciary Committee by two
former federal prosecutors _ Thomas Sullivan, a former U.S.
attorney in Illinois, and Richard Davis, formerly a prosecutor at
the Justice Department and Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   Both said that perjury prosecutions require two witnesses or
substantial corroborating evidence _ not, as in this case, evidence
from friends of Ms. Lewinsky who said she told them the same story
at the time as she later told government investigators.
</P>
<P>
   That point had particular relevance, Craig said, to one of the
conflicts in testimony on which the managers ``place great emphasis
and weight'' _ the disagreement between Ms. Lewinsky and Clinton as
to whether he touched her breasts and genitalia during their sexual
encounters. The counsel described it as ``a classic, oath-on-oath,
`he says, she says''' matter.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that Clinton might be removed from office over
such a narrow disparity _ that his fate ``might hinge on whether
you believe him or her'' _ struck him as ``a staggering thought,''
Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the president himself, Craig insisted that Clinton had
never lied to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with Clinton's evasive behavior before the grand jury,
including his famous statement, ``It depends on what the meaning of
`is' is,'' the counsel said: ``The president makes a political
mistake here and gives in to his instinct to play his own lawyer,
to be his own advocate. You may find it frustrating, you may find
it irritating when you watched him do this. But he is not
committing perjury. He is committing the offense of nitpicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mills' brief was narrower. She focused on two charges of
obstruction of justice, both dealing with Clinton's secretary,
Betty Currie. And she rebutted both of them in fairly short order.
</P>
<P>
   The first involves the box of gifts from the president that Mrs.
Currie hid under her bed for Ms. Lewinsky, and turns on the
question of who asked Ms. Lewinsky to give them to Ms. Currie. The
Republicans say it was Mrs. Currie, acting on the president's
suggestion, relying heavily on Ms. Lewinsky's testimony that the
president had told her he would think about what she should do with
the gifts and surmising that he had decided they must be hidden.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Mills brought out the fact that in only one of 10
accounts did Ms. Lewinsky quote the president as saying he would
think about the hiding plan or anything of the sort. The managers
had not cited the other nine versions, she argued, ``because they
weaken an already fragile circumstantial case.'' In fact, Mrs.
Currie testified five times that the whole thing was Ms. Lewinsky's
idea, Ms. Mills continued, and Mrs. Currie agreed ``because she's a
friend, and that's not obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The other incident was Clinton's discussion with Mrs. Currie in
which he seemed to some to be coaching her, seeking her agreement
to untrue statements, such as ``Monica came on to me and I never
touched her _ right?'' The Republicans said the president, who had
earlier said Mrs. Currie would be the ideal witness on some
important points, was trying to corrupt her eventual testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But after a quick review of the obstruction statutes, Ms. Mills
noted that Mrs. Currie had testified that she had felt neither
pressured nor intimidated by the president, her boss, during the
series of exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence whatsoever of any kind of threat or
intimidation,'' Ms. Mills said. ``And as we discussed, the U.S.
attorney's manual indicates that without a threat or intimidation,
there is no corrupt influence. Without corrupt influence there is
no obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mills concluded with a spirited rebuttal to the idea that
Clinton had tried to deny a woman, Ms. Jones, her lawful civil
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about civil rights,'' she told the Senate,
``because this president's record on civil rights, on women's
rights, on all of our rights, in unimpeachable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
