<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT GLAD TO BE A LAKER AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He returns with a bulkier body and a fatter
wallet, and now, the chance to win a championship. Travis Knight is
a Laker once more, and how could things be any better?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting some sunshine, but I haven't gotten any of
that yet,'' Knight said Wednesday, looking at the clouds instead of
the silver lining. But, he quickly added, ``At least it's not ice
on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe he is leading a charmed life after all.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, a former San Diego resident, is back in Southern
California. He's playing again for the team he broke in with as a
rookie in 1996. And he's left the Rick Pitino rebuilding project
back in Fahrenheit-impaired Boston.
</P>
<P>
   And to top it all off, he has six years remaining on the
seven-year, $22 million deal he signed with the Celtics, the deal
that prompted him to leave L.A. in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Truly, things couldn't be much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real happy, I'm really excited about it,'' Knight said of
his return. ``Obviously this is a team that's going to be one of
the most dominant teams in the NBA for the next few years. It's
hard not to be excited about that.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked out with his old/new teammates Wednesday at Southwest
College, for the first time since he was swapped for Tony Battie.
</P>
<P>
   While he was not the low-post center the Celtics wanted, Knight
said he had no hard feelings about Boston or coach Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good experience in Boston, a learning experience,'' he
said. ``I don't regret my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   His return to L.A. also means a return to his preferred
position, power forward. And he's better equipped for the banging
now that he's bulked up from about 220 pounds his rookie year to
236 today.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a trade for a power forward, coach Del Harris expects
Knight to compete for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to plug some holes,'' Knight said. ``Whatever
coach Harris wants me to do is fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates were glad to see Knight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked even better to me,'' Eddie Jones said after
practice. ``It seemed like he got every loose ball, every offensive
rebound that came off, tip-ins, hitting the wide open jump shot,
defending.... I think as soon as he heard he was coming back here,
his confidence, it went up to the clouds probably.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbying: Elden Campbell is still a Laker, and an option at
power forward and center. But Olden Polynice is ready to take those
roles at the drop of a hat, if the Lakers trade Campbell, as has
been expected.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice, a free agent entering his 12th NBA season, has been
working out with the Lakers and openly lobbying players and
management alike. He'll sign for the veteran's minimum ($1
million), and all they have to do is ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can make it happen, I'm theirs to lose basically,'' he
said. ``I want to be here. I think I'd be a good fit for this
team.... One thing I can do is play hard and bang and rebound,
which is something the Lakers have lacked.''
</P>
<P>
   And Polynice gave the best indication yet that the team could
still trade Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Lakers) just told me to hold on, don't make any
rushed decisions (about signing elsewhere),'' Polynice said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers don't sign him, Polynice said he has a standing
offer from division rival Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
