<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY HAS NEW ROSE BOWL DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Galaxy and Rose Bowl officials confirmed Wednesday
that they have reached an agreement in principle on a new
three-year deal for the Major League Soccer team to continue to
play at the famed stadium and to build a practice field adjacent to
it.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the City Council and the Rose Bowl Operating
Committee, the agreement would ensure the Rose Bowl would retain
one of its major tenants and end the Galaxy's search for a new
training site.
</P>
<P>
   For its first three seasons, the Galaxy trained either at
Occidental College, Azusa Pacific University or in the parking lot
grass outside the Rose Bowl. The team had been looking at Azusa
Pacific University, Mt. San Antonio College in Walnut and Rio Hondo
College in Whittier as possible sites for a new training facility.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Bowl General Manager Dave Jacobs said he and Galaxy
president Tim Leiweke reached the agreement late last week
following a series of meetings. It includes an option for the
Galaxy to play at the Rose Bowl for a fourth year. The Galaxy's
current three-year deal with the Rose Bowl was due to expire this
month. The team held an option for the 1999 season, which begins
March 21.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new agreement, the Galaxy will be able to build a
weight room at the Rose Bowl, new stadium offices for team
management, a permanent locker room, and a fenced practice field to
be constructed in parking lot K. Galaxy vice president David Bolton
estimated the total cost at slightly less than $400,000, and said
it would be paid for by Philip F. Anschutz, who purchased the
Galaxy in October for $26 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've decided to stay at the Rose Bowl and make that not only
our home for games but for training facilities and our entire
operations,'' said Bolton. ``We have begun construction on our
weight room for players underneath the stadium and have also
started upgrading and expanding our coaching offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have also made a commitment to build a regulation-size
field in parking lot K, which we're hoping to be able to break
ground on March 1. Right now, we're in the process of designing the
field and also doing all the environmental studies we need to get
that done. We're hoping to have that process ready for review with
the City Council and RBOC (Rose Bowl Operating Committee) by the
end of February to allow us to break ground in March.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs admitted he was concerned when the Galaxy began looking
elsewhere for a training site. At one point, Azusa Pacific
University officials believed they were on the verge of signing a
joint deal with the Galaxy to build a training facility near the
Azusa campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because there are a lot of benefits to keeping them
here,'' Jacobs said of the Galaxy. ``This will lock them in for a
long time and that's a great benefit to us. They're an important
source of revenue. We make about $200,000 a year off the Galaxy, so
that's a tenant we didn't want to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolton said the Galaxy-Rose Bowl contract has been agreed to in
good faith, but added there are some contractual points that need
to be finalized. ``If for some reason we build a state-of-the-art
stadium somewhere in L.A., it would give us the option to leave
after three years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said that all that remains for the contract to be signed
is for the new practice field to be approved. Jacobs said it would
cause the loss of up to 200 parking spots in lot K, but he said the
Rose Bowl could recover those spots in lot J.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Galaxy has received permission from the
RBOC to practice on the Rose Bowl turf. Training camp opens Monday.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilwoman Ann-Marie Villicana, whose district includes
neighborhoods west of Rose Bowl, held back from endorsing the
agreement, saying she wants to see the details first. But she said
she supports the concept of adding the practice field to the
stadium area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm supportive of keeping the Galaxy here,'' said Villicana,
who is running for mayor. ``There is no question that the Galaxy is
fulfilling a need in Pasadena. It's filling the Rose Bowl and
providing great entertainment for families and children.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the practice field will be built on public property, if
the Galaxy decides to leave, the Rose Bowl will take control of it.
``We would call it our contribution to soccer and the Rose Bowl,''
Bolton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This training facility would provide a lot of benefits for
everyone,'' Jacobs said. ``For one, the Tournament (of Roses)
wouldn't have to rent out the Coliseum, this could be their
training site.
</P>
<P>
   ``But before we get ahead of ourselves we still need approval
from the Rose Bowl Operating Committee and the City Council. We're
trying to do this as expeditiously as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The new practice field will provide a place for Pasadena's
public high schools to play tournament or championship soccer
games, said Porfirio Frausto, a former Blair High School football
coach who serves on the Rose Bowl Operating Company.
</P>
<P>
   It will also allow Pasadena to attract more big-name soccer
events and offer the Galaxy a safer place to practice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not right to send a million-dollar athlete over to Area H
after UCLA games -- there's glass on the field,'' Frausto said.
``You'd hate to see a guy get injured because it's a poor training
site.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano welcomed the news of the agreement
and new practice field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only think what could have been if we did not have to
deal with those conditions the past three years,'' Zambrano said.
``Now we don't have an excuse at all. Hopefully they can break
ground on area K and get that thing done for us.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Zahniser contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
