<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ROBINSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON BLAMES HIMSELF FOR KINGS' DEMISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been a season of many lows and few highs for the Kings, a
season of great expectations unfulfilled, and Larry Robinson
admitted Wednesday that his team's difficulties have shaken his
faith in his abilities as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often question whether I'm a good coach - a good head
coach,'' Robinson said Wednesday afternoon following the Kings'
practice at the Forum. ``There are certain qualities to being a
great head coach. There are a lot of things I think about, and I
don't know if I communicate them properly.''
</P>
<P>
   It is more than halfway through a season scarred by injuries and
marred by inconsistency. After a miserable start, the Kings
(16-24-4) hit a hot streak in late December and early January, but
recently have cooled off once again. They enter tonight's home game
against the New Jersey Devils with a 1-3-1 record in their last
five games.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star break begins after tonight, and the Kings will
enter the hiatus as few as three or as many as seven points out of
a playoff berth. After the break, the Kings face a difficult
four-game trip, and his team's precarious situation has tested
Robinson's ability to maintain a hopeful outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to stay as positive as I can,'' said Robinson, 47, in
his fourth year on the job. ``If you want to have sleepless nights
and ulcers and gray hairs, you do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the dye job early in the season that turned Robinson's
hair from gray to brown wore off awhile ago, and he said he's had
more than his share of sleepless nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them,'' he said. ``Ask me if I have any sleepful
nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Robinson was asked in what areas he felt he could
improve, and he replied, ``Reading people's personalities, being
able to take a guy aside and tell him exactly how I feel and maybe
the things he should be doing. My problem is maybe I care too much
about hurting a guy's feelings or telling a guy really what he's
playing like or what he should be doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to put myself in the same situation and how I'd like to
be treated. Maybe one of the qualities of being a great coach is
being (a jerk). There are quite a few of them around.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Robinson be as hard on his players as he needs to be? Is it
imaginable he would ever learn to make a point by throwing a skate
at a player's head? One former NHL player has said he saw
Vancouver's Mike Keenan do exactly that in 1993-94, the year Keenan
coached the New York Rangers to the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Detroit's) Scotty Bowman is probably the greatest coach of
all time, and (former Montreal Canadiens coach) Toe Blake was
great, too,'' Robinson said. ``But I've heard stories about them
that would make your hair stand up. I can't treat people like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though he questions whether he is tough enough with his
players, Robinson said he has little difficulty pondering his own
inadequacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm my own worst enemy, my biggest critic of myself,'' said
Robinson, a member of the Hockey Hall of Fame who played for the
Canadiens and the Kings. ``I was like that when I played. I never
thought of myself as a great player. That's what helped me become a
great player. What I hope will make me a great coach is that I am
hard on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson insists he wants to continue coaching the Kings beyond
this year, even though he declined to sign a contract extension
before the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I question myself and my ability doesn't mean I
don't want to do it,'' Robinson said, adding that he has put
contract discussions with the Kings on hold until after the season.
``There comes a time where you say, `Do I need it?' I don't think I
could totally get away from hockey. But eventually, I'd like to get
away from the travel and live in my home for more than a month. But
that's a ways away.''
</P>
<P>
   Norstrom an All-Star (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Mattias Norstrom was added to the World team for
Sunday's All-Star Game in Tampa. His partner, Rob Blake, will play
for the North American team.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first All-Star selection for the 27-year-old Norstrom,
who will replace injured New York Islander Kenny Jonsson. Norstrom
has only four points this season but is second to Nashville's Bob
Boughner among NHL defensemen with 122 hits. His blue-collar style
is the type that often is ignored when All-Star teams are put
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling,'' said Norstrom, a native of Sweden.
``I'm really surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said, ``I think it's wonderful. Matti deserves it. It's
great to see a guy with his work ethic get his just rewards.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he is hopeful that right wing Glen Murray might be
able to play several weeks earlier than his targeted mid-March
return date. Murray, sidelined since Jan. 2 with a knee injury, has
progressed more quickly than expected, Robinson said, and is due to
undergo tests next week to determine whether his return date can be
moved up. ... Winger Craig Johnson was placed on injured reserve.
Johnson has missed two games with a rib injury. ... Stephane Fiset
is expected to start in goal tonight despite a shaky performance in
Tuesday's 5-4 loss to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Game: vs. New Jersey Devils
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:35 p.m. at the Forum
</P>
<P>
   TV: Fox Sports West
</P>
<P>
   Radio: KRLA 1110/AM
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: 4,000 remaining (1-888-KINGS-LA)
</P>
<P>
   Matchups: Though the Devils are one of the top teams in the
Eastern Conference and the Kings are one of the bottom teams in the
Western Conference, the Kings won the teams' previous meeting by a
4-0 margin on Oct. 28 at New Jersey. In fact, the Kings have
dominated the Devils recently, winning last season's two meetings
by a combined margin of 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   -- Roger Phillips
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2208EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
