<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0534 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1893 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEFENSE-MISSILE-1STLD     01-20 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFENSE-MISSILE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAY BUILD ANTI-MISSILE SYSTEM, SEEKS TO AMEND TREATY WITH
RUSSIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.D., Wash., Alaska)  (Eds.: LEADS with 7 grafs to recast, raise background, ADD that
Soviet Union collapsed in 1991; Creates new 10-12th grafs to raise
treaty history higher in story.)  (sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration said on Wednesday that
it was asking Russia to renegotiate the Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty to permit a limited national missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   The administration acted after concluding that the threat of a
strike from a country like North Korea now justified building a
limited number of ground-based interceptor missiles that could
shoot down incoming missiles. The system is not designed to protect
the nation from an all-out nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has not approved the final project, but he
wrote to President Boris N. Yeltsin last week outlining plans to
move ahead in developing and testing a system, a senior
administration official said. Clinton urged Yeltsin not to view the
development of a missile defense as a threat to the strategic
balance between the United States and Russia, the official said,
speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   While the White House sought to reassure the Russians that the
change would be limited, Defense Secretary William Cohen said on
Wednesday that the United States would not rule out unilaterally
withdrawing from the treaty if an agreement was not reached.
</P>
<P>
   With a growing number of nations building or acquiring ballistic
missiles and with political pressure from Republicans legislators
mounting, the administration has come much closer to a decision to
build a system than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is scheduled to visit
Moscow next week, and the missile defense program will be a major
topic of her three days of meetings with senior leaders, including
Prime Minister Yevgeny M. Primakov and Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction on Wednesday from Yeltsin's
government, but Russia has long opposed the creation of an American
missile defense, vehemently so after President Ronald Reagan
envisioned a space-based ``Star Wars'' program in 1983, to defend
the United States from an all-out nuclear attack by the Soviet
Union. The Soviet Union collapsed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Cohen also outlined a series of changes
in the Pentagon's programs to build a national missile defense
system and more limited anti-missile defenses intended to protect
specific regions or troops in combat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton still has not approved building any national missile
defense. But with more nations building or acquiring ballistic
missiles and with political pressure mounting from Republicans in
Congress, the administration has come much closer to a decision to
build a system.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and the Soviet Union signed the Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty in 1972 to limit the number, type and placement of
missiles that could be used to counter enemy missiles. The treaty
has been amended in the past, most recently in 1997 to acknowledge
the breakup of the Soviet Union and to clarify the distinction
between national missile defenses and the more limited ``theater''
missile defenses permitted under the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty allows either the United States or Russia to withdraw
with six months notice ``if it decides that extraordinary events
related to the subject matter of this treaty have jeopardized its
supreme interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Withdrawing from the treaty would have profound diplomatic
repercussions for the United States. Such a move could be
interpreted as a lack of American commitment to other treaties, and
it could undercut efforts to get Russia's parliament to ratify the
second strategic arms reduction treaty, or START 2.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing beside the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen.
Henry H. Shelton, Cohen confirmed the administration's plans to
pledge $6.6 billion in the next six years to build a defensive
network of radars and interceptor missiles.
</P>
<P>
   That pledge _ sort of like earnest money put down by a home
buyer _ would increase the budget for a national missile defense
system to $10.5 billion between now and 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's remarks also made it clear that the Pentagon considers
the possibility of a ballistic missile attack from ``rogue'' states
like North Korea, Iran or Iraq no longer a distant threat, which
was the Pentagon's official position only a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are affirming that there is a threat and the threat is
growing and that we expect it will pose a danger not only to our
troops overseas but also to Americans here at home,'' Cohen said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on Capitol Hill have long advocated a more
aggressive effort to protect the United States from a strike by a
rogue state or terrorist group or an accidental launch in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Americans are shocked to discover that our country is
unshielded from the accidental or ruthless launch of even a single
missile over our skies,'' Rep. Steve Largent of Oklahoma declared
in the Republican response to Clinton's State of the Union message
on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., and one of the strongest proponents in
Congress of a missile defense, welcomed the administration's
announcement but said he remained ``skeptical given the president's
continuing lack of a firm commitment to proceed with deployment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., introduced legislation on Wednesday
that again called for the deployment of a national missile defense
``as soon as it is technologically possible'' and called for still
more money to be spent on the effort. A similar bill failed in the
Senate last year by only one vote.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran endorsed negotiating changes in the treaty but also said
the United States should consider withdrawing from it, if
necessary. ``The most important thing is doing what is in our
national security interests to protect American citizens and the
territory against ballistic missile attack,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cohen emphasized that he believed it was in the U.S. interest to
continue to abide by the treaty, which he said served to deter a
resumption of a nuclear arms race. But he said the treaty needed to
make room for a national missile defense, which he added was
``focused primarily on countering rogue-nation threats and will not
be capable of countering Russia's nuclear deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   While amending or abrogating the treaty would complicate
relations with Russia, the deployment of a national missile defense
system could also anger China, which has only limited nuclear
ballistic missile capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   There are still enormous hurdles to overcome before the United
States could even field a defense system. Even with a pledge of
additional money, the program remains burdened by technological
problems, and some analysts doubt that a viable system can ever be
built.
</P>
<P>
   The system now being developed is a shadow of Reagan's grand
vision of using lasers in space to create an impenetrable shield
protecting the nation from nuclear attack. In recent years, the
Pentagon's researchers have instead concentrated on using missiles
_ perhaps based in Alaska or North Dakota or on ships _ to
intercept a handful of incoming missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The system faces a pivotal test in June when the program's
developers, led by Boeing Co., will launch a dummy missile from
Vandenberg Air Force Base in California to try to destroy a missile
fired from Kwajalein Atoll in the Marshall Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon now plans four tests before next June. At that
time, Cohen said, the administration will decide whether to move
ahead with deployment. But Cohen signaled that the administration's
plan now envisioned building a system, if one proves feasible, in
2005, a delay of two years from the administration's previous
timetable.
</P>
<P>
   While the administration has not yet given final approval, the
nation's military leaders believe a decision to build a system is
now inevitable, a senior defense official said. ``In the
Pentagon,'' the official said, ``there's no question this is going
to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
