<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-AZNOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READERS SHARE VIEWS ON CLINTON'S TRAVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The caller wanted to make a confession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever he did, it happens all the time. In everyone's lives.
Even in mine. I cheated on my wife _ several times!'' he shouted
into the phone. ``But she took me back. She forgave me. And we need
to do the same to Bill Clinton. He's a good man. And he's a good
president. Life happens. Just leave the guy alone.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, he hung up without leaving a name.
</P>
<P>
   Since I started writing this column on Jan. 9, hundreds have
called and written. People have been eager to share their personal
stories and sentiments _ and explain how those accounts affect
their views on President Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   This is the pulse of some of the Americans in Arizona who sought
to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Like the man with the adulterous disclosure, many voiced their
support for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton has been good for the country. We have a
budget surplus,'' said one elderly female caller. ``So what about
the other stuff? We have to measure him by what he's gotten done in
office.''
</P>
<P>
   A self-described construction worker wrote: ``He's kept me
working. He's kept the economy running. That's better than a lot of
other presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   One offered continued support because he respected Clinton's
human flaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us like Bill Clinton because he is the closest thing
to a human being we have seen in the White House in quite awhile.
He eats, he sleeps, he has sex and when he gets caught he misleads
people about it until he gets cornered and then he does what he can
to salvage the situation,'' James Lenfers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all called human nature. Personally, I used to not like
Bill Clinton. He came across as an obvious phony. But you know
what? The more sanctimonious people give him a hard time, and the
more he sticks in there and deflects it, the better I like him.''
</P>
<P>
   While some, like Lenfers, offered lengthy discussions, others
kept it brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeach the crook as soon as possible,'' one man said.
``Thanks and bye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop harassing the president,'' another wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One asked me to look at Shakespearian literature in evaluating
the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to preface my remarks by saying I'm not a Republican
and I'm not a right-wing zealot. I feel the president and his wife
are very close and similar to MacBeth and Lady MacBeth,'' explained
this male caller. ``There's a line in Shakespeare's ``MacBeth''
that says, `Not even Neptune's great ocean can wash the blood off
my hands.' And I feel that that's a perfect phrase for the blood
that's on the hands of the president and his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were more visceral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one person they never polled. I hate Clinton. I hate
Hillary. They have done more harm than anything in the whole whole
history of the country,'' raled a caller who identified herself as
Ann Hess. ``He's trash. He came from trash. It's no wonder he knew
what to call Paula Jones, he came from it. You can tell I'm upset
by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Petro had this to say: ``I find it incredible that he's
still in office. That he can stand up there and look the camera in
the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disgusted by him. I am disgusted by all his people. It's
not just his sexual escapades, although that's a good enough reason
to get him out of there. He's a very sick man,'' she said, raising
her voice. ``As I said, it caused me to leave the Democratic Party
after being a lifelong Democrat from Chicago. I just think about
the amount of support he gets, some of it from people in my family,
and I don't know what they see in him. It's like we're looking at
two different human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Many offered their prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I are very concerned about the Senate trial. We
listen to reports on the radio, read the paper and watch coverage
on TV. We pray daily that the senators may have wisdom and courage
to find the truth and act accordingly. We have been concerned for
several years that President Clinton's vetoing of legislation that
upheld high moral standards was an indication of his inner life.
Unfortunately, this has proved true. Character does count. Now he
is trying to buy his way into greater popularity by his promises in
the State of the Union address. I could go on and on, but you have
other things to do,'' wrote Floyd and Barbara Torkelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``God help the president and God help all the elected officials
involved in this sad chapter of our country,'' one caller said.
</P>
<P>
   One offered this fear:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I do think Americans are concerned with the impeachment
of this president, and I think most of us are more concerned about
the fact that if he is impeached Al Gore will become president,''
wrote a man who identified himself only as Al. ``What we've got is
a bum, what we don't need is an idiot. Sorry, but that is how a lot
of folks feel.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, it wasn't about the president. But more about the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julie, I am not from the Valley, but from Tucson. I am
strongly opposed to the continual barrage of salacious material
from the House managers. This ridiculous episode of moral madness
has cost the country's standing in the international community
immensely,'' wrote Theodore Bundy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party is telling the people of these United
States that they don't matter. It has become increasingly
obvious &UR; to all who pay any attention that this is a coup. And the
Christian Coalition and their allies in the so-called
`conservative' movement claim that they now control the country
through the Republican Party. It is shocking and sad to see a once
vibrant party dig their own grave so willingly and with such
gusto,'' Bundy said.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Bernstein shares this: ``Have you ever heard of the saying:
`Don't kick a man when he's down'? &UR; I have little sympathy with
President Clinton when I consider his personal behavior, which I
think is deplorable. However, I am convinced that he should never
have been asked such personal questions in the first place, and
that he is truly a victim of a long-running vendetta initiated and
perpetuated by Republican zealots and that inquisitor, Kenneth
Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, one woman is taken aback by America's reaction to
the Clinton trial and offered this poignant point to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm more sad for America. Because all I hear is people
saying `I, I, I.' We don't seem to care about anything but
ourselves anymore. What happened to the America that cared about
people and what's right and those kinds of things. I'm &UR; not sure
what I think about Bill Clinton. But it hurts to read that nobody
cares and that all they care about is themselves, money and
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Could she be right? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton's impeachment trial progresses, Julie
Amparano will be taking the pulse of people in the Phoenix area. Do
they care about President Clinton's trial? Do they want him removed
from office? What does captivate Americans? She looks for the
answers. Amparano can be reached at 444-8394, or at
julie.amparano(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
