u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT &LR;      01-20 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTENTIAL OLYMPIC SPONSORS SAID TO BE UNEASY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Utah)  (See also OLY-SCANDAL-INVESTIGATE) 
 (af)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two prospective corporate sponsors for the 2002 Winter Olympic
Games in Salt Lake City have said they will not make their deals
final until all investigations into the unfolding corruption
scandal have been completed, a senior U.S. Olympic official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   John Krimsky Jr., the marketing director for the U.S. Olympic
Committee, would not identify the sponsors, but said their
decisions to hold off on signing formal sponsorship contracts
reflected considerable uneasiness among the many corporations whose
money is essential to financing the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Any growing reluctance on the part of sponsors to get involved
with the 2002 Games could have serious consequences for American
efforts to stage a full Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Olympic officials still have to raise $250 million in
sponsorship money in a joint-marketing agreement with Salt Lake
City to reach the proposed budget of $1.45 billion. Olympic
officials have said that the Games may have to be reduced in size
if the full budget figure cannot be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Word of nervousness on the part of corporate sponsors came as
the International Olympic Committee prepared to release a
preliminary report on the efforts by Salt Lake officials to win the
right to play host to the Olympics. Salt Lake officials have
already admitted to a range of inappropriate inducements made to
gain favor with members of the IOC during the selection process,
including cash payments, expensive gifts and college scholarships
for family members of IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported Wednesday that a draft copy of
the IOC's preliminary report concluded that as many as 16 of the
114 IOC members may be implicated in the Salt Lake City scandal for
accepting more than $780,000 in payments and gifts during and after
the bidding process for the 2002 Winter Games. The report, The
Journal said, also concluded that such conduct had taken place
during previous competitions among cities.
</P>
<P>
   The report, prepared by Richard Pound, an IOC executive, also
details the activities of agents, or middlemen, who sought money
from officials of different cities, claiming they could influence
votes, according to The Journal. Pound's report, which is scheduled
to be released this weekend in Lausanne, Switzerland, claims that
one such middleman told officials of the bid city of Sion,
Switzerland, that he could deliver 25 IOC votes for $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC's sponsorships have become radioactive,'' said David
D'Alessandro, the president of John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance,
one of a dozen worldwide sponsors of the Olympics. ``All corporate
Geiger counters are going off the chart. They've got to find a way
to make sponsorships safe again.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro said that he had begun to wonder whether Juan
Antonio Samaranch, 78, president of the IOC, would or could remain
in his job if the scandal escalated and corporate sponsorship was
seriously imperiled. Hancock and other sponsors are eagerly
awaiting the IOC meeting this weekend in Lausanne to see how many
IOC members will resign or face expulsion and to see what changes
will be initiated in light of the burgeoning Salt Lake corruption
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether they can achieve reform with
credibility under the current leadership,'' D'Alessandro said.
``Only the IOC can answer that question. Can Samaranch go into a
boardroom and credibly sell a sponsorship? I don't know the answer
to that. I think he survives if his changes are extraordinary,
sweeping, and he shows enormous courage as a leader. And he takes
no prisoners and recognizes that all he has built is in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   While Samaranch, a Spanish marquis who became IOC president in
1980, stated emphatically last week that he would maintain his
position until his current terms ends in 2001, he has seemed to
qualify his remarks in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have the confidence of all IOC members, I go on,''
Samaranch told The Wall Street Journal. ``If not, I will be
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Leavitt, the governor of Utah, has called on Samaranch to
clean up the Olympic movement. A growing chorus, led by Robert
Helmick, a former IOC member from the United States, has been
calling for Samaranch's resignation, and news reports have linked
him to expensive gifts such as guns and a samurai sword sent by bid
cities such as Salt Lake City and Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But as of Wednesday, Samaranch still had his defenders. ``We are
facing problems, but I would say Samaranch is leading and in
control of the institution,'' Francois Carrard, the executive
director of the IOC, said in an interview. ``He's perfectly apt to
act as president. We see no reason for him to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Krimsky, the American Olympic official, also expressed support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical that the president move quickly to heal the
Olympic movement so it can be effective and productive in moving
forward,'' Krimsky said. ``We've got to get this behind us. I'm
absolutely convinced Samaranch is the president to do it. Any
change would be disruptive.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic marketing experts Wednesday said in New York that the
financial picture of the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City, as a
whole, remained encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Payne, the IOC's marketing expert, said that the $615
million in corporate money raised by Salt Lake doubled the amount
raised for the 1998 Winter Games in Nagano, Japan, and that the IOC
had received ``full and total commitment'' from its sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear any number of American sponsors have made clear
that the Salt Lake scandal has caused concern.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Deutsch, a spokesman for the longtime Olympic sponsor
Coca-Cola, which spent up to $250 million on the 1996 Summer Games
in Atlanta and is signed through 2008, said the company had had
``frequent dialogue'' with Olympic officials and had expressed the
need for change. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a process that needs to be in play so this won't ever
happen again,'' Deutsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Rosenberg, a spokeswoman for United Parcel Service who
said the company had previously been pleased with its Olympic
association, said the company had been monitoring the scandal. ``We
believe the Olympics are strong enough to take a hit,'' Rosenberg
said. ``People need to be held accountable. For the Olympics to
emerge from this, however, there needs to be more than pointing
fingers and holding people accountable. That doesn't set a
correctional attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound, a lawyer from Montreal who has headed a six-man
commission to look into the Salt Lake scandal, met Wednesday in New
York with lawyers retained by the Salt Lake City organizing
committee as the two bodies prepared to release their reports in
coming days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
