<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0541 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-INVESTIGA     01-20 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-INVESTIGATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF IT COMES TO COURT, SALT LAKE'S NONPROFIT STATUS COULD BE
JEOPARDIZED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah)  (With OLY-SCANDAL) 
(js) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The allegations are tantalizing: cash payments, college
scholarships, hotel suites, airline tickets, jobs and free medical
operations _ all exchanged to help Salt Lake City win the 2002
Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But finding criminal behavior to prosecute may prove tough,
lawyers said in interviews Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest violation for prosecutors to prove may be of federal
tax laws. By allegedly giving as much as $600,000 in gifts to
International Olympic Committee members, the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee may have violated its nonprofit status. If so, the IRS
could revoke the committee's status retroactively and demand
payment of back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a charity is that you give to legitimate objects
of charity,'' said Boyd Kimball Dyer, a professor of tax and
business law at the University of Utah. Referring to allegations
that as many as 16 foreign Olympic officials received gifts from
the Salt Lake committee, he added: ``You cannot support private
people, especially not people who are wealthy. That is not charity,
that is corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like the Al Capone story, the taxes are not the
central thing,'' Kimball Dyer added. Noting that whoever signed the
committee's tax return could possibly be prosecuted for filing a
false return, he said, ``But it is hard to link the people who did
the corruption to the people who actually prepared the tax
returns.''
</P>
<P>
   In Salt Lake, IRS investigators and a legal team from the U.S.
Justice Department are digging through records of the Salt Lake
committee. Headed by Richard Wiedis, a specialist on white-collar
crime, the justice team includes Peter Clark, an expert on the
Foreign Corrupt Practices Act.
</P>
<P>
   However, that federal law probably does not apply because the
alleged recipients of the gifts were not foreign government
officials, but members of the International Olympic Committee, a
charity, said E. Lawrence Barcella, a defense lawyer who
specializes in white-collar cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bribing a foreign government official to get business'' is the
core of the Corrupt Practices Act, Barcella said from Washington.
``It would become a significant stretch to include IOC officials
under the definition of government officials.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that prosecutors may be looking at possible money
laundering violations, the Justice Department investigation has
also been aided by the U.S. Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   But money laundering laws would not apply in this case, Barcella
said, if it was not illegal for officers of one charity, the Salt
Lake committee, to give gifts to officers of another charity, the
IOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``For money laundering, you have to have an underlying illegal
activity,'' said Barcella, who is a former federal prosecutor. ``If
you are bribing an IOC member in Africa, in South America and the
bribe itself is not illegal, you may not have a money laundering
case.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents are also studying the books of a defunct Salt Lake
City escort service to determine the validity of news media reports
linking visiting IOC members to prostitutes. Prostitution is
illegal in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors have subpoenaed as many as a dozen people
close to the Salt Lake committee. On Wednesday, prosecutors
interviewed Stephanie Pate, who worked for Tom Welch until he
resigned as president of the committee in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client engaged in no criminal conduct herself and she knows
of no conduct by others which we believe to be criminal,'' David B.
Watkiss, her lawyer, said.
</P>
<P>
   Max D. Wheeler, a lawyer for Welch and for David Johnson, a
former senior vice president of the committee, did not return
telephone calls Wednesday. But on Tuesday, Wheeler was quoted by
The Washington Post as characterizing Johnson's view of the
payments to IOC members as ``an effort to maintain friendships.''
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before an independent state review panel, Johnson
apparently said that some of the cash was given to IOC members from
developing countries for their national Olympic committees and that
the money was often given in cash because members said it was
difficult to cash American checks in their home countries.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Utah's attorney general, Jan Graham, announced that
her office would investigate possible violations of Utah law, once
reports are completed by the state panel and by an IOC review
panel. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
