<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-FOLEY-NYT &LR;      01-20 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-FOLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' FOLEY COULD BECOME A CLEVELAND BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glenn Foley has once again received stunning, disappointing news
from Jets Coach Bill Parcells. Foley, who never got over losing his
starting quarterback job to Vinny Testaverde after an early season
rib injury, is one of five New York Jets who will be available for
next month's expansion draft to stock the roster of the Cleveland
Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the message has been passed on to me that I'm no
longer part of their plans,'' Foley said Wednesday. ``I assume I'll
be going, but I guess there's a possibility I'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley admitted that he was confused by several aspects of the
move. He said Parcells had told him it was being made for
salary-cap considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that big,'' Foley said of his base salary, which is
about $1.5 million a year. ``That's what confuses me. I've got to
believe there's something going on, maybe a hidden agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   If Foley were taken by the Browns, then the Jets would probably
be looking for a proven backup quarterback. The inexperienced Ray
Lucas was the third-string quarterback this past season. He spent
the year learning how to be a quarterback while performing as a
special-team player. The kind of backup the Jets want is someone
who could step in and perform at a high level.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the established quarterbacks who will be available as
free agents include Scott Zolak, who played for Parcells at New
England; Tom Tupa, the Patriots' punter who is also a quarterback;
Scott Mitchell of the Detroit Lions; Steve Beuerlein of the
Carolina Panthers and Kerry Collins of the New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Gus Frerotte of the Washington Redskins and the Saints'
Heath Shuler _ both placed on the Cleveland list _ will probably be
cut if they are not picked up by the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns' president, Carmen Policy, has said he is interested
in taking University of Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch in the
college draft, so Foley's selection by Cleveland is not assured.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Cleveland would be interested in Foley could not be
determined. Policy did not return a phone call Wednesday. A Jets
spokesman said Parcells would not be available to explain his
decision to expose Foley in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Foley said he had enjoyed his five Jets seasons, and
believed the Jets could make another run for the Super Bowl.
``There's worse jobs than being a quarterback in New York,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that if he did come back, there would not be a
quarterback competition on the Jets. ``Vinny's the guy,'' Foley
said. ``There's no question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley added: ``I've signed a contract with the Jets through next
year. I know a lot of people don't understand that, but I'd honor
the contract. As the backup, you're one hit away from starting.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his ability level remained high even though he had seen
no game-time action since Oct. 11. ``The way we practice, full
speed, game speed, your skills don't diminish,'' he said. ``That
New York Jets team of 1998 was a special team. There's not one of
us wouldn't want to be back. It was a great locker room. I'd have
to go back to college to find a locker room like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley had been named the Jets' starter in June once Neil
O'Donnell had been cut and Testaverde brought aboard. But Parcells
always had a disquieting question about Foley: his health. Thus,
Parcells said that Foley was being given ``the benefit of the
doubt'' as the starter. In other words, it was his to lose.
</P>
<P>
   That happened soon enough. In Game 2 against Baltimore he
sustained a rib injury. Testaverde replaced him in the next two
games, which the Jets won to even their record at 2-2. But Parcells
went back to Foley to start against St. Louis. He was benched
during the game, in which he completed only a third of his passes
and tossed two interceptions. He did not throw a pass the rest of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Foley's three losses as a starter dropped his career won-lost
record to 1-7 and left him without a complete-game victory. He has
made 16 appearances since the Jets drafted him in 1994. He has been
hurt seriously enough to miss playing time on three occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' fears about Foley's durability seemed answered with
the rib injury, although the quarterback's two earlier problems
were freakish accidents. Against the Patriots in 1995 he was hit on
the final play of the game just as he was throwing the ball. He was
driven shoulder first into the turf. He spent the rest of the
season and off season rehabilitating from surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Parcells' first season with the Jets, Foley replaced
O'Donnell midway through the season after starring in backup
victories. But this time he was injured at Chicago when he was
sacked and his cleats became caught in a Bears jersey. Foley
severely sprained a knee.
</P>
<P>
   One agent with access to the Jets' expansion list said that
Foley would join the former starting free safety Jerome Henderson,
the special teams star Chris Hayes, the long snapper John Hudson
and offensive lineman Mike Gisler.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion draft will be held Feb. 9, and the Jets can lose a
maximum of two players. However, once one player is selected, then
the Jets can pull back another.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
