<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, JANUARY 21
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-JAMA-SEXSURVEY-NYT (moved on Friday, Jan. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Jan. 15,
about the dismissal of the editor of the Journal of the American
Medical Association misstated the surname of the association's
executive vice president at a few points in some editions. He is
Dr. E. Ratcliffe Anderson, not Dr. Ratcliffe.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GENITAL-MUTILATION-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 17,
about a decision by the Parliament of Senegal to ban genital
cutting of women misspelled the name of a Senegalese women's
organization that has campaigned against the practice. It is
Tostan, not Tofhan.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CALIF-GUNSALES-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 17,
about efforts by Los Angeles to limit handgun sales misstated the
origin of a study of handgun seizures by the Los Angeles police.
The study was conducted for an article in the Nov. 2 issue of
``Policing: An International Journal of Police Strategies and
Management.'' It was not commissioned by the Los Angeles police.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LINUX-MICROSOFT-CHALLENGE-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 17,
about the potential for the Linux computer operating system to pose
a threat eventually to Microsoft's Windows misidentified the
headquarters city of Corel, which is hoping to make its software
compatible with Linux. It is Ottawa, not Toronto.
</P>
</TEXT>
