<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USIA-HACKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USIA SAYS HACKER KILLED WEB SITE AND DAMAGED COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An outsider breached the Internet security of the
U.S. Information Agency a week ago, knocking its Web site out of
action and forcing the agency to re-evaluate its computer
protection, a USIA official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site was invaded about 9 p.m. on Jan. 13 by someone who
diverted users to other locations and then dismantled the site,
according to James McGregor, a computer expert for the agency.
McGregor said the site might function again by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the sabotage, the second such incident in six months,
had caused ``a constant stream of phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency oversees educational and cultural-exchange programs,
including the Voice of America radio network and the Fulbright
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   American diplomats abroad and foreign diplomats constantly use
the Web location for statements on American policy or texts of
official speeches not covered by news organizations, McGregor said.
</P>
<P>
   The new invasion of the site, created in 1994, is far more
serious than the first, McGregor said. The FBI is working on the
case, and anyone caught could face serious criminal charges, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   McGregor said there were similarities between the two break-ins.
The first crippled the site for several days.
</P>
<P>
   In each attack the invader left the message, ``Crystal, I love
you,'' and the signature ``Zyklon,'' McGregor said. Zyklon-B was
the poison gas widely used in Nazi extermination camps.
</P>
<P>
   The styles of sabotage, however, were different in the two
cases. In the first the hacker inserted his page into the site and
then destroyed some of the agency's electronic documents.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts at the agency said they thought that they had
repaired the damage, but the saboteur had planted a ``Trojan
horse'' that repeated the destruction hours later, McGregor said.
</P>
<P>
   The new assault resulted in basic hardware damage and the
destruction of the site, McGregor said. The invader's message was
also accompanied by a strange scrawl. ``Before, he was just into
text,'' McGregor said. ``Now he's into bad graphics.''
</P>
<P>
   Since news of the new invasion began circulating in computer
circles, the USIA has heard from people who call themselves hackers
but disassociate themselves from the tactics of the taunters,
McGregor said. People who consider themselves hackers affect a
Robin Hood-like code of honor and describe more malicious saboteurs
as ``crackers,'' McGregor said, adding that the distinction is
irrelevant to him.
</P>
<P>
   The invasion occurs as the information agency is about to pass
from the scene. The independent agency will become part of the
State Department on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   McGregor said the damage from the break-ins could not be easily
estimated. More significant than dollars, he said, has been the
time spent by employees and outside contractors to make repairs.
</P>
<P>
   McGregor said a more permanent cost would be tighter security at
the Web site. Users will not notice, he said, but employees will
see changes as they have to go through additional elaborate steps
to place items on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply can't have this happening every six months,''
McGregor said. ``People rely on us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0545 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-HOPE-NYT &LR;      01-20 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-HOPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN DRAWS A CROWD AND SOME LAUGHS 
 (DW) 
 BY CLIFTON BROWN  
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA QUINTA, Calif. _ As Michael Jordan prepared to tee off
Wednesday morning, Charles Barkley surveyed the throng of at least
5,000 spectators who surrounded the 10th tee. ``I want to thank my
10 fans for coming,'' Barkley said. ``Everybody else came to see
Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day for laughs, a day for golf and a day for Jordan to
bask in the newfound glow of his retirement from the National
Basketball Association. Jordan was one of the amateur celebrities
who competed in Wednesday's first round of the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic, and his presence was the talk of Bermuda Dunes Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of all ages, including kids seeking autographs, senior
citizens screaming, ``Hi, Michael,'' and some who had never
witnessed a round of golf in person, followed Jordan's every move.
</P>
<P>
   For those keeping track of the professionals, Ben Bates, John
Huston and Tom Pernice Jr. ended the first round in a three-way tie
for the lead at nine-under par 63.
</P>
<P>
   Bates and Huston played at Indian Wells Country Club, and
Pernice played at the Arnold Palmer Private Course at PGA West. But
the majority of the gallery was interested in Jordan. David Duval,
considered by many to be the world's best golfer, played two groups
ahead of Jordan, yet Jordan's gallery was six times larger than
Duval's. Duval, who shot a two-under par 70, did not mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a golfer, you're used to seeing celebrities on the golf
course,'' Duval said, ``but Michael is at a whole different level.
This is great. Just watching people react to him is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan held his own with two birdies, eight pars, six bogeys and
two holes where he picked up without finishing. It was an admirable
performance, considering that Jordan will have surgery Monday to
repair a torn tendon in his right index finger. Jordan injured the
finger while cutting the tip off a cigar earlier this month, and
the surgery will prevent him from playing in the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach
National Pro-Am next month.
</P>
<P>
   The injury had no bearing on Jordan's decision to retire because
he had already made that decision. But even if Jordan had decided
to return to the NBA, he would not have been ready for the start of
the season. ``It's going to take about four or six weeks to
recover,'' said Jordan, who spoke briefly on the golf course but
generally avoided interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's team shot 11 under par, playing a two best-ball format.
Payne Stewart was the professional in Jordan's group, joined by
Barkley and Roy Green, the former National Football League star.
Stewart shot a 71 and showed patience with the frenzy surrounding
his partners. It figures to be another chaotic scene Thursday, when
Jordan and Barkley play in a group with John Daly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Jordan is an icon, so I knew what to expect,'' said
Stewart, winner of the 1989 PGA Championship and the 1991 United
States Open. ``I was looking forward to the day, and it was a
blast. There was a lot of needling going on, and it was chaotic.
But I had a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Barkley and Jordan. Hope, the 95-year-old host of the
tournament, greeted Jordan and Barkley on the first tee, and the
threesome posed for pictures. Starting on the 10th tee, Jordan
looked relaxed and hit a strong first tee shot. He went on to par
the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Barkley struggled mightily. At No. 18, his approach
shot sailed over the green and over the grandstand. Jordan fell to
the ground in laughter. ``I've never seen a guy hit so many bad
shots,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart agreed with Jordan's assessment of Barkley's game.
``Charles flinches over the ball,'' Stewart said. ``I don't know
how to cure that. I tried all day, but I couldn't. I don't know if
there's any hope. It's pretty ugly. I don't think he hit anybody
today, so that's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael's got a beautiful rhythm, he's an exceptional athlete,
and it kind of flows into his golf game. Charles might be beyond
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Barkley's difficulties did not stop him from talking. About
Jordan's retirement, Barkley said, ``I've got 500 channels on my
dish, and he was on every one of them.'' Asked about Jordan's golf
game, Barkley said, ``He's a better golfer than me, and a better
liar, masquerading with a 10 handicap. Michael's a lot better than
a 10, maybe about a three or four. He plays every day.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan's group reached its final hole, No. 9, the joking
didn't stop. Barkley looked at Green, by far the least famous of
the foursome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to figure out who you are,'' Barkley said
to Green. ``Anybody got a name tag?''
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan did not need a name tag, and he ended his day with
style, making a 30-foot birdie putt on No. 9, as the gallery
cheered. ``It was a lot of fun,'' Jordan said, leaving quickly
after his round. After one week, Jordan and retirement seemed to be
getting along just fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
