<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SUPER SPITE: DAN REEVES VS. BRONCOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dan Reeves was recuperating from heart bypass surgery last
month, the Atlanta Falcons' coach got a get-well phone call from
Pat Bowlen, the Denver owner who had fired Reeves as the Broncos'
coach after the 1992 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both kind of chuckled,'' Bowlen recalled last Sunday, ``and
said, `What if?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning what if both the Falcons and the Broncos were to get to
Super Bowl XXXIII?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, that scenario has materialized with all its spiteful
subplots: Reeves, once dismissed by Bowlen and dissed by
quarterback John Elway, will be opposing Bowlen, Elway and the
reigning Super Bowl-champion Broncos, coached by Mike Shanahan,
once dismissed by Reeves from his Bronco staff for siding with
Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Only once before in the Super Bowl matchups has the coach of one
team opposed a team he previously coached: The late Weeb Ewbank,
the Jets' coach in their 16-7 upset of the Baltimore Colts in III,
had taken command of the Jets in 1963 after nine seasons (and the
1958 and 1959 National Football League championships) as the Colts
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was,'' Ewbank told his wife, Lucy, after that Super Bowl,
``the most satisfying victory of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the most satisfying because it had stung Carroll
Rosenbloom, the Colts' owner who had fired Ewbank.
</P>
<P>
   But to listen to Reeves or Bowlen or Elway or Shanahan now, all
is forgiven, if not forgotten. Reeves insisted, ``We're not
enemies.'' When the Falcon coach was recuperating, Bowlen called,
Shanahan sent a card and Elway made a donation to the Falcons Youth
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't live in the past,'' Reeves said Monday at the Falcons'
complex. ``I teach my players to look at the next play, not the
last play. I look at life the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowlen insisted, ``I have a great relationship with Dan
Reeves,'' who coached the Broncos for 12 seasons before Bowlen
fired him after an 8-8 record in the 1992 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual,'' Bowlen said, ``that after 10 or 12 years
in one organization, coaches and owners can burn out with each
other. That's symptomatic of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Giants' coach before moving to Atlanta, in 1997, Reeves
and the Giants' owners burned out after only four seasons with each
other over Reeves' desire for more control.
</P>
<P>
   Elway and Reeves also had burned out with each other, but the
Broncos quarterback is quietly diplomatic about that now.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at what Dan has done in the last two years with
Atlanta,'' Elway said Sunday, ``it's just unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Broncos' 23-10 victory over the Jets in the American
Football Conference championship game, that's about all Elway would
say, or wanted to say. But when Elway arrived at the Broncos'
training camp in 1993 after Reeves had been fired, he had much more
to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``These last three years have been hell,'' Elway said then,
alluding to Reeves' ball-control offense. ``I know I would not have
been back here if Dan Reeves had been here. It wasn't worth it to
me. I didn't enjoy it. It wasn't any fun, and I got tired of
working with him.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Giants' training camp, Reeves responded, saying: ``Just
tell him it wasn't exactly heaven for me either. One of these days
I hope he grows up. Maybe he'll mature sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway had been Reeves' quarterback in each of the Broncos' three
losing Super Bowls _ to the Giants, the Redskins, and the 49ers (in
a 55-10 rout after the 1989 season). But even during that '89
season, Elway had grown disenchanted with Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do now is ball-control,'' Elway complained. ``I
think we've got to start looking for the big play more.''
</P>
<P>
   During that season, Reeves hired Shanahan, who had been
dismissed as the Oakland Raiders' head coach, as the Broncos'
quarterback coach. Including his years as the Broncos' offensive
coordinator from 1984 to 1987, Shanahan was on the Broncos' staff
for all three Super Bowl losses under Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1991 season, Shanahan was out; Reeves thought he was
too cozy with Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times Dan and I were great friends,'' Shanahan said Sunday.
``He's a great coach.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Dan Reeves is a Super Bowl opponent of Mike Shanahan,
John Elway and Pat Bowlen. And a victory on Jan. 31 in Miami will
surely be most satisfying for one side or the other. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
