<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TALENT IS RESURRECTED ON BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BKN-NBA) 
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association lockout is officially over,
training camps open Thursday and the Knicks, of all teams, have
boldly jumped ahead of the pack before so much as a shot is taken.
Never in my wildest dreams did I think that Latrell Sprewell would
wind up on Broadway; now that he is on the way, I find myself
actually looking forward to this abbreviated season.
</P>
<P>
   There should be a loud amen from celebrity row, from all who
have watched _ up close _ these same ol' Knicks get bounced out of
the second round of the playoffs for four consecutive seasons. You
actors, actresses and film producers, aren't you tired of seeing
the same show?
</P>
<P>
   At worst, Sprewell is a jerk. At best, he is insightful and
distant. In any event, he is not Anthony Mason who, despite the
chapel services and accouterments of religion, had difficulty
extricating himself from the pull of the street. Sprewell's problem
was that he despised his coach. He snapped 13 months ago and
wrongfully attacked P.J. Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   The incident carried subtle racial undertones; the idea that
black-on-white crime always elicits harsher penalties _ the NBA
originally suspended Sprewell for a year, before an arbitrator
reduced the penalty _ or black players chafing under an old-boy
power structure that keeps recycling the P.J. Carlesimos.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I'll be surprised if Sprewell so much as sneezes the
wrong way during his tenure in New York. This unexpected run on
Broadway may well be the blessing of his life, let alone of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell will flourish in New York for a couple of reasons. The
first and simplest is that Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy is not
Carlesimo. Some coaches get ahead because they coach; some get
ahead because they know how to maneuver. Van Gundy worked hard for
everything, and he has earned it the traditional way: as an
assistant here, an assistant there. He stood in line and finally
got his shot.
</P>
<P>
   Carlesimo, whose father, Peter Sr., is an important figure in
college basketball, in particular the National Invitation
Tournament, never served as an assistant. He learned how to
maneuver. He could disrespect players and get away with it because
his daddy, or some facsimile thereof (athletic director, team
president) was standing by to bail him out. One day last December,
Carlesimo and Sprewell simultaneously crossed their respective
lines, and no one's daddy was there to intervene. Now we'll see who
will have the biggest impact: Latrell or P.J.? My guess is that
you'll see Sprewell in the winner's circle before you see
Carlesimo's Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was that bad, teams wouldn't be trying to get him,'' the
Nets' Chris Gatling said recently. ``He's definitely a good
professional. And they know that.''
</P>
<P>
   The second reason the 28-year-old Sprewell will flourish in New
York is that the veteran is coming to a city of the fallen and the
resurrected; a city filled with souls who have overcome
indiscretions and excess. Surely the sports media will cheer
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   This is the city of Don Imus, the popular nonsports sports-radio
disk jockey who overcame years of abusing alcohol and drugs to
become one of the most prominent personalities on the air. Marv
Albert had a humiliating fall when the sordid details of his
private life were revealed, and he pleaded guilty to misdemeanor
assault charges. Albert was rehired last July by the MSG Network.
In explaining the decision, the MSG executive producer Mike
McCarthy said Albert was too much of a talent to be sitting on the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it. Talent. In the end it is all about winning
and ratings. Radio needs Imus, television needs Albert, the Knicks
need Sprewell. Who would have thought the Knicks had the nerve to
make a bold move that could actually push the franchise out of its
second-round doldrums?
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' renaissance, the Yankees' stunning dominance and even
the Nets' aggressive Calapari-led attack, persuaded the Knicks to
dispense with nice _ whatever that is _ and get real. So the
popular Charles Oakley goes to Toronto, the popular but volatile
John Starks and the erratic Chris Childs go west to Golden State.
The question now is whether Van Gundy and his staff have the nerve
to tell Patrick Ewing that there must also be changes in his game
if the Knicks plan to steal a championship in this abbreviated
season.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Latrell Fontaine Sprewell is coming to Broadway,
and I'm excited. For a change, the news media _ which shapes,
colors and forms so much of the public's perception _ instead of
leading the attack, can remind fans that New York, after all, is a
city of second and third chances.
</P>
<P>
   For Sprewell, the Knicks represent a golden second opportunity.
For Ewing, Sprewell may well represent his last chance. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
