<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0550 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-INFLATION-ART-     01-20 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-INFLATION-ART-815(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY AT RISK AS ISRAEL CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In the first heated weeks of Israel's four-month
election campaign, it appears that an early loser may be the
tight-fisted anti-inflation policy once championed by Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu but now defended only by the
politically isolated central bank.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, one of the proudest boasts of the Netanyahu
government was that in just two years it had nearly halved the
budget deficit and kept inflation in single digits for the first
time in three decades. But now Netanyahu has rattled some market
analysts and political rivals by saying that he may abandon
long-stated quests to slow inflation to 4 percent this year and to
cut the deficit still further, to 2 percent of the gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the perception that fiscal discipline has succumbed to
electoral pressure, Netanyahu is now simultaneously a candidate for
re-election and his own finance minister. He took over the finance
portfolio when Yaakov Neeman faxed his resignation from a European
vacation last month, frustrated by the governing coalition's
failure to unite behind its own 1999 budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 budget remains stalled in Parliament, leaving Israel
without one for the first time. Netanyahu has proposed additional
spending not contemplated in his original $214 billion proposal,
including free schooling for 3- and 4-year-olds, and the
reinstatement of tax subsidies for the elderly that he had once
decided to eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if I were handing out videocassette recorders,''
the prime minister said, dismissing accusations from opponents that
he is abandoning principle in an effort to buy back voters
disaffected by his dealings with the Palestinians and by his
personal style. He lost a functioning majority in Parliament and
called new elections, serving during the campaign now in a
caretaker role.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Netanyahu's critics nonetheless endorse his newly
espoused view that it is time to ``loosen the belts'' and embrace
more inflation and higher spending if it brings another point or
two of job growth.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the sole point of concord in the battle to form the next
government seems to be across-the-board opposition to the Bank of
Israel's steadfast refusal to prime the pump with lower interest
rates. The central bank's key discount rate is 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Meridor, who resigned as Netanyahu's first finance minister
in 1997 and now seeks the prime ministership in a new centrist
grouping, called current interest rates exorbitant. ``To get
inflation down is important, but this cannot be the only God we
worship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Market analysts warn that acceding to expansionary pressure
would impose costs of its own on an economy that succumbed to
hyperinflation a decade ago, but had recently seemed to be entering
an era of price stability and export-driven economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with unemployment rising to nearly 9 percent last year and
per-capita income declining 0.4 percent, to $17,178, politicians
across the spectrum are pushing hard for cheaper credit and more
state spending. The alternative, they say, with global markets
wobbling and local political uncertainties discouraging foreign
investment, could be a deep and prolonged recession.
</P>
<P>
   Avraham Shohat, who served as finance minister in the last Labor
Party government, said that Israel could not afford to combat
inflation at the cost of high unemployment. ``We have a very
expensive life, with our security problems, and with immigration,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a choice between 2 percent inflation and 12 percent
unemployment, and 5 percent inflation and 5 percent unemployment, I
would choose the latter,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, Netanyahu surprised rival politicians and
financial analysts by declaring his intention to raise the
government's official inflation target for 1999 to a range of 5
percent to 7 percent from the previously announced 4 percent _ an
increase he called ``not that significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for a government that had pledged to keep inflation at
levels of the leading industrial nations, the statement was seen as
a philosophical reversal _ and a transparent effort to force the
Bank of Israel to relax its tight money policies.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank's president, Jacob Frenkel, now at the midpoint
of his second presidentially appointed five-year term, has
suggested that overt pressure by the prime minister may backfire,
making a rate cut even less likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Markets are impressed by the degree of commitment by
policy-makers to price stability,'' Frenkel said in an interview
last week. ``If this is put into question, it makes the job for
monetary policy even more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be an ``extraordinary mistake,'' he said, to raise the
inflation target at a moment when the central bank believes that
the annualized rate is already falling back to the 4-to-5 percent
range.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Netanyahu reiterated his intention to revise the
target upward, but did not say when the new figure would be
formally adopted. Though the central bank has almost complete
autonomy in setting interest rates and managing the money supply,
it is legally obligated to work within a government-determined
framework of inflation goals and other macroeconomic targets.
</P>
<P>
   Frenkel is worried that he may end up officially committed to a
higher target than the credit markets would dictate in the course
of trading. ``It would be an extraordinarily awkward challenge and
task for the central bank to reverse course and support higher
inflation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of Netanyahu's announcement portrayed it as a simple
acknowledgment of economic reality. Prices last year jumped 8.6
percent, the central bank announced last Friday, up from 7 percent
in 1997. The 4 percent target for 1999 was no longer viable, they
argued.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, however, says that the inflationary surge of 1998 was
a short-term problem that has since been contained. The Russian
financial crisis that began in August reverberated locally with a
slight but jolting devaluation of Israel's currency, the shekel, in
September. Sharp price increases resulted for imports and other
dollar-pegged goods in October and November.
</P>
<P>
   Frenkel pushed up interest rates in a successful effort to stop
a continuing run on the shekel, which dropped to an exchange rate
of 4.4 in October from 3.9 in September, and has since rebounded to
4.049 to the dollar on Wednesday. The interest-rate spike worked,
but at the price of a virtual freeze in new lending to business.
</P>
<P>
   A University of Chicago economist and a former research director
of the International Monetary Fund, Frenkel is an unapologetic
defender of this bitter monetary medicine. His former IMF
colleagues are strong supporters, urging the government not to
raise the inflation target and praising the bank's tough
interest-rate stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This firm monetary-policy response, which occurred against the
background of uncertainty about the passage of the 1999 budget,
provided a strong signal that price increases beyond those stemming
directly from the depreciation of the shekel would not be
accommodated,'' the IMF noted approvingly last month.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic political reaction, though, was unremittingly
hostile, with members of Parliament from left, right and center
assailing the belt-tightening. Netanyahu's aides echoed the
criticism of Frenkel, and Shohat introduced a bill that would
transfer interest-rate authority to a new committee presided over
by the bank but controlled by appointees of the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed its first reading last week. This politicization
of monetary policy would be preferable, Shohat said, to the present
system, ``where one man has the power to decide by himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
