<HEADLINE>
LARGEST STUDY YET RATES EFFECT OF FERTILITY DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass.) (lb) 
 By PHILLIP HILTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using fertility drugs increases a woman's chances of getting
pregnant, but the drugs should be used cautiously to avoid the
possibility of multiple birth, said a study and an accompanying
editorial in the current issue of The New England Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The report was the first large, well-controlled study to ask and
answer the question about whether using fertility drugs actually
improved chances of pregnancy. Some doctors have suggested that
conception would occur normally without drug treatment for couples
who were patient, and some have suggested that other treatments
without fertility drugs might work just as well.
</P>
<P>
   But the new study, carried out on 932 couples at 10 fertility
centers around the United States, showed that for couples with no
known physical bars to pregnancy who had tried to get pregnant for
three and a half years, on average, using fertility drugs and
injecting the husband's sperm directly into the wife's womb was the
most effective method.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of drugs and uterine injection used each month
for four months resulted in pregnancy for 33 percent of the women.
A second method, using drugs but injecting sperm onto the cervix,
had a 19 percent success rate. A third group, using no drugs but
with injection of sperm into the womb, had a success rate of 18
percent. Injecting sperm onto the cervix produced pregnancies in 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But in an editorial accompanying the study, two Dutch fertility
experts, Dr. Egbert te Velde and Dr. Bernard Cohlen, both of
University Hospital in Utrecht, raised a caution about the study.
The doctors wrote that the data in the study supported the idea
that if patients were willing to wait another year and continue
with sexual intercourse alone, a result that was just as good might
be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting has the advantage of avoiding the possibility of
multiple births caused by fertility drugs. In this study, 24 of the
72 women who took drugs and became pregnant had multiple
pregnancies _ including three sets of quadruplets and four sets of
triplets. Without fertility drugs, about one in 90 pregnancies
might produce multiple births.
</P>
<P>
   The editorial suggested that couples seeking to have children
often were not given full information on their choices, and might
believe they no longer had a good chance of getting pregnant
without drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Guzick of the University of Rochester, the chief
author of the paper, argued that although 10 percent of the
patients in the study who did not take drugs still became pregnant,
that did not suggest that if the study were carried on for another
year or two, an additional 10 percent or 20 percent would get
pregnant. Some patients might have unknown problems that prevented
pregnancy, Guzick said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the fertility treatments studied were
generally not the first option. The women in the study took
gonadotropins, which induce women to produce more eggs than normal,
in conjunction with sperm injected directly into the uterus,
usually the third approach. The first two methods are carefully
timed intercourse and treatment with weaker drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Benjamin Younger, executive director of the American Society
of Reproductive Medicine, said that the editorial's suggestion that
couples wait for treatment was ``great in theory, but doesn't work
in practice,'' adding, ``People who have been trying for years are
very frustrated and don't want to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the authors of the study noted that they were paid
consultants for Serono, a Massachusetts company that makes
fertility drugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
