<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS OF BASKETBALL NOW BEGINS IN EARNEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN) 
(lb) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gymnasium doors open at 2 p.m. Eastern time, and the
free-agent-signing floodgates will burst. Coaches will coach and
players will be gasping for air for the first time in six months
and every wild bit of speculation will either become reality or
remain rumor.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the season was rescued from cancellation, the
National Basketball Association is open for business. On Wednesday
night, the league and the players union completed details and
formally signed the new six-year collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The 29 teams will play a 50-game schedule beginning Feb. 5, and
a full complement of playoff series is expected to begin in May and
last until the final week of June.
</P>
<P>
   The lifting of the lockout, which lasted 204 days, means teams
can immediately begin talking to their players and give physical
exams both to those under contract and to potential free agents.
</P>
<P>
   It also clears the way for a bevy of signings, including the
deal that will take Latrell Sprewell to the New York Knicks and
send John Starks, Chris Mills and Terry Cummings to the Golden
State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   The league also announced the start of the exhibition season on
Sunday in Chicago, where you will need a program to identify the
six-time champion Bulls. In the first of 29 exhibition games
between neighborly franchises, Chicago will be host to Indiana at 3
p.m. Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Jordan retired, Scottie Pippen on a plane to
Houston to be introduced by the Rockets on Friday, Steve Kerr
headed to San Antonio and Luc Longley on his way to Phoenix,
Chicago will field a roster that will include Roy Rogers, Martin
Murrsepp, Bubba Wells and Mark Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio was scheduled to meet Houston on Saturday in the
first preseason game, but the delay in signing the new agreement
forced the teams to push the game back to Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and the New Jersey Nets meet each other at Madison
Square Garden at 7:30 p.m. next Wednesday and at Continental Arena
at 7:30 p.m. Jan. 29.
</P>
<P>
   There were other developments Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles Barkley was trying to drive up his earning power in
Houston, implying that he had not ruled out Atlanta and Seattle as
possible teams he would sign with. Speaking from the Bob Hope
Chrysler Classic in La Quinta, Calif., Barkley mused out loud
whether to sign with Houston or Seattle. ``Who do you think is
better? Me, Olajuwon and Pippen? Or me, Gary Payton and Vin
Baker?''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said seven teams inquired about his services, and he
told four not to phone back _ including the Knicks. The prevailing
feeling among team officials is that Barkley will re-sign with
Houston. Also, the SuperSonics are interested in Olden Polynice and
Billy Owens to help shore up their front line.
</P>
<P>
   _ Glen Rice, the deadeye shooting guard for the Charlotte
Hornets, will undergo elbow surgery and will probably miss at least
the first month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Detroit Pistons were on the verge of signing Loy Vaught
and Christian Laettner to multiyear deals, despite injuries that
may prevent them from playing in February. Laettner, one of the
biggest lockout casualties, underwent arthroscopic surgery for a
torn knee ligament he suffered in a pickup game last summer at Duke
University. But he has been rehabilitating ever since, and may be
ready to play as early as March.
</P>
<P>
   _ Denver outlasted Phoenix in the scramble for the sky-walking
forward Antonio McDyess. ``It was a real close call,'' McDyess'
agent, James Bryant, told The Associated Press. ``It came down to a
question of do you want to inherit a contender or do you want to
build one? Phoenix is a great franchise, but Denver is doing a lot
of exciting things that haven't come out yet.'' The Suns,
meanwhile, began pursuing Tom Gugliotta, whom Minnesota hopes to
re-sign.
</P>
<P>
   League lawyers have been working on the new agreement round the
clock since the two sides settled on Jan. 6, and will get little
rest between now and Feb. 5. Every one of at least 15 deals on the
table on Thursday must be approved by the NBA before the trade or
acquisition is made final.
</P>
<P>
   One league official said on condition of anonymity: ``It's all
going to be happening rapid-fire. Teams will be talking to agents,
players will be meeting their new teammates and general chaos will
reign for a few days. But at least it's back to the business of
basketball, thank God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
