<SLUG> BC-NY-BUILDING-COLLAPSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAULTY CONSTRUCTION CITED IN TIMES SQUARE TOWER COLLAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 700-foot construction scaffold that buckled and
broke in Times Square last summer, killing a woman in a nearby
hotel and paralyzing traffic for several days, was built improperly
and was missing critical support braces on 10 floors, according to
citations issued Wednesday by federal safety officials.
</P>
<P>
   The citations issued by the federal Occupational Safety and
Health Administration against the builder of the scaffold,
Universal Builders Supply, do not state that the defects were the
cause of the collapse, the city's most serious construction
accident in a decade. But investigators involved in a city inquiry
say the violations were among the problems that contributed to the
accident on July 21 at the construction site of the Conde Nast
building, on Broadway between 42nd and 43rd Streets.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing the citations accusing the company of four safety
violations, the federal agency recommended fines totaling $26,000.
Universal Builders, which is based in Mount Vernon, N.Y., has until
Feb. 10 to contest the citations.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the accident,'' said Robert Kulick, director of the
federal safety agency in New York, ``we found that the scaffold had
not been built in accordance with an engineer's plans, that support
braces were missing and that the company had failed to insure that
the mast bolts were maintained for tightness. We consider these
serious safety violations.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's official investigation into the causes of the
accident is still months away from completion. One person involved
in that investigation said that early on, ``it was clear that there
was some crossbracing that was missing.'' The braces were designed
to insure that the scaffold remained straight, level and square
against the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``My suspicion is that we'll undoubtedly agree with OSHA,'' said
the investigator, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   City investigators and engineers said they were unsure whether
they could identify a single reason for the accident, but that they
could probably identify a series of problems that built one upon
another, creating a ``cascade effect,'' until the scaffold
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin O'Callaghan, president of United Builders, declined to
comment on the accusations of violations because the city was still
investigating the collapse. He did issue a statement saying that
``the actual cause of the collapse has not yet been determined.''
</P>
<P>
   United Builders, which erected scaffolding for the renovation of
the Statue of Liberty, Grand Central Terminal and the Washington
Monument, is already contesting citations for other safety
violations in the death of a carpenter, Charles Robbins, in an
earlier accident at the Conde Nast site, which is known as 4 Times
Square.
</P>
<P>
   The city's report may not be completed until May 1, said Gaston
Silva, the city's building commissioner. ``We will look at OSHA's
findings and incorporate them into our findings,'' Silva said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the scaffolding cast a pall over what was
supposed to have been a triumph for the developer, Douglas Durst,
and a symbol of the rebirth of Times Square. Durst was building the
first new office tower in Manhattan since the recession in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But on the morning of July 21, the scaffold and an elevator
tower that had been erected next to the 48-story tower buckled at
the 21st floor as the sound of tearing metal echoed across midtown.
The scaffolding above the 20th floor dropped about eight feet,
wrenching the elevator tower, which snapped off and fell. A 50-foot
section of that tower pierced the roof of the Woodstock Hotel
across 43rd Street, knocking a concrete slab onto Thereza
Feliconio, 85, and killing her as she sat in her top-floor
apartment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
