<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Peers' Voting Rights
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair's government submitted to Parliament
legislation aimed at fulfilling his promise to eliminate the voting
rights of 750 hereditary peers, members of the House of Lords who
gained their seats by the circumstances of birth. Some 500 life
peers would remain in a transitional assembly while a proposed
Royal Commission produced recommendations due Dec. 31 for
longer-term reform of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Party Chief to Step Down
</P>
<P>
   Paddy Ashdown, left, said he would step down in June as leader
of the Liberal Democrats, Britain's third-largest political party,
and would not run for re-election to Parliament in 2002. Ashdown
took over leadership of the party in 1988 and in the last national
election in May 1997 saw it capture 45 seats in Parliament, the
best showing by a third party in Britain in 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Fugitive Caught
</P>
<P>
   After a 13-month manhunt, South Africa announced that it finally
captured its most wanted man, Colin Chauke. The former
anti-apartheid guerrilla fighter was facing murder and robbery
charges when he escaped from prison late in 1997. Chauke is accused
of masterminding a series of attacks on armored cars.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe: Detained Journalists Moved
</P>
<P>
   An editor and a reporter for The Standard newspaper who were
arrested after writing about an alleged army coup plot have been
removed from Harare's central police station, their lawyers said.
The police refused to say where the two suspects, Mark Chavunduka
and Ray Choto, were taken, raising fears that they were being
interrogated by the army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
