<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AND US AIRWAYS POST WEAK FOURTH QUARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Ariz.) 
(lb) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Airlines and US Airways posted disappointing quarterly
earnings Wednesday on weaker-than-expected revenues, while America
West Airlines exceeded Wall Street estimates by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that American and US Airways, like other major
domestic airlines, were hurt during the final months of 1998 as
revenue declined from the premium fares most often paid by business
travelers flying at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines make most of their money off business travelers and
you saw business travel stall in the fourth quarter,'' said Glenn
Engel, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Low fuel prices helped ease the carriers' pain by lowering
expenses. But the savings were not enough to offset the slide in
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   AMR Corp., the holding company for American, the second-largest
airline in the United States, said earnings declined 13 percent to
$182 million, or $1.09 a diluted share, compared with $208 million,
or $1.16 a share, during the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusting for a stock split and one-time gains, AMR earned $1.00
a share compared with $1.09 in 1997. The consensus estimate of
analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. was $1.16 a share.
</P>
<P>
   While total revenue at AMR rose 1.3 percent to $4.6 billion in
the quarter, passenger revenue at American Airlines fell 3 percent
to $3.5 billion compared with the same period last year. The
company attributed the decline primarily to softening demand on its
international routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing are weaker economies in Europe and Latin
America and Asia at a time of capacity increases by the industry,''
Gerard Arpey, AMR's chief financial officer, said.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways, the sixth-largest domestic airline, earned $104
million, or $1.18 a share, in the quarter, compared with $479
million, or $4.66 a share in the same period a year earlier.
Excluding a one-time $125 million charge and a $467 million tax
credit, earnings declined 25 percent. The consensus earnings
estimate by First Call had been $1.20 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's costs, not including fuel, declined 1 percent
compared with a year earlier, largely because of the introduction
of Metrojet, the low-cost airline it started last year to combat
growing competition from Southwest Airlines. But Metrojet also
charges lower fares, which along with the softening of business
travel pushed US Airways' total per-passenger revenues down nearly
5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company was also hurt during the quarter by the transition
to a new computer reservations system that confused many
reservation agents.
</P>
<P>
   Engel said that Rakesh Gangwal, US Airways' chief executive,
told analysts during a teleconference on Wednesday that downward
pressures on revenues would continue this year as the airline
expands Metrojet and faces more competition. Gangwal warned that
the consensus 1999 earnings estimate of $6.40 a share might be too
high.
</P>
<P>
   America West, which struggled to improve its operations last
year, bucked the industry trend by attracting more business
travelers on long-haul flights to cities like New York and Boston
from its hubs in Phoenix and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Net income for America West, which is based in Phoenix and is
the ninth-largest airline in the country, remained flat at about
$20 million in the quarter, but soared 11 percent to $22.4 million
after excluding a one-time charge. Stock purchases helped per-share
earnings soar to 56 cents from 43 cents in 1997, easily surpassing
the First Call consensus estimate of 39 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Parker, America West's chief financial officer, said
America West plans to continue to woo business travelers this year
and will expand capacity by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange on Wednesday, America
West shares rose $1.375 to $19.50; US Airways fell $6.3125 a share,
to $51.125, and AMR fell $4.4375, to $59.8125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
