<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1938 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-BILLYPAYNE21-COX     01-20 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BILLYPAYNE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Payne welcomes any look into Atlanta's bid
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's Olympic organizers say they would welcome an
investigation, if only to quash continuing speculation about what
misdeeds might have occurred in trying to get the 1996 Summer
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be delighted to talk about the experience: the good, the
bad and the difficult,'' said Billy Payne, leader of the volunteer
bid committee and later president of the Atlanta Committee for the
Olympic Games. ``We ain't perfect, and we ain't arrogant, but we
didn't bribe anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he is weary of the media barrage distracting him from
his current job as a top executive with Premiere Technologies. He
also said he hasn't heard the first word from any of the four
investigations into suspected wrongdoing by Salt Lake City Olympic
organizers. Although the International Olympic Committee said it
would expand its inquiry to other cities if presented with
evidence, Payne said no one has contacted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will talk to anybody,'' he said in an interview in his
sixth-floor office at Premiere headquarters near Lenox Square.
``Notwithstanding the fact that we all have other jobs now, and
this was 10 or 12 years ago, and it's hard to remember, we're still
put in a position where we have to explain the fact that we
competed under the rules, which is kind of regrettable. But we're
not stonewalling anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he responded to IOC inquiries in 1990 after Atlanta
won the Games. At that time, the IOC convened representatives of
all bid cities in Lausanne, Switzerland, and grilled them about the
bid process and any abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so euphoric, we didn't have anything bad to say about
the process,'' Payne said. He said he does not recall any losing
bidders citing specific problems. ``We would say what we already
said. We played by the rules. There was nothing untoward, nothing
unethical.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Atlanta bid to heat up
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Battle, a key member of Atlanta's bid effort and later
head of ACOG's international relations, said Wednesday, ``In some
ways I wish they'd just investigate us, because I don't think
they'd find anything. And then they'd give us a clean bill of
health, and we could get on with things.''
</P>
<P>
   Battle, now president of Central Atlanta Progress, a downtown
business group, is the most public member from the Atlanta Olympic
effort. He said he has fielded dozens of media calls from around
the globe since the Salt Lake influence-peddling scandal broke in
November. The interest in Atlanta will only intensify now that the
IOC has promised to look beyond the awarding of the 2002 Games and
reportedly has unearthed unethical activities in Toronto and
Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   A report authored by the IOC's Dick Pound, a Montreal lawyer,
details influence-peddling in the awarding of Olympics dating back
to the 1980s, according to the Wall Street Journal, which has seen
the report. Pound details activities of sports agents attempting to
sell IOC votes for millions of dollars in bribes. And it implicates
as many as 16 IOC members, who could face expulsion for violating
IOC ethics by accepting payments and gifts from Salt Lake City bid
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he was ``shocked'' when told of allegations that Salt
Lake officials provided scholarships, medical care, lavish gifts
and cold cash to IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salt Lake had the best bid on its merits to host the Winter
Olympic Games,'' Payne said. ``It was not necessary, given the
incredible impressiveness of their bid, to move outside at all the
permitted boundaries of the bidding process.''
</P>
<P>
   While all bidding cities were required to provide first-class
airfare and accommodations for visiting IOC members, Payne said,
the scholarships, cosmetic surgery and expensive rifles and ski
trips supposedly offered by Salt Lake officials crossed the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's inappropriate, clearly,'' Payne said, referring to the
$400,000 scholarship program that benefited relatives of at least
six IOC members. ``It is systematic. It is organized. It is
intentional. I even saw where a member of their board said, `Yeah,
we used the Atlanta model.' Well, we didn't have a scholarship
program. We didn't have a model.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne's close ally on the Atlanta bid effort, former Mayor
Andrew Young, said last week he thought the scholarship program was
acceptable, because it helped poor Africans receive an education.
Payne said he disagrees but conceded that he understood Young's
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Andy espouses that there is nothing wrong with this
program, I know from the bottom reaches of his heart he sincerely
believes that,'' Payne said. ``In this particular context, as it
relates to the fact that relatives of these students were to later
cast their vote, I think it is inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Young recently admitted delivering athletic equipment and
apparel to Jean-Claude Ganga, an IOC member implicated in the
scandal. The goods, to be distributed to African youth, were
delivered a month before Atlanta won the bid in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But Payne gave Young his unqualified support. ``You're talking
about the conduct of one of the greatest human beings that God ever
put on this Earth,'' Payne said about Young, bristling when asked
if Young's activities were questionable in the context of the
current scandal. ``So, when Andy Young tells me and others that in
taking those balls and T-shirts to those kids he was doing it as a
part of what he considered his mandate in life, to help others,
then I would support that with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   No control over plane tickets
</P>
<P>
   As for courting the IOC, Payne said, ``We were told that
first-class air fare was what you provide them, that gifts up to
$200 or $150 were permitted. Instead of taking them to fancy
restaurants, we took them into our homes. We felt it was just an
extension of Southern hospitality. I felt we were showing our city
in its best light.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he did not know that some IOC members habitually
cashed in their first-class tickets instead of using them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an obligation to reimburse them for first-class air
fare,'' he said. ``Whether or not we had an obligation to strap
them in a lie detector chair and ask them if they used it, I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he was never approached by any consultants seeking
bribes for votes and wouldn't have responded favorably if he had.
</P>
<P>
   As the IOC executive board convenes in Lausanne this weekend to
interrogate the indicted and discuss reform of the bid-selection
process, Payne and other former Atlanta Olympic officials debate
whether to hold a news conference here to manage what might become
a flood of inquiries. ``I have ultimate responsibility and
accountability for everything that happened during the bid,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he expressed disagreement with calls by Salt Lake
organizers and others for IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch to
take similar responsibility for the actions of IOC members. ``I'm
giving him the benefit of the doubt, primarily because I'm grateful
to him,'' he said. ``And I haven't seen any hard evidence to date
that connects him to this wrongdoing, and he's done so much for the
Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
