<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SBC-COMCAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SBC TO ACQUIRE COMCAST'S CELLULAR TELEPHONE OPERATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Md., Mass., N.Y., Conn., R.I., Pa., N.J., Del.)  By GERALDINE FABRIKANT  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As part of continuing consolidation in the cellular telephone
industry, SBC Communications Inc. has agreed to acquire the
cellular telephone operations of the Comcast Corp. for $400 million
in cash and $1.27 billion in assumed debt.
</P>
<P>
   SBC will add Comcast's 800,000 cellular customers, most in the
Northeast, to the 6.5 million cellular subscribers it already has,
also concentrated in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, first reported in The Philadelphia Inquirer, offers
Comcast a way to focus more aggressively on its core cable business
and substantially reduce its debt.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast has been gradually reducing its debt, and its ratio of
debt to cash flow after the deal will be about 3.4 to 1, compared
with 8.7 to 1 in 1994. Along with other cable operators, Comcast's
stock has been rising steadily and closed Wednesday at $66.3125
after touching a 52-week high of $69.25 during the day. Once the
deal is completed, the company will have $4.9 billion in debt and
pro forma cash flow of $1.44 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was logical in an industry that has been consolidating
rapidly and is under intense pricing pressure because of the
popularity of the AT&AMP;T Corp.'s single-rate program, which allows
customers to use their phones anywhere in the United States and pay
one rate, with no roaming or long-distance charges. That plan has
forced regional competitors to consolidate and match the low
prices, and explains why the Bell Atlantic Corp. wanted to buy
Airtouch Communications Inc. so badly before it lost out to
Vodafone Group P.L.C. of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   With only 800,000 customers, Comcast could not hope to compete
aggressively, and Salvatore Muoio, who heads his own investment
partnership, said that the sale should have occurred years ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, SBC is paying only 10 times 1998 cash flow for the
cellular customers, or about $2,100 a customer. That multiple is
far lower than the roughly 18 times cash flow that Vodafone agreed
to pay for Airtouch in its $60 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of Airtouch's customers are overseas. Muoio
noted that American cellular properties are selling at lower
multiples because buyers think that there is more growth potential
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Roberts, the president of Comcast, acknowledged Wednesday
that there was a trend toward national and global competitors in
the wireless industry, making it harder for smaller operators. And
Comcast can use the cash from the sale to help pay off pending
acquisitions. It has agreed to pay $700 million for a controlling
stake in Jones Intercable Inc., which has a million subscribers,
and $760 million for Prime Communications, with 450,000
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   SBC already has agreed to buy the Ameritech Corp., the
fifth-largest local phone company. Its cellular customers are in
Washington, Baltimore, Boston, upstate New York, Connecticut and
Rhode Island. Comcast has customers in Philadelphia, Delaware and
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Salomon, a spokesman for SBC, said the merger would
slightly dilute earnings, but he added that it would not affect
Wall Street's projection of $2.37 a share for 1999. SBC fell 50
cents Wednesday, to $58.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2259EST &QL; 
