<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HOCKEY-BURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURE, MAN OF MYSTIQUE, JOINS THE ICE WARS 
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Russia, Canada, Wash., Mich.) By JOE LAPOINTE  
  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ After flying in Wednesday from Moscow, Pavel
Bure slept from midnight until 9 a.m., more hours than some hockey
players get on the road. Next to Bure in the first-class cabin was
Yuri Ushakov, on his way to Washington as Russia's new ambassador
to the United States. Bure was en route to New York as the newest
Florida Panther.
</P>
<P>
   High over the Atlantic, these two citizens of the world could
talk about hockey and politics and who knows what else. Perhaps
they discussed capitalism. Bure's next contract, currently being
negotiated, might pay up to $10 million per season. Russian players
such as Bure, Detroit's Sergei Fedorov and Ottawa's Aleksei Yashin,
the last generation raised under Soviet Communism, are among the
most determined bargainers in the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   One of the elite athletes in his sport, Bure forced a trade by
refusing to report to the Vancouver Canucks and missing half the
season. Idle for nine months, no longer a resident of Canada, he
was back in the U.S. of A. for a morning skate with his new
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Bure decided to compete Wednesday night against the
Islanders at the Coliseum and Thursday against the Rangers in
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to start to play anyway,'' Bure said. ``So I'll start
tonight. I really want to play. The sooner I start, the better. It
was pretty hard, especially the last five months. I was missing it
a lot. Finally, it's over and I'm glad.''
</P>
<P>
   He wore black slacks, a black shirt with a zipper to the neck, a
black suit coat with little lapels, shiny, black buckled shoes on
his feet and the usual wary look in his eyes. His longish hair is
reddish-brown and his full mouth often seems to pout. In many ways,
Bure is hockey's international man of mystery. A few years ago,
Bure said he would re-establish his family's watch-making business,
which dates back to the days of the czar. Wednesday, he said that
it is hard to concentrate on hockey and business and that his
factories aren't yet on line.
</P>
<P>
   In recent seasons, Bure's name has been heard in whispers of
players targeted for extortion by Russian mobsters. When he travels
around to Moscow night clubs in luxury sedans with bodyguards, it
can promote gossip.
</P>
<P>
   His father, a former Olympic diver, was Bure's personal trainer
_ until Bure fired him.
</P>
<P>
   Among the teams mentioned in the trade talks for Bure were the
Islanders and the Rangers. After the Islanders dropped out, the
Rangers, seemed to be a logical fit. They need another scorer if
they are to avoid missing the playoffs for the second consecutive
season. They have the money, as their $42 million payroll suggests.
They have the Russian community of Brighton Beach nearby and they
have the big spotlight that Bure seems to enjoy, although he
pretends to shrug it off with insouciance. ``Do I have a choice?''
he said, with a smile, of the attention. ``Mostly, I enjoy playing
hockey. Anything else I have to do, I'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers declined Bure when Vancouver insisted on the
rookie Manny Malhotra as part of the deal. The Rangers project
Malhotra as a future captain, a two-way center who could be a star
for a decade. With Wayne Gretzky at $6 million, Mike Richter at $5
million and free agent-to-be Brian Leetch negotiating in the range
of $6 million to $10 million, even the Rangers have their limits.
Neil Smith, the president and general manager, says that, at this
stage of rebuilding, a trade of Malhotra and other young players
for Bure would risk long-term infrastructure for limited,
short-term success.
</P>
<P>
   In the news media this week, Smith has spun his case with vigor
rarely seen outside impeachment defenses. It remains to be seen if
Smith's jury, his bosses at the Garden, will allow Smith to finish
his term, especially if the Rangers miss the tournament again.
</P>
<P>
   Bure dodges the Ranger issue as deftly as he avoids checks of
defensemen. He is a Panther now, dedicated to beating the Rangers
and finishing ahead of them and other teams in the race for the
playoffs. Ranger fans, wishful and wistful, can see him Thursday
night in his only scheduled New York appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Murray, the Panthers coach, said Bure would play on a line
with two other Russian skaters, Viktor Kozlov and Oleg Kvasha.
``The chemistry could be pretty good right away,'' Murray said.
``The fact that they speak the same language is going to make him
feel more comfortable at the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray's brother, Bryan Murray, is the general manager of the
Panthers. When he worked in Detroit, Bryan Murray helped assemble
the ``Russian Five'' that made up the core of the Red Wings'
championship squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous move for hockey,'' Bryan Murray said of
Bure's return.
</P>
<P>
   He is probably right, although he gambled big by trading
defenseman Ed Jovanovski and several other assets. In an era of low
scoring, great goalies and stifling defensive systems, Bure is a
virtuoso, able to create goals with solo rushes of speedy skating
and hard shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In the Olympics last winter in Japan, Bure's five-goal explosion
eliminated Finland and put Russia in the gold-medal game. Even
hockey's devoted aficionados can count its top gate attractions on
the fingers of two hands, and Bure could be the one with a ring.
For hiring him, the Murrays rate two thumbs up, even if their
fingers are crossed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2306EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0562 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2084 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-SOLOVITZ-NYT     01-20 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SOLOVITZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMMY SOLOVITZ, 71, A MENTOR AT THE TIMES 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Texas)  By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sammy Solovitz, a wise-cracking, hard-living mentor to
generations of copy boys at The New York Times, died on Jan. 12 in
Houston. He was 71 and had lived in Texas since his retirement in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   He died in his apartment of natural but as yet undetermined
causes, said his niece, Brenda Polunsky.
</P>
<P>
   From the day he was hired at The Times _ Nov. 18, 1943 _ Samuel
Leo Solovitz captivated the low and the mighty with his feisty
manner and pugnacious wit. To the scores of well-known reporters
and editors who came to the business through his newsroom boot
camp, he became a figure in lore _ a symbol of an era when
newsrooms still pulsated to the clack of typewriters and copy boys
rushed stories, a few paragraphs at a time, from reporters to
editors, and then to the printers in the composing room.
</P>
<P>
   On the day he was hired, he was 16 and delivering telegrams. At
4 feet 9 inches, he was too short for the Army but tall enough to
work as a uniformed messenger for Western Union. When he whisked
into the city room, Edwin L. James, the managing editor, looked up
from his desk and was intrigued by the sight of a pillbox hat
bobbing above a railing that surrounded his corner office _ all he
could see of Solovitz.
</P>
<P>
   James investigated and engaged the messenger in conversation.
The messenger spoke his mind. (He always did.) James asked him if
he would like a job. Solovitz said he would. He went to the Western
Union office, turned in his uniform and then returned to take up
his duties as a copy boy, earning $16 a week, $2 more than he got
from Western Union.
</P>
<P>
   He had found his calling and rose quickly to become head of the
nightside copy boys, supervising a crew of journalistic aspirants,
many of whom would stay in the business and many who would not.
</P>
<P>
   Over 40 years, Solovitz could often tell the difference,
developing a fine eye for character and talent. ``He was the best
judge of people,'' said Arthur Gelb, who started as a copy boy and
later became the paper's managing editor. He remembered what an odd
couple they were when they went out to Times Square to pick up the
first editions of competing papers. Gelb stood 6 foot 2, while
Solovitz, to his delight, was often taken for a jockey. On such
occasions, he was not above telling attractive women that he was
riding at Belmont the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who counted him as their first boss at The Times are
Russell T. Lewis, now president and chief executive officer of The
New York Times Co.; Joseph Lelyveld, executive editor of The Times;
Norman Pearlstine, who led The Wall Street Journal and who is now
the editor in chief of Time Inc.; and Vice President Al Gore, who
spent a summer as a copy boy.
</P>
<P>
   Solovitz would start work at 7:30 p.m. and finish at 3 a.m.,
when the last edition went to press, repeatedly goading his
dawdling charges: ``Tell your story walking!'' or ``This is a
daily, not a weekly!'' or ``Where do you think you are, the Yale
Club?''
</P>
<P>
   At times he would resort to obscure Yiddish curses he had picked
up at his mother's candy store in Brooklyn, where his formal
education involved nothing more than spotty attendance at P.S. 17.
There were Ivy League magna cum laudes who feared him as a
martinet, but there were many more of his copy boys who later gave
him a place of honor at their weddings and at parties celebrating
the birth of their children.
</P>
<P>
   Though he loved life's diversions, he was dedicated to his job
and energetically made sure that every bit of paper got where it
was supposed to go. When the electricity failed and the lights of
New York City went out on Nov. 9, 1965, Solovitz found a kerosene
lantern to help the staff put out its ``blackout edition.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 10, 1970, after the paper had closed for the night,
Solovitz, was lingering alone in the office when the bells on the
Teletype machines signaled a bulletin. Charles de Gaulle had died.
Realizing that the presses were still rolling, he raced across West
43rd Street to Gough's bar and led back a group of editors and copy
boys who were able to prepare a replate and get the news into some
copies of the paper.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Solovitz became the stuff of legend. A.J. Liebling, the
``Wayward Press'' critic for The New Yorker, called him ``a
newsroom institution.'' Sketches of him appeared in Editor &AMP;
Publisher and The Columbia Journalism Review. He lectured to
students at the Columbia School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   More informally, he would pass on the romance and lore of the
newspaper business to his charges, telling them what happened in
the newsroom on V-E Day or V-J Day, or the day that Franklin D.
Roosevelt died, or the nights that Robert F. Kennedy and the Rev.
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. were assassinated. Sometimes, he would
do it over late-night poker games, or sometimes, he would tell his
story walking, heading to Sam Wo's restaurant at 3 o'clock in the
morning or taking copy boys _ there were not yet any copy girls _
eager for authenticity to race tracks or to second-floor tearooms
on Allen Street, where men with pinkie rings played cards until
after dawn.
</P>
<P>
   After enjoying Solovitz's wit and intelligence, one senior
editor once tried to talk him into continuing his education. ``Why,
school never did any thing for Meyer Berger,'' he replied, evoking
the Pulitzer Prize-winning star reporter and columnist of The Times
who never earned a high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   When technological change came to the newsroom in the 1980s,
Solovitz took it hard. He had loved the Linotypes, the delivery
trucks being loaded outside the building, even the spittoons that
one or two die-hard editors kept by their desks. When computers
replaced typewriters, copy boys, and by then, copy girls, were no
longer as vital to the operation as they had been. Smoking was
increasingly frowned upon, not to mention spittoons.
</P>
<P>
   It was harder to find people to go to the track or to Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Mrs. Polunsky, his niece, persuaded him to retire and
move to Houston. Mrs. Polunsky and a nephew, Lewis Solovitz,
survive him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy had an apartment nearby,'' Mrs. Polunsky said. ``He
missed New York, but he had a life here. He would go to New Orleans
and Las Vegas. He kept active. Right up until the end, he smoked,
he drank, he gambled and he told people exactly what he thought.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
