<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON IS SAN JOSE STATE'S MIRACLE WORKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former Arizona assistant Phil Johnson was hired in
March to rebuild San Jose State. Less than a month later, the
Spartans were leftovers in the Western Athletic Conference breakup.
</P>
<P>
   It was horrendous timing, since Johnson planned to use WAC
competition and television exposure to lure recruits. But San Jose
State was in such disarray _ one of the nation's worst programs,
especially from a power conference _ that the breakup was the least
of Johnson's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were about 50 things ahead of that to worry about,''
Johnson said. ``I thought it was a monumental job when I took it,
and I still do. The biggest fight is changing the kids' attitude so
that when things go bad, they don't say to themselves, `Here we go
again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that and other problems, Johnson has delivered perhaps
the finest coaching performance on the West Coast this season _
turning San Jose State into a respectable, energized program. The
talent pool is comically shallow for a WAC team, but last week the
Spartans (9-7) defeated Fresno State and Texas-El Paso and took New
Mexico into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   With nine wins, they've already tripled last year's total.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was a head coach at Oklahoma's Seminole Junior College a
decade ago, and he later apprenticed under two of the best: Tim
Floyd (New Orleans, now the Chicago Bulls) and Lute Olson
(Arizona). He has taken morsels from each and added a personal
touch _ intensity _ to revitalize the Spartans, who are holding
opponents to 40 percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing very solid basketball,'' Olson said. ``They're
defending well. That's the big thing. They're working hard and
taking good shots. I don't know that they have a lot of offensive
firepower.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans' leading scorer is L.A. native Ben Sanders (13
points per game), and their roster accurately reflects the
program's makeshift existence. Guard R.J. Powell, a Pepperdine
castoff, asked Johnson if he could walk on because his mother
attends San Jose State. Top reserve Terrance Richmond commutes
daily from Oakland, the equivalent of living in Anaheim and
attending UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   One of Johnson's problems is the recruiting budget, which was
nonexistent. Every dollar he needs, he must raise himself. And he's
probably the only coach in the nation who doesn't have free use of
his own gym. The Spartans rent the 5,000-seat, multi-purpose Events
Center from the student body. The doors are locked unless Johnson
books time in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two recruits in from Florida, and at the time I had no
idea that we just rented the place,'' Johnson said. ``I took them
over to show them the arena, and we couldn't get in. Needless to
say, we didn't get the recruits.''
</P>
<P>
   Help will arrive next season, thanks to an eight-man recruiting
class that will dramatically improve San Jose State's talent base.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image of the program is terrible, especially in
California,'' Johnson said. ``The perception is a little better
out-of-state than in-state.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's improving by the week.
</P>
<P>
   Next generation: Monday's Dream Classic, a high school bonanza
at Pauley Pavilion, may have lacked the high-profile college
recruiters of recent years, but it had plenty of top Southern
California prep talent. Here's a look at the five best prospects,
with comments from former USC coach and current Fox analyst George
Raveling:
</P>
<P>
   1. Tyson Chandler , the 7-foot sophomore from Compton Dominguez
High who many think will skip college and enter the NBA. ``He has
unlimited potential. He's so fluid. He runs the floor well, and he
doesn't have a lot of highs and lows emotionally. I question
(skipping college), because he'll have to improve each year in
quantum leaps to be ready for the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   2. Casey Jacobsen , the Stanford-bound wing guard from Glendora
who scored 43 points Monday against Capistrano Valley. ``He's
tailor-made for the way Stanford plays. He understands how to use
screens and he's mentally tough. He has NBA range and excellent
size. He's definitely an impact freshman. He could help Stanford
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Travon Bryant , a junior forward from Long Beach Jordan.
``He's pregnant with possibilities. He has good size (6-7, 200
pounds) and his body looks like it would carry 230 or 240. He has
got to be a power forward at the high Division I level.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Andrew Zahn , a junior forward from Redondo Union. ``He's an
excellent rebounder, but he has a little tendency to get
frustrated. He's shown meaningful improvement year to year.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Tito Maddox , a senior guard from Compton who committed to
Arizona State in the fall but did not sign a letter-of-intent. ``He
doesn't need an offense to get his shot. He could be a go-to guy
wherever he goes. He can play either guard position, and he could
probably get away playing small forward, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddox has narrowed his choices to four schools (Connecticut,
Maryland, Michigan and UCLA) but hasn't received a qualifying SAT
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way UCLA plays, and I like Steve Lavin's
coaching,'' Maddox said. ``They're just starting to recruit me
hard. Everyone thinks Baron (Davis) is leaving (for the NBA).''
</P>
<P>
   Around the Pac-10: Washington's starting point guard, Dan
Dickau, is out for the season with a broken foot. Freshman Senque
Carey, who is more athletic but less consistent than Dickau, will
run the team. . . .
</P>
<P>
   You heard it here first: If he stays in school, Arizona freshman
Michael Wright will be the first player to lead the Pac-10 in
rebounding for four years. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The latest Ratings Percentage Index Report _ it approximates,
but does not duplicate, the NCAA Selection Committee's power
ratings _ has five Pac-10 teams in the top 30: Stanford (No. 2),
Arizona (14), UCLA (23), Oregon (26) and Washington (29). . . .
</P>
<P>
   Bad news for the Huskies, who opened the league season with
three losses: Only two teams in the 1990s have started 0-3 and made
the NCAA Tournament: USC ('91) and Washington State ('94). . . .
</P>
<P>
   And finally: Someone check coach Ernie Kent's blood pressure.
Three of Oregon's six conference games have gone into overtime; two
others (USC, UCLA) were decided by three points. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
