<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TEAM GIVES FORCEFUL DEFENSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's legal team delivered a forceful
rebuttal of the impeachment charges against him Wednesday,
meticulously challenging the facts presented by House prosecutors
as little more than nitpicking over semantics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to take the charges seriously when in each case
they boil down to arguments over semantics,'' said White House
special counsel Greg Craig.
</P>
<P>
   Using videotaped testimony of the president and legal opinions
from top federal prosecutors to bolster his argument, Craig spent
nearly three hours trying to convince the Senate that Clinton never
intentionally lied about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky,
although he may have walked ``up to the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Labeling the House Republicans' descriptions of the president's
grand jury testimony as ``absolutely false,'' Craig said a reading
of Clinton's statements would show that he did not try to conceal
the affair but admitted to carrying on an ``inappropriate,
intimate, wrongful relationship with Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When he made that admission, there was no doubt in anyone's
mind what he meant,'' Craig said, taking issue with the
prosecution's contention that Clinton misrepresented the scope of
his entanglement with the young woman that began when she was a
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   He said House prosecutors were intent on criminalizing what
amounted to ``utterly meaningless'' conflicts in testimony,
including the president's and Lewinsky's different recollections of
when their affair began.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors insist that Clinton was trying to hide the fact that
Lewinsky was still a White House intern by testifying that their
relationship started in 1996 when she was a full-time federal
employee. Lewinsky, on the other hand, testified that their sexual
contact began in 1995 before she was given a staff job at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most likely explanation here is that there is just a
disagreement. There is simply no way that a reasonable person can
look at this testimony and conclude or agree with the (prosecutors)
that it is a ... direct lie,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every element of the crime of perjury must be proven, and if
it's going to be used as a criminal standard here, it must be
proven beyond a reasonable doubt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you convict and remove President Clinton on the basis of
these allegations, no president of the United States will ever be
safe from impeachment again. And it will happen, and people will
look back at us and they will say, `We should have stopped it then,
before it was too late,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-line presentation by Craig came on the second day of
White House defense arguments in the Senate impeachment trial,
which grew out of charges that Clinton tried to hide his affair
with Lewinsky. If convicted on either of the House articles of
impeachment alleging perjury and obstruction of justice, Clinton
would become the first president to be removed from office by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The senators also heard from White House deputy counsel Cheryl
Mills, who spent nearly 90 minutes picking apart the Republican
allegation that Clinton obstructed justice with a ``scheme'' to
influence the testimony of witnesses in the now settled Paula Jones
sexual harassment lawsuit and the investigation of the Lewinsky
matter by independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big picture is this: The president had a relationship with
a young woman. It was inappropriate, but not obstruction of
justice,'' Mills told the 100 senators, who are sitting as both
jurors and judges in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Mills also raised eyebrows among some senators by using her
presentation to charge the 13-member House Republican prosecution
team with misconduct in the trial. Mentioning some of them by name,
she said they had ``dramatically shortchanged the truth'' when they
accused Clinton of pressuring his secretary, Betty Currie, into
retrieving gifts he had given Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, citing Currie's own testimony, said the secretary was
never instructed to retrieve the gifts, but simply agreed to hold
them for Lewinsky because she was ``a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   In one lighter reference to the charges against her boss, the
White House lawyer drew smiles from both sides of the aisle when
she disputed a contention made by Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., one of the
House prosecutors, that the facts of the case against Clinton fit
together like ``a finely tuned ... Swiss watch.'' In her view,
Mills said, ``they might not even make a good sausage.''
</P>
<P>
   Her performance was later singled out by Democrats and
Republicans as the most impressive at the trial. ``She put it in
laymen's terms, terms that I could understand,'' said Sen. Robert
Bennett, R-Utah, who called Mills' defense presentation ``very
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Craig, Mills addressed the House allegations point by
point, putting a different spin on the facts and evidence presented
by the prosecution team as she sought to prove that there was no
legal basis for the charges against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``His conduct is not criminal. That's the rule of law in this
case. We ask only that the rule of law be applied equally, not
emotionally or politically,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   The aggressive presentation by the two lawyers incensed House
prosecutors, who released statement after statement rebutting every
single point that Craig and Mills made.
</P>
<P>
   They called it ``a mirage'' defense, designed to mislead and
confuse senators about what really happened. They also labeled the
charge of prosecutorial misconduct from the Clinton team as ``an
insult to the House of Representatives,'' which approved the two
articles of impeachment last month on a vote that broke down mostly
along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers began their defense of the president on
Tuesday with an opening presentation by White House counsel Charles
Ruff, who described the Republican charges as a ``witches brew'' of
circumstantial evidence. They will wrap up their defense
presentation today with summations beginning at noon Houston time
from former Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., and Clinton's private
attorney David Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   Although the impeachment trial is now in its second week, the
prosecution's case has apparently had little impact on the public's
view of Clinton. Polls released Wednesday indicated that Clinton's
job approval rating had climbed to an all-time high of 76 percent
following his State of the Union address Tuesday night. Most of
those surveyed said they support his proposals on Social Security
and other issues and oppose any attempt to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's performance in his speech, the arguments presented by
his defense team and the polls were almost too much for one
prominent Republican. The Associated Press reported that Christian
broadcaster and former presidential candidate Pat Robertson told
viewers of his ``700 Club'' show Wednesday that Clinton had ``hit a
home run'' with his speech and had probably killed any chance of
his being ousted.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a public relations standpoint, he's won,'' said
Robertson, one of Clinton's biggest critics. ``They might as well
dismiss this impeachment hearing and get on with something else,
because it's over as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic supporters of the president said they are hopeful
that the defense presentation will help convince Republicans not to
allow House prosecutors to seek further testimony from Lewinsky and
other witnesses in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Mills and Craig arguments, Sen. John Breaux,
D-La., said members should be able to ``easily conclude that there
is sufficient evidence on the record'' to help them ``reach an
accurate and fair decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment rules require that a two-thirds majority of senators
vote for conviction in order for a president to be removed from
office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
