<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TRIES TO DEAL WITH DEPLETED BASKETBALL ROSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was love at first sight _ Chris McColpin and the Erwin
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the 10th grade when my dad and I went to the state
basketball tournament,'' McColpin recalled. ``I saw those kids out
there on the floor and I knew I wanted to play out there one day
myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we never got to the state tournament in high school, I
knew the only way I'd ever get to do that was to play for the
University of Texas. And it didn't look like that was ever going to
happen _ not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny how things transpire.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the former all-district player at Carrollton Turner High
School who was never offered an NCAA Division I scholarship, is
averaging 10 minutes a game as a sophomore walk-on point guard for
the University of Texas _ one of the key role players on Rick
Barnes' seemingly ever-shrinking roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad to have him,'' Barnes said. ``Chris is a true point
guard who thinks like a coach on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   These days Barnes is glad to have just about anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The midweek, one-game suspension of junior forward Gabe Muoneke
for unsportsmanlike conduct in Monday's loss at Kansas, coupled
with the loss of backup inside player Marlon Drakes to a broken
foot leaves the Longhorns (9-9, 5-1 Big 12) with McColpin and six
scholarship players to face No. 23 Oklahoma State (12-4, 4-1) on
Saturday (8:30 p.m.) at the Erwin Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows it's going to be tough for us and we're all
going to have to dig down deep and get this done,'' forward Kris
Clack said. ``We may lose if we don't step it up. It's just
something we have to get through.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke's absence will impact Barnes' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that Chico \RVazquez\S will have to play inside and
now Kris Clack becomes our fourth post player,'' Barnes said.
``We'll just deal with it. That's all we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   That, in essence, has been Barnes' outlook all season. No
excuses, no whining. Cut and paste. Mix and match. Most nights, it
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I have a great appreciation for the way \RBarnes\S
is coaching this team,'' said Vazquez, a utility player who at
times this season has worn the shoes of every position. ``He's
overcome a lot with this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the coaching staff has done is see to it that every day,
every practice, every second, you play your role and nothing else.
Coach Barnes tells you where your shots are coming from, who's
going to get the shots and what to look for if the other team does
this or that. And when you get outside of your role, it shows. That
philosophy has helped us out a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes will use 6-foot-9 senior Wendell Carter in Muoneke's
power-forward slot against the Cowboys. That leaves McColpin and
William Clay in their usual roles as respective backups at the
point and shooting guard, where Vazquez starts. Carter can play
both inside spots and either Vazquez or Clack can play power
forward. Barnes also can use Vazquez as a pseudo-center offensively
and use him to draw an opposition post player to the perimeter to
guard him.
</P>
<P>
   But a turned ankle here, early foul trouble there and things
quickly get more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   If Barnes' first season at Texas is sometimes frustrating
because of the lack of numbers, he said it is at the least
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the more unpredictable years I've had in
coaching,'' he said. ``We can talk about different scenarios _ if
this guy gets hurt or this guy gets two fouls in the first minute _
but one thing I found out about the job a long time ago is it's not
scientific. The way you have to do it is take what you've got, play
the way you have to and don't make excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter has been one of Barnes' pleasant surprises. He logged
only insignificant minutes last season, but has become a
contributor under Barnes. He is, however, under no illusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a garbage man,'' Carter said. ``I go for loose balls,
rebounds, blocks, steals _ whatever it takes, you know? I have a
nice little jump hook when we need it, but my strengths are
rebounding and running the floor and my quickness. I just try to do
as much as I can to help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   All Barnes asks is all you've got.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach has this four-minute game he talks to us about,'' Carter
said. ``You go as hard as you can for four minutes and he'll take
you out and see you get your rest, get refreshed and go out and do
it again. It's working pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   All parts considered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
