</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE PRESIDENT'S SIDE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Jan. 21:
</P>
<P>
   In two days of vigorous rebuttal before the Senate, the White
House defense team put some significant dents in the House
prosecutors' case for removing President Clinton. Though Gregory
Craig and Cheryl Mills could not disentangle Clinton Wednesday from
his misconduct and false statements, they did raise technical and
substantive doubts about the perjury and obstruction accusations
leveled by the House. They argued that the House prosecutors had
brought in extraneous charges that went beyond the articles of
impeachment and the independent counsel's charges. Craig pounded at
the central issue of the case _ that Clinton's actions, while
reckless and reprehensible, do not meet the constitutional test for
canceling the verdict of the voters who elected him.
</P>
<P>
   Even before former Sen. Dale Bumpers begins his summation, the
Senate arithmetic seems clear. The 67 votes needed to convict and
remove Clinton from the White House are not in sight. Hearing
witnesses will not make the evidence appreciably stronger, and it
will extend the trial for weeks and throw the Senate into partisan
strife. Therefore Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, should be
looking for an endgame.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the State of the Union address should underscore
the point for him, even if Clinton's polls drift down a bit from
their current spike. Clinton reads the American mainstream better
than anyone now on the public stage, and knows how to assemble a
domestic program that trumps much of the Republican agenda.
Removing a popular president is unworkable in the absence of a
compelling constitutional case. Lott and many Republicans in the
Senate know that. Sealing their image as the party of impeachment
could cost Republicans heavily in the 2000 presidential and
congressional elections, risking their control of the House and
possibly even the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   So if Lott is to complete the wise and skillful leadership work
he began last week, he must find a way out among moderate
Republicans and Democrats, even if Republican hotspurs object. It
could come next week in a simple majority vote to dismiss the case
or to suspend the trial. It could be defeat of a motion to summon
witnesses. The end might even be a definitive vote on the two
articles of impeachment. The Senate can then move immediately to
censure Clinton, the sanction he deserves and the country supports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
