<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-SOCIALSECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN BLASTS PLAN BY CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan on
Wednesday assailed President Clinton's plan to funnel a portion of
the nation's Social Security fund into the stock market, arguing
such investments could be held hostage to politics.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's central banker also raised fresh concerns about the
gravity-defying stock prices, warning investors not to expect the
Fed to bail out the market.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan told members of the House Ways and Means Committee
that he cannot support the Clinton administration's plan to invest
up to $700 billion from Social Security reserves over the next 15
years in stocks and bonds as a way to boost returns for taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is part of a broader strategy outlined by the
president in his State of the Union address to use an estimated
$2.7 trillion worth of budget surpluses to bolster the Social
Security system in time to handle an aging baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said he fears political priorities might dictate
investment decisions, and he worries that a future administration,
caught in a financial crunch, might try to divert the money for
other uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe it is politically feasible to insulate such
huge funds from governmental direction,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of state and local pension funds already invest in the
stock markets, and Greenspan noted that their rates of return
typically are two to three percentage points lower than private
pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are also studies which suggest that the greater the
proportion of trustees who are political appointees on those
pension funds, the lower the rate of return,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic committee member Bob Matsui of California pointed
out that while state and local pension funds may have lower rates
of return than the private sector, they still outperform the
current Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Wednesday that they share Greenspan's
concerns about political influence on the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's plan calls for the creation of an
independent board that would contract with private pension managers
to handle the investments, similar to the way the federal
government's 401(k)-style retirement plan is now handled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aiming to put this in the hands of private-sector
managers who are free from political interference,'' said Jake
Siewert, a spokesman for the White House's National Economic
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's opposition is a tremendous political blow for the
proposal. Lawmakers, who largely credit Greenspan for the longest
economic expansion in peacetime history, speak of Greenspan in
almost reverential tones, although they don't always follow his
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw cold water on the president's Social Security idea,''
said Bob Brusca, chief economist for Nikko Securities in New York.
``He made it very, very clear having the government invest in the
stock market is a bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee, contends that the Clinton proposal is fraught with
potential abuse, from political favoritism to government attempts
to dictate policy in companies in which it invests. Instead,
Republicans favor proposals that would allow taxpayers to invest
some of their Social Security funds themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ferrara, a policy analyst for the libertarian-leaning Cato
Institute, said the proposal would grant ``broad new powers over
the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan did applaud the administration's efforts to try to
deal with the Social Security problem, which according to
administration projections is slated to run out of cash in 2032.
``We cannot go on the way we are,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's opposition to Clinton's Social Security plan was in
keeping with the Fed chairman's general wariness of the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Greenspan spooked the markets when he referred to
investors' ``irrational exuberance.'' At that time, the Dow Jones
industrial average was below 6,500. On Wednesday, the Dow closed at
9,335.91, down 19.31 points.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan refrained from employing such colorful verbiage
Wednesday, but he did suggest current stock values may be out of
sync with actual corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of equity prices would appear to envision
substantially greater growth of profits than has been experienced
of late,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also warned investors that the Federal Reserve's moves
to lower interest rates last year were not done in an effort to
bail out the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not attempting to prop up equity prices, nor did we
plan to continue to ease rates until equity prices recovered, as
some have erroneously inferred,'' Greenspan said. ``This has not
been, and is not now, our policy or intent.''
</P>
<P>
   Brusca said Greenspan had been ``getting criticized in Europe
for having cut interest rates to help goose the stock market. I
think he just wanted to make it really clear ... the Fed was really
aiming at something else,'' to help cushion the blow of the world
economic crisis on the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2328EST &QL; 
