<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RUSSIA-NUCLEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REDUCING RUSSIAN DANGERS  
 
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Jan. 21:
</P>
<P>
   No investment in American national security has paid higher
dividends than the $2 billion Washington has spent over the last
eight years to help Russia and other former Soviet republics
dismantle nuclear, biological and chemical weapons. President
Clinton was right, in his State of the Union address Tuesday night,
to call for significantly increased spending on such programs.
Congress, including members who oppose other foreign aid to Russia,
should approve this White House request in full.
</P>
<P>
   There is no longer any threat of Russia's deliberately attacking
the United States. But Moscow's still-formidable stocks of nuclear
bombs, nuclear ingredients and biological and chemical warfare
agents pose a different kind of danger. Much of this material is
inadequately secured, and the workers guarding it are paid poorly
or not at all. That creates an unacceptably high risk that some
material could be sold to potential aggressors like Iraq, Libya,
North Korea or Serbia. Many Russian weapons scientists are also
unemployed or unpaid and vulnerable to foreign recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the $4.5 billion the administration is requesting for
the next five years would be used to speed the safe disposal of
bomb plutonium and chemical and biological weapons stocks, and
further improve security at storage sites. Washington would add new
defenses against smuggling by helping Russia to establish better
border controls and export monitoring. There would also be an
expansion of efforts to re-employ scientists in civilian work.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, the United States spent trillions of
dollars to deter Russia from using its nuclear, biological and
chemical weapons. It would not take much more than $10 billion to
eliminate most of the risks from those weapons today. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-99 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990120.0572 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-20 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2107 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PAN-AMERICAN-TEX     01-20 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PAN-AMERICAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELRAY BROOKS BUILDING BASE AT ISOLATED UT-PAN AM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURG, Texas _ Welcome to college basketball's loneliest,
most-secluded outpost. This is the sport's Fort Apache, its Foreign
Legion, its Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   This is the home of UT-Pan American, one of 310 Division I
basketball programs chasing that dream of NCAA Tournament
participation and glory. Know this: The Broncs have never
participated in the NCAA Tournament and, at 3-15, that's not going
to change this season.
</P>
<P>
   Where does UT-Pan American rate on the Hoops Scale? ``The worst
job in college basketball. I don't think there's another coach in
the country who would disagree with me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Delray Brooks, 33, the Broncs' second-year coach who
has a glittering pedigree. Brooks is a former Mr. Basketball from
Indiana who played two years for the Hoosiers, transferred to
Providence and played in the 1987 Final Four. As an assistant with
Rick Pitino at Kentucky, he was a part of three Final Four teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said, pointing to the picture of the 1996 national
championship Kentucky team hanging on the wall in his office, ``is
about as far away from here as you could get.''
</P>
<P>
   UT-Pan American isn't Kentucky or North Carolina, but it has a
fair amount of basketball tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, the Broncs, led by future Olympian and NBA player Luke
Jackson, won the NAIA national championship. The next year, they
finished second. Abe Lemons and Lon Krueger coached here before
moving on to Texas and Kansas State, respectively. Marshall Rodgers
in 1976 and Greg Guy in 1993 led the nation in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a serious resurrection under way,'' said
federal judge Richard Jinjosa, who has been a fan for 20 years.
``This program has had some great coaches and teams, but because of
Brooks, for the first time in a long time, this program has a
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent history has been bleak. There have been two stays in
the NCAA's jailhouse (one year of probation in 1990, three years
starting in 1992). Other than a 16-12 record in 1993-94, the Broncs
have struggled. Since the 1990-91 season, UT-Pan Am is 57-161 _ a
winning percentage of .261.
</P>
<P>
   After seven seasons as a member of the Sun Belt Conference, the
Broncs were asked to leave after last season, making UT-Pan Am one
of three Division I independents. Independents have little chance
of making the NCAA Tournament _ the last to do so was DePaul in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the budget to salaries to scheduling to not being in a
conference, that's why this job was so bad,'' Brooks said. ``A lot
of the things to run a program, they're just not here. We're
struggling to put those in place. It's not an impossible task, but
it makes it more challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' program operates on a shoestring. The basketball budget
is approximately $450,000 (Texas first-year coach Rick Barnes earns
approximately $700,000 a season). Brooks earned $35,000 more as a
Kentucky assistant than he did in his first season at UT-Pan Am.
</P>
<P>
   This season, with no conference games, Brooks played a ``money''
schedule. Trips to Providence, New Mexico, Pittsburgh and DePaul
brought in $350,000 in game guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   UT-Pan Am has only nine home games scheduled. That sort of
scheduling contributes to an impending NCAA record. The Broncs have
lost 54 consecutive road games; the NCAA record is 55. Their next
game is Saturday at Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   As an assistant at Kentucky, Brooks worked with Tubby Smith,
Ralph Willard, Herb Sendek and Billy Donovan, his Providence
teammate. After making coaching debuts at other schools, all have
moved on to bigger jobs: Smith is the coach at Kentucky; Willard is
at Pittsburgh; Sendek is at North Carolina State; and Donovan is at
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Pitino would tell me the jobs I was applying for weren't
bad enough,'' said Brooks, who was 3-24 last season in his debut.
``The reason I'm here is that I wanted to be a head coach. Why
here? I wanted to be a coach and this is the school that hired
me.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the University of Texas system, Pan American knows
that NCAA indiscretions and embarrassing won-loss records will not
be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some big steps we need to take, but we're taking
them,'' said UT-Pan Am athletic director Bill Weidner, who was an
assistant athletic director at SMU for seven years. ``We think
we've got a state-of-the-art compliance program. We're committed to
being successful without taking shortcuts. We've done a lot of work
trying to rebuild trust in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Broncs' record is 3-15, there is improvement.
Last season, the Broncs allowed 100 points six times and lost 12
games by 20 or more points. This season, UT-Pan Am has allowed 100
points three times and has lost by 20 or more once.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never heard of UT-Pan American, but I came here because
of coach Brooks,'' said guard Brian Meriweather, who leads the
nation in scoring at 25.9 points per game. ``We have the talent and
the coaching to get it done here. We can compete and be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks plans to bring in some junior-college transfers next
season to bolster this year's recruiting class, which was ranked in
the top 50 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I was crazy to take this job and they think I'm
crazy when I say we can be successful,'' Brooks said. ``With the
parity in college basketball, we can compete. We're going to bring
in some players next season who are going to be bigger, faster,
stronger. They'll make us better and we're going to start making
some serious noise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
