<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: THE 2002 OLYMPICS AND GLOBAL PROVINCIALISM
</HEADLINE>
   (See also OLY-SCANDAL, OLY-SCANDAL-INVESTIGATE) 
 
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG  
(DW) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Jan. 21:
</P>
<P>
   Every small-town kid knows, or used to know, how a town can
change when the carnival sets up its rides and its plush-toy,
deep-fried midway at the fairgrounds. What's so exciting isn't just
the chance to get dizzy on the Tilt-a-Whirl or to spend money in a
way you'll soon regret. It's the presence in your midst of a closed
society of strangers conforming to a way of life _ no matter how
ordinary it may be at heart _ that makes your own look dull.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, the carnival will leave, but until it does your
town looks larger and smaller all at once. Larger for the noise and
the cotton candy and the unfamiliar glow among the trees at night,
but smaller because the carnival will drive off into the enormous
world it came from while you lie asleep in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City isn't a small town and the International Olympic
Committee isn't a carnival, but you can see the parallels. The IOC
is a closed society with its own opaque way of doing business _ a
family, its president, Juan Antonio Samaranch, calls it, though he
has also said, ``We function as a state.''
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake was eager to capture the 2002 Winter Olympics _ any
city would be _ and it was also eager to prove something about
itself by doing so, to ease the suspicion, which the Olympic
possibility only heightened, that it was not quite front and center
on the world stage. So Salt Lake played along with the practices
the IOC brought to town.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has its own problems. Some are outlined in a draft
report by Richard Pound, the member appointed to investigate the
present mess, and many more will emerge. But what is interesting is
the psychology of Salt Lake itself. Salt Lake is already a global
city. It has enjoyed the kind of high-tech-industrial explosion
that has transformed other cities in the West. The Mormon Church is
as cosmopolitan, if not as urbane, an institution as the IOC
itself, and vastly more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, like every city in this country at one time or another,
Salt Lake's boosters have clamored for something they feel it
lacks, something that the money and the crowds the Olympics will
bring can only partially satisfy. That something is attention _ the
satisfaction of seeing your town enlarged, redefined, because it
has been broadcast to the world.
</P>
<P>
   What this suggests, I think, is a rather different meaning for
Marshall McLuhan's old metaphor of the global village. In its
original sense, the phrase forecast the way the new electronic
media would bind the world into a single place. The point was not
only the coherence of this new world but also the absence of a
center. But as we've begun to discover, wherever the media focus
their powerful glare is the center, and everywhere else is the
provinces. The global village is now a place of unalleviated
provincialism, except when the media _ a carnival of their own kind
_ come to town on an Olympic scale.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Salt Lake clamored for the Olympics, though so far the
city has only garnered an attention its boosters could never have
wanted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
