<HEADLINE>
UCONN-DUKE COLLISION COURSE IFFY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Midway through the season, the game we'd like to see is the game
we likely won't see until the Final Four: No. 1 Connecticut vs. No.
2 Duke. Both teams have played difficult nonconference schedules,
but they aren't scheduled to play each other this season.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Connecticut and Duke have distanced themselves as the
nation's top two teams. Assuming each is a top seed in its
respective regions (Connecticut in the East, Duke in the South),
this year's bracket wouldn't have those two regional champions
meeting until the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   While each team has the ability to win the national title, the
odds of both reaching the Final Four, much less meeting in the
title game, are slim. The NCAA Tournament doesn't work that way.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's only loss came to Cincinnati. The Blue Devils were 17-1
going into last night's game with Clemson. The Huskies were 15-0
going into last night's game with Miami (Fla.)
</P>
<P>
   Both teams could stumble along the way. Connecticut plays at
Stanford on Feb. 6. Duke has two games remaining with North
Carolina, one with Maryland and a nonconference matchup with St.
John's.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Connecticut and Duke occupy the top two spots in the
poll and continue their dominating play, the debate will continue:
Who's better?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's better,'' said forward Harold Swanagan,
whose Notre Dame team has lost to both. ``They're pretty close. The
big-man edge would probably go to Duke with Elton Brand in the
middle. But UConn's guards are certainly some of the best in the
nation. You've got to give them credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech coach Bobby Cremins sounds as though he's ready to
concede the national championship to the Blue Devils and coach Mike
Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to take an injury or someone playing a
perfect game,'' Cremins said of a team beating Duke. ``I can't get
over what Mike has done. Mike has gone off the charts this year. I
thought last year he had a great team. This year, he's gone off the
chart.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams have three common opponents. Connecticut beat
Fairfield, 102-67; Michigan State, 82-68; and Notre Dame, 101-70.
Duke beat Fairfield, 98-66; Michigan State, 73-67; and Notre Dame,
111-82.
</P>
<P>
   In this week's NCAA statistics, Duke is No. 1 in scoring,
Connecticut is No. 7. In scoring margin, Duke is No. 1, Connecticut
No. 2.  &LR; tagtop:Wendell Barnhouse, (817) 390-7238
 &LR; tagbottom:wbhoops\Nstar-telegram.com
FREE THROWS Stanford's standard Injuries have reduced Stanford's
superior depth. And losses to North Carolina and Maryland knocked
the Cardinal off the radar screen of this season's dominating
teams.
</P>
<P>
   But since the Maryland loss on Dec. 6, Stanford (15-2) has won
11 consecutive games and again is displaying the form that put them
in the Final Four last March.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Stanford swept UCLA and Southern California in Los
Angeles. That's the second consecutive year the team has done that.
Before last season, the last time Stanford had won both games in LA
had been 1941-42.
</P>
<P>
   And Pacific-10 Conference coaches are talking about the
Cardinal's becoming the first team to go through the league 18-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just trying to put pressure on us to see if we can't
handle it,'' Stanford coach Mike Montgomery said. ``We have no
designs on 18-0, it's not what we're thinking about.'' Mass appeal
Massashusetts was 6-8 going into Saturday's game with Kansas. The
Minutemen had been a preseason Top 25 team, but their season had
been defined by inconsistency and indifferent effort.
</P>
<P>
   So, with chances of postseason play slipping away, Massachusetts
upset the Jayhawks, 64-60. It was the school's first victory
against Kansas in four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, it's not like our season is over,'' Massachusetts
coach Bruiser Flint told his team before the game. ``We can turn
this thing around. People have thrown dirt on us before.''
</P>
<P>
   Flint said that after Kansas' Jeff Boschee hit two 3-pointers to
tie the game, he was afraid his team would fold because that's how
it had played previously. But guard Charlton Clarke sealed the
victory with two free throws with eight seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I wanted to be,'' Clarke said. ``I wanted to be
there at the end, to seal the game. These are the type of games we
live for. What we've got to try to do now is apply the same
intensity to the rest of the games we have to play this year.''
Quotebook Northwestern coach Kevin O'Neill on his team's defense:
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams we play usually say, `We just didn't shoot well.' After
a while you might decide we do something right. We watch a lot of
videotape. We guard the guys who can shoot, and we don't guard the
guys who can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's C.J. Black after the Volunteers' 47-46 victory at
Kentucky, the first win for Tennessee in Lexington since 1979:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play in front of 25,000 people and can make them all
hush, that's the greatest feeling you can have.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Earl Watson after Stanford defeated the Bruins, 72-59, in
a game featuring 49 Stanford free throws:
</P>
<P>
   ``They kicked our butts up and down the court. They came out and
exposed us tonight. There's nothing more to say. They killed us.
Exposed us. Beat us. Whatever you want to say.''
THE BUZZ Briefly All three of Florida's losses have come in road
games against ranked teams _ Duke, Kentucky and Auburn. The average
margin for defeat in those three games has been 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   When No. 10 North Carolina plays Virginia tonight, it will be
the Tar Heels' 300th consecutive game ranked in The Associated
Press Top 25. That's not the longest streak in the Atlantic Coast
Conference. From 1973 to 1983, North Carolina was ranked in 319
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   When the Wooden Award is presented April 2 in Los Angeles, there
will be an inaugural ``Legends of Coaching'' lifetime achievement
award presented. Former North Carolina coach Dean Smith will be the
first recipient. That handshake between Smith and John Wooden will
be a special photo opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Jaeson Maravich, son of late Louisiana State star Pete Maravich,
is a walk-on at Alabama. When the Crimson Tide played at the Pete
Maravich Assembly Center in Baton Rouge, La., last week, Jaeson
received a standing ovation when he was introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Entering last night's game against Wofford, freshman Adam
Harrington was averaging 13.7 points per game to lead North
Carolina State. The school has never had a freshman lead the team
in scoring.
Midseason numbers The NCAA released its Division I men's basketball
midseason trends yesterday. Compared to last year's midseason
numbers, scoring is down nearly a point a game and shooting
accuracy has declined. However, no trend is apparent because
scoring was up for the 1997-98 season compared to scoring for the
1996-97 season. A look at this year's midseason statistical trends
(statistics are per-game, per-team averages): Category 1999 1998
Field goals made 25.0 25.4 FG attempts 57.3 57.9 FG pct. 43.7 43.9
3-point FG made 5.9 5.9 3-point FG attempts 17.2 17.3 3-point FG
pct. 34.2 34.3 Free throws made 14.5 14.7 Free throws attempts 21.7
22.0 Free throw pct. 67.1 66.7 Points 70.5 71.4
</P>
</TEXT>
