<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ROBERTSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAT ROBERTSON SUGGESTS CLINTON TRIAL BE HALTED 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Utah)  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-TRIAL, EDIT-IMPEACH, IMPEACH-BUSH,
IMPEACH-SCENE) 
 (bl) 
By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pat Robertson, the conservative television
evangelist who has been an important leader in pressing for the
impeachment and ouster of President Clinton, said Wednesday that
the president had ``hit a home run'' in his State of the Union
address and that the impeachment trial might as well be halted.
</P>
<P>
   While Robertson's remarks were the most dramatic, he was only
one of many prominent Republicans around the country who said
Clinton's speech Tuesday was an unsettling reminder that their
party cannot compete with the president's political skills _ and
that the impeachment trial can only endanger their prospects in
competitive states.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a public-relations standpoint, he's won,'' Robertson said
on his television program, ``The 700 Club.'' ``They might as well
dismiss this impeachment hearing and get on with something else,
because it's over as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments by Robertson, who is the founder and chairman of
the Christian Coalition and was a candidate for president in 1988,
marked a stunning reversal because he had for months urged the
ouster of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's remarks carry great weight because he is one of the
most popular and influential Christian conservatives; many leading
Republicans, including presidential candidates, take their cues
from him.
</P>
<P>
   And his comments could also provide cover for Republicans who
have felt pressure to move forward for impeachment so as not to
alienate their conservative supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Robertson's remarks brought a stern reaction from one of the
House prosecutors in the impeachment trial. ``It's discouraging,
because he's missing the point,'' said Rep. Christopher Cannon,
R-Utah. ``This is not a PR war _ this is a matter of law.''
</P>
<P>
   And Robertson sought Wednesday night to back down from his
remarks. Speaking through a spokesman, he said: ``I was speaking in
my capacity as a political analyst. I was not advocating this, nor
do I favor this. But it was my view that this is how things are
likely to play out.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's comments were a striking contrast to what he said at
the Christian Coalition's annual meeting last September, when
congressional Republican leaders were hesitant to attack Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson thundered that the president should not resign, but
should be impeached so he could be punished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
