<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SOCIAL PROMOTION BILL HAS ESCAPE HATCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush is scheduled to unveil
legislation Monday aimed at ending social promotion _ one of his
key campaign promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sets a standard,'' said Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, and
one of the chief architects of the bill. ``It says we should not be
promoting students from one grade level to the next if they clearly
demonstrate they're not able to do the work.''
</P>
<P>
   But contrary to the governor's adamant pronouncement last year
that there would be no way a student could advance to a higher
grade without passing the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills, the
bill as Bivins outlines it would establish an appeals process that
gives discretion to schools to promote students who repeatedly fail
the test. The bill also contains measures designed to prevent abuse
of the appellate process.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing here is setting the bright line, setting the
standard but then allowing an appeals process, in the event of
extenuating circumstances, that is driven by local
decision-makers,'' Bivins said. ``I don't see this as a major
departure from this goal of ending social promotion. I think it's
more of what's practical, what's going to work out there in the
real world.''
</P>
<P>
   If the bill is approved, though, Bivins and Bush spokeswoman
Karen Hughes said Houston school officials, who have tough new
promotion standards for grades 1 through 8 ready to take effect at
the end of this school year, would have to alter their policies for
third, fifth and eighth grades.
</P>
<P>
   That's because in addition to TAAS scores, the Houston
Independent School District will factor in course grades and
performance on the Stanford Achievement in deciding whether to hold
back students.
</P>
<P>
   HISD would be allowed to implement its promotion policies in
other grades, but not in the three covered by state law, Bivins and
Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only say that our board and superintendent have taken a
strong stand that we want to have multiple criteria and not use
TAAS as the sole determining factor,'' said HISD spokesman Terry
Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our leadership will be discussing that with legislators,''
Abbott said, adding that HISD would favor a law that would allow it
and other districts that have already implemented strong promotion
policies to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins, who also chairs the Senate Education Committee, said Lt.
Gov. Rick Perry has designated the legislative proposal as Senate
Bill 1, a symbolic acknowledgment of its importance. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Under the proposal, students in three grades would face
retention based on failing test scores, Bivins said. Third-graders
would have to pass the TAAS reading test to move ahead to the
fourth grade, fifth-graders would be required to pass reading and
math, and eighth-graders would face exams in reading, writing and
math.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said his bill also would require TAAS tests to be
administered three times in those grade levels, first in early
spring. Students who fail the test would be required to attend
intensive remedial instruction classes either during regular school
hours or in extended-day programs, he added.
</P>
<P>
   TAAS tests would be administered a second time near the end of
the school year, and those who failed again would face mandatory
summer school. The state would pick up the tab for remedial
instruction, Bivins added.
</P>
<P>
   TAAS tests would be administered a third time, at the end of
summer school. If they didn't pass then, students could still
appeal decisions to hold them back.
</P>
<P>
   Local school campuses would establish appeal committees
consisting of the retained students' parents, teacher and principal
to determine whether there were extenuating circumstances that
warranted moving the child ahead despite three TAAS failures,
Bivins said.
</P>
<P>
   He said said he decided an appeals process was necessary after
talking with Waco school officials about the appeals process they
established as part of the aggressive promotion policy they
implemented last school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was influenced by the reality that there were going to be a
host of horrible hypotheticals out there,'' Bivins said. ``What's
the best way to deal with what will certainly arise (with)
extenuating circumstances?''
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said the bill would not specify the extenuating
circumstances a school could weigh when deciding whether to promote
a student. He added, though, that committees might advance a child
whose test scores improve with each test administration or one who
just moved to Texas from another state.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the appeals process will leave Bush with little more
than the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Although social promotion is illegal under current law, many
education officials now acknowledge that it has been going on for
years. A 1996 survey by the Texas Federation of Teachers determined
that 150,000 students each year are promoted without passing their
courses.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins, however, said his bill would create a safeguard to
prevent blanket promotions of failing students by making the
appeals process part of the school accountability system. Schools
would be required to report the number of students they advance
based on the appeals committee decisions. The Texas Education
Agency would then factor those numbers into its campus and district
ratings, he added. Schools that promote too many students despite
failing TAAS scores could face lower ratings.
</P>
<P>
   It's that appeals process that is the clearest departure from
what Bush outlined during his re-election campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing his plan to end the practice of social promotion,
Bush said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The message to our schools is this: Do what it takes to teach
our children to read. The voices of the status quo will say too
much is riding on one test. And I say stop the excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no flexibility. Beginning in the year 2003, we are
shutting down social promotion, and we have given school districts
ample warning.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
