<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE BASEBALL HAS 19 NEW FACES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's a regular occurrence around the Cal State
Northridge baseball team. The season begins in January _ Friday at
home against San Francisco, to be exact _ yet coach Mike Batesole
won't have a starting eight set for about 25 games, which means
March 11 against Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Batesole is going to need the time because the Matadors have 19
new players in the program, including six freshmen. This follows
last year's surprise 37-19 finish in which the team won 25 of its
last 27 games with mostly junior college and Division I transfers.
That came about because the program had been cut then reinstated
and few saw it through. Batesole was named Collegiate Baseball
magazine's national coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Since CSUN is playing as an independent again, it will require
an at-large berth into the NCAA playoffs. Last year, 37 wins
against what many thought to be a weak schedule wasn't enough. This
year, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Batesole said it depends on what other teams do as well as
against who and where the Matadors win. Road victories help, and
CSUN will have plenty of chances late in the season to do that,
with 23 of its last 33 games away from Matador Field. The team
begins with 15 of 20 at home.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors have been practicing since September, so they
welcome the chance to play other teams, even if starting positions
remain undecided.
</P>
<P>
   With so many new players, Batesole is aware losing could become
more frequent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for a quick fix,'' he said. ``If we have to
get kicked in the teeth, so be it. To get to the highest quality,
like in '96 (a 52-18 record to win a Western Athletic Conference
title and an NCAA regional appearance), it means we'll be taking
our lumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen players have earned opportunities to win spots. Some won
chances based on their fall performances. Others got help from
outfielder Jason Watkins' separated finger. Watkins was to be the
center fielder and leadoff batter, but since he's out six weeks,
Batesole is shuffling.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Phillips moves from left field to center field, leaving
four players battling for the spot. Tom Morefield, a Chatsworth
graduate, and Mike Bumstead will try to win the right-field spot.
</P>
<P>
   Around the infield, things are a little more set. Adrian Mendoza
is the first baseman, and freshman J.T. Stotts, from Hart, has won
the shortstop position for now. Senior Kevin Patrick moves from
third base to his natural second base, and Eric Horvat, a Hart
graduate who was the only freshman last year to stay with
Northridge, moves from the outfield to his natural third-base spot.
</P>
<P>
   Junior catcher Jeremy Sickles, along with Mendoza, started the
last 21 games of his freshman year and all of his sophomore season,
so Batesole said there's no reason he won't start.
</P>
<P>
   Three pitchers return. Senior Jose Vasquez won 10 games last
year. Relievers Tim Bell and Jim DeBiase move into starting roles.
Bell is scheduled to start Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The relievers will be a pair of freshmen, Mike Frick and Andy
Davidson from Hart, as well as sophomore Tom Manos from Royal and
senior Andrew Sanchez, a transfer from New Mexico State.
</P>
<P>
   But who will do what? Like with the rest of the team, Batesole
said, it will take time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
