<HEADLINE>
AMERICA WEST WORKERS CHEER POSSIBLE BUYOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN CRENO 
 LISA GONDERINGER 
 and REBECCA ROLWING 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ America West Airlines employees, some still stinging
from tense union negotiations, cheered a possible United Airlines
buyout that they said would bring them higher pay.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if United keeps them on the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Some America West pilots said there was a constant buzz
Wednesday about a possible sale.
</P>
<P>
   But such speculation is nothing new. Word among workers recently
had Delta Airlines as a possible suitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rumors probably are some of the best sources of entertainment
for flight crews. After awhile &UR; , you don't get excited. I'll
believe it when the new uniform shows up in my locker,'' one
America West pilot &UR; said.
</P>
<P>
   America West flight attendant Lara Ketterman said she is excited
about the prospect of a merger with United and doesn't fear she
would be laid off. United is a strong company with good management,
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Other America West employees interviewed for this story insisted
that their names not be used. The airline, like many big companies,
has a strict policy that forbids employees to talk to the media.
Some workers have been reprimanded after being quoted.
</P>
<P>
   Two flight attendants said a buyout would benefit their
pocketbooks, noting that United has strong union representation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be wonderful for us. Getting into their union, our
pay would double,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, their own union continues to be at odds with America
West management.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pay for America West flight attendants is $15,571 and
reaches $25,974 after 12 years, according to figures from the
flight attendants union. Southwest Airlines starts its flight
attendants at $15,465, but they reach $42,700 in the 12th year, the
union says. Figures for United were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 America West mechanics settled on a contract in
October after two years of negotiations, but contract talks
continue with the Association of Flight Attendants, with meetings
resuming Monday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,100 flight attendants have voted to strike if an agreement
can't be reached on pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, about 2,000 baggage handlers and other fleet service
workers voted this month for representation by the Transport
Workers Union, which has now launched an effort to organize America
West's gate, ticket counter and reservation workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Transport Workers Union also represents about 35 America
West dispatchers.
</P>
<P>
   From pilots to ramp workers, most America West employees said
they hoped a buyout would lead to better pay.
</P>
<P>
   It also would allow them to work for America's largest airline.
</P>
<P>
   A sale to United would be ``a great thing,'' one pilot &UR; said.
That's because pilots get more money when they fly larger planes,
which United has more of than America West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think even the most junior pilot would be happy,'' said a
longtime America West captain. ``There's no comparison as to what
America West pays for flight crews vs. what United pays.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, United offers a pension plan, something America West
lacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a pilot at America West, you put in 20 years and
hope you saved some money. United has a great pension,'' said a
United pilot who was in transit at Sky Harbor International Airport
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   America West officials would not comment beyond saying it has
been approached by ``a number of airlines expressing interest in
possible transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   A pair of ramp workers hoped a buyout would lead to better pay
if United kept them on board. Their hourly salaries float from $7
to about $11.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be awesome if they took us with them,'' one ramp
worker said.
</P>
<P>
   The low pay has led to high turnover among America West's ground
crews, something the airline appears ``content with,'' a worker
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
