<SLUG> BC-EARNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE POSTS RECORD INCOME DESPITE TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ America West Airlines, knocked off course in 1998 by
labor battles, chronic flight delays and a $5 million FAA fine over
maintenance violations, still managed to report record net income
of $108.6 million for the year.
</P>
<P>
   That was an increase of 45 percent from net income of $75
million in 1997, according to figures released Wednesday by the
Tempe carrier in its earnings report.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its troubles, passengers are returning to fly America
West and investors seem encouraged by the airline's financial
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are particularly pleased with our improvement in the
fourth-quarter earnings at a time when the airline industry in
general is experiencing declining profits,'' Chairman William
Franke said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   While America West Holdings Corp. financial results were
soaring, with total revenue topping the $2 billion mark for the
first time, the airline was buffeted last year by the largest fine
in U.S. aviation history, bitter disputes with its mechanics and
flight attendants unions and the worst on-time arrival record of
the 10 major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanics settled on a contract, but negotiations continue with
the Association of Flight Attendants, with talks resuming Monday in
Washington. . The 2,100 flight attendants have voted to strike if
an agreement can't be reached on pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, about 2,000 baggage handlers and other fleet service
workers voted Jan. 8 for representation by the Transport Workers
Union, which has also launched an effort to organize America West's
gate, ticket counter and reservation workers.
</P>
<P>
   America West expects to reach agreement with the flight
attendants union this year, according to Chief Financial Officer
Doug Parker. He declined further comment on the negotiations, other
than to say that the union's threatened strike over the Christmas
holidays did not have any material effect on the company's
fourth-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   America West's final quarter net income of $22.4 million,
excluding non-recurring charges of $3.7 million, is 11 percent
better than the previous record of $20.1 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings per share of 56 cents were 30 percent above last year's
record of 43 cents and well above the 39 cents predicted by
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Parker characterized America West's performance as a ``really
fantastic year,'' following a good year in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Airline analyst Edward Starkman of Warburg Dillon Read said
America West is performing well, but not quite as good as the
earnings report showed.
</P>
<P>
   A drop in fuel prices has masked some ``revenue softness'' at
America West and other airlines, he said, adding that Warburg
Dillon Read has a ``hold'' rating on America West and all other
airlines except Southwest and US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   America West's fuel costs for the fourth quarter were down 17.5
percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-quarter revenue, up 4 percent to $507 million, was higher
than expected, said Parker, adding that the company didn't know how
quickly it could improve its operations and convince customers to
fly America West again.
</P>
<P>
   The airline was plagued by a rash of canceled and delayed
flights, some of which it attributed to its dispute with the
mechanics union. Only 66.5 percent of the carrier's flights arrived
on time from July through September. That improved to 73.3 percent
in November.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration levied its $5 million civil
penalty at start of the third quarter in July. America West agreed
to pay $2.5 million to settle the allegations of lax maintenance
and operations violations and the FAA waived the remaining $2.5
million if the airline meets the terms of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   America West's sales force has done a good job of convincing
travelers that the third quarter operations were an aberration,
Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue passenger miles were up 4.4 percent in the fourth
quarter to 4.03 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bookings for the first month of this year appear to be strong,
but it's hard to tell how America West will do in the first quarter
because most passengers book flights only a month in advance,
Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   America West is planning for 10 percent growth in 1999 and will
continue to add flights on long-haul routes from Phoenix and Las
Vegas to the east coast, including New York, Boston and Baltimore,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy has proved successful in luring more business
passengers to America West, Parker added. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
